<HEADLINE>
LUCK RUNS OUT FOR TORNADO-STRICKEN FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tornado experts always envied Tarrant
County's ``dumb luck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your luck has run out,'' meteorologist Harold Brooks said
Tuesday night from Norman, Okla., home of the National Severe
Storms Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that, in the early 19th century, American Indians
camped in between two Trinity River forks because they believed no
tornado would strike the river delta. In 1849, the U.S. Army built
the original Fort Worth atop the overlooking bluff across the Clear
Fork.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 150 years, Fort Worth was a scientific anomaly _
the only major American city without a single tornado fatality,
Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legends are just that: legends,'' Brooks said. ``This could
happen again next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's safety _ and complacency _ has been discussed by
storm experts, Brooks said. Residents of Emporia, Kan., also
believed they were protected until a 1974 tornado killed six.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, experts at the Norman center plotted possible damage
from a head-on tornado strike in downtown Fort Worth as part of an
areawide study for the North Central Texas Council of Governments.
The study projected a mile-wide tornado like the one that struck
Moore, Okla., last year. It foresaw the possibility of as many as
300 fatalities and 21,000 demolished structures valued at $2.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that would be a wakeup call,'' Brooks said. ``The
entire Metroplex has a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of a tornado striking the Texas Motor Speedway
is a serious concern at the storm center, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race there, the Kentucky Derby, the Indianapolis 500 _
they're all events with a tremendous number of people at the height
of tornado season,'' he said. Speedway officials have said the
arena has an elaborate weather forecast center, but Brooks said
forecasters worry whether it could be evacuated quickly.
</P>
<P>
   After the Storms Laboratory study was released, Fort Worth City
Council member Clyde Picht immediately repeated his call for a $2
million warning siren system. Council members have discussed the
system twice but did not include it in the 1998 or 1999 budgets; it
was excluded in favor of a less expensive public education
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Storms Laboratory forecasters believe cities need both education
and sirens, Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sirens have been shown to be very effective where people are
outdoors and simply in drawing public interest,'' he said. ``You
hear a siren, you call your sister.'' Education campaigns are very
effective for schoolchildren, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The current Fort Worth sirens are an expanded version of the
Civil Defense system installed in 1956 to warn a city of defense
factories of a Russian attack.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
