<HEADLINE>
DEADLY TORNADO DEVELOPED SUDDENLY, WEATHER SERVICE SPOKESMAN SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Radar images show the tornado that struck
downtown Fort Worth on Tuesday developed suddenly northwest of the
city center, said Skip Ely, a meteorologist with the National
Weather Service in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had it a little southwest of Meacham (Airport) when we
issued the tornado warning. ... It was in the Sansom Park or River
Oaks area, and then it headed toward downtown as it curved kind of
eastward,'' Ely said.
</P>
<P>
   He said local weather service forecasters were unable to judge
the intensity of the storm Tuesday. ``We won't fully know until we
can survey it. It could vary widely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ely said zigging and zagging is common for this type of tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``They move. They change shape. They almost breathe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After striking the Cash America Pawn building at West Seventh
Street and the Clear Fork of the Trinity River, it appeared to head
east, zigzagging between Third and Sixth Streets with a little less
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Ely said forecasters' instruments showed that the twister
appeared to break up in the vicinity of North Riverside Drive or
North Beach Street along Interstate 30 southeast of downtown, but
that it was quickly replaced by a separate but related tornado that
swept through southwest Arlington east of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Arlington storm likely developed in the area of
Collins Street and I-30. It moved to the southeast where it was
tracked toward DeSoto, Lancaster and Wilmer.
</P>
<P>
   Ely said power outages were reported along that track.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ely said, tornadoes were reported in Lampasas,
Hamilton and Cooke County.
</P>
<P>
   Ely said Tuesday's twister was what forecasters call a ``cyclic
storm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that a tornado develops and dissipates, and another
tornado develops and dissipates nearby, and sometimes the process
will go on four or five times.''
</P>
<P>
   A tornado is a balance between downdrafts and updrafts, he said.
Sometimes, a downdraft will wrap around the updraft and choke off
the supply of warm, moist air, which causes that tornado to weaken
and dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the parent air circulation aloft in the middle to upper
levels of the storm remains, and a new tornado sometimes develops
in the new updraft of the storm complex,'' he said. The new tornado
frequently moves east or southeast of the first tornado.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
