<HEADLINE>
POUGHKEEPSIE STUDENTS TRY TO SHAPE CITY POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Mass., Pa., Conn.)  (mk) 
 By CLAUDIA ROWE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Within a few miles of this tough Hudson
River city are two elite colleges, a renowned cooking school, a
college with a nationally watched political polling center and two
state undergraduate institutions. Yet the thousands of students at
these campuses seldom venture past the gates to mingle with their
city neighbors, who often struggle with poverty, homelessness and
the city's faltering attempts at urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   But 27 students from the six schools _ Vassar, Bard, Marist,
Dutchess County Community College, the State University of New York
at New Paltz and the Culinary Institute of America _ are involved
in an unusual cross-campus class that uses the city as a laboratory
and whose findings the city, by legislative fiat, must examine.
</P>
<P>
   Several evenings a week, Catherine Schloegel, a senior at Vassar
who describes herself as a typical, ``innocent-looking college
kid,'' waits at the bus stop where homeless men pick up a shuttle
to the county shelter. There, she and Terri-Ann Sweet, a student at
Dutchess County Community, speak to as many men as will allow them
an interview. The results of their work will be included in a
report to the city on the realities and causes of Poughkeepsie's
homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first night people were like, `You're never going to
understand what it's like to be homeless,''' Schloegel said.
</P>
<P>
   Schloegel, of Boulder, Colo., hung on long enough to watch one
of her subjects, a man who had been homeless for 17 years, find a
job and a place to live. The experience has changed her so much
that she plans to remain in Poughkeepsie after graduation and work
in education.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the program, known as the Poughkeepsie Institute,
tackles an issue important to Poughkeepsie, offering research and
an academic perspective with the hopes of affecting government
policy. Last year, the subjects were race and ethnicity. Previous
classes have focused on mass transportation and welfare. Students
from the Culinary Institute, whose schedule does not mesh with
those of the other colleges, serve meals to the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   While the Poughkeepsie Institute's impact has thus far been
small, last year's class on race and ethnicity increased awareness
of issues surrounding the surging Mexican population and was a
factor in prodding the city's Common Council to hold an annual
Cinco de Mayo festival for Hispanic immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the issues could be explored through conventional
lectures and books, but the real-life fieldwork, students and
college officials say, has been invaluable. ``The question for
undergraduates is how do you connect theory and practice,'' said
Leon Botstein, president of Bard College. When looking at these
issues by working in the field, he said, students ``leave the realm
of cliched generalizations immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   While unusual in that it involves a group of colleges, the
Poughkeepsie initiative is not unique. Colleges around the country
have abandoned a fortress-like, town-gown isolation and are finding
a variety of ways, from anthropological and sociological study to
outright redevelopment, of building bridges to their host
communities.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the real-world problem-solving is valued by
career-minded students; another is that campuses want to make their
host cities as attractive as possible to prospective recruits.
Harvard is building low-cost housing in Cambridge, the University
of Pennsylvania has helped rebuild parts of West Philadelphia and
the president of Connecticut College is chairwoman of the New
London, Conn., development authority.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Leonard, chairman of the institute and a Vassar College
faculty member, believes Poughkeepsie's comparatively small size
(population: 29,000) makes it an ideal place for such an effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's small enough that you can become a player on any issue
and big enough to have all the problems and all the promise of a
major American city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Poughkeepsie, the governing powers welcome the help. Both
Mayor Colette Lafuente and the chairman of the city's Common
Council, Thomas O'Neill, are institute board members. O'Neill said
in his annual address that he hoped to use the students'
information ``as a cornerstone of any meaningful reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Thomas, 22, a biology major at Dutchess County Community
College, spends much of her time videotaping interviews with
homeless men and women and has learned just how simplistic her
previous notions about homelessness were.
</P>
<P>
   At the Living Room, a daytime center for the homeless run by the
Mental Health Association of Dutchess County, Thomas leaned
forward, her hand on her chin, as she asked Trudy Dillard, 35,
about her trips in and out of prison; questioned Nancy Reyes, 32,
about the children who were taken away from her, and asked
25-year-old Carmen McClaurin about a life of physical abuse and the
time she spent in jail for stabbing her boyfriend in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you become homeless?'' she asked, filming every
minute. ``Were you abused as a child? What would turn things around
for you?''
</P>
<P>
   The video will be presented to the city's Common Council at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your story touched me,'' Thomas told McClaurin. ``For so many
women, this is the real issue, domestic abuse, and homelessness is
just the end of a long cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   McClaurin nodded and then hugged her interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're learning about us as people, who are out there on the
street,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the class, which is held in a community center in
downtown Poughkeepsie, is structured in traditional fashion, with
three hours of classes and required reading. Students work under a
team of teachers representing each college and a variety of
disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a different way of learning,'' Schloegel said. ``I
think a traditional classroom experience is valuable, but so is
knowing where you live. In fact, I think it's more important to
understand the lives of people around us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
