<HEADLINE>
FCC EXPECTED TO REJECT SBC'S LONG DISTANCE APPLICATION
</HEADLINE>
  (mb) 
By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission is expected to thwart
efforts by SBC Communications to enter the $80 billion
long-distance telephone market early this year, according to people
close to the commission.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, these people have said that the FCC will almost
certainly reject SBC's application to offer long-distance service
in Texas, because the company has not provided sufficient evidence
that it has opened its local networks in the state to potential
competitors. The FCC probably will not announce a decision until
April 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act of 1996 says that the local telephone
carriers, which split from the former American Telephone and
Telegraph Company in 1984, must convince the FCC that they have
opened local networks to competitors on a state-by-state basis
before they will be allowed into the long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only Bell Atlantic has passed that test. Just before
Christmas, the FCC cleared the way for Bell Atlantic to sell
long-distance services to its customers in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling appeared to prompt long-distance giants like AT&AMP;T to
step up efforts to offer local service.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last year, senior SBC executives had hopes of
beating Bell Atlantic into the long-distance market, and many
analysts thought that if Bell Atlantic's application were approved
first, SBC's would follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department, which advises the FCC on the
long-distance applications, has said that SBC, based in San
Antonio, has not opened its systems sufficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Since filing its original petition, SBC has amended the
application to include additional information. But the Justice
Department has not been convinced. Some analysts have said that
Bell Atlantic's successful application was so thorough that it set
a high standard for the other Bells to meet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
