A0844 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      03-29 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The Florida portion of the Astros' preparation
for the upcoming season was rather uneventful, which is just the
way the club hoped it would be.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After last spring, when the Astros watched Moises Alou go down
with a knee injury, Ken Caminiti get hospitalized because of an
acute sinus infection and Doug Henry try to pitch through pain in
his elbow that eventually required surgery, no news is good news
this time around.
</P>
<P>
   The team will head back to Houston today for a tour of Enron
Field for the first time as a group. Their luck was so bad last
season, the Astros probably would have hesitated to take their
players to a construction site, but 1999 and 2000 have been hardly
similar in that respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camp ran smoothly,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker said.
``We got a lot of work done, and we stayed away from serious
injuries. The goal is always to get through the spring without
having injuries factor into the composition of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   There still is one roster spot open, and it could very well come
down to Hunsicker's deciding whether to carry six outfielders _
with Glen Barker being the man on the bubble _ or three catchers.
The Astros want to find a way to keep catcher Mitch Meluskey, but
Paul Bako is out of options, and they don't want to expose him to
the waiver process, which they would be forced to do if they tried
to send him to Class AAA New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   One way of getting around that would be to trade Bako, but to do
that the Astros almost certainly would have to get a
major-league-caliber catcher in return, one who would be willing to
serve as a Class AAA insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   Another trade possibility is to upgrade the bullpen with a
lefthanded specialist. It's also conceivable the Astros could trade
a reserve infielder, possibly Russ Johnson, to open a spot on the
roster for Tripp Cromer, or perhaps prospect Julio Lugo, because
the club does not have a true backup shortstop behind starter Tim
Bogar.
</P>
<P>
   So while there hasn't been much news out of the Astros' camp,
things could change. As per his normal policy, Hunsicker does not
discuss trade speculation involving specific players.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at how the Astros shape up in various areas:
</P>
<P>
   Infield
</P>
<P>
   It's loaded with veterans, which makes it reasonably easy to
predict performances. The Astros know what to expect from Jeff
Bagwell, Craig Biggio and Caminiti if they stay healthy. The only
question regarding Bogar is how he will respond to playing every
day. The fact he appeared much stronger this spring went a long way
toward easing those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Outfield
</P>
<P>
   The most significant development was the shift of Alou from left
field to right field, which allows manager Larry Dierker the
flexibility of platooning Richard Hidalgo and Daryle Ward in left.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's only position in the outfield is left field, but Hidalgo
also could see action in center field, where Roger Cedeno is the
starter. Cedeno had some defensive lapses early in the spring but
has been much better lately, and the Astros are thrilled with the
way Alou has bounced back from major knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alou has been impressive from day one,'' Hunsicker said.
``Many times, veteran players sleepwalk through spring training,
but he worked hard and played a lot of innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting rotation
</P>
<P>
   Chris Holt was the hard-luck pitcher in the Astros' rotation
last season when he was 5-13. But he has looked like a different
pitcher this spring, and it has more to do with his quality stuff
than it does luck. If Holt takes his game to the next level, he'll
go a long way toward helping the Astros compensate for the loss of
22-game winner Mike Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Shane Reynolds nor Jose Lima was impressive, but their
track records speak for themselves. If they're healthy _ Reynolds
was bothered by two bulging disks in his back _ each is capable of
winning 16 to 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran righthander Dwight Gooden gave plenty of indications
there still is a lot left in his 35-year-old arm, but Octavio Dotel
got himself into trouble with control problems, one of the Astros'
concerns when camp began. He has walked 13 batters in 19 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation could get a boost in mid- to late April when Scott
Elarton is expected to be ready to join the big-league club.
Elarton is recovering from offseason rotator-cuff surgery and won't
start the season on time.
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner's elbow was something of a concern when camp began,
but it almost has become a non-issue. Kid Heat has looked like his
old self. A return to form by Jay Powell also has the Astros
excited. Powell was a sinkerball pitcher without a reliable sinker
in 1999, but he appears to have rediscovered his signature pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cabrera has earned the right to pitch in some setup
situations, and Henry's conversion from setup man to middle
reliever will give Dierker far more options than he had last
season, when his bullpen was basically a collection of one-inning
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Mike Maddux has enjoyed a strong spring, but lefthander
Trever Miller has struggled, which no doubt is one of the reasons
the Astros would like to have another lefty in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Bench
</P>
<P>
   This is where decisions still must be made. Super sub Bill
Spiers is the main man on the bench, and the outfield depth further
feeds the reserves. But the Astros must decide if they have more
need for a pinch runner/defensive replacement like Barker or a
third catcher, which would free up Tony Eusebio or Meluskey for
more pinch-hitting assignments, assuming Bako is on the team.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
