<SLUG> BC-HKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO PAY ATTENTION TO KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Somehow the impression has been created that Los
Angeles sports fans pay scant attention to the Kings, that we have
no time in our busy schedules for the soccer-on-ice contrivance
known as hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Not true. In fact we might be able to squeeze in a couple of
minutes for hockey right now. Permit us to check our calendar to
make sure.
</P>
<P>
   Why, yes, it seems we've had a cancellation and are free at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Our college basketball team has been bounced out of the
tournament. Our pro basketball team is on cruise control until the
playoffs begin, our baseball team won't open its season until next
week, and our Arena League football team is still learning the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   As for soccer, we never did care for hockey on grass.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the golf and tennis tours have moved on to the next town,
the Academy Awards season is over and the presidential campaign is
in hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's a light week on the local sports and
entertainment schedule. So if the Kings want our attention, then
this is the week to grab it.
</P>
<P>
   Which fits into the Kings' plans quite neatly. They have six
games left in the regular season, beginning tonight against the San
Jose Sharks at Staples Center. They're on the verge of clinching a
spot in the NHL playoffs, a formality for many teams but a sign of
progress for this one.
</P>
<P>
   They could make it dramatic and clinch that playoff spot
Saturday afternoon when they face their rivals, the Anaheim Mighty
Ducks, at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   It's nervous time at the HealthSouth Training Center, the Kings'
new practice facility in El Segundo.
</P>
<P>
   In the dressing room, head coach Andy Murray has been updating a
message board headlined ``The Situation.'' It shows the Western
Conference standings and makes the point that the Kings can't
expect to glide effortlessly into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They're fifth in the 13-team conference with a 36-30-10 record
and 86 points. The top eight make the postseason eliminations.
You'd think the situation is pretty safe for the Kings. But the
board shows that every team below them can still get 86 or more
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're worried about making the playoffs?'' someone asked
Murray after Tuesday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``I think that's part of my job. I'd like my
players to worry about it too.''
</P>
<P>
   A bigger worry might be what happens after they do make the
playoffs. If the season ended today, they'd have to face the
Detroit Red Wings (46-22-9) in the first round, and the Kings'
progress would likely be measured in a short step.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Kings will have their devotees no matter what
happens this week. The old joke was that the team drew the same
8,000 fans every night. The good news is that at least the number
is expanding.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is running about 16,400 a game in the first season in
Staples Center, up about 3,600 from last year. Sellouts are up too,
from five to 16 so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't worry about it,'' Murray said of the size of
the Kings' following. ``I think we have great fans. There are more
Kings jerseys (in the stands) at our games than (hometown jerseys)
in other cities. We just go about our business every day here. We
work hard for our fans, and anybody else who wants to jump on
board, you're welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, coming to the end of his first season as Kings coach,
said that until three weeks ago, he could gad about town fairly
anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I get the odd person who says, `Aren't you the coach of
the Kings?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's an older gentleman who writes four-page letters to
Murray every week. Murray has kept them all. ``He has some good
suggestions,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a woman in Anaheim who regularly fires off faxes
addressed to ``Andy,'' although he doesn't recall having met her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get !ital!someone!off! in front of the net for the
rebounds. It's killing us!!!'' read such a fax last Wednesday,
after the Kings had lost three games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   A follow-up Sunday night, with the Kings on a three-game
unbeaten streak, reflected the new mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great! Great! road trip,'' it read. ``Loved to see the boys in
front of the net for the rebounds. Now back to the Oscars.''
</P>
<P>
   The faxes wore big initial R's and smiling faces.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the Kings have been around long enough to remember the
brief time when Los Angeles was a hockey town wearing a smiling
face _ when Wayne Gretzky was here and the team went to the 1993
Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (fan excitement) comes with winning,'' said Luc Robitaille,
leading scorer on that team and this one.
</P>
<P>
   Going past the first round of the playoffs in 2000 would be a
nice way to begin reclaiming the Kings' lapsed fans. To do that,
they'll need to get injured Ziggy Palffy back and they'll have to
heat up one of their goaltenders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the Kings want to become brighter blips on the L.A. radar
screen, the answer is to make the playoffs for more than one year
in a row. They missed the playoffs in 1999 and in four of the five
seasons before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to earn your credibility,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a long process. But this is the week to start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
