<SLUG> BC-NY-RESTAURANT-WORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCREASE IN NEW YORK MINIMUM WAGE MAY BE KEPT LOWER FOR SOME
</HEADLINE>
   (hm) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ On Friday, the minimum wage will rise for New
York's lowest-paid workers, but lawmakers plan to prevent the
absolute lowest wage earners, restaurant and bar employees who earn
tips, from collecting the entire increase.
</P>
<P>
   Under a combination of federal and state laws, restaurants and
bars in New York can pay their workers as little as $2.90 an hour
if they also earn tips, a wage that has not changed in nine years.
On Friday, the minimum for some groups of workers will rise to
$5.15 an hour from $4.25, and the minimum for those who make tips
is slated to increase to $3.52 from $2.90.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats who control the Assembly, including Speaker
Sheldon Silver, want to set a new minimum for restaurant and bar
workers who earn tips at $3.30, not $3.52. Until last week, they
proposed freezing the wage at $2.90.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly is expected to pass the bill on Wednesday or
Thursday, said Patricia Lynch, a spokeswoman for Silver. The
speaker's office declined to discuss the rationale for the bill.
The Republican-controlled state Senate has approved a bill freezing
the minimum for tipped workers at $2.90. Michael McKeon, a
spokesman for Gov. George E. Pataki, said that the governor
supports the idea of setting the wage below $3.52, but that he
objects to some technical provisions of the Assembly bill.
</P>
<P>
   The debate pits some of the Democrats' traditional
constituencies, low-wage workers and unions, against powerful
small-business lobbying groups. It also strikes a dissonant note at
a time when the economic talk is of stock options, dot-coms and
full employment _ a reminder that in the service economy, low wages
persist even in rosy times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make $200, $250 a week, with tips,'' said Fernando, a
Colombian immigrant who buses tables in a downtown Manhattan
restaurant, and asked that his surname not be used for fear he
would lose his job. ``I have a wife and two children. It's not
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Donnelly, legislative director of the state AFL-CIO, said,
``To take the lowest-paid worker, a waitress in a greasy spoon, and
convene the best minds in the Capitol to rob her of a quarter, to
me is immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   But restaurant owners insist that workers have done well in the
booming economy, with their income rising quickly through tips.
``We don't think those people need a statutorily authorized
62-cent-an-hour increase in pay,'' said Scott Wexler, executive
director of the Empire State Restaurant and Tavern Association,
which represents 5,000 small businesses. ``For our average member,
that would cost $15,000 a year.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that among his group's members, employees who are paid
$2.90 an hour actually earn, on average, $10 an hour with tips. But
a 1997 survey by the state Department of Labor found that the
average income for waiters and waitresses was $6.34 an hour, with
tips. That survey found more than 150,000 people working in what
are typically tip-earning restaurant and bar jobs, but the
department could not say how many earn the $2.90 minimum today.
</P>
<P>
   The ``tipped wage'' varies enormously from state to state, and
New York's ranks 17th. The highest minimum is $6.50 in Washington
state, which does not differentiate between tip earners and others.
The lowest is $2.13, in several states, including New Jersey.
Connecticut's is $4.73.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law sets the minimum wage for most workers at $5.15, but
it allows states to set lower minimums for a few categories of
workers, like farm laborers and restaurant employees. (A handful of
states actually have higher minimums than the federal standard.)
New York state's minimum wage has stood at $4.25 an hour since
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law also allows states to set even lower minimums for
workers who make tips. When New York raised its state minimum to
$4.25, the state Department of Labor set a $2.90 wage for people
like waiters, bartenders and busboys. Legally, the worker must earn
at least $4.25 an hour with tips, but employees' groups say that
rule is often flouted.
</P>
<P>
   In December, state lawmakers raised the minimum to $5.15 from
$4.25, effective March 31. Under a 1991 ruling by the state
Department of Labor, that would automatically raise the wage for
workers who make tips by the same percentage, to $3.52 from $2.90.
The current bills would overturn that rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
