<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HOMELESS-MAYOR-NYT     03-29 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER HOUSE FIRE, A MAYOR REVISITS HIS NOMADIC PAST
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREWSTER, N.Y. _ To hear John Cesar tell it, he has always been
one step away from homelessness. But a raging fire on Monday erased
that step, leaving Cesar, who at 82 is the oldest and possibly the
most unconventional mayor in the state, truly without a home.
</P>
<P>
   The one-room apartment that Cesar had called both home and
campaign headquarters was incinerated by a midafternoon fire that
is believed to have started in faulty electrical wiring. Cesar lost
everything but the stale clothes on his back, including his poetry,
the books he collected on history and European royalty, and the
first draft of his libretto for a political opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first was elected mayor in 1987, the paper said I was
almost homeless because I financed my campaign by collecting
bottles and cans,'' said Cesar, a onetime circus clown with a Santa
Claus beard and a chuckle to match. ``I'm really homeless now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cesar is in his third two-year term as mayor of Brewster, a
1-square-mile village of 1,800 people about 60 miles from Midtown
Manhattan. After his first term, it took him several years to win
again. In the interim he ran for other offices, including town
councilman and Putnam County executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran five times in 10 years and lost every time,'' Cesar said
Tuesday, recalling his political fights as he stood on the steps of
the Bagel Depot, a popular breakfast spot where a chair is named in
his honor and a jar asking for donations to help him contained $405
on Tuesday morning. ``I said, `You can beat me, but you are never
going to get rid of me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cesar was born in Bedford, in neighboring Westchester County, in
1918. ``That was the year Ronald Reagan was born, Babe Ruth, Billy
Graham and me,'' he said, putting himself in good, if not
historically accurate, company. (Reagan was born in 1911, and Ruth
in 1895.) He hitchhiked across the country in 1937 and grew to like
the hobo life, joining the circus so he could get a good hot meal,
he said. When he moved to Brewster in 1945, he started a trucking
company, opened a bar named the Poorhouse and raised a family.
</P>
<P>
   His popularity was evident Wednesday as he walked down Main
Street. Every few steps, he was approached by someone offering
help.
</P>
<P>
   A woman from the Animal Rescue thrift shop, where winter clothes
sell for $5 a bag, said she had put some shirts and pants aside for
him. The minister of the First United Methodist Church offered him
one of the six bedrooms in the parsonage. Others just stopped to
say they were sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar, who lived alone, and the three families who had shared
the rickety apartment building in an alley off Main Street were put
up at a motel by the local chapter of the Red Cross. Members of the
Elks, the Knights of Columbus and the Veterans of Foreign Wars
called Cesar at Village Hall to offer help.
</P>
<P>
   But Cesar, who earns $6,556 a year as part-time mayor, already
has plans for his next home. On a village street dotted with
magnolia trees, there is a trailer that he hopes to rent starting
next week.
</P>
<P>
   It is not fancy, but it is perfect for a man who raised $1,100
in campaign funds by recycling bottles and cans. He used most of
the money to make fliers and to buy paints and poster board to make
campaign signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent $500 for a commercial and I was on TV for 30
seconds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His latest crusade is a fight for independence. Brewster is a
small, aging village within the booming town of Southeast (though
locals and outsiders alike refer to Southeast as Brewster). Cesar
has started a campaign to secede from Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started it,'' he said. ``They want our water. They want
our sewage. They want our railroad station. They even want our
name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
