A0853 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-1STLD-1     03-29 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-1STLD-1500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY'S FIRST DEADLY TWISTER KILLS 2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERNIE MAKOVY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A rampaging tornado, the first deadly twister in the city's
history, blasted downtown Fort Worth Tuesday evening, killing two
people and shattering skyscraper windows.
</P>
<P>
   A second twister smashed into south Arlington east of Fort Worth
about a half-hour later, leveling six homes and damaging as many as
100 others. No serious injuries were reported in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth emergency workers were searching late Tuesday for two
missing people whose car was found along the Trinity River.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is believed two people were in the car, and they haven't
been able to find them,'' said Lt. Kent Worley, the Fire Department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Six other people were rescued from the river.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Chief Larry McMillen said elsewhere there was ``some
concern that there are people trapped. There are people unaccounted
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of people were injured in Fort Worth, at least two
critically, as buildings were ripped apart and flying shards of
glass splayed downtown streets about 6:20 p.m., as many workers
headed home from their offices.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most seriously hurt was a man struck by a hailstone
that paramedics said was the size of a softball, said Dr. Michael
Hickey, a trauma surgeon at Harris Methodist Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire skull is fractured, so it'd have to take a
tremendous force,'' Hickey said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials closed the downtown area ``to make sure downtown
is safe before we allow people to return,'' Mayor Kenneth Barr
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way in the dark to know what the situation is,''
Barr said. The area is expected to remain closed for part of
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said it is ``somewhat a miracle'' that more people did
not suffer serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, Mayor Elzie Odom declared a state of emergency
that granted police broad powers to limit access to the damaged
areas.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Reps. Kay Granger of Fort Worth and Martin Frost of Dallas
offered Fort Worth federal assistance Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   TXU Electric &AMP; Gas had 30,000 customers without service in Fort
Worth and Arlington, a company spokeswoman said. The hardest hit
areas were downtown and north and west Fort Worth and south
Arlington, said spokeswoman Carol Peters.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth tornado tore its devastating swath along a
two-mile route stretching roughly from University Drive to just
east of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Meterorologist Harold Brooks of the National Severe Storms
Laboratory in Norman, Okla., said the storm would probably reach an
intensity of F2 on the Fujita scale used to compare tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit were the Mallick Tower on One Summit Avenue, the
Cash America building at 1600 W. Seventh St., the Bank One Tower
downtown, Tandy Center and the Calvary Cathedral, where all the
brick work of the steeple was ripped off, exposing steel beams.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen cars in the area were flipped over or tossed on
their sides.
</P>
<P>
   One of two homeless men who sought shelter under a porch of the
empty Burns Graphics Building, on West Seventh at the Trinity
River, was killed when a wall behind them collapsed. He was
identified as Carl Spence, 67.
</P>
<P>
   Spence's companion, John Barr, 70, was also buried under the
debris but was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fell upon me and I was under a pile of bricks,'' Barr said.
``When I looked back, I saw it fell on him, too. When I got up and
got back to him, I realized he was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The other dead man was identified as Howard D. Thornton, 52. He
was crushed by a truck trailer that flipped onto him behind the
landmark Montgomery Ward catalogue building on West Seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The area behind the 70-year-old building, which survived the
April 1949 floodwaters that reached the second floor, was a
shambles of crazily twisted truck trailers jammed against the
loading dock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Thornton) was warning people back by the guard shack to
get down, get down, but the tornado caught up with him and he
didn't make it,'' said Frank Godoy, 26, a Montgomery Ward
maintenance worker from Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Pieces of glass, chunks of metal and building panels continued
falling to the West Seventh Street pavement an hour after the
storm. Trees surrounding the building were bent and broken. Light
poles were crushed against trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it looks like we are all alive,'' said Jose Rico,
director of marketing for Cash America International, who had left
his seventh-floor office five minutes before the storm hit, got in
his car, then ``I ran back into the building.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is incredible. My office is gone. I haven't found my car
yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour after the Fort Worth tornado, another twister
ravaged a southeast Arlington neighborhood. Several retail
businesses and a gas station were heavily damaged, roofs were
ripped off and buildings were flattened.
</P>
<P>
   About eight houses in the area sustained heavy damage, and 30
houses sustained minor damage. Another two dozen homes in the area
near Williams Elementary were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just felt like the oxygen got sucked out of the house, and
you could hear glass breaking and stuff flying around,'' said J.D.
Walker, who with his wife and 3-year-old twins covered themselves
with a mattress as winds swept through their neighborhood in the
300 block of Chasemore Lane, just south of Interstate 20.
</P>
<P>
   Other neighbors walked up and down the darkened streets,
carrying flashlights, as they checked on damage and offered to help
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Several dogs ran free through the streets in the storm's
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the fences are down _ there's dogs running everywhere,''
said Arlington police Cpl. Michael Van Steenburg.
</P>
<P>
   The building housing the regional office of the Texas Department
of Health and the Department of Human Services was heavily damaged.
The entire east side appeared to be stripped away.
</P>
<P>
   The post office next door also appeared to have been severly
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Ava Mitchell of Fort Worth was working in the Lear plant about 7
p.m. and was caught off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anything. We just heard it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the storm passed the damage was evident: Two truck
trailers on the west side of the building were overturned. In a
field behind the building, the air-conditioning units from the roof
were strewn about.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, the Rev. Bob Nichols of Calvary Cathedral
International watched in awe from his church office as water from
the Trinity River spiraled into the sky and roared toward his
church at 1600 W. 5th St.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have been ripped to shreds if I hadn't run into the
hallway with my wife and two other church members,'' said Nichols,
whose office faces west toward the river. ``We didn't even hear
anything before it hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Only steel beams remained of the cathedral's five-story tower
from the second-story upward to the steeple. Bricks and mortar from
the church were thrown nearly 200 feet across Penn Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like this building has been bombed,'' Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   East of the church, Louis Zapata was among five people inside
the Summit Building, 1500 W. 5th St., which was hammered by the
tornado. Walls crumbled and most of the building's roof was ripped
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``My computer shut off, then the lights went out, so I bent down
to get a flashlight out of my bag,'' said Zapata, 65, a lifelong
resident of Fort Worth who was in the building's second-floor.
``When I bent down, the roof started to just rip off and the walls
started disappearing. Everything was blowing everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good Lord said to me, `Bend down and pick up your life,'
'' he said. ``It was a good solid desk. If it would have moved, I
would have had it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the downtown YMCA, Robert Viana watched as the tornado cut
its deadly path.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking out the window and you could see a funnel of
debris heading right toward us,'' said Viana, 39, of Fort Worth.
``It looked like fingers dangling from the sky. There definitely
was more than one cloud coming down. We started yelling to
everybody and we all took off for the stairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressing himself against the glass in a 28th floor office at the
City Center Two Tower, Joe Garbe could see the black tornado
weaving its way between buildings in downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a vortex,'' Garbe said. ``You could see the lights
sparking different colors and then go dead.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials sought to evacuate everyone from downtown who was
not a resident because of several major areas of concern.
</P>
<P>
   A major gas leak was reported at 3000 W. 7th St. In addition,
damage done to buildings caused officials to declare areas around
Sundance West, the Cash America building and the UPR Building areas
of major concern.
</P>
<P>
   Severe damage was reported at a 7-Eleven near University and
Seventh streets west of downtown. Trees and debris was scattered
across the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Urban Search and Rescue team was deployed from College
Station Tuesday night to help Fort Worth officials. The team, which
includes structural engineers, is expected to arrive Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were reportedly arrested for looting at the Cash
America building.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, police reported that eight semi-trailer trucks had
overturned on Interstate 20 and that as many as 15 houses were
damaged around Matlock Road and I-20.
</P>
<P>
   The storm lost much of its punch as it swept east.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 0045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
