<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0855 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-WARRIORS-     03-29 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-WARRIORS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
If there's anything the Rockets need after the way things have gone
during this trail-of-tears season, it's a couple of good laughs as
the year winds down.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead, they've settled on a couple of laughers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets hammered what's left of the Golden State Warriors on
Tuesday night 121-86 before 14,496 at Compaq Center, their second
straight blowout of monumental proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Their victory came on the heels of Sunday's 45-point victory
over the Bulls, meaning the Rockets have won their last two games
by a combined 80 points. The Rockets also broke the 120-point mark
for the second consecutive game, the first time they had done so
since the end of the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good for us to get two back-to-back victories like
this at home,'' said Steve Francis, who finished with 15 points,
eight rebounds and five assists. ``I think it was the assist factor
(30 against the Warriors) that played a role today, because we all
passed the ball around. Everyone who played tonight scored, and
that's a great accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been really pleased and impressed by the way our guys
have been taking care of business,'' he said. ``I can't tell you
how pleased I've been with our passing. Everybody moved the ball,
everybody got involved, and there were wide-open shots all over the
place. That's fun basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the last two games showed how easy it is to enjoy a pair
of laughers when you're playing a couple of the league's top jokes.
And it also showed how much of a gap there is between the Rockets
and those teams in the league that are truly horrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I don't have much to say about this game,'' said
Golden State's Jason Caffey. ``It was a terrible outing, and it's
an embarrassment. The sooner I can put this behind me, the
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite different from how the Rockets will remember the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is having a winning attitude,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``You have to play as a team and do the right things so it's
not just a wasted year. I don't think by any means or any way you
look at it that this is a wasted year, because this is very
valuable time for our young guys. We can get a really good
foundation in place here, and these guys can leave this season with
a positive attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all laughs, however.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rogers received a nasty hit to the chin while taking a
charge in the second quarter, a shot from the Warriors' Vonteego
Cummings that buckled Rogers and opened up a gash in his chin that
required seven stitches to close. Rogers was helped from the floor,
but he got woozy and again fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was tough,'' Francis said. ``He had stitches in his chin,
and I had stitches in my lip (after getting hit by Denver's Tariq
Abdul-Wahad). But I told him I didn't pass out while he did. But
he's all right. He went home, and he said that hopefully he'll be
able to practice (today) with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, though, it was all fun and games for the
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   One guy who has really been enjoying himself is Walt Williams,
who posted his eighth straight solid start. After scoring a
season-high 24 points against the Bulls on Sunday, Williams came
back Tuesday to put up 20 points, his third straight game of 20 or
more.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't mention the fact he started out 0-for-4 from the
floor, including a missed dunk with 7:15 left in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the dudes on the sidelines were just clowning me crazy out
there, so I knew I had to turn it around,'' said Williams, who also
had a game-high 11 rebounds and six assists. ``I knew I was going
to come out at the end of the first quarter, so I just said, `Hey,
I have to turn this around before the second quarter comes.' So I
just stepped it up.''
</P>
<P>
   As did the rest of the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Shandon Anderson matched Williams' scoring total, while Kelvin
Cato was just a notch behind with 18 points. Cuttino Mobley had 16
points, and Matt Bullard tossed in 10 in just 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Down by two points halfway through the first quarter, the
Rockets went on a 35-9 run over the next 12 minutes to blow the
game wide-open. Down 14-12 at the start of the run, the Rockets
found themselves up 47-23 when Bullard tossed in a jumper with 6:19
to play in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Game over.
</P>
<P>
   Well, except for Golden State's Larry Hughes, who shot as if his
life depended on it, going 9-of-26 from the floor for his 22
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys earlier that these games are important in how
we handle (the losing), stay focused and not just play out the
season,'' Tomjanovich said. ``It's a good opportunity to see the
work ethic and the character of the team, and they've responded
really well.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
