<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0856 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     03-29 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ As training camps go, this one was as clean as
they come. It concludes today with there having been no injuries of
consequence, no rainouts and no real surprises of any kind. Nary a
bigot nor a bigamist could be found in the Astros' clubhouse, and
Houston's new brick-red, sand and black color scheme seemed to be a
smashing hit, judging by how prevalent the new duds were in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   No small thing, that. If he sells enough ball caps, perhaps
Drayton McLane Jr. can get Mike Hampton out of hock for next
season. Hampy might be a free agent, you know.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros came to Florida under a cloud because of offseason
budget-trimming measures that cost them the services of the
lefthanded 22-game winner and outfielder Carl Everett, the
brash-talking outfielder who may emerge a superstar in Boston if a
rogue Yankees fan doesn't do a Tony Soprano on him first. But the
Astros seemed to take the roster broadsides in stride, and they
return to Houston, by and large, sound of both mind and body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever been associated with a better spring
training _ I think we're leaving here in good shape,'' general
manager Gerry Hunsicker said, although he was speaking before he
saw Octavio Dotel get mauled by the Royals on Tuesday. And he
admits he's not done fiddling with the bottom of his roster to
extract as much production from it as he can.
</P>
<P>
   Still, things have been markedly different from a year ago, when
everything that could go wrong did. Then came the regular season,
and things got worse. But the Astros proved resilient enough to win
97 games for a third consecutive Central Division title, and for
all their problems, they were still a far more known quantity than
they are today.
</P>
<P>
   Owner McLane's stubborn determination to eliminate the club's
brick-red bottom line _ he hopes to replace it with a black one _
cost the Astros their best hitter and best pitcher of last season.
Hampton's departure (he failed his fiscal, you might say) saddled
Larry Dierker with a 100-percent righthanded rotation.
</P>
<P>
   But the real X-variable for Houston is Enron Field, the
antithesis of the pitcher-perfect Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   While the Astros' end run to Enron assures them of some
profitability for the coming season, they are no sure thing to make
hay while the sun shines on them and become four-peat champions as
trendy downtown dwellers. Enron's tight confines, in fact, may
prove downright unfriendly. We just don't know yet, because never
in baseball's modern era has a team successfully built over time
for one venue attempted to reinvent itself in short order for such
a starkly different one.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the aforementioned starting pitchers, for example,
statistical research shows the following:
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds' Dome ERA for the last five seasons was 3.42,
with 8.84 strikeouts per nine innings. Elsewhere, his corresponding
numbers were 4.06 and 6.80.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima posted a 2.90 ERA under glass from 1997-99 but 4.79 on
foreign turf, and his strikeouts fell from 7.48 to 6.13.
</P>
<P>
   For his career, Chris Holt clicked to the tune of a 3.67 ERA and
5.99 K's in the Dome but slumped to 6.55 and 3.65 on the road, and,
no, I didn't get those numbers backward.
</P>
<P>
   While Holt has had a splendid spring, you worry if both Reynolds
and Lima are already psyched out by the move. The former, who makes
his final exhibition start today with a Class AAA lineup behind
him, has given up 27 hits and 12 earned runs in 17 tuneup innings.
Lima's vitals are 26 innings worked, 38 hits allowed and 18 earned
runs charged to his account. Scary.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, no doubt, will have to win their share of 9-8 games
to keep the Cardinals and the Reds at bay. Fortunately, statistics
indicate both Jeff Bagwell and Craig Biggio are as likely to
prosper at Enron as the pitchers are to struggle. Bagwell ripped 30
of his 42 home runs last year on the road and hit 66 points higher.
Biggio's Dome average was 20 points under that when he was
traveling. Hopefully, the net result will be an equal
offense-defense trade-off.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Astros will need to wring every possible run
from their available talent pool, Hunsicker is still trying to
tweak the 25-man roster to ensure that all his bases _ and
shortstop, too _ are covered. He gleans great satisfaction out of
plucking players from obscurity, players who were available for the
taking by any club, and seeing them carve out not-insignificant
roles for themselves with Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry has to outsmart his competition, because he can't outspend
it. Of late, he's 3-for-3. But they keep raising the bar on him.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
