<HEADLINE>
SCHEDULE SEEMS TO FAVOR DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Mighty Ducks' remaining schedule would seem to be
a favorable one, especially since Anaheim is a combined 7-0-3
against the Kings, Nashville and Chicago -- the three teams that it
plays its final five games against.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim is 2-0-2 versus the Kings, who they play twice, 2-0
against the Predators who they also play twice, and 3-0-1 versus
the Blackhawks who they play once.
</P>
<P>
   But Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg doesn't put much credence in
such numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been saying our games are like playoff games, and when
the playoffs start what you've done before doesn't matter,'' he
said. ``We don't talk about it, just like we didn't talk about how
we hadn't played well versus Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were 1-4 versus the Coyotes before they defeated them
4-3 in overtime on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   -Winger Marty McInnis returned to practice for the first time in
nearly three weeks. McInnis has missed nine consecutive games and
20 of the last 27 due to a groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked good, but we will see how he feels today,'' said
Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis scored 19 goals and 52 points last season when he was
valuable member of the No. 2 line and No. 1 power play unit.
McInnis has been limited to 57 games this season, scoring 10 goals
and 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   -After a lengthy practice on Tueday, most of the Ducks will
concentrate on off-ice conditioning today before returning to the
ice Thursday and Friday in preparation for Saturday's game versus
the Kings.
</P>
</TEXT>
