<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0860 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-OPEC-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-     03-29 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC AGREES TO INCREASE OIL PRODUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 18th graf starting: Wednesday's split comes, etc., to make it
read `production cuts' stead of `price cuts') 
 (See also OPEC-COST, OPEC-IMPACT) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ After two days of disputes, OPEC decided
Wednesday to increase oil production without the participation of
its second-largest producer, Iran. But the increase was not what
the United States had pressed for, and was not expected to bring
down gasoline prices any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare break in the solidarity of its ranks, the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries announced that nine of its members
would raise production by a total of 1.45 million barrels a day,
despite bitter opposition from Iran to any increase. The higher
production would begin next month.
</P>
<P>
   With Iran, the total would have been about 1.7 million barrels,
but analysts said the actual increase would end up at the higher
level because other OPEC members were likely to seize the
opportunity to cheat on their quotas to fill the gap left by Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had pressed for increases of up to 2.5 million
barrels a day to reduce gasoline prices, which have soared to more
than $1.60 a gallon in most cities. Iran's irritation at the
American pressures was apparently a major reason behind its
opposition to any increase.
</P>
<P>
   Experts estimated that it would take at least six to eight weeks
before any increase in oil production found its way to the gasoline
pumps, and with inventories already unusually low in the United
States as the summer driving season approaches, gasoline prices are
not expected to decline soon. In fact, some analysts predicted,
they would rise still more before easing by fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who expects to get back to gasoline at $1 or $1.20 a
gallon will be seriously disappointed,'' said Raad Alkadiri, an
analyst at Petroleum Finance Co., an industry research firm based
in Washington. ``Whatever happens, you're going to have a tight
gasoline market this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, however, was more optimistic and
said that several other oil-producing nations that do not belong to
OPEC would also increase output. ``I think our quiet diplomacy
worked,'' said Bill Richardson, the energy secretary, at a White
House briefing on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said that when all sources of production were taken
into account, ``we will be well above our objective.'' He and other
officials pointed out that prices were already down, to about $27 a
barrel from a high of $34 a barrel, in anticipation of more
production.
</P>
<P>
   In New York trading on Tuesday, crude oil for May delivery fell
70 cents, to $27.09 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual break in OPEC's ranks came after two days of
wrangling between Iran and Saudi Arabia, the largest producer,
which pushed for an increase in production. In the end, OPEC
announced that nine of its 11 members would go ahead and increase
their quotas. The production of Iraq, which says it now produces
2.4 million barrels a day, has been separately governed by U.N.
resolutions since the 1991 Persian Gulf war. Iraq said Tuesday
night that it planned to significantly increase its production by
the end of the year, but experts were skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   The fissure with Iran has major implications for the United
States. Indeed, the battle within OPEC was as much political as
economic, and much of the debate was over whether the group would
be capitulating to pressure from the United States for lower oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   It was OPEC's decision to cut production last year, joined by
several non-OPEC nations like Mexico and Norway, that sent oil and
gasoline prices soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's split could damage OPEC's discipline and
credibility, just as the organization seemed to have regained some
of the power it had in the 1970s and early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's oil minister, Bijan Namdar Zangeneh, accused the other
OPEC countries of trying to ram through decisions that were not
justified by economic conditions. ``OPEC is not an organization to
rubber-stamp the decisions already made,'' Zangeneh said in a short
but biting statement about 1 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to show our flexibility,'' he continued. ``OPEC needs
a spirit of compromise, which unfortunately we didn't trace at this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   If OPEC's discipline does come unhinged, the United States could
be a major beneficiary and see its bill for imported oil drop. In
the past, when OPEC failed to agree on production limits, prices
have plummeted as production soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC had a commendable record in the past year, and now one of
its founding members is not taking part in their agreement,'' said
Gary N. Ross, chief executive of PIRA Energy Group, an oil industry
research firm based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's split comes after a bitter test of wills between
Iran and Saudi Arabia, which was determined to reverse the
production cuts of last year and to allow the price of oil to
settle at about $25 a barrel, compared with about $27.50 today and
its recent high of $34 in early March.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi officials wanted to raise prices, partly because the
United States is its biggest market and partly because of concern
about political wrath from Congress, where some lawmakers have
pushed for legislation to block aid and sales of military equipment
to OPEC nations.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian leaders, on the other hand, had angrily denounced
American demands and insisted that OPEC should not make decisions
in response to political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Oil experts, as well as Saudi leaders, argued here that Iran was
already producing virtually all the oil it could pump, about 3
million barrels a day, and that any increase in production would
come from other countries _ Saudi Arabia in particular _ leading to
lower prices that could hurt Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia, with a daily output of 7.6 million barrels, has
enough spare capacity to flood world markets in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Saudi officials, alarmed when prices suddenly surged recently to
around $30 a barrel, adamantly demanded an increase in OPEC output
that would prevent worldwide shortages and stabilize prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been lobbying OPEC leaders
intensively for the last several weeks, arguing that the world
markets needed as much as 2.5 million extra barrels a day to meet
demand and to restore depleted inventories.
</P>
<P>
   It has been clear that OPEC would not go that far, but Saudi
Arabia had managed to persuade all other members except Iran to
reverse the cuts they had imposed on themselves last year. The
Saudi plan had called for an increase of 1.7 million OPEC barrels
of oil a day in production limits.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the agreement Wednesday morning, many OPEC leaders
were still fuming about what they viewed as heavy-handed pressure
from Washington that only made their own political situation more
awkward.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan leaders, taking a cue from their outspoken president,
Hugo Chavez, have been particularly sensitive about being portrayed
as puppets of the American government, and went out of their way
last week to criticize lobbying efforts by Richardson, the energy
secretary. Venezuela is one of the top suppliers of crude oil to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Iranian officials almost gleefully pounced on the
issue of American pressure when Richardson reportedly called the
oil minister of Qatar, another OPEC member, just as he was meeting
with his counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Though modest, the proposed increases are still significant.
Indeed, oil prices have already drifted down about 18 percent since
March 8, to about $28 a barrel from $34, and most of that decline
reflected the anticipation that OPEC would agree on an increase of
roughly that magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi officials have made it clear that they would like to see
the price of oil settle at around $25 a barrel, a price they
believe could be sustained and would allow the United States and
other major oil-consuming countries to rebuild their badly depleted
inventories.
</P>
<P>
   But the increase would also fall well short of what the Saudis
envisioned. Experts said it would provide only a modest relief in
gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Rilwanu Lukman, secretary general of OPEC, tried to put the best
possible face on Wednesday's split, noting that countries have on
occasion dissented from the organization's decisions before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will remain as a group despite all of these tensions,'' he
said after Iran announced that it would not join in the agreement.
``Many people wrote off OPEC many years ago, and we're still
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 0105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OPEC-NYT &LR;      03-29 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OPEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OPENING THE OIL SPIGOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 29:
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries to increase its oil production by 1.45 million barrels a
day is welcome and may, over time, lead to lower American gasoline
prices. The action, which Iran, an OPEC member, unexpectedly
refused to take part in, restores just over a third of production
cut by the cartel over the past two years. But it should not be
seen as a definitive answer to the recent sharp rise in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Those prices reached a peak of $34 a barrel in early March, more
than three times what they had been a year earlier. But those 1999
prices were artificially depressed _ lower, once inflation is
accounted for, than at any time since the 1970s. A rebound to more
realistic levels was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC's power is not what it once was. Its 11 member countries
now account for less than 40 percent of world oil production, down
from more than 50 percent in 1974. Internal discipline is weak,
with many countries cheating on their production quotas to earn
extra revenue. Even before the OPEC meeting, prices had dropped by
almost 20 percent, to about $28 a barrel. Raising production should
bring further price declines.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's OPEC decision came in response to strong American
pressure. Aside from Iran, most other OPEC countries preferred not
to risk being cast as villains in American political debate if oil
prices remain high. Many of these countries also recognize that
their own self-interest calls for moderation to protect the
economies of major oil-consuming nations.
</P>
<P>
   Washington had sought a larger production boost, of at least two
million barrels a day. But the Vienna decision is constructive and
will take significant pressure off world oil prices, which may now
stabilize around $25 a barrel. Gasoline prices, which reflect low
inventories as well as expensive oil, will probably stay high for a
few more months. But their inflationary impact on the American
economy is likely to be relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   After the oil shocks of the 1970's and early 1980's, the United
States and other industrial countries undertook significant energy
conservation measures, like raising automobile fuel economy
standards. They also intensified efforts to discover and exploit
new energy sources, including non-OPEC oil. With oil prices as low
as they have been in recent years, conservation measures have
lagged and the search for new supplies has slowed. By reviving
these efforts, America can gain some protection against future oil
price increases. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 0105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ELIAN-NYT &LR;      03-29 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ELIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE IMPASSE OVER ELIAN GONZALEZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 29:
</P>
<P>
   Everyone involved in the Elian Gonzalez case needs to pull back
from the nasty confrontation that now looms so this matter can be
resolved without disorder or further harm to young Elian. The Miami
relatives who have been caring for him since he was rescued off the
Florida coast last November must firmly commit themselves to
accepting his return to his father in Cuba if their court appeals
are rejected. The Justice Department, which is right to seek his
repatriation, should lift its threat to remove the boy from Miami
this week, and the Cuban-American community in south Florida ought
to cease its disruptive efforts to block Elian's return and to make
him into a political symbol.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has made every effort to resolve the case
in a fair and calm manner. The relatives have had the opportunity
to challenge in federal court Attorney General Janet Reno's
decision that Elian must be returned to his father, who has sole
authority to speak for his son. Last week Federal District Judge
Michael Moore correctly ruled that Reno's decision was proper and
dismissed the relatives' legal case. That ruling affirmed the
Justice Department's authority to carry out its intent to reunite
Elian with his father.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said last week that it would not
terminate the temporary custody of the Miami relatives if they
wanted to seek an expedited appeal of Moore's ruling. But that
offer was made on the reasonable condition that the relatives issue
a written promise to turn the child over to the Immigration and
Naturalization Service if the appeal fails.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives have so far refused to do so, a sign that they are
not interested in abiding by the appeals court decision. They seem
intent on prolonging this wrenching process, perhaps hoping that
anti-Castro sentiment in Miami will make it politically impossible
for the INS to retrieve the child. Or they may be expecting
Congress in an election year to provide them a legislative way to
prevent Elian's return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's impatience with the relatives is
understandable, but the answer for now is not to threaten to
terminate the relatives' temporary care of Elian immediately. The
government may eventually have no choice but to enforce
repatriation, but removing Elian from his relatives' care without
their cooperation would clearly be the least desirable way to
return him to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Responsible voices in the Cuban-American community need to step
forward to mediate the situation. In due time the appeals process
will run its course. The federal appeals court has set oral
arguments in the case for the week of May 8. The Miami relatives
may have come to love Elian, but they cannot stand outside the law
and break the bond between a young child and his parent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 0109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      03-29 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COMMON SENSE PREVAILS ON THE MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 29:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's decision to end his campaign to evict
the Brooklyn Museum from its premises, cut its funding and remove
its board of trustees is a sensible bow to First Amendment
principles. The agreement between the mayor and the museum ends six
months of legal wrangling over the staging of ``Sensation,'' the
exhibition that included Chris Ofili's notorious dung-adorned
painting of the Madonna. The Brooklyn Museum can now go about
mounting shows that will stimulate, and perhaps offend, visitors
instead of defending in court its right to do so. The mayor can
praise or criticize or ignore those exhibitions as he sees fit,
without tying up the courts with fruitless litigation that runs
headlong into the First Amendment's guarantees of free expression.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been far too quick to use governmental powers in an
attempt to censor artistic expression or restrict political
demonstrations. As two justices for the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the Second Circuit noted this week, this administration's policies
have resulted in ``a heavy stream of First Amendment litigation,''
litigation that has not, as a rule, gone well for New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over ``Sensation'' was marked by rancor reminiscent
of earlier national battles over contemporary art financed by the
National Endowment for the Arts. With the exhibit now over, City
Hall professes to be pleased with a settlement that ends the
hostilities. But the Brooklyn Museum clearly emerged the winner.
The city's monthly payments to the museum will be restored. The
museum will be given $5.8 million for capital improvements. And it
will be protected from future retaliation by a provision that
prevents Giuliani from imposing any funding cuts that are
disproportionately larger than those affecting other major
city-supported museums.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the free-speech issues, the battle over
``Sensation'' raised troubling questions about the role of private
companies and individuals in financing a museum exhibit from which
they might profit commercially. These practices, which are said to
be common at many institutions, need to be addressed by leaders of
the museum world now that the furor over ``Sensation'' has ended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
