<HEADLINE>
ASSESSMENT TEAM BLAMES ALL INVOLVED WITH MARS POLAR LANDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff writer Usha Sutliff contributed to this report) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The loss of the $165 million Mars Polar Lander was
most likely caused by a premature engine shutdown, which sent the
spacecraft crashing into the planet's surface at about 50 mph,
NASA-commissioned investigators said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Program Assessment Team found fault with all key
players in the failed mission, including NASA, the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena, which managed the effort; and Denver-based
Lockheed Martin Astronautics, which built the spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited poor communication among the three parties and
inadequate testing of systems. It also said tight NASA budgets and
time constraints contributed to the doom of the Mars Polar Lander
and the $29 million Deep Space 2 probes it was to have deployed on
Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The report also laid down the law for future Mars efforts by
stating: ``If not ready, do not launch.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration, JPL and
Lockheed officials pledged to make needed reforms and NASA
announced it was delaying the 2001 launch of another Mars lander.
The 2001 launch of a Mars orbiter will go on as planned. A NASA
official also said the agency would increase funding for needed
testing and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the report will be well-received,'' said JPL's John
Casani, who served on the assessment team.
</P>
<P>
   He said JPL is already implementing recommended organizational
changes, including the establishment of a separate management
office for Mars programs. Previous Mars efforts were managed by an
office that also oversees a number of unrelated JPL space programs.
</P>
<P>
   Casani, who retired in August as JPL's chief engineer and
returned as a consultant, said he was pleased with NASA's pledge of
more funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more funding or fewer programs, one or the other,''
Casani said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the Mars Polar Lander was 131 miles
above the Red Planet when it deployed its three landing legs as
planned. However, the deployment sent a false signal to the
engines, indicating the spacecraf
</P>
</TEXT>
