<SLUG> BC-EDIT-YOSEMITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: YOSEMITE'S NEW LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 29:
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when California's Merced River jumped its banks
in Yosemite National Park _ uprooting cabins, burying parking lots
under mud and rock and generally making a mess of things _ federal
officials took it as a sign that the time had come to strike a
better balance between man and nature. There was human overload
everywhere _ four million visitors a year, shops and restaurants
jammed into the Yosemite Valley flood plain, a stream of cars,
trucks and recreational vehicles that not only fouled the air but
made the mile-long trip through Yosemite Village seem like rush
hour in Manhattan. On some days visibility was bad enough to
obscure the towering rock formations that rise from the valley
floor and the long waterfalls that seem to descend from the
heavens.
</P>
<P>
   The flood gave officials a chance to refine a long-mothballed
plan to reduce pollution and overcrowding in the park, and on
Monday, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt unveiled the results. The
new plan would tear out many parking lots and roads in the eastern,
more scenic parts of the valley, as well as three bridges and the
Cascades Dam, which interrupts the Merced River's flow. It would
also demolish various commercial and administrative buildings. The
parking lots would be replaced with three new lots at the western
edge of the park from which visitors would be bused into the
valley.
</P>
<P>
   Although some environmentalists said the plan did not go far
enough, it can be improved during the public hearing process in the
months ahead, perhaps reducing automobile traffic still further by
eliminating more parking inside the valley. But even in its present
form it represents a big step forward. The Merced will begin to
look more natural, asphalt will give way to meadows, and the park's
wildlife will have more room to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   The plan could also serve as a model for other national parks,
many in varying stages of decay. A disastrous flood provided the
opportunity to set things right in Yosemite. But Congress, which
has consistently underfinanced park maintenance, should not await
further calamities to begin restoring the system as a whole to good
health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
