<SLUG> BC-CARTOONS-PBSPROTEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTOONISTS BLAME CANADA, PBS FOR LOST JOBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Watching Canadian-drawn cartoons on U.S.
taxpayer-supported TV is no laughing matter for local cartoonists,
who plan to picket Los Angeles' PBS affiliate KCET on April 13.
</P>
<P>
   The protest is the latest step in a campaign the cartoonists
union launched last fall to urge PBS not to send millions of
dollars worth of work to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing when private companies do this. But when it's
American tax dollars, we have a problem,'' said Steve Hulett,
business manager for the North Hollywood-based Motion Picture
Screen Cartoonists Local 839 IATSE. Hulett said he expected at
least 200 cartoonists, both union and nonunion, to take part in the
picketing from 11:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m. in front of KCET's Hollywood
office on Sunset Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   A KCET spokeswoman referred all questions on the subject to PBS
headquarters in Alexandria, Va. ``This is a PBS issue. We happen to
be the local PBS affiliate, and that makes us handy,'' said the
spokeswoman, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Epstein, director of communications for PBS, disputed the
union's ``implication ... that federal dollars are going to
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Epstein said no public money is going into the cartoon programs,
which are produced by Montreal-based Cinar Films and Toronto-based
Nelvana Entertainment. Epstein said about 16 percent of PBS's
annual budget of roughly $350 million comes in the form of public
funds from the Corporation for Public Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein said CPB funds are used at the discretion of PBS, and
currently are being used to acquire several American-produced shows
from such companies as Burbank-based DIC Entertainment and
Scholastic Productions.
</P>
<P>
   Cinar produces PBS' top-rated ``Arthur,'' along with ``Wimzie's
House'' and ``Zaboomafoo.'' Hulett says PBS is a partner in the
production of these shows; PBS spokesman Tom Epstein counters that
PBS is prohibited by its charter from producing.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he said, Boston PBS station WGBH - which has produced or
co-produced many of PBS' most popular shows - is the co-producer of
``Arthur.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelvana signed a multiyear agreement last year to produce PBS'
first-ever Saturday morning children's programming block. Hulett
said Nelvana touted PBS' commitment as being $40 million; Epstein
said PBS' contribution was actually a fraction of that amount, but
that the exact figure was proprietary.
</P>
<P>
   Although they generally get less money up front by selling shows
to PBS rather than commercial outlets, many kids-show producers
consider a berth on PBS to be prime real estate. Programs are
uninterrupted by commercials, get a ``halo effect'' from the
educational reputation of PBS and, in the case of a handful of
programs, including ``Arthur,'' get more viewers than any other
kids TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing this fact and seeing another potential revenue
stream, PBS in the past few years has been seeking and getting a
small cut of licensing revenues tied to kids shows.
</P>
<P>
   Hulett said the protest ties into the larger issue of runaway
production. ``Animation has never been more popular,'' Hulett said,
``but at the same time, we've had more layoffs over the past 20 to
24 months than in the past nine years. Disney, DreamWorks, Fox -
they've all had layoffs. There's been a huge downsizing of staffs.
... We have 25 percent to 35 percent unemployment now. Companies
are looking to do it faster and cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Even U.S.-based companies, Hulett said, have been sending much
of their work overseas for the past couple of decades. ``Yes, even
if shows are produced in the U.S., they're going to be sent to
Asian subcontractors after the scripts, the storyboards and the key
art is done here,'' Hulett said. ``But I think there is a public
trust that PBS is violating by not dealing with American
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulett said he had been told by American animation producers
that ``they can't get PBS to return their calls.'' Epstein insisted
that PBS is constantly on the lookout for good programs from all
sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seek the best ideas. Our mission is to acquire and
distribute the finest quality children's programming we can find.
We make every effort to do that, and we think our record speaks for
itself,'' said Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein added that the ``lion's share'' of PBS programs are
produced by American companies, and that four new animated programs
that have recently debuted or will debut by next year are
U.S.-produced. He added that PBS' new head of children's
programming, Patricia Nugent, will be encouraged to travel to Los
Angeles to meet with domestic producers.
</P>
<P>
   Over PBS' most recent three-year fiscal period, only about 4
percent of all shows were produced in Canada, Epstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Hulett said that isn't good enough: ``Come on. Don't say it's
only 4 percent. ... Why isn't it zero?''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the cartoonists have succeeded in raising some
awareness on the issue, on the part of both viewers and PBS. A PBS
source, who asked to remain anonymous, said: ``Honestly, I don't
think we ever thought about whether (public money) was going into
acquiring Canadian shows. Now, I think we'll be more aware of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
