<HEADLINE>
MARK STUART, 80, COLUMNIST IN NEW JERSEY 
HENRY W. MCGEE SR., 90, CHICAGO POSTMASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Stuart, a longtime newspaper columnist and editor at The
Record in Hackensack, N.J., and The Paterson Morning Call, died
March 24 at the Valley Hospital in Ridgewood, N.J. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pneumonia complicated by Parkinson's disease, said
his wife, Melba, from their home in Rivervale, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart wrote a general interest column called ``Marking Time,''
which he began in 1968 at The Morning Call, where he was city
editor, and then wrote for 17 years at The Record, where he was
assistant editorial page editor. After retiring in 1989, he
continued to write it for the weekly Ridgewood News.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation from the City College of New York in 1947, he
was editor of a Manhattan weekly, The West Side News. Recognizing
the potential for readers in the developments of Stuyvesant Town
and Peter Cooper Village, which were then attracting returning
veterans, he persuaded his publisher, Charles Hagedorn, to start a
new weekly, Town and Village, and served as it first editor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a daughter, Jane, of
New York City; a son, Thomas, of Washingtonville, N.Y.; and two
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Henry W. McGee Sr., the first black postmaster in Chicago, died
on March 18 at his home in Chicago. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   McGee became postmaster in 1966 and retired in 1973. He began
his career at the post office as a temporary substitute clerk in
1929 and became a full-time clerk in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Wadsworth McGee Sr. was born on Feb. 7, 1910, in
Hillsboro, Texas. He attended the Illinois Institute of Technology
and received a master's degree in public administration from the
University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, he was president of the Chicago chapter of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People. In the
1970s, he served on the Chicago Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   McGee is survived by a son, Henry W. Jr., of Seattle; two
daughters, Sylvia E. Morrison and Marguerite Porterfield, both of
Chicago; eight grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
