<HEADLINE>
TORNADOES, RAIN WREAK HAVOC ON FORT WORTH GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J CHRIS ROSELIUS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Hundreds of Fort Worth area athletes were
prepared to hit the baseball, softball and soccer fields Tuesday
night. But instead of looking for victories, players, coaches and
fans searched for shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took our kids and the kids from Trinity and the parents and
loaded up the buses,'' Richland High School baseball coach Brian
Master said. ``We went up and took shelter in the basement at
Richland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around 6 p.m., we had a pretty steady and hard rain. At 6:30
p.m., we had the tornado siren go off. We started getting hail,
pea-size and quarter-sized hail.''
</P>
<P>
   Players, coaches and parents from both Richland and Trinity High
School also took shelter in the concession stands and bathrooms,
Master said. At 6:45 p.m., a second tornado siren sounded.
Listening to a radio report, Master said he heard a report that a
tornado had been sighted near I-35 and Loop 820.
</P>
<P>
   Haltom High School coach Randy Porter never even made it out of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around 6 p.m., it started hailing,'' Porter said. ``Then, it
got real still, the sky looked green. From what we could see toward
Fort Worth, it wasn't pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Haltom softball team was scheduled to face Irving High
School at Buffalo Ridge Park. Instead, the girls were forced to
take shelter in the concession stands.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Catholic baseball coach Art Senato said he saw first-hand
the storm that forced everyone to run for cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got pounded,'' Senato said. ``We detected lightning with
the lightning meters,'' Senato said. ''Just as we got off the
field, the (tornado) sirens went off. I watched the tornado come
right by the school, down I-30.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Catholic was leading Dallas St. Mark's, 6-0, in the fourth
inning before the storm blew through. The game was suspended and
Senato said the game will likely be made up in a doubleheader in
April.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to a game against MacArthur High School in Irving,
Richland softball coach Mike Fielder received the news about the
approaching storm. Seeking safety, Fielder stopped at a local
Braum's and asked the manager if his girls could take refuge in the
freezer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it wasn't very safe to be on the bus,'' Fielder said.
``We looked for a brick building, someplace safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm and the threat of harm wiped out many of last night's
scheduled contests, including several key soccer games. The girls
Class 4A Region II semifinal game between Highland Park and Crowley
was postponed until 7 p.m. tonight at Highland Park. The Coppell
boys Class 4A Region II semifinal game against Dallas Wilson has
been rescheduled for 7:30 p.m. tonight at Cedar Hill High School.
</P>
<P>
   The Class 4A Region II boys semifinal match between Carroll and
Mesquite Poteet at UT-Dallas in Richardson has been rescheduled for
7 p.m. tonight. The Richland-McKinney Class 5A Region I
quarterfinal game scheduled for 7:30 p.m. last night at Wildcat-Ram
Stadium is tentatively scheduled for 7:30 p.m. tonight at Goldsmith
Stadium in Lewisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just saw a lot of lightning and rain,'' Richland boys
soccer coach Mark McCanlies said. ``With the threat of tornado
activity, we were packed under the stadium like sardines.''
</P>
<P>
   Left in the storm's wake was broken glass, downed trees and
power lines and debris on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going across downed power lines and four 18-wheelers
were tipped over,'' Country Day softball coach Don Hicks said. ``It
was a mess. There was a Porta Potti splattered on I-20. We were
underneath the overpass at Highway 360 and I-20 and our bus was
getting hit by softball-sized hale. We were in that situation for
about five to seven minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm left Dunbar softball coach Alvin Selmon with a lasting
memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew something was wrong when we were on the bus and I heard
the dispatcher sounding really excited,'' Selmon said. ``Then I
heard her telling all the bus drivers to get off the streets. That
made me feel uneasy. By the time we got back to the gym, it was
raining buckets, but we felt safe there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the (Dunbar) gym, and it was just raining so hard
... the phones were out and the electricity went out twice,''
Selmon continued. ``After it stopped raining, we looked outside and
we could still see the clouds swirling and we watched it move
through Arlington and southeast Fort Worth at about 7:30 or 8 p.m.
I'm from out in West Texas by Lubbock, so I was used to seeing
stuff like this, but seeing it happen here in Fort Worth was
something that I won't forget.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
