u s BC-BKC-NIT &LR;      03-29 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NIT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME ROLLS TO MEET WAKE FOREST IN THE FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Notre Dame was out to prove that it belonged in
the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament, the Irish
did it on Tuesday night with a convincing 73-52 victory over Penn
State in the semifinals of the National Invitation Tournament at
Madison Square Garden before 14,268.
</P>
<P>
   This was a victory with an exclamation point, as the Fighting
Irish (22-14) jumped on Penn State early and never let up. Before
the Nittany Lions (18-16) could get into any kind of rhythm, they
were fighting for their lives. Midway through the second half, they
were trailing by 56-36 and playing a desperate game of catch-up.
Penn State never caught up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When seven different people score the first few points of the
game, that says something,'' the Notre Dame sophomore forward David
Graves said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fighting Irish will play Wake Forest, which defeated North
Carolina State, 62-59, in overtime in the first semifinal, for the
championship on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was also a showcase for the Notre Dame sophomore
forward Troy Murphy, who averages 22.9 points and 10.5 rebounds a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the Nittany Lions seemed intent on keeping Murphy from
making the Garden his playground. Every time Murphy touched the
ball, two Penn State defenders would collapse on him. He finished
with 18 points and 8 rebounds before leaving with 1 minute 36
seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penn State couldn't just concentrate on one person,'' Murphy
said. ``I think we showed that we can spread it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame point guard Jimmy Dillon twisted his ankle with 6:56
left to play and had to be helped from the game. The injury could
loom as a problem against Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I would have put him back out there even if it
had been a close game,'' Notre Dame Coach Matt Doherty said. ``I'm
really concerned about him. I think he's going to have to sleep
with a bag of ice on it and we'll have to see on tomorrow and
Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions were led by guard Joe Crispin, who had 16
points, and forward Jarrett Stephens, who had 11 points and 9
rebounds. Penn State dug a deep hole for itself in the first half
and couldn't climb out. Notre Dame kept dropping in 3-pointers,
hitting 5 of 11 3-point attempts in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good news-bad news kind of night for Penn State. The
good news was that Murphy, the Big East player of the year, only
scored 8 points in the first half. The bad news was that his
teammates didn't need much help from him.
</P>
<P>
   Crispin, of Pitman, N.J., tried to keep things close in the
first half. He contributed greatly on during an 8-0 run during a
crucial stretch in the first half, helping trim Notre Dame's 23-11
lead to 23-19. During that run, Crispin hit a 3-pointer and dished
out two assists. After a layup by Stephens with 2:28 to play in the
first half made it 27-23, Notre Dame went on an 11-0 run to close
out the half and go to the locker room with a secure 38-23 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me I'm never comfortable until there's 30 seconds to go and
we're up by 20 points,'' Doherty said.
</P>
<P>
   In the other semifinal game, North Carolina State shot 20
percent from the field against Wake Forest before waking up in the
second half and giving the Demon Deacons a game. It was a wildly
swinging affair with nine ties and six lead changes in regulation
before Wake Forest (21-14) prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest forward Darius Songaila, who led the Demon Deacons
with 18 points, scored 8 points over the last 1:38 of overtime _
all of his teams points in that stretch _ to help seal the victory.
Songaila's slicing layup with 58 seconds to play gave Wake Forest a
58-56 lead. Then Songaila finished things off on the free-throw
line, making all four of his attempts after getting fouled twice
with less than minute to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the points were going to come hard tonight and they
came to easy early,'' Wake Forest Coach Dave Odom said. ``That gave
us a false sense of security. That was an old fashioned ACC Tobacco
Road game. I knew it was going to happen. Herb Sendek knew it was
going to happen. Both teams played with great will and great
passion. We just hit a few more free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had a chance to win the game in regulation. North
Carolina State guard Justin Gainey went to the free-throw line for
two shots with the Demon Deacons trailing by 51-50 and just eight
seconds to play after being fouled on a driving layup by Wake
Forest guard Josh Howard. Gainey made the first free throw and
missed the second. Wake Forest got the rebound from the second
missed shot, but time expired before the Demon Deacons could get a
shot off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
