<HEADER>
A0885 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-MAGIC-BOS     03-29 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-MAGIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS IN SUSPENDED ANIMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Heads, apparently, are going to roll.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of the Celtics' blowout loss Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night to the
Orlando Magic, coach Rick Pitino said he was so appalled at his
team's behavior during the game that he would announce ``major
suspensions'' Wednesday. The 122-87 defeat, the Celtics' worst of
the season, pretty much ended their playoff hopes, but that was not
what bothered Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   He said behavior during the second half, in timeouts and on the
bench, led him to his decision. He did not name names, but
observers close to the Celtics bench said the coach exchanged words
with Danny Fortson when Fortson was taken out of the game. In
addition, Antoine Walker was said to be jawing with reserve guard
Doug Overton.
</P>
<P>
   The coach said the suspensions could last for anywhere from a
couple of games to the final 11 games of the season. He said he
would ``sleep on it'' before making a final determination. He also
said the behavior might lead him to overhaul the team again at the
end of the season. The coach publicly has praised his players all
year for having excellent chemistry and togetherness, but he noted
what happened Tuesday night was not an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very upset. It will never happen again,'' Pitino said.
``It's extremely unprofessional, very un-Celticlike. These guys
have been good. Unfortunately, they're going to pay dearly for
this. I told them in all my years of coaching, I've never seen as
unprofessional an attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for specifics, Pitino said there was too much
finger-pointing, blaming one another, and ``picking on the weak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yelling, finger-pointing, childish behavior,'' he went on.
``Things you'd never see from a professional athlete. I've never
seen it from a Bernard King. You can't be a Celtic and have that.
It has nothing to do with frustrations. You don't do that. You
can't do that as a pro. We'll nip it in the bud. It will never
happen as long as I live.''
</P>
<P>
   It all happened as the Celtics were getting outscored, 72-35, in
the second half, including an astonishing 40-11 in the third
quarter. Walker sat out the final 14 minutes of the game after a
2-for-11, 5-point performance. Fortson played 12 minutes and,
amazingly, did not collect a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen crazier stuff,'' said Celtics cocaptain Dana Barros.
``But at this point, it's hard to swallow. You realize your season
may be slipping away, and doing things like that might come to
mind. But you just don't do it. We've all been through it. It's the
sign of an immature team. You can't have that as a team. It's
disturbing the privacy of a family. It wasn't the first time, and
it probably won't be the last time. But you can't have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker was fined last season for an on-court squabble with Kenny
Anderson in Washington. Pitino also left Anderson at home for a
game last season after another conflict. This, however, clearly was
worse than either of those incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really, really upsetting,'' Pitino said. ``Very
upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who in the first half was talking trash with Darrell
Armstrong, downplayed the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 71 games into the season,'' Walker said. ``Guys are
emotional. Guys want to win. Guys want to play hard. Situations
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is a professional athlete here. Everything is not
going to be picture perfect, the way you want it to be. But
everybody on this team is still great friends and good friends with
each other. It's just frustration from the game, when things aren't
going well. You played well in the first half and it doesn't go
well in the second half. Frustration sets in. We've got to regroup.
It's good we don't play a game until Friday. We've got to regroup
and catch ourselves, get back together, and put some wins
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by what Walker's coach said, it might be a different
look Friday night. It may be too late to salvage the season, but
Pitino obviously believes it's never too late to try to salvage a
club's reputation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
