<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINBALL-RECORD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN FINISHES 23-DAY PINBALL MARATHON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Canoga Park, Calif.) _ Pinball wizards around the globe,
beware!
</P>
<P>
   Mandi Martin, known for her supple wrists and iron will,
finished a marathon 23 days of consecutive pinball play Tuesday to
surpass her old mark and set a new world record that even Tommy
from The Who's rock opera would envy.
</P>
<P>
   And she finished her 555 hours, 55 minutes and 55 seconds in
signature over-the-top style.
</P>
<P>
   For the final ball-smashing, point-racking fun, Martin took her
show on the road, playing an antique machine aboard a flatbed truck
in a victorious motorcade through the streets of the San Fernando
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the support of great friends, you can do anything if you
want it bad enough,'' the Canoga Park woman told a crowd of about
30, mostly friends from her team of witnesses. ``This is a dream
come true to me, and I couldn't have done it without you all.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she felt confident her reign as world pinball champion
was untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now I'm not even thinking about trying to raise the stakes
again,'' she said. ``I feel like I could do it again, but for now I
just want to celebrate by eating some sushi and sleeping it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Renee DePalma, an independent film maker, is filming a
documentary about Martin, who is now working on a book about her
life and is scheduled to hit the nationwide talk show circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the past month, many took time off from work and
other activities to motivate Martin, massage her, feed her and lend
her moral support as she played a perpetual game of pinball in her
Canoga Park home.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Martin and her following planned a big finale
outside a Valley coffee shop.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a dark fur coat and donning a New Year's tiara, the
local pinball queen was flanked by witnesses and followed by a
caravan of horn-tooting cars. At the front was a Ford pickup truck,
modified to look like a steam locomotive and driven by members of
the American Legion's 18th District.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, curious motorists honked horns in what could have
either been interpreted as support or annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Residents came out of their homes in pajamas and robes to wave
to the early-hour caravan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just amazing what she's doing,'' said Barry Katz,
a friend of Martin's who volunteered to do a couple of graveyard
shifts as a witness. ``She's got a heck of a lot of stamina. When I
was just trying to stay awake, she just kept playing away.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dazzling display of pinball prowess, Martin has played
around the clock at her home since Mar. 5, with less than two hours
rest each day and sworn witnesses at all times in accordance with
rules set by The Guinness Book of Records.
</P>
<P>
   The final mark of 555 hours, 55 minutes and 55 seconds was
achieved at a celebration in the parking lot in front of the Coffee
Junction in Tarzana.
</P>
<P>
   A singer and songwriter by profession, Martin said she decided
to upgrade her record at the urging of friends as a way to mark her
55th birthday last week and deal with the passing of her husband,
Jerry Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has held the previous world record of 505 hours of play
since 1979, seriously challenged only by a pair of spunky Brits who
reached 216 hours, according to Guinness spokesman Neil Hayes in
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a category that is often challenged,'' Hayes said.
``Ms. Martin's record is quite impressive, and of course we'll have
to verify her latest feat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes said other unusual categories recently called in by
would-be record setters include the world's biggest umbrella and
the world's biggest pencil collection.
</P>
<P>
   The oddest record Hayes could recall was a political party in
Brazil that reported the most votes ever tallied for a political
office by a nonhuman species. They reported 4,000 votes collected
for a monkey on a local campaign ticket with the slogan ``Vote
monkey, get monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   What might set Martin apart from other record seekers is that
she was after more than just fame. She took advantage of the
occasion to call for donations to some local charities that support
families who lose a loved one, including the Chad Aitken Foundation
and Haven Hills, a domestic violence prevention group.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
