<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-PACERS-NYT &LR;      03-29 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS TOP PACERS, 111-106 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ As yet another seemingly insurmountable
lead sank like a barbell in the ocean on Tuesday night, many of the
17,676 New Jersey Nets fans looked on in stunned disbelief,
wondering what type of curse must hover over their woebegone team.
</P>
<P>
   After more than three quarters of brilliant basketball, of
spectacular alley-oops and feverish defense against the premier
team in the Eastern Conference, the Nets were crumbling again.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers, mimicking the Denver Nuggets of two days
before, began chopping at the Nets' advantage with frightening
effectiveness and speed. In five minutes, the Nets' 21-point
fourth-quarter lead was down to 8. Fifty-nine seconds later, it was
5. Less than two minutes after that, the teams were separated by
only 1 point.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who blew an 18-point lead late in the game in a loss
to Denver on Sunday, looked as if they would pull a repeat.
</P>
<P>
   But this time Coach Don Casey's embattled unit was able to fight
off defeat, if only slightly. Despite being outscored by 36-20 over
the final 11 minutes, the Nets beat the Pacers, 111-106, and saved
themselves from the indignity of monumental collapses in
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank god we took care of business because if we had lost this
one, I don't know if anybody would have come to the game Thursday
night,'' Kendall Gill said. ``There was big-time panic. I felt a
sense of urgency on my part because this had happened the previous
game. And you could hear the fans talking about, `Ahh, we can't do
this again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gill could hear the fans clearly because he was on the bench for
much of the Pacers' run. After scoring 15 of his 17 points in the
third quarter and playing stifling defense against the Pacers'
Jalen Rose to help the Nets turn a 5-point halftime advantage into
an 85-70 lead heading into the fourth quarter, Gill was taken out
of the game with 10 minutes 8 seconds remaining and the Nets ahead,
91-72.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, the Pacers, who were without Reggie Miller
because the star shooting guard was ejected for hollering at the
officials with 11:57 left in the game, began to charge. As the lead
dwindled and Gill watched, the game took on the eerie feel of
Sunday's debacle in which Casey sat Gill, one of the league's best
perimeter defenders, for the entire fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, with the injured Jayson Williams and numerous
fans screaming and pointing for Gill to be put on the floor, Casey
reinserted him with 6:09 left. By that time, a 13-2 Indiana run had
trimmed the Nets' lead to 93-85.
</P>
<P>
   When Gill returned, Rose, who had scored only 10 points on
5-of-14 shooting through the first three quarters, was rolling and
not even the Nets' best defender could stop him. The Pacers' small
forward scored 7 of his 27 points in less than three minutes and
pulled Indiana within 97-96 on a short jumper with 3:49 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understood that they were going to make a run,'' Keith Van
Horn said. ``They're a quality veteran team that has won a lot of
games, so I just tried to keep my composure, keep the fire under
the team, and fight back and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn had a monstrous game, matching a season high with 30
points and 10 rebounds. He scored 5 points and made a steal down
the stretch to help the Nets avoid defeat. With 2:16 to play, he
hit a 3-pointer that made it 104-99, and the Pacers never got
closer than 3 points again.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury, who shook off a head cold to contribute 28
points and 10 assists, was also big in the clutch, scoring 6 points
in the final three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which improved the Nets to 30-40, did little to
bolster their scant postseason hopes since Orlando, holder of the
East's eighth and final playoff spot with a 36-36 record, routed
Boston on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   That reality led Gill to admit being somewhat disturbed with
Tuesday night's Nets performance, which above all was just another
example of their season-long pattern of losing games to lesser
teams, like Denver, and playing well against members of the
league's elite, like Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real disappointing because we beat this team, but we
can't take care of Denver,'' Gill said. ``That's where we have to
grow. We're like Jekyll and Hyde.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
