<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CELLPHONE-BACKLASH-LA     03-29 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONE-BACKLASH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLULAR PHONES FEED OUT HANG_UPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff Writer Robert Monroe contributed to this report) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hold those calls!
</P>
<P>
   On the leading edge of a cellular phone backlash, Los Angeles
County supervisors voted Tuesday to silence cell phones in their
board room, joining churches, colleges, theaters and restaurants
that are sick of the incessant chirping, beeping and ringing.
</P>
<P>
   Movie theaters now run warnings against cell phone use, some
restaurants have cell phone sections, and one London anti-cell
phone group has gone as far as smashing people's phones and
displaying its exploits on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It has even been suggested that motorists caught with cell phone
in hand be charged with driving under the affluence.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, exasperated supervisors said the ringing and
chatting has been drowning out their meetings, so they voted
unanimously to require cell phones and pagers to be set on vibrate
mode or be turned off.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many people with cell phones today, they should give
us the courtesy to turn them off during the hearing,'' said
Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite Burke, who sponsored the motion. It
will only get worse. The number of people with wireless telephones
has gone from 283,600 in 1985 to 76 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   While cell phone abuse irritates some people, many are finding
these devices of convenience and security really are modern torture
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get away from people,'' said Ken Sereno, associate
professor of communications at the Annenberg School of
Communications at the University of Southern California. ``I feel
that way. That's why I'm reluctant to give people my cell phone
number. I think that supports the idea that it's intrusive and
prevents you from getting away.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sereno said cell phones have many obvious advantages,
among them giving ready access to 911.
</P>
<P>
   Don Slater, a Kirkland, Wash., resident in Los Angeles on
business, uses a cellular phone but only when he has to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in a meeting, they're just annoying,'' the
53-year-old said. ``I don't consider anything in life so important
that I need my cell phone on all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   He might be the exception to the rule, however. In many ways,
cell phone abuse is a symptom of a technology moving too quickly
for society's rules of etiquette and civility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much communications happening too quickly,'' said A.
Michael Noll, a USC communications professor.
</P>
<P>
   Like cowboys of the Old West, Noll said, it could get to the
point where ``we have to park our guns outside. Only instead of a
gun rack, people will park their cell phones in a cell phone
rack.''
</P>
<P>
   Many cell phones have vibrating modes, but that can be a
problem, particularly for women who don't wear their phone on their
belt.
</P>
<P>
   A Pacific Bell Wireless spokesman said the vibrating mode and
voice mail are designed specifically to defuse some of the
complaints now surfacing about cell phone abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage our customers to use the technology and features
of their phones to enhance convenience, safety and courtesy when
using the phones in public,'' said Brian Brokowski, a PacBell
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Some cell phone users apparently don't care about their
intrusion, and some might even enjoy it, according to one expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called Self-Imposed Importance, or SIP,'' said Nancy
Friedman, president of Telephone Doctor, a St. Louis, Mo.-based
training company specializing in customer service and telephone
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little disease that people get. It says, 'Hello, I'm
important. I have a cell phone.' The frustration with annoying cell
phone users is growing.''
</P>
<P>
   At California State University, Northridge, students in a
journalism class are asked to vote on whether a classmate should be
marked absent for the day if her or his cell phone or beeper goes
off. So far no one has been sent home.
</P>
<P>
   At Valley Beth Shalom in the Los Angeles suburb of Encino, board
chairman Avery Greenburg said the synagogue put up signs a few
months ago asking people to turn off their cell phones and pagers
to ``be respectful of the services.''
</P>
<P>
   One of a growing number of restaurants in Southern California
that have banned cell phones is Millie's in Silver Lake, where the
staff will chant ``No phones, no phones'' to anyone who breaks the
rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never allowed cell phones in the eight years I've owned
this place,'' owner Patti Peck said. ``We're an old-fashioned
place. We like people to enjoy their food. You can't legislate
courtesy, but in our case we have the right to say, not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurants in Hong Kong have ``cell phone'' and ``noncell
phone'' sections, said Sereno.
</P>
<P>
   And some Los Angeles County judges hold attorneys in contempt if
their phones ring in the courtroom. Court officials say they
haven't heard of the rule being enforced yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been occasions when a person's cell phone rings and
it's kept until the court is out of session for the day,'' said Los
Angeles Superior Court spokeswoman Jerrianne Hayslett.
</P>
<P>
   On area golf courses, those teeing up have become teed off by
rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a recreational golfer, it's a slight annoyance,''
said Westlake Golf Course professional Ted Lehmann. ``But if you
are a serious golfer, it could disrupt your shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Thomas, spokesman for the Southern California Golf
Association, said cell phone abuse is penalized on some courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Etiquette doesn't happen without teaching people the rules of
etiquette. The way we do that is to penalize them when they break
the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 0152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-KINGS-NYT &LR;      03-29 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS OUTSHINE KNICKS, 103-95 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The Knicks tried to imitate the Kings' blinding
flash and telegenic moves only to find the uniforms didn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   All of this hocus-pocus _ quick shots, loose possessions and
circus attempts _ was as unnatural as imitation cheese for a team
that usually places defense as its priority. Without this staple,
the Knicks could not deter the Kings from executing their
sleight-of-hand ways, 103-95, at Arco Arena on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the feel-good high the Knicks were on after winning in
Portland was punctured with a loss that left them one game out of
the Atlantic Division lead. Once they tucked Phoenix away on
Tuesday night, the Heat took over the lead once again.
</P>
<P>
   Just 48 hours earlier, a youthful-seeming Patrick Ewing had put
the Knicks in a tie with the Heat and had been anointed team
savior. On Tuesday night, his body language showed how worn the
elastic in his 37-year-old body can be. On Tuesday night, Chris
Webber reminded Ewing and the rest of the Knicks how inconsistency
remains the bane of their existence. Using an All-Star incident
with Coach Jeff Van Gundy as motivation, Webber humbled the Knicks
with a triple-double that read like this: 21 points, 11 assists and
10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   He was part of a Kings team that shot 50 percent from the field.
As the reserve Pedgrag Stojakovic (20 points) slipped around the
soft defense of Allan Houston (33 points), as Vlade Divac (19
points) stepped outside to escape the lethargic Ewing (8 points),
the Knicks' undisciplined chase ended when the Kings use a 6-2 run
to close out a game that consisted of shots from a pool shark's
handbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't us; we like to buckle down and play solid
defense,'' Houston said. ``But they baited us out of that. We
didn't attack them on the defensive end. We can't allow another
team to dictate the game, especially on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   It was so different Sunday night. The Knicks were in control and
Ewing was back on top after his heroics against the Trail Blazers.
On Tuesday night, he provided an uninspiring encore. Once Divac
opened up the third quarter with 11 points in eight minutes to put
the Kings up, 70-60, Ewing was taken out and sat for the next 12
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, the Knicks went on a 14-5 run that was fueled
with good defense on Webber by Marcus Camby and patience on offense
by Charlie Ward. Until then, Webber had been a problem for Larry
Johnson, who started out well with 9 points in the first quarter,
but found himself in foul trouble. ``I just sat on the bench,
didn't do nothing,'' said Johnson, who finished with 11 points and
missed five of his last six shots. ``The fouls? No biggie. I just
had to get out there and be professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson remained cool. Ewing did not. Soon after his return to
the game with 5 minutes 42 seconds left, he let his frustrations
boil over. After having his shot blocked by Divac and then getting
called for a foul on the other end, he barked obscenities at
Referee Nolan Fine with 4:23 left and the Knicks down, 94-86.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take technicals in the fourth, players or coaches,''
Van Gundy said. ``Points are too valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ewing was in a fit of anger, and probably a little
embarrassed by Divac's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just tired of everything,'' Ewing said. ``I thought I
was getting hit on my shot and not getting the calls they were. I'd
had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was an example of a team that lacked composure down the
stretch. Although they started getting serious on defense, and held
the Kings to 30 percent in the fourth, they were far too careless
on offense. With nine minutes left, Chris Childs went spinning into
the lane early in the shot clock and whirled up a crazy shot.
Between 5:19 and 5:16 left, Childs and Latrell Sprewell managed to
turn the ball over twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks finished with 15 turnovers, while the Kings had just
11. Even the usually untethered Jason Williams played with more
restraint than the Knicks' point guards. After two turnovers in the
opening minutes of the game _ which allowed the Knicks a brief
9-point first quarter lead _ he buttoned down and ended with 11
points, 4 assists and 4 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, buttoned down for Williams. He still winged passes behind
his back, but Webber was the coolest King on the floor. A day
before the game, he had told The Sacramento Bee he was still
irritated by Van Gundy's slight of him at the All-Star Game. During
the game, Van Gundy, who was wearing a microphone, said, ``Leave
Webber alone.'' As a response to Van Gundy's unwillingness to
double-team him in the All-Star Game, Webber told The Bee he wanted
to ``bust'' the Knicks on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he didn't double-team me again,'' Webber said after
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had enough trouble keeping tabs on everyone else,
particularly Stojakovic. As hot as Houston was to burn Stojakovic's
soft defense, he was hit right back by the European. As one of the
Knicks' mental lapses on defense, Houston fouled Stojakovic from
3-point range in the fourth. Stojakovic hit all three free throws.
``I knew he was a shooter, but he moves really well,'' Houston
said. ``He makes guarding a tough team even tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   The odd part of the fourth was how the Kings played more like
the Knicks. In the tense finish, they tightened on defense and shut
the Knicks down. The Knicks hit just 5 of 20 shots in the fourth.
``That's what we're trying to do,'' Webber said. ``We have style,
but we have to keep substance with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The usually substantial Knicks just pretended to have style
instead of being true to themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
