<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0895 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MARSCRASH-RESEND-LADN     03-29 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARSCRASH-RESEND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSESSMENT TEAM BLAMES ALL INVOLVED WITH MARS POLAR LANDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff writer Usha Sutliff contributed to this report) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The loss of the $165 million Mars Polar Lander was
most likely caused by a premature engine shutdown, which sent the
spacecraft crashing into the planet's surface at about 50 mph,
NASA-commissioned investigators said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Program Assessment Team found fault with all key
players in the failed mission, including NASA, the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena, which managed the effort; and Denver-based
Lockheed Martin Astronautics, which built the spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited poor communication among the three parties and
inadequate testing of systems. It also said tight NASA budgets and
time constraints contributed to the doom of the Mars Polar Lander
and the $29 million Deep Space 2 probes it was to have deployed on
Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The report also laid down the law for future Mars efforts by
stating: ``If not ready, do not launch.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration, JPL and
Lockheed officials pledged to make needed reforms and NASA
announced it was delaying the 2001 launch of another Mars lander.
The 2001 launch of a Mars orbiter will go on as planned. A NASA
official also said the agency would increase funding for needed
testing and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the report will be well-received,'' said JPL's John
Casani, who served on the assessment team.
</P>
<P>
   He said JPL is already implementing recommended organizational
changes, including the establishment of a separate management
office for Mars programs. Previous Mars efforts were managed by an
office that also oversees a number of unrelated JPL space programs.
</P>
<P>
   Casani, who retired in August as JPL's chief engineer and
returned as a consultant, said he was pleased with NASA's pledge of
more funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more funding or fewer programs, one or the other,''
Casani said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the Mars Polar Lander was 131 miles
above the Red Planet when it deployed its three landing legs as
planned. However, the deployment sent a false signal to the
engines, indicating the spacecraft had touched down.
</P>
<P>
   The engines shut down and sent the lander into a free fall.
</P>
<P>
   Computer software designed to thwart false signals had been
tested before the lander's launch, the report said. But the system
had been incorrectly wired and failed to respond during the test.
</P>
<P>
   No full-scale follow-up test was conducted after the wiring had
been repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Software was also the culprit in the Sept. 23 loss of the $125
million Mars Climate Orbiter, another NASA-JPL-Lockheed project.
The orbiter, which was to have relayed data from the Polar Lander,
burned up in the Martian atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   It veered off course after Lockheed engineers sent JPL
navigational data that they had failed to convert to metric
measurement units.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Young, the retired Lockheed Martin chief executive who
chaired the assessment team, also said that NASA, JPL and Lockheed
made ``a major mistake'' when they failed to equip the lander with
a device that would send signals to controllers during the landing.
The equipment was deleted to cut the cost and the weight of the
lander.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Young noted, investigators might never know the
true fate or location of the spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Other theories on the demise of the Mars Polar Lander include a
tumbling fall into a mile-deep canyon, a breakdown of fuel systems
and the failure of a parachute designed to brake the descent.
</P>
<P>
   Both Young and Edward J. Weiler, NASA associate administrator
for space science, cited cost restraints on the Mars Climate
Orbiter and Mars Polar Lander. They noted that both spacecraft had
budgets below the $200 million spent on Pathfinder, the successful
lander that broadcast the first images of Mars to Earth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (the Climate Orbiter and Polar Lander) had been a
little less cheap, they would have been a lot better,'' said Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission was underfunded from the start and people tried to
work in a box,'' said Peter Lyman, a Pasadena-based consultant and
member of the assessment team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have people working 60- to 80-hour weeks, you get
fatigue and the wrong risks are taken,'' added Lyman, who was
involved in the successful Viking and Voyager programs during 30
years at JPL.
</P>
<P>
   Weiler, who stressed that the effort to find life on Mars would
continue, had high praise for JPL's staff members, calling them
``the best talent in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We pushed JPL too far,'' added Weiler. He pledged ``not to ask
JPL to do the impossible'' on future missions.
</P>
<P>
   The NASA administrator also said that despite the delay of the
2001 launch, work would go on at JPL on improving the newest Mars
lander. He also said that NASA, which had required officials at JPL
and Lockheed to deal with a number of agency officials, had begun
its own reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   He announced the appointment of Scott Hubbard, a veteran of
several major space efforts at the Ames Research Lab in Sunnyvale,
as NASA's Mars program director.
</P>
<P>
   At JPL, Director Ed Stone announced the formation of the Science
Flight Projects Directorate, which will be headed by JPL employee
Thomas Gavin and focus on overseeing space science missions at the
lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a matter of individuals not doing their job. Every
individual was in fact doing their best for mission success,''
Stone said. ``There were not enough checks and balances in place to
catch the inevitable human errors which are made. ... In the
future, we will be sure that the budget is such that we can have
the appropriate JPL work force engaged in all these missions.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
