<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, March 29.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-CULT (Rugazi, Uganda) _ In one room, the concrete floor
looked a little newer and, on a hunch, the police began to dig.
First they found a human foot, sole upturned, poking up from the
rubble. Within a few hours Tuesday, 28 corpses were hauled out of a
pit _ carefully sealed over with cement, maybe months ago _ inside
the house owned by a leader of a cult in western Uganda. By dark,
the pit was only half emptied. It was, on one level, another
horrifying discovery in the two weeks since more than 300 people
were found burnt to death at a church not far from here. The death
toll, from three different sites, has now risen to at least 593.
There are at least two more suspected grave sites. But the
discovery of the pit may also indicate just how well-organized and,
perhaps longstanding, this march to mass murder in Uganda was. By
Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ After months of intense
behind-the-scenes political maneuvering, the Turkish Parliament is
about to begin the delicate work of deciding whether to re-elect
President Suleyman Demirel. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-PATERNITY-LEAVE (London) _ Prime Minister Tony Blair has
spent nearly three years in office telling the British they have to
shed their fusty traditions and get with the times. Now his wife is
telling him there is no better place to stage the revolution than
in his own home. Cherie Blair, 45, is seven months' pregnant with
the couple's fourth child, and last week she said that she expected
Blair, 46, to take some of the paternity leave that his government
has just made part of British law. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HAITIAN-PARENTS-DEPORT (Miami) _ Esta Pierre built a solid life
on shaky ground in Florida, scrubbing hotel room toilets and
bathing people in nursing homes to earn a living. She married a
Haitian immigrant and made payments on a little house in southwest
Florida. They had two children here, Jean Gardy, now 6, and Gaelle,
21 months. Ms. Pierre has received a deportation order from the
U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service, and barring one last,
thin appeal, said her Miami lawyer, she will be sent back. Her
husband, who also entered the U.S. on fake documents, has also been
ordered home. But their children, born here, are U.S. citizens by
birthright and cannot be deported. So, Ms. Pierre, like thousands
of other Haitian mothers and fathers in the U.S., must someday
choose whether to take her children with her or leave them, to save
them? By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-EXECUTE (Nashville) _ Philip Workman, who was convicted of
killing a police officer during a fast-food restaurant robbery in
1981 in Memphis, could become the first person executed in
Tennessee in 40 years. Lawyers for Workman, whose execution is
scheduled for April 6, have made a fairly compelling case about the
fairness of his trial, including some ballistics evidence that
suggests the officer may have been killed by friendly fire from
other cops. The only eyewitness at the trial has recanted, saying
he fabricated his story after being coached and threatened by
police. And just a few weeks ago, the medical examiner turned over
a potentially exculpatory x-ray of the victim that had never been
seen by the defense. The issue may ultimately be whether Workman is
guilty of felony murder even if he didn't fire the fatal shot
because he clearly committed the crime that led to the officer's
death. The question is now before the U.S. 6th Circuit Court of
Appeals. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEANDERTHAL-DNA (Undated) _ A new sample of ancient DNA has
been retrieved from a Neanderthal infant exhumed from a cave in the
Caucuses. Scientists say the sample, only the second ever retrieved
from Neanderthal remains, confirms that they were genetically very
different from humans and argues against the idea that modern
Europeans in particular are partly of Neanderthal descent. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-LOOPHOLE (Washington) _ The tiny remnant of the
American peace movement had a little money and was looking for a
voice in the political process. The pharmaceutical industry had a
lot of money and was looking for a bullhorn. Both found it in an
obscure corner of the IRS known as Section 527, a provision that
allows groups to raise and spend unlimited sums on political
activities without any disclosure as long as they do not expressly
advocate voting for one candidate or another. Section 527 has
become the loophole of choice this year for groups large and small,
left and right, to spread their messages without revealing the
sources of their income or the targets of their spending. And there
is no prohibition against accepting foreign money. By John M.
Broder and Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-COSTS (Dallas) _ Though surging fuel prices and rising
costs for chemicals, plastics, resins and other products have
driven up expenses for many businesses, not all industries or
companies have been affected equally. And those that have suffered
have not, by and large, passed along the higher costs, in part
because global competition and a relatively strong dollar have made
it unwise to raise prices. Even inflation hawks, including Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, have noted that consumers
have generally been spared, outside of direct expenses for gasoline
and home heating oil. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos and graphic have been sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-IMPACT (Dallas) _ Surging fuel prices and rising costs for
chemicals, plastics, resins and other products have driven up
expenses for many manufacturers. And even though oil prices have
retreated somewhat recently in expectation of increased production
by the oil-producing nations, there is little relief in sight. So
far, however, the higher petroleum costs have not for the most part
been passed on to consumers _ outside of direct expenses for fuel,
which have led airlines and shippers to raise prices _ as global
competition has made it impossible to raise prices. By Richard A.
Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTCH-AD-COLUMN (Madison, Wis.) _ For the last year, Anders
Carlson, 25, and his friend Rick Streed, 28, have freelanced for J.
Walter Thompson to produce irreverent print advertisements for J&AMP;B
Scotch based on posters they created as managers of Badger Liquor,
a short walk from the University of Wisconsin campus here. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   BEN&AMP;JERRY'S-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade ice
cream company became as well known for its commitment to causes
like helping the homeless and saving the rain forests as for
selling pints of Chubby Hubby and Cherry Garcia. But it has long
struggled to balance its social initiatives with shareholder
demands for better profits. On Tuesday, it appeared that part of
the struggle was over. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EMPLOYEE-TRAINING (Undated) _ Nanette Solow remembers the day
she stood in a row with 10 co-workers, tucked an orange under her
chin and transferred it to the space beneath a colleague's chin.
The goal was to move the orange down the entire line in less than
five minutes. But there was a deeper purpose: to build teamwork,
enhance communication and promote problem solving. And, oh yes: to
have a hoot in the process. But after the fun ended, employees
returned to their desks, submerged themselves in their daily chores
and forgot all about the great fruit exchange. More and more
corporations _ at least 70 percent, according to some estimates _
are relying on external training programs to foster leadership
skills and companywide bonding. Trouble is, many of these programs
have no practical value whatsoever. By Abby Ellin.
</P>
