<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE TROUBLE FOR CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers, who go 20-20 when the writing's on
the wall, have saved some graffiti for their shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Dallas Mavericks had the last word Tuesday
night, walking away with a 112-102 victory over the Clips before
10,157 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   But Tyrone Nesby and interim coach Jim Todd made additional
statements in a verbal scrimmage that soured what could be termed
an entertaining defeat.
</P>
<P>
   More on that later.
</P>
<P>
   With Lamar Odom (calf strain) and Maurice Taylor (ankle sprain)
joining the usual casualties (Brian Skinner, Eric Murdoch) in
street wear, the Clippers (14-58, eight losses in a row) were given
superb moments from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Olowokandi produced a career-high 27 points and eight
rebounds; Eric Piatkowski tossed in 28 points and point guard Jeff
McInnis had 14 points and nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned roll call of the wounded created a few more
shots for the common Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of guys in suits on the bench,'' said Todd on
taking on the Mavericks, who actually suit up nine assistant
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   But his team's combative nature impressed the Dallas head coach,
Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me congratulate the Clippers,'' Nelson said. ``Olowokandi
just dominated our inside people, and that's good news for him. But
the Clippers really pushed us with three starters out of their
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, just two. Nesby did start and produced eight points before
a disagreement with Todd on the sense of responsibility led to a
spot on the bench and a halftime confrontation over, well, shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Nesby declared his opposition to the team waiving close friend
Troy Hudson by writing Hudson's name on his sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Todd) subbed me out and I got mad,'' Nesby said. ``Then at
halftime, he got mad because I had Troy's name on my shoes. He told
me he wasn't going to play me for the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   You're witness, coach Todd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving it at disciplinary reasons,'' Todd said as
explanation for why Nesby didn't play in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the Clippers actually led, 55-51, at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (31-40) used 20 points each from triple-doubler Michael
Finley (12 rebounds, 10 assists) and Dirk Nowitzki to extend its
winning streak over the Clippers to six. The Mavericks made 13 of
26 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   Another positive word should be aimed at Etdrick Bohannon, a CBA
escapee who grabbed five rebounds in 11 minutes in his Clipper
debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised he used me this early,'' Bohannon said of
Todd. ``I thought I would have more of an impact on the game,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Clipper gurney keeps rolling, he'll probably get the
chance. But playing time for the acrobatic Nesby could be up in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can put me on injured reserve the rest of the year,'' Nesby
said. ``That's cool with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
