<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE WORKPLACE GREAT, ONE NOT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ In the dirty old heart of the city ...
<P>
   THEY'RE DROPPING like flies in SoMa, the traditional businesses
that are being priced out of the neighborhood by the
Johnny-dot-com-latelies.
</P>
<P>
   One of the firms that recently closed up was, I'm told, San
Francisco's only locally based phone-sex company, headquartered on
Second St. The rent tripled and that was it for a business that
thrived for about 15 years, and about 50 hard-working and creative
women are out of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our company was one of the few places where a woman from any
part of the world, with limited job skills, could get work with
decent pay and good benefits,'' says Serena, who worked the phones
for the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had quite a mixture of employees, all ages and races, from
college students to housewives to grandmothers, who were always
quite good at their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boss is a wonderful, wonderful man. We had catered food
every Friday and great benefits. More babies were born to my
co-workers than at any other place I've ever worked, and none of
the mothers had to pay a dime for hospital care. In scheduling, the
company worked with each employee's needs and was sensitive to
family problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great job, if you have the stomach for it, because it
can get kind of weird. But it's amazing the honest-to-god
friendships that form over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I'm going now, but I'll be damned lucky if
I find anything even remotely comparable to this company. As far as
I'm concerned, gentrification can go to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena, I love it when you talk like that.
</P>
<P>
   ON HIS WAY to work recently at one of S.F.'s very very big
corporations, a man died of a heart attack on BART.
</P>
<P>
   Another employee from the corporation's executive office was on
the train and reported the tragedy when she arrived at the big
office downtown. Nothing was done, no calls made.
</P>
<P>
   The coroner's office called to get a phone number for the dead
man's wife, a teacher, but nobody had the number.
</P>
<P>
   The wife phoned at about 4 o'clock to speak to her husband, but
the husband's boss declined to speak to her.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 minutes, her call was routed to the new human resources
manager, first day on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing very human going on there. But they can always pay their
rent.
</P>
<P>
   THE JUDGE likes to unwind.
</P>
<P>
   He's a traffic court judge and they know him at all the
neighborhood bars because he's a neighborhood guy. Everybody calls
him Judge. W'as up, Judge?
</P>
<P>
   They are amazed that he makes it to court every morning, because
he likes to stay out late. Maybe his secret is the sleep he gets at
the bar, standing up, using his right arm for support.
</P>
<P>
   He likes white wine and he's not a mean drunk, although they say
he can get kind of grouchy if you bump him while he's trying to get
some shut-eye.
</P>
<P>
   SHE'S LATE for the Big Utility's board meeting and can't find a
parking place in the city, imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   The big board member finally wheels into a parking garage, yells
to the attendant that she has to get to a very big board meeting,
they can't start without her. She leaves the key in the ignition
and dashes off.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a valet lot. When she returns after the meeting,
the car is gone, stolen.
</P>
<P>
   The other board members spring into action, ordering office
minions to comb the neighborhood. Then they call a limo for Ms.
Bigshot. And later they vote to buy her a new car, but then her car
is recovered.
</P>
<P>
   And you wonder why your Big Utility bill is so big.
</P>
<P>
   BEHOLD the lowly Parking and Traffic Officer, the meter maid,
object of scorn and loathing by the city's drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Now meet one of them, B. Lance Greenfield, veteran of the force.
</P>
<P>
   There's Lance, putt-putting south on Eighth St. in his
three-wheeler, a glorified golf cart, when he sees a car turn off
Brannan onto Eighth. It's a one-way street and the car is going the
wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Greenfield alertly stops his DPTmobile in the middle of
the street across two lanes, to halt the cars behind him and give
the errant driver time to realize his mistake and turn around.
</P>
<P>
   But the errant driver is making his own rules. He guns his car
straight for Officer Greenfield's cart and rams it at about 40 mph.
Greenfield, with three fractured ribs and a mangled kneecap, crawls
out of his vehicle and phones the cops on his cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   The wrong-way driver, in a Pac Bell car he has just stolen from
the company lot on 16th St., then slams head-on into a taxi, jumps
out and flees. The taxi driver gives chase, tackles the bad guy and
holds him down to wait for the police. But the bad guy's friends
pull up in another car and threaten the Good Samaritan cabbie, who
has no choice but to let the bad guy go.
</P>
<P>
   So the man gets away and Greenfield gets to spend a month trying
to breathe without pain and waiting for the swelling in his knee to
go down so he can have surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The reward for information in the case of the man who tried to
road-kill one of your dedicated officers is now up to (most recent
tally): Zero dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
