<HEADER>
A0911 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SWEET-TASTE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEET-TASTE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICINES CAN ALTER SENSE OF TASTE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Most prescription drugs not only are
foul-tasting but also can lead to profound changes in the sense of
taste, particularly in older people, scientists said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Drug researchers hope to use the latest findings to make
medicines easier to take while also gaining a better idea of what
happens to the senses as people age.
</P>
<P>
   New studies on the chemistry of taste were presented Tuesday
during the national meeting of the American Chemical Society, under
way this week in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Among conference highlights, taste experts said they are closing
in on a long-sought ``sweet tooth'' gene believed to influence how
people perceive some flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists working with mice already have narrowed it down to
about a 100-gene region of the mouse's set of genetic instructions,
or genome, which closely mirrors the human genetic code.
</P>
<P>
   The key segments of human DNA underlying taste differences are
expected to become clear within about six months to a year, said
Gary Beauchamp, an expert on taste genetics at the Monell Chemical
Senses Center in Philadelphia, which bills itself as ``the world's
first scientific institute for multidisciplinary research on taste,
smell and chemosensory irritation.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Schiffman, professor of medical psychology at Duke
University, summarized elaborate taste tests involving 62
prescription medications.
</P>
<P>
   Her research found that brief exposure to a bitter taste
releases a flood of stress-related neurotransmitters, presumably
part of a natural response to a sense of being poisoned. Such
responses could help explain problems of wasting and appetite loss
in patients on a steady regimen of bitter, taste-distorting
medications.
</P>
<P>
   Chemotherapy patients lose, on average, 20 to 30 pounds.
Scientists hope the new wave of research will lead to ways for
improving taste and smell, perhaps giving cancer patients more
ability to withstand high-dose therapies.
</P>
<P>
   In Schiffman's laboratory, tongues of research volunteers were
dabbed with samples of pharmaceuticals at concentrations four times
above a previously determined ``detection threshold.'' Subjects
were then given a choice of 14 adjectives to characterize the
dominant taste sensation.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, only three adjectives _ bitter, sour and
metallic _ were needed to describe all the drugs that had any taste
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Mind-altering drugs were found to taste ``awful,'' Schiffman
said, while some analgesics were among those rated ``least awful.''
Nearly all the anti-microbials tested were deemed ``terrible'' to
the taste.
</P>
<P>
   Nine AIDS drugs tested were all found to be peculiarly bitter.
Saquinavir, sold under the brand name Invirase, the first of the
protease inhibitors to hit the market, also turned out to be
detectable at the lowest concentration of any drug tested.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming what many patients on long-term anti-HIV therapy have
experienced, researchers concluded that taking antivirals can
dramatically and unpredictably alter the taste of other things.
</P>
<P>
   Schiffman said she is just starting experiments designed to sort
out the complex biochemistry involved in taste distortion, a
phenomenon, known clinically as dysguesia, also associated with the
aging process.
</P>
<P>
   Young and old alike perceive some of the worst-tasting
medicines, particularly anti-microbials, as bitter, in part because
such drugs tend to be highly soluble in fat, a characteristic that
drug designers cannot easily do much about.
</P>
<P>
   But studies are now being conducted to find designer ``bitter
blockers'' _ potentially yet another category of drugs that may
someday be prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   An even more intriguing puzzle concerns how the taste-sensing
system can change as a result of aging, as well as from a steady
diet of medicines. These changes may occur not only in how taste
buds on the tongue respond to a given chemical, but also in how the
brain processes taste signals.
</P>
<P>
   Gene studies ``may explain quite a bit,'' Beauchamp said,
although he conceded that upbringing, cultural influences and
numerous other factors influence changing tastes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
