<HEADER>
A0912 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-DAVIS-CHAVEZ-SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-CHAVEZ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DAVIS SEEKS CESAR CHAVEZ HOLIDAY BILL BY FRIDAY  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL and GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Looking to capitalize on the media's love of
coincidences, Gov. Gray Davis hopes to sign a bill making Cesar
Chavez' birthday a state holiday on Friday _ the late labor
leader's date of birth.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Davis asked the Legislature to speed passage of a
bill making the former United Farm Workers union leader's March 31
birthday a paid holiday for state employees.
</P>
<P>
   Davis wants the bill before Friday, so he can sign the measure
in Los Angeles, the state's largest media market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is appropriate to have the bill signed on the date of this
great hero's birthday,'' said Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles,
the author of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is gaining a reputation for usurping popular bills in
order to maximize his public exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bustamante, Davis' press secretary, denies lawmakers are
rushing the bill through at the governor's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not driving it,'' Bustamante said. ``I don't think we
asked them to speed it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Using bill signings for political gain is nothing new in
Sacramento, but Davis has taken it upon himself to be prominently
associated with some of the most popular legislation he has signed.
</P>
<P>
   The governor staged two large-scale press conferences on last
year's assault weapons ban _ one held in Los Angeles and the other
in San Francisco _ and at both he was surrounded by police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Davis staged a photo opportunity to announce his
support for a Senate bill to fight a bug that causes Pierce's
Disease, a bacteria that is threatening the state's all-important
wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   For the Chavez bill, the plan is for the Assembly Appropriations
Committee to hear the bill Thursday morning, then waive the
Assembly's rules and take it up on the Assembly floor.
</P>
<P>
   A final vote by the state Senate is also needed before the bill
goes to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governor's sudden request that lawmakers speed up
approval of the bill is a sharp change from earlier this year when
administration aides privately told lawmakers the price of the bill
was prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante confirmed that the governor was worried about the $90
million cost of giving a holiday to court, school and state
employees.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, at Davis' request, the bill was scaled back to just a
holiday for state workers _ a move that angered some lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To create a Chavez holiday that gives state workers a day off
and leaves farmworkers toiling in the field is misdirected,'' said
Assemblyman Mike Briggs, R-Clovis. ``Scholarships for children of
farmworkers would be a much more fitting tribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante says limiting the bill to state workers now lowers
the price tag to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But an analysis by the Assembly Appropriations Committee, using
figures provided by Davis' own administration, pegs the costs at
$34 million to give the state's nearly 280,000 employees another
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   State workers already enjoy 13 paid holidays a year. They also
have a memorial day for Chavez which allows workers to take March
31 off in lieu of another holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Adding Chavez's birthday to the paid holiday list would also
cost an additional $12.5 million to pay time-and-a-half to health
and safety workers like prison guards and highway patrol officers
who would have to work on the holiday, according to administration
figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
