<HEADER>
A0913 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-PARTNERS-BILLS-SFCHRO     03-29 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTNERS-BILLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMESTIC PARTNER RIGHTS OKD BY ASSEMBLY PANEL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ A trio of bills expanding the rights of domestic
partners to include inheriting property, making funeral
arrangements and legal standing to sue for wrongful death were
approved Tuesday by a key Assembly committee.
<P>
   The measures would greatly broaden California's domestic
partners law, which allows partners to register with the state and
have hospital visitation rights.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters claimed the bills are modest and humane changes to
the law. Opponents said there were already legal mechanisms
available to solve the problems the bills address and that
approving them would promote same-sex marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still live in a society in which there are certain taboos
and phobias about people who choose a lifestyle that might be
different from our own,'' said Assemblywoman Gloria Romero, D-Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a bill about morality. It is not a bill about
redefining marriage,'' Romero said of her bill, which allows a
domestic partner registered with the state to make medical
decisions for an incapacitated partner.
</P>
<P>
   The first public hearings on the bills come three weeks after
voters overwhelmingly approved Proposition 22, which prevents
California from legally recognizing same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   But backers of the domestic partnership bills said polls show
that even Californians opposed to same-sex marriage are willing to
increase domestic partner benefits. The bills are the first efforts
of lawmakers to build on Gov. Gray Davis' approval last year of a
bill that creates a statewide registry for domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the proposed legislation is unknown, however. A
Davis spokeswoman said the governor had no position.
</P>
<P>
   If last year was any indication, Davis is unlikely to embrace
such sweeping changes. He made lawmakers water down the domestic
partners bills and finally consolidate them into one measure before
signing it.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposed rights for domestic partners are contained in
three bills: AB 1990 by Romero, AB 2047 by Assemblyman Darrell
Steinberg, D-Sacramento and AB 2211 by Assemblywoman Sheila Kuehl,
D-Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   For partners who register with the state, the three bills give
them the rights to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Sue for negligent infliction of emotional distress and
wrongful death, the same right spouses have.
</P>
<P>
   -- Make funeral arrangements and autopsy decisions for a
partner.
</P>
<P>
   -- Be the conservator for a partner or the partner's estate.
</P>
<P>
   -- Be a beneficiary of a partner's will.
</P>
<P>
   -- Inherit property from a partner if that partner has no will.
</P>
<P>
   -- Act as administrator of a partner's estate.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehl's bill also would have California recognize domestic
partnerships from other states but would only afford those couples
the rights extended to partners in California.
</P>
<P>
   California began official recognition of domestic partnerships
three months ago by creating a statewide registry.
</P>
<P>
   A domestic partnership is defined as a couple, over 18 years of
age, ``who have chosen to share one another's lives in an intimate
and committed relationship of mutual caring.''
</P>
<P>
   People 62 years old or older and living together also can
registered with the state as domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Secretary of State's office, which maintains the
registry, has received 2,805 applications.
</P>
<P>
   Being registered confers no special benefits. Domestic partners
are granted hospital visitation rights under the bill creating the
registry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just adds a few benefits for those who register,'' Kuehl
told the Assembly Judiciary committee, which approved all three
bills on party-line votes.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents said many of the benefits the bills seek to
provide are unneeded if domestic partners use existing legal
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   People already can designate whomever they wish to act as a
conservator or grant them power of attorney to make medical and
financial decisions, said Steven Burlingham, a Sacramento family
law lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not asking too much to merely check a box and sign a
form, particularly when we're asking people to register as domestic
partners,'' Burlingham said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jane Pearce, another Sacramento family law lawyer, said she
favored the bills.
</P>
<P>
   She said 20 percent of her clients are gay and lesbian couples
seeking estate planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the lucky ones. Lucky they have knowledge that
planning is essential for them to protect their last wishes,''
Pearce said.
</P>
<P>
   The bills still must move through the Assembly and be approved
by the Senate before being sent to Davis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
