<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0996 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-CULTURE-WRESTLE-KANSA     03-29 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-WRESTLE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE TAKES TO THE MAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PAUL  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even in the big city, cultural ripples from back home
can assert themselves
</P>
<P>
   Here's the scene: It's Mardi Gras night in Kansas City. A
downtown block party, a near-debauch with beer and a band, attracts
a couple of artist-made floats: wacky, bejeweled trucks, things
like that.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the evening, the bed of a pickup truck receives
a layer of mud and becomes an ad hoc wrestling ring. As the truck
and the other floats begin to head down the street for a short
parade, two bad girls go at it. Everybody laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you can look at girl mud wrestling in any number of ways:
Is it a) a spectacular performance art, b) a pathetic yahoo
regression or c) a neo-feminist pose?
</P>
<P>
   A few culture-centric days in New York will prompt big life
questions like that.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker notwithstanding, you can celebrate your place in the
human crowd while riding the subway. At the same time you can
engage in a lively sort of contemplation, a kind of synaptic
pinball that doesn't always unfold during the behind-the-wheel
commute back home. One subway thought hypertexts to the next, and
pretty soon the idea of wrestling's place in the culture begins to
make sense.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been reminded of that Kansas City mud-wrestling scene as I
passed an attitudinal shop window in lower Manhattan, where a
bumper sticker shouted, ``Girls Kick Ass.'' It's part of the new
consciousness that turns self-made young women into girls (or,
often, ``grrrls''), whether they're in cyberspace or the mud pit.
Forget the Martha Stewart thing; the operative image is Xena in Doc
Martens.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling, of course, is in the air. Judging from the TV ratings
and bookdom's best-seller lists, you can hardly avoid the new
over-the-top celebrities. (Hello, Chyna. Howdy, Mankind.)
</P>
<P>
   But what does all that have to do with culture?
</P>
<P>
   Metaphorically, we wrestle with big ideas, when we have the
time, which isn't often. Writers and readers wrestle with words,
and artists of all kinds wrestle with perception, consciousness and
the tools of their expression.
</P>
<P>
   But, literally, wrestling and its muscle-popping cousins can
show up when you least expect it.
</P>
<P>
   At the opera, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   The current Metropolitan Opera season in New York includes a
smashingly surreal production of the Shostakovich ``Lady MacBeth of
Mstensk.'' It has everything one could hope for in the opera:
seduction, sex, betrayal, death _ and wrestling, if only for one
sweaty moment.
</P>
<P>
   In the starring role Catherine Malfitano has a huge voice and
pours her zaftig frame into a series of blond-bombshell dresses _
imagine Shelley Winters in a Marilyn Monroe number.
</P>
<P>
   In an early scene the sultry, unsatisfied Katerina (Malfitano)
confronts the swaggering new laborer Sergei (Vladimir Galouzine) in
the work yard outside the home she shares with her cold,
businessman husband and his domineering father.
</P>
<P>
   Katerina protests when the workmen fondle the family cook, and
she stands up for the strength of women. She is taken aback when
Sergei grabs her hand and proposes a little upstairs-downstairs
wrestling match.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic grapple that ensues is played out against a steamy
backdrop: a male-chorus orgy of bump-and-grinding sexuality, a
scene that seems to have been imported from one of those
Christopher Street leather bars one hears about.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the spark is lighted and later Sergei and Katerina
end up, er, upstairs, in that other kind of tangle, atop her
hot-pink bed.
</P>
<P>
   HHH
</P>
<P>
   There's no sex in David Mamet's play ``American Buffalo.'' But
the language is raw, and there is an eruption of violence, a
momentary smackdown of sorts, in Mamet's thinly veiled rant against
the evils of American business.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet's 25-year-old play is enjoying a thrilling run, first in
London and now at the Atlantic Theatre Company, the actor-friendly
Chelsea house that Mamet founded with William H. Macy. Macy (he's
everywhere) heads the cast of thieving lowlifes, along with veteran
Philip Baker Hall and young Mark Webber, making an impressive
theatrical debut as Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Buffalo'' seems as vital as ever, and the way Mamet
conquers all with words is simply astounding. (``That's what
business is,'' says Hall's Don, proprietor of Don's Resale Shop,
the play's sole set, ``people taking care of themselves.'')
</P>
<P>
   The stage is a convincing junk-shop repository of American
consumerism: broken radios, stacks of dusty books, milk crates of
LPs, shelves of old luggage ring the action; a dartboard, a saw and
a cheap guitar hang from the back wall. No wrestling paraphernalia
that I could see, but there was a Chicago Bears pennant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not here to smother you in theory,'' Mamet's Teach
(Macy), a tightly wrapped bundle of aggression and angst, blurts
out in a typical bit of irony.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, could be the motto of wrestling's Vince McMahon
and company, the entrepreneurial force behind the resurgence of
testosterone entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   HHH
</P>
<P>
   Only in retrospect did it occur to me that evidence could be
gathered no matter where I turned up in New York. Even at the Frick
Collection, in all its quiet, Upper-East-Side, old-money glory.
</P>
<P>
   Among the treasures are a pair of gorgeous, allegorical
paintings by Veronese. Four hundred years old. In one of them,
``Wisdom and Strength,'' the brain wrestles with brawn and comes
out, if not the victor, then at least in the lead. The painting
depicts Hercules, with all his brute force and courage, and
Minerva, goddess of wisdom and the arts. She has the upper hand,
and her heavenward gaze trumps Hercules' apparent submission.
</P>
<P>
   Veronese's background reinforces the subtext of culture vs.
nature: Minerva stands in front of a fluted column and Hercules
against a backdrop of trees.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, deep in the shadow of the painting, at the base of
Minerva's column, is the inscription ``Omnia Vanitas'' (all is
vanity).
</P>
<P>
   Our girl mud wrestlers _ remember them? _ might find inspiration
in a mysterious, haunting object that stands as the centerpiece of
a charming and understated exhibit currently showing at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art. It's the ``Leonine Goddess,'' a
5,000-year-old piece of carved and polished limestone that is said
to come from southwestern Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture is the signature item of the Guennol Collection,
the eclectic holdings of A.B. and Edith Martin, who since the late
1940s have sought out rare and beautiful objects from around the
world: Olmec jade, carved Egyptian marble, painted-wood folk art
from Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what the Martins admire pays homage to the natural
world, but their connoisseurship extends to humor and the
often-unexplainable sublimities that art and the human hand present
to the eye.
</P>
<P>
   At less than 4 inches tall, the ``Leonine Goddess'' packs much
more aesthetic wallop than one might first expect. The lion's head
is turned to its left, and from the shoulders down the figure seems
like nothing less than a human body builder, hands clasped, elbows
out, pecs and arm muscles bulging.
</P>
<P>
   It's far more subtle than the mud-covered faux warriors in the
back of a Kansas City pickup. And, in its way, it's far more
effective as an astounding portrait of pride and assertive
identity. Grrrl power. Hear it roar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
