<HEADER>
A0997 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-POETRY-POPULAR-KANSAS     03-29 1601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POETRY-POPULAR-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WELL OF WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  Nature never set forth the earth in
so rich tapestry as divers poets have done; neither with so
pleasant rivers, fruitful trees, sweet-smelling flowers, nor
whatsoever else may make the too much loved earth more lovely.
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Sir Philip Sidney, ``The Defence of Poesy,'' 1595
</P>
<P>
   Poetry has been under attack for hundreds of years. Long before
Sir Philip Sidney's time and long after, it was accused of
promoting immorality and impure thoughts, in addition to being a
terrible waste of one's time.
</P>
<P>
   When not being oppressed, poetry has been overlooked. It has
never been as popular as prose, as mainstream as music, as, well,
theatrical as theater. In the last century, poetry has faced
increasing competition, with the rise of the novel; the birth of
film, radio, TV; and the evolution of computers from scientific
tool to entertainment powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no surprise that in 2000, poetry is ... more vital than
ever?
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, yes. April is National Poetry Month, and to hear
people talk, there's much to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a hunger to hear words used well,'' says
Rebekah Presson Mosby, who produces spoken-word recordings for
Rhino Records. ``People are burned out on the vulgarity and
ugliness and flatness of language they hear on TV and in movies
these days. People know instinctively that there is power in the
spoken word, and what they're hearing ... isn't evoking that power.
Poetry contains the tools they can use to unlock their souls.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps it contains enough appeal to survive commercially.
Rhino recently released ``Our Souls Have Grown Deep Like the
Rivers,'' a collection of African-American poets reading their
works. Recently it stood at No. 1,300 on amazon.com's sales list _
which isn't bad, considering that the list includes hundreds of
thousands of books, CDs and other titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first compilation I did for Rhino, 1996's `In Their Own
Voices: A Century of Poetry,' blew the lid off Rhino's expectations
for sales,'' Mosby says. ``They thought they'd sell 5,000 copies,
and they've sold 10 times that amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course these two examples involve listening to poetry, not
reading it. These days, though, that's the point: Poetry is finding
its way off the page and into pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Electric verse
</P>
<P>
   Mosby, who for years was host for Kansas City's ``New Letters on
the Air'' program but now lives in Hamilton, N.Y., believes that
one of the forces behind poetry's popularity is its return to the
oral tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a dimension you get from hearing a poem that you can't
get from reading it. ... Even if a poet is not a good reader, you
still learn something about their work from hearing how their voice
works the line endings, the rhythms.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Vando Hickok may be a publisher (she operates KC's
Helicon Nine Press), but she agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing more poetry readings, poetry on television, on
the radio _ and on records; and there's also hip-hop and rap. It's
becoming more of a spoken art, like it used to be. In the '50s
there were a lot of poetry readings, then it went underground. Now
the coffeeshop has come back, and poetry has come back with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, poet//activist Bob Holman spreads the news that
poetry matters. Last April he drew 10,000 people to the People's
Poetry Gathering, which featured writers ranging from rocker Ani
DiFranco to U.S. poet laureate Robert Pinsky. The next gathering
will be in April 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem with getting an audience for poetry is how
poetry is defined,'' Holman says. ``As long as it's defined as
exquisite but elitist art, it will attract an exquisite but elitist
audience. ... But when you can define poetry as Ani DiFranco, you
start to see a different kind of vigor.
</P>
<P>
   ``People enjoy reading with their ears. The sounds in poems are
as critical to meaning as are the texts. Text has proven to be a
very acute method of transmission, but something is lost in that
transmission. It can be reconstituted, like orange juice, if you
read it aloud and hear the meaning. ... It puts the tongue back in
literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Holman is working on a series for PBS called ``The World of
Poetry'' that will be an international sequel to his ``United
States of Poetry.'' He also plans to open a poetry nightclub in a
building he's buying in downtown Manhattan _ a ``seven-day-a-week
poetry hangout spot.''
</P>
<P>
   KC may not be ready for that yet, but there are plenty of
readings here: the Riverfront series, the Writers Place, events
scattered among the local bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   But are we to abandon texts altogether?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Looks good on paper
</P>
<P>
   Helicon Nine has been holding literary contests for a decade,
and poetry submissions outnumber prose offerings 3-to-1, Hickok
says. There is no shortage of poets.
</P>
<P>
   And no shortage of outlets for their talents. Last month the
Mid-America Press Inc. of Warrensburg, Mo., produced the inaugural
issue of The Mid-America Poetry Review. The new review will focus
on poets from Missouri, Kansas, Nebraska, Iowa, Oklahoma, Arkansas
and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Editor Robert C. Jones is optimistic but also apprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed emotions, because I look what's going on with
major publishers,'' Jones says. ``They're publishing a million
copies of `thud and blunder' stories, and people seem to be buying
it. But the typical poetry book press run is usually under 10,000
and more like 500 to a thousand _ and bookstores have trouble
selling that many.''
</P>
<P>
   If not books, though, can a thrice-a-year journal survive?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of betting that regionalism is making a comeback,''
Jones says of his decision to focus on the seven-state area. As for
marketing, he's sending complimentary copies to libraries, working
on a Web site to allow Internet sales and selling copies by mail.
</P>
<P>
   And Jones is encouraged about the quality of work. ``I'm seeing
some marvelous poetry. There's always the `moon, june, spoon'
doggerel kind of thing, but there are also some tremendous poets
writing in our seven states.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stewart, managing editor of KC's New Letters literary
magazine, not only agrees on the quality issue but also isn't
bothered that poetry will never be as popular as other art forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap lies in the fact that mass-media culture has a natural
aversion to it because serious poetry _ not to mean humorless, but
poetry as art _ by its nature is eccentric, that is, original and
unpredictable, which generally is not how the mass media wants to
appeal to a wide audience base.''
</P>
<P>
   But those not glued to a screen of some kind do turn out for
poetry events.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1984 the Midwest Poets Series, which I run, attracted about
40 people for a major poet, Mona Van Duyn,'' Stewart says. ``Today
a relatively unknown poet will attract an audience of 150 easily,
and last October W.S. Merwin on two consecutive nights drew 300 and
400 people, respectively.''
</P>
<P>
   G.S. Sharat Chandra, an internationally known poet and writer of
eight books who is also a professor at the University of
Missouri-Kansas City, enjoys the ``private'' kind of fame that
being a poet provides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is true that poetry is marginalized ... but I can't
think of any time that it has not been. It has never been
commercially feasible; poets can't make money out of writing
poetry, and publishers can't make money out of publishing poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   There are occasional exceptions, Chandra notes: James Dickey,
Robert Frost, Dylan Thomas. ``By and large, though, I think poets
always stay in the shadows and most are content to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poetry is not a public art. It's a private art, and the
aesthetics are such that the enjoyment one gets is very personal.
However, I feel exuberant about what has been happening in the last
decade or so. There does seem to be more attention given to poetry
and more poetry written by good writers.''
</P>
<P>
   `Ancient lava'
</P>
<P>
   In the archives of a Web site called Poetry Daily
(www.poems.com), one may find a poem called ``Parchment'' by
Michelle Boisseau. She also has published in the traditional way:
two books of poetry and a how-to book with Robert Wallace called
Writing Poems. She is an associate professor of English at UMKC.
Boisseau seems delighted with poetry no matter the form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poetry is ancient lava, really. It's the oldest form of using
words that we have, and it connects us back to our earliest roots.
Most of the time when we read newspapers or even novels, the words
are there to convey information or provide data. But with poetry,
the words themselves have the power.''
</P>
<P>
   In our high-tech age, poetry wouldn't seem to be a good fit. And
yet Boisseau says poetry is one of the most sought-after subjects
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems strange that poems would be right up there with
pornography,'' she says with a laugh. She is pleased that poetry is
extending tendrils into the wider world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have a misconception of poetry as something
elite and far removed from everyday language, like truffles or
Camembert. But really it's more akin to something you pull out of
your garden. We're used to eating language that is canned.
Sometimes when students get their first taste of a poem, it
quickens them in an amazing way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poetry is for people who love the twists and turns of
sentences and the sizzle of an interesting metaphor. After awhile
as an adult, you know how all the stories turn out _ but there's
nothing like a good poem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
