<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glamour, revelry reign over long Oscars night
 &HT;    By Robert Janjigian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like a Cecil B. DeMille production, Sunday's
Academy Awards ceremony had a cast of thousands and a running time
of several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to figure out the number of valet parkers required for
the night alone was mind-boggling, considering there were about
5,000 limousines expected to bring the 6,000 or so members of the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The 72nd annual bestowal of Oscars officially began at 5:30 p.m.
PST. At 2:30 p.m., everyone _ media, security, Academy personnel,
ushers _ with credentials for the arrivals area, the red-carpeted
zone that stands between the limo door and the entrance doors to
the Shrine Auditorium, was in position. Though it was midafternoon,
each was wearing the Academy-sanctioned tuxedo or long gown. Most
sported sunglasses. In the press section, several people slathered
on suntan lotion as protection against the strong Los Angeles rays.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long afternoon and night. The first limousine pulled up
at 2:50 p.m. Movie fans in the bleachers looking for anything to
cheer about _ they'd been waiting at the Shrine auditorium to catch
a glimpse of a star since early that morning _ cheered on their
favorite television hosts, the men and women from ``Entertainment
Tonight,'' ``Access Hollywood'' and ``E! Entertainment
Television.''
</P>
<P>
   The first nominees to walk the gauntlet were Haley Joel Osment
and Chloe Sevigny, about one hour later. Pandemonium in the
bleachers. At last, somebody from the big screen had shown up.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, a parade of famous faces passed by. What wasn't
apparent to television viewers was the staggering noise level in
the arrivals area, with reporters and photographers screaming out
stars' names, the fans screeching whenever one of their favorites
came into view and the live interviews columnist Army Archerd did
over the loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   What was missing was the usual sound of cellular telephones
ringing. Either everybody had put their phones on silent mode or
the ensuing cacophony just filtered the ringing out.
</P>
<P>
   What there was, after a relatively quiet prelude of a couple of
hours, was a definite buzz, an old-fashioned Hollywood opening
flavor characterized the whole affair.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Schwarzenegger and Maria Shriver came through the metal
detectors in the entrance tent at just after 5 p.m., the final big
names to arrive on the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   It was then time to head for the seats and see Billy Crystal if
you had a ticket to the show, or to the backstage area, where the
international press corps of about 250 reporters and photographers
watched the show on headsets and television monitors. Here they all
waited for the winners in various categories, accompanied by the
actors and actresses who served as presenters during the telecast,
to appear for photos and question-and-answer sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The streamlined Oscar telecast promised by show producers
Richard D. and Lili Fini Zanuck was received well by those in the
press room. Applause and laughter for Crystal's opening number. Not
many tough questions for the winners. There was laughter during
Robin Williams' archly staged production number for Best Song
nominee ``Blame Canada.'' And a little disappointment when John
Irving, who took home the Oscar for the screenplay adaptation of
his novel ``The Cider House Rules,'' chose only to enter the photo
room, not facing the reporters. When Hilary Swank was announced as
best actress for her role in ``Boys Don't Cry'' and the cameras
focused on her teary-eyed husband Chad Lowe in his seat, the best
crack of the night was heard: ``I guess boys do cry,'' said one
jaded reporter.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the final winners of the night _ ``American
Beauty's'' lead actor Kevin Spacey, director Sam Mendes (who
received the award for his debut as a feature film director),
writer Alan Ball, and producers Bruce Cohen and Dan Jinks _ were
shepherded in and out of the interview room and a quick appearance
at the Academy's Governor's Ball at the Shrine's Expo Center, it
was time to venture to a few parties. The third portion of the
night began around 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes' drive away in Beverly Hills, DreamWorks SKG, the
studio behind ``American Beauty,'' had taken over Spago for the
night. Here, the Oscar winners from the film and a number of
Tinseltown celebrities, including Steven Spielberg, Judi Dench,
Molly Shannon, Sean Young and San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown,
faced another line of photographers and reporters before heading
into the soiree.
</P>
<P>
   Bars close at 2 a.m. in Los Angeles. At about 2:30 a.m. in West
Hollywood, at the intersection of Robertson Boulevard and Melrose
Avenue, the much-hyped Vanity Fair party was just winding down.
People were shuffling out of the InStyle/Elton John party, just
across the street from Morton's restaurant, the site of Vanity
Fair's celebrity-filled fest. The faces in the crowd were mostly
famous _ and mostly glazed over, as faces will look at this time in
the morning after nine or so hours in the spotlight. Even Swank,
clutching her Best Actress Oscar as she left Morto's, looked as if
she'd had just about enough for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The big, long night in Hollywood was over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
