<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State agency's new employee perk: the boot
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ No one can accuse management at the Texas
Natural Resource Conservation Commission of being overly warm and
fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday when the state agency on North Interstate 35 wanted
to show its workers what could happen to them if they parked in the
wrong spot at work, they displayed a state van in a company parking
lot with a vehicle restraint device attached to the left front
wheel. Some departments even showed off the ``boot'' to employees
inside the office, said commission spokesman Andy Saenz.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how the pilgrims used to put people in stocks and taunt
them in the town square when they got caught messing up? This
policy kind of reminds me of that.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I am exaggerating for a cheap laugh. But _ and here's
the funny part _ the agency did e-mail its employees about the
display beforehand so that they could come by and see the state van
affixed with the boot in the parking lot. Dear employees: Please
come to the parking lot and see what you'll be getting if you
continue to screw up. Love and kisses, your boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a demonstration, one of these devices will be applied to a
state vehicle for employees to view in the building A visitor lot
on Tuesday, March 21th (sic) between 9:00 a.m. and 4:00 p.m.,''
said the e-mail inviting employees to come see the boot. March
21th? So parking Nazis aren't English majors. What can I tell you?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the new employee parking policy: The first two times you
park in the wrong place, they put the boot on your car. Each time,
to set your car free, you have to go to your deputy director _ make
that one of the big bosses _ and go through the embarrassment of
asking him to unlock the boot for you.
</P>
<P>
   The third time, they tow. Then they throw you in hot oil and
send your mamma a snapshot. Just kidding about the oil.
</P>
<P>
   I think a better policy would be to make parking violators wear
large red P's around their necks.
</P>
<P>
   I went out to the conservation commission last Tuesday to
witness the boot demonstration, and I'm here to report that it was
a pretty boring show. We're talking about one state van, parked
with an orange contraption clamped to it to keep it from moving. So
is it any wonder, despite the considerate invitation, that only a
handful of employees walked by to look at the display while I was
there? The commission could have at least set out some chips and a
bowl of salsa.
</P>
<P>
   If you think this is tough you should have been here last year,
Saenz said. He says the agency has a problem with employees parking
their vehicles in the visitor lot, instead of in the company
parking garage. So last year, Saenz said, the agency hired a guy
named Big Al to tow employee vehicles. After complaints about Big
Al being too expensive, he was replaced by the boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Al does not take American Express,'' Saenz said. ``Big Al
wanted cold, hard cash _ $91. And if Big Al got to keep your car
overnight, he charged you an extra $20 for storage.''
</P>
<P>
   If the boot doesn't work, I wonder when they're going to start
the floggings in the parking lot?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if Big Al isn't busy next year, they could hire him back
and give him a whip.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears in the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
