<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about presidential disability and succession made
me wonder: Has there ever been a case in the United States when an
acting president was required to step in for a short emergency
period?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. As World Book Encyclopedia explains, Vice President
George Bush became the first U.S. acting president in your scenario
when, on July 13, 1985, he officially held that position for eight
hours while President Reagan underwent cancer surgery.
</P>
<P>
   This matter is addressed in Section 3 of the 25th Amendment to
the Constitution, which states: Whenever the president transmits to
the president pro tempore of the Senate and the speaker of the
House of Representatives his written declaration that he is unable
to discharge the powers and duties of his office, and until he
transmits to them a written declaration to the contrary, such
powers and duties shall be discharged by the vice president as
acting president.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Gasoline prices have been in the news a lot lately. Adjusted
for inflation, how much have they changed over, say, the past 10
years?
</P>
<P>
   A: Statistics compiled by the American Petroleum Institute are
available only up to August 1999, before the recent surge in
prices. But information in API's booklet ``How Much We Pay for
Gasoline'' shows how adjusted prices have moved over the years. It
says that in 1990, the inflation-adjusted U.S. city retail price
for all types of gasoline, not including taxes, averaged $1.20.3 a
gallon. In the first eight months of '99 it averaged 74.9 cents a
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   For historical perspective, API says gasoline prices staged a
long decline after the Depression, down to an inflation-adjusted
average (not including taxes) of 97 cents in 1972, when prices
jumped with the 1973-74 oil embargo. Prices climbed even higher in
1979 when Iranian crude supplies were curtailed, reaching an
inflation-adjusted peak of $2.20.3 in 1980. Then they fell,
especially during the winter of 1985-86, owing to the large
production increases by OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   And now they're higher once again, changing so frequently that
it's hard to keep track.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the telephone number to check on a federal tax
refund?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call 1-800-829-4477.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When are the next sets of state quarters going to be issued?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a popular question. The quarters are being issued
over a 10-year period. The first five, in 1999, were Delaware,
Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Georgia and Connecticut. This year's
group: Massachusetts, Maryland, South Carolina, New Hampshire
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining schedule: 2001, New York, North Carolina, Rhode
Island, Vermont, Kentucky; 2002, Tennessee, Ohio, Louisiana,
Indiana, Mississippi; 2003, Illinois, Alabama, Maine, Missouri,
Arkansas; 2004, Michigan, Florida, Texas, Iowa, Wisconsin; 2005,
California, Minnesota, Oregon, Kansas, West Virginia; 2006, Nevada,
Nebraska, Colorado, North Dakota, South Dakota; 2007, Montana,
Washington, Idaho, Wyoming, Utah; 2008, Oklahoma, New Mexico,
Arizona, Alaska, Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're wondering about the sequence, the coins are being
issued in the order in which the states became part of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-872-6468, or online at
www.usmint.gov/50states.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several months ago, it was reported that a student somewhere
in the Carolinas was scheduled to receive a kidney transplant from
his teacher. But the surgery was delayed because he developed a
fever. I never saw anything more about it. What happened?
</P>
<P>
   A: The case involved Michael Carter, a student at Max Abbott
Middle School in Fayetteville, N.C., whose eighth-grade science
teacher, Jane Smith, offered to donate one of her kidneys. As
reported Dec. 18, the surgery, which had been planned at UNC
Hospitals in Chapel Hill, N.C., was postponed in the wake of
Carter's fever.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital spokeswoman Karen Stinneford told Q&AMP;A on March 22 that
the surgery still has not been rescheduled. She added that the
families of both Carter and Smith had been overwhelmed by the
public's response, and although they were grateful that the case
had ``touched a chord in people,'' they had asked hospital
officials not to provide the media with any more information this
time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hoping that when the surgery does take place, they can
slip into the hospital without much fanfare and have the
transplant,'' Stinneford said. ``Then, of course, we would let the
media know.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that the families and doctors hoped the surgery could
be rescheduled soon, but she provided no specific timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Chelsea Clinton taken a leave of absence from Stanford?
I've seen pictures of her in Washington, and taking trips and
making appearances with her parents. A newspaper photo showed her
in India recently with the presidential party.
</P>
<P>
   A: The first daughter is still enrolled at Stanford University,
and the first lady's press office confirmed that Wednesday. She's
on spring break, a spokeswoman said, which allowed her time to join
the current overseas trip.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported several years ago that a U-boat that was sunk
in 1945 was found off the Danish coast. It was supposed to be
recovered and its contents examined. What became of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 255-foot German submarine, which was on its way to the
North Sea and ultimately to Japan, was sunk by a British bomber on
May 5, 1945. It was brought to the surface 15 miles off the small
Danish island of Anholt on Aug. 23, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A Danish consortium, hoping to find jewels, gold and art stolen
from occupied territories, as well as secret documents, financed
the operation to salvage the U-534. But when the sub was opened,
and detonators removed from its torpedoes, salvagers found no such
treasure.
</P>
<P>
   However, they discovered a number of well-preserved supplies and
effects of the U-boat crew, and that was a relative treasure to
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Henrik Linnemann, head of registration and preservation on the
project, credited their preservation after 48 years in salt water
to a thin film of oil caused by leaks inside the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items recovered: nautical maps, logbooks and diaries,
binoculars, gas masks, clothing and tinned food.
</P>
<P>
   The sub's crew of 52 escaped before it sank, but three died in
the water from exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could Al Gore choose Bill Clinton to be his running mate? If
so, and Gore becomes our president and Clinton our vice president,
and then Gore resigns or has to leave office for whatever reason,
could Clinton become our president again?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 12th Amendment to the Constitution states that ``no
person constitutionally ineligible to the office of president shall
be eligible to that of vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How c The intercepted Ecuadoreans were turned over to
Ecuadorean authorities Monday, ending the Coast Guard's
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
