<HEADER>
A1036 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SPENCERTRACY-BDAY30-C     03-29 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPENCERTRACY-BDAY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebrating a century of Spencer Tracy
 &HT;    By Steve Uhler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The story goes that when lanky Katherine Hepburn
was first introduced to Spencer Tracy, she looked down her
aristocratic nose and said, ``You're rather short, aren't you?'' He
responded, smiling confidently, ``Don't worry. I'll cut you down to
size.'' Thus began one of Hollywood's most enduring partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   As an actor, Spencer Tracy cut everyone down to size. Frequently
cited as the screen's all-time greatest (Olivier thought he was the
best), he projected a seemingly effortless, masculine naturalism,
rock solid. Though never a conventionally handsome heartthrob (he
had a face for Mount Rushmore), Tracy conveyed more strength and
conviction than a dozen Erroll Flynns. You never see Spencer Tracy
acting; roles bent to the force of his will like mountains came to
Muhammed.
</P>
<P>
   This Wednesday, April 5, marks the centennial of his birth in
Milwaukee, 1900. Celebrate his 100th birthday by checking out one
of his great performances on video or DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy's early movie roles were marked by playing cocky tough
guys (``20,000 Years In Sing Sing,'' 1932) or second banana to
top-billed Clark Gable (``San Francisco,'' 1935). In 1938, he won
his first Best Actor Oscar for his role as Manuel, the
life-embracing fisherman who teaches spoiled rich kid Freddie
Bartholomew the lessons of life in the seafaring adventure,
``Captains Courageous,'' a still-splendid film, even if Tracy's
Portuguese accent was a bit dodgy. He won again the following year
for his stern but compassionate Father Flanagan in ``Boys Town.''
He was so quietly authoritative that you actually believed him when
he said ``There's no such thing as a bad boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy could handle physically demanding roles. As Major Rogers
in King Vidor's robust ``Northwest Passage'' (1940), he leads a
regimen of Rangers into Canada in the late 1700s to quell Indians
who have been attacking American colonists. A rousing, entertaining
adventure that still looks great (thanks to beautifully rendered
Technicolor photography), ``Northwest Passage'' was originally
intended as the first of a two-part series. The sequel never got
made because Tracy and Vidor didn't get along, but the first half
was splendid enough.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Tracy made several films with real-life love
Katherine Hepburn, including ``Woman of the Year,'' ``Pat and
Mike,'' ``Sea of Grass,'' and ``Desk Set.'' Their chemistry was
tangible both on-screen and off. The best of their co-starring
vehicles is the delightfully witty ``Adam's Rib,'' where they play
Adam and Amanda Bonner, husband-and-wife lawyers on opposite sides
of a particularly volatile battle-of-the-sexes case. Snappy
direction by George Cukor, a sharp script by Ruth Gordon and Garsin
Kanin, and a marvelous performance by Judy Holliday make this
courtroom courtship an absolute delight.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy showed his superb flair for light comedy as bride-to-be
Elizabeth Taylor's doting and harried father in the amiable
``Father of the Bride'' (1950); the part was so successful he
reprised it the following year in ``Father's Little Dividend''
(1951), where Tracy faces the prospect of being a grandfather. Both
films were re-made recently with Steve Martin in the part. While
amusing, the Martin versions lack the originals' depth and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after his performance as Manuel, Tracy returned to
the sea with a tour-de-force performance in the screen adaptation
of Hemingway's epic symbolic struggle between a fisherman and a
giant marlin, ``The Old Man &AMP; The Sea'' (1958). Though slightly
marred by poor back projection, the movie actually improves on the
small screen; its faults aren't as glaring and its strengths _
mostly Tracy's performance _ are still intact. Keep an eye peeled
for a cameo by Hemingway himself in a bar scene near the end.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy's twilight years contained some of his finest hours: The
one-armed war veteran who finds himself an unwelcome visitor in a
hostile desert town that holds a dirty secret in ``Bad Day at Black
Rock'' (1954); the passionate liberal lawyer (based on Clarence
Darrow) in the 1960 courtroom drama ``Inherit The Wind''; the
conflicted judge who is the conscience of Stanley Kramer's
``Judgement at Nuremberg'' (1961). These were meaty, intense roles,
brilliantly played. By the time he got to lighten up in ``It's A
Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World'' (1963), Tracy's old age and failing
constitution were showing (he was a chronic drinker, and suffered
from lung congestion). In some scenes, you can actually see him
drifting away, losing his lines, looking years older than his age.
</P>
<P>
   He rallied for his last film, co-starring again with Hepburn, as
Mathew Drayton, the cantankerous but loving husband and father who
must contend with his daughter's impending interracial marriage to
a young doctor (Sidney Poitier) in 1967's ``Guess Who's Coming To
Dinner?'' Though the script is a bit dated and soggy, Tracy's
performance is a vintage valedictory, funny, touching, and
remarkably rich. I've always believed that during his speech at the
end, where he acknowledges his enduring love and many happy years
with his wife, Hepburn's tears were unscripted. He died two weeks
after completing the film.
</P>
<P>
   The oft-told advice Spencer Tracy gave to younger actors was
``know your lines and try not to bump into the furniture.'' No one
ever caught Spencer Tracy bumping into the furniture. Happy
birthday, Spence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
