w d BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV12-     03-29 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV12-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV12 
 (FOR RELEASE WED., APRIL 12, 2000, AND THEREAFTER) 
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: SPICED PORK WITH POLENTA, BRUSSELS
SPROUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 (th) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For this menu of pork and polenta with brussels sprouts, you
will find quick-cooking polenta has been put on the ``your pantry''
list. The theory is that readers of this column have seen many
recipes call for it so perhaps they are keeping it in the pantry.
</P>
<P>
   It is a wonderful way to enjoy the earthy flavor and texture of
this Italian dish without having to stir it for 45 minutes. Yes, I
know purists will argue that quick-cooking polenta isn't the same
as regular because it isn't as coarsely textured.
</P>
<P>
   But if the choice is between having polenta quickly or not
having it at all, I vote for the quick variety. Polenta is so easy
to make and so satisfying, and the corn meal absorbs the strong
flavors of the pork and its seasonings. When you prepare polenta,
don't cook it so long that it is stiff and will not drop off the
spoon. Cook it just enough so that you can still hear it ``plop.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you plan to reheat polenta by spreading it in a pan and
baking it in an oven or turning it into cakes and sauteing it in a
pan, use the polenta right away because it thickens rapidly after
it is removed from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   The use of fresh ingredients _ the scallions, cilantro and mint
_ makes a refreshing contrast with the earthiness and of the
polenta and pork, and you could use beef or lamb instead of pork in
this dish, if you prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Any green vegetable will be happy with the treatment accorded
the brussels sprouts here: broccoli, green beans, asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   SPICED PORK WITH POLENTA
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces boneless pork loin
</P>
<P>
   Enough ginger to yield 1 tablespoon coarsely grated
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups no-salt-added chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup quick-cooking polenta
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced ripe tomatoes (about 3/4 of a pint basket of cherry
tomatoes, depending on size; l large tomato or 3 or 4 plum
tomatoes)
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 large scallions
</P>
<P>
   Few sprigs cilantro to yield 2 tablespoons chopped
</P>
<P>
   Few sprigs mint to yield 1 tablespoon chopped
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash and dry pork and cut into 1/2 inch chunks.
</P>
<P>
   2. Grate ginger coarsely; crush garlic. Add the ginger, garlic
and cumin to a plastic bag large enough to hold the pork. Add the
pork; seal the bag and coat the pork with the mixture.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat a nonstick pan until it is hot. Reduce heat to medium
high and add oil. Add the pork and brown on all sides, cooking
through, just a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Meanwhile, bring the stock to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   5. Wash, dry and coarsely chop the tomatoes. When pork is brown,
add to the pan. Reduce heat to low, cover and cook until tomatoes
soften, just a couple of minutes. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   6. Slowly add the polenta into the boiling stock, constantly
stirring; reduce heat and cook the polenta until it has absorbed
all the liquid.
</P>
<P>
   7. Wash the scallions and trim. Slice the white portion and a
little of the green; wash and dry the cilantro and mint and
coarsely chop.
</P>
<P>
   8. Spoon the polenta onto two plates and top with pork and
tomatoes. Sprinkle with scallions, cilantro and mint and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS SPROUTS WITH OLIVE OIL DRIZZLE
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces brussels sprouts
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash and trim sprouts and steam over water for 7 to 10
minutes, depending on size.
</P>
<P>
   2. Drain, drizzle with olive oil and season with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare pork through step 2
</P>
<P>
   Prepare brussels sprouts through step 1
</P>
<P>
   Continue with pork and polenta through step 7
</P>
<P>
   Finish brussels sprouts
</P>
<P>
   Finish pork
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Fresh or frozen ginger
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil and extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   No salt added chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   Quick-cooking polenta
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces boneless pork loin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ripe tomatoes, cherry, plum or regular
</P>
<P>
   Bunch scallions (2)
</P>
<P>
   Bunch cilantro (2 tablespoons)
</P>
<P>
   Bunch mint (1 tablespoon)
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces brussels sprouts
</P>
<P>
   Nutrition Information per serving: 510 calories; 20 grams fat,
85 milligrams cholesterol, 265 milligrams sodium, 40 grams protein;
45 grams carbohydrate.
</P>
