<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Thursday, March
30, 2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA: Local cemeteries alive with history
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters.
Photos and a sig/locator map are available.)
</P>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Listen closely. The dead might be talking. But
don't be alarmed. It's not the chain-rattling, haunting kind of
talking. Instead, the dead are spinning their tales into the web of
history even as they rest in local cemeteries _ cemeteries that
play an important role in preserving the past, according to Dr.
Norman Black. Black is a Longview, Texas, dentist who has headed
the Gregg County Historical Commission for 15 years. ``We don't
have anything spectacular here, but we do have some oddities,''
Black said. Among those oddities is a mystery that captivated
Longview in 1975. (Hammer, Longview News Journal). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FETUS-PHOTO _ DOUGLASVILLE, Ga. _ Baby pictures of Samuel Armas
of Douglasville were taken a little earlier than usual, and
circulated more widely. Samuel, now 3 months old, was a 21-week-old
fetus with spina bifida when a freelance photographer shot his
penny-sized hand emerging from an incision in his mother's uterus
during controversial surgery to correct the defect. Weeks later,
Samuel became an inadvertent celebrity: The photo was on Page 1 of
USA Today and subsequently went worldwide as a kind of
right-to-life icon. (Internet gossip Matt Drudge lost his Fox TV
show in a dispute over using the photo.) Samuel was born in
December and in their first interview since the birth, his parents
Julie and Alex Armas of Douglasville talk about how their
opposition to abortion led them to discover the risky surgery, and
their amazement and bemusement (part discomfort, part belief in
God's plan) that their infant son's image stimulated reaction
worldwide. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUYER'S-EDGE _ With stores such as Target and Kmart taking the
lead, there's a design revolution going on in the aisles of mass
merchandisers. We explore the trend and offer up 10 finds we love.
(Brooks, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-GUIDE _ A weekly feature telling how to locate
hard-to-fnd items. (Johnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (EDS: Moving on l (Lifestyle) and a
(General News) categories.) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOOD _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOOD page for the current
week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOOD 0328: SPRING GREENING -- Nothing says spring like
tender, young leaves from the garden. Those heavy, leafy greens we
ate during the winter have given way to sweet baby spinach, Swiss
chard, broccoli raab and peppery cress. The epitome of ``fast
food,'' these fresh greens cook in minutes and are packed with
nutrients. Add them to salads, bake them in stratas or saute a
handful as a nest for a grilled fish fillet. Here's a quick guide
to spring greens. Color, nutrition, taste and convenience is yours
for the picking. (Norris, Palm Beach Daily News) Art includes
5-column color illustration detailing eight different kinds of
greens.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MEXICO'S WINE RENAISSANCE -- The Pacific coast of Mexico
could soon rival California's Napa Valley as a producer of
delicious wine. (Ferriss, Cox Washington Bureau) Art includes a
1-column color photo of a winemaker pouring a glass of wine at his
winery.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES -- Yellow Squash and Greens Gratin, Fresh Baby
Spinach Sauce with Chives, Watercress, Celery and Red Onion Salad,
and Traditional Cucumber and Watercress Tea Sandwiches.
</P>
