<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC (Vienna, Austria) _ Complaining about U.S. pressure on the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, Iran said Wednesday
that it would join other OPEC members and increase crude oil
production to avoid losing its share of the market. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 12:30 p.m. EST)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-GUYANA (Lethem, Guyana) _ Brazil, the giant of South
America with 170 million people, is busy flexing its economic
muscle these days, relentlessly pressing forward with policies
aimed at strengthening ties with its neighbors. And tiny Guyana,
nestled on Brazil's northern flank, with a population of just
800,000 but with port access to the Caribbean, is squarely on its
radar.
</P>
<P>
   EMBRAER-EARNINGS (Sao Paulo) _ Empresa Brasileira de
Aeronautica, one of Brazil's most successful companies, says
earnings more than quadrupled in the fourth quarter because of
strong demand for its jetliners. The results at Embraer, as it is
known for short, greatly exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPS-CZECH (Prague, Czech Republic) _ Royal Philips
Electronics, the Dutch consumer electronics giant, will build one
of the world's largest television tube factories in the Czech
Republic. The project, which could cost more than $500 million, is
the biggest single foreign investment in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-WRITER (New York) _ Jachym Topol, one of the leading
literary voices to emerge in the Czech Republic after the fall of
Communist rule, discusses his novel that will soon be available in
English. By Alison Smale.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   DESERT-PILGRIMS (Buenos Aires, Ariz.) _ A multicultural group of
O'odham, Comcaac and Yoeme Indians, as well as their
botanist-ecologist friends walked 240 miles from a Mexican village
on the Sea of Cortez, across the Sonoran Desert to Tucson, Ariz.,
following the steps of their ancestors. Eating only native foods
and treating their ailments with wild plants from the desert, they
walked to raise awareness of diabetes, which affects 250,000 Native
Americans in the Southwest. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `l' news category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARTDECO-CLUB (New York) _ After eight months of renovations
and $600,000, the Lenox Lounge, the legendary Harlem night spot
built in 1939 _ the year Billie Holiday first sang ``Strange
Fruit'' _ is reopening: the sole surviving Art Deco club interior
in New York City. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `l' news category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Will move in `s' news category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-METS-CUBS-JAPAN (Tokyo) _ Short on drama, long on tedium,
the first major-league game ever held outside North America looked
mundanely like thousands of other games, particularly those held
indoors _ except of course for the presence of the Crown Prince of
Japan. The Chicago Cubs beat the New York Mets, 5-3, Wednesday
night, 13 and 14 time zones ahead of their respective home cities.
By George Vecsey.
</P>
