<P>
   MISSING-STUDENTS (San Francisco) _ For a team of UC-Davis
students and scholars, it was to be a routine, weeklong research
trip on remote islands off the coast of Baja California, but it
ended up costing at least three of them their lives when their
inflatable boat capsized in high waves as they tried to return to
shore. By ANASTASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CONDOMS (Austin, Texas) _ Among the items that will soon be
exempt from the state sales tax in Texas are condoms. The
exemption, part of a bill signed by Gov. George W. Bush, is not the
kind of tax cut that makes some conservatives happy. By RUSSELL
GOLD and CINDY TUMIEL.
</P>
<P>
   CASINO-BRIBE (Baton Rouge, La.) _ Getting mixed up with a
smooth-talking politician like former Louisiana Gov. Edwin W.
Edwards was the worst thing he ever did, and he's paid a dear price
for that involvement, Eddie DeBartolo says. DeBartolo left the
witness stand Tuesday after two days of testimony that was
alternately forceful, pathetic, persuasive and contradictory in
Louisiana's epic riverboat casino licensing racketeering case. By
ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ The California Legislature
is moving to grant gay and lesbian couples some of the same legal
rights that automatically come with marriage, just three weeks
after California voters overwhelmingly approved a ballot measure
defining marriage as between a man and a woman. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   NAZIS-INSURANCE (San Francisco) _ The largest reinsurance
company in the world once had strong ties with Adolf Hitler, and is
now ``hiding out'' overseas to avoid an investigation of
Holocaust-era insurance claims, state officials contend. By PETER
HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   ATOM-TRAPPING (San Francisco) _ Like pool sharks, scientists are
using lasers to nudge ``clouds'' of atoms into tiny ``traps'' where
the particles' properties can be studied. ``Atom trapping'' is
helping scientists to test the merits of the so-called ``standard
model'' of physics that dominates physics textbooks. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-PROSECUTORS (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Attorney General John
Cornyn has invited lobbyists to a resort here as part of his effort
to get Republicans elected as attorneys general in other states.
Among the leading speakers at the gathering is Karl Rove, the chief
strategist for Gov. George W. Bush's presidential campaign. By
PEGGY FIKAC. (Already filed.)
</P>
