<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-1000(2T     03-29 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO BATTERS FORT WORTH, ARLINGTON; AT LEAST 3 PEOPLE KILLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERNIE MAKOVY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Officials in Fort Worth and Arlington on
Wednesday began the massive task of cleaning up the devastation of
tornadoes that killed at least three people, leveled buildings,
shattered skyscraper windows and shut down downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Two men were crushed to death on the outskirts of downtown _ one
by a truck trailer that toppled onto him and the other by a
collapsing wall _ as the tornado plowed its way through the heart
of the city at about 6:30 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities on Wednesday recovered the body of a third victim, a
man who was swept away with his grandmother in floodwaters from the
Trinity River. The grandmother remained missing Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   City officials closed much of the downtown business district
Wednesday, barricading it as fears mounted that cracked plate-glass
windows would break loose from skyscrapers and rain onto downtown
streets. Officials said at least parts of downtown will remained
closed through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The first deadly twister to hit Fort Worth was followed by a
second tornado about 30 minutes later in southeast Arlington, where
at least six homes were leveled and about a 100 more were damaged.
No injuries were reported in that storm.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth officials said seven buildings on the west side
collapsed and a search was being conducted Wednesday for possible
victims still trapped in the debris.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of people were injured in Fort Worth, at least two
critically, as buildings were ripped apart and flying shards of
glass crashed onto downtown streets at about 6:20 p.m., just as
many people headed home from work.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most seriously hurt was a man struck by a hailstone
that paramedics reported was the size of a softball, said Dr.
Michael Hickey, a trauma surgeon at Harris Methodist Fort Worth
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire skull is fractured, so it'd have to take a
tremendous force,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials closed the area ``to make sure downtown is safe
before we allow people to return,'' Mayor Kenneth Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way in the dark to know what the situation is,''
Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said it was ``somewhat a miracle'' that more people
did not suffer serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, Mayor Elzie Odom declared a state of emergency
that granted police broad powers to limit access to the damaged
areas.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Reps. Kay Granger, R-Fort Worth, and Martin Frost,
D-Dallas, offered Fort Worth federal assistance Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   TXU Electric &AMP; Gas had 30,000 customers without service in Fort
Worth and Arlington. The hardest-hit areas were downtown, the north
and west parts of Fort Worth, south Arlington around Collins Street
and Interstate 20, and Grand Prairie, TXU spokeswoman Carol Peters
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth tornado tore a devastating 2-mile-long swath
stretching roughly from University Drive to just east of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologist Harold Brooks of the National Severe Storms
Laboratory in Norman, Okla., said the storm probably reached F2
intensity on the Fujita scale, which is used to measure the
strength of tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit were the Mallick Tower at One Summit Avenue, the
Cash America building at 1600 W. Seventh St., the Bank One Tower
downtown, Tandy Center and Calvary Cathedral International, where
all the brickwork on the steeple was ripped off, exposing steel
beams.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen cars in the area were flipped over or tossed on
their sides.
</P>
<P>
   One of two homeless men who sought shelter under a porch of the
empty Burns Graphics Building, on West Seventh at the Trinity
River, was killed when a wall behind them collapsed. He was
identified as Carl Spence, 67.
</P>
<P>
   Spence's companion, John Barr, 70, was also buried under the
debris but was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fell upon me and I was under a pile of bricks,'' Barr said.
``When I looked back, I saw it fell on him, too. When I got up and
got back to him, I realized he was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Another dead man was identified as Howard D. Thornton, 52. He
was crushed by a truck trailer that flipped onto him behind the
landmark Montgomery Ward catalog building on West Seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The area behind the 70-year-old building, which survived the
April 1949 floodwaters that reached the second floor, was a
shambles of crazily twisted truck trailers jammed against the
loading dock.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton ``was warning people back by the guard shack to get
down, get down, but the tornado caught up with him and he didn't
make it,'' said Frank Godoy, 26, a Montgomery Ward maintenance
worker from Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Pieces of glass, chunks of metal and building panels continued
falling to the West Seventh Street pavement an hour after the
storm. Trees surrounding the building were bent and broken. Light
poles were crushed against trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it looks like we are all alive,'' said Jose Rico,
director of marketing for Cash America International, who had left
his seventh-floor office five minutes before the storm hit and got
into his car, and then ``I ran back into the building.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
d nn
</P>
<P>
   ``This is incredible. My office is gone. I haven't found my car
yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour after the Fort Worth tornado, another twister
ravaged a southeast Arlington neighborhood near Bardin and Matlock
roads at about 7 p.m. Several retail businesses and a gas station
were heavily damaged, roofs were ripped off and buildings were
flattened.
</P>
<P>
   About eight houses in the area sustained heavy damage, and 30
houses sustained minor damage. An additional two dozen homes in the
area near Williams Elementary School were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just felt like the oxygen got sucked out of the house and
you could hear glass breaking and stuff flying around,'' said J.D.
Walker, who with his wife and 3-year-old twins, covered themselves
with a mattress as winds swept through their neighborhood in the
300 block of Chasemore Lane, just south of Interstate 20.
</P>
<P>
   Other neighbors walked up and down the darkened streets,
carrying flashlights, as they checked on damage and offered help to
one another.
</P>
<P>
   Several dogs ran free through the streets after the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the fences are down _ there's dogs running everywhere,''
said Arlington police Cpl. Michael Van Steenburg.
</P>
<P>
   The building housing the regional office of the Texas Department
of Health and the Department of Human Services, on Bardin between
Collins and New York, was heavily damaged. The entire east side
appeared to be stripped away.
</P>
<P>
   The post office next door also appeared to have been severely
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Ava Mitchell of Fort Worth was working in the Lear plant on
Bardin at about 7 p.m. and was caught off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anything. We just heard it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the storm passed the damage was evident: Two truck
trailers on the west side of building were overturned. In a field
behind the building, the air-conditioning units from the roof were
strewn about.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, the Rev. Bob Nichols of Calvary Cathedral
International watched in awe from his church office as water from
the Trinity River spiraled into the sky and roared toward his
church at 1600 W. Fifth St.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have been ripped to shreds if I hadn't run into the
hallway with my wife and two other church members,'' said Nichols,
whose office faces west toward the river. ``We didn't even hear
anything before it hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Only steel beams remained of the cathedral's 5-story tower from
the second story to the steeple. Bricks and mortar from the church
were strewn nearly 200 feet across Penn Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like this building has been bombed,'' Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   East of the church, Louis Zapata was among five people inside
the Summit Building, 1500 W. Fifth St., which was hammered by the
tornado. Walls crumbled and most of the building's roof was ripped
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``My computer shut off, then the lights went out, so I bent down
to get a flashlight out of my bag,'' said Zapata, 65, a lifelong
resident of Fort Worth who was on the second floor. ``When I bent
down, the roof started to just rip off and the walls started
disappearing. Everything was blowing everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good Lord said to me, `Bend down and pick up your life,'''
he said. ``It was a good solid desk. If it would have moved, I
would have had it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the downtown YMCA, Robert Viana watched as the tornado cut
its deadly path.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking out the window and you could see a funnel of
debris heading right toward us,'' said Viana, 39, of Fort Worth.
``It looked like fingers dangling from the sky. There definitely
was more than one cloud coming down. We started yelling to
everybody and we all took off for the stairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressing himself against the glass in a 28th-floor office at the
City Center Two Tower, Joe Garbe could see the black tornado
weaving between buildings downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a vortex,'' Garbe said. ``You could see the lights
sparking different colors and then go dead.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials sought to evacuate everyone from downtown who
does not live there because of several major areas of concern.
</P>
<P>
   A major gas leak was reported at 3000 W. Seventh St. In
addition, damage done to buildings caused officials to declare
areas around Sundance West, the Cash America building and the UPR
Building areas of major concern.
</P>
<P>
   Severe damage was reported at a 7-Eleven store near University
and Seventh streets. Trees and debris were scattered across the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Urban Search and Rescue team was deployed from College
Station last night to help Fort Worth officials. The team, which
includes structural engineers, is expected to arrive this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were arrested, suspected of looting the Cash
America building.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, along I-20 east of Cooper, police reported that
eight semi-trailer trucks had overturned on the highway and that as
many as 15 houses were damaged around Matlock Road and I-20.
</P>
<P>
   The storm lost much of its punch as it swept east. Little damage
was reported in Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
