<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1066 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-GOP-PROSECUTORS-HNS &LR;      03-29 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PROSECUTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH AIDE UNDER FIRE FOR SPEAKING TO GROUP OF GOP PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At a time when campaign finances are a
ballyhooed issue in the presidential race, Gov. George W. Bush's
chief political strategist is a featured speaker Friday for a group
that is under fire for its fund-raising to help elect Republican
attorneys general across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Strategist Karl Rove is scheduled to give a political briefing
to the Republican Attorneys General Association (RAGA), which meets
at the Barton Creek Resort here Thursday and Friday. The meeting is
closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   A Thursday reception that had been scheduled at the Governor's
Mansion, which the Bush presidential campaign said the governor
never planned to attend, has been moved to a restaurant. The
association said the restaurant is larger.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has repeatedly criticized Vice President Al Gore for the
Democrat's past fund-raising problems. Both candidates have said
they want to change campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
   Two watchdog groups that look at campaign finances, the Center
for Public Integrity and Texans for Public Justice, criticized RAGA
for soliciting corporate donations and not disclosing specifically
who donates.
</P>
<P>
   Donations to the association, which is part of the Republican
National Committee, are reported to the Federal Election Commission
by the RNC.
</P>
<P>
   The watchdog groups contend that the corporate donors are at
least potentially gaining influential allies and access, including
access to Rove.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Republicans dismissed the criticism as ridiculous
and said attorneys general would not hold back from prosecuting
lawbreakers due to contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters also noted that the group is separate from
Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl was invited to give a political briefing. That's the
extent of his involvement,'' said Scott McClellan, a Bush campaign
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Rove has been a campaign consultant to two attorneys general who
led the Republican association, including Texas Attorney General
John Cornyn, said RNC press secretary Mike Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl was speaking to groups like this before Bush was even
governor. He is well-respected and well-known in his own right,''
added Ray Sullivan, spokesman for Texas Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, also a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Some questioned the credibility of the watchdog groups, noting
in part that Texans for Public Justice refuses to disclose its
donors. Both the Texas group and the Washington-based Center for
Public Integrity describe themselves as nonprofit and non-partisan.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, speaking for the attorneys general association, also
contended the Democratic Governors' Association has been more
secretive in its fund-raising, partly because it files its reports
state-by-state rather than with the Federal Election Commission.
George Shelton of the Democratic group said that is what it is
required to do.
</P>
<P>
   The RNC goes beyond what is required by federal law by filing
its reports monthly, said Collins. The attorneys general
association has raised $525,000 since it was formed a year ago, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn has helped solicit association members, who pay $5,000 to
$25,000 or more to belong, according to a mailing sent to
lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Attorneys General Association was born out of
concerns arising out of recent industry-wide lawsuits that seek to
promote policy changes via the courthouse rather than the
statehouse,'' said a letter signed by Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn added in a Tuesday statement, ``As attorney general, I
will always take action against those who have broken the law. No
exceptions. No excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An article by Marianne Holt and Kathryn Wallace posted on the
Web site of the Center for Public Integrity said: ``At the very
least, association with RAGA could give businesses advance word of
costly state-prosecuted lawsuits, such as claims against the
tobacco industry that cost the industry some $246 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``At best, corporations that join RAGA secure potential allies
in the White House and advocates in the offices of attorneys
general who could discourage joining in such litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig McDonald of Texans for Public Justice said of the GOP
attorneys general, ``It appears they are selling immunity to large
corporate contributors.''
</P>
<P>
   He said for Rove to participate is unseemly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is happening, it appears RAGA is not only selling
immunity from attorneys general but also selling access to what
might be the new White House,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn lashed back at McDonald's group, calling it ``a secretive
front group for the trial lawyers, who don't like that I've stood
for conservative principles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponents practice politics by litigation and want to
further enrich themselves by using the power of the state against
law-abiding citizens. I believe that I should fairly enforce the
law, not make social policy through the courthouse,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
