<HEADLINE>
FACING CORRUPTION CHARGES, TOP MINISTER RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Thailand's tough and powerful interior
minister resigned Wednesday after a newly formed anti-corruption
agency charged that he had concealed his assets by fabricating a
million-dollar loan.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of the minister, Sanan Kachornprasart, is a
severe blow to the ruling party at the start of an election year in
which Sanan had been expected to play a major role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am innocent,'' Sanan said in his resignation statement. ``I
will prove the truth in the Constitutional Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanan is the most powerful public official that the National
Counter-Corruption Commission has targeted since it was formed in
1997 as part of a wide-ranging attempt to reform Thai politics.
</P>
<P>
   According to the commission, Sanan falsely claimed to have
borrowed 45 million baht ($1.21 million) from a private company in
an attempt to conceal his assets.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth of the charges against him, the fact that an
independent body toppled one of the most influential figures in
Thai politics was a sign that the landscape of the nation's deeply
corrupt political system has begun to shift.
</P>
<P>
   A separate commission, also formed under Thailand's new
constitution, that monitors electoral fraud has in recent weeks
disqualified 78 of the 200 winners in an election last month to the
newly formed Senate. One of those disqualified was Sanan's wife.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Sanan, 64, said he was resigning from all his
government positions, which include a deputy premiership and a seat
in Parliament. He said this would avoid any suggestion that he was
influencing the conduct of his case, which now goes before a
special Constitutional Court. The court was also recently formed
and adjudicates issues involving the country's new liberal charter.
</P>
<P>
   If the court rules against him, he could be banned from any
political activity for five years, whether or not he holds any
office.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a severe blow to the Democratic Party, which came
into office in the depths of the Asian economic crisis in late
1997. The party, led by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, is credited
with cleaning up the country's fiscal affairs and restoring
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposition _ which was notoriously corrupt during the
years it held power _ has leveled continuing charges of corruption
against the Democratic Party. One of those charges led to the
investigation of Sanan.
</P>
<P>
   Sanan said Wednesday that he would remain as the party's
secretary-general and would play a key role in the party in advance
of the elections that Chuan must call before November.
</P>
<P>
   But the party's political future and its coalition government
have now been thrown into uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credibility of the whole coalition is also at stake, given
the fact that Sanan, the government's Mr. Fixit, is such a central
figure,'' the Bangkok Post, the English-language daily, said
Wednesday in an editorial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The question of replacing Sanan as interior minister is expected
to be a difficult political challenge for Chuan as he balances the
forces of his coalition, and it has led to speculation that the
prime minister might call an early election.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the Interior Ministry, Ong-art Klampaiboon,
said, ``There is no reason to think there will be any change in
government for the moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1307EST &QL; 
