<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1077 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BUSH-CONDOMS-HNS &LR;      03-29 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONDOMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS TAX CUT GIVES BREAK TO CONDOM BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUSSELL GOLD and CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At the University of Texas at San Antonio,
students can walk into the health center and grab a handful of free
condoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students are not hesitant at all to come in and ask for
them,'' said James Sawyer, the health center director.
</P>
<P>
   Such events, repeated on campuses across the country, are a
telltale sign that the availability of condoms for students is
becoming less controversial as Americans recognize the role
prophylactics can play in preventing not only unwanted pregnancy,
but the transmission of disease.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as recent events demonstrate, condoms can still pack a
political punch, especially when presidential ambitions are at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   On March 21, the Texas comptroller released a list of
over-the-counter medicines and health aids that will become exempt
from the sales tax on April 1. Condoms are on the list.
</P>
<P>
   This puts Gov. George W. Bush in an awkward position.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, an advocate of sexual abstinence for teen-agers, got a
widespread, popular tax cut passed last year before launching his
presidential campaign. The bill he signed into law eliminated the
sales tax on condoms, an unpopular move with certain conservative
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Cathie Adams, president of the conservative Texas Eagle Forum,
said tax-free condoms will promote promiscuity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is loath to talk about the issue. His spokesman, Mike
Jones, said, ``The governor has stated before that abstinence is
the only 100 percent effective way to prevent pregnancy and
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones noted the vast majority of the $160 million tax cut
involves such items as vitamins and aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bush is afraid of appearing to give tacit approval to
premarital sex, studies have shown that the elimination of sales
taxes on condoms will not encourage promiscuity, said Michael Ross,
a public health professor at the University of Texas-Houston Health
Science Center.
</P>
<P>
   If the price of condoms is lowered, ``all that will happen is
that the people who are promiscuous will continue to be
promiscuous, but they will not be transmitting the diseases they
would otherwise be transmitting,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas spends $3.6 million per year to combat the notion among
teens and pre-teens that sexual activity among middle school
students is expected, said Rachelle Hill, head of the abstinence
education program at the state Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you bring in the use of contraceptives, you are already
implying that sexual activity is accepted,'' she said. So condoms
and other birth control are not discussed.
</P>
<P>
   The state money is matched by federal funds, a program that
Bush, the presumed Republican presidential nominee, has called for
expanding.
</P>
<P>
   Condoms are a health issue and should not become a political
issue, said Peggy Romberg, executive director of the Texas Family
Planning Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get very frustrated that so much public health policy is
being driven by politics and what religious extremists want, as
opposed to basing public health policy on what is good for the
health and well-being of Texas citizens,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For public health workers, condoms are not a scandalous item. In
San Antonio, Bexar County officials respond to outbreaks of
sexually transmitted diseases by handing out condoms on the street,
in bars and even at flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say that (condoms are) probably the most effective
method of preventing the spread of sexually transmitted disease and
also of preventing unwanted pregnancies,'' said Dr. Fernando
Guerra, director of the San Antonio Metropolitan Health District.
</P>
<P>
   But Adams of the Texas Eagle Forum said the wrong message is
being sent when the government makes getting condoms easier, either
through a tax cut or free distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as parents, and certainly our governor, have been saying
that we want our children to be abstinent from sexual activity
until they are married,'' she said. The state tax code, by
providing an incentive to buy condoms, creates a mixed message, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tax exemption for condoms became part of the law almost by
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rodney Ellis, a Democrat from Houston, introduced the first
version of the bill in 1999. His legislation would have cut the
sales tax on diapers and other medicine for children, but not
condoms.
</P>
<P>
   He did not want his bill ``bogging down into a divisive
argument,'' spokesman Jeremy Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had proposed a similar tax cut in 1998 as a way to help
families. He, too, ruled out condoms.
</P>
<P>
   To simplify matters, Ellis' bill was rewritten to state that all
medicinal items ``labeled with a national drug code'' would be
exempt from the sales tax. Prophylactics help prevent the spread
sexually transmitted diseases, so the federal government gave them
a drug code. But the bill was still targeted at children's
medicine, ruling out condoms.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, an amendment was tacked on to greatly expand the
reach of the tax cut. The new version covered all over-the-counter
medicines and health aids, not just those for children.
</P>
<P>
   These two sets of changes opened the door for condoms.
</P>
<P>
   As the only pharmacist in the Texas House, then-state Rep.
Leticia Van de Putte, a Democrat from San Antonio, said she made
her fellow lawmakers aware of the new amendment's implications. She
is now a state senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mentioned to my colleagues on the House floor that (the
amendment) included things below the belly button,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Roberto Gutierrez, a Democrat from McAllen, who
helped write the amendment, said few questions were asked about
condoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one asked,'' he said, ``and no one said.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1307EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
