<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1111 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BRIT-BANDS-HNS &LR;      03-29 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIT-BANDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FROM BRITAIN, A ROYAL TREAT WITH A BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE GANAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The British are coming! Again.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's wishful thinking since I'm a sucker for all things
Britpop, but I have a feeling that 2000 will be year in which the
United Kingdom's jangly psychedelia stages another siege on these
shores.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits last ruled in 1997, spearheaded by the Verve and
Radiohead, and secondarily assaulted by Kula Shaker and Blur. And
the signs are there for a repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the hottest tickets in San Francisco so far in
this short year were (a) the Cure at the Fillmore (b) Travis, at
the Bottom of the Hill, who will be returning with Oasis to the
Berkeley Community Theatre April 8.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Wheel's April-due album and tour is buzz-worthy.
Elastica's new album is so eagerly anticipated that songs are being
leaked on the Internet. And Richard Ashcroft, singer-songwriter for
the now-defunct Verve, has finished a much-ballyhooed solo album
and is soon to tour behind it.
</P>
<P>
   But the newest tangible evidence of a U.K.-based uprising was
heard Tuesday night at the Warfield, where two of the island
nation's most popular bands lit up the chilly sky: the venerable
standard-bearers Charlatans UK, and relative upstarts
Stereophonics, from Wales.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd to think that these two bands could fill Wembly Stadium
in London with 50,000 screaming fans, but in this country are still
just a notch above curiosities. Still, that may yet change,
especially for Stereophonics, who have potentially greater
alt-rock-radio appeal than Charlatans. Both bands are fronted by
gorgeous, emotive (if diminutive) singers _ also a plus in MTV
land.
</P>
<P>
   Stereophonics' excellent new album, ``Performance and
Cocktails,'' earned them several Brit Awards nominations (the
equivalent of our Grammys). In their hour-long opening set (this
tour is more of a co-headliner setup), Stereophonics showed why
they were causing such a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Kelly Jones has an engagingly hoarse tenor, somewhere
between Paul Westerberg and Rod Stewart, writes impressively
literate lyrics, and knows how to interpret a song. A high point
was the band's U.K. Stonesy hit, ``The Bartender and the Thief,''
which rocked the house down. Also excellent were the haunting
``Hurry Up and Wait,'' and the anthemic ``I Wouldn't Believe Your
Radio.'' Like Travis' show last month, this one was all about the
song, which meant lulls while ballads were crooned.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Charlatans UK flat-out rocked, with nary a
dip in intensity. In the early `190s, the band, along with the
Stone Roses and Happy Mondays, helped define what became known as
the ``Manchester sound.'' Because they never made it as big as
their imitators (who include pretty much everyone mentioned above),
there's always confusion as to who influenced whom, but listening
to the band Tuesday night, and to their excellent, watershed new
album, ``Us and Us Only,'' it was clear that this is a band that
has developed its sound to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Singer-heartthrob Tim Burgess (who was still a teen when
Charlatans formed) showed off his eccentric, floppy-handed delivery
and pouty lips to perfection, although his normally hearty and
fluid vocals were much diminished by a cold. Opening with the
Dylan-fused ``Forever,'' Charlatans UK laid claim to the stage with
the authority of a band that's played together for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impossible,'' their newest single, was simple and poignant,
and smacked of alternative country. ``Senses'' was bluesy euphoria,
reminiscent of the Stones' ``Exile on Main Street'' era. And with
``A House is Not a Home,'' they exploded with a joyful noise
reminiscent of the Verve's majestic show here two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cross your fingers that the euphoria felt among audience members
will translate to record sales and radio play. If this is the
British invasion, I hope they win the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
