<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-AFRICA-HUNGER-$ADV01-     03-29 1539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-HUNGER-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUILDING AN AFRICAN BREADBASKET, ONE ACRE AT A TIME
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With chart information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Kano is in north-central
Nigeria, about 80 miles from the Niger border.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., April 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANO, Nigeria _ Squinting in the hot West African sun, farmer
Sabo Garba wades into the waste-high wheat that has turned the pale
amber color of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is perfection,'' Othman Yahaya Othman shouts to Garba
with pride. ``This is what it is supposed to look like.''
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Othman has worked with Garba, showing him how to
increase his yield of crops with new methods of farming. This
harvest will represent a passage of sorts: Garba now will employ
these new techniques on the rest of his land and teach his
neighbors by example.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it also will represent a small passage for all of
Africa, which has been struggling for decades to feed its
burgeoning population.
</P>
<P>
   Othman is the Kano state coordinator for Sasakawa Global 2000, a
joint venture of the Tokyo-based Sasakawa Africa Association and
Global 2000, an arm of the Carter Center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Kano rests on an arid plain a hot breeze away from the Sahara
desert. But beneath much of the dusty plain lies fresh water _ in
some places just a few feet underground. When the land is properly
irrigated and farmed, it is immensely productive.
</P>
<P>
   Othman envisions an African breadbasket stretching more than 400
miles across northern Nigeria to Lake Chad. ``When you see this
here, it's only a start,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospects for this vision are uncertain. Nigeria is
struggling in its first year under a fledgling democracy. The new
government's agriculture policies _ which can be life or death to
small farmers _ have as yet to take. And peace in Africa is always
tenuous. Recent weeks in Nigeria have included spurts of sectarian
violence between Muslims and Christians _ killing more than 3,000
people in one violent episode.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Othman has continued making his rounds to the
farmers. On test plots of an acre or less, he teaches them how to
apply fertilizer, to plant disease-resistant seeds and better
methods of pest control and weeding.
</P>
<P>
   SG 2000 insists that farmers adhere strictly to the regimen.
When they stray, they are dropped to make way for farmers who will
follow the rules.
</P>
<P>
   When the recipe is followed faithfully, the results can be
dramatic _ doubling, and even tripling yields.
</P>
<P>
   Using the methods he learned as a boy, Garba used to get five
bags of wheat _ less than half a ton _ from his parcel of an acre
or so carved out of the dry brown savanna. Now he expects to
harvest 13 bags _ about a ton and a half _ from the same land.
</P>
<P>
   Even though wheat prices have become depressed by an influx of
cheap imports since the government removed restrictions on
agricultural products, Garba expects to make a little extra money.
He intends to invest some of it in his small appliance shop in the
nearby village.
</P>
<P>
   SG 2000 organizers are committed to using farmers such as Garba
as the medium for their message. ``We depend on farmers showing
other farmers how this works _ they teach each other,'' says Jose
Antonio Valencia, SG 2000's director for Nigeria and the only
non-African working with the program in the country.
</P>
<P>
   When the program came to Nigeria eight years ago, the SG 2000
system was greeted with skepticism. Initially, it requires more
labor, precision and money than traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers must sow within narrow windows of time, space plants
according to exact measurements and work precise amounts of
fertilizer into the soil rather than simply tossing a handful on a
young plant. To make measuring fertilizer easier, SG 2000 had
special spoons made.
</P>
<P>
   When Garba first heard the organization's pitch, he listened
with wizened suspicion. ``At first I was thinking that this won't
work, that they're planting these too close together, But, now,
look,'' he says pointing at his second dense crop of wheat.
</P>
<P>
   SG 2000 uses few outside experts and places on farmers the
burden of using the new techniques and financing seed and
fertilizer. Early on, the program provided loans to farmers to get
started. Now, farmers must pay in advance for seed and fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, farmers work with the program about two years, long
enough to learn the system but not so long that they become
dependent.
</P>
<P>
   Even though farmers must invest more time, money and energy on
their crops, their yields and incomes tend to rise by more than
enough to justify the trouble. Average yields of corn have more
than tripled using the techniques, while wheat has enjoyed similar
success.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been in Africa since the mid-1980s. It has
operated in a dozen countries in addition to Nigeria, and has been
credited with dramatic increases in corn, wheat and rice production
throughout the sub-Saharan region.
</P>
<P>
   Its methods were developed by Norman Borlaug, the American
agronomist who heads the Sasakawa part of the venture. Borlaug won
the Nobel Peace Prize in 1970 for breeding the high-yield wheat
that set off Asia's green revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which has involved more than 12,000 Nigerian
farmers, operates in six states here, mostly in the poor, rural
north.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is seen as crucial to the goal of making Africa
self-sufficient for food. With more than 110 million people,
Nigeria is home to 20 percent of the people in sub-Saharan Africa
and the largest and most influential country in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the SG 2000 program nearly gave up on Nigeria, which in 15
years of military rule became one of the world's most dangerous and
corrupt places. ``It was very difficult dealing with the military
regime,'' said Valencia, who also is the country director for
Malawi.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Corruption, which for decades has entered every facet of
Nigerian existence, also consumed SA 2000's resources. ``Out of a
budget of $500,000, maybe $200,000 would actually get to the
farms,'' Valencia said, adding that government officials appeared
to be more interested in lining their pockets than seeing farmers
progress into the modern age. ``Nobody has been willing to teach
the farmers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Things were so bad that Valencia said he was reluctant to bring
new cars into Nigeria despite the severe needs of his staff.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   SG 2000 officials decided to stay only after last year's
election of Olusegun Obasanjo as president. Obasanjo, a respected
chicken farmer, also is a former member of SG 2000's board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties of working in such an environment, the
program has endured because it has remained focused, Valencia said.
``We bypass everybody and go directly to the farmers _ that's the
only way it works.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Winning farmers over to fertilizer and new seeds is only half
the battle. The other half is convincing governments to pursue
policies that provide farmers high enough prices to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   While SG 2000 has shown the region's potential for growing
wheat, the Nigerian government has undermined these efforts by
allowing in nearly unlimited cheap imported wheat, Valencia said.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged farmers have been turning to growing tomatoes,
peppers and other crops that get a better price but do little to
help the continent's food needs.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia regards this as a tragic trend that undercuts the
effort to ensure Africa's food supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the farmers can't make any money at wheat _ as important as
it is _ they'll grow something else that has a better market,'' he
said. ``This is a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   COSTS AND RETURNS USING SG 2000 TECHNIQUES:
</P>
