<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUGH-RECIPES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A ROLL WITH FROZEN DOUGH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
CAPTIONS: 
no photo credits: 
Frozen bread dough makes a great base for creations such as Lemon
Danish Rolls and Salami, Provolone and Pepper Torte. 
 
 
Charcoal Grilled Pizza Style Breads lend themselves to a variety of
toppings, including tomatow-basil. 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever spent a little time perusing the freezer cases at
the market, you've probably run across those snow-white loaves of
frozen unbaked bread dough.
</P>
<P>
   They are nothing new. They've been around since the early '60s
when Bridgeford Foods Corp. introduced them at a cost of 49 cents
for three. And the product _ which other companies also produce _
continues to have a faithful following today.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I have baked a couple of the white loaves over the
years, I could never get jazzed about the flavor or texture. But
that's not surprising because I grew up around fabulous homebaked
yeast rolls, coffee cakes and breads.
</P>
<P>
   However, after a little exploration recently, I discovered that
you can transform the dough into something more _ and delicious _
by adding a medley of different ingredients. It's easy to change
flavors and shapes.
</P>
<P>
   The loaves offer lots of short-cut options for making all kinds
of yeast dough-based creations ranging from a variety of sweet and
savory items _ from pizzas, focaccia, sandwiches, twists,
empanades, calzone, fondue bread, pizza rolls, herb twists, stuffed
sandwich loaves and garlic herb bread to cinnamon rolls, monkey
bread, turnovers, Danish, coffee cakes, hot cross buns and all
kinds of special holiday breads.
</P>
<P>
   An outgrowth of the Bridgeford's food service sandwich and meat
business, the frozen dough product came into being at a time when
convenience products were all the rage, said Lorene Salcido,
director of advertising and public relations at the Anaheim-based
company,which opened in 1932 as a meat market.
</P>
<P>
   The product _ the formula has not changed _ enabled consumers to
serve a fresh-baked loaf of bread hot from the oven without
spending time making and kneading the dough. What a boon!
</P>
<P>
   ``For a number of years, the main consumer of the product was 55
years or older, but today there is increased interest from younger
mothers who desire more input in meal preparation,'' said Salcido.
``Also, with the resurgence of interest in comfort foods and bread
in the '90s, more people are baking bread again, either from
scratch or using frozen bread dough.''
</P>
<P>
   Grab a loaf of frozen dough _ or two or three _ and begin having
some fun. Use today's recipes as a starting point to come up with
your own combinations and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's feasible to substitute honey wheat (packaged two
1-pound loaves to a bag) for the white bread dough (which is the
most readily available locally) in recipes _ or in some cases white
rolls (available in 27-ounce bags) or parkerhouse rolls (in
25-ounce packages) _ these products are more difficult to track
down in local supermarkets (we tried unsuccessfully).
</P>
<P>
   I turned out a focaccia-like creation effortlessly with one and
a half loaves in a 14-inch pizza pan. After pressing the thawed
dough in the greased pan, it was drizzled with some extra virgin
olive oil, a sprinkling of dried basil and grated Parmesan cheese.
A 15- to 20-minute bake in a 350-degree oven yielded a
lovely-looking golden, fragrant creation that tasted good, too.
</P>
<P>
   I also whipped up a cream cheese coffee cake by lining a 9-inch
round cake pan (or use a pie pan) _ bottom and sides _ with thawed
dough and adding a cream cheese filling made with a package of
cream cheese, an egg, 1/2 cup sugar, two teaspoons flour, a little
vanilla and grated orange peel. Before pouring on the cream cheese
mixture, I sprinkled the dough with a couple of handfuls of
chocolate chips. After baking the filling until set (20 to 25
minutes), the end result was delicious. Tasters gave it a thumbs
up.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I plan to try making bread bowls for soups or chilis along
with some stuffed sandwiches and filled appetizers. The dough
definitely has possibilities, so give it a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
