<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONFESSIONS OF AN SUV CRITIC 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This is a tough confession to make, but I've
gone over to the other side.
</P>
<P>
   I now have both a sport utility vehicle and a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, first I became a Republican, and now I'm despoiling the
environment and talking loudly to myself in restaurants. But hold
on. It isn't quite like that.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, I'm not piloting one of those 10 mpg,
Toyota-squishing, Tiger tank SUVs. It's just a baby SUV, a Honda
CRV with a Civic engine that gets 25 mpg around town and is built
just barely tough enough to get up my driveway _ which genuinely
requires four-wheel drive or deer hooves.
</P>
<P>
   I've had the car for a while, but as an early campaigner against
SUVs I've been ashamed to admit it. The thing about having a Honda
SUV is that you're betwixt and between, neither fish nor fowl and
permanently a little pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban panzer drivers in Ford Explorers and Land Rovers
sneer at your wimpy little on-road four-wheel-drive with no low-end
gear ratios. Meanwhile, your 25 mpg doesn't win you any points with
tree-huggers, bicyclists and pedestrian liberationists.
</P>
<P>
   You're just another jerk in an SUV _ and you probably have a
cell phone, too.
</P>
<P>
   And I do. But I don't dial and drive at the same time. I don't
have the skill, for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   You can see I'm making fine distinctions to avoid being
convicted as a typical phone-carrying, SUV-driving idiot.
</P>
<P>
   Idiot, maybe, and here's why.
</P>
<P>
   This is the worst confession of all. I wear my little Nokia
clipped to my belt, or if I'm feeling really jaunty, I hang it low
on my pocket like a Western six-gun.
</P>
<P>
   I've been traipsing around like that for 2 1/2 weeks, and my
wife still laughs when she sees me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' I tell her, ``if I put it in a coat pocket, it'll fall
out, and I won't be able to keep in constant touch with you, my
love. That's the reason we got these phones remember?'' That's what
I tell her.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I feel kind of macho geeky with a Nokia gunbelt. Geeks
are the new macho men and macha women, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens when my wife calls, and I hear one of the 36
ditties I can choose as a ring? (I chose ``quiet phone ring'' from
Pacific Bell's Canon, forgoing Pachebel's Canon.)
</P>
<P>
   Every time I've had incoming calls, I've jumped and been unable
to get the phone out of its quick-release holster, pressed a wrong
button or two and canceled the call. I'm the Barney Fife of the
cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Some columnists aspire to be arbiters of fashion. Not me. I'm
the canary in the newspaper at the bottom of the birdcage. I'm an
early warning system for out of fashion. Make that a late warning
system.
</P>
<P>
   I like Dockers (they're the trouser equivalent of oldies radio,
but you don't have to iron them), chambray shirts, brown work boots
and leather bomber jackets _ all the things that embarrass entire
offices on casual Fridays, and cause absolute revulsion at dot-coms
on casual everydays.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm wearing a cell phone and driving an SUV, even a small
one, then you know cell phones and SUVs are over.
</P>
<P>
   They've come to Kmart, as my wife puts it. But you know, Kmart
isn't so bad, and Target is even better.
</P>
<P>
   A Nokia on your belt can be hazardous. My wife just got a
message from me that I accidentally left when I leaned my cell
phone against a cafe chair, auto-dialing her number and recording a
cafe yakfest on her phone.
</P>
<P>
   Phone klutzes who have something to hide from their wives could
get in real trouble by carelessly dropping their belts and phones.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be great when we can hide these things in a handsome
wristband or shoe. And you'll have me to thank for being an
unerring fashion stopper, and ending the reign of terror of Nokia
gunbelts and SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   If only there was an easy and decorative way to hide the SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
