<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUGH-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS ON THE RISE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: This is sidebar to main story, which is slugged
`Dough-Recipes'; main story includes captions. Recipes have been
transmitted in file slugged Dough2-Recipes. Accompanying photos
have also been transmitted to the NYTimes wire.) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
 
 
Following are a few tips for success when using frozen bread dough.
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Before you begin, you'll need to thaw the frozen dough. It'll
take about 8 to 12 hours in the refrigerator. Leave in the bag and
move from freezer to fridge. (Use the refrigerated dough within 24
hours of placing it there initially.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Or you may take the dough out of the freezer and thaw at room
temperature in about 1 to 2 hours (half that amount of time for
rolls). Be aware that temperature (of the dough, room, etc.)
affects thawing and rising times. If the dough is allowed to rise
in a warm place, it will double in volume more quickly than in a
cold room.
</P>
<P>
   _ To thaw in the microwave, place one loaf of frozen dough (or
rolls) on a microwave-safe plate and microwave on low power about
three minutes, checking often. Depending on the wattage of your
oven, a longer or shorter time may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   _ For best results, Lorene Salcido of Bridgeford Foods
recommends stashing the dough in your freezer (away from the door
to avoid shortening the life of the dough) immediately after
purchasing if you are not planning to use it right away. Use the
frozen dough within 30 days of purchasing (be sure it is solidly
frozen and contains no ice crystals when you buy it).
</P>
<P>
   _ If thawed and refrozen, the yeast action in the dough may
decrease _ and the dough may never rise. ``The fresher the dough,
the better the yeast works,'' said Salcido.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't attempt to change the texture of the dough by
incorporating an egg. It won't work as the dough is already set.
However you can change the flavor by kneading in a little sugar or
other ingredients such as dried fruits, cut up pepperoni, chocolate
chips and the like.
</P>
<P>
   _ When it comes to working with the dough, the warmer it is, the
easier it is to roll out. ``It tends to be elastic if cold,'' said
Salcido.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also, avoid using too much flour for rolling the dough as it
will change the flavor and texture of the finished product. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
