<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1173 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS30-COX-     03-29 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS30-COX-FILE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   FILE 1 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: Neil Armstrong, speaking at the National Press Club in
Washington recently, discussed the 20 greatest engineering
achievements of the 20th century as determined by the National
Academy of Engineering. Can you list them?
</P>
<P>
   A: The achievements were ranked according to how they affected
the quality of life, in the opinion of a committee of engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong presented them in reverse order, starting with No. 20:
high-performance materials (synthetic resins, plastics, polymers,
composites, ceramic materials); nuclear technology; lasers and
fiber optics; petroleum technology; health technologies; household
appliances; imaging technologies; the Internet; space flight;
development of the Interstate highway system; air conditioning and
refrigeration; the telephone; computers; agricultural
mechanization; radio and television; electronics; technologies that
purify and deliver safe water; the development of aircraft; the
development of automobiles; and the development of electrification
(the delivery of power to homes and businesses).
</P>
<P>
   Information can be found online at www.greatachievements.org.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Academy Awards ceremony included a segment on film
industry people who died in the previous year. Why was Stanley
Kubrick, who was a giant of filmmaking, left out?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kubrick died March 7, 1999, at age 70. The director was
included in the montage of memorials at last year's Oscar ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about Delta Air Lines repainting its aircraft
mentioned that some older planes would be retired. What does it
mean when a plane is retired? Is it sold? Is it broken up for
parts?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both are possibilities, said Delta spokesman John Kennedy. In
general, retired aircraft can be ferried to a desert location in
Arizona where they're broken down or otherwise scrapped and the
parts sold, or they can be sold to other organizations for
continuing use as passenger or cargo planes.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the aircraft Delta is retiring this time around,
they're primarily being sold to other organizations, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of Kato Kaelin of O.J. Simpson fame?
</P>
<P>
   A: At last report, Brian ``Kato'' Kaelin, once the nation's most
famous house guest, was said to be living in the Hollywood Hills
and pursuing an acting career. He did a short radio talk show
stint, but that fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he doesn't need a job anyway to make ends meet. In
October, it was reported that Kaelin had settled his $15 million
libel lawsuit with Globe Communications Corp. over this headline in
the National Enquirer: ``Cops Think Kato Did It!''
</P>
<P>
   Kaelin's lawyer, Gary Bostwick, wouldn't discuss how much Globe
Communications agreed to pay his client.
</P>
<P>
   The National Enquirer ran the headline a week after Simpson was
acquitted of criminal charges in the 1994 slayings of his ex-wife,
Nicole Brown Simpson, and her friend, Ronald Goldman. While the
tabloid argued that it never accused Kaelin of murder and the word
``It'' in the headline meant perjury, a federal appeals court in
1998 ruled that the headline alone could be grounds for libel.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With John and Patsy Ramsey back in the news, I'm reminded of
a question I've had for some time: Where does the name of their
slain daughter, JonBenet, come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a combination of the first and middle names of her
father, John Bennett Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article reported that more than 1,000 women won a
settlement of $508 million in a federal sex discrimination case.
Where will the money come from, the taxpayers?
</P>
<P>
   A: Whatever amount is ultimately awarded would come from the
Treasury Department's justice fund, said Charles Miller, Justice
Department spokesman. When the government wins cases, it puts money
into the fund; when it loses them, it draws money back out. So some
of the justice fund may be taxpayer money, and some from other
sources.
</P>
<P>
   This particular case involved gender bias in hiring and
promotions at the U.S. Information Agency and Voice of America
radio service. If the $508 million settlement agreed to by the
government is accepted by the federal judge who oversaw the
lawsuit, it will be the largest ever recorded in a federal
sex-discrimination case.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I receive Social Security payments, and I've misplaced the
W-2 equivalent that the Social Security Administration sent me. How
do I get a replacement?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call 1-800-772-1213 and a replacement form 1099 will be sent
to you, said Patti Patterson of the Social Security Administration.
The field office numbers can be found in the U.S. government blue
pages of your business telephone directory, under Social Security
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm very much aware of the middle names of many past
presidents, such as Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Dwight David
Eisenhower, Richard Milhouse Nixon and George Herbert Walker Bush.
But I'm curious about our early presidents. Did George Washington,
for example, have a middle name? Who was the first president to
have a middle name?
</P>
<P>
   A: George Washington didn't have a middle name or middle
initial. He was the first of 17 presidents without them. The
others: John Adams, Thomas Jefferson, James Madison, James Monroe,
Andrew Jackson, Martin Van Buren, John Tyler, Zachary Taylor,
Millard Fillmore, Franklin Pierce, James Buchanan, Abraham Lincoln,
Andrew Johnson, Benjamin Harrison, William McKinley and Thedore
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   The first president to have a middle name was John Quincy Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting for the next trivia contest: Grover Cleveland was
born Stephen Grover Cleveland. But he dropped his first name, as
did (Thomas) Woodrow Wilson and (John) Calvin Coolidge.
</P>
<P>
   And another tidbit: Ulysses S. Grant was born with the name
Hiram Ulysses Grant. Before he entered West Point, the first name
on his appointment was written, by mistake, as Ulysses. The middle
name also was erroneously listed as Simpson, from his mother,
Hannah Simpson Grant. Ulysses never corrected the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported on the middle names and initials, or lack of
them, of many U.S. presidents. What about Harry Truman? It's often
claimed that his middle initial, S, had no period because it didn't
stand for anything.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's true that Truman had no middle name. But it appears not
to be true that the initial wasn't followed by a period.
</P>
<P>
   Harry was the oldest of the three children of John Anderson
Truman and Martha Ellen Young Truman. His parents named him Harry
in honor of his uncle, Harrison Young. They chose the middle
initial ``S'' but gave him no middle name, so that each of his
grandfathers, Solomon Young and Anderson Shippe Truman, could claim
that the grandson was named for him.
</P>
<P>
   The Harry S. Truman Library &AMP; Museum in Independence, Mo.,
addresses the matter of the period after the initial on its Web
site. An oversized signature in Truman's own handwriting, clearly
showing a period after the S, illustrates a segment on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The text states that evidence provided by Truman's own practice
``argues strongly'' for the use of the period, even though he
frequently signed his name in a single stroke without lifting pen
from paper. The text continues by saying the Truman Library's
archives has numerous examples of the signature written at
different times during his life where his use of a period after the
S ``is very obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Information can be found online at www.trumanlibrary.org or in
World Book Encyclopedia, Congressional Quarterly's ``Guide to the
Presidency,'' Current Biography, and ``The Book of Presidents,''
among others.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was told that PETA dropped its campaign for college
students suggesting that beer was better than milk. I thought it
sounded ill-advised. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: PETA (People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals) indeed has
backed away from the campaign it launched March 14, which urged
college students to put milk products out to pasture. In that
campaign, PETA said ``even beer was better for them,'' and _ in a
slap at ads showing celebrities with a white ``mustache'' from
drinking milk _ said a foam mustache should be from a brew, not a
``moo.''
</P>
<P>
   After an outcry led primarily by Mothers Against Drunk Driving
(MADD), PETA quickly pulled the ``Got Beer?'' promotion. In a March
16 announcement, PETA, while not apologizing, said it was
``shifting the focus'' to appeal to college students' compassion
for animals instead.
</P>
<P>
   On its home page, PETA, meanwhile, announced that its ``Got
Beer?'' campaign was ``such a hit with college students'' that the
antidairy Web site attracted 41,000 visitors in 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   PETA also said that as a goodwill gesture, it was donating $500
given by its employees to MADD, and was including a link on its Web
site to that of MADD.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is meant by the term ``right-to-work state''?
</P>
<P>
   A: A ``right-to-work'' law provides that a person need not
belong to a labor union to get or keep a job. It also provides that
a person may not be denied a job because of union membership. About
20 states have such laws. The Taft-Hartley Act permits the union
(or ``closed'') shop, in which employers can hire only members of
the union, but its Section 14B also permits states to pass laws
prohibiting them (right-to-work legislation).
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
