</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about presidential disability and succession made
me wonder: Has there ever been a case in the United States when an
acting president was required to step in for a short emergency
period?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. As World Book Encyclopedia explains, Vice President
George Bush became the first U.S. acting president in your scenario
when, on July 13, 1985, he officially held that position for eight
hours while President Reagan underwent cancer surgery.
</P>
<P>
   This matter is addressed in Section 3 of the 25th Amendment to
the Constitution, which states: Whenever the president transmits to
the president pro tempore of the Senate and the speaker of the
House of Representatives his written declaration that he is unable
to discharge the powers and duties of his office, and until he
transmits to them a written declaration to the contrary, such
powers and duties shall be discharged by the vice president as
acting president.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Gasoline prices have been in the news a lot lately. Adjusted
for inflation, how much have they changed over, say, the past 10
years?
</P>
<P>
   A: Statistics compiled by the American Petroleum Institute are
available only up to August 1999, before the recent surge in
prices. But information in API's booklet ``How Much We Pay for
Gasoline'' shows how adjusted prices have moved over the years. It
says that in 1990, the inflation-adjusted U.S. city retail price
for all types of gasoline, not including taxes, averaged $1.20.3 a
gallon. In the first eight months of '99 it averaged 74.9 cents a
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   For historical perspective, API says gasoline prices staged a
long decline after the Depression, down to an inflation-adjusted
average (not including taxes) of 97 cents in 1972, when prices
jumped with the 1973-74 oil embargo. Prices climbed even higher in
1979 when Iranian crude supplies were curtailed, reaching an
inflation-adjusted peak of $2.20.3 in 1980. Then they fell,
especially during the winter of 1985-86, owing to the large
production increases by OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   And now they're higher once again, changing so frequently that
it's hard to keep track.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the telephone number to check on a federal tax
refund?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call 1-800-829-4477.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When are the next sets of state quarters going to be issued?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a popular question. The quarters are being issued
over a 10-year period. The first five, in 1999, were Delaware,
Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Georgia and Connecticut. This year's
group: Massachusetts, Maryland, South Carolina, New Hampshire
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining schedule: 2001, New York, North Carolina, Rhode
Island, Vermont, Kentucky; 2002, Tennessee, Ohio, Louisiana,
Indiana, Mississippi; 2003, Illinois, Alabama, Maine, Missouri,
Arkansas; 2004, Michigan, Florida, Texas, Iowa, Wisconsin; 2005,
California, Minnesota, Oregon, Kansas, West Virginia; 2006, Nevada,
Nebraska, Colorado, North Dakota, South Dakota; 2007, Montana,
Washington, Idaho, Wyoming, Utah; 2008, Oklahoma, New Mexico,
Arizona, Alaska, Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're wondering about the sequence, the coins are being
issued in the order in which the states became part of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-872-6468, or online at
www.usmint.gov/50states.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several months ago, it was reported that a student somewhere
in the Carolinas was scheduled to receive a kidney transplant from
