</HEADLINE>
 - copy only &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, March 30,
2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN _ MIAMI _ Amid warnings of potential civil unrest,
relatives of Elian Gonzalez meet Wednesday afternoon with Justice
Department officials, who are insisting that they promise to give
up the 6-year-old Cuban boy if they lose a court battle. If the
family refuses, the federal officials say they will revoke custody
Thursday morning and spell out the procedure for returning Elian to
Cuba. (Williams, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PRAYER _ WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court's consideration of
the legality of student-led prayer before school football games
started off with a zinger from Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg. She
asked the attorney for a school district in Galveston County,
Texas, whether the prayer could consist of these words: ``Break
their necks, Make them wrecks, Buckle down, boys.'' After
Wednesday's hour of oral arguments, the court is expected to set
new national precedents by answering that question and others in a
decision to be handed down by early July. (Mollison, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-GAMBLING _ WASHINGTON _ With the Final Four a few days
away, two senators, with the support of the NCAA, introduced
legislation that would ban wagering on collegiate and amateur
athletic competition. (Turay, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: Moving in (w) Washington and (s) sports categories.)
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-OPTIONS _ WASHINGTON _ A broad spectrum of tech industry
officials, bipartisan Congress members and Clinton administration
officials announced a bill Wednesday that would allow employers to
provide stock options for all employees. (Geewax, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton holds a 2 p.m. ET news
conference. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   OSTEOPOROSIS _ WASHINGTON _ After a three-day National
Institutes of Health consensus conference, experts issue
recommendations for prevention and treatment of osteoporosis, the
calcium-loss disease that places elderly people, particularly
women, at increased risk of fractures. (Nesmith, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS _ ATLANTA _ Nine people were hidden under the overpass.
Even though it was hours before dawn and they were all covered with
layers of blankets, the homeless people were cooperative and polite
to the Census workers who interrupted their rest with flashlights
and questions. One of the men, who told a reporter his name was
``just Harry,'' said he didn't mind that Census takers had come to
question him while he was in bed, because he hadn't gone to sleep
yet. ``I just laid down,'' Harry said. Before dawn Wednesday,
between the hours of 4 a.m. and 7 a.m., census workers wearing
orange vests searched nationwide for people living under bridges,
in abandoned buildings and in secret spots sheltered by bushes.
(Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUS-TRAIN _ TENNGA, Ga. _ Main news of the day from the school
bus-freight train collision. Conditions of the injured children
should drastically change today _ some for the better, some maybe
for the worse. (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-8DEAD _ ACWORTH, Ga. _ Eight members of a working family
are killed early Wednesday by a fire that swept through their
trailer in Acworth. (Visser, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REUNITED-IMMIGRANTS _ ATLANTA _ Lots of families from Nicaragua
and Haiti are reuniting after many years apart. Kids are flying to
Atlanta to join moms and dads who left 10 years ago. They're coming
because of a March 31 deadline to take advantage of a federal law
that gives legal status to people from those countries. We focus in
this story on a 32-year-old woman separated from her kids _ 12 and
14 _ for 10 years. They were reunited this month. (Bixler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ALAMIN _ ATLANTA _ Ed Brown, Jamil Al-Amin's brother, and Karima
Al-Amin, his lawyer-wife, are exerting greater control in the
selection of his defense team. The selection of Mike Mears, who
represents indigents and is a leading anti-death penalty lawyer,
signals an end to the talk of big shots like Johnnie Cochran. What
the family seems to want is a team with expertise in death penalty
cases, as well as an African-American presence. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA: Local cemeteries alive with history
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters.
Photos and a sig/locator map are available.)
</P>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Listen closely. The dead might be talking. But
don't be alarmed. It's not the chain-rattling, haunting kind of
talking. Instead, the dead are spinning their tales into the web of
history even as they rest in local cemeteries _ cemeteries that
play an important role in preserving the past, according to Dr.
Norman Black. Black is a Longview, Texas, dentist who has headed
the Gregg County Historical Commission for 15 years. ``We don't
have anything spectacular here, but we do have some oddities,''
Black said. Among those oddities is a mystery that captivated
Longview in 1975. (Hammer, Longview News Journal). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ National political column. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GUNS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As gun control once again becomes a
focal point of debate on Capitol Hill, we take a look at George W
Bush's record on guns, from his signing of a controversial
concealed weapons bill to contributions and support he has received
from the gun lobby. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   HIV _ How much of the AIDS virus circulates in a person's blood
stream may be a predictor of whether they'll transmit the virus to
a partner, a study suggests. The research was done in Africa among
heterosexual couples who didn't have access to antiviral drugs,
which reduce levels of the virus in some people to practically
undetectable levels. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
