<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1190 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      03-29 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHRONICLE URGES JUDGE NOT TO BLOCK NEWSPAPER SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Chronicle has asked a federal
judge to reject a request for an emergency order blocking the
Hearst Corp. from buying the morning newspaper, saying it would
cause the daily to continue losing money.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers filed Tuesday, Chronicle Publishing Co. called
the antitrust suit filed by former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly
``baseless'' and said that each day he was allowed to delay the
sale beyond its March 30 closing date would cost the company nearly
$102,000.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has asked U.S. District Judge Vaughn R. Walker to hold a
hearing Thursday and issue a temporary order blocking Hearst from
concluding its purchase of the Chronicle, pending a full hearing on
his claim that it would give Hearst an illegal newspaper monopoly
that would raise advertising and subscription prices.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing and Hearst have denied Reilly's claims.
They say Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle and sale of its San
Francisco Examiner to the publisher of the weekly Independent would
restore economic competition between daily newspapers in San
Francisco for the first time in 35 years. Even if the Examiner
closed, Hearst says, the Chronicle would still face competition
from a host of other media in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends that delaying the sale would not significantly
harm the Chronicle because it makes a daily profit, a claim the
Chronicle disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The court papers shed light on why the Chronicle's owners are
eager to sell and Hearst, based in New York, is eager to buy: The
morning newspaper loses money under its current joint operating
agreement with the afternoon Examiner, but could be highly
profitable on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle has a daily circulation of 465,535. The Examiner
has a daily circulation of 108,968.
</P>
<P>
   J. Thomas Rosch, a lawyer for the Chronicle, said the
newspaper's owners would lose $100,000 a day in interest that they
could earn if they invested the $660 million in cash that Hearst
has agreed to pay for the Chronicle and its SF Gate Web site at an
annual rate of 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rosch also said any delays caused by Reilly's suit would force
the Chronicle to incur additional daily losses.
</P>
<P>
   In a declaration, Martin A. Jaffe, the Chronicle's chief
financial officer, said that so far this year the Chronicle and SF
Gate had lost $1,900 per day, after depreciation and amortization
of the company's buildings, computers, trucks and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Depreciation and amortization are accounting methods that deduct
from revenue the cost of business equipment over its useful life.
Figuring them into the equation produces a lower net revenue than
does a cash flow analysis, which does not take those costs into
account.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe's figures are based on revenue for January and February, a
period following the holiday buying season when advertising falls
off.
</P>
<P>
   While it may seem odd that a newspaper with the Chronicle's
circulation would lose money, the explanation lies in its joint
operating agreement with the Examiner, according to sources at each
company familiar with the finances.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, Hearst's Examiner and the locally owned Chronicle
have published under a joint operating agreement, an exception to
federal antitrust laws allowing them to combine business operations
while maintaining independent editorial staffs. The exception is
authorized by the Newspaper Preservation Act, which seeks to
maintain multiple editorial voices in cities.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and Chronicle Publishing created the San Francisco
Newspaper Agency, which handles all advertising, circulation,
printing and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The agency collects the revenue for both newspapers, deducts the
cost of their business operations and evenly splits the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   Each newspaper takes its share, pays its respective newsroom
costs and winds up with a net gain or loss, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Chronicle has an editorial staff of 375, it has far
higher newsroom costs than does the Examiner, with a staff of 217.
</P>
<P>
   But if Hearst buys the Chronicle and sells the Examiner to the
publishers of the Independent, it would have the opportunity to
boost revenue, cut expenses and operate profitably.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has agreed to provide the Independent with a $66 million
subsidy over 32 months to help cover costs of publishing the
Examiner as a daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends it would cost $250 million over five years to
publish a viable competitor, and that Hearst would end up owning
the only metropolitan daily in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
