<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      03-29 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT-ELECT NAMES PRIME MINISTER FROM NATIONALIST PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In a surprise announcement, Taiwan's president-elect,
Chen Shui-bian, said Wednesday that the outgoing Nationalist Party
defense minister would be prime minister of his new government,
which takes office May 20.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the defense minister, Tang Fei, a 68-year-old
former air force general, may help reassure nervous citizens as
well as the Chinese government that Chen does not intend to make
radical changes in policy toward the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Chen had long advocated Taiwan's formal independence, which
Beijing has warned would lead it to attack Taiwan, which China
considers an integral part of the country rather than a separate
entity. Chen, who leads the Democratic Progressive Party, recently
moderated his position, saying that a declaration of independence
is unnecessary because Taiwan is already sovereign in practice.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Tang may also help Chen gain the support of
senior military officers, most of whom are lifelong supporters of
the Nationalist Party and strongly oppose declaring independence.
The appointment of a respected Cabinet member from the outgoing
Nationalist government will also aid Chen's drive in broadening his
political base, which is needed because he won with just 39 percent
of the popular vote and faces a Nationalist majority in the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Tang was appointed prime minister after the post was turned down
by Chen's first choice, a Nobel-prize winning scientist, Lee
Yuan-tseh, who is head of the Academia Sinica, Taiwan's premier
research institution. Lee's endorsement of Chen before the March 18
election was credited with helping him win. Chen had sought to
bring Lee into his government as a sign of nonpartisanship and
experience.
</P>
<P>
   James Soong, the Nationalist maverick who came in second in the
presidential election, said Wednesday that he would form a new
political party called the People First Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
