<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATOM-TRAPPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCIENTISTS `LASSO' ATOMS FOR CLOSE INSPECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scientists are using lasers to nudge clouds of
atoms into tiny traps where the properties of the particles can be
studied.
</P>
<P>
   This atom trapping is helping scientists to test the merits of
the so-called standard model of physics that dominates physics
textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the standard model seems to be ``in very good shape,''
Gene Sprouse, a physicist from the State University of New York at
Stony Brook, told the American Chemical Society on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The standard model is a general theory of the underlying nature
of matter and energy, which is presumed to consist of certain
families of particles and sub-particles. The best-known
sub-particles are quarks, the building blocks of atoms.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of moving atoms around like so many billiard balls, and
corralling them in pens like so many obedient sheep, would have
amazed scientists not so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Only a century ago, the very existence of atoms was denied by
scientific titans such as Ernst Mach, whose philosophy strongly
influenced the great physicist Albert Einstein and others.
(Ironically, Einstein's early research on a phenomenon called
Brownian motion provided smoking-gun evidence for the existence of
atoms.)
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, nowadays, atom trapping has become a major
enterprise in physics research.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists like Sprouse use particle accelerators to generate
fast-moving beams of atoms. First, they fire these beams into
chambers _ in Sprouse's case, a transparent glass sphere. Then,
they use magnetic fields and lasers to nudge the particles into
small clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Within the glass sphere, a few thousand atoms float around.
Then, scientists illuminate them with bursts of laser light. In
response, the atoms flash back different frequencies of light.
</P>
<P>
   The electromagnetic frequency of those flashes, and other
technical details, reveal much about the atoms' innards. For
example, different types of atoms are expected to emit radiation in
different ways. Sprouse's technique allows him and his colleagues
to see whether the atoms are behaving as expected.
</P>
<P>
   If they ever misbehave, that might be a possible hint of
problems with the standard model.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Sprouse and his colleagues have analyzed trapped
clouds of atoms of the element francium. Discovered in 1939,
francium is so rare and short-lived _ it rapidly decays into pure
energy _ that according to Sprouse there is only ``about an ounce
of it on the Earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1512EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
