<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1217 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     03-29 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IT'S TIME TO CHANGE PRIMARIES' SCHEDULE AND FUND-RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 2)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Democrats gathered in Baltimore in the summer
of 1912, they sweated and fretted through 46 roll calls before
Woodrow Wilson won the necessary two-thirds majority and became the
party's standard bearer.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, in 1924, the Democrats met in New York's
Madison Square Garden and suffered through a heat wave and an
all-time record political endurance test of 103 ballots over nine
days. When the battle was over, neither of the frontrunners, New
York Gov. Alfred E. Smith and former Treasury Secretary William
Gibbs McAdoo, emerged triumphant. Neither man was able to win two
thirds of the vote and neither would yield to the other. So the
delegates nominated a colorless, little-known compromise candidate,
former Solicitor General John W. Davis.
</P>
<P>
   McAdoo, a defender of Prohibition, had won nine primaries;
Smith, an outspoken opponent of Prohibition, had entered none and,
therefore, won none. But Smith was popular with northerners while
McAdoo was the choice of many southerners and westerners.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the Democrats lost badly in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   The two-thirds vote had been a part the Democrat's nominating
process since 1832 when both parties staged their first national
conventions. That rule provided southerners an opportunity to veto
the nomination of presidential candidates whose policies they
disapproved.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates from Dixie got the veto, but the two-thirds
requirement made it difficult, even for men of such stature as
Wilson and Franklin D. Roosevelt, to be nominated.
</P>
<P>
   After 1932, the year of FDR's first election as president, the
Democrats wisely scuttled the two-thirds rule. Henceforth, a simple
majority of delegate votes was enough to choose the nominees in
both parties.
</P>
<P>
   As presidential primaries spread across the land, they were seen
as the means by which power was taken from professional politicians
and given to the people.
</P>
<P>
   But primaries are not without their faults.
</P>
<P>
   We now are at the beginning of April, with the Democrats having
chosen Al Gore and the Republicans, George W. Bush. But suspense
has gone out of the nominating process, except for discussion of
who will be nominated for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, straight-talking Sen. John McCain of Arizona may
have become the most admired politician in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The primaries are a vital force in the nominating process
because they permit the people to choose the ultimate candidates.
Of course, the people can make mistakes just as the bosses do.
Among such mistakes in recent years were the Republican nomination
of Barry Goldwater in 1964 and the Democratic nominations of George
McGovern in 1972 and Michael Dukakis in 1984. All had won in the
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Timing continues to be a problem. We now have seven months to
listen to Gore and Bush repeat their cliches, indulge in flamboyant
rhetoric and attack each other. Meanwhile, voters and the news
media will grow bored with the process and its negativism, and
dissatisfaction with the lengthy campaign could reduce voter
turnout in November.
</P>
<P>
   For years the primaries were spread over the first six months of
a presidential election year. But that meant the states voting in
May or June would have less impact on the final decision than those
that voted in February and March.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception in recent years has been California with its
huge block of delegates to both conventions. Traditionally,
California's primaries were held in June.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Goldwater's victory in the California Republican
primary that sealed his nomination over Nelson Rockefeller in 1964.
Success in California might have done the same for Robert Kennedy
four years later had he not been assassinated on the night he won
the contest.
</P>
<P>
   But in an effort to play an even more decisive role in the
nominating process, California moved its primary into early March
along with other populous states.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the race for this year's nominations was over in
mid-March, following primaries in California, New York, Texas,
Florida, Michigan and Ohio and other states.
</P>
<P>
   In those races the candidates in both parties spent obscene
amounts of money. No previous candidate had ever raised an
estimated $70 million, as Bush did just to win in the primaries.
But Gore, Bradley, and McCain also raised millions. Forbes spent
his own millions trying, but failing, to win the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Now, reform is once again in the air, both as to how candidates
accumulate campaign funds and when the states should stage their
primary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers have suggested that primaries be staged in regional
clusters such as New England one week, the Mid-Atlantic the next,
and then the South until all sectors of the nation have voted. But
there is no easy solution.
</P>
<P>
   Unless all states vote in a national primary on a single day,
which would pose grave travel and fund-raising difficulties for the
candidates, some states will inevitably ballot ahead of others.
</P>
<P>
   We should try to narrow the gap between the last primaries and
Election Day. And we should overhaul the way campaigns are
financed, which was McCain's major issue.
</P>
<P>
   The primaries should be concluded closer to Election Day because
democracy suffers when campaigns become boring and repetitive and
when candidates become beholden to special interests that provide
the funds for them to keep up the fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
