<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEERNUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG RASPBERRY AND APOLOGIES TO ALL YOU BELGIANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First off, it might be good to mention that lambic beer has
nothing to do with sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Lambic is a sour brew, native to Belgium and produced by
``spontaneous fermentation.'' That means they let all kinds of
airborne dust, pollen, bacteria, yeast and who knows what fall into
the mix to get it going.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if you think about it, it's good to remember that beer
is representative of a culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, for instance, brew up aggressive beverages that
invade the tongue and make it snap to attention. ``Ach du lieber!''
</P>
<P>
   Australians make friendly g'day-mate beers big enough to quench
a way-out-in-the-Outback kind of thirst.
</P>
<P>
   Now take Belgium, please. Everyone else has.
</P>
<P>
   Have the Belgians ever invaded anything? Have they ever won a
battle? Quick, name one Belgian war hero.
</P>
<P>
   Belgians make even the French seem really macho, so it's only
natural that they would be a major producer of fruit-flavored ales.
Which, in a roundabout way, brings us to Framboise Lambic Ale.
</P>
<P>
   The ingredient list on the label starts out fine: water,
barley-malt, wheat, hops and yeast _ all of your beer-making
essentials. But then they ruin it by adding not just raspberries,
but fresh raspberries.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a very tart beverage with a raspberry flavor that
overwhelms any beer characteristics. It comes in a 750 milliliter
wine bottle and sells for $9. It's made by Lindemans Brewery in
Vlezenbeek. They also make varieties with cherries and peaches, and
with PRUNES and RAISINS??!
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't look like it knows if it wants to be wine or beer,''
said The Norm, a general know-it-all who claims to be homeless but
who lives in my back yard. He also refers to himself as ``The
Norm,'' but he's far from it.
</P>
<P>
   I had offered a glass of lambic to The Norm to calm him down
after I had proposed including him on my census form. He found the
idea highly unsettling, not only because he doesn't want the
government or the space aliens to know where he is, but because, as
he said: ``The Norm is homeless and proud.''
</P>
<P>
   He also claims to be a world traveler who had spent enough time
among the Belgians to pick up their language, which he said is
called ``Belch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never tasted anything like this when I was there,'' he
said. ``If this is the kind of stuff they're making now, I'm glad I
don't drink anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Norm and I give this a .5 on the international 1-5 scale.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
