<P>
   COUPLAND-TOTEMS (Chicago) _ It was a Sunday and the novelist
Douglas Coupland, chronicler of disaffected youth, was trawling for
mid-century American ceramics. He bought one piece after another,
never inquiring who made them or so much as glancing at the prices.
What he didn't tell storeowners (``I don't have the heart'') is
that the vases aren't going to be vases much longer. ``They're an
art supply,'' said Coupland, who studied sculpture before taking up
writing. Back home in Vancouver, Coupland will sand the finishes
off the vases, stiffen them with plaster, then join them with metal
rods and an adhesive he called ``shoe-goo'' into Brancusi-like
columns (totems, he calls them), with which he is currently filling
his 1960 post-and-beam house to the point of overcrowding. By Fred
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDIO (San Francisco) _ The bugles are silent now. But in
secluded vales of eucalpytus and along once-dusty parade grounds
lined with red-brick Victorians, history still stands watch over
the Presidio, the windswept 1480-acre former Army base wrapped by
the headlands of the Golden Gate Bridge. Since 1994, when this
National Historic Landmark _ about twice the size of Central Park _
became a national park, a novel and controversial experiment in
park planning and historic preservation has been underway at this
200-year-old military garrison that, though part of the city, still
feels like the edge of the world. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   DESERT-PILGRIMS (Buenos Aires, Ariz.) _ A multicultural group of
O'odham, Comcaac and Yoeme Indians, as well as their
botanist-ecologist friends walked 240 miles from a Mexican village
on the Sea of Cortez, across the Sonoran Desert to Tucson, Ariz.,
following the steps of their ancestors. Eating only native foods
and treating their ailments with wild plants from the desert, they
walked to raise awareness of diabetes, which affects 250,000 Native
Americans in the Southwest. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARTDECO-CLUB (New York) _ After eight months of renovations
and $600,000, the Lenox Lounge, the legendary Harlem night spot
built in 1939 _ the year Billie Holiday first sang ``Strange
Fruit'' _ is reopening: the sole surviving Art Deco club interior
in New York City. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
