A1224 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-LOLONIS-WINES-TEX     03-29 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOLONIS-WINES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LADYBUG, LADYBUG, YOUR WINE IS FINE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a reason Lolonis Winery uses a ladybug as its trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1956, no chemical pesticides have been applied there.
Instead, ladybugs (released twice each growing season) and praying
mantises are used to eliminate pests. To further ensure organic
purity, vine leaves are picked off by hand to expose grapes to the
sun and to allow air to circulate. That allows sunshine to develop
more fruit intensity in the grapes and additional air to control
the mold and mildew. Sulfur is applied in the vineyard to prevent
mildew, but the grapes are still organic because sulfur is a
naturally mined product.
</P>
<P>
   Lolonis was founded by Greek immigrants who came to the Redwood
Valley of Mendocino County, Calif., in 1914. It is the only winery
still owned by Greek-Americans who own their vineyards and whose
parents planted the original vines. Most grapes are grown for the
family winery, but some are sold to Beringer, Kendall Jackson,
Fetzer and other wineries.
</P>
<P>
   The reds impressed us the most. Lolonis Zinfandel 1997 ($18) is
a star. The wine, made from 50- to 60-year-old vines, has a nose
full of spice and some smoke. Full of rich, dark berry fruit,
abundant structure and a peppery taste, this wine is delicious with
beef fajitas.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabernet Sauvignon 1997 ($18) has generous body but minimal
tannins. In fact, it is similar to a merlot in its softness and
smoothness. Because it is so full of fruit and easy to drink, the
cabernet blends with any all-American meat dish such as pot roast
or chicken-fried steak. Serve it the next time you grill steaks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the first year Lolonis was distributed in Texas.
Because production has gone to 27,000 cases per year, enough is
available so we can sip the good taste here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Renie and Sterling Steves
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
