<HEADER>
A1225 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS &LR;      03-29 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA LAWMAKERS WEIGH SEVERAL GAY PARTNERSHIP BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The California Legislature is moving to
grant gay and lesbian couples some of the same legal rights that
automatically come with marriage, just three weeks after voters
overwhelmingly approved a ballot measure defining marriage as
between a man and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Gay and lesbian couples were given the right to register as
domestic partners under legislation signed by Democratic Gov. Gray
Davis last year. But pressure from Davis, Republicans and moderate
Democrats from the Central Valley cut the scope of the law so that
it only granted hospital visits to gay and lesbian partners and
excluded all but state workers when it came to sharing state
medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   This legislative session, which began in earnest this week,
includes four bills that would grant homosexual couples the right
to inherit property if one partner dies without a will, let a
surviving partner make funeral and autopsy arrangements, and grant
the partner the right to make medical decisions in dire
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   One of the bills also allows a domestic partner to sue for
emotional distress and wrongful death if their companion is killed,
a legal right married couples are granted. A separate bill would
grant gay and lesbian couples the right to make decisions over
donating organs after death.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said the bills were designed to put weight and meaning
behind the state's nascent domestic partnership registry, which was
set up for gay and lesbian couples and any couple, gay or straight,
older than age 62. As of Tuesday, 2,805 California couples have
applied for the domestic partnership registry with the secretary of
state.
</P>
<P>
   On March 7, voters approved Proposition 22, which codified
traditional marriage as between only a man and a woman. Statewide
polls, however, have shown voters agree with granting legal rights
to domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loving relationships must be honored,'' said Dr. Aaron Aronow,
a neurologist at the University of Southern California School of
Medicine who has treated patients with AIDS, the acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Aronow said he has seen parents and siblings of AIDS patients
arrive at the last minute and deny a partner access to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents have demanded religious funeral services even
though their child had requested secular services; others have
taken possession of the body to hold separate funerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a client who was barred from attending the funeral of
his partner because his partner's parents obtained a restraining
order to keep him away,'' said Jane Pearce, an estate attorney in
Sacramento. ``They had been together for seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Democrat-dominated Assembly Judiciary Committee
approved three of the measures. The organ-donor bill, written by
Assemblywoman Carole Migden, a Democrat from San Francisco, will be
introduced later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The bills faced opposition from conservative groups that
normally oppose all gay-rights legislation. The groups see the new
measures as a roundabout way to impose gay marriage even though
California voters overwhelmingly rejected the concept with
Proposition 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't injure the definition of family,'' said Randy Thomasson
of the Campaign for California Families, one of three opposition
witnesses Tuesday who noted that gay and lesbian couples can simply
write wills and sign over power of attorney to their partners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1545EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-UGANDA-CULT-NYT &LR;      03-29 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-CULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BODIES FOUND NEAR CULT LEADER'S HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUGAZI, Uganda _ Another 53 bodies were discovered Wednesday
crammed into a small pit inside the house of a Ugandan cult leader.
A total of 81 bodies have been found in the pit in the past two
days, 48 of them children.
</P>
<P>
   With each day bringing some new horror in one of the largest
mass murders in recent history, the police said Wednesday night
that they believe they have found yet another mass grave at a
building about 80 kilometers south of here, in southwest Uganda.
Excavation will begin Thursday morning, the police said. But even
before that work begins, the death toll already stands at more than
600.
</P>
<P>
   Here at the home of an excommunicated Roman Catholic priest,
Dominic Kataribabo, investigators unearthed 74 bodies in the back
yard on Monday. On Tuesday and Wednesday, another 81 bodies were
found inside the indoor pit, covered over with concrete in one of
the stone house's 10 rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The space for so many corpses was incredibly small: The pit,
lined with banana leaves, was just six-feet deep and four-feet
square, and the corpses were packed together in a dense,
interlocking heap.
</P>
<P>
   Since Feb. 17, at least 654 bodies have been recovered in the
wreckage of a cult, Movement for the Restoration of the Ten
Commandments of God, splintered off from the Roman Catholic church.
The cult demanded strict adherence to the Ten Commandments,
required members to sell their possessions and preached that the
world would end on Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The police originally suspected mass suicide by more than 300
followers found burned to death in a church in the town of Kanungu,
less than 50 miles from here. But since then, more bodies have been
found, a number with unmistakable signs of strangulation _ some by
rope or banana leaves, others by hand. Many bodies have shown no
sign of violence, leading some investigators to suspect mass
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   The police are increasingly calling this an organized slaughter,
though they have not speculated publicly about how so many people
could have been killed or by how many executioners.
</P>
<P>
   The scene at the house here Wednesday was particularly wrenching
because so many bodies of children were found. Workers with rubber
gloves pulled out the bodies one by one and placed them in a row on
the lawn for a quick examination by a police pathologist. Then they
were dragged to the rear of the compound to be buried in a long
trench with the 74 bodies found earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the police gave no details about the sight they
intend to search Thursday except to say that it is in the village
of Kabira, where they said cult members often stayed the night.
</P>
<P>
   A Ugandan police spokesman, Mugenyi Assuman, said investigators
also expected to take soil samples from the various mass graves,
particularly the original site in Kanungu.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what investigators would be testing for, Assuman would not
say exactly: ``Maybe poison,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1552EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-NYT &LR;      03-29 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS DEFEAT METS, 5-3, IN FIRST OFFICIAL GAME HELD OUTSIDE NORTH
AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Short on drama, long on tedium, the first major-league
game ever held outside North America looked mundanely like
thousands of other games, particularly those held indoors _ except
of course for the presence of the Crown Prince of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs beat the New York Mets, 5-3, Wednesday night,
14 and 15 time zones ahead of their respective home cities, in
front of a Tokyo Dome crowd announced at 55,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time an official American game had ever been
held outside the United States, Canada and Mexico, as part of Major
League Baseball's attempt to expand its impact. Baseball is
fitfully becoming more of an international game now that the sport
has been included in the Olympic Summer Games since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs took advantage of early wildness by Mike Hampton, the
left-handed rent-an-ace the Mets imported from Houston for the
remaining year on his contract. Hampton walked nine batters in five
innings before leaving. Shane Andrews later slugged a two-run home
run and Mark Grace hit a bases-empty homer for the Cubs. Jon Lieber
went seven innings for the Cubs and was the winning pitcher. Mike
Piazza launched a long two-run homer in the eighth for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the two-game series, which concludes Thursday
night, was an American style rather than a Japanese feel. Crown
Prince Naruhito and his wife, Masako, sat in the owners' box high
behind home plate, an extremely rare appearance by members of the
royal family at a baseball game. There was a brief glimpse of them
on the Mitsubishi message board, but no introduction.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the crown prince met with Sammy Sosa, whose face
can be seen in advertisements all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bowed to him, of course,'' Sosa said. ``Then we were
talking about the game. He enjoyed it. He told me everybody wanted
me to hit a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa did not hit one, but he did have two hits and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   Once it started, the game felt very much like any North American
game under a dome _ that is, it had a certain airless sterile
quality to it, magnified by the sickly pale green of the artificial
turf. In a perfect example of commonality far across the sea, the
incessant blare from the loudspeaker was trapped by the roof,
making sure that nobody could possibly have a conversation with the
person in the next seat.
</P>
<P>
   There was none of the traditional American bunting for opening
day and World Series games, but there was some Japanese presence in
five women in kimonos presenting flowers to the managers as well as
the umpires and Sosa and Piazza, the two stars imported for this
very short run.
</P>
<P>
   Among the strange cross-cultural notes was the absence of
organized cheering sections, a staple of regular Japanese games.
With tickets going for as much as nearly $200, this was a different
crowd, consisting of many button-down business executives, known
here as salarymen, and their guests.
</P>
<P>
   There was a bit of the expectation of a rock crowd. The fans had
come to see the two stars, who touch the imagination of the
Japanese public. Hampton was having trouble with his control, and
maybe even with the mound, but when he walked Sosa to load the
bases in the third, some boos were heard, almost unheard of at
Japanese baseball games or any other public gathering.
</P>
<P>
   The boos got even louder in the fifth when Hampton walked Sosa
again, this time with a runner on first and one out. With the crowd
approximately 95 percent Japanese, it could only be assumed that
the fans were hip enough to know that American fans would boo in
such a situation.
</P>
<P>
   The fans have a long way to go to approximate New York fans.
Nobody hurled invective _ to say nothing of AA batteries _ at the
heads of the players. Civility reigned.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs scored right away when Eric Young walked, stole second
and scored on a single by Damon Buford.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets tied it in the third on a single by Rey Ordonez, a
sacrifice by Hampton, a single by Rickey Henderson and a sacrifice
fly by Darryl Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs went ahead, 2-1, in the fifth on a single by Buford,
and after an out, three straight walks, including one to Shane
Andrews, to force in a run.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was struggling, either with the mound or himself. There
was talk before the game that the players were not happy with the
mound and the dirt area around home plate, feeling there was not
enough clay to provide traction for their large and powerful
frames.
</P>
<P>
   Players did seem to have trouble with the dirt. Both Robin
Ventura and Derek Bell of the Mets slipped after hitting the ball.
Ventura never got out of the batter's box after grounding to second
in the second inning. In addition, Todd Ziele, newly acquired by
the Mets and making his debut at first base, had his foot nicked by
a runner.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the game, with the Cubs leading by four runs, chants of
``Let's Go Mets'' could be heard. Piazza did not disappoint,
whacking a two-run homer, a signal for hundreds of tired fans to
start their trek homeward in this sprawling metropolitan region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1557EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1234 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-VIDEO-ART-2TAKES-$     03-29 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VIDEO-ART-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOSTON TV PARTY IN AID OF A VIDEO REVOLUTION  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
Miles Unger writes on art for boston.citysearch.com, an online
guide to the city. 
 By MILES UNGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On March 23, 1969, the infant medium of video art launched a
guerrilla raid on broadcast television. The attack, a show titled
``The Medium Is the Medium'' and described in the program guide as
``six avant-garde artists take over television,'' consisted of a
barrage of abstract images and visual non sequiturs.
</P>
<P>
   And if most viewers were too busy singing along with Peter, Paul
and Mary on ``The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' to notice the
artistic coup d'etat, the broadcast nevertheless marked a turning
point in the history of an art form that is now firmly entrenched
in the bastions of high culture.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sights that would have greeted the adventurous viewer
of Boston's WGBH that night was a psychedelic go-go dance _
interrupted by random splats of abstract color and the
electronically distorted face of Richard Nixon _ set to Beethoven's
``Moonlight Sonata.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Nam June Paik's ``Electronic Opera, No. 1.'' It begins:
``This is participation TV. Please follow instructions,'' and
continues with admonitions, delivered in Paik's heavily accented
English, to ``close your eyes,'' and then ``three-quarters close
your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The absurd instructions capture the mood of the project as a
whole, which through Dada-inspired mayhem tried to jolt viewers out
of the mindless passivity induced by the boob tube.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a strong belief among these artists in the late '60s
that they wanted to reinvent TV,'' says John Hanhardt, who
organized the current retrospective of Paik's work at the
Guggenheim Museum. Like many of their colleagues, video artists had
a utopian vision of breaking down the barriers between the museum
and the public in the belief that they could transform the world.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from the ``The Medium Is the Medium'' return to
broadcast television this Sunday at 4 p.m. when WGBH presents ``The
Electronic Canvas,'' a history of video art that highlights that
city's crucial contribution to the medium. In showing ``The
Electronic Canvas,'' which will be made available to other public
broadcasting stations after its Boston premiere, WGBH is returning
to its roots, since it was in its studios that much of the early
history of video art took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Medium Is the Medium'' was put together by a young
producer and director at WGBH named Fred Barzyk, and it marked the
first time that artists got their hands on broadcast equipment. It
was the artistic equivalent of a sit-in, an attempt to wrest, at
least for a moment, control of the mass media from the
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   The video artist Peter Campus remembers: ``There was this
political idea in the late '60s of not being in the galleries and
museums. To reach the masses, the work had to be broadcast, and at
the time WGBH was the only place in the country to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1969 Fred Barzyk already had a reputation for daring work. As
far back as 1964, Barzyk and his colleagues at the station had put
together a piece called ``Jazz Images'' in which music was
accompanied by such quirky vignettes as a view through a 50-cent
child's kaleidoscope and a potato reassembling itself out of bits
of peel. Though it was never meant to go on air, it helped foster a
spirit of invention that would later bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my way of proselytizing, `C'mon, we can do something
different,''' Barzyk explains.
</P>
<P>
   Now 63, with more than 40 years at WGBH behind him, Barzyk, his
once shaggy Beatles-style mane more neatly trimmed and gone gray,
still shows flashes of the mischievousness that helped launch an
artistic revolution. His own low-tech contribution to ``Jazz
Images'' was made with wire screens, a couple of candles and a
Miles Davis record.
</P>
<P>
   These experiments led to ``What's Happening, Mr. Silver?,'' a
local talk show starring David Silver, a Tufts University professor
with an iconoclastic bent and a Mick Jagger look. The program,
which Barzyk directed, favored illogical juxtapositions and such
experimental techniques as asking the audience to tune in
simultaneously to the two local WGBH stations, on which they would
run contrasting sound and images; another episode featured Abbie
Hoffman tossing drugs around the set. The show was almost canceled
after Silver made ``inappropriate remarks'' about Nancy Sinatra's
anatomy, leading to an on-air mea culpa by Barzyk and the host.
</P>
<P>
   The contribution of WGBH in those early days was to explore the
technical and aesthetic possibilities of video rather than to take
on political issues directly. ``WGBH early on was crucial,''
Hanhardt says. ``There was the idea of a laboratory, a place where
one could create, experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many at the time, Barzyk believed that artistic radicalism,
by expanding consciousness, somehow contributed to social change.
Ironically, what ultimately did in ``What's Happening, Mr.
Silver?'' was management's response to the assassination of Martin
Luther King Jr., which was to push more socially relevant
programming.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was the notoriety of ``Mr. Silver?'' that brought WGBH to the
attention of a group of young artists working with video at the
Howard Wise Gallery in New York. ``I was inside the castle, with
all this sophisticated equipment,'' Barzyk says. ``The artists were
on the outside looking in. Someone needed to lower the drawbridge
and let them in.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first to cross was Nam June Paik, the Korean-born
artist often regarded as the father of video art, who came to the
station as part of the Rockefeller Artists-in-Television program.
Though Barzyk's creed was to push the envelope, there was still a
culture clash between the technicians whose job was to get skin to
look like skin and an artist whose career had been built on
treating the television signal like electronic Play-Doh, something
to be squeezed and molded at will.
</P>
<P>
   Barzyk laughs as he tells of Paik tramping around the studio in
oversize rubber boots so he wouldn't get electrocuted while
fiddling with the insides of his TV sets. The crisis came during
Paik's 1970 ``Video Commune,'' a four-hour psychedelic romp set to
Beatles music; the juiced-up, synthesized signal blew the station's
transmitter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite tensions between technicians and artists, public
television, through WGBH and related programs at WNET in New York
and KQED in San Francisco, remained the one place where artists
could work with broadcast equipment and get their visions on the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who came to WGBH as part of the Television Workshop,
successor to the Artists-in-Television program, was a young video
artist named William Wegman. Wegman views his time at WGBH in the
early '70s as a missed opportunity. ``It was very hard for me to
work in front of other people,'' he remembers. ``I was sort of an
anti-tech person at the time, and my own studio seemed to suit my
more offhand style.''
</P>
<P>
   One who did take full advantage of the high-tech equipment the
station offered was Peter Campus, who made his seminal ``Three
Transitions'' at WGBH in 1973. Unlike Wegman, who tended to
improvise with whatever was at hand, Campus came with a complete
scenario. Working with multiple cameras and switchers that could
superimpose and merge different images of his own face, Campus used
the medium to explore psychological space.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what was going on at the time was: `Isn't it groovy?
Isn't this fun?''' Campus recalls. ``I thought of myself as
conveying something deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   If the late '60s and early '70s was a time when artists believed
they could change the world by changing mass media, that moment
soon passed. ``A window was created,'' Hanhardt says, ``where the
artists could explore what TV could be, one that's largely been
lost.'' In some sense, video art has come full circle, conquering
the world of the museum while losing the battle for broadcast
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Electronic Canvas'' _ which will also be screened
throughout April at the DeCordova Museum and Sculpture Park in
Lincoln, Mass., where viewers can check out more complete versions
of much of the historical material _ provides a taste of those
early experiments, but the antic sensibility of Barzyk and his
peers has been replaced by an earnest historicism.
</P>
<P>
   Such retrospective tributes are a sure sign that the medium has
come of age, but they also make one nostalgic for the days of
video's wild youth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1559EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1237 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SPORTS-GAMBLING30-COX     03-29 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-GAMBLING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE BILL WOULD BAN WAGERING ON COLLEGE SPORTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (s) sports categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two senators Wednesday introduced a bill that would
ban wagering on collegiate and amateur sports, calling it a
corrupting influence on young athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The Amateur Sports Integrity Act, co-sponsored by Sens. John
McCain, R-Ariz., and Sam Brownback, R-Kan., and backed by the
National Collegiate Athletic Association, would prohibit gambling
on high school and college sports as well as the Summer and Winter
Olympic Games. Congress last moved to restrict sports wagering in
1991, banning it in all but a handful of states, none of which have
any significant betting activity except Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   In that state, $2.3 billion is wagered legally each year on
sporting events, one-third of it on college athletics. The National
Collegiate Athletics Association's men's basketball tournament and
football bowl games account for between $50 to $60 million each.
</P>
<P>
   ``By closing the Vegas loophole and banning college sports
gambling completely, we will end a practice that has turned college
athletes into objects to be bet upon, exposing them to unwarranted
pressure, bribery and corruption,'' McCain said at a Senate
Commerce Committee hearing at which several government, NCAA and
gambling officials testified.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback said, ``I realize that a ban on collegiate sports
gambling will not eliminate all gambling on college sports.
However, a total ban will prevent another avenue for those
participating in point-shaving scandals to spread out their
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee released a letter from 65 college coaches from
across the country that said gambling on amateur games was a
corrupting influence on young people.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 84 percent of NCAA referees said they had
participated in some form of gambling since beginning their
careers, according to a University of Michigan study discussed at
the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   That study found that nearly 40 percent of referees bet on
sporting events, and 20 percent said they gambled on the NCAA
basketball tournament. Some referees even admitted they had been
asked to fix games they were officiating, while others said they
were aware of the spread on a game and it affected the way they
officiated the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill said it represented an attempt by the NCAA
to divert attention from its problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevada is not the problem, and the NCAA should stop trying to
cover up its own non-existent efforts to teach student athletes
about the laws which prohibit betting on college sports,'' said
Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the NCAA should invest some of the billions of dollars
they are raking in on college athletics to spread the word about
the dangers of illegal gambling on their own campuses,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada's other senator, Richard Bryan, also a Democrat, noted
that a recent survey of six colleges in five states found that 23
percent of students gambled at least once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Fahrenkopf, president of the American Gaming Association,
told the committee there is nothing improper in betting legally on
college athletics. Outlawing it, he said would only drive betting
underground or overseas via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Closing sports books to send a message about gambling is like
closing restaurants to send a message to young people about
alcohol, added Rep. Shelley Berkley, D-Nev.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need better education and law enforcement, not a punitive
measure against one state's primary industry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1602EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
