<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1239 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FRIEDKIN-FILMS-2TAKES     03-29 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDKIN-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIEDKIN TRIES AGAIN FOR THE A-LIST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ William Friedkin was a golden boy in Hollywood in
the early 1970s. Two of his films, ``The French Connection'' and
``The Exorcist,'' were among the most successful of that decade.
But Friedkin responded to sudden wealth and power with the kind of
self-destructive arrogance all too common in Hollywood. The town
waited for him to fail. And he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I was arrogant, I let success go to my head, I did not
suffer fools gladly,'' said Friedkin, the director of the new drama
``Rules of Engagement,'' which opens Friday. He spoke quietly. ``I
probably was more enamored of myself than my talent deserved,'' he
said. ``I thought I was infallible. I wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 64, Friedkin accepts his fallibility with a shrug,
and still seems brashly confident. But the years have taken their
toll. ``If someone is successful as a filmmaker, you have the keys
to the kingdom, you can do what you want,'' he said, seated in a
small lounge near the editing facilities at Culver City where he
was adding the final touches of music to the new film. ``But if you
have a failure, you virtually must beg for alms with the rest of
les miserables.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules of Engagement,'' which has stirred more anticipation
than any Friedkin movie in recent years, is mostly a military
courtroom drama in which a highly decorated United States Marine
colonel (played by Samuel L. Jackson) asks another Marine colonel
and his comrade-in-arms from Vietnam (played by Tommy Lee Jones) to
serve as his lawyer in a court martial. The Jackson character is
accused of killing unarmed civilians who have engaged in a violent
demonstration outside the United States Embassy in Yemen.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, by Stephen Gaghan, was adapted from a story by
James Webb, the novelist who was secretary of the Navy in 1987-88.
Webb, a decorated Marine infantry commander in Vietnam, is also
executive producer of the film, which is being released by
Paramount.
</P>
<P>
   The actors said that Friedkin was, in many ways, a welcome
change from the hotshot music video directors who have surged into
the movie business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Billy's mellowed over the years, but there's a
definite fire there,'' Jackson said. ``What makes him unusual
compared to so many other directors is that he really knows what
he's doing. He has a very clear idea of how the picture begins and
plays and ends. A lot of times guys have no idea what they really
want. Billy knows. He hires you because you can do the job that he
wants you to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has heard all the war stories about Friedkin's tantrums
and misbehavior. ``The arrogance and, I guess, the hardness is no
longer there,'' he said. ``All the things he went through got him
to the place he is today. He's able to do things calmly today that
he was hotheaded about years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is not exactly a comeback for Friedkin, who has, in
recent years, directed ``Blue Chips'' (1994), a well-received
basketball drama starring Nick Nolte and Shaquille O'Neal, as well
as ``Jade'' (1995), with David Caruso and Linda Fiorentino, which
fared disastrously at the box office. In 1997, Friedkin also
directed a Showtime/MGM television remake of the classic ``12 Angry
Men,'' which earned him strong reviews.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Rules of Engagement,'' from its stark opening in the
jungles of Vietnam to its mob scenes in Yemen (actually filmed in
Morocco) to the military courtroom, could mark a turnabout in a
career that floundered after extraordinary success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy just picked poor subjects _ his selection of material
was not good,'' said Richard D. Zanuck, who produced the film with
Scott Rudin. ``And when you're dealing with poor material,
everything else gets dragged down.''
</P>
<P>
   Zanuck has known Friedkin for nearly 30 years, going back to
when the director came to 20th Century Fox with ``The French
Connection'' after every other studio in town had rejected it. At
the time Zanuck was Fox's president of production. ``He's probably
the most focused director I've ever worked with,'' Zanuck said.
``He's very organized. He has a clear-cut vision. And he sticks to
it. There's no indecisiveness about Billy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Friedkin's poor choices over the years _ films like
``Sorcerer'' (1977), ``The Brinks Job'' (1979), ``Cruising''
(1980), ``Deal of the Century'' (1983) and ``Rampage'' (1987) _
were compounded by a reputation that haunted him. In Peter
Biskind's 1998 book ``Easy Riders, Raging Bulls,'' about film
directors of the 1970s, Friedkin was described as demanding,
autocratic, bullying and immensely difficult to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin hardly disagrees. ``I had come, quite quickly, from
obscurity to great success,'' he said. ``I mean, the two hardest
things to live with are success and failure. Success is often as
difficult as failure. To be extremely honest about it, I was
arrogant beyond my talent. That's what it boils down to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an adversarial relationship with the heads of the
studios then. When you're riding a string of hits, there's very
little problem with that. But then the worm turns.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure of ``Jade,'' a mystery thriller, especially
disturbed him. ``After `Jade,' I thought I must be doing something
wrong because I liked the film and I thought it delivered,'' he
said. ``But the audience is right. They're always, always right.
You hear directors complain that the advertising is lousy, the
distribution is no good, the date was wrong to open the film. I
don't believe that. The audience is never wrong. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudin said he hired Friedkin for the current film because of a
hunch that he would prove especially adept at a film about the
military. ``We needed someone who was muscular and ascetic,'' Rudin
said. ``There was a danger of it being bathetic, that it would
become sentimental. I knew Billy wouldn't fall for that trap. He's
got an astringent tone. That's what was needed here. It's emotional
but tough at the center. It's about guys who are not especially
verbal. I knew Billy could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rudin said that Friedkin, like some other well-known directors
of the 1970s, had, over the years, become ensnared in a Hollywood
spiral. ``Billy made a couple of turkeys,'' he said. ``And once you
get off the A-list, you don't get the scripts anymore. But you
can't get back to the A-list without the scripts. Well, he got the
script here and he did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Friedkin has mellowed, because of his age and,
perhaps, his seemingly stable personal life. After some tumultuous
relationships, he has been married for eight years to Sherry
Lansing, chairman of Paramount Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``She totally backs away from anything to do with any film I
make there,'' Friedkin says, adding that most of his dealings are
with producers and production executives at the studio.
</P>
<P>
   Before Lansing, he was wed three times, including a brief
marriage to Jeanne Moreau. ``Sherry is my fourth wife _ we should
leave out the other names to protect the innocent,'' said Friedkin,
who has two sons from his earlier marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin's survival, and his stubbornness, are probably the
result of a childhood and early career that were marked by an
intense hunger to succeed that has never diminished.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in a one-bedroom apartment on the north side of
Chicago; his Russian-immigrant father barely earned a living and
his mother was a nurse. At the age of 16, he got a job in the
mailroom of the television station WGN. At about the same time he
saw the film ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it five times,'' he recalled. ``I stayed in the theater
all day. I was stunned. It moved me so profoundly. I had never seen
a film that embodied the various art forms _ music, composition,
lighting, editing, performance. It was incredibly powerful to me.''
</P>
<P>
   By his early 20s, Friedkin was directing live television in
Chicago, and he soon turned to documentaries. By the early 1960s he
had made a documentary called ``The People Versus Paul Crump,''
about a black man on death row accused of killing a guard in the
course of a holdup at a baby-food factory. The inmate, who insisted
that he was innocent, was later given a sentence of life
imprisonment and was subsequently released from jail. The film won
numerous awards and caught the attention of the television producer
David Wolper, who offered Friedkin a job in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin soon began working in network television, including
directing episodes of ``Alfred Hitchcock Presents.'' His first
feature film, in 1967, was ``Good Times,'' with Sonny and Cher. It
was during a period when studios were seeking to imitate ``A Hard
Day's Night.'' Friedkin said with a laugh: ``I loved both Sonny and
Cher, but, I tell you, you'd have to be sentenced to see that film.
It's inept. And that's being charitable.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed were ``The Night They Raided Minsky's'' (1968) and
adaptations of two plays, Harold Pinter's ``Birthday Party'' (1969)
and Mart Crowley's ``Boys in the Band'' (1970). After that came the
classic ``The French Connection'' (1971), which not only won five
Academy Awards, including best picture, but whose sharp, gritty
documentary style has certainly had an impact on police films and,
notably, television series like ``N.Y.P.D. Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stylistically as far out as `The Blair Witch Project'
is today,'' he said. ``It's been copied a lot. Just look at
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin's style in ``The French Connection'' was
straightforward, unsubtle. The film was made as if it were a
documentary, with cameras catching events unexpectedly. At times,
Friedkin did not tell the camera crew precisely what to shoot, but
merely told it to follow the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was making documentaries, I would often not know where
to put my camera if an event was taking place _ a riot, a police
chase,'' he said. ``I wanted to make this film, which was based on
an actual case, look like the cameras just happened to drop in on
an actual event.''
</P>
<P>
   His next film, ``The Exorcist,'' is being reissued shortly with
an additional 10 minutes that had been cut in its original version.
Friedkin said the newer version of the thriller has a spiritual
element that had been missing. The film itself has grossed more
than $500 million, a startling figure given the low cost of tickets
in the 1970s. (Within a few months of the film's release, Friedkin
got a check for $1 million, a huge profit check at the time for a
director).
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin is uncertain about his next films, although he has been
working on one about the boxer Sonny Liston and another about the
battle for Jerusalem in the 1948 Israeli-Arab war. But these films
hinge, to some degree, on the critical and audience responses to
``Rules of Engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   He sipped some water out of a bottle. ``If the film doesn't work
for an audience, I will be tremendously disheartened and
disappointed and depressed,'' he said. ``But only because I have
failed. I can't blame anyone else. The failure ends up in one
place. I made the choices. With a lot of help, of course. But I
made the decisions. And I'll have to live with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1605EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1241 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HIGH-FIDELITY-FILM-2T     03-29 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-FIDELITY-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING FAITH WITH `HIGH FIDELITY'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Jamie Malanowski's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
the director M. Night Shyamalan.  
 By JAMIE MALANOWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the transition from novel to film, Rob, the hero of ``High
Fidelity'' _ Nick Hornby's 1995 novel, Stephen Frears' new film _
undergoes some minor transformations: he ceases being British and
becomes American, relocates from London to Chicago and sees his
last name change from Fleming to Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The first two changes were no doubt to accommodate the casting
of the Chicago native John Cusack; the last you can speculate about
on your own. Otherwise, much remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   Rob is still the owner of a marginally failing vintage record
shop, still called Championship Vinyl, which is still manned by
``the musical moron twins,'' Dick and Barry; he is still moping
about his love life, especially his recent dumping by his
girlfriend, Laura; and he is still the gloomy underachiever whose
relentless navel-gazing is made palatable by his honesty about his
shortcomings and his often quite funny insights about men, women
and romance. As film adaptations go, this one is almost fiercely
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``I never expected it to be so faithful,'' Hornby fairly
chirped last week. ``At times it appears to be a film in which John
Cusack reads my book.''
</P>
<P>
   Which should be good news for the novel's rabid fans. ``High
Fidelity'' isn't exactly a cult novel _ there's no shape-shifting,
no artificial intelligences, no pages-long hallucinogenic spiels _
but it does seem to be something of a cultural hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has become one of those books that people of a
certain age have all read,'' says Wendy Carlton, Hornby's editor at
Riverhead Books. ``It was the kind of book that everybody in my
summer house just had to read. There's a lot of us _ aging
teen-agers, thirtysomething teen-agers _ who are a lot like Rob:
not married, not settled, career in the air. We love the freedom of
it, but at the same time we feel this nagging guilt. You know, that
`By the time they were my age, my parents already had me' kind of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornby said: ``Both `High Fidelity' and my earlier book, `Fever
Pitch'''_ a memoir about his life as a devoted fan of Arsenal, the
powerhouse English soccer club _ ``received the most curious
response. People would come up and say, `This book is about me _
literally, this book is about me.' I've been told, I don't know how
many times, `I know the record shop you wrote about,' and the
shop's in some part of the country I've never been to. It's a
fairly depressing indictment of the state of things, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Guys, of course, find it easy to identify with at least some
part of Rob: if not his thoughts on women, dating, sex,
relationships and disappointment, then his ardor for pop culture,
for rock music and movies and sitcoms, and his tireless willingness
to ponder, critique and rank their tiniest nuances. Which albums
have the best side-one, cut-one songs? Which are the five best
episodes of ``Cheers''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Men have a way of talking in superlatives,'' says Hornby,
speaking by telephone from London. ``There's no point in saying
that someone is good at something; you have to say he's the best
whatever since so and so. Men like to have a frame of reference.''
One of the funniest, smartest riffs in ``High Fidelity'' is Rob's
lengthy rumination on whether Laura's dumping of him ranks as one
of the ``desert-island, all-time, top five most memorable
split-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   But the novel has also found a receptive audience among women.
``The first wave of readers had a lot of guys,'' Hornby says. ``But
there was a second wave of women, perhaps because the story was
told from the man's perspective and the men liked it, so the women
maybe thought it would give them an inside line into what the men
were thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlton recalls: ``Nick had a reading at Astor Place. There were
a lot of couples. I can't tell you the number of times you'd see
girls nudging the guys, saying like: `See? That's what drives me
crazy about you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hornby muses: ``Yes, the nudge seems to be my literary bit.
Other people get reviews. I get nudges.''
</P>
<P>
   Attaining nudgability is certainly the hope of the makers of
``High Fidelity,'' the film. The book was optioned by Disney's
Touchstone division, where it went into development and was finally
presented to John Cusack and his writing and producing partners on
this film, D.V. DeVincentis and Steve Pink.
</P>
<P>
   They were also members of the writing team for ``Grosse Pointe
Blank'' (1997), a successful dark comedy that happened to star
Cusack and happened to be about a young man caught up in both a
career crisis and romantic confusion, and that made such a fruitful
use of pop music that it spawned two volumes of soundtrack hits. In
other words, in ``High Fidelity'' they found about as close to a
sequel as they could get without needing Roman numerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge in adapting the novel,'' Cusack says,
``was to commit to direct address.'' Indeed, Rob in ``High
Fidelity'' shares with other protagonists of the new century, like
television's Malcolm in ``Malcolm in the Middle'' and Christopher
Titus in ``Titus,'' an affinity for breaking the fourth wall and
talking directly to the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob, like a lot of Nick's characters, is a guy who ought to
know better than to be the way he is,'' Cusack continues. ``And in
fact he does know better. He's a lazy, delusional slacker, but he's
brutally honest with himself, and has these terrifically incisive
insights, and that's what makes him redeemable. Rob does a lot of
things where he messes up, and those were fairly easy to show.
</P>
<P>
   But the inner, more confessional aspects were harder. Almost
immediately we thought, let's just do what Michael Caine did in
`Alfie''' _ speak directly to the camera _ ``but then I vetoed that
idea. I thought there'd just be too much of me. But then Frears
brought it up, and we went with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Frears, who had worked with Cusack a decade ago, memorably,
in ``The Grifters'': ``The direct address was very liberating. Once
you commit to that, you can bypass naturalism completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving the setting to America subtly altered the characters'
behavior in ways sure to start purists debating. ``Nick's
characters are very English,'' says Frears, who is English himself
and whose early films ``My Beautiful Laundrette'' and ``Sammy and
Rosie Get Laid,'' which were set in London, share a sensibility
like that of ``High Fidelity.'' ``Rob is mental, stoical, a passive
observer. And quite glum. And I think this is one of the
differences between English and American actors. American actors
like to do things, they want to be engaged in things, they want the
audience to like them, even if their characters are doing some not
so likable things. So I was enormously relieved to be doing it in
America. To have left that English glumness of it was a great
relief. Now I'm sure I'll be spat at on the streets when I
return.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge the writers faced was the partly creative,
partly legal problem of figuring out what songs would go where.
Given that Rob and his cohorts, Dick and Barry, are such musical
snobs _ ``The three of them see themselves as misplaced royalty,''
Cusack says, ``as kings of somewhere, though maybe not here on
earth'' _ the cues clearly had to be smart, and if not immediately
recognizable, then at least very intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film has 70 song cues, and we probably listened to 2,000
songs to get those 70 cues,'' Cusack says. ``We used our Rob and
Dick and Barry dispositions a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornby says: ``The movie was made by people who are exactly the
right age. They shifted some of their reference points slightly,
but the book clearly made sense to them. One of the things
different is the adoration of all things black American, which is
such an English thing. We're great curators of black America. But
the filmmakers transferred their sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   If the soundtrack is studded with nuggets _ the Velvet
Underground's ``Who Loves the Sun?,'' Bob Dylan's ``Most of the
Time,'' Elvis Costello's ``Shipbuilding,'' the 13th Floor
Elevators' ``You're Going to Me'' _ so are the performances.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Robbins, Lili Taylor and Joan Cusack all get to swipe a
scene or two, and Lisa Bonet and Sara Gilbert, of whom we've seen
little since they stopped being the daughters on ``Cosby'' and
``Roseanne,'' make appealing appearances. Todd Louiso and Jack
Black are hilarious in what should be career-boosting portrayals of
Dick and Barry, and Catherine Zeta-Jones, in an uncredited
performance, plays an ex-girlfriend, showing in flashback all the
sexiness and verve that appealed to the collegiate Rob and in the
present all the boorishness that makes him wonder what he was
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand, in an all-too-brief ``Play It Again, Sam''-like
cameo, is Bruce Springsteen, who offers Rob a bit of romantic
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had this idea to have Rob have this conversation with Bruce
in his head,'' Cusack says. ``Of course we never really thought
we'd get Bruce, we just thought putting him in there would make a
good read for the studio and get them all excited. But I had met
him socially, so I thought even though he's going to say no, I may
as well call him and throw the Hail Mary pass and get it over with.
And he kind of just laughed at the idea and said, `Send me a
script.' So when we finished shooting, we wrapped around 2 a.m.,
flew to New York, and taped him the next morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The riskiest choice the filmmakers made was casting a Danish
newcomer, Iben Hjejle, as Laura. ``We had been reading a lot of
actresses,'' Cusack says, ``and we had no consensus about choice.
And then Stephen went to a film festival in Berlin where he saw
`Mifune,' in which Iben is just wonderful, and she was there
getting an award. And he called me in the middle of the night,
screaming: `I've found her! I've found Laura!' I said, `Where are
you?' He says, `In Germany!' I say, `Laura's German?' He says, `No,
from Denmark.' That's when I asked him if he was drunk. And then I
got on a plane to Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   Frears says: ``I don't know what she thought. I talked to her
for two hours. I felt like a salesman. I was ashamed of myself,
like I was a white slaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the truth is that this is a story about a man obsessed
with a woman. Well, this has to be something everyone understands.
You have to have someone who fulfills that requirement. Well,
that's an incredible thing to hang on someone; no woman in life is
like that. But on that cold night in February in Berlin, Iben
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack says: ``Laura has to be the ballast of the film. The
actress who plays her has to provide the weight, has to convey the
sense of what he'd lose, has to say, `Look, you're playing with
real bullets here.' And Iben has that depth and presence. And she
does it without pushing. She doesn't have it in her to fall into
melodrama. I'd hate to be on the wrong side of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack and Frears know they have not undertaken a simple
assignment; adapting a beloved book, no matter how faithfully, is
an invitation to criticism. But they appear to have at least one
fan. ``It's a really good movie,'' Nick Hornby says. ``All authors
should be so lucky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
