<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-NUDE-NYT     03-29 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NUDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIES AND STATES MAY BAN NUDE DANCING, COURT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa., Ind.)  (Eds: Longer version to follow.) 
(nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that cities and
states may ban nude dancing as a way of combatting crime and other
``negative secondary effects'' associated with establishments that
offer this kind of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In its 6-3 vote upholding an Erie, Pa., ordinance that requires
exotic dancers to wear at least pasties and a G-string, the court's
fractured majority did not explain how that requirement would
reduce the crime, prostitution, sexual assaults or other problems
associated with places where dancers appear fully nude.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be sure, requiring dancers to wear pasties and G-strings
may not greatly reduce these secondary effects,'' Justice Sandra
Day O'Connor conceded in her opinion. But she said such a
regulation needed only to further the government's legitimate
interest rather than fully accomplish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may also be true that a pasties and G-string requirement
would not be as effective as, for example, a requirement that the
dancers be fully clothed,'' O'Connor said, ``but the city must
balance its efforts to address the problem with the requirement
that the restriction be no greater than necessary to further the
city's interest.''
</P>
<P>
   In its decision Wednesday, Erie v. Pap's A.M., No. 98-1161, the
court took up where it left off nine years ago, when an even more
splintered majority upheld a public indecency law in Indiana that
also banned nude dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, the court ruled that nude dancing _ as opposed to
simple public nudity _ was a form of expression that had at least
some minimal protection under the First Amendment but that could
nonetheless be regulated under an appropriate standard.
</P>
<P>
   The court failed in the Indiana case to settle on a standard,
and did only marginally better Wednesday as Justice David H. Souter
changed his mind on the amount of evidence cities needed in order
to justify a ban on nude dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Joining O'Connor in the majority were Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justices Anthony M. Kennedy, Stephen G. Breyer,
Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Souter
dissented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1612EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1246 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-EILEEN-HECKART-THEATE     03-29 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EILEEN-HECKART-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LAST, PLAYING GRANDMA, SHE GETS TO BE THE STAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You may not know the name, but you know the face: the
big baggy eyes, the sensual mouth with the overbite. And then there
is that deep hoarse voice and that sulfurous laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Heckart has been acting for more than 50 years now,
almost always as the second banana. She was the spinster teacher
who gets tipsy in ``Picnic'' in 1953 and the alcoholic mother whose
son is drowned in ``The Bad Seed'' in 1955, both on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do one, they have no imagination,'' said Heckart about all
the drunks she has played. Sometimes she is the aunt, as she was in
the Mary Tyler Moore television show. She was Marilyn Monroe's
waitress friend in the 1956 movie ``Bus Stop.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time, and at 81, Heckart has the lead. Indeed, she
dominates the stage at the Promenade Theater for nearly every one
of the 110 minutes of ``The Waverly Gallery,'' Kenneth Lonergan's
memory play about his grandmother's decline, in which Heckart
portrays Gladys Green, a woman who is gradually becoming senile.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Anderman and Mark Blum play her daughter and son-in-law;
Josh Hamilton plays her grandson, who is the narrator, and Anthony
Arkin the last painter whose work Gladys exhibits at the gallery of
the title, in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   Heckart was having tea at the Plaza recently before an evening
performance. She is driven to the theater each day from her home in
Norwalk, Conn., except for the Wednesday and Saturday matinees,
when Scotty Bloch takes the part. ``This is my swan song, my last
performance in a play; it just takes too much energy,'' Heckart
said. ``You get such a good one, you may as well go out on a
wave.''
</P>
<P>
   And a wave it is. Ben Brantley called her performance
``uncanny'' in The New York Times, describing her ``beautifully
coherent and intelligent portrayal of a woman sliding into
incoherence.''
</P>
<P>
   To disintegrate mentally and physically onstage in front of an
audience is, to say the least, taxing. ``She has to have a sense of
what she's doing and thinking, even though she is
self-destructing,'' said Scott Ellis, the play's director.
</P>
<P>
   Heckart portrays Gladys's decline in almost imperceptible
gradations. She begins Act I with a slight stoop, a faint
trembling, a cheery deafness. In the second act comes the cane, the
language is increasingly disorganized, the trembling becomes more
noticeable. Until finally she is a tiny figure, wasting away, ready
to die.
</P>
<P>
   So it is a shock to see Heckart at the curtain call, walking
briskly onto the stage and bowing gracefully to the audience. And
it is a surprise to meet her in person, to see the pink-and-white
complexion, the soft white hair neatly coiffed, the careful makeup,
the big sapphire and diamond ring, the shapely legs and the high
heels.
</P>
<P>
   How did she go about creating the performance? ``I don't know
how to act,'' Heckart said, with her deep laugh. ``I don't know how
to talk about it.'' Actually, her son Luke, a theater director
himself, said in a separate interview that his mother is ``a
perfectionist, so exacting, so specific; she does a great deal of
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Alzheimer's is never mentioned by name in ``The Waverly
Gallery,'' which takes place from 1989 to 1991, Lonergan said about
Gladys's decline, ``We assumed it was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want it to be a play (italics)about(end italics)
Alzheimer's in particular,'' he added. ``I wanted it to be
analogous to other things that have happened to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Heckart said she had seen the effect of Alzheimer's on a number
of friends. And when the play was in rehearsals last summer at the
Williamstown Theater Festival, where it had an earlier run, Ellis
brought in a nurse who cares for Alzheimer's patients, and a woman
whose husband had the disease, to talk to the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Heckart was ideal for the part of Gladys, said Lonergan, who
also wrote the hit 1996 play about slackers, ``This Is Our Youth.''
``Eileen is a great actress and she also has a certain urban
sharpness to her,'' he said. ``You believe her as someone who spent
all their life in Greenwich Village. It's a big personality under
assault. A milder personality falling apart is less dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress's early life had its own dramas. She was born in
Ohio in 1919. Her parents separated when she was 2. Her father took
her younger brother to live with him, she said, and she remained
with her mother. Heckart's mother, Esther, was married five times.
``She liked it a lot,'' Heckart said with a wicked laugh. When her
mother finally went into a nursing home she asked her daughter:
```Was I married three or four times?' I said, `Would you believe
five?''' Heckart made a list of all her husbands for her mother.
``Do you remember anything about them?'' Heckart asked. ``They were
all gorgeous,'' her mother replied.
</P>
<P>
   Heckart graduated from Ohio State University. It was while she
was in college that she caught whooping cough, which, she said, she
ignored. The result was the deepening of her voice to its
distinctive register.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, she married her college sweetheart, John
Harrison Yankee Jr., who became an insurance broker. The couple had
three sons, Mark, 47, a liquor salesman; Philip, 45, a stage
manager for cruise ship theatrical productions, and Luke, 40, the
director.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In her brief biography in the program for ``The Waverly
Gallery,'' Heckart mentions what is important to her: the sons, of
course, her two granddaughters and, among other awards, her Oscar
(for best supporting actress in the 1972 ``Butterflies Are Free'').
</P>
<P>
   She began her career in summer stock. ``When I was young, I
wanted to drag a mink stole around like Joan Crawford,'' Heckart
said. ``But I wound up in all those kitchen dramas.''
</P>
<P>
   She came to New York and, like many actors of her generation,
cut her teeth in live television _ ``The Alcoa Hour,'' ``The Philco
Television Playhouse,'' ``Goodyear Television Playhouse.'' The
actresses wore black lipstick for the cameras then, and the heat
from the lights was so intense that costumes wilted, Heckart said.
But the pressure of performing live provided unparalleled
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Once, on an NBC show _ Heckart couldn't remember which _ an
actor missed his line and the director simply cut off the cameras
to give him a cue. For a few seconds there was only static on
television screens across America. But ``everyone was used to
having snow'' in those days, Heckart said.
</P>
<P>
   Her first break onstage came in William Inge's ``Picnic,'' when
she was 33. She played a schoolteacher with, as Brooks Atkinson put
it in The New York Times, ``a hunger for life and a knack for
getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Woodward was an understudy and fell in love with Paul
Newman, who played the rich boy. Did Heckart suspect? ``We all
suspected, yes. She was a very Southern beauty, very gentle, very
quiet; in her little assertive way, though, there was a lot of
steel in that lady.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bad Seed'' followed ``Picnic.'' Heckart found she could
hardly endure the role of a mother whose son is drowned by a
little-girl murderer. ``Mark was a year old,'' she said. ``I saw
his face going underwater at night. The doctor said, `You have to
get out of it.''' She acted the part again on film, but disliked
the movie. ``The Hayes office had to have a happy ending,'' she
said. The little girl is struck by lightning. ``It was tacky,
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   She portrayed Van Heflin's wife on Broadway in Arthur Miller's
``View From the Bridge'' in 1956, and in 1958 was an unhappily
married woman in another Inge drama, ``The Dark at the Top of the
Stairs.'' In 1969 came ``Butterflies Are Free'' on Broadway with
Keir Dullea and Blythe Danner, in which she played Dullea's mother.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, she was supposed to arrive onstage to find Dullea
and his girlfriend, played by Danner, in a state of half dress
after they have made love. But one night, Heckart recalled, Dullea
couldn't get the zipper closed on his trousers. ``It was top of the
second act,'' said Heckart. ``Blythe got so hysterical laughing she
walked offstage. The next scene was Blythe and me. Without her
there was nothing. She didn't come back.''
</P>
<P>
   So Heckart, the trouper, turned to the audience and said,
```Ladies and gentlemen, we're a group of actors who can't cope
with a zipper. If you don't mind, we'll start again.' It took us so
long to get that audience to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Heckart's husband died suddenly on his morning
walk. She was standing at the kitchen window when she saw him fall.
``I looked out the window and he was gone,'' she said. ``It was the
worst year of my life.'' The two had been married for 53 years.
Their son, Luke, ``got me out of it,'' Heckart said. Luke Yankee
put together a video retrospective of all his mother's major roles,
and the two of them presented it as a lecture on cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   Heckart is grateful that before her husband's death, the couple
had moved out of their big house in Connecticut, with the swimming
pool and all the gardens, into another home that is easier to
maintain. ``Jack was very wise,'' she noted. ``He said let's get
rid of this big house before one of us is ill and has to make this
decision alone.'' Today, she lives near her oldest son, Mark.
</P>
<P>
   What is the secret of her seeming youthfulness and vigor? Does
she exercise? ``As little as possible,'' Heckart said. Yes, walking
is good for you, she acknowledged: ``But, oh, my, I think, what a
chore! I'd rather drive than walk anyplace.''
</P>
<P>
   And let it be said, Heckart also smokes, a great deal. ``I go
down there,'' said Ellis, the director, about Heckart's dressing
room, ``and all I do is cough as I'm giving notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, if she doesn't exercise, what does Heckart do with her
spare time? ``I needlepointed myself to death,'' she said. What she
likes most these days is going to the Foxwoods casino in Ledyard,
Conn., with a friend. At the entrance, the friend heads to the
blackjack tables, Heckart to the slot machines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
