<HEADLINE>
HISTORY MADE AT THE TOKYO DOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sports Column with BBN-METS-CUBS) 
(jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the end of the Mets' 5-3 opening game loss to the Cubs on
Wednesday, Thom Brennaman, the Fox Sports Net's effusive
play-by-play announcer, described the game from Tokyo as ``one of
the most historic nights in the grand history of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Where should this mediocre game be placed in baseball history?
Between the ``Black Sox'' scandal and Cal Ripken playing his
2,131st consecutive game? Between Boston Red Sox owner Harry Frazee
selling Babe Ruth to the Yankees and, let's see, Mark McGwire's
62nd home run in 1998?
</P>
<P>
   But let's give Brennaman some slack even if he blithely
pooh-poohed all criticism of opening the season in Tokyo by saying
one happy Japanese boy's cheering for Mike Piazza's home run made
the trip all worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, history was ultimately made at the Tokyo Dome.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first regular season game played by Major League
Baseball outside North America. It forced Mets fans to rise by 5:05
a.m. ET and Cubs fans up by 4:05 a.m. Central Time.
</P>
<P>
   The game was certainly the first time that an American-born
manager, the Mets' Bobby Valentine, who once managed a Japanese
team, returned to play a game under protest.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, it was the first time that Japanese fans witnessed a
nine-walk performance by the starting pitcher for a major league
team on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   What lessons shall be learned, passed down through generations,
thanks to the uneconomic pitching of the Mets' Mike Hampton!
</P>
<P>
   The game bore witness to major leaguers wearing advertising on
their persons _ a sight not yet seen in North America _ uniform
sleeve patches promoting AIU, the Japanese subsidiary of the Auto
Insurance Group, and helmet decals for AM/PM, a convenience store
chain.
</P>
<P>
   It was disappointing to watch this historic event along with
Brennaman and his partner, Bob Brenly. Brenly, a credible analyst,
is always better than Brennaman, but much better when he is teamed
during postseason telecasts with Tim McCarver and Joe Buck. With
Brennaman, Brenly shifts too easily into the hype mode; beside
McCarver, he thinks and works harder.
</P>
<P>
   Brenly certainly did not need to pause at midgame to say, ``The
stands are full of baseball fans at the Tokyo Dome.'' We got the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   For New York fans, the game needed Howie Rose, who is still
fulfilling his last few games of Islanders' play-by-play chores,
Gary Thorne, Ralph Kiner or Tom Seaver.
</P>
<P>
   The telecast lacked the feel of an historic event, or even a
memorable one. Where was the Japanese prime minister? The American
ambassador to Japan? Somebody reading ``Shogun?''
</P>
<P>
   The production needed an Al Trautwig, of the MSG Network, or a
Matt Laughlin, of Fox Sports New York, to patrol the Tokyo Dome to
speak to some of the clearly ecstatic fans who were enthralled with
the first of the two-game series. And viewers should have been
treated to more video clips of former major leaguers who spent
quality time in the Japanese leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The game needed an expert on Japanese baseball, like a Robert
Whiting, the author of the authoritative book, ``You Gotta Have
Wa,'' to explain the hold baseball has on Japanese fans.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we got some graphics about former major leaguers like
Randy Bass and their success in Japan, and information about the
cost of a platter of sushi at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports Net should have given us a show to reward those of us
who cut into their sleep to catch opening day. Fortunately, I fell
asleep four times (the third time, Hampton walked in a Cub run)
waiting for something historic to happen. Hearing ``Twist and
Shout'' on the Tokyo Dome loudspeaker system just did not measure
up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
