<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VOICE-MATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATH SOFTWARE FOR BLIND AND DISABLED STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Md.)   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless you are like the character played by Matt Damon in ``Good
Will Hunting,'' solving complex mathematical equations is no walk
in the park. But for those with visual or physical impairments,
doing advanced math is even more daunting because of the difficulty
of converting Braille or the spoken word into equations on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is more help for such students. Programs developed by
Henry Gray, a professor of statistics and mathematics at Southern
Methodist University in Dallas, have taken a step beyond other
software that aids the disabled because they can accept and read
back mathematical symbols and commands. The programs are intended
to give disabled students greater access to a high-level math
education.
</P>
<P>
   Gray's software works in combination with other programs to
translate mathematical voice commands into corresponding
expressions on the computer and to help perform the computations.
The solutions can be printed out with a voice command as well.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gray's programs, called MathTalk for the Visually
Impaired, is still being tested. It is designed for high school and
college students and works in combination with Dragon Dictate,
speech-recognition software from Dragon Systems; Scientific
Notebook, a computational program by MacKichan Software; JAWS, a
screen reader from Henter-Joyce; and a Nemeth converter program,
shareware that converts conventional math symbols into Nemeth
Braille, the standard code for math and science notation used in
North America.
</P>
<P>
   Physically impaired students who cannot type can do high school
and college math by using another of Gray's programs, called
MathTalk Scientific Notebook. It lets a student dictate math
assignments or information, line by line, into a computer
microphone, just as someone would dictate a letter with a dictation
program. If the wrong word or symbol is recorded, the student can
say ``erase'' or ``wrong word'' to have MathTalk Scientific
Notebook make a correction. The program can handle about 3,000
mathematical commands.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the high school and college-level programs, Gray
has designed an elementary school version of MathTalk Scientific
Notebook that could help physically handicapped children. The
software, called ArithmeticTalk ($395), lets students speak
commands like ``put down a seven and carry a one'' to direct the
solving of multiplication, division, subtraction and addition
problems on a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   To use MathTalk for the Visually Impaired, a student must have a
sighted person type in the math material or dictate it into the
computer microphone. Then the student can get a printout in Nemeth
Braille. The student can do math problems in Nemeth Braille and can
produce a conventional copy for the teacher without the help of a
sighted reader.
</P>
<P>
   The program helps students who cannot see well, or at all, but
who want to move beyond high school math, said Jason Balusek, a
graduate student at Stephen F. Austin University in Nacogdoches,
Texas, who is testing the program.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Balusek had help from a sighted teacher who
translated math equations from Nemeth Braille into print for
teachers, and from print into Nemeth Braille for students. Now
Balusek is studying for a master's degree and must handle more
complicated math and symbols.
</P>
<P>
   When he uses MathTalk for the Visually Impaired, Balusek can
dictate his results into a computer microphone so the computer
program can convert the work into a printed copy with standard math
notation for his professors. And a copy in Nemeth Braille can be
printed out on his embossing printer.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said his program was the first to allow blind students to
print copies for their professors with all the standard math
notation, in addition to Nemeth Braille hard copies for themselves.
After printing a copy in Nemeth Braille, the student can check for
any translation errors by listening as the problems are read back
by the computer program.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he did not know of any colleges that taught Nemeth
Braille so the program also helped the students by teaching them
unfamiliar Nemeth symbols. ``This reinforces the Nemeth they know,
and helps teach them what they don't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another program from Gray, MathBraille Talk, allows sighted
teachers to dictate problems into a computer and have them
translated into Nemeth Braille code, which can be printed on an
embossing printer. But unlike MathTalk for the Visually Impaired,
MathBraille Talk does not allow a student to dictate work done in
Nemeth Braille into the computer so it can be printed in
conventional form for a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a need for this kind of software,'' said Richard Ring,
supervisor of the International Braille and Technology Center for
the Blind, a division of the National Federation of the Blind in
Baltimore. ``There aren't as many people in the sciences in general
because of the difficulty in representing math in Braille.''
</P>
<P>
   Programs developed by Gray are distributed by Metroplex Voice
Computing of Arlington, Texas; the e-mail address is
mathtalk(at)onramp.net. MathBraille Talk and MathTalk Scientific
Notebook each cost $395 per copy. MathTalk for the Visually
Impaired will be available in a few months and will cost $300 to
$500, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Balusek, the student in Texas, said he hoped that other people
with visual problems would be able to use the math software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there aren't many blind college math majors,''
Balusek said. ``I'm hoping it will encourage more people to think
about doing this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
