<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
  
 GETTING VIDEO ONTO THE iMAC  
 (Circuits)  
 (Eds: Question may be italicized)  
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is there some way of transforming old home videotapes into
the digital video format so that they could be edited using the
iMovie software on the new iMacs? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. While the new iMacs are designed for easy video transfer
between digital camcorder and computer with a FireWire cable, older
analog video formats like VHS must be converted to the digital
video format for use with iMovie, the iMac's video-editing program.
A Web search can point you to companies that handle video transfers
between formats, but there are other options if you would like to
do it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   If you already own (or can rent or borrow) a digital camcorder,
you should be able to dub your existing videocassettes directly to
the camcorder to make a digital copy. To do this, you will need a
set of standard video patch cables (usually available from
electronics stores for less than $10) to connect the video output
ports on the back of your VCR to the video input ports on the
digital camcorder. Press Record on the camcorder and Play on the
VCR to dub the video. Once you have the footage copied onto the
camcorder, connect it to the iMac's FireWire port and import the
video.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a digital camcorder, you may want to invest in
an analog-to-digital video converter, which can convert the data
and send it right into your iMac. A converter box can also transfer
digital video back to analog if you would like to give
videocassettes of your opus to others. Apple's Web site says the
Sony DVMC-DA1 Media Converter ($499) is compatible with the iMovie
software. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New ork, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1621EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
