u a BC-CIR-SEARCH-PROTOCOL-N     03-29 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SEARCH-PROTOCOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UPDATE FOR THE INNARDS OF THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By MAURA KELLY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HTTP, or Hypertext Transfer Protocol, is the reason the Web, as
we know it today, works. It is the standard for communication among
Web servers that enables Web browsers to call up pages when users
type in URLs or click on hyperlinks.
</P>
<P>
   But HTTP is getting a bit long in the tooth. It was created to
control the transfer of Web documents constructed with Hypertext
Markup Language, or HTML, the Web's current standard programming
language, so it cannot get the most out of HTML's younger, more
versatile cousin, eXtensible Markup Language, or XML.
</P>
<P>
   Now a new protocol, nicknamed Blocks, has been written with the
idea of wringing as much as possible out of XML, and it would add
another dimension to Web searches as well.
</P>
<P>
   While HTML labels the pieces of a Web page with generic tags,
XML labels pieces with tags that are customized to describe the
information itself. That allows the data to be used in many more
ways after it is downloaded. Many people in the industry believe
that XML will become the major formatting language for all
business-to-business electronic commerce, used alone or in
combination with HTML to create Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   XML labels could, for example, mark a piece of downloaded
information as a 1999 budget figure, and that would allow the
company receiving the information to plug it into the correct spot
in a spreadsheet or database right away. That kind of information
about information is called metadata. An HTML tag would say only
how to display that piece of downloaded information on the screen,
not what it was.
</P>
<P>
   XML's metadata capabilities are not fully exploited by HTTP, but
they would be with the Blocks protocol, or BXXP. That is short for
the Blocks eXtensible eXchange Protocol, which is designed to
transfer blocks of data from one computer network to another.
</P>
<P>
   The protocol, developed by Invisible Worlds, makes a different
sort of data exchange possible. Invisible Worlds is a new company
with many of the Net's royalty on its boards, including Dr. Paul
Mockapetris, who invented the Internet system for naming domains;
Tim O'Reilly, president of O'Reilly &AMP; Associates, a publisher of
books about Internet technologies; and Paul Vixie, a Metromedia
Fiber Networks senior vice president who is best known as the
creator of BIND (Berkeley Internet Name Domain).
</P>
<P>
   The Blocks protocol is meant not to replace HTTP but simply to
enhance it. It is likely to make the Web more user-friendly by
allowing a faster, smoother exchange of XML documents.
</P>
<P>
   Malamud's company presented the new protocol on Tuesday to the
Internet Engineering Task Force at an informal session at its
meeting this week in Adelaide, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   While a stamp of approval from the task force, an open
international group of Internet experts, does not carry the weight
of a governmental edict, the group is widely respected by
information technology professionals. The task force defines online
standards, approving protocols it finds to be stable, competently
designed and useful.
</P>
<P>
   So the presentation to the task force is the first step toward
getting an imprimatur of approval for Blocks as an Internet
standard, something that the majority of Web users would be able to
use.
</P>
<P>
   Invisible Worlds would make money on the venture by working with
other companies to prepare them to handle the protocol. ``We are
the folks who have to build and maintain a digital Hoover Dam, if
you will,'' Malamud said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to make sites act something like databases. For
instance, changing a single digit in one cell of an Excel
spreadsheet changes the sums or products in other cells. Similarly,
with the Blocks protocol, changing one piece of information
anywhere on the Web could have a ripple effect, changing related
information all over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it might work. Let's say you are searching for a
newspaper article about a hypothetical Internet company called
Hypocomp.com on a site that offers a searchable archive of
newspaper and magazine articles. You find the article and then
decide you want to see how Hypocomp.com is trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Under HTTP, you would have to leave the first site, connect to
the stock exchange site and search there for Hypocomp.com. But the
Blocks protocol could be set up so the current stock price of a
company would be displayed when that company's name came up in
search results. In effect, it would make possible an automatically
generated hyperlink.
</P>
<P>
   The new protocol would make that sort of interaction between
sites possible and could make searches easier.
</P>
<P>
   It relies on three software applications developed by Invisible
Worlds: mixers, which search for text and data; space servers,
which receive information from mixers, compare the pieces of
information and share them with other servers to generate
hyperlinks; and builders, which assemble information for display.
</P>
<P>
   BXXP, like HTTP, would operate behind the scenes, invisible to
the Web surfer, but its dynamic links would make the Web ``seem
more coordinated and useful,'' said Mockapetris, a member of the
Invisible Worlds protocol advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Others outside the company are also interested in the protocol.
``I think there has been enough interest in Blocks and similar
topics so that I would not be surprised if this did become a
working group,'' said Steve Coya, executive director of the
Internet Engineering Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion and study by a working group would be a first step
toward becoming a standard Internet protocol, Coya said, but no
guarantee. Nevertheless, he said, ``the objective of a working
group is to produce something for use by the Internet community.''
</P>
<P>
   Invisible Worlds is viewed as having a competitive edge because
it has so many academics and Internet pioneers on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offhand, I don't know of anything else like Blocks,'' said
Jonathan Zittrain, executive director of Harvard's Berkman Center
for Internet and Society, who said it was highly likely that Blocks
would eventually be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes Blocks different is not necessarily its technical
aspects but the way in which you have a venture-backed dot-com
integrated with the academics and researchers who comprise the
Internet engineering community _ people who gave us the
fundamentals of the Net _ on board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
