u a BC-CIR-SISSY-FIGHT-NYT &LR;      03-29 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SISSY-FIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLING LITTLE MONSTERS IN THE SCHOOLYARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're still looking for that special place to let your inner
child run free, better keep her away from the playground in Sissy
Fight 2000 _ she's very likely to get roughed up.
</P>
<P>
   Sissy Fight is the brainchild of editors at Word, an online
magazine. Since the free game's official debut in late February, it
has developed something of a cult following of players attracted to
its deceptively simple premise.
</P>
<P>
   Players simply go to www.sissyfight.com or click a link found on
the Word site (www.word.com). Sissy Fight 2000, a Web-based,
multiplayer free-for-all, is a game not for children but for adults
in the mood for a little whimsical regression, often in the form of
marauding parochial-school girls going by names like Big Patty, Sky
Witch and PMS Angel. Be warned, though: Many players assume
character names that are not suitable for printing in a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Players need a fairly speedy Internet connection (anything
slower than a 56K modem is excruciating) and a Web browser that can
handle the Shockwave plug-in from Macromedia.
</P>
<P>
   After you are whisked inside to create a little warrior princess
from a selection of hairstyles, dress colors and skin tones, you
give your girl a name and choose a password.
</P>
<P>
   The rules posted can call up unfortunate flashbacks, depending
on your childhood experience: ``Three to six girls can play in a
game. Everyone starts out with 10 Self-Esteem points. When other
girls humiliate and abuse you, you get really embarrassed and lose
your self-esteem. If your Self-Esteem goes down to zero, you
become, like, totally mortified and a loser and have to sit out for
the rest of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A built-in chat feature adds an interactive touch. Players
logged on from all over the world can gang up on other girls and
claim the teeter-totter. No one is completely safe _ girls you're
merrily chatting with may turn on you suddenly. Think of a Sissy
Fight game as a virtual community theater re-enactment of ``Lord of
the Flies'' _ with pigtails and knee socks.
</P>
<P>
   Sissy Fight 2000 probably won't appeal to those who like
fast-paced shooting action or buxom Lara Croft-type characters. As
a study in social dynamics and cultural anthropology, though, Sissy
Fight can be fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   It can also provide a cheap vicarious thrill after a bad day at
work, and the basic attacks (scratching, grabbing and teasing) and
defensive moves (cowering and tattling) make one realize that
office politics have not evolved very far from playground
squabbles.
</P>
<P>
   The game was developed in less than a year by several staff
members at Word, including Marisa Bowe, the magazine's founding
editor in chief; Eric Zimmerman, the game's designer; and Tomas
Clark, an associate editor who coordinated the production and
assisted with the Sissy Fight design. Bowe said the creative team
had wanted to make a game that would force people to interact with
one another online.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting the insular world of the role-playing-game subculture
to a broader audience was also one of the goals. ``Could you apply
other types of humor and style to it to make it attractive and
appealing to a much broader audience?'' Bowe recalled wondering. In
Sissy Fight, evil ogres and fire-snorting dragons have been
supplanted by the taunting of Big Patty and PMS Angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who would never normally take on those roles in a
literal-minded way are really happy to take on this absurd role of
a little girl and march in there and take people down,'' Bowe
observed. ``They're very enthusiastic about that because it's sort
of ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relatively simple game,'' Zimmerman said, ``but I think
what makes it so satisfying to play is that it's an understandable
strategic system that's embedded within the social system that the
game creates. That adds a whole different kind of unpredictability.
We're not simulating a military conflict here. We're simulating a
social conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no gloriously realistic 3-D character renderings in
Sissy Fight 2000. The animation is purposely somewhere between
Frogger and early Nintendo. The little girl avatars were partly
inspired by the works of the folk artist Henry Darger, Bowe said.
</P>
<P>
   The game's creators said more than 17,000 people had signed up
to play since Sissy Fight went online last month. There always seem
to be at least 75 players on the Web site's counter on any given
visit.
</P>
<P>
   The Sissy Fight creators are still refining the game and hope to
build up the virtual community aspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know in Doom and Quake, people have spontaneously formed
these clans,'' Bowe said, ``and that's what we're going to
encourage in our own game with stuff that we're going to develop.
She added that Sissy Fight clans would probably be called cliques,
for obvious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1625EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
