<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DESTINY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALOGUE FOR A DIATRIBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BELLA ENGLISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTINY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Tim Parks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arcade, 249 pp., $24.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imagine you are stuck sitting in a train next to a compulsive
talker. On and on she chatters to a companion, without so much as
coming up for air, thinking, of course, that she is the smartest of
conversationalists, the wittiest, the most profound. It's enough to
drive you mad.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Destiny,'' author Tim Parks describes such a scene, with
his protagonist as the bored bystander. ``I am impatient for
silence,'' he writes, adding that their chitchat makes it hard for
him to read. He goes on to complain about the predictability, the
banality, the pretentiousness of their conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Parks could well be talking about himself. ``Destiny,'' his 10th
novel, is an irritating, untidy book. For 250 pages, Parks delivers
a run-on soliloquy about his protagonist's life, his family, his
work, his marriage _ until the reader too becomes impatient for
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Destiny'' begins with a phone call that will change the life
of Chris Burton, one of Britain's top foreign correspondents. The
caller tells him that his schizophrenic son has committed suicide
in Italy, where the family lives. In London on an extended stay
with his wife, Burton immediately concludes that their 30-year
marriage is over. The rest of the book is an attempt to explain
why, in a stream-of-consciousness interior dialogue that rambles on
and on in Burton's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason,'' he tells himself, ``no reason at all for
you and your wife to go on living together now that your son is
dead.'' His wife, Mara, is a flirty Italian who turns her charm on
everyone except her husband and their adopted daughter. Estranged
from the daughter, she lavished attention on the biological son,
who has attacked her and sledgehammered her house.
</P>
<P>
   If the book is supposed to delve deeply into the complexities of
a mother's unconditional love for her son, it fails, for Mara
Burton is presented as a cardboard character, a flimsy construction
we don't really come to know. The same goes for the other
characters, who are filtered through Chris Burton's jaundiced eyes.
With subjects that should make the reader sympathetic _ teenage
suicide, the death of a long-term marriage _ the reader is instead
left feeling impatient.
</P>
<P>
   The Burton marriage may be endlessly fascinating to Chris
Burton, but not to the reader. Mara Burton is presented as the type
of woman who has cheated on her husband, doesn't see her daughter
or grandchildren, won't discuss their son's death with her husband;
who won't allow him in as she sits by his body in the morgue, who
makes all the funeral arrangements without consulting him, and then
goes to the service alone while he is sick in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burton is no innocent victim here. He has betrayed his
wife on a number of occasions and has allowed the marriage to
deteriorate into a cold war. At late midlife, he is hoping to
resurrect his ``obsolete ambition'' by writing the definitive book
on Italy's former prime minister, a corrupt old gasbag who finally
grants him the interview he has been waiting for. But it's too
late. During the interview, Burton realizes the man is a hopeless
narcissist, a revisionist who has fooled himself into thinking he
is a simple, heroic man.
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery is an appropriate spot for the showdown of a dying
marriage, and in a memorable scene after Marco's funeral, Burton
finally unleashes years of hostility on his wife. Again, the
glimpse is interior, so that the reader gets only his now-familiar
side. And the cemetery tirade only serves to set up an
unsatisfactory denouement.
</P>
<P>
   If Chris Burton had been more interesting, more insightful,
displayed some backbone and a sense of humor, Parks might have
pulled off 250 pages of stream-of-consciousness wandering. But what
the reader ends up with is a mishmash of male menopause, Italian
politics, and complaints about England, Italy, and a nagging kidney
problem. Burton's wife is no more interesting. By the end of the
book, a cynical reader could surmise why the son killed himself: to
escape his tedious, egocentric parents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1628EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
