<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1261 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VOICE-RECOGNITION     03-29 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VOICE-RECOGNITION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAK SOFTLY, CARRY A BIG CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By SUSAN M. FULTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've read a lot about speech recognition software but
aren't a user yet, it's time to take a deep breath and start
talking to your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't breathe on the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the many tips you'll begin to follow right after
installation. But first you need to figure out what program to get,
among the many available.
</P>
<P>
   People use speech recognition for a variety of reasons. They may
want to be more productive or to accommodate disabilities, or they
may be unable to type or to have secretaries type for them.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, using speech recognition requires an
investment of both time and money _ money not just for the software
but, most probably, for more up-to-date hardware. If a computer is
more than a couple of years old, it may well need to be replaced by
a new one before dictation software can be used successfully. Even
a newer computer may need more RAM or a better sound card. And
picking out a software program and learning how to use it well
means an investment of time.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing among available software can be daunting. Dragon
Systems, which brought continuous speech dictation to the consumer
market in the spring of 1997, has nine products for general use,
from NaturallySpeaking Essentials at $60 to Professional at $695.
IBM and Lernout &AMP; Hauspie both have a handful of products for
general use; IBM's are priced up to $180, while Lernout &AMP; Hauspie's
are up to $150. A fourth competitor in the personal computer arena
is Philips Speech Processing, with FreeSpeech 2000 at $99. L&AMP;H's
plans to acquire Dragon promise to complicate things. These
companies also offer high-end products like legal and medical
editions and add-on vocabularies, as well as packages that include
handheld recorders.
</P>
<P>
   IBM seems to be taking care of other operating systems by
including speech recognition as part of OS/2, offering a
developers' kit for Linux and selling ViaVoice for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, MacSpeech, is working with Philips on a Mac
continuous-speech product (while offering a free program, ListenDo,
just for commands). Dragon has backed off its plans for a Mac
product, saying it is awaiting the Mac OS X.
</P>
<P>
   All these programs take dictation in continuous speech. This is
not really ``natural'' speech, no matter what the companies say in
their marketing pitches. But the well-enunciated speaking style is
a far cry from the halting word-pause-word speech that earlier
programs required as they wrote down things you didn't say.
</P>
<P>
   Today's programs do write down what you say, with accuracy
levels reaching above 98 percent, with speeds as fast as you can
talk (clearly). That is not an off-the-shelf miracle, however. The
high levels are reached after you have trained the program on how
you speak and the program has, along the way, trained you on how
you ought to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The training is essential. You can't just go up to a computer,
start talking to it and expect to have your words accurately
transcribed into text. But the first session of training is shorter
than ever, 5 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After the initial training, you will improve the program's
accuracy as you dictate, by correcting its mistakes in
transcription. Another way these programs improve in accuracy is by
analyzing existing documents for new words and for your syntax.
These three steps _ initial training, making corrections and
vocabulary analysis _ are common for NaturallySpeaking, IBM's
ViaVoice and L&AMP;H's Voice Xpress. Both Voice Xpress and FreeSpeech
sometimes balk at adding new words or phrases to the software
vocabulary when those words or phrases are introduced during the
correction process.
</P>
<P>
   Features vary within and between the product lines. The products
to buy for more than a dalliance with speech recognition have a
street price of $100 to $150 or so: IBM's ViaVoice Millennium
Professional or Dragon NaturallySpeaking Preferred version 4, or
L&AMP;H's Voice Xpress Professional version 4. Although FreeSpeech 2000
is a contender _ something that could not be said of its
predecessor, FreeSpeech 98 _ its sales are small compared with
those of the other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Which program is the most accurate? There is no way to answer
that question given the huge mix of variables involved in speech
recognition on the Windows platform, not least of which is the
human being with the microphone. As the initial ViaVoice training
script points out, ``No one ever says a word in exactly the same
way twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound cards and microphones vary; computers vary in speed,
memory and noise. Environmental factors come into play. ``All
things being equal'' is a state that cannot really be reached
outside the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   That said, experienced users participating in Internet speech
recognition forums have found that ViaVoice Millennium and
NaturallySpeaking version 4 are both capable of accuracy rates
exceeding 98 percent. Voice Xpress trails a bit, but even saying
this seems somehow unfair _ and points up another difficulty in
making comparisons. The current version of Voice Xpress was
released last May, months before the others, and for all the
programs, accuracy has been improving with every release.
</P>
<P>
   New features are introduced with every release, too, often going
one-up on something another product already has. Just wait long
enough and the program you know best will adopt something you have
eyed with envy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, when NaturallySpeaking was released, Dragon Systems
highlighted its ``select and say'' feature, letting the user select
a word or phrase by saying it. It was later adopted by IBM and L&AMP;H,
although in fact, IBM had a rudimentary selection feature like this
in its earlier Simply Speaking Gold program.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon has polished this feature so well for its users that you
can select a block of text in a single voice command. For example,
you can select the two preceding sentences in this article by
saying ``select it was through command period.''
</P>
<P>
   Commands that help you edit as you go are one reason
NaturallySpeaking is popular. Say ``cap that'' to capitalize the
word you just spoke, for example, or ``correct that'' to teach the
speech engine a thing or two. Say ``insert after  &UR; are one reason''
 &LR; then say ``that'' to edit the first sentence of this paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   The program does have its limitations. Its dictation boilerplate
is limited to one line; thus, a four-line address that would be
``typed'' by simply saying, for example, ``full address macro'' is
not possible as a shortcut. Other than that, NaturallySpeaking is
an excellent choice for writers.
</P>
<P>
   Although offering a full range of editing commands,
NaturallySpeaking has less comprehensive computing commands than
its competitors. Yet you can't make your own commands unless you
buy the $695 can-do-just-about-anything Professional edition, sold
through resellers. IBM's ViaVoice, L&AMP;H's Voice Xpress and
FreeSpeech 2000 all allow you to make your own commands (though
they are not as robust as NaturallySpeaking Pro's macros).
</P>
<P>
   FreeSpeech 2000 offers many editing and computing commands. A
difference from other programs is that FreeSpeech has a distinct
dictation mode.
</P>
<P>
   L&AMP;H's Voice Xpress Pro has the tightest integration with
Microsoft Office, hardly a surprise given Microsoft's 7 percent
stake in L&AMP;H. And it carries the natural language concept the
farthest.
</P>
<P>
   With natural language commands, you carry out an action by
saying a command naturally, and not necessarily the way you said it
the last time. ``Open a new document'' works as well as ``create a
new file'' or ``create a document.'' The natural language concept
has not been applied throughout the computer interface, so you use
these commands in some applications but you use the stiff and
choppy command style in others: ``File menu.'' ``New.''
</P>
<P>
   In one respect, Voice Xpress goes NaturallySpeaking one better
on the ``select by saying'' feature. You can do this in any
application, while NaturallySpeaking has this trademark capability
in only a handful of applications. Philips' FreeSpeech also has
widespread ``select by saying.'' IBM's ViaVoice has this only in
its own text editor and in Microsoft Word.
</P>
<P>
   Another Voice Xpress favorite is that you can quickly tell the
speech engine to ``hear'' just commands, or just dictation, or just
letters and numbers. FreeSpeech is somewhat similar in this regard.
NaturallySpeaking can be limited to understanding continuous
spelling (and numbers) only in its correction window. The IBM
program has a spelling mode but is slow to switch to it.
</P>
<P>
   Both the L&AMP;H and IBM products provide for out-of-the-box number
entry and commands for Microsoft Excel spreadsheets. In other
words, you do not need to make a command or switch modes. Just say
the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's ViaVoice does not provide the range of word-processing
commands that L&AMP;H's Voice Xpress and Dragon NaturallySpeaking do in
their basic text editors, but it offers broad voice control of the
computer (except on Windows NT because of limitations in that
operating system). For example, you can close an application
without first switching to it. You can move a window with a simple
command. You can open Web site favorites as you would a program; no
need to open the browser first. The What Can I Say? window is
unique among the speech recognition programs in being able to show
what is available to say in whatever program is active.
</P>
<P>
   With ViaVoice you can make multiline dictation boilerplate on
the fly. Select that four-line address, say ``create macro,'' and
supply a name. More elaborate boilerplate is also possible.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature points toward the future. Say ``send an e-mail
to Charles Jones about Allied proposal.'' The e-mail program is not
even open, but ViaVoice will open a blank e-mail message, put
``Charles Jones'' in the recipient field, put ``Allied proposal''
in the subject field and position the cursor in the message field
ready for your dictation. All you have to do beforehand is specify
the e-mail program (among five, including Netscape Messenger and
Microsoft Outlook) and have it inhale the contents of your address
book.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse and the keyboard cannot do this. With natural language
commands and features of this sort, speech recognition is no longer
emulating those devices _ it is coming into its own as a way to
command the computer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
