<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-OIL (Washington)_ President Clinton, hailing OPEC's oil
production boost, says skyrocketing oil prices over the past year
ought to be a ``wake up call'' for America to resume the quest for
greater energy independence by forging ahead with fuel-efficient
vehicles, homes and offices. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-WILLEY (Washington) _ A federal judge says President
Clinton and aides violated Kathleen Willey's privacy by releasing
letters that she wrote after Clinton allegedly groped her in 1993.
Clinton says he will appeal ruling. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-STRIPPING (Washington) _ The Supreme Court restricts the
protection previously given to nude dancing under the 1st
Amendment's right to freedom of expression. In a 6-3 vote, the
justices uphold an Erie, Pa., ordinance that requires women barroom
dancers to wear at least pasties and a G-string when performing. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PRAYER (Washington) _ The Supreme Court is divided as it
tackles the controversial question of whether school districts may
let students lead stadium crowds in prayer before high school
football games. Nearly four decades after the court banned
officially sponsored prayers from public schools, the justices
struggle to balance the Constitution's
separation-of-church-and-state requirement with students'
free-speech rights. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-FLAG (Washington) _ The Senate moves toward a possible
vote on an amendment to the Constitution that would ban desecration
of the flag. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ The Clinton administration and key
Republican and Democratic lawmakers urge Congress to broaden
Medicare to include more prescription drugs. But in testimony
before the Senate Finance Committee, witnesses differ on how such
an expansion should be funded and who should be covered. By AUSTIN
ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-OPEC (Vienna, Austria) _ The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries bows to U.S. pressure for cheaper fuel as the
oil ministers agree to higher production limits, sending petroleum
prices into an immediate tailspin. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-DOWNTOWN (Fort Worth, Texas) _ The central business
district of Fort Worth is closed in the aftermath of Tuesday's
destructive tornado, and downtown entrepreneurs are waiting to
learn when Cowtown can get back in business. Four people were
killed and dozens injured in the twister. By EVAN MOORE.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-MARS (Undated) _ NASA Administrator Daniel Goldin takes the
blame for pushing the agency too far and for failures in its Mars
missions. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-ATHEIST (Austin, Texas) _ Gary Paul Karr, the only
person charged with the alleged kidnapping and murder of atheist
Madalyn Murray O'Hair, is assigned a lawyer in his first appearance
in a Texas court. Karr was indicted late last year on five charges,
including kidnapping, robbery and extortion in connection with the
1995 disappearance of O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray, and
daughter Robin Murray O'Hair. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
