<HEADER>
A1265 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-MARRIAGE-A     03-29 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-MARRIAGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING HOOKED ON AN ONLINE GAME, AND HITCHED TO A FELLOW GAMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Wash.)  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By KAREN J. BANNAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time Debra Sartore saw her husband-to-be, Dean
Morrell, he was wearing a kilt and a cape. ``Dean had blond hair, a
beard and a ponytail,'' she said. ``And, as always, had a bare
chest. He looked like a gigolo type even though he was always very
polite when he spoke to the ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple, whose first meeting took place at a mutual friend's
party, exchanged only pleasantries that day. Their chance meeting
was brief since Sartore was there with another man. In the next
year, the relationship progressed from friendship to love and
culminated in marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Debra and Dean Morrell's story sounds like a million other love
stories, with one big difference. The party, the mutual friend and
even Morrell's ponytail do not exist. All are part of a virtual
world called Ultima Online, a popular game played over the
Internet. But the friendship and love, as well as the marriage
earlier this month in Minnesota, were real.
</P>
<P>
   Morrell, a 36-year-old department manager at a store in
Evansville, Ind., was no stranger to romance that blossoms over the
Internet. In fact, when she first met Morrell through Ultima, she
was living with another man whom she had met online.
</P>
<P>
   But for Dean Morrell, a 39-year-old Navy veteran living in
Seabeck, Wash., near Seattle, who specialized in electronics,
online courting was a new experience. Although he had played online
games for more than a decade, Morrell had never considered dating
someone he had met online. His opinion changed as he played Ultima,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultima Online is a role-playing game set in medieval times.
Players _ there are more than 160,000 of them around the world _
pay a one-time fee of $20 for the game itself and then $10 a month
to play. Players take on the role of a character (or more than one)
who has a skill or profession and slay monsters, earn virtual money
from their trade and, in some cases, participate in online
marriages and adoptions.
</P>
<P>
   Games like Ultima Online are high-drama worlds where people
become immersed in the details of the game and in interacting with
other players, said Billy Pidgeon, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications, a technology research firm in New York.
Participants in multiplayer online games average more than 22 hours
a week of playing time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many romances have occurred between online game
players, but the Morrells' experience is not unique. Another couple
who met playing Ultima Online were recently engaged: Kristine
Baron, a 28-year-old Chicago resident, is in Denmark spending time
with Jan Christensen, whom she met 17 months ago. A reciprocal trip
is planned for June.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than some other online games, Ultima has qualities
that make it ripe for offline romance, Pidgeon said. ``Ultima is a
very social and ethical world, so people tend to believe that who
they are online is similar to who they are offline,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Davis, a psychologist and professor at Haverford College
who is researching the psychology of online gaming, said the
connection goes deeper. ``Ultima has this tremendous involvement
that gives players the feeling that they get an immediate glimpse
into who people are,'' he said. ``People quickly feel that they are
learning something important about each other as they play the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   That, indeed, was the Morrells' experience. ``You can put on a
face, but your true self always shines through online,'' said
Morrell, who was known as Flint in the game. He said he was
attracted to Sartore's intelligence and altruism. Sartore, known as
Tess to other players, said she fell in love with Morrell's
generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always so helpful to other characters,'' she said. ``He
gives money or armor to poor characters. He is always willing to
stop and help anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The first impressions stuck with them, said the Morrells, and
then on Sept. 3, 1999, their relationship began to change from
virtual to real.
</P>
<P>
   That morning, Sartore heard from an online friend that Morrell
was retiring from the Navy that month and was planning on leaving
the game. ``I hated to hear he was leaving,'' she said. ``Our
friend, Dennar, said, `Let's marry him off before he leaves the
game.' I thought it was a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Sartore went online and sent a message to Morrell, telling him
she had something to ask him. ``I blurted out, `Will you marry me?'
and that's when it began,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrell said he thought Sartore was asking him to marry her, not
for their two characters to wed. ``I was so shocked and amazed,''
he said. ``I had always had feelings for Deb and her proposal hit
home. It was just what I wanted to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   The two spent nine hours talking online that night until the
game's server went down for maintenance. Over the next five days,
they spent countless hours online, talking and sharing aspects of
their lives that had previously remained outside the game. During
that time, Sartore's character moved into Morrell's online house.
``After I moved in, I started sharing all of his belongings,'' she
said. ``It felt like something we should do.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was also a pivotal element of their first face-to-face
meeting. Sartore planned to attend an Ultima Online players'
luncheon on Sept. 18 in Seattle, so she flew there nine days early
to get to know Morrell. Their meeting prompted them to continue
their relationship outside the virtual world, Morrell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was getting serious from our online discussions,''
Morrell said, ``so our first meeting was so important. No matter
what, when you're dealing with a virtual person, you're building up
a fantasy in your mind. As soon as I saw Deb, I knew the fantasy
matched the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Sartore flew home after the user's meeting, and the two
continued their correspondence, even agreeing to a marriage of
their characters online in a ceremony attended by a large group of
their online friends. Shortly after the October virtual wedding,
Morrell went online again and asked Sartore to marry him in real
life.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Morrell's brother flew Sartore and her 10-year-old
daughter to Cottage Grove, Minn., where Morrell had moved, as a
surprise for the holidays. During that week, they began planning
their wedding and searching for a house. The wedding, small and
private, took place in their new house on March 13.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Williams, a senior vice president at Gerard Klauer
Mattison &AMP; Co., a financial analysis and consumer research business
based in New York, said that although the Morrells' experience is
somewhat unusual, relationships initiated online will become
increasingly commonplace. ``The social nature of the games will
make friendships and relationships more prevalent,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   But in some ways, Davis of Haverford said, the Morrells'
experience is not a new phenomenon. It mirrors thousands of other
relationships started in the virtual world of written
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times did someone fighting in World War I write home
to the girlfriend of a buddy that died and fall in love?'' Davis
said. ``There's something about a virtual meeting that's very
seductive.''
</P>
<P>
   Two more of the Morrells' online characters, Levi Strauss and
Sable, will marry online in April. Since many of Morrell's friends
or relatives didn't attend the two previous weddings, virtual and
real, many will be online for that ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
