<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK DIGGING A HOLE IS SIMPLE? THINK AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Digging a hole can be hard work, but the job can be made easier
if you have the right tools. Before breaking ground, call your
local utility companies and outline your plans. Have them come to
the site and locate and mark any underground water, gas, electrical
and drainage lines, and telephone and television cables. Cutting
into one of these can disrupt service and possibly injure or kill
you. These line markings are only approximate, so to be on the safe
side, avoid digging within two feet of them.
</P>
<P>
   If you need to dig an ordinary hole for, say, planting a large
shrub, the best tool to use is a pointed spade shovel. Make sure
the blade is free of dried dirt and clay lumps. To make it easier
for the shovel to bite into the soil, sharpen the blade edge with a
metal file.
</P>
<P>
   Digging holes for fence posts or footings requires a different
tool because the holes should be deep and cylindrical with sides
that are flared at the bottom. A clamshell digger (also called a
post hole digger) is a good tool for this type of work.
</P>
<P>
   The clamshell digger is essentially two shovels hinged together
at the top of the blades. It works like a combination shovel and
tongs. To use the tool, push the handles together, then plunge the
blades into the dirt. Spreading the handles will close the blades
so they grab a clump of dirt. Lift the digger out of the hole,
keeping the handles spread apart, then dump the load by bringing
the handles together.
</P>
<P>
   Clamshell diggers are difficult to use in deep holes because the
narrow width of the hole makes it awkward to spread the handles
apart. For deep holes, you may have to use a breaker bar to loosen
the soil and a small trenching shovel to scoop it out, or you can
switch to another digging tool.
</P>
<P>
   You can use a hand auger to excavate holes. Hand augers dig as
you push them into the soil while twisting the handle. The parallel
jaws loosen the soil and churn it up to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   These manual diggers are fine for digging one or two holes but
if you have to dig a log of holes, you might want to consider
renting a power auger to do the job. The power auger is essentially
a giant corkscrew that twists dirt to the surface as it bores into
the ground. This sounds easy, but these machines are heavy and can
generate a lot of torque. You must maintain a strong grip on the
handles or the auger can twist out of control. In addition, power
augers are heavy, so moving them into position can be hard on the
back.
</P>
<P>
   Power augers are available in different diameters, from 6 to 12
inches, and lengths, and in one- or two-person models. They are
powered by gasoline engines.
</P>
<P>
   As the auger digs deeper into the ground, you must lift it
periodically so it can spin out the loosened dirt. This can be
tiring because the gasoline engine is heavy. If you are working
alone, you might consider renting a flexible shaft auger. This
model has a remote engine that sits apart on the ground. A flexible
shaft transmits the power from the engine to the auger.
</P>
<P>
   Two-person augers are easier to operate because there are four
hands gripping the handles and two people to lift and maneuver the
tool. Still, it is essential that both operators maintain a firm,
even hold on the handles at all times. This will ensure that the
final hole is straight and allow adequate control in case the auger
hits a hidden rock.
</P>
<P>
   If the thought of holding on to a twisting power auger sounds a
little dangerous, one type of power auger is much easier to
control, although it takes time to set up. It is called a mobile
digger and can be operated by one person. The mobile digger is
mounted on a small trailer that must be towed to the job site. Then
it must be secured in place with heavy chains and ground spikes.
The auger is enclosed in a vertical housing. The operator raises
and lowers the auger bit into the ground by turning a steering
wheel. He has total control of the tool at all times.
</P>
<P>
   As with all power tools, it is essential that you understand how
power augers operate. Make sure the dealer at the rental store
explains all the features of the unit before you take it home. Do
not start the hole with the engine at full throttle. Instead, start
slowly and increase the speed as the auger digs deeper. When you
hit a large rock, stop digging and remove it with a breaker bar.
When operating augers, always wear proper safety gear, including
ear protectors, goggles, heavy-duty gloves and work boots.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
