<HEADLINE>
COLA JINGLE REALLY DID HIT THE SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I remember an RC Cola or Pepsi jingle that said the drink
sold for a nickel and ``hits the spot.'' Which drink was it? _
R.H., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a Pepsi jingle and was voted the third-best commercial
slogan of the century by ``Advertising Age.''
</P>
<P>
   The full jingle: ``Pepsi-Cola hits the spot,/ 12 full ounces,
that's a lot,/ Twice as much for a nickel too/ Pepsi-Cola is the
drink for you!/ Nickel, nickel, nickel, nickel/ Trickle, trickle,
trickle, trickle.''
</P>
<P>
   The jingle was created in the late '30s and eventually recorded
in 55 languages. ``More than 1 million copies were released to
jukeboxes,'' according to an official company history.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer Video Yesteryear sells a $19.95 videotape called
``Pepsi-Cola Hits the Spot'' containing 100 Pepsi TV commercials
from 1946 to 1984. For ordering information, call (800) 243-0987 or
visit the Web site www.mediabay.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I reach Peter Masterson? _ M.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to the director and actor in care of Endeavor Agency,
9701 Wilshire Blvd., 10th Floor, Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   Masterson directed the films ``Trip to Bountiful,'' ``Blood
Red'' and ``Arctic Blue.'' His most recent project is the 1998 film
``The Only Thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   A Houston native, Masterson is the father of the actress Mary
Stuart Masterson, who appeared in his 1996 TV movie ``Lily Dale.''
He's also a cousin of Horton Foote, the screenwriter of
``Bountiful'' and ``Lily.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to Susan Smith, who killed her two little
boys, and her ex-husband David? _ L.L., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Susan Smith is serving a life sentence for murder at the
Women's Correctional Institution in Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1994, after breaking up with a man who said he
didn't want a family, Smith drove her car into a lake outside
Union, S.C. Her sons Michael, 3, and Alex, 14 months, were strapped
into their child safety seats and drowned.
</P>
<P>
   David Smith wrote a 1995 book, ``Beyond All Reason _ My Life
With Susan Smith,'' and has battled depression and thoughts of
suicide, according to a Tampa TV interview broadcast in February.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
