<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLTOWN-EATS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MMMMMMMM, GOOD; OUT-OF-THE-WAY DINING DELIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greenwood is a mighty small Texas town.
</P>
<P>
   It's so small, it barely has two players for a domino game.
</P>
<P>
   It has the Greenwood Grocery, though, and a narrow country road
leading to thick cheeseburgers and home-baked meringue and fruit
pies that are stirring talk across four counties.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood, population 76, is in the ultimate North Texas middle
of nowhere. It's between Slidell and Rosston, near the Denton
County-Wise County line. Take Interstate 35 north to Sanger and
turn west, or take U.S. 287 north to Decatur and turn east. Look
for Texas 51 and then for Farm Road 1204.
</P>
<P>
   Cook-owner Virginia Mann and her husband, Carlton, both
Bridgeport school employees, took over the 60-year-old Greenwood
Grocery Jan. 1. They quickly beefed up breakfasts and lunches, and
word of the fresh-ground cheeseburgers spread quickly across area
farms and horse pastures.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking runs in the family, Virginia Mann said proudly: ``I'm a
Pinkerton'' _ a Decatur grocery family known for homemade Pinkerton
Peanut Patties.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody at the Denton County Courthouse told me about great
pies in Greenwood. On the Saturday when I finally found the town,
the Greenwood Grocery pies included chocolate meringue, coconut
meringue and buttermilk. Another recent Saturday offering included
pineapple cream.
</P>
<P>
   Weekday lunch specials include soft tacos and sandwiches.
Cheeseburgers and pie are great any day. The Greenwood Grocery is
open from 7:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. weekdays, until 6 p.m. Saturdays.
It's at 102 Main St. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hey, even the ``Zagat'' voters know good barbecue and fried
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1639EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SELENAFOREVER-MUSICAL     03-29 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELENAFOREVER-MUSICAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSICAL TRIBUTE TO SELENA PROMISING BUT UNPOLISHED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past year in the Metroplex, musical biographies have
immortalized Al Jolson, Elvis Presley, Hank Williams, Buddy Holly
and Dinah Washington. The problem is that these musical bios
typically take a `` ... and-then-this-happened'' approach, loosely
stringing together the artist's greatest hits with bits of dialogue
in a straightforward chronology. The result is usually less than
the sum of its subject.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Selena's turn _ and the creators of her stage
biography, opening this week in Dallas, are taking a slightly
different approach, combining elements of a revue with those of
traditional musical theater. As an ambitious hybrid, ``Selena
Forever'' earnestly tries to bring as much personality to the stage
as did the late Tejano superstar. The good news is that, given the
material seen at the world premiere in San Antonio last week and
the quality of the performances, it could achieve that _ and more.
The bad news is that it's not there yet. It could use a little more
workshopping and a lot more rehearsal, from the staging and
technical ends, before it makes its hoped-for run at Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Composer Fernando Rivas and playwright Edward Gallardo have
written 20 songs that tell the events of Selena's life and are
linked with several of her hits. Few, however, live up to Selena's
magic onstage. The mother, Marcela, has the best songs with
``Living on a Bus'' and ``To Him She's a Woman,'' beautifully sung
by Margo Reymundo. In fact, the most memorable numbers are
performed by everyone other than Selena: the brother, A.B. (Maxx)
sings ``You're Gonna Die Today, Brother'' and the sister, Suzette
(Liza Ybarra) does a lovely job with ``Amame, Quireme.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that the voices of these performers are
stronger than that of Veronica Vazquez in the title role. Reymundo,
Maxx and David Casanova, who plays Selena's husband, Chris Perez,
all have powerful, textured voices. Vazquez's voice is pretty and
precise, but she simply doesn't match the magnitude of the others.
</P>
<P>
   Acting-wise, the performances are fine. Daniel Valdez, who plays
Selena's father, Abraham, is a better actor than singer and does a
nice job of conveying compassion and love for his family. However,
he also plays the part more sternly and crankily than did Edward
James Olmos in the movie about Selena's life. Maxx gets several
chances to overact and comes away being the comic relief, and
Reymundo's performance shows her pathos well. Eleven-year-old
Denise Gonzalez plays the young Selena and is perfectly charming.
</P>
<P>
   There's much that's promising, but there's also much work to do
to get the show where it enthralls the entire time. As it is, those
moments are few and far between, and technical problems experienced
opening night, mostly with sound, didn't help. As it is now,
``Selena Forever'' often feels like it lasts that long.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
