<HEADLINE>
LITTLE FOLKS LIKE THESE BIG IDEAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: There used to be a store in Las Vegas that sold big items:
big color crayons, pencils, et cetera. Where can I find these
things today? _ D.R., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The kids' novelty company Ralphco has been selling giant
crayon banks since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   A 36-inch-tall bank sells for $6.99 and a 54-inch-tall bank for
$10.99. Available colors are pink, blue, red, teal and purple.
</P>
<P>
   Ralphco, which is based in Worcester, Mass., also sells crayon
lamps, giant baby bottle banks, giant Pepsi bottle and can banks
and a Pepsi Slam Dunk Clock.
</P>
<P>
   For ordering information, call (800) 477-2574 or visit the Web
site www.ralphco.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What game show did Charles Nelson Reilly and Brett Somers
play on? _ J.B., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: They were two of the celebrity panelists who appeared most
often on ``Match Game 73'' through ``Match Game 80'' along with
Richard Dawson, Betty White, Joyce Bulifant, Patti Deutsch and Gary
Burghoff.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, who turned 70 in January, was nominated for guest actor
Emmys for roles on ``Millennium'' in 1998 and ``Drew Carey Show''
last year. He's also the voice of Killer on the animated film ``All
Dogs Go to Heaven'' and its TV sequels.
</P>
<P>
   Somers, 72, played Oscar's wife on ``Odd Couple'' and was
married to actor Jack Klugman.
</P>
<P>
   The '70s version of ``Match Game'' airs on the Game Show
Network.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is another name for the jack of clubs? _ C., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: That playing card is also called Lancelot after King Arthur's
knight, according to playing card collector Bob Lancaster. The
other clubs are Alexander the Great (king) and Argine (queen) _ an
anagram of ``regina,'' a synonym for queen.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of the suits:
</P>
<P>
   Hearts: Charlemagne (king), Queen Judith of Bavaria or the
biblical figure Judith (queen) and the French warrior La Hire
(jack).
</P>
<P>
   Diamonds: Julius Caesar (king), the biblical figure Rachel
(queen) and either Roland or Hector of Troy (jack).
</P>
<P>
   Spades: King David (king), Pallas or Minerva (queen) and Hogier
the Dane (jack).
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster publishes a Gallery of Unusual Playing Cards on the
Web at members.aol.com/rslancastr.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
