<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1276 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MARK-O'CONNOR-VIOLINI     03-29 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARK-O'CONNOR-VIOLINIST-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDDLING WHILE THE OLD BARRIERS BURN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash.)   (Eds: Tony Scherman's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about Andy Warhol and pop music.)  
 (af) 
By TONY SCHERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the cellist Yo-Yo Ma, the bassist Edgar Meyer
and the violinist Mark O'Connor take the stage on Wednesday at
Avery Fisher Hall to play selections from their best-selling album,
``Appalachia Waltz,'' and its new sequel, ``Appalachian Journey,''
most eyes will be on Ma.
</P>
<P>
   The trio's celebrity, its meal ticket, he is a classical-music
superstar, perhaps the greatest string player of our time. But he's
not as remarkable a musician as his ensemble-mate on violin.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Connor's unfinished trajectory, from largely self-taught
fiddle player to concert-hall virtuoso and classical composer, is
already one of the most spectacular, if underpublicized, journeys
in recent American music. A onetime prodigy, O'Connor, 38, spent
his teens and 20s moving through successive musical environments,
managing always to convey _ not through arrogance but through a
surfeit of talent _ that he was only passing through.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago he finally encountered a challenge big enough to
last him for the rest of his career: forging what he calls ``a new
American style,'' a musical vocabulary that makes full use of the
classical tradition without sacrificing the folk and jazz that
nourished him in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   Ma, who has known O'Connor since 1988, considers his friend's
technical command equal to that of any of today's classically
trained virtuosos. ``Mark is a supreme master at what he does,'' Ma
says. ``Between thought and execution there are no impediments,
zero. But what really interests me is that this is a person in
constant development, hungry to develop. The intriguing question
is, `Where is Mark O'Connor going?'''
</P>
<P>
   Here is where he has been.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor grew up in a rundown section of Seattle. His father was
an alcoholic, his mother a semi-invalid whose few indulgences
included a big collection of classical, jazz and folk LPs. Music
was the boy's escape. Picking up the violin at 12, he became the
terror of the fiddle-contest circuit, a natural who absorbed music
with astonishing ease, who remembers he could improve just by
thinking about playing.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 17, he won the country's most prestigious fiddling
contest in Weiser, Idaho; a few months later, he joined the jazz
mandolinist David Grisman's top-flight quintet _ as a guitarist. At
19, he was playing electric violin with the virtuoso jazz-rockers
the Dregs. He moved to Nashville at 23, and before he was 30 he was
the most celebrated musician in a city crawling with them, the
Country Music Association's Musician of the Year from 1990 through
1995.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1995 he had already molted again. Jaded by the endless
round of country-music record dates, he had begun investigating
classical composition at the beginning of the '90s. In 1993 he
presented his Fiddle Concerto (as he pointedly titled it, to assert
the compatibility of folk and classical music) with the Santa Fe
Symphony; he has since played the piece 150 times. His second
concerto, ``Fanfare for the Volunteer,'' had its premiere in 1996,
the same year as the release of ``Appalachia Waltz,'' a pleasant if
unchallenging collaboration whose sales of 190,000 copies made it a
classical smash hit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 came O'Connor's unaccompanied solo album, ``Midnight on
the Water'' (to which this writer contributed liner notes), its
core the fiendishly difficult ``Six Caprices,'' homages to Paganini
that are both pyrotechnic and emotionally resonant. ``The American
Seasons,'' a concerto for violin and chamber orchestra, was first
performed last month at the Troy Savings Bank Music Hall in Troy,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 12 the violinist Nadja Salerno-Sonnenberg and the
Chicago Symphony will help O'Connor introduce his Double Concerto
for Two Violins at the Ravinia Festival. The two violinists will
tour the piece with the Nashville Symphony, stopping at Carnegie
Hall on Sept. 25. On Sept. 8 in Stuttgart, Germany, O'Connor will
be the featured soloist in a new ``St. Matthew's Passion'' by the
composer Tan Dun, part of the commemoration of the 250th
anniversary of Bach's death.
</P>
<P>
   To offer an impromptu definition: fiddling simply means an
aural, i.e., folk-based, approach to the violin. There are
countless fiddling styles, from eastern European to eastern
Canadian. So-called Texas fiddling, which the young Mark O'Connor
learned at the feet of his only teacher, a sweet-tempered auto
mechanic and unsung musical hero named Benny Thomasson, is a
sophisticated, blues-tinged style with ample room for virtuosity.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the hallmarks of O'Connor's playing _ two-part
polyphony, a whiplike bowing arm, frequent use of open strings and
an emphasis on wringing inspired variations from a melodic phrase _
are a result of his apprenticeship in the Texas style.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas fiddling never claimed him wholly, O'Connor insists;
he called it merely a staging area, a foundation. At the same time
he was perfecting his version of the style, he was playing lead
guitar in his own Seattle fusion band; absorbing Menuhin, Gershwin
and Beethoven from his mother's records; traveling to Nashville to
appear on the Grand Ole Opry; and touring with the great jazz
violinist Stephane Grappelli.
</P>
<P>
   By the time O'Connor was 18, his playing owed as much to jazz,
blues, country and rock as to Texas fiddling. When he began his
immersion in classical music 10 years later, he broadened his
vocabulary still further (refining his vibrato, for instance).
Today, his playing is beyond category; he is ``an artist who has
crossed over so many boundaries,'' as John Henken recently wrote in
The Los Angeles Times, ``that his style is purely personal.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE)
</P>
<P>
   O'connor could have built a career as an itinerant solo fiddler,
plying his trade across America. That's what he did, in fact, when
he first quit session playing, and he still performs several dozen
solo shows a year. But having composed for solo violin and string
quartet, he was eager to tackle larger forms. There was also an
iconoclast's desire to prove lowly fiddling's adaptability to the
most hallowed of Western ensembles, the classical orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiddle music contains some of the most complex, sophisticated
things I've ever had to play,'' he says. ``Yet I've listened my
whole life to classical-music people scoff at the very idea of a
fiddler meeting a classical orchestra on an equal footing.'' So he
set out to disprove the scoffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fiddle Concerto'' is the orchestral work as autobiography,
its three movements reflecting O'Connor's own journey. As the piece
unfolds, solo fiddle and classical orchestra do an elaborate mating
dance: they're introduced, clash, nurse their wounds and finally,
via a jig _ a form shared by classical music and fiddling _ are
reconciled. O'Connor has solved his problem, uniting the two
supposedly hostile traditions (if a bit schematically _ jigs aren't
exactly vital currency in today's classical music).
</P>
<P>
   The second concerto, ``Fanfare for the Volunteer'' (commissioned
for Tennessee's bicentennial celebration), picks up where the first
left off: if the first sealed the union of classical music and
fiddling, the second celebrates it. The fiddler has absorbed a
degree of classical technique, the orchestra a measure of
O'Connor's richly melodic, folk-rooted sound.
</P>
<P>
   As a piece of writing, the second concerto is a big step beyond
the first. The earlier piece is a bit stiff, an apprenticeship in
orchestral composing, but the second cascades luxuriously, an
evocation of America's land, history and myth that invites
comparison to Copland.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's next two orchestral pieces leave folk music behind
for a new challenge. ``I don't feel that anyone has effectively put
jazz'' _ the second musical language of his youth _ ``into an
orchestral work,'' he says. ``Gershwin and Bernstein tried, but
they don't convince me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Double Concerto for Two Violins'' hasn't been performed yet,
but ``The American Seasons'' was introduced memorably, on a chilly
night four weeks ago in Troy, by O'Connor and the Metamorphosen
Chamber Orchestra. A four-movement reflection on the stages of life
(hence the ``seasons'' of the title), it is a very different piece
from the first two concertos, with their largely consonant
harmonies. ``Seasons'' is bracingly dissonant. Angular and
bristling, it scuttles along, off center.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its dissonance and density (at one point in the
final movement, violins, violas, cellos and O'Connor each play an
entirely different theme _ a very heady stew), ``Seasons'' is
wholly listenable, buoyed by its jazzy rhythms and by O'Connor's
unstoppable melodic gift.
</P>
<P>
   At the premiere, O'Connor came out to play a solo encore: a
medley of the two Texas fiddle tunes ``Midnight on the Water'' and
``Bonaparte's Retreat.'' ``Midnight on the Water'' is a beautiful
rubato song with a plaintive, insistent drone and a sad melody.
O'Connor accelerated into ``Bonaparte's Retreat,'' and kept
accelerating, until he was playing almost impossibly fast, so fast
that the simple, repeated melody became an abstract whir, a blur of
machine noise like a 747 taking off, and finally O'Connor thrust
his bow up and away from the strings, finished.
</P>
<P>
   The audience was on its feet. I'm certain that at least some of
the concertgoers were moved not merely by O'Connor's solo, as
exciting as it was, but by its having come on the heels of the
orchestral piece.
</P>
<P>
   They were moved by O'Connor's journey without maps, cheering for
the only musician today who can reach so deeply first into the
refined, then the vernacular, giving his listeners a complex,
sophisticated piece of early-21st-century classical music and then
knocking them dead with the brown-dirt whine of a Texas fiddle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
