<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-EDITORIAL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite shortcomings, Putin provides hope for nursing Russia to
health
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Thursday's Atlanta
Constitution.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Very much in character for a former KGB spy, Vladimir
Putin managed to win the 11-man contest for Russia's presidency
without revealing a lot about his personality or program. That is
troubling.
</P>
<P>
   So too was the low road the state-run TV networks took in
promoting Putin's candidacy, mostly blacking out coverage of his
rivals and sinking to anti-Semitic slurs against one of them. The
election may have been reasonably fair; the campaign wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   These stains on Putin's election victory pale, however, beside
the issue that won him the favor of many Russians: the ruthless
military offensive he ordered in Chechnya. Never mind that many
civilians have been killed and a quarter-million of them uprooted
from their homes. From a typical Russian's viewpoint, it was
payback for terrorist bombs planted in Russian cities and a
breakaway uprising that a diminished Russia cannot countenance.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, for all his shortcomings, Putin is a fact of life.
The United States must deal with him and the fumbling and fractious
nuclear-armed nation he leads.
</P>
<P>
   Say this for him. He is sober, focused and fit, the antithesis
of Boris Yeltsin. To his credit, Putin seems serious about
establishing the rule of law, pushing for economic reform and
fighting graft.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter case, his KGB experience and the cronies he brings
with him into his administration strike most Russians as the right
antidote for Russia's rampaging corruption, which costs the country
an estimated $20 billion a year, about the size of its 1999 federal
budget. If stanching that hemorrhage is the KGB alumni's overriding
mission, good luck to them.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has yet to spell out his economic agenda, but he has made
it clear he plans to strengthen the courts, overhaul the tax system
and fight crime in order to improve Russia's business climate and
make it attractive to foreign investors. He is no Marxist-Leninist
throwback.
</P>
<P>
   True, he does believe in rebuilding Russia's armed forces,
having boosted its military budget as much as 50 percent. To put
that in perspective, though, the increased spending is still less
than 3 percent of the annual U.S. outlay for defense. And Russia's
military establishment has become so decrepit and disordered that
an overhaul could be a positive development, giving this fallen
power a feeling of stability and self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's relations with the West, especially the United States,
have deteriorated since the heady days following the Communist
collapse. Many there are disappointed with outside aid and advice,
just as the West is unhappy about how its help has been misused.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Washington has to persevere in coaxing Moscow to minimize
the dangers of weapons of mass destruction, to remove impediments
to an effective economy and to find accommodations with its
rambunctious republics. These should be priorities if Putin means
to make good on his vow to raise Russia's standing in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1642EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
