<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1283 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-REAL-LIFE30-COX     03-29 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A nonsmoker again - one day at a time
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It started with just one. I was going to
smoke one _ just one _ just that one time, I swear. But that was
all a pipe dream, which is to say, that was all a lie. A
cigarette's not exactly a Lay's potato chip. Someone should tell
the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   It's pathetic, really. A week from today, I would have been
smoke-free for two years. Two years! I'd finally gotten myself to
the point where days, even weeks, could fly by without me so much
as thinking about a cigarette. When I finally broke down and told
my kid I'd been cheating, I felt as though I was in the second
grade kneeling inside the dimly lit confessional at St. Patrick's
Cathedral in Leetonia, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you mad at me?'' I asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said the 9-year-old, the same dear child who had
cheered me on with such pride in April of 1998. ``I have to say I
thought we'd moved past all that.'' A priest couldn't have said it
any better.
</P>
<P>
   EVERYONE ELSE WAS SMOKING
</P>
<P>
   I'm not really sure how it happened, except that I was in a room
far away with people I'd just met while traveling in Cuba. Everyone
was smoking. Nothing seemed real. So when I took that cigarette, it
was as though it wasn't even me. I lived somewhere else and wore
different clothes and ate different foods.
</P>
<P>
   Except it was me, all right.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 18, 2000. Lighter, please.
</P>
<P>
   It was filterless. And strong. It made me nauseated and
lightheaded. At one point, I thought I was going to pass out.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I smoked an entire pack.
</P>
<P>
   I got back from my trip, gave them up, carried on. And then when
I got to feeling a little better, when all the disgusting side
effects had passed, I smoked again. And before I knew it, in no
time flat, smoking was driving my life again. I was thinking about
it all the time, always looking for a light, always waiting for
just enough time to pass so I could have another. It happened one
cigarette at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Over spring break, on a trip to visit my parents in Ohio, I
smoked outside in the freezing rain. The cigarettes made my head
throb and my stomach all queasy. Afterwards, I'd walk to the end of
the building, where the weather whipped around the corner, and I'd
stand, arms flapping, so the wind could blow away the awful stink.
Then I'd go inside, brush my teeth and spritz myself with my
mother's perfume. And so it went, off and on, on and off, like I
was 18 again, until I could actually smoke a cigarette without
wanting to throw up. I'm sure you can imagine my pride.
</P>
<P>
   WEARING THE PATCH AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   So, there you have it. My stupid, awful, predictable
predicament. Two weeks shy of what was supposed to be my big
good-for-you anniversary, I'm wearing the patch. I've written down
all the reasons I hate smoking. I'm chewing gum. I'm cranky. I'm
miserable. I want just one.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bad news. The good news is, it was all different this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Holding it, flicking it, smelling it, inhaling it. The stomach
pains. The headaches. The fibs. None of that seems like me anymore.
For the first time in my grown-up life, I feel more comfortable as
a nonsmoker. Not smoking finally feels like the real me. It's that
thread of fragile sanity that got me through yesterday. And the day
before that. I'll have to let you know about today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
