<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FLA-COACHES-NYTR &LR;      03-29 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-COACHES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FLORIDA COACHES FOLLOW SAME PATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIC HUBER    
 c. 2000 Sarasota Herald-Tribune    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a striking similarity in what two coaches with diverse
backgrounds have been able to do in two different sports at one
success-driven school.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Donovan and Steve Spurrier have much more in common than
the success they have had in their respective sports at the
University of Florida and the way they have turned on Gator fans to
those sports.
</P>
<P>
   It is more the journey than the destination that connects these
two brash leaders who accept nothing less than complete commitment
and the pursuit of perfection. They have each made a practice of
breaking down barriers. Winning was not enough. Proving people
wrong while doing it fueled the drive.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier heard how the Florida football team couldn't win big
games. He listened to how the Gators couldn't win on turf, how they
couldn't win on the road. Or in a dome. Or in cool weather. Or beat
Florida State. Or win a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   One by one the barriers fell. Each obstacle the Florida football
team overcame was accompanied by a Spurrier glare that said, ``I
told you so.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan has that same look these days. It's a little less
powerful, perhaps, but it's still a look of satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, going to the Sweet 16 was a shock to everybody,''
Donovan said Monday. ``I think going to the Final Four is a shock
to people now. They think we were a year away.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Donovan. Not ever.
</P>
<P>
   Like Spurrier in football, Donovan came to coach at Florida when
the basketball program was floundering.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Spurrier, who was a Gator long before he was named coach,
Donovan came to Florida as an outsider, with slicked-back hair and
a rapid-fire way of speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan followed Spurrier's recipe for winning games, attracting
athletes and satisfying fans.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan brought in a wide-open Fun, Run and Gun offense that put
points on the scoreboard and fans in the seats. He sold his players
on the system, convincing recruits that winning was more important
than playing time. With that, he began breaking down his own
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan heard how Florida couldn't recruit in the state and the
Gators couldn't win big games, how they couldn't win on the road,
or in domes, or how they couldn't beat ranked teams, or win close
games.
</P>
<P>
   Well, in this NCAA tournament, his Gators beat Butler at the
buzzer, then beat Illinois and Lon Kruger, the coach who took
Florida to its only other Final Four in 1994, in Winston Salem,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   They then went to the Carrier Dome in Syracuse and knocked off
No. 1-ranked Duke, then punched a ticket to Indianapolis by beating
Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   They got to the Final Four a year earlier than most expected by
beating the No. 1, No. 3 and No. 4 seeded teams in the East
Regional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so gratifying to return to the Final Four,'' said Florida
athletic director Jeremy Foley, who looked for a Spurrier clone
when he went searching for a new basketball coach four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we've been talking about, being in the hunt every
year, contending for a national title. Billy has assembled a team
that the entire University of Florida community can be proud of.
And we are not done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is a heck of a start. Donovan got his team into the Sweet
16 a year ago and has taken a team made up primarily of freshmen
and sophomores two steps farther this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now this team is two strides short of a national championship,
something Spurrier got in his seventh year on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan insists that more important than getting to a Final Four
is having the chance to get there year after year. It was hoped
that would happen after the Gators got there in 1994, but that
appearance proved just a tease. Two years later the Gators were on
the outside looking in, with little hope of getting another
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Then Donovan arrived with his frenetic style on the court and
his incredible ability to sell his program to players who had no
reason to believe there was something special in Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   But Donovan went right to work, determined to keep the top
players in the state from leaving. The first week on the job he was
in the halls at Miami Senior High, a place Kruger was never seen.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got an early commitment from Teddy Dupay, a McDonald's
All-America player and high school legend, who said he ``had a gut
feeling.'' Udonis Haslem and LaDarius Halton climbed aboard, with
Haslem saying he believed.
</P>
<P>
   That took care of the state of Florida, and Mike Miller took
care of everything else when he left South Dakota to take a chance
on Florida. Miller turned down Kansas and Kentucky to go with the
Gators. He decided he wanted to lead a team to the promised land
and start a tradition rather than be a part of one that had already
been established.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan knows basketball. He lived in the gyms growing up,
played in a Final Four at Providence under Rick Pitino. He then
coached in one at Kentucky as Pitino's assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Donovan and Miller walked arm in arm after knocking down
one more barrier. Donovan looked at Miller, grinned, and said,
``And people wondered why.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller says he knew why when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true. People were wondering why,'' Miller said. ``Now
they are all looking and saying, `Wow, he must've known a lot.'
Well, I told everybody I knew more than they did, and that's what
made the decision easy.
</P>
<P>
   And living in the shadow of football is an easy thing to do for
Donovan, who embraced Spurrier when he got to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He told Spurrier he admired the way he coached. Spurrier, in
turn, helped Donovan recruit Miller by hosting the recruit in his
office shortly before Florida played Tennessee in a football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the football here is a tremendous bonus to us
basketball-wise,'' Donovan said. ``I am part of a team here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota Herald-Tribune is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
