<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1299 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-LABASTIDA-$ADV     03-29 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LABASTIDA-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN TIGHT RACE, PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE OF MEXICO'S RULING PARTY
FIGHTS IMAGE AS 'MORE OF THE SAME'
 &HT;    (1100&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., April 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICALI, Mexico _ Francisco Labastida's jaw tightens just a bit
when asked to respond to being mocked as ``More of the Same.''
</P>
<P>
   It obviously bothers him. But the man who has the best chance to
become Mexico's next president quickly recovers his generally
confident composure. His political party _ Mexico's omnipresent
Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI _ has controlled Mexico's
highest office since 1929. After more than 70 years controlling the
presidency, the PRI holds the world's record for domination by one
party.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's race for president, which culminates in a July 2
election, could be the toughest ever for the party that emerged
from the Mexican Revolution and has always espoused a mixed
ideology of nationalism, socialism and capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida leads in most independent opinion polls, but only by
about five to six percentage points. His challenge is to convince
voters that despite the PRI's stained reputation _ stemming from
repeated scandals and economic policy failures _ he is still the
best option Mexicans have.
</P>
<P>
   Up to election day, Labastida is in for a bruising war with his
chief rival, the National Action Party's charismatic Vicente Fox, a
tall who has derisively referred to Labastida as ``shorty'' and
``More of the Same.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, 57, is an economist and a former governor of Mexico's
northern Sinaloa state. He is courtly, mild-mannered man who
brightens when describing his ideas for boosting farm subsidies for
embattled country folk, as well as proposals for putting computers
in every school ,and reforming Mexico's notoriously corrupt and
inept police.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Labastida came directly from the ranks of the
current PRI government _ serving both as agriculture minister and
interior minister, which put him in charge of law enforcement _ he
is portraying himself as the candidate of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greeks said that we should never bathe twice in the same
river,'' Labastida said during a recent interview with Cox
Newspapers as he criss-crossed northwestern Mexico on one of his
weekly campaign trips.
</P>
<P>
   In his speeches, Labastida sometimes takes pre-emptive aim at
Mexico's obvious difficulties _ too much poverty and corruption _
but he is careful not to blame the current administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of those to deny problems,'' Labastida recently
told a conference of Hispanic-American journalists in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   In a one-on-one interview with Cox Newspapers, he elaborated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that everything inside the party has been good.
I'm not blind. I'm not deaf. I know the party's problems and the
country's problems. I know people have committed acts of
corruption,'' he said, as his bus rolled toward a rally with
farmers near this agricultural and industrial border city.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, given Mexico's explosive population growth,
the PRI's previous governments have also made ``substantial
improvements in some areas,'' such as health services, potable
water and highways. The party has a historic link to farmers
because it distributed land after the Mexican Revolution, Labastida
said.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded: ``Problems with public safety, pollution and
corruption have grown in recent years. . . . I am aware of and
taking responsibility for the demands of society to fight what's
bad. I don't want to be president so things will continue as they
are. I don't want to be a conformist president.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida is viewed as a candidate who can attract a
cross-section of the PRI because he's not an Ivy League-educated
free-market ``technocrat'' like the Mexico's last two presidents,
nor is he a ``dinosaur,'' one of the party's old-fashioned
autocratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign, he's using modern television commercials,
polling under the counsel of President Clinton's adviser James
Carville and the PRI's vote-mobilizing political machine.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has to ``strike a balance that's very difficult,''
said Mexico City political scientist Jose Antonio Crespo. ``He has
to offer something that's different from the PRI, but still is the
PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's acknowledgment of PRI failures may seem bold, Crespo
added, but ``it's actually become a tradition now for every PRI
candidate to engage in (party) self-criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for the election, Labastida's party is promoting
itself as ``a new PRI'' that is more internally democratic, attuned
to citizens and fiscally responsible. For at least a generation,
Mexicans have witnessed their economy go into a tailspin after PRI
presidents finished their terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we didn't do well,'' Labastida said, ``is that to pay
attention to (social) demands we relied on deficit spending . . .
We took credit without any backing. . . Well, that generated
inflation and a lack of confidence in economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Revelations that PRI politicians not only mismanaged, but also
pocketed exorbitant sums of money hasn't helped the party's
reputation either.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1988-1994 term of President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, Mexicans' hopes soared as the country relaxed
protectionist trade barriers and invited foreign investment. When
an overvalued peso collapsed in December 1994, however, Mexicans
aimed their wrath at the PRI and the party started losing key
elections. Salinas' brother was charged with murdering a party
rival and stealing money.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo has stabilized the economy and
recovered some public trust, but a hard core of voters is now
anti-PRI. Sentiment against the ruling party has also been fueled
by more recent unsavory revelations about other PRI politicians,
such as Mario Villanueva, former governor of Quintana Roo state,
who escaped the country before he could be arrested for consorting
with drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   On March 27, Mexico's Reforma newspaper published a poll showing
that only 39 percent of voters prefer Labastida. More voters prefer
opposition candidates, but are divided between the PAN's Fox, with
32 percent, and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the Democratic Revolution
Party with 11 percent. Seventeen percent are undecided and 1
percent prefer lesser-known candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Another poll published the same day by El Universal newspaper
shows a preference of 45 percent for Labastida, compared to almost
40 percent for Fox and almost 13 percent for Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Last November, as part of its image makeover, the PRI held its
first-ever primary election to select a presidential nominee.
Labastida won, but many analysts said the election was stacked in
favor of Labastida because he was the party elite's favorite
choice.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1968 from Mexico's National Autonomous
University, Labastida worked as a federal budget and public
investment manager, as well as energy secretary in the
administration of President Miguel de la Madrid. Under Zedillo, he
was an agricultural minister, a post that put him in contact with
leaders of PRI-affiliated farmers' groups that expect special
attention in exchange for votes.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent stop here, near Mexicali, Labastida met with
about 1,500 farmers wearing cowboy boots and hats and listened to a
litany of complaints about low cotton and wheat prices, the high
price of electricity and business debts few can afford to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hopes of the farmers are with you, Francisco Labastida,''
shouted Rodolfo Fierro, Baja California state leader of the
PRI-affiliated National Confederation of Farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida was in his element among the northern Mexican farmers,
who appeared to be more like small businessmen rather than
peasants. To cheers from the crowd, he would at least double a
federal farm subsidies program and pass a law to help alleviate the
high cost of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's experience as agriculture minister could garner him
votes, or it could be an Achilles' heel since many Mexican farmers
have grown disenchanted with the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for his tenure as governor of Sinaloa, a state
that remains notorious for drug trafficking although Labastida
publicly battled criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse the comment,'' Labastida said, getting defensive when
asked about the PRI's poor reputation for cracking down on crime.
``But I have acquired a reputation for making changes in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started to make changes in public safety in my state,
the first thing I did was clean up the police,'' Labastida said.
``The judicial police were protecting delinquents. We put three
groups of them in jail, and there were reprisals. They killed my
state security chief . . . I myself was threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1658EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
