u w BC-STOCK-OPTIONS30-COX     03-29 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-OPTIONS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL WOULD REMOVE BARRIER TO WORKERS' STOCK OPTIONS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Employers will be free to continue granting stock
options to hourly workers under a bipartisan bill introduced
Wednesday in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, backed by the White House, would clarify labor laws to
ensure that companies can grant stock options without having to
include stock gains in overtime pay calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Today, an estimated 6 million hourly wage earners have stock
options, which give them the right to buy or sell their companies'
stock at a specified price by a specific date.
</P>
<P>
   Such options can become extremely valuable if a company's stock
price shoots up. If a worker's windfall were included in his base
pay, overtime pay would rocket up too.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, employers assumed they did not have to worry
about calculating gains from options. But last year, the Labor
Department issued an opinion saying the Fair Labor Standards Act
does require them to count options in calculating a worker's base
pay.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure that opinion doesn't get enforced, the Worker
