<HEADER>
A1303 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TCU-CHOREOGRAPHER-TEX     03-29 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TCU-CHOREOGRAPHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUJONES WILL RETURN TO CENTER STAGE _ AT TCU AND IN FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Fernando Bujones, long renowned as a dancer
and now establishing himself as a choreographer and ballet
director, made one thing clear when he recently accepted a new job
as artistic director of Southern Ballet Theatre in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to maintain my affiliation with TCU,'' he said in a
recent interview on the Texas Christian University campus, between
classes and rehearsals for the scholarship benefit dance concert
that will be held at Ed Landreth Auditorium through this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Along with works by faculty members and a restaging of a famous
Paul Taylor work, the program includes the premiere of Bujones'
``Greek Breeze and Tease,'' a setting of music of modern Greek
composer Mikis Theodorakis, who did the score for the film ``Zorba
the Greek.''
</P>
<P>
   Bujones has been associated with the TCU ballet and modern dance
program since the mid-1990s, when he was a visiting teacher. Since
then, he has returned to Fort Worth about five times a year to
teach and stage ballets, and to try out ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude of the students motivates me to do my best
work,'' Bujones says. ``A student here can be more motivated than
some professional dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   Dance students like the fact that Bujones sets the bar high.
``He's highly demanding,'' says Colleen Comer, a third-year ballet
major from Atlanta. ``But in a good way. He expects
professionalism. He says, `If you can work with me, you can work
with any professional choreographer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bujones' career originated in the volatile world of Cold War
politics and American-Cuban hostilities. Born in the Cuban-American
community in Miami in 1955, before Castro's takeover of Cuba, he
traveled back and forth between Cuba and the United States with his
mother during his preschool years. He ended up on the Cuban side of
the water after the Castro-led revolution in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was a U.S. citizen, he and his mother were allowed to
leave Cuba, going first to Prague, then Paris, then back to Miami
to rejoin relatives. Bujones has never returned to Cuba, and says
he probably won't until democratic government is established there.
</P>
<P>
   His mother hoped he would become a pianist. His nervous energy
dictated that he become a dancer, however, although he picked up
extensive musical ability from years of piano lessons. At 12, he
was offered the chance to go to New York on a scholarship to the
American School of Ballet, where he completed his training before
winning international fame by taking the gold medal for highest
technical achievement at the Seventh International Ballet
Competition in Varna, Bulgaria, in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   One of his fondest memories as a touring artist is receiving a
pair of boots in Fort Worth at the end of a performance at the
Convention Center Theatre in 1976. When he began turning more to
teaching, directing and choreography in the 1990s, the dance
department at TCU offered him plenty of opportunities to do all
three.
</P>
<P>
   Dance careers often begin when youngsters are teen-agers,
because dancers, like athletes, reach their physical peak
relatively early. But college dance departments offer an
alternative approach, and TCU has long been a pioneer in
college-level dance studies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, the school led the way with the first bachelor of fine
arts degree program in ballet. TCU added modern dance to its
program in the early 1970s, shortly before Ellen Page Garrison
joined the faculty in 1977. Garrison became department head in '91,
and today, TCU serves about 70 dance majors with a full-time
faculty of five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our students have teaching as a goal,'' Garrison says.
``Our students become therapists, writers, artists and teachers at
all levels.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Garrison points out, dance instruction at the grassroots
level _ out in the small town and suburban studios where
5-year-olds line up for early training _ is often low in quality. A
program like TCU's _ which offers complete training for a dancer in
modern dance and ballet, and in related academic studies _ helps to
raise the quality of dance education when college-trained dancers
begin to teach at the beginner level.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's performances will reflect the dance department's
insistence on diverse training, including modern dance and ballet,
for all undergraduate dance students. Taylor's ``Aureole,'' of
1963, will be staged by Mary Chochran, a former TCU dance student
who became a principal dancer in the Paul Taylor company. Other
works will include modern dance pieces, as well as new works in the
ballet tradition and an interpretation of swing dance.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Bujones is also a part of the program as choreographer
in residence. Still lean at 5 feet 9 inches and 145 pounds, he is
constantly accompanied by his wife of 10 years, Peruvian-born Maria
Arnillas Bujones, whom he met while dancing in ``Sleeping Beauty''
at the Stuttgart Ballet, where she was a member of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando, with a company comparable in size to the Fort Worth
Dallas Ballet, will become the Bujones' home base, but Fort Worth
will be a home away from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the city,'' he says of Fort Worth. ``And I like that
TCU is part of the city's cultural life.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
