<HEADER>
A1307 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CAMPAIGN-LAURA-INGRAH     03-29 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-LAURA-INGRAHAM-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, WOMEN AND GUN VIOLENCE: AN OPPORTUNITY, NOT A WEAKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Campaign
Countdown commentary column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.)
 By LAURA INGRAHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Sometimes it's not a bad thing to let your opponents shape the
campaign agenda _ as long as you can turn it to your own advantage.
 &HT;    George W. Bush has been doing his post-primary best to keep the
campaign focused on issues that he knows well: education and
Clinton-Gore 1996 fund-raising abuses.
 &HT;    But come Mother's Day, when thousands of pro-gun-control women
will descend upon Washington for the so-called ``Million Mom
March,'' Al Gore is going to have some major help in changing the
subject to an issue he thinks is a plus for the Democrats.
 &HT;    We already know how Gore will handle the gun issue _ he'll
indulge in demagoguery and play loosey-goosey with the statistics
to justify ever-more-intrusive restrictions on gun ownership by
law-abiding Americans.
 &HT;    Bush, on the other hand, has said precious little on the
subject, other than that he favors trigger locks.
 &HT;    Many of the same people urging Bush to ``make a deal'' with John
McCain are also telling him to ``move to the middle'' on guns. Both
ideas are bad advice, yielding control of the campaign dynamic to
Bush's rivals, past and future.
 &HT;    Moreover, there's no need for Bush to seek middle ground _ he
can be true to his pro-gun principles and still close the gender
gap in the coming election.
 &HT;    Right now Bush trails Gore only slightly among women _ he lags
by only five points in the latest voter.com/Battleground 2000 poll.
Bush is already doing well among mothers, married women and white
suburban women, while Gore holds the upper hand among minority
women, single women and retirees.
 &HT;    But gun control isn't the way to those voters' hearts. Despite
what antigun forces would have us believe, women don't rank
gun-control legislation among their greatest concerns.
 &HT;    In fact, according to the mid-March Battleground Poll, the
issues that most worry women are tailor-made for Bush: ``Restoring
moral values'' drew 18 percent, and ``improving education'' 13
percent. Social Security/Medicare, at 11 percent, and health care
at 10 percent came in third and fourth, respectively. Gun control
ranked down at No. 5.
 &HT;    Does this mean that George W. should steer clear of the gun
issue?
 &HT;    On the contrary _ Bush should use this hot-button issue to show
that he won't run and hide when the going gets tough and the media
pressure is on. The ``Million Mother March'' provides exactly that
opportunity.
 &HT;    Everyone knows Gore will be there, railing against the NRA and
the GOP-controlled ``Do Nothing'' Congress. But few expect Bush to
show up to face a largely hostile crowd _ which is just the reason
he should. Standing up in the face of opposition shows just the
kind of courage Americans are looking for in a president.
 &HT;    Besides, organizer Rep. Carolyn McCarthy (D.-N.Y.) told the New
York Times, ``We're working very hard to make sure it's not a
Republican or Democratic event.'' Bush should help her guarantee
that.
 &HT;    So, if he does show up, what should the Texas governor say?
 &HT;    With so many women concerned about our country's moral decline,
Bush should put the hideous phenomenon of children shooting
children in the context of the greater national problem, an overall
decline of respect for human life.
 &HT;    Fifty years ago, more Americans owned more guns than today, yet
school shootings were unthinkable. Since then, however, divorce,
illegitimacy, drug use, abortion and rampant sex and violence in
entertainment have created a toxic atmosphere for our children.
 &HT;    Women on both sides of the political aisle have seen how the
culture can corrode the values that they try to instill in their
children. That's why so many women yearn for a leader who carries
himself with dignity and decency _ John McCain understood this _
even if they don't always agree with him.
 &HT;    As far as gun control is concerned, Bush should talk about
lapses in enforcement and also point out the dangers of
partisanship on issues such as gun violence.
 &HT;    Last year, after all, the White House urged House Democrats to
kill a bill, supported by a bipartisan coalition, that would have
included provisions for trigger locks and a juvenile Brady Bill, as
well as a 24-hour waiting period for purchases at gun shows.
 &HT;    It didn't go far enough, the Democrats said _ which conveniently
allows Gore to rail against Congressional foot-dragging on
``sensible gun laws.''
 &HT;    Finally, wouldn't it be refreshing if Bush spoke of gun
ownership as a ``women's issue''?
 &HT;    Thousands of women across the country have, at one time or
another, felt threatened, been attacked or needed a restraining
order against a violent boyfriend or ex-husband. If antigun forces
win out, these women won't be able to choose to defend themselves.
 &HT;    Women are every bit as concerned about protecting their homes
and families as men are. To many women, gun ownership is an
antidote to the sense of powerlessness that a woman feels when she
or her children are threatened.
 &HT;    When Gore talks about ``choice,'' he means abortion _ a stance
that will keep him in good stead with the Planned Parenthood
constituency.
 &HT;    But Bush can use the rhetoric of ``choice,'' too, and in the
process he just might capture a majority of the women's vote. He's
already gotten good results talking about choice in terms of
education. Now it's time for him to extend the concept of choice to
another important American value _ self-defense.
 c.2000 Laura Ingraham  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Laura Ingraham is a lawyer and a special election correspondent
for MSNBC. She is the author of the upcoming book, ``The Hillary
Trap: Looking for Power in All the Wrong Places,'' due from
Hyperion in June 2000.)
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.)
