<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-COUPLAND-TOTEMS-2TAKE     03-29 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUPLAND-TOTEMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGLAS COUPLAND CREATES A COTTAGE INDUSTRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Canada)  By FRED BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was a freezing cold Sunday and the novelist Douglas
Coupland, chronicler of disaffected youth, was trawling Belmont
Avenue for midcentury American ceramics. He bought one piece after
another, never inquiring who made them or so much as glancing at
the prices.
</P>
<P>
   What he did not tell the store owners (``I don't have the
heart'') is that the vases aren't going to be vases much longer.
``They're an art supply,'' said Coupland, who studied sculpture
before taking up writing. His 1991 novel, ``Generation X,'' gave
20-somethings a catchy name and slacker reputation. Now Coupland
was in Chicago to promote his seventh book, ``Miss Wyoming''
(Pantheon Books, $23).
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Vancouver, British Columbia, Coupland planned to
sand the finishes off the vases, stiffen them with plaster, then
join them with metal rods and an adhesive he calls ``shoe-goo''
into Brancusi-like totems, with which he is filling his 1960
post-and-beam house to the point of overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   The totems are one of a dozen or so art and furniture design
projects that consume him. All begin with favorite shapes. Or, as
he puts it, ``I have a morphological agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupland (pronounced cope-land) says he has never been in
therapy. How then to decipher his obsessions, which include plastic
bottles? While on book tours, he runs from drugstore to drugstore,
buying shampoos and detergents, which he then pours down the drains
of hotel bathrooms. Back home, he fills the bottles with brightly
colored resins, then peels the bottles away. Displayed against a
nearly white wall, the result resembles a futuristic Herbal
Essences museum.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite vases _ ``I guess I could drill a hole big enough for
one daisy,'' he said reluctantly _ the objects are familiar and yet
oddly unsettling, especially mixed in with a few empty bottles and
ikebana vases on Copeland's wall. ``Your brain can't reconcile all
three at once,'' he said. ``When people come into the house,
there's usually 15 or 20 seconds when their brains are trying to
catch up to what their eyes are seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   As he nears middle age (``I'm 38.3,'' he says with geeky
precision), Coupland is creating a cottage industry, which is as
much about recapturing the past as reconfiguring the present. He
has enlisted art-school friends to help bring the products of his
imagination, including pop culture inspired furniture, to market.
</P>
<P>
   Coupland plans to release five of his mutated bottles in
editions of 50. He may also make a set in bronze _ as doorstops or
bookends, perhaps. But functionality is an afterthought in his
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first day of art school,'' Coupland said nostalgically,
``was the first day in my life I could pick up an object and say
`That's so beautiful' without getting beat up.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupland, who claims he is so out of sync with his own
generation that he does not bother to invest (``It makes me feel
parasitic''), uses his earnings to ``smooth out the peaks and
valleys'' in the lives of the Vancouver artists who are helping
him, some of whom he has known for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose our ability to make friends about the same time we
acquire our first expensive piece of furniture,'' he writes in
``Miss Wyoming.'' That might explain why he is surrounding himself
with his old friends, although he jokes, ``In my case, I'm still
waiting for the aphorism to kick in.''
</P>
<P>
   Still in art school mode, he pulls all-nighters, as he recently
did with a trio of young entrepreneurs in Edmonton, Alberta, who
asked him to join their stable of designers that already includes
Karim Rashid and Nick Dine. Their company, Pure Design
(800-483-5643 or www.pure-design.com), now sells created laminate
tables in patterns inspired by the face-off circle of a hockey rink
(a Canadian obsession) and Roy Lichtenstein (a Coupland obsession,
along with the other Pop artists).
</P>
<P>
   Another piece is called the Henry Table; it is a homage to
Moore. The rotund forms of Henry Moore sculptures are immediately
recognizable, despite the fact that the $649 table is made of flat
sheets of lacquered fiberboard.
</P>
<P>
   That is Coupland's foray into mass marketing. At the same time,
he is looking to sell handmade pieces, including a giant fiberglass
chair inspired by the ``secret world domination headquarters'' in
the movie ``Men in Black.'' It costs $5,500, crated, but he resists
the suggestion that as a youth-culture chronicler, he has somehow
strayed by making expensive furniture. ``It's sculpture, and
sculpture has always been expensive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Janet, who raised four Coupland sons in West
Vancouver, says she has no idea where her son's artistic
sensibility comes from. ``I was afraid you were going to ask
that,'' she said, recalling that, as a toddler, ``Doug pretty much
lived with his Legos.'' But about the time he turned 10, she said,
all he wanted for Christmas was a Lichtenstein poster.
</P>
<P>
   At that point he was already a Pop Art devotee, having seen a
James Rosenquist collage in an encyclopedia when he was 7. The
collage was F-111, a powerful antiwar statement juxtaposing images
of small children and military hardware. As soon as he could afford
to, Coupland bought a limited-edition print.
</P>
<P>
   It hangs in Coupland's house in West Vancouver, 5 miles from
where he grew up, a doctor's son in a
moose-strapped-to-the-hood-of-the-Ford Fairlane neighborhood.
Designed by Ron Thom, a brand-name Canadian Modernist, the house
steps down a hillside; Coupland calls the style ``Alpine Neutra.''
Instead of a yard, there is a forest so thick, Coupland said, ``I
don't know what color the house is.'' He dislikes views, which he
explains by saying he is descended from cave dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years he has modified the house with walls of
backlighted plexiglass and varnished madrona wood. He resurfaced
one wall in sheets of brightly colored plywood made especially for
road signs. ``It's unbloatable,'' he said. Gridded shelves were
made by an art school friend, Jud Beaumont, to Coupland's precise
specifications. One shelf holds geometric fantasies rendered in
metal by another art school classmate, Tim Lepp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can call Tim and say, `I really, really, really, really need
an 8-inch copper icosahedron,''' Coupland said, ``and he'll say
`Cool.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As to why he might need a copper icosahedron in the first place,
Coupland explained that he simply had no choice. ``It was a
`Richard-Dreyfuss-making-Devil's-Tower-out-of-mashed-potatoes
moment,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Coupland, who speaks calmly and patiently, even when describing
obsession, said he rearranges his furniture weekly. This after
observing, ``The interior of a person's house is the closest you're
going to get to the interior of that person's brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupland is an expert in the ennui of the middle-class slacker.
To write ``Microserfs'' (1995), he went to live with computer
programmers. For ``Shampoo Planet'' (1992), he depicted a world of
globally enfranchised teens. One of them, Tyler, is obsessed with
hair products, including bottled shampoos. (``Oh my God, I never
noticed that! Wow!'' he e-mailed a reporter who pointed out that
Tyler foreshadowed his own bottle collecting.)
</P>
<P>
   Although his books have sold hundreds of thousands of copies,
when he went looking for a new publishing house after leaving Regan
Books in 1998, he welcomed a 15-page critique of his writing by
Sonny Mehta, the head of Knopf Pantheon, and members of his staff.
The memo cited such things as his ``misuse of sentimentality'' and
``shifts in point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Impressed, Coupland took the Knopf Pantheon offer, although it
wasn't the most lucrative. ``At some point, if you're going to
evolve, you're going to have to work with someone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Wyoming,'' about a beauty queen turned television
actress, prompted by a 1998 National Enquirer article about the
marriage of Catherine Oxenberg and Robert Evans, has received mixed
reviews in the United States. While Tom Wolfe called him a
``Nathanael West with an eye for the year 2000,'' Tom Shone wrote
in The New York Times Book Review, ``For all its outward-bound
urges, `Miss Wyoming' remains a curiously clipped and uptight
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans, Coupland lamented, ``like naturalistic books, with a
dollop of history and a sprinkle of folksy wisdom, and I can't
write that kind of book.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of his best writing, including travel articles for
Wallpaper, is available on his Rosenquist-inspired Web site,
Coupland.com. Also available are collages created by Coupland from
the ephemera that fills his pockets while he is touring. (He
carries scissors and a gluestick everywhere.)
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration comes from what he sees around him. Looking at ice
breaking up on the Chicago River, says Coupland, who speaks more
readily in visual than in literary terms. ``It's just like that
laminate Ettore Sotsass did in the early '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   A man who finds laminate in nature is a man who is always going
to follow his Modernist instincts. ``Just as you can't picture
Philip Johnson using a doily in the glass house,'' he says, ``there
won't be any antimacassars on Coupland.com.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
