<HEADER>
A1326 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TORNADO-HOMELESSMAN-T     03-29 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-HOMELESSMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(EDS: ACCOMPANIES TORNADO-TEXAS)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BECHETTA JACKSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Carl B. Spence was a former Navy man who
sought odd jobs during the day and nestled under trees with a
bottle of booze at night.
</P>
<P>
   Homeless for more than a decade, Spence, 67, died while seeking
shelter from the tornado that roared through downtown Fort Worth on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Spence and his buddy John Barr were sheltering on the porch of
the empty Burns Graphics building on Seventh Street when a wall
behind them collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Both were buried under debris, but Barr, 70, escaped unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised if he had not been trying to head this way,''
John Suggs, director of the Presbyterian Night Shelter east of
downtown, said Wednesday. An estimated 500 homeless people sought
refuge from the storm at the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Spence's name was on a sheet of paper posted on the shelter
bulletin board, which meant that he had mail to be picked up, Suggs
said.
</P>
<P>
   Had Spence made it to the shelter, he would have found a letter
from his older sister, Sarah Pentecost of Winder, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   He mailed her a birthday card two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall that your birthday is sometime this month,'' Spence
wrote inside the card. ``Hope you are well. I do remember all of
you in my prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, Pentecost said the family thought often of
Spence, who made money doing day labor. Police reports show that he
had been arrested a few times for disorderly conduct and public
intoxication.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't perfect, but we never discarded him because he was
homeless,'' said Pentecost, 75, breaking into tears upon learning
of her brother's death.
</P>
<P>
   Pentecost had heard about the tornado on the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had him on my mind all night,'' she said, her voice
quivering. ``He was a good person. He just had a disease,
alcoholism, that he couldn't control.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the letter that Pentecost sent to Spence was a
newspaper article about their eldest living sibling, Opal Deaton,
78, who recently retired from teaching Sunday school after more
than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `I know you are as proud of her as I am,' '' Pentecost
said. ``I sent him another letter this morning because I was
concerned about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Spence, the youngest of five children, was a responsible man
before he became addicted to alcohol, Pentecost said.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped out of high school in Georgia to join the Navy.
Spence married and had a daughter who was killed in an automobile
accident about a decade ago, Pentecost said. Spence had three
grandchildren, Pentecost said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never talked about his situation,'' she said. ``I had told
him many times that if I knew he wouldn't drink again, he could
come stay with me anytime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just let alcohol ruin him, take him over. But I never
failed to pray for him every day.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
