<HEADER>
A1328 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-FOREIGN-LEGION-NY     03-29 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FOREIGN-LEGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF TO THE WEB TO JOIN THE LEGION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: In Web addresses, replace (underscore) with the typographical
symbol, no parentheses . )  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, the shifting sands. Fort Zinderneuf. Soldiers of fortune
with no past. Oui, mon capitaine. Buster Crabbe in ``Captain
Gallant.'' Gary Cooper in ``Beau Geste.'' Gene Hackman in ``March
or Die.''
</P>
<P>
   Now you can remember all those men who joined to forget all
those women, because the French Foreign Legion did not march out
with the final credits. In fact, the legion is not only alive, with
recent service in trouble spots like Chad and Bosnia, but it also
has its own Web site
(www.info-france-usa.org/america/embassy/legion/legion.htm),
courtesy of the French Embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1831, 902 officers, 3,176 noncommissioned officers and
more than 30,000 legionnaires have died for France, one-third of
them while fighting directly for the defense of the country,'' the
site reports. ``Foreigners by birth, the legionnaires have become
Frenchmen by the blood they have spilled.''
</P>
<P>
   The embassy's site has a short history of the legion, from its
founding in Algeria to modern times. While it is most identified
with North Africa in cinematic imagination, its most celebrated
battle occurred in Mexico in 1863, at an inn named Camerone in Palo
Verde, near Puebla. There, at the French equivalent of the Alamo,
three officers and 62 legionnaires resisted 2,000 Mexicans. ``After
a day of heroic fighting, the last five survivors fixed bayonets
and charged.''
</P>
<P>
   The site also covers some of the legion's traditions, its code
of honor, its uniform and its music. But the English version of the
bilingual site is there for a practical purpose, not just
nostalgia: to answer the questions of would-be recruits (ages 17 to
40) about enlistment procedures. ``The legionnaire is seldom an
angel but never a criminal,'' the site says. ``Once he has joined,
under an assumed name if he wishes, the legionnaire enjoys an
unequaled protection for as long as he serves because of the
anonymity rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Less official but equally heartfelt sites, created by
ex-legionnaires or admirers, offer more information than the
embassy's. You can listen to legion songs at
home.talkcity.com/spiritcir/lediable, a site created by Collin Rae
Smith, a former legion corporal (1994-99). Those thinking about
joining, he says, should be able to run 2,800 meters (about one and
three-quarter miles) in 12 minutes or less and climb a 20-foot rope
using only the arms.
</P>
<P>
   Smith describes basic training at one of the legion's ``farms'':
running, French lessons, combat training, rope climbing and more
running. ``The evenings are usually spent by learning legion songs
(the legion takes singing very seriously) or night marches,'' he
writes. Then comes the Kepi Blanc march, 80 to 100 kilometers (50
to 62 miles) over two or three days in full gear. Basic enlistment
for those who make it is five years.
</P>
<P>
   The legion is not for weaklings, but despite the escapist image,
it is not for losers, either. It is a highly professional outfit,
now based in Aubagne, near Marseille. Most of its officers and
about 40 percent of its men are French. Specialized units include
underwater demolitions teams and an elite paratrooper regiment,
which is very difficult to enter and is based in Corsica.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jungle Training School in French Guiana is the best on the
planet,'' Larry B. Lambert wrote by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert has perhaps the most thorough English-language legion
site on the Web 
(users.deltanet.com/users/llambert/public(underscore)html/legion(und
erscore)index.html), especially for military history . The legion
has 8,000 members and accepts 1,300 men for training each year out
of about 10,000 applicants, his site says. It chronicles the legion
in the world wars; Africa; Indochina, including the siege of Dien
Bien Phu; and Bosnia. The site is illustrated with color
photographs of historic legion recruiting posters, worth a visit
all by themselves. (Asked to say something about himself, Lambert
replied, in appropriate legion fashion, ``I'd rather not.'')
</P>
<P>
   There is also a biography of John Hasey, who enlisted in 1940 in
a Free French unit of the legion and was badly wounded the next
year. Among the 1,036 Companions of the Liberation, honored by de
Gaulle for having done the most to free France from German
occupation, there are two Americans: John Hasey and Dwight D.
Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it is still under construction, a site by Thierry de
Cervens, a surgeon (www.cervens.net), should be a required tour of
duty. It is partly a memorial to his father, Guy Rubin de Cervens,
a decorated captain of the legion's paratroopers who died in 1996.
It shows the legion's insignia, medals, uniforms and current
assignments. Its archives section has an open message board where
former legionnaires tell what it was really like. It lists famous
legionnaires, including Capitaine Danjou, hero of Camerone. And it
reprints a 1991 thank-you letter from a new honorary legionnaire,
Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
