<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1330 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-NETSCAPE-TV-NYT &LR;      03-29 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NETSCAPE-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CODE RUSH: A YEAR IN THE LIFE OF A SILICON VALLEY SUPERNOVA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   (Eds: Michelle Slatalla is the co-author
(with Joshua Quittner) of ``Speeding the Net: The Inside Story of
Netscape and How It Challenged Microsoft.'')  
(lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no lack of drama in the history of Netscape, the
company that introduced millions of Internet users to the World
Wide Web and then was driven to its knees after locking horns with
Microsoft in a struggle known as the browser wars.
</P>
<P>
   When an independent film crew arrived at the company's offices
in Mountain View, Calif., in early 1998 to make an hourlong
documentary called ``Code Rush,'' scheduled to be broadcast by the
Public Broadcasting Service Thursday at 10 p.m. ET (check local
listings), Netscape was trying to resurrect its fortunes by
adopting a radical new strategy: giving away the source code, or
the underlying program instructions, to its browser in the hope of
blunting competition from Internet Explorer, which Microsoft was
giving away.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, looking inside a software company _ where employees
spend most of their time typing _ does not guarantee riveting
visuals even under the best of circumstances. But I can think of a
lot of moments in Netscape's history that might have been
interesting on film.
</P>
<P>
   There were, for example, the heady days of 1994, when the
company, still called Mosaic Communications, consisted mainly of a
handful of programmers who worked 120-hour weeks, napped fitfully
under their desks and refrained from bathing until the boss'
secretary implemented a forced hygiene regimen. And there was the
day in August 1995 when the success of Netscape's initial public
offering created instant millionaires among the ranks of the
company's young coders.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the ``Code Rush'' crew began its documentary,
Netscape's brief, wild ride had long been over. What remained was a
crippled company that had lost more than $85 million in the last
quarter of 1997. By 1998, Netscape had become a cautionary tale
about what can happen when optimistic entrepreneurs run into the
side of a big truck, especially a truck called Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, produced by Winton duPont Films and television
station KTEH of San Jose, Calif., follows a small team of Netscape
programmers engaged in open source code strategy. The idea was to
enlist the help of independent software writers to create bits and
pieces of a new and irresistible version of the Netscape browser
that would become the Internet standard. (It didn't happen, of
course.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead of capturing the thrill of a struggling company in the
throes of a desperate gambit, the cameras found sad-eyed
programmers working with an air of resignation on a project that
would not save their company. A viewer spends the better part of
the hour watching emotionless footage of programmers talking about
their work as they walk along claustrophobic corridors lined by
rows of the cookie-cutter cubicles where they live their lives.
Sometimes they talk about their work while driving. Oh, and
sometimes they type.
</P>
<P>
   Among the team's members were some of Netscape's earliest
employees, who had lived through the company's exhilarating early
days. But curiously, the film did not make much of the contrast
between what the company had been and what it had become. Only a
Netscape junkie will appreciate the painful scene in which
Netscape's co-founder, Marc Andreessen, tries to get past the
switchboard at Apple (ailing Apple) to get permission to use a bit
of code.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the grim loyalty the programmers exhibited toward
Netscape _ a lot of them appeared to own wardrobes that consisted
exclusively of clothing emblazoned with the company's distinctive N
logo _ made me wonder if this is what an inside look at the last
days of the Heaven's Gate sect might have looked like. Even after
the announcement in late 1998 that America Online would buy (or
more accurately, swallow) Netscape, some of the programmers were
insisting that the idea of Netscape would somehow survive. ``They
like us,'' one programmer says in ``Code Rush.'' ``They like what
we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking-head commentary in the film rushes wildly through
shopworn themes: software as the new frontier, Silicon Valley as
the new gold rush, the difficulty of balancing work and family for
programmers who might stay at the office for 60 hours straight.
Somewhere in the confused narrative is the sad story of bright
people doomed to failure. It is hard to see how Netscape's
open-source gamble accomplished anything, either for the company in
the short term or for the open-source movement in general.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary points out that much of the Internet's early
growth was aided by programmers offering free code. But the big
question of how a commercial enterprise like Netscape would benefit
from releasing its source code remains. It shouldn't have. Not
after a year of filming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
