<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1331 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WEATHER-RADIO-ART     03-29 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEATHER-RADIO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIOS WATCH WEATHER SO YOU DON'T HAVE TO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ark., Ore.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC TAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if you're on the lookout, tornadoes, blizzards, hurricanes
and floods are dangerous. But when storms sweep up suddenly,
perhaps in the middle of the night, it's all too easy to be caught
looking the other way.
</P>
<P>
   What is needed is an early warning system, a way to learn that
dangerous weather is on the way. Even a heads-up warning only a few
minutes before catastrophe strikes is often enough time for someone
to figure out how to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Such a system is available throughout most of the country,
thanks to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, but
only a small part of the population listens to it. Most people
either don't know about the agency's network of 24-hour weather
radio stations, known as NOAA Weather Radio, or don't have radios
that can pick up the broadcasts. Or they don't want to wade through
maritime updates or irrelevant forecasts for areas far away.
</P>
<P>
   What would be really useful would be a system that could tell a
person's radio to wake up to issue a weather alert, so the radio
wouldn't have to be kept on all the time. It would also be
convenient to filter the weather information so listeners got only
the weather information they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Now NOAA has several new technologies that will do just that.
These advances come at a time when the damage from severe weather
is costing more than ever. The 10 most costly disasters in the
history of this country, including four hurricanes, have all
happened in the past decade, according to NOAA, which is part of
the Commerce Department. And as more people move to coastal areas,
more people will be at risk.
</P>
<P>
   NOAA's first weather radio station started broadcasting marine
and aviation advisories in the 1950s. Today nearly 500 transmitters
send out meteorological information gathered from the agency's 122
weather forecasting offices. Each transmitter can customize its
transmissions for its locale.
</P>
<P>
   Every time a local television weather forecaster announces a
``flash-flood watch'' or a ``tornado warning,'' that information
comes directly from NOAA, the only organization that uses those
terms to designate weather conditions. A watch means that current
atmospheric conditions could produce that storm, flood or tornado.
A warning means that such a danger has already been sighted.
</P>
<P>
   Often a few minutes' warning is all that is needed. In January
1999, the school superintendent in Beebe, Ark., Dr. Kieth Williams,
was monitoring NOAA radio and found out about a tornado watch. At 7
p.m., the tornado watch turned into a warning, Williams told 500
people at Beebe High School to evacuate the gym, which a twister
flattened 20 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Close to 90 percent of the nation's population can get access to
weather service broadcasts _ as long as they have weather radios,
which can pick up one of the seven frequencies NOAA uses between
162.4 megahertz and 162.55 megahertz. About eight million weather
radios have been sold, only one for every 33 people. That includes
units on some luxury cars, like BMW's, Mercedes-Benzes and Saabs,
as well as combination AM-FM weather radios from manufacturers like
Oregon Scientific, Midland Consumer Radio and Radio Shack.
</P>
<P>
   The use of weather radios is most important at night, when
tornadoes and floods can catch sleeping populations unawares, but
nobody wants to keep a radio blaring all night on the off chance
that a tornado might hit. So several years ago NOAA developed
technology that lets weather radios operate on standby, coming
alive only when a weather watch or warning is broadcast. An
inaudible subtone tells the radio to turn on, using a variation of
technology employed throughout Europe to activate car radios
automatically during dangerous traffic situations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the spoken warning that is broadcast over the
radio, weather radios that operate in standby mode also sound a
90-decibel alert tone, which is loud enough to wake just about
anyone. Certain models will also display a text message specifying
the exact weather event, like ``hurricane warning'' or ``flood
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers let users limit the number of times that a
report of an emergency will appear on the display. Or the user can
set the radio to display only certain emergencies; floods might
trigger the alert, for instance, while tornadoes would be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Still, information about severe weather in one area may turn out
to be irrelevant for a town 60 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure that radios issue alerts for only local weather
problems, NOAA has created a digital technology called Specific
Area Messaging Encoding; radios with the SAME technology turn on
only when weather alerts are broadcast in specified areas.
</P>
<P>
   Radios can be set to respond to weather alerts for areas within
50 miles so they do not awaken people unnecessarily. ``Prior to
SAME technology, 50 percent of the weather alerts were false
alarms'' warning people of weather problems far away, said Jesse
Rotman, marketing manager for Oregon Scientific.
</P>
<P>
   To use the technology, a radio owner enters codes to specify the
areas of interest. The codes identify individual counties or parts
of counties; they are available on NOAA's Web site (www.noaa.gov)
or through a toll-free number, (888) 697-7263.
</P>
<P>
   Information about fast-moving dangerous weather does not lend
itself well to Internet transmissions. By the time someone logs on
to a Web site to learn about an approaching tornado, the computer
could be swept up in the maelstrom. But that does not mean that
weather-information technology will remain stuck in the analog age.
</P>
<P>
   NOAA envisions that weather radio capabilities will eventually
be embedded in cell phones and pagers (which could automatically
sound an alert tone in an emergency). Digital televisions, which
are designed to carry data as well as high-definition pictures,
could also be easily programmed to turn themselves on when they
received the right signal so they could sound a tone and broadcast
a weather alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a devastating tornado hit on Palm Sunday 1994, Vice
President Gore said that he wanted weather radios to be as
ubiquitous as smoke detectors,'' said George Wilcox, a NOAA
spokesman. ``That remains our goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
