<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER30-COX     03-29 1638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Wow, talk about fund-raising
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush will collect a record-shattering $15 million in a
single night next month, lending his fund-raising prowess for the
first time to the Republican National Committee. Bush will headline
a black-tie gala in Washington on April 26 that will surpass the
previous one-day fund-raising record of $14 million set by his
former-president father in 1999, GOP officials said. And Bush's
one-day take will be nearly double the total President Clinton and
Al Gore together have been able to raise for the Democratic Party
in a series of fund-raisers across the country so far this year.
Turnout for the Bush affair is expected to be so large that it will
be held at a National Guard armory.
</P>
<P>
   YOU MEAN THEY MIGHT GET SOMETHING FOR THEIR MONEY?
</P>
<P>
   At a time when campaign finances are a ballyhooed presidential
issue, George W. Bush's chief political strategist is a featured
speaker Friday for a group that is under fire for its fund-raising
to help elect Republican attorneys general across the nation. Karl
Rove is slated to brief the Republican Attorneys General
Association meeting in Austin, Texas. The Center for Public
Integrity and Texans for Public Justice criticized RAGA for
soliciting corporate donations and not disclosing specifically who
donates.
</P>
<P>
   The watchdog groups contend that corporate donors are at least
potentially gaining influential allies and access, including access
to Rove.
</P>
<P>
   TOGETHER WHEN THEY NEED TO BE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and President Clinton plan to appear together April 15
at a fund-raiser in Beverly Hills for the Democratic National
Committee. The event's hosts will be the DreamWorks trio of Steven
Spielberg, David Geffen and Jeffrey Katzenberg. It'll be held at
Greystone, the fortresslike Tudor mansion built in 1928 and still
the largest home in Beverly Hills. Gore has kept his distance from
Clinton over the last few months. They last appeared at a
fund-raiser together Dec. 9 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   BEACHCOMBER RAKES UP MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton visited Laguna Beach, Calif., for a
$2,000-a-plate luncheon at a private beachside home that raised
$90,000 for her Senate campaign on the opposite coast. The event
was organized by Janice and Roger Johnson, friends of the Clintons.
Roger, a former CEO or Western Digital Corp., once headed the
General Services Administration. The Los Angeles Times said the
three-course menu included pecan-encrusted chicken stuffed with
goat cheese, shrimp-and-crab enchiladas, lemon creme brulee, Louis
Roederer Reims champagne and souvenir candy bars embossed with
``HRC.''
</P>
<P>
   NO LITMUS TEST FOR WHITMAN
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush suggested that support for abortion rights
wouldn't necessarily disqualify a potential running mate. Asked in
New Jersey on Wednesday about the chances of New Jersey Gov.
Christie Whitman as a possible No. 2, Bush said he isn't even
working on a list. But he also said their opposing views on
abortion were no reason ``we can't be pulling for the same thing,
being on the same team.'' Bush said, ``Good people can disagree on
the issue, and I understand that and I'm standing up here with a
friend of mine. ... I respect Governor Whitman's views, and I
respect her as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   REACH OUT AND TOUCH SOMEONE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and John McCain talked by phone for the first
time in more than two weeks. They talked about getting together,
but set no date. Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said his boss called
McCain from his car ``to reach out and to keep in touch and to be
in touch.'' The approach came after '96 GOP presidential candidate
Bob Dole lunched with McCain and then called Bush. Bush wants
McCain's endorsement, too, but McCain aides said it is too soon to
talk about that. Still, McCain adviser John Weaver said, ``The ice
has been broken.''
</P>
<P>
   SOME FAST TALKING NEEDED
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party opened a campaign to rally enough public
support to enable expected nominee Pat Buchanan to qualify for the
nationally televised debates this fall. Party Chairman Pat Choate
said the step-by-step effort over the next six months is designed
to generate a 15 percent showing for Buchanan in nationwide polls
by September. The private Presidential Debate Commission requires a
15 percent threshold in the polls in order to win a place at the
debates. That's going to be tough: A CBS News survey out Monday
showed Buchanan drawing just 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY AND THE REFORMERS
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party Chairman Pat Choate challenged Al Gore and George
W. Bush to prove they're really reformers by forgoing unregulated
campaign contributions. ``Either do the reform thing _ stop taking
soft money, stop taking PAC money _ or stop calling yourself a
reformer,'' Choate said at the National Press Club a day after a
federal judge upheld his chairmanship of the fractured
organization. But Choate said that stabilizing the party won't be
as difficult as skeptics contend: ``George Bush is going to have a
tougher time getting John McCain's endorsement than I am pulling
this party together.''
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY ON THE MOVE
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party is in another search for a nominating
convention site. Party Chairman Pat Choate and party founder Ross
Perot had fought to hold it in Long Beach, Calif., this summer.
Their opponents, supporters of Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, wanted
St. Paul. But while Reform Party members were fighting it out for
control, the Long Beach Convention &AMP; Entertainment Center was
rented to Jehovah's Witnesses immediately after the scheduled
convention. Now, not enough hotel rooms remain available, and there
won't be enough time to set up. Reform front-runner Pat Buchanan,
said sister and campaign manager Bay Buchanan, thinks Nashville,
Tenn., might be good.
</P>
<P>
   HANGING TOUGH
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore says the Republicans are chasing their tails pursuing
questions about his missing e-mail and staff calls to the IRS, but
he offered little additional explanation about either in an
interview with The Associated Press. ``I hope they spend a lot of
time and a lot of energy on this,'' he said with a confident grin.
The AP said Gore appeared untroubled by the newest inquiries and
their implications for his presidential campaign, and was vague
about their details. Question: How much did he use e-mail in 1996
to communicate about fund-raising? Answer: ``Didn't.'' Q: Just
didn't? A: ``Well, first of all, I don't know. But whatever is
there will be disclosed _ fully and completely.''
</P>
<P>
   EXAGGERATING THE EXAGGERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Monthly explored how the media has been treating
Al Gore: An ``examination of dozens of these articles, which
purport to detail the chief cases of Gore's exaggerations and lies,
finds journalists often engaging in their own exaggerations or even
publishing outright falsehoods about Gore.'' The publication blames
the New York Times, Washington Post and other major news outlets
for taking Gore's comments out of context. For one, making it look
like Gore had claimed to have discovered the toxic-waste problems
at Love Canal in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   GOING TO WASHINGTON FOR MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani raked in more than $100,000 at a Capitol Hill
fund-raiser for his Senate campaign in New York. John McCain put in
a brief appearance and nearly stole the limelight from the mayor.
McCain said he expects to campaign with Giuliani in New York next
week. ``I've been experiencing withdrawal from my defeat,'' McCain
joked. ``I've been spending all my time on the phone to Betty
Ford's place.'' Giuliani has raised $11.8 million for his race
against Hillary Rodham Clinton. She's raised $8 million, according
to federal election filings.
</P>
<P>
   REFORMERS AND PERCEPTIONS
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News poll found voters believe Al Gore is more interested
in changing the system than is George W. Bush. Thirty-nine percent
said Gore wanted the status quo; 57 percent said Bush did. But 43
percent said Gore had made decisions based on campaign
contributions and 35 percent said Bush had. The poll had a margin
of error of 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   CAN YOU PUSH A TAX INCREASE AND WIN?
</P>
<P>
   Republican challengers were expected. But New Hampshire Gov.
Jeanne Shaheen also will be facing a rival from her own Democratic
Party this year. State Sen. Mark Fernald, is planning to announce
formation of an exploratory committee. He's running, he said,
because the state is in a 27-month-old crisis over how to finance
its schools, and Shaheen has refused to consider an income tax as
the best source of money. Fernald is proposing an income tax
dedicated solely to paying for public education, and said that
polls showed that residents of New Hampshire, for all their
tax-hating habits, are ready for the idea.
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE PUSHING AND SHOVING
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson has been quiet about his future
political plans, but his lieutenant governor seems to be trying to
make Thompson's plans for him. Scott McCallum is telling voters
that Thompson, a Republican, will not seek re-election in two
years. McCallum, a likely Republican candidate for governor if his
boss steps aside, sent a fund-raising letter to 30,000 Wisconsin
voters recently saying that the governor is in his final term. The
New York Times said Thompson, apparently not pleased with the
letter, told his staff he wants to see McCallum's missives to
voters before they're sent.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
