<HEADER>
A1343 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     03-29 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV16-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., APR. 16, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The crawl space under our house has a dirt floor with poured
concrete walls.
</P>
<P>
   We recently found a bunch of small insect wings that somebody
told us was most likely a sign of termite activity in or around our
house.
</P>
<P>
   Could termites be a threat to our house, even though the walls
are concrete and there is no wood in contact with the ground?
</P>
<P>
   A: Termites can sense cellulose (their principal source of food)
many feet away, including the wood floor beams across the top of
your crawl space.
</P>
<P>
   They can't go up through concrete (unless there are cracks that
they can travel through) but they can and do build mud tunnels
along the surface of the concrete, as shown in the illustration.
</P>
<P>
   These enable the termites to travel from the ground up to the
wood beams without exposing them to light and air (which they must
avoid).
</P>
<P>
   If you see such tunnels in the crawl space there is a good
chance that there are termites present.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the winter deep piles of snow accumulate around the bottom
ends of our downspouts which then often fill up with water that
backs up into the gutters.
</P>
<P>
   This in turn causes water to back up onto the roof, causing
leaks in our ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think that if I cut off the end of each downspout to
about 12 to 15 inches above the ground this will prevent them from
getting buried in deep snow and so allow better drainage?
</P>
<P>
   A: The trouble with doing this is that when there is no snow,
water will come pouring out in a heavy stream that will wash away
soil and/or turf. The water will also not get carried away from the
house as it would do if it had seeped into the soil slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in freezing weather ice can still form on the inside and
cause a blockage that will cause water to back up.
</P>
<P>
   A better solution to your problem would be to either install
heating cables along the roof edges, or to have a roofer install
proper flashing material along the bottom three or four rows of
shingles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My old house has plaster walls and we removed the wallpaper
in our bathroom because we wanted to paint the walls and ceiling in
that room.
</P>
<P>
   However, under the wallpaper we found that part of the wall is
old plaster that is grooved (from tiles), part is dry wall and part
is wood that was put up to cover a hole where a former cabinet was
installed.
</P>
<P>
   What would you recommend to cover all this and end up with a
smooth surface suitable for painting?
</P>
<P>
   A: It sounds to me as though your best bet would be to install
drywall panels over everything, using panel adhesive and a few
nails (where necessary).
</P>
<P>
   You can fill and seal the seams with tape and joint cement sold
for this purpose, and you will end up with a smooth surface that
can be properly painted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My home has stucco on the outside that has been painted
several times with a popular type of powdered cement paint that is
mixed with water.
</P>
<P>
   I now want to repaint with a ready mixed latex paint that will
be simpler and easier to apply.
</P>
<P>
   Can this be done and, if so, are there any special preparations
or sealers required?
</P>
<P>
   A: It can be done, but you must remember that those old cement
paint finishes often develop considerable chalking and powdering as
they age, so you have to make certain all this powdery residue is
removed before painting _ preferably by power washing.
</P>
<P>
   Also, make sure you get rid of all peeling and flaking before
you apply the new coat of paint.
</P>
<P>
   Read the label on the can to determine if any type of sealer or
primer is required as a first coat.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``TERMITE MUD TUNNELS'' goes with this
column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Termites can sometimes build mud tunnels on the surface
of concrete walls to enable them to travel from the soil up to the
wood beams without exposing them to the air.
</P>
