METAL ROAD WARRIORS PANTERA UNDAUNTED BY GAP BETWEEN CDs 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ For most of the '90s, Arlington metal heroes
Pantera worked, and worked, and worked some more: Record a new CD,
tour for months on end, record a new CD, tour for months on end.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked. The band went from playing Joe's Garage to
co-headlining Ozzfest and opening for Black Sabbath during the
band's farewell U.S. tour. Several of their CDs, most notably
1994's ``Far Beyond Driven,'' ascended to the national pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   So when drummer Vinnie Abbott is asked about the long gap
between 1996's ``The Great Southern Trendkill'' and the new
``Reinventing the Steel,'' he laughs a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had too many opportunities to play,'' he says. ``We
toured `Trendkill' for two years, and then Black Sabbath calls, and
there's no way we're turnin' 'em down, and we get back and they
call again. And then Metallica called and asked us to play in
Mexico before 70,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   It was last summer before the band members finally took a
breather. They spent most of that time crafting ``Reinventing the
Steel'' but, ``If you condense it down, we recorded for four to six
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted time to go away from the songs and evaluate them,
instead of being under a really tight deadline like in the past,''
Abbott says. ``We got a chance to rewrite some songs and get what
we felt was the best of them. `Trendkill' was released when metal
was at an all-time low, and we made the most abrasive, brutal
record we could, and we'd gotten that out of our system. We didn't
feel like we really needed to do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   And true enough, ``Steel'' is not the hardest, most punishing
record in the Pantera catalog _ which is not a slight. There's
certainly enough of the band's pummeling thrash, but there's also
more than a hint of the blues-boogie of ZZ Top, as well as touches
of Thin Lizzy and Judas Priest, bands whose glory days predated the
'80s, when thrash came to the fore via Slayer, Metallica and
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The title is a play on Judas Priest's `British Steel'
record,'' Abbott says. ``Yeah, there are some songs that use that
shuffle vibe; it's been way overlooked, and not enough bands use
it. There's nothing wrong with us grabbing our roots. There's a
void for our music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trendkill'' addressed people jumping on musical bandwagons
lyrically; ``Steel,'' Abbott says, does it musically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much reinventing anything _ you can't reinvent the
wheel _ but it is about doing metal music played by people,'' he
says. ``So much music is made by drum loops and synthesizers. And
we're staying with hard music played from the core.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never follow this trend or that trend, and we've never
written a song for the radio. The record is 10 songs, a straight-up
rock record. It doesn't have to have drum loops or a drum machine
to make it sound like it's from the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The first single, ``Revolution Is My Name,'' would seem to prove
the point. The song is getting more airplay than anything else the
band has done, Abbott says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 'N Sync wasn't coming out this week, I think we'd have the
potential to have a No. 1 CD,'' he says. ``I think the support will
be there. I know there's people out there saying, `It's been four
years. Pantera's going to fail.' I just want to put that to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
