<HEADER>
A1347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PRESIDIO-2TAKES-625(2     03-29 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDIO-2TAKES-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDIO EVOLVING INTO HYBRID OF NATIONAL PARK AND PRIVATE
DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Optional sidebar at end of article . )  
 (bl)  
 By PATRICIA LEE BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The bugles are silent now. But in secluded vales
of eucalyptus and along once-dusty parade grounds lined with
red-brick Victorians, history still stands watch over the Presidio,
the windswept 1,480-acre former Army base wrapped by the headlands
of the Golden Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, when this National Historic Landmark _ about twice
the size of New York's Central Park _ became a national park, a
novel and much-debated experiment in preservation and park planning
has been underway at the 200-year-old military garrison. Once the
northernmost point of the Spanish Empire, it is a place that,
though part of the city, still feels like the edge of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Home to some 470 historic structures and now about 2,000 people,
the Presidio is, as one resident puts it, an ``oddball'' national
park _ the only one that is required by Congress to pay for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most of this vast, wild urban terrain of
wildflower-covered sea cliffs and extraordinary architecture _
officers' homes, cavalry stables, airline hangars, a psychiatric
ward _ is presided over by the Presidio Trust, a corporation
created by Congress that assumed control over 80 percent of the
park two years ago (the park service controls the rest).
</P>
<P>
   The Presidio is a delicate work in progress, and the trust a
controversial landlord. Born in a cost-cutting Republican Congress
that had seriously considered selling off this verdant jewel, the
trust has a dual, and, some critics say, impossible mission: to
preserve and protect the Presidio while making the park
economically self-sufficient by 2013.
</P>
<P>
   The Force may be with them. To create an ``economic engine''
generating around $5 million a year toward the $36 million the
trust estimates it will cost annually to maintain the park, the
filmmaker George Lucas, after a heated competition, recently won
preliminary approval to build a 23-acre Digital Arts Center on the
site of a dilapidated 1960s hospital. He envisions a ``Lincoln
Center West,'' he has said, a corporate campus, stylistically
drawing on Presidio military architecture that would house five
Lucas enterprises, including Industrial Light and Magic, his
special effects and animation company.
</P>
<P>
   Where enlisted men once exchanged war stories in mess halls,
there is now talk about ``synergy'' and wireless Internet access.
So far, about 80 historic structures have been rehabilitated. Among
the new tenants, a quirky array of businesses and not-for-profits,
are Fiber Futures (dedicated to tree-free paper), the Pachamama
Alliance (protects indigenous Amazon cultures), Trash Talk (a waste
prevention radio show) and the San Francisco Film Center, a group
of 14 film-related businesses and organizations that spent $6
million to restore a sprawling mission revival barracks built by
the WPA. The Sundance Institute is eyeing a mission revival post
theater as a potential cinema for independent films.
</P>
<P>
   Development has long been planned for the site. But some charge
that the Lucas proposal, along with the rental of some houses for
upwards of $5,000 a month, signifies the intrusion of a business
culture into a national park. And that the need to generate income
may irrevocably change the nature of the place, recasting the
Presidio as an elite city-within-a-city for wealthy individuals and
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Presidio, Congress looked at one thing and one thing
only _ how much would it cost?'' said Brian Huse, Pacific Region
director of the National Parks Conservation Association, a private
watchdog group. ``The question has become: Is it possible to
preserve the Presidio's natural and historic treasures unimpaired
with a mandate to raise money off the very resources we're trying
to protect?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``You can't help but be inspired here,'' said Mark Lindner, who
is the unofficial ``mayor'' of his neighborhood, called Simon's
Loop, and president of Food, Land and People, an environmental
organization. ``Being in the Presidio helps us to think bigger than
we normally think.''
</P>
<P>
   The juxtaposition of dotcoms like WebMD with the still-operating
Army PX, the Sustainability Art Show with Burger King _ not to
mention a nudist beach beside a string of bunkers with retractable
cannons _ gives the latter-day Presidio a sort of loopy charm. It
has always been a place of secret corners awaiting discovery, like
the tombstone in the pet cemetery that reads ``SKIPPER: Best Damm
Dog We Ever Had.''
</P>
<P>
   The country's longest continuously operating military base until
1994, the Presidio parallels America's growth as a world power.
Established in 1776 as El Presidio de San Francisco, an isolated
garrison (a fragment of the original adobe foundation can be seen
inside the Officers Club), the Presidio was briefly controlled by
Mexico prior to 1847. It was not then a place of beauty. ``The view
of the bay is fine from the high hills,'' noted a visiting Army
officer. ``But everything looks dirty and sandy; you cannot void
the impression that it is a mean country.''
</P>
<P>
   By the Civil War, it had become one of the nation's most
important military complexes, adding a central parade ground
surrounded by rows of enlisted men's barracks and Officers' Row, a
Civil War streetscape that survives essentially unchanged. The
Presidio was the central deployment point for the Indian campaigns,
the Spanish-American War and Pacific operations.
</P>
<P>
   Its winding, thickly forested landscape _ highly unusual for a
military base, where roads and terrain are usually flat and
straight _ was strongly influenced by the late-19th-century City
Beautiful movement. A foresighted Army engineer, Major William A.
Jones, planted the now-historic forests of eucalyptus, cypress and
pine in orderly rows, like soldiers in formation.
</P>
<P>
   A role model for the rest of the new Presidio is the Thoreau
Center for Sustainability, where some 50 organizations, most of
them nonprofit, have taken over a dilapidated hospital complex and
restored it according to green principles. At its heart is a
three-story white clapboard hospital (1899), where pressed tin
ceilings and Victorian banisters now commune with a glass canopied
entryway with photovoltaic panels.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest success story so far may be at Crissy Field, a 1921
airfield from which Army aviators and De Havilland biplanes once
patrolled the skies. After decades of environmental abuse, this
mile-and-a-half stretch of waterfront beside the Golden Gate Bridge
has been reborn as one of the country's most ambitious public
spaces, under the aegis of the National Park Service, which still
oversees the base's perimeter, and the Golden Gate National Parks
Association, which raised $32 million in private funds to reclaim
the site. It opens this year, replacing 70 acres of asphalt with a
recreated tidal marsh and native grasses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But this is not Yellowstone or Yosemite. The Presidio sits on
prime real estate in one of the world's most desirable cities. The
Lucas proposal, and the decision to rent historic buildings at
fair-market prices, have tenants like Dorie Heeren, 49, who is
married to a park service ranger, frankly worried. ``This is no
longer going to be a national park,'' Heeren said. ``My feeling is
that this will be a gated community.''
</P>
<P>
   The trust, overseen by a seven-member presidentially appointed
board, is obliged to follow federal environmental and historic
preservation guidelines. It was created based on Congress' view
that the scope and complexity of the Presidio required real estate
expertise that was beyond the National Park Service. Board members
include Donald Fisher, founder and chairman of the Gap, and William
K. Reilly, a former administrator of the Environmental Protection
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   But tensions have come to roost recently around the question of
who gets to live in the Presidio's 1,100 housing units. Right now,
the full-time Presidio community is a hodgepodge of park service
employees, office workers, students, park police and firefighters,
about 150 remaining military families (who will be phased out over
five years), and members of the public who can afford the rents,
which range from $450 or so for a student single to $6,000 a month
for an officer's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, said Jim Meadows, the trust's executive director, is a
community of people who live and work in the Presidio, from low
earners to CEOs _ people like Leanne Hoadley, 32, who lives in a
complex mostly for students. ``I live in an ugly apartment,'' she
said. ``But I'm looking over the Pacific Ocean 10 minutes from
Robin Williams' house.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say the trust has not established a strong connection with
the community or the National Park Service. ``There's an insularity
that's unfortunate,'' said Ed Blakely, a former board member who is
now dean of the School of Management and Urban Policy at the New
School in New York. ``The trust is hunkering down rather than
opening up.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand test case may be the Letterman Digital Center, as the
Lucas complex would be known, where local environmentalists and
others have raised concerns about traffic, water quality and the
appropriate scale and density for a national park. Speaking at the
University of California at Berkeley last month, Lucas said, ``I
think the park should stay a park.'' But he also observed: ``One of
the prominent issues is: What is the park? There's no Old Faithful,
there's no Half Dome, there's no Grand Canyon there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Radley, president of Lucasfilm Ltd., described a
corporate campus with underground parking for 1,500 cars, various
public spaces from cafes and coffee bars to a tuition-free digital
training institute, and a special-effects visual archive open by
appointment. ``No one wants to create Universal Studios at the
Presidio,'' he said. But in a private filmmaking campus some
foresee a waning of the soul and spirit of America's great national
parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a significant departure for a national park,'' said
Drummond Pike, president of the Tides Foundation, in the Thoreau
Center, which funds environmental and social justice projects. ``I
don't believe the public interest is served by having Lucas as a
tenant, though it will be nicer to have Lucas than a bunch of
venture capitalists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Meyer, a board member and Bay Area environmentalist, argues
that the Lucas plan, which must still pass various environmental
and design reviews, creates a financial entity that will keep the
rest of the Presidio intact as a park. She agrees with Meadows of
the trust, who says that preservation and self-sufficiency aren't
mutually exclusive. ``If we do our job right,'' he said, ``the
Presidio will look a great deal like it does today, with 20 percent
more open space and historic buildings all renovated to code.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Kennedy, a former director of the National Park Service,
noted that other parks aren't expected to pay for themselves and
that the trust concept, born of political compromise, must be
watched zealously. ``The question,'' he said, ``is how many
transactions do you consummate during the course of this process
toward self-sufficiency that you will regret later?''
</P>
<P>
   The park service, which will still be largely responsible for
interpreting the park to visitors, has recently brought in a team
from the Smithsonian Institution to help dream up new museums and
exhibits for the site.
</P>
<P>
   For all the future-thinking, wireless or otherwise, it is still
the past that will anchor this place, where soldiers' tombs peek
through eucalyptus trees. Sensitive reshaping is not for the meek,
but it seems well worth the fight to Richard Moe, president of the
National Trust for Historic Preservation, who is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not trouble free,'' he said, ``and there are and will be
inevitable tensions in the formula.'' The good news, he said, ``is
that nobody is talking about tearing down historic buildings, but
rather, preserving them in innovative ways.''
</P>
<P>
   At its best, the Presidio contains the architecture of
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many empty buildings here,'' said Marcia
Smith-White, head of the neighborhood association, ``you find
yourself thinking, `Why not?'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
