<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1351 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     03-29 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS AND WHITES, AND SHIPPING BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To avoid frivolous online purchases that I might later regret, I
follow a simple rule: Before buying, I close my eyes and conjure an
image of my husband. I see him arriving home in the dark and
tripping over yet another parcel that UPS has left on the front
stoop. Then with his endearing, trademark look of deep suspicion,
he sniffs the package before gingerly handing it to me and asks,
``This isn't a bomb, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   If I cannot imagine myself reassuring him in that same calming
tone I use to trick the baby into a bath that the adorable green
glass bunny dish I bought from Martha Stewart's Web site is
absolutely essential to the efficient functioning of our household,
then I know I should not buy the item.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this rule does not always work. I did recently sneak
the bunny dish into the house and, although charmed by his little
ears, I am disheartened that I so easily fell prey to temptation. I
know that it is better in the long run to restrict myself to those
practical products that we both agree are necessary to keep our
household running smoothly. And that is why I spent much of last
week searching online for wine.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't looking for just any wine but a red wine from the
Franciacorta region of Italy. In the hills near Lake Iseo,
Franciacorta often arrives at the table in a wide-mouthed ceramic
pitcher that would be more likely, in this country, to hold ice
water.
</P>
<P>
   The wine tastes like violets, only better because you do not
have to chew the petals, and is not widely available in the United
States. The reason for the scarcity, according to one of the
informative sites I found at www &QL; 
.cucina.italynet.com, is that the region's 179 producers of red,
white and sparkling wines inhabit only a small geographic area in
the province of Brescia (``number of hectares inscribed: 636.14'').
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for wine, I realized how much the Internet has spoiled
me. While I do not know how big a hectare is _ and frankly, do not
care _ I have come to believe that I can buy just about anything I
want, from just about any hectare on earth. Emboldened by past
triumphs (French cheeses and Chinese art posters come to mind), I
gamely spent a couple of hours hunting for an Italian wine seller
who would ship Franciacorta to me.
</P>
<P>
   I was not even deterred by the fact that most Italian Web sites
are written in Italian. That is, until after I pasted a phrase into
AltaVista's free Italian-English translator and realized that
instead of ordering wine, I had been on the verge of applying for
admittance to a sanatorium called the House of Clinical Private
Cure Saint Rocco di Franciacorta. As I glanced at the green bunny
on my bookshelf, I realized that an extended stay might not have
been a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Having failed to communicate my wishes in Italian, I turned,
reluctantly, to the small group of online wine retailers whose
headquarters are in the United States. I have in the past avoided
them for several reasons: the shipping costs always seemed
extremely expensive, it could take up to 10 business days to
receive an order and, most important, the selection had been
extremely limited by the regulatory climate in this country.
</P>
<P>
   That is a nice way of saying it is impossible to understand the
mishmash of state laws that govern liquor distribution. After
Prohibition, the federal government mandated a three-tier system of
distribution requiring wine producers to sell to wholesalers who
sell to retailers, and then put the states in charge of
implementing it as they saw fit.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some wines are for sale in some states but not in
others. Depending on where you live, half-bottles may be illegal,
or containers larger than a gallon may be illegal, or even asking
your neighbor to pick up a bottle for you while he is at the store
may be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, a bottle may have to pass through all three
tiers before it reaches your doorstep. In others, the wine may be
shipped directly, but the paperwork must pass through all the
tiers. And some states like Georgia and Utah and Tennessee so
heartily discourage direct shipments to individuals that online
wine sellers find themselves scratching their heads in trying to
devise legal routes around the roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   Even people who were paid to understand how the system works
told me they often could not. ``I genuinely try to understand the
market and I really gave up after talking to some people who knew
it well,'' said Ken Cassar, a senior retail analyst at Jupiter
Communications, an Internet research company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you know, the more involved and confusing it gets,''
said Michael J. Rusinko, a partner in Andersen Consulting's retail
division.
</P>
<P>
   Some brave online merchants like Wine.com, Winebins.com,
eVine-yard.com and Ambrosiawine.com have managed in the past few
months to put together more sophisticated shipping systems and can
send wine to 17 to 45 states, depending on the seller. With
inventories as large as 2,500 different wines (compared with the
400 or so that an offline store might stock), the selection is
getting much better.
</P>
<P>
   But then consider that the nation annually produces 10,000
varieties of wine under 2,100 brands. ``The promise of availability
on the Internet is not yet fulfilled when it comes to wine,'' said
Jeremy Benson, the executive director of Free the Grapes, a
coalition of consumers and wineries.
</P>
<P>
   If you visit an online wine seller, the first thing you should
do is look for a query box on the home page where you can type in
the name of your state. Had I done that at eVineyard.com, I could
have avoided the heartbreak of learning that the site sells
Bellavista's sparkling Franciacorta for $28.39 but not to people
who live in New York. None of the other three sites I visited
offered Franciacorta either.
</P>
<P>
   When I called Wine.com's chief executive, Bill Newlands, to
complain, he said: ``One of our wine merchants just came back from
a run-through of many of the European areas because we want to
broaden our selection. Don't lose faith.''
</P>
<P>
   I felt mollified enough to browse on Wine.com, where I found an
article called ``Twelve Little Known Facts About Wine,'' which
included the heartening news that dry wine may be a significant aid
in the treatment of obesity, the claim that the majority of
hospitals in California have wine on their menus and the reassuring
information that moderate drinkers are on average of higher
intelligence than nondrinkers.
</P>
<P>
   So how could I not take a serious look at the site's selection
of 15 labels from the Bonny Doon winery in Northern California?
Only 10 were available to New Yorkers, but that was nine more than
my local wine store usually offers. I ordered three bottles, for a
total of $40 (including $10.95 for shipping).
</P>
<P>
   At least I know UPS will not leave the box on the stoop for my
husband to trip over. The law requires a signature from a recipient
who is 21 or older. Those glass bunnies are starting to look better
already. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
