<P>
   ELIAN _ MIAMI _ Amid warnings of potential civil unrest,
relatives of Elian Gonzalez meet Wednesday afternoon with Justice
Department officials, who are insisting that they promise to give
up the 6-year-old Cuban boy if they lose a court battle. If the
family refuses, the federal officials say they will revoke custody
Thursday morning and spell out the procedure for returning Elian to
Cuba. (Williams, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PRAYER _ WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court's consideration of
the legality of student-led prayer before school football games
started off with a zinger from Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg. She
asked the attorney for a school district in Galveston County,
Texas, whether the prayer could consist of these words: ``Break
their necks, Make them wrecks, Buckle down, boys.'' After
Wednesday's hour of oral arguments, the court is expected to set
new national precedents by answering that question and others in a
decision to be handed down by early July. (Mollison, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-GAMBLING _ WASHINGTON _ With the Final Four a few days
away, two senators, with the support of the NCAA, introduced
legislation that would ban wagering on collegiate and amateur
athletic competition. (Turay, Cox News Service)
</P>
