<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's a Yearwood to remember
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her most mature album to date, the Monticello songstress
pours stunning depth and emotion into 12 tracks that weave the
accessibility of pop melodies with the earthy traditionalism of
country. Unlike many of today's crop of Nashville albums, this CD
isn't cluttered with cheaply sentimental electric piano and B-drama
strings. Most tunes are built on the beautiful simplicity of James
Taylor-esque acoustic guitar, with dobros, mandolin, fiddle and
pedal steel dripping around Yearwood's warm honey vocals like
barrel-aged whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   Like Linda Ronstadt in the '70s, Yearwood has a knack for
finding great writers and interpreting their work with nearly
hypnotic emotional seduction. When she wails ``Where are You Now,''
the lump-in-the-throat opening tune by Kim Richey and Mary Chapin
Carpenter, it's like reading a tear-stained diary. ``Some Days (Are
Better Than Others)'' is the weary resignation of the next morning.
Yearwood yodels Bruce Springsteen's ``Sad Eyes'' as a sweet
seduction, her voice flirting with a pedal steel like strangers
exchanging glances at a bar.
</P>
<P>
   On the title track Yearwood confidently sings, ``I offer no
apologies for the things I believe and say.'' Trisha, you don't
have to. Just keep it up.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY/POP
</P>
<P>
   `Real Live Woman'
</P>
<P>
   Trisha Yearwood/ MCA/12 tracks/ Our critic's grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
