<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1359 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-SENSE30-COX     03-29 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SENSE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thriller packs otherworldly wallop
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    ''c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A surprising, spine-tingling gem. Eight-year-old Cole (Haley
Joel Osment) can see ghosts, not the Casper variety, but restless
phantoms with their skulls blown open.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fascinating, odd film that speculates on what the
relationship between the restless dead and a liaison to the living
world might be. Plus, this film has the best, and loveliest,
last-act twist of last year.
</P>
<P>
   `The Sixth Sense'
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13 / Our critic's grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RELEASES:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Last Night'' (R) _ A lovely, offbeat look at the end of the
world. Unlike Hollywood's special-effects behemoths, Canadian
writer-director-actor Don McKellar treats the final apocalypse with
a dry wit and a sense of decorum that consciously tweaks that
nation's reputation for civility. A strong ensemble cast
(especially Sandra Oh) relate a variety of tales that are simple on
the surface, but cut deep. Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Crazy in Alabama'' (PG-13) _ An odd mix of civil rights
drama and Southern Gothic comedy that goes down just fine. The
movie splits time between the wild adventures of Lucille (Melanie
Griffith), who breaks out of a small Alabama town and heads West
and a graver story back home, about the struggle for civil rights.
Griffith does her best work since ``Working Girl,'' and hubby
Antonio Banderas' direction is professional, even if it doesn't
ever fully catch fire. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Body Shots'' (R) _ Here's proof positive that being
twentysomething isn't pretty. Eight party-hearty twentysomethings
(including ``Scream 2's'' Jerry O'Connell) traipse L.A. nightlife,
get superdrunk and start having rampant sex. The big question for
two in the group: was it consensual sex or rape? Quick, brutal and
ugly, the movie may not be any fun, but it sure delivers the
dramatic goods. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Omega Code'' (PG-13) _ The evangelical Trinity
Broadcasting Network made this big-screen film, starring Michael
York and Casper Van Dien in an overly talkative tale reminiscent of
the biblical book of Revelation. As a wealthy businessman, York
steals and uses a secret biblical code to effect a world takeover.
The hammy Van Dien plays a glam gadabout and motivational leader
who uncovers York's plot and must act to save the globe.The movie
has no obscenities, no sex, little blood and a minimum of bullets.
It also doesn't have much of a script. Priced to buy: $22.95 VHS,
$24.95 DVD. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Bob Longino write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
