<HEADER>
A1360 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS30-COX     03-29 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Shane Harrison and Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Opposite of H20''
</P>
<P>
   Drag-On. Ruff Ryders. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Two things can happen when you ride in on a noteworthy's
coattails: One, you can prove yourself worthy of the company. Or
two, you can do what Drag-On does, fade into the stars' backdrop.
Though this is his debut, the 20-year-old rapper is familiar
because he's performed on DMX's multi-platinum albums and Eve's
million-selling debut. They are all part of the Ruff Ryders, a
hip-hop circle known for both party anthems and the occasional
meaningful tune, neither of which Drag-On does well here. Like all
the Ruff Ryders' records, his has the keyboard-crafted horns and
strings that have become producer Swizz Beatz specialty. But apart
from DMX's hefty growl and Eve's confident approach, Drag-On's
commonplace delivery is hardly fire _ the ``Opposite of H20.''
</P>
<P>
   Drag-On will perform on the Ruff Ryders/Cash Money tour April 9
at Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Gung Ho''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Smith. Arista. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   As she first proved on her 1975 debut, ``Horses,'' Patti Smith
is, to borrow a phrase from Todd Rundgren, a wizard and a true
star. She coaxes pure gold from the base elements of rock 'n' roll
and poetry. That's a deadly combination in lesser hands, but Smith
is that rare successful alchemist. On her eighth album in 25 years,
Smith sounds re-energized. The rockers are up there with her best.
``Glitter in Their Eyes,'' with backing vocals from Michaal Stipe,
and ``Persuasion,'' highlighted by a sinuous guitar solo from
Smith's teenage son Jackson, compare favorably with Smith classics
such as ``25th Floor'' and ``Free Money.'' Her softer side comes
through in ``China Bird,'' a sweet lullaby that showcases Smith's
powerful vocals. Her imperfect, emotionally rich voice is a
remarkable instrument. Though it's rarely described as pretty, it
conveys more raw feeling than any '90s pop diva.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Music From and Inspired By Jesus: The Epic Mini-Series''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Capitol. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Pray for a miracle to get through this cloying collection of
sugar-pop tunes from the upcoming mini-series about the life of
Christ. With the exception of an opening fanfare by Patrick
Williams and the angelic ``Pie Jesu'' closing hymn from diva Sarah
Brightman, this CD sounds like Galillee has become an Orlando theme
park and we are visiting Holyland. Most tunes from artists such as
Edwin McCain (``Jesus, He Loves Me'') and Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish
(``City by a River'') are uninspired pop puff pieces. Edgier
tracks, such as a cover of ``Spirit in the Sky'' by DC Talk, sound
ridiculous when imagined alongside healing lepers and raising
Lazarus from the dead. The single from Leann Rimes, ``I Need You,''
is soaring up the pop charts, but sounds like typical
closing-credit melodrama. Sure, ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' used
rock and roll to tell the Christ story, but at least it was an
opera built on dramatic plot development and creative original
music. This is just Jukebox Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Shane Harrison and Miriam Longino write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
