<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1361 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-TAMAR30-COX     03-29 0190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-TAMAR30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tamar not resting on sister's laurels
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No wonder Tamar decided not to boost her solo debut by adding
the heft of her last name. All you have to do is fast forward to
the bridge of track number six, the ballad ``If You Don't Wanna
Love Me.'' The breathy vibrato and phrasings say _ shout, even _
that this is definitely someone who shares the same impressive gene
pool as R&AMP;B singer Toni Braxton. The difference between Tamar and
big sis is you're not likely to find Toni on a record with Jermaine
Dupri and Amil rapping, as Tamar is on ``Get None.'' And somehow
the profane language Tamar uses on ``No Disrespect'' would probably
be startling coming from her sibling, inoffensive enough to do a
Disney-produced Super Bowl halftime. But that's what distinguishes
Tamar not only from Toni but from many in her peer group who don't
offer this vocal, lyrical and musical range.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamar''
</P>
<P>
   Tamar. DreamWorks. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
