<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1364 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL30-COX     03-29 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oscar ceremony spurs a look at an earlier generation
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' showed a lot of flower power at
Sunday/Monday's Oscars (host Billy Crystal is right; the ceremony
is a two-day affair). That turned out to be oddly fitting since the
rest of the evening was dotted with reminders of the flower-power
generation, the young Turks of the '60s and '70s who've become the
Old Guard of the '90s. Consider a few of these connections and have
your own '60s film festival.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Angelina Jolie, winner of best supporting actress for ``Girl,
Interrupted,'' acknowledged her father, Jon Voight, saying,
``You're a great actor, but you are a better dad.''
</P>
<P>
   You could rent: ``Midnight Cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Voight won his Oscar (making them father-daughter Oscar-winners
like Henry and Jane Fonda, John and Anjelica Huston and Vincente
and Liza Minnelli) in the late '70s for ``Coming Home,'' but the
world discovered him in 1969's ``Midnight Cowboy,'' the first _ and
so far, only _ X-rated movie to be named best picture. As Joe Buck,
the naive hustler who comes to New York and is befriended by the
seedy but streetwise Ratso Rizzo (Dustin Hoffman), Voight is all
dumb-hick gullibility. The lessons he learns are about users and
losers, loyalty and the lies of the good life. Ironically, Voight
was not the first choice of director John Schlesinger. He wanted
Michael Sarrazin, but the actor was tied up on another project.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Michael Caine, winner of best supporting actor for ``The Cider
House Rules,'' earned a standing ovation and a place in future
Oscar clips with his gracious acceptance speech: ``I'm here to
represent you as what I hope you'll all be _ a survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   You could rent: ``Alfie.''
</P>
<P>
   Caine had made almost a half-dozen films before his star was
born in this madly mod, very Swinging '60s flick about a Cockney
hustler (hmm, do we sense a trend?) seducing and abandoning a
variety of women. However, unlike Joe Buck, Alfie is a knowing cad
whose life lesson is more like a comeuppance. But like Voight,
Caine wasn't first choice for the role. It was offered to his pal
Terence Stamp and in his memoir, ``What's It All About'' (taken
from the title song of you know what), Caine recalls trying to
convince Stamp to take the part. He didn't think he had a chance
because he'd failed to be cast in the play. Stamp refused and the
next thing you know, Caine had the role. And, a few months later,
his first Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best actor Kevin Spacey (``American Beauty'') cited the
inspiration he'd gotten from seeing Jack Lemmon in ``The
Apartment'' when he accepted his award. He was followed by his
director and fellow Oscar winner, Sam Mendes, who paid homage to
Billy Wilder. Who just happened to have directed Lemmon in ``The
Apartment'' (1960). Which just happened to win an Oscar for best
picture and best director.
</P>
<P>
   You could rent: ``The Apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmon is a faceless clerk in a huge Manhattan conglomerate who
realizes he can get ahead by making his tiny in-town apartment
available to a number of philandering senior execs (among them,
Fred MacMurray, who hasn't been this sleazy since he made ``Double
Indemnity'' for Wilder in the '40s; at the time of ``The
Apartment,'' he was more into his Disney ``Absent Minded
Professor'' mode). Shirley MacLaine is the pixieish, victimized
elevator operator who ends up at Lemmon's place more than once. An
interesting everybody's-a-critic aside: In the original script,
Lemmon has tickets to ``The Sound of Music,'' but Wilder saw the
musical while filming in Manhattan and hated it so much he switched
the tickets to ``The Music Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
