<SLUG> BC-BUYER'S-EDGE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Modern design trickles down to tickle the workaday world
 &HT;    By Michelle C. Brooks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Target has designs on you _ not to mention a stampede of other
big box stores eagerly following the lead. It's hard to miss the
design revolution taking place in the aisles of the nation's mass
merchandisers.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, Cindy Antila of Lilburn was perusing a
selection of clocks by Robert Abbey and Michael Graves at the
Snellville Target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love them! They are all beautiful, different, modern
designs,'' says Antila of the designer items. ``I come in to buy
one thing, and I could redo my house.''
</P>
<P>
   At Target, established designers including Graves, Abbey,
Philippe Starck and Peter Max are creating something of a design
sensation. Linens &AMP; Things, Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond and the Container
Store have joined the fray with designs by Umbra, Thomas Stender
and Guzzini. And don't forget Martha Stewart, whose designs for
Kmart have prompted some to call the store ``Kmartha.''
</P>
<P>
   What's with designer looks at discount prices?
</P>
<P>
   ``America is ready to recognize good design at a good price,''
says Michele Caniato, vice president of Culture &AMP; Commerce. As
Starck's U.S. agent, Culture &AMP; Commerce was instrumental in forging
the connection between the French designer and Target.
</P>
<P>
   Starck's first foray into mass-market design is a minimalist
chair reflective of his signature style. It has a $89.99 price tag.
</P>
<P>
   The design world is taking notice of the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've waited a long time for this,'' says Lorianne Justice,
director of the industrial design program at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Justice, who served as a juror in the Designs of the Decade
awards sponsored by Business Week magazine and the Industrial
Designers Society of America last winter, applauds U.S. efforts to
catch up with Denmark, Italy, Germany and Japan in design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really pleased that people are becoming attuned to having
things that are well-designed,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, good design means good business. In a market
saturated with retailers, cost-cutting alone isn't enough to
attract shoppers. You've got to stand out. ``Target has been on the
forefront of establishing a distinctive identity,'' says Candace
Corlett, a principal with WSL Strategic Retail consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affordable sophistication'' is what Gerald Celente, director
of Trends Research Inc., calls it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Target is giving people what they want before they know they
want it,'' says Celente.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it's a marketing strategy that works.
</P>
<P>
   Starck recently signed a contract with Target for about 100
items to be released in January of 2001. Wal-Mart has a deal with
Noritake Co. Inc. for a line of china, Epoch Exclusives, due to
arrive in select supercenters this spring.
</P>
<P>
   And look who else is hopping on the design trend bandwagon:
Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse. The company is working with
fashion designer Alexander Julian to develop a line of home
improvement products to hit stores this summer.
</P>
<P>
   10 items
</P>
<P>
   Stylish home accessories don't have to cost as much as your
monthly mortgage. Heck, a few are even less than a fill-up in your
SUV. Here are 10 of our favorite designer items found at mass
merchandising stores.
</P>
<P>
   Teakettle with red coach's whistle
</P>
<P>
   Price: $34.99.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy: Target.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: 1-800-800-8800 or www.target.com.
</P>
<P>
   Designer: Michael Graves Design Collection.
</P>
<P>
   Why: One of the first designs by Michael Graves to debut at
Target. Let's just call it the teakettle that started it all.
</P>
<P>
   Umbra Garbino Can
</P>
<P>
   Price: $6.99.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy: We found it at Linens &AMP; Things, but have also
spotted it at Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond and the Container Store.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.umbra.com.
</P>
<P>
   Designer: Karim Rashid for Umbra.
</P>
<P>
   Why: Fun, funky and functional, this wastebasket puts the spunk
in taking out the trash.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap Chic chair
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $89.99.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy: Target.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: 1-800-800-8800 or www.target.com.
</P>
<P>
   Designer: Philippe Starck.
</P>
<P>
   Why: It looks like modern art, but you can sit on it.
</P>
<P>
   OXO Good Grips Can Opener
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $12.99.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy: We found this at Linens &AMP; Things but have seen the
line at several other mass merchandisers.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.oxo.com.
</P>
<P>
   Designer: Smart Design Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Why: This line of kitchen tools, originally designed for people
with arthritis, is the winner of several design awards: Good
Housekeeping Good Buy Awards, Industrial Design Excellence Gold
Award, and the Arthritis Foundation Design Award.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Clock
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $49.99.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy: Target Stores.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   1-800-800-8800 or www.target.com.
</P>
<P>
   Designer: Robert Abbey.
</P>
<P>
   Why: Tiffany stained glass meets Frank Lloyd Wright architecture
in this stylish clock.
</P>
<P>
   WORX Stapler
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy: Office Max and other office supply retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Designer: ACCO brands.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.acco.com.
</P>
<P>
   Why: This handy little gizmo can sit vertically or horizontally.
Currently, it's featured in the Cooper-Hewitt National Design
Museum National Design Triennial.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle C. Brooks writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
