<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'N Sync batters Boys with record CD sales
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not content to merely break the Backstreet Boys' first week
sales record, 'N Sync's ``No Strings Attached'' smashed it to bits.
</P>
<P>
   The band's label, Jive, reports that the album sold a whopping
2.4 million in one week, dwarfing the 1.13 million first-week sales
of the Backstreet Boys' ``Millennium,'' a record set last May. ``No
Strings Attached'' also set a record when it topped the 1 million
mark its first day out. The album has taken up residence at the top
of the heap for online retailers Amazon.com and CDNow.com. With
numbers like those, a debut at the top of Billboard's Top 200 is
pretty much assured.
</P>
<P>
   At Tower Records in Atlanta, general manager John Montes reports
that the album has done ``very well,'' though not the
record-breaking numbers seen nationally. ``I kind of thought (the
numbers) would be a little higher. But, I think it's a record
that's going to have some longevity, especially with the tour
coming up. Because of the single (``Bye Bye Bye''), it crossed over
to a lot of people. Non-'N Sync listeners like that record.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen dreams are no slouch on the ticket sales front, either.
Ticketmaster reports selling more than 600,000 'N Sync tickets
nationwide on Saturday. In Atlanta, the two Philips Arena dates,
May 18 and 19, sold out in under an hour.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Jorunal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
