<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WONDERLAND30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crazy, mixed up world of psychiatric facility is fascinating in
ABC's new series ``Wonderland''
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC's ``Wonderland'' is more wondrous than wonderful, its
through-the-rabbit-hole title a wryly insufficient signal of the
madness to come.
</P>
<P>
   This is some high-test TV. Set in a New York City psychiatric
hospital, it's an exhausting, unsparing, gets-to-you drama that is
not your mother's ``E.R.,'' the NBC bulldozer that ``Wonderland''
has the awful luck to compete against tonight at 10.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Peter Berg (``Chicago Hope'' doc, ``Very Bad Things''
writer and director), ``Wonderland'' makes it clear early that
insanity is not restricted to the hospital's cracked clientele.
We're all nearly crazy, is the not-so-subtle theme, including the
psychiatrists whose high-stress urban lives have them teetering on
the brink.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the pressure of modern society becomes too great for a
person, when one's chemical dynamic becomes such that ... they
cease painting within the lines, they come to us,'' one doctor
explains of the wee gap between the so-called sane and insane.
``These are the shadow people _ the shadow people that project on
us their shadow and remind us just how tenuous mental health is.
They remind us how easy it is to slip.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's premiere is a nonstop series of people slipping all
over the place: one guy shoots five strangers in Times Square after
mistaking his role in the ancient struggle between Zeus and the
Titans; a patient wakes to see a small rhinocerous sniffing around
his sandals; a stockbroker driven by his divorce to slice his
wrists.
</P>
<P>
   Another day in ``Wonderland,'' which also includes one doctor's
child custody fight, another doctor's distress over gaining weight
during pregnancy and another doctor's girlfriend tearing up his
apartment when she discovers he's sleeping around. There are no
easy answers here to any easy questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You all right?'' one doctor asks another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm fine,'' says the doctor due at a custody hearing.
``I just have to play with my kids for about three hours under the
observation of a court appointed psychologist so I can be deemed
unfit as the primary guardian of my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked if you're all right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even close.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast is a cooly eclectic ensemble that never overplays a
note: Ted Levine (``Silence of the Lambs''), Michelle Forbes
(``Homicide: Life on the Street''), Martin Donovan (``The Opposite
of Sex''), Billy Burke (``Without Limits''), Michael Jai White
(``Tyson''). (Berg isn't in it.) They move between the personal and
professional without taking a breath; by the end of tonight you'll
know them better than your best friend.
</P>
<P>
   It can get a little headachey; when the camera isn't frantically
following the action, it's following a whim, darting up and down
and all around. Don't they know we're watching from a couch?
</P>
<P>
   It can also get disorienting. ``Wonderland'' is never unmanic,
unloud, unbureaucratic ... unmad. Either a phone's ringing or a
patient's babbling or a bureaucracy needs to be tamed.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Wonderland'' is also rarely less than brilliant at paring
down to a sharp dramatic point the politics, personalities and
insanity of this astonishingly realized world.
</P>
<P>
   It might be too much to fit inside network TV. The wonder is
that it made it at all.
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' tonight at 10 on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
