r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP30-COX     03-29 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peanut butter mix becomes frosting, fudge
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anne Aiken of Dallas, Ga., came through with the
``grand-tasting'' frosting requested by Bill Jefts of Rome, Ga. ``A
peanut butter lover's delight'' was Jefts' description of this cake
topping he had years ago and had been unable to duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   An Aiken family favorite, too, the recipe also works well as a
fudge.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Butter
</P>
<P>
   Frosting
</P>
<P>
   Makes frosting for a 9-inch layer cake or 13-by-9-inch sheet
cake (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 stick butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 jar (12 ounces) marshmallow creme
</P>
<P>
   1 heaping cup peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   Bring butter, sugar and milk to a boil in a saucepan. Set timer
for 5 minutes. Stir constantly. Remove from heat after 5 minutes
and add vanilla, marshmallow creme and peanut butter. Mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Frost cake while still warm and frosting is of spreading
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This also makes a fine fudge. Pour into a lightly greased
13-by-9-inch dish. Cool completely before cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (1/12th of recipe): 513 calories, 6 grams protein,
19 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 34), 83 grams
carbohydrates, 3 milligrams cholesterol, 236 milligrams sodium, 1
gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   V. Mendes of College Park hopes someone has a recipe she saw on
a TV cooking show for corned beef marinade in which the beef was
cooked slowly overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Dianna Thompson of Flowery Branch is looking for 9-Minute Fudge
made in the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Published recipes
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of a recipe previously published in the newspaper,
call the Stacks at 404-526-5668.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
