<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONES WITH NO CORDS BUT MANY OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although electronic mail is now the preferred means of
communications for many people, the telephone is still an
indispensable tool. How else are you going to call people to find
out if they got your e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   In the hopes of finding a new cordless phone that makes me feel
like a teen-ager again, I've been auditioning several of them for
my home office: the Plantronics 900-megahertz CT10 cordless headset
telephone, the Siemens 2.4-gigahertz Gigaset 2420 cordless phone
and answering system, and the 2.4-GHz BeoCom 6000 cordless phone.
Each has a particular appeal. Each has a particular annoyance. The
trick is to find the one that is least annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Why cordless?
</P>
<P>
   Cordless phones now outsell corded phones, which shows that
people like to stay connected to everyone without being connected
to anything. The newer models have many of the features of corded
phones, like built-in answering machines, Caller ID, speakerphones,
speed dialing, intercoms, paging and two-line support.
</P>
<P>
   But they also depend on batteries, which are finicky and require
recharging and special treatment. They are subject to interference
from nearby electrical devices, and, at least in their traditional
form, they are very hard to hold between one's shoulder and ear.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike cellular phones, which operate on their own wireless
networks, cordless phones require a nearby base station that is
attached to a conventional phone line. The handset communicates
with the base station by low-power radio waves. The frequency of
those waves determines, at least in part, how far the handset can
roam from the base and how clear the signal will be. The first
generation of cordless phones operated at frequencies from 43 to 49
megahertz and were often subject to interference from fluorescent
lights, electric toys and personal computers. They also had a
fairly short range and signals were often blocked by walls or
floors.
</P>
<P>
   An aside: Although the phone's range was short, the range of a
police scanner is long. A snoop with a scanner could listen in on a
neighbor's cordless conversations from up to a mile away. If the
neighbor had a baby monitor, a cordless phone set to the right
channel could eavesdrop on conversations taking place in the house,
even if the occupants were not using the phone. That is why we all
owe a debt of gratitude to the late actress Hedy Lamarr, who was a
co-inventor of spread-spectrum technology. (Completely true, as I
will explain later.) But I digress.
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of cordless phones moved to the less crowded
and more secure 900-MHz spectrum and provided greater range, up to
150 feet in a typical house, even through walls and floors.
</P>
<P>
   The newest cordless phones operate at 2.4 GHz, which in theory
provides neighborhood-roaming range, freedom from most interference
and the best voice quality. As pleased as I am with the 2.4-GHz
cordless phones, I do have a nagging concern each time I hold one
to my ear. After all, microwave ovens use the same frequency to
boil water.
</P>
<P>
   That is why I started my search with a 900-MHz headset phone,
Plantronics CT10, which will go on sale in early May. It is a
marvel of miniaturization, with a pager-size keypad that clips onto
a belt or slips into a pocket, plus a lightweight headset with a
boom microphone connected to the keypad by a thin wire.
</P>
<P>
   The CT10 includes a base station that takes up only a few square
inches of desk space. Once the system is set up _ it takes less
than a minute _ the user can roam around the office, house or yard
making and receiving calls while using both hands for work. The
headset is light enough to wear all day, and the combination is the
best hands-free, untethered phone solution I've found.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, the CT10 works with only a single phone
line, which is an annoyance in two-line houses. The numbers on the
keypad are dinky and require nimble fingers, but then, so do the
keypads on a cell phone. The most serious fault is that even a
gentle knock can separate the phone from its clip-on battery,
causing a lost connection or an unexpected tumble. If the tiny
phone should accidentally fall into some nearby liquid _ a cup of
coffee, say, or perhaps a toilet bowl, well, let me tell you, the
hisses, crackles and pops of a small, drowning phone are truly
pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   The Plantronics CT10 will cost $129.95 when it reaches stores
this summer, and if I were to buy one, I would also buy the
extended warranty plan that offers a replacement phone in case
something unfortunate happens to the original.
</P>
<P>
   In the form-over-function category, the BeoCom 6000, from Bang &AMP;
Olufsen Telecom of Denmark, has the most striking design. The base
station is a brushed aluminum pyramid, and the handset, with its
asymmetric but ergonomic swoop, is a brilliant and comfortable
design. This is functional desk sculpture, and it is priced like
fine art, too. The base station and one handset cost $475,
available only from B&AMP;O dealers, and additional handsets are $325
each. The system can handle up to six handsets so rich people can
scatter extra sets all over the house.
</P>
<P>
   However, like other B&AMP;O audio products, the BeoCom 6000
practically cries out to be carefully placed in isolation on an
uncluttered desk, which immediately puts it at a disadvantage in my
office. The sound quality is superior, the 2.4-GHz range is
excellent, and it has a modest list of features, including built-in
caller ID, a 200-entry phone book and the ability to forward a call
to a specific handset.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although the BeoCom 6000 is a work of art, it lacks the art of
work. It is a single line device, and it comes with a belt clip but
no headset option. When properly docked with its base station, the
Caller ID display is facing backward and downward, away from the
user, which means that you cannot just glance to see who is
calling. In short, it is not a phone for the home office, unless
you wear Armani suits around the house.
</P>
<P>
   The best balance of style, function, features and cordless
convenience was the Siemens Gigaset 2420, a 2.4-GHz system. It is a
two-line, corded and cordless modular phone and answering system
that can use as many as eight cordless handsets, which means
big-business phone features for a small office, home office or big
family system.
</P>
<P>
   The base station and one handset cost about $350; extra handsets
are $120 or so apiece. Its many features include a digital
answering machine that answers each line separately, a digital
speakerphone, three-way conferencing, call transferring, intercom
and a room monitoring function. If you subscribe to the phone
company's extra services, the Gigaset supports Caller ID and Caller
ID on Call Waiting, as well as distinctive ringing for voice and
fax calls. Unlike the BeoCom, the handsets work with standard
hands-free headsets.
</P>
<P>
   My two main complaints about the Siemens Gigaset are that the
answering system has just one voice mailbox per line, and that with
so many features, the instruction booklet should have been less
confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, for my needs, the Siemens Gigaset 2420 answered the
call. Best of all, it employs frequency-hopping digital
spread-spectrum technology, which randomly changes channels 100
times a second. It is as secure from eavesdroppers as a cordless
phone can be.
</P>
<P>
   And that takes us back to Lamarr, the German beauty who died
earlier this year at age 86. During World War II, the actress, a
foe of the Nazis, and the composer George Antheil conceived and
patented frequency-hopping spread-spectrum technology as a way to
control remote-control torpedoes and protect them from radio
jamming. Today, spread-spectrum technology is the basis for many
forms of modern communication, including secure cordless phones.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
