r e BC-FILM-SUCHALONGJOURNEY     03-29 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SUCHALONGJOURNEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOURNEY' WORTH MAKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chances are that actor Roshan Seth's name won't ring any
immediate bells, and odds are that you won't catch his new movie,
``Such a Long Journey,'' until it arrives on video, because it's
receiving such a limited theatrical release.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. As Gustad Noble, the beleaguered hero of ``Journey,''
Seth gives the year's first great performance as a man who tries to
maintain his pride while everything around him is falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journey'' is set among Bombay's Parsi community in late 1971,
shortly before one of India's wars with neighboring Pakistan. The
movie is as dense and disheveled as the city, but Seth's Gustad _
his bank-clerk uniform of white shirt and modest tie always neatly
in place _ stands out above the mess. We first see him chanting a
Parsi prayer before the movie becomes noisy; it's a bit of calm
before a rambunctious storm.
</P>
<P>
   Gustad is nostalgic for the old days, probably because the new
ones are bringing him nothing but grief: His son is suddenly
balking at a longtime family plan to attend a technical college;
his young daughter becomes ill; his wife no longer automatically
supports his every decision and has started consulting a
neighborhood mystic in an attempt to fix family problems. Outside
Gustad's house, the city is planning to knock down a wall that
separates his home from people who use the street as a public
bathroom. Gustad comes up with a solution to the sanitation
problem, with the help of a street artist, but he has a harder time
dealing with progress. And things just get more difficult when he
agrees to do a favor for an old friend, an estranged uncle who has
become involved in espionage.
</P>
<P>
   This is an ambitious movie, and it's so thick with plot that it
can be a little hard to get a grip on. It's interested not only in
Gustad's family and work problems, but in the Parsi situation in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   Director Sturla Gunnarsson, an Iceland native who grew up in
Canada, shows a keen eye for other cultures in his adept direction,
but his smartest choice was in casting. The film works because Seth
provides it with such a strong anchor: prideful, a little angry,
ambitious, scheming, weary and pained. The supporting cast is
strong, especially Soni Razdan as Gustad's wife and Om Puri as a
mystery man, but they all stand in Seth's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a Long Journey'' has so much going on that it might be
tough to take in all at once. Seeing it might involve a long
journey, but if you're in the right neighborhood, drop in and check
it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a Long Journey'' is not rated, but is probably an R
equivalent for profanity, sexual situations and nudity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Such a Long Journey'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Sturla Gunnarsson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Roshan Seth, Om Puri &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not rated &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
