<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAN LINKED TO MISSING ATHEIST APPEARS IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gary Paul Karr, the only person charged with the
alleged kidnapping and murder of atheist leader Madalyn Murray
O'Hair, appeared in federal court here Wednesday to get a
court-appointed lawyer in advance of his scheduled arraignment next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Karr, of Novi, Mich., was indicted late last year on charges
that include kidnapping, robbery and extortion in connection with
the 1995 disappearance of O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray, and her
adopted daughter Robin Murray O'Hair. He spent the last year
incarcerated in Detroit on federal gun charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in good spirits. He's going to plead innocent,'' said
David Weber, who represented Karr at the hearing before U.S.
Magistrate Stephen Cappelle.
</P>
<P>
   Cappelle appointed Thomas Mills of Dallas to represent Karr in
the upcoming trial before U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks. He also
set Tuesday as the tentative arraignment date and said he would
hear arguments then about setting bond for Karr.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a dark green jumpsuit from the Bastrop County Jail and
orange laceless slippers, Karr was clean-shaven and pallid and said
little during the brief hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement he made last year to the FBI, Karr admitted a
limited, non-criminal role in the 1995 disappearance of O'Hair and
her children, claiming he had been hired by David Roland Waters,
O'Hair's former office manager, to assist the family in fleeing the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities say Waters was the mastermind of the plot, but
the Austin man has not been charged with the disappearance of the
three. He is serving a lengthy state prison term for stealing
$54,000 from the atheist organization that O'Hair headed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities believe the O'Hair family was kidnapped,
held for a month in San Antonio, robbed of $500,000 in gold coins,
and then killed and dismembered. The three bodies have not been
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not charged with murder but he's been charged with
committing a crime of violence that resulted in the death of
another person, so you can draw your own conclusions,'' Assistant
U.S. Attorney Gerald Carruth said of Karr.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, Karr came to Texas from Florida in
late 1995 and over the next two months played an integral role in
the abduction of the family, including renting vans and hotel rooms
and accompanying Jon Murray on various financial errands in San
Antonio and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of the five counts, Karr, 52, faces a life term in
prison. Talks between Karr's lawyers and Carruth over a possible
plea bargain in exchange for his testimony against Waters have so
far proved fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side, however, ruled out future conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never say never,'' Carruth said when asked about a possible
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That depends on the government,'' Weber said. ``It depends on
what type of plea they might offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the government is believed to have amassed a strong
circumstantial case against Karr and Waters, they do not have a
witness or the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Fry, a Florida man who also was allegedly involved in the
abduction and murders, was himself killed. Fry's headless, handless
body turned up on a Dallas riverbank two days after O'Hair and her
children were last seen in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair became widely known in the 1960s for her campaign against
prayer in schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
