<HEADER>
A1394 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-TAG-POPULAR     03-29 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-TAG-POPULAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once shunned for the superstar, tag teams growing in popularity
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Eds. WITH WRESTLING-KOWALSKI, WRESTLING-TAGTEAMS
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What goes around comes around. After years of playing second
fiddle to the superstars, tag team wrestling is becoming the rage
once again.
</P>
<P>
   Teams like the Hardy Boyz, the Dudley Boyz, Christian and Edge,
and Degeneration X's Road Dogg and Billy Gunn have led a resurgence
in the WWF of tag team wrestling. The popularity of the teams have
allowed matchmaker Vince McMahon to increase his roster and improve
the quality of matches.
</P>
<P>
   The irony here is that McMahon was instrumental in tearing apart
the tag team division.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s and early 1990s, McMahon's company was
struggling to find a top singles' wrestler. Hulk Hogan's ride at
the top was starting to fade and no lone wrestler seemed to grab
the audience's attention. So McMahon turned to his most popular tag
team, the Hart Foundation _ Bret Hart and Jim Nienhart. McMahon
split them up and Hart grabbed the fans' attention and was soon the
WWF champion. He would reign for several years, but soon ran out of
competition. That's when McMahon split up another successful tag
team, The Rockers _ Shawn Michaels and Marty Jannetty, and worked
Michaels to the point that he and Hart were the two most popular
wrestlers in the WWF.
</P>
<P>
   Their successful careers, coupled with the relative failure of
Nienhart and Jannetty, made tag team wrestling a risker venture for
the wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, McMahon has used the tag team arena to bring in
new talent from other organizations (the seven-time ECW tag
champion Dudleys), allow his young talent to find their niche
(re-packaging of the Hardy Boyz) and sell a lot of merchandise (the
very successful Rock-n-Sock connection).
</P>
<P>
   Such success makes it financially possible for group wrestling
to grow. In fact, WWF's main event for its Super Bowl of
pay-per-view, ``Wrestlemania,'' will feature more than half the
matches with three or more combatants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
