<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1395 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-TAGTEAMS-CO     03-29 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-TAGTEAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: With WRESTLING-TAGTEAMS, WRESTLING-KOWALSKI,
WRESTLING-TAGPOPULAR
 &HT;    Dynamic duos once were the main attraction in wrestling
 &HT;    By Kevin Braun
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In biblical times, anyone searching for an expert on pairs would
probably look up Noah. In pro wrestling, the most likely source of
expertise on twosomes is Captain Lou Albano. And with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Albano has managed 19 tag-team champions, including several duos
that held the titles more than once. And he even wore a tag-team
championship belt around his own ample waist at one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked for guys that were a good size and could work
together in the ring,'' said Albano, now a 67-year-old grandfather
(he has 13 grandchildren to go with his four grown children). A
rundown of Albano's list of champions reveals that ``good size''
might be putting it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest were the Wild Samoans, Afa and Sika, whom
Albano said would probably come out on top if all his tag champs
competed against each other in a tournament. Then there were the
Moondogs, Rex and King, whom Inside Sports magazine once described
as ``640 pounds of gap-toothed mayhem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Moondogs stowed menacing-looking bones in their corner, and
they inevitably were used as weapons. During the Moondogs' reign,
Rex was replaced by Spot, and a wrestling magazine said that Rex
had to step aside because he had come down with rabies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Albano's other teams that reached the tag title included
The Executioners (Killer Kowalski and Big John Studd), The
Blackjacks (Mulligan and Lanza), The Valiant Brothers (Tarzan Tyler
and ``Crazy'' Luke Graham) and (after Albano became a ``babyface''
manager) The British Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Tag-team matches aren't as prevalent today, and it seems the
wrestling associations focus their promoting on individual stars.
Because tag-team wrestlers have to sacrifice some of their
individuality, observers might think the emphasis on singles
matches is ego-driven.
</P>
<P>
   But Kowalski, who donned a mask as Executioner No. 1 when he and
Studd teamed to win the titles in the 1970s, offered a simple
explanation for the reduced role of tag teams: Singles matches are
a bigger attraction. ``Whatever draws people,'' he said. ``Pack
those houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Kowalski, now 73, was also a tag team champ in the 1960s with
400-pounder Gorilla Monsoon. He won singles titles all over the
world, but he said it wasn't difficult for him to shift to tag
teams, and there were never any clashes. ``Not with me and my
tag-team partners. We were always good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kowalski, who at 6-foot-9 was an inch shorter than Studd,
didn't sacrifice much of his ego to be part of the team. ``I was
the image then,'' he said. ``I was the star then. It was me the
people were noticing. My whole career was like that. Make the
people notice me.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to getting the fans' attention, Kowalski also got
the referee's attention, distracting him by climbing on a
turnbuckle. And while the ref's back was turned, Kowalski's partner
would pummel the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   That distraction factor is especially important in tag matches,
and having Albano outside the ring as a manager made his teams even
more effective. Albano's verbal skills didn't hurt, either. ``He's
a good talker,'' said Kowalski. ``He can talk anybody out of their
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Albano, who wrote ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to Pro
Wrestling'' with Bert Sugar, also sees quick tags in and out as
important. ``You don't want to let your partner get tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Before turning to managing and commissioning himself as ``The
Captain,'' Albano earned his stripes in the ring. He and Tony
Altamore, known in tandem as The Sicilians, held the belts in the
1960s. During their first television interview, he and Altamore
held up black-gloved hands and shouted ``Mafia!''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that interview aired, Albano said, they were paid
a visit, and ``We were told there's no such thing as Mafia.'' Of
course, he and Altamore quickly agreed with that observation.
</P>
<P>
   Even when he was managing, Albano donned the tights
occasionally. Once when Sika got hurt, he joined forces with Afa in
a Wild Samoans match. With a chuckle, Albano acknowledged that his
abilities were best used outside the ring. ``I was never a great
wrestler,'' he said. ``I did mostly running.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all his tag champs were heels, and Albano was reviled.
``Albano is a bum'' was a frequent chant at matches, and he clasped
his hands over his ears in an attempt to tune it out. But the fans'
view of Albano changed after ``Wrestlemania I.'' He was managing
the Fabulous Moolah, the longtime women's champion, and Moolah lost
the title to Wendy Richter, who had rocker Cyndi Lauper in her
corner. The Captain had to apologize to all women, and all of a
sudden he was a good guy.
</P>
<P>
   He's still a good guy. Among the personal appearances he makes
are at churches or to steer youngsters away from drugs. ``If you do
drugs, you go to hell before you die,'' he tells them. Overall, his
schedule is lighter, even with the promotional appearances and
occasional movie roles. ``I don't want to do it full time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He's troubled by the current state of wrestling, in terms of the
violence, profanity and sexual nature. ``The kids look at that and
it sets a bad example,'' he said. ``You've got 5-year-olds holding
their finger up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Albano said he's dropped 100 pounds, but those who think they
might not recognize him don't have to worry: The trademark rubber
bands still adorn his face, even around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
