<HEADER>
A1397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COURT-PRAYER30-COX     03-29 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PRAYER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COURT QUIZZES ATTORNEYS ON PRE-GAME PRAYERS
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Supreme Court justices plunged eagerly Wednesday
into a Texas controversy over the constitutionality of allowing
student-led prayers before public school football games.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour of coping with the justices' barrage of swift,
pointed questioning, lawyers and their supporters on all sides of
the issue agreed on one thing: They expect a complex new national
policy to emerge in the decision the court is due to hand down by
early July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we draw the line?'' Justice Stephen Breyer asked his
colleagues at one point in the arguments over the first case the
court has taken up on pre-game prayers.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the three attorneys quizzed by the justices was
willing to predict how a majority of the justices will balance the
public school students' right to freedom from religious coercion
with their rights to free speech and religious expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way to tell'' what the court will decide, said
Washington attorney Jay Sekulow of the American Center for Law and
Justice, a veteran of eight appearances before the high court.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's case, he defended the policy of his client, the
Santa Fe Independent School District in rural Galveston County,
Texas, to allow the pre-game prayers.
</P>
<P>
   The district's procedures start with an election in which
students decide whether to have a pre-game ``invocation or
message,'' followed by an election in which students pick a student
who then writes and delivers the message to the crowd over the
loudspeakers just before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, do we allow a message, even if it's a prayer,
to be given before a football game,'' Sekulow said. ``I think the
answer is yes, if it's student-initiated and student-led.''
</P>
<P>
   But that amounts to letting ``majoritarian rule'' impose prayer,
which would violate the rights of the smaller number who object,
argued Anthony Griffin, the Galveston attorney from the American
Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) who represented the Catholic and
Mormon families who challenged the district's policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we made our points, and I hope the court accepts
them,'' Griffin said as the rival lawyers circled the plaza in
front of the court, giving post-battle sound bites to more than two
dozen camera crews.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn appeared on behalf of
himself, Gov. George Bush of Texas and officials from seven other
states who intervened on the district's side.
</P>
<P>
   If the court clarifies a jumble of decisions that now lead to
constant lawsuits over school-related prayers, school districts
could lower their legal bills and concentrate on educating their
students, Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we hope for is a clear decision here, to trace a pathway
of neutrality neither favor nor disfavoring religion, but at the
same time not requiring a policy of official hostility to religious
expression,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The court session opened with traditional solemnity, all nine
justices standing behind their chairs as a clerk intoned, ``God
save the United States and this honorable court.''
</P>
<P>
   But the mood quickly lightened after they sat down.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg shot her opening zinger at Sekulow.
She asked him whether the student-written prayer could have this
wording: ``Break their necks, make them wrecks, buckle down,
boys!''
</P>
<P>
   That would violate the school's requirement that the student's
message, whether or not it is a prayer, promote good sportsmanship,
Sekulow said. He denied, however, that this meant the school
officials were unconstitutionally controlling the text of a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The election of the student message-giver might turn into
campaigns between one student claiming to be well-trained in prayer
and another claiming to oppose prayer in schools, said Justice
Anthony Kennedy, a frequent swing vote when the court is closely
divided. He said that could have the unfortunate effect of ``the
school becoming a forum for religious debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Another justice asked Cornyn whether the policy might sometimes
lead to the election of a student whose pre-game message would be,
``Religion is bunk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Respectfully, your honor, we just don't know,'' the attorney
general replied.
</P>
<P>
   When Griffin said his clients didn't want to be forced to listen
to another religion's prayer, Chief Justice William Rehnquist told
the ACLU attorney, ``Nobody has to go to a football game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Griffin said one of his clients is a band member who, like
team members and cheerleaders, is required to attend the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is anybody forced to be a cheerleader, football player or band
member?'' the chief justice asked.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin drew appreciative laughter from the hundreds of
spectators by replying, ``When you're a teenager, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
