<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SELENA-COX     03-29 2086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELENA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Echoes of Selena's spiritBy Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ This is the time of year when this
popular Texas beach city could more aptly be named
Selena-by-the-Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Curiosity seekers and fans of the late, great Selena stream here
in honor of the Grammy-winning Tejano music superstar who was shot
to death by her former fan club president in a
blink-and-you'll-miss-it interstate motel.
</P>
<P>
   They come every day of the year. But springtime is High Selena
Season.
</P>
<P>
   This is when hearts open fullest for the young Hispanic woman
whose musical talent, work ethic, belief in education and stance
against drugs and gangs turned her into a wholesome role model.
</P>
<P>
   Friday is the fifth anniversary of Selena's murder, and April 16
is Selena's birthday. This year, she would have turned 29.
</P>
<P>
   So let's grab the official Selena map handed out by the Corpus
Christi Area Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau and join the pilgrimage
to the land of ``Bidi Bidi Bom Bom'' (Selena's catchiest pop
lyric).
</P>
<P>
   The map, with ``SELENA'' labeled in half-inch letters that shout
like blinking neon, shows four sites to visit:
</P>
<P>
   Selena's grave.
</P>
<P>
   Selena's life-size memorial statue.
</P>
<P>
   The recording studio run by her family.
</P>
<P>
   Selena's Etc., the boutique and salon opened by Selena.
</P>
<P>
   But enterprising Selena fans use their own knowledge or tips
passed along by other buffs they meet to add more locations:
</P>
<P>
   Selena Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Selena's house.
</P>
<P>
   Selena murals.
</P>
<P>
   Her former school.
</P>
<P>
   And, the most uncomfortable location of all: the Days Inn where
Selena was shot in Room 158 shortly before noon on March 31, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the management has changed the room numbers so the room
where Yolanda Saldivar shot Selena now is Room 150. But the new
numbering system apparently doesn't fool enough memento-seeking
fans. The number plaque on Room 150 looks cheaper than the plaques
on the other rooms _ as if it has to be replaced more often.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a warm welcome at the Days Inn at exit 3A off
Interstate 37 (Navigation Boulevard). Only registered guests are
allowed to linger, and, one day last week, a clerk at the front
desk became angry when we asked one Selena question too many.
</P>
<P>
   The woman said hotel staff had bent over backward to be nice to
Selena fans for four years, but now they are weary of the
inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's dead! She's dead! I don't care anymore!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's off the record,'' she tried to add before
disappearing into a back room.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Barbara Schultz, who placed the 911 call when
Selena collapsed in the motel's lobby five years ago, said
employees have been instructed to answer ``no comment'' when Selena
questions are asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotel has gone to a great deal of trouble to move on, and
we would prefer that we not even get mentioned,'' Schultz said.
``This hotel really had absolutely nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough bad memories. Let's head for the water.
</P>
<P>
   The most-visited Selena site is her memorial statue along the
Corpus Christi bayfront promenade. The bronze statue captures
Selena in a reflective moment, leaning against a white pillar and
holding her microphone on her left leg. She's clad in her trademark
tight pants and bustier under a short leather jacket with
decorative studs. Guitar-shaped earrings 4 inches long hang from
her ears, and cowboy boots boost her 5'5'' frame to 5'8''.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vivacious entertainer of international fame had begun to
mainstream a style of music called Tejano when her life tragically
and senselessly ended,'' the inscription reads in part.
</P>
<P>
   It concludes by saying, ``Selena Quintanilla-Perez was a role
model all communities need for their youth, and we are proud she
was a citizen of Corpus Christi.''
</P>
<P>
   Four signs ask fans to refrain from writing on the Selena
monument, but the request goes ignored. The white pillar Selena
leans against is covered with scrawled messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like your songs Babe,'' says one. ``To My Beautiful Angel
Selena, you have given me so much inspiration and because of that
me and my sisters dreams are coming true. ... I love you so much,''
says another.
</P>
<P>
   Mike and Kim Malloy topped off a vacation in South Padre Island
last week by bringing their 5-year-old daughter, Cheyenne, to see
Selena's statue. Cheyenne became a pint-sized Selena fan a few
years ago after her parents rented the video of ``Selena,'' the
movie starring Jennifer Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just fell in love with it. We had to buy a microphone and
move the coffee table out of the way,'' said Mike Malloy.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyenne has watched the movie dozens of times, and still
doesn't understand why anyone would kill Selena. ``Why did that
happen?'' Cheyenne asks her parents. Her father said it's difficult
to explain why Saldivar shot Selena during a dispute over whether
Saldivar had been stealing money from Selena's company. Saldivar
was sentenced to life in prison for the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a long time ago to a child. Right now, all Cheyenne
wants is a photo of her parents posing by the Selena statue. She
grabs the family camera, backs up, instructs her parents where to
sit and pops off her souvenir picture.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at the Selena map shows another site just a few miles
away. It's Seaside Memorial Park, where the music star is buried.
</P>
<P>
   Here, fans leave flowers and trinkets of affection: seashells,
pennies, colorful stuffed animals, Happy Meal toys from McDonald's
and even Pokemon cards. Some have carved or written messages on the
young mesquite tree at the head of her grave marker.
</P>
<P>
   Selena's grave is adorned with a flat bronze sculpture of
Selena's face, and the eyes are hollowed out. When it rains, fans
say, water runs like tears from her carved eyes. One day last week,
a tiny gold crucifix had been placed in one of Selena's hollow
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In a five-minute period, three families drive up to pay
respects.
</P>
<P>
   Three-year-old Lorena Garcia runs up and checks out the gifts
that have been left. She squats down and lovingly rubs her small
hand over Selena's sculpted face.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not old enough to know what's going on, but she likes
her songs,'' said Lorena's father, Eddie Garcia of Mathis, 30 miles
from Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   Selena is a good role model for his daughter because the singer
lived in the barrio and grew up to conquer the international stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``And everyone she met, she touched that person in some way,''
Garcia said. ``It means something to come back (to her grave) and
try to keep her music alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's head to the Selena museum.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Q-Productions, the recording studio run by Selena's
father, often bump into the well-known stage dad who pushed Selena
and her brother and sister into a family band when they were young.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Quintanilla works the phones and walks the halls in his
trademark straw hat and dark glasses. After Selena's death, he
gathered her self-designed performance dresses and award gowns and
put them on display in a museum at the back of the production
studio.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the free museum are Selena's Grammy and other music
awards, her red convertible Porsche with the 1995 car registration
forever frozen in time on the front windshield, scores of
photographs of Selena on stage and with fans. On the back walls are
Selena's dress designs drawn when she was 15. Quintanilla even
threw in a newspaper clipping showing her as the second-place
winner in a fifth-grade spelling bee.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dad first wanted to put the museum up, I thought it was a
great idea. But at the same time it was real difficult going in on
a day-to-day basis for me,'' said Selena's older sister Suzette
Quintanilla Arriaga, who played drums in Selena's band. ``It was
very depressing for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you see people come in and you see how happy they
are, and then you start to look at it from their perspective and it
becomes cool,'' she said. ``It becomes easier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum is definitely a celebration of her life,'' she
said. ``It keeps her alive in our own little way.''
</P>
<P>
   Selena's parents plan no official activity on the fifth
anniversary of their daughter's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think of Selena every day, and that's one day I don't want
to remember,'' Quintanilla said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death is a painful thing, but time heals,'' he said. ``You'll
never get over that, but you eventually have to cope with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Selena's family understands that the singer's music was so
powerful that it continues to attract young and old fans to Corpus
Christi. But the adulation becomes a problem when the Quintanillas
visit Selena's grave. So many fans have tried to photograph the
family at the grave site that they do not visit it as often as they
would like.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are days you just can't,'' said Marcella Quintanilla,
Selena's mother. ``Other days you're drawn.''
</P>
<P>
   She worried last week about when she would get the next
opportunity to visit the grave and not be bothered. She wants to
place new flowers there so people coming to town next month for the
new Selena musical will see fresh bouquets rather than weather-worn
blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, the Selena store beckons.
</P>
<P>
   Selena's sister oversees the boutique and salon that Selena
opened in 1994. (And she recently opened her own children's
clothing shop called MoonChild, which was what Selena called her
designs when she was a teen.)
</P>
<P>
   Selena, Etc. stocks clothing with the Selena label, which also
can be found in many Sears and JCPenney stores. The boutique also
sells Selena T-shirts, dolls, perfume, postcards, hats, calendars
and more. Across the room, customers can get a manicure or a
haircut.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, 13-year-old Letty Rico from Dallas was all smiles as
she sat in a salon chair and had her hair styled by Celia Macias, a
makeup artist and stylist who was hired by Selena when the shop
opened. Macias used to give Selena manicures.
</P>
<P>
   Letty is shy and overwhelmed that she is in Selena's shop while
Selena's sister is there. Letty's brother, Alex, 11, asks Suzette
Arriaga to autograph the Selena calendar his family just bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans keep constantly coming in,'' Arriaga said. ``They
come here because they love her and they want to know more about
her.''
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke, the boutique was so full of customers that they
bumped into one another as they browsed.
</P>
<P>
   Let's move to the next stop on the Selena tour: the barrio.
</P>
<P>
   Selena and her husband, guitarist Chris Perez, lived in a tidy
brick home next door to Selena's parents in the Molina barrio, at
705 Bloomington St. On the other side of her parents lived Selena's
brother. All three brick houses now are rented out by the
Quintanilla family.
</P>
<P>
   After Selena's death, a suggestion was made to rename
Bloomington in honor of Selena, but then someone realized that
Yolanda Drive, a chilling reminder of her killer's first name,
would intersect with the street named Selena, and the idea was
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks from Selena's former house is the 7 Till Late
convenience store, where a mural of Selena was painted after her
death by students at nearby West Oso High School.
</P>
<P>
   One of the store's clerks, Mario Gomez, knew Selena and has
become a one-man fan machine. He volunteers to paint over the
graffiti on her bayfront statue, offers to take fans on free tours
of the Selena sites and every year helps organize a Selena tribute
on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, as in previous years, the street in front of the
convenience store will be blocked off and a stage will be erected.
Then, one by one, little girls dressed like Selena will sing her
songs and perform for the barrio crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, who as a then-security guard at the Days Inn stood watch
at Room 158 after Selena's murder, hands out maps to the Selena
sites and often leaves a bundle of them tucked into the Selena
statue by the bay. He keeps a photo album at the convenience store
that includes all the pictures he took during the filming of the
``Selena'' movie, in which he had a bit part as a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   He stills tears up when he remembers the superstar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd meet so many people from all over the
world,'' he said. ``I've met people from Africa, Canada, Peru,
Puerto Rico, Hawaii and Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say I knew her and that I considered her my neighbor,''
he said. ``I took it real hard. She meant a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gamino at dgamino(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
