<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-POWELL-2TAKES(89     03-29 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-POWELL-2TAKES(890)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTHONY POWELL, 94, NOTED ENGLISH NOVELIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: An abridged version, OBIT-POWELL-ABRIDGED, and excerpts from
Powell's writings, POWELL-SAMPLER, are also being sent.)  
(lh) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anthony Powell, the English novelist whose 12-volume work, ``A
Dance to the Music of Time,'' is regarded as one of the great
achievements of postwar literature, died Tuesday at his home near
Frome, Somerset, England. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Powell _ his name rhymes with Lowell _ was a contemporary of
Evelyn Waugh, George Orwell and Cyril Connolly. He began his career
as a novelist in the early 1930s chronicling the doings of
Britain's bright young things and their Bohemian hangers-on. His
middle period, the quarter-century that begins with the publication
of ``A Question of Upbringing'' in 1951, was given over to ``A
Dance to the Music of Time,'' an ambitious effort to trace the
fortunes of a group of schoolmates from their adolescence at the
outbreak of World War I to old age in the Britain of the early
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In his late 70s and early 80s, Powell surprised critics by
producing two novels that compare favorably with the best of his
work, ``O, How the Wheel Becomes It!'' and ``The Fisher King.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Powell was born on Dec. 21, 1905, in Westminster,
London, the only child of an Army officer, P.L.W. Powell, and the
former Maude Welss-Dymoke. At Eton, he fell in with a
self-consciously arty set that included Harold Acton and Henry
Green.
</P>
<P>
   By temperament, Powell was an observer rather than an actor.
``He is a little different from the other boys, and I feel that his
quiet reserve and dignity may prevent him from having any strong
influence upon others when he gets to the top of the house,'' one
teacher reported to his parents. ``I hope this may not be so, but I
sometimes fear that they may regard him as superior and coldly
critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell himself later said, ``The whole of my life at Eton was
spent in well-deserved obscurity.''
</P>
<P>
   After earning a third-class degree in history at Balliol
College, Oxford, where his classmates included Acton, Waugh, Green,
Connolly and Graham Greene, Powell found work as an editor at
Duckworth, the house that published four of his five early novels,
beginning with ``Afternoon Men'' in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   While at Duckworth, he published Waugh's first book, ``Rossetti,
His Life and Works,'' and, through a series of reissued novels,
helped spur a revival of interest in Ronald Firbank.
</P>
<P>
   In his early fiction, Powell deftly satirized the social milieu
he knew best _ the minor aristocrats, members of the polite
professions and their artistic hangers-on, whose lives were defined
by parties, outings and the ever-present specter of boredom. It is
telling that ``Afternoon Men,'' which relates the story of a
mild-mannered junior museum official's search for love in a
rapacious, shallow world, begins and ends with an invitation to a
party.
</P>
<P>
   Like Firbank, Ernest Hemingway and E.C. Cummings, three early
influences, Powell made use of clipped, often inane dialogue to
create a distinctive brand of comedy that relied, as he later put
it, on ``purposeless exchanges that are their own purpose,'' made
meaningful by ``an undercurrent of innuendo and irony.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Afternoon Men'' was followed by ``Venusberg'' (1932), ``From a
View to a Death'' (1933) and ``Agents and Patients'' (1936), a
novel whose title neatly suggested one of Powell's great subjects,
the ineffectual, cultivated Englishman out of step with a world
shaped by cut-rate mass culture and cutthroat commerce, here
represented by a film director and a psychoanalyst.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936 he left Duckworth to write movie scripts for Warner
Bros. of Great Britain. A brief trip to Hollywood in search of
screenwriting work led nowhere, although he did meet F. Scott
Fitzgerald. In 1939 he published ``What's Become of Waring?'' a
comic novel about a publishing house's search for its prize author,
who is reported missing but whom no one in the company has ever
actually met.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's novels, although critically well received, sold only a
few thousand copies each, and his only steady income came from book
reviews for The Daily Telegraph and The Spectator. His financial
situation eased in 1934, when he married Lady Violet Pakenham, a
daughter of the fifth Earl of Longford. She survives him, along
with their sons, Tristram and John.
</P>
<P>
   With the outbreak of World War II, Powell relied on his family
connections to enlist with the Welch Regiment, in which his father
had served. He spent two years as an infantry lieutenant before
transferring to the Intelligence Corps, with which he served in
London until 1945. He was a liaison officer with the Allied Forces
in exile, achieving the rank of major and earning the Czechoslovak
Order of the White Lion and the Belgian Order of Leopold II.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Powell resumed work on ``John Aubrey and His
Friends'' (1948), a biography of the 17th-century antiquary, who,
Powell wrote, stood out among his contemporaries in his
appreciation of ``the oddness of the individual human being.'' With
Aubrey, Powell shared a fascination with genealogy, peculiar
anecdotes and gossip.
</P>
<P>
   When Powell returned to fiction writing, he made a decisive
break with his early manner. In a later interview, he said: ``I
decided that the thing to do was to produce a really large work
about all of the things I was interested in _ the whole of one's
life, in fact _ for I have no talent for inventing plots of a
dramatic kind in a comparatively small space.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He embarked on a comprehensive social study of Britain's
upperish classes, a nebulous social stratum consisting of minor
aristocrats, the members of the ``right'' professions, assorted
Bohemians and academics. This genteel milieu, defined more by
schooling and temperament than by money, is seen through the
writer's alter ego, Nicholas Jenkins, a detached, even passive,
observer who takes up a position on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Although the series includes hundreds of characters across some
70 years of time, three fellow classmates play major roles in most
of the books. Peter Templer and Charles Stringham, whose
aestheticism and eccentricity hark back to a more genteel age,
struggle to find a place in the new England. Kenneth Widmerpool, an
object of scorn to his classmates, emerges as a powerful, decisive
force, the right man for a mean and mercenary age.
</P>
<P>
   The title and inspiration for the series came from Nicolas
Poussin's painting, ``A Dance to the Music of Time.'' The painting,
which Powell saw in the Wallace Collection in London, depicts four
outward-facing nymphs dancing in a circle. Tantalizingly ambiguous,
their dance suggested to Powell the way that time and circumstance
bring people together and then push them apart. ``An almost
hypnotic spell seemed cast by this masterpiece on the beholder,''
Powell later wrote. ``I knew all at once that Poussin had expressed
at least one important aspect of what the novel must be.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next quarter-century, beginning with ``A Question of
Upbringing'' in 1951 and concluding with ``Hearing Secret
Harmonies'' in 1975, Powell worked on this grand project, its
underlying pattern ruled by what he called ``the inexorable law of
coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Buyer's Market,'' the second volume of ``Dance,''
Nicholas Jenkins muses on chance and fate, the connection of
opposites and the different worlds one encounters in life: ``Nearly
all the inhabitants of these outwardly disconnected empires turn
out at last to be tenaciously interrelated; love and hate,
friendship and enmity, too, becoming themselves less clearly
defined, more often than not showing signs of possessing
characteristics that could claim, to say the least, not a little in
common; while work and play merge indistinguishably into a complex
tissue of pleasure and tedium.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Powell rejected complicated interpretations of
``Dance,'' insisting it dealt with ``things as they are.'' He
disliked suggestions that he based his characters on particular
people. He worked hard at making sure that every title, every name,
every place was accurately set down.
</P>
<P>
   While working on ``Dance,'' Powell served as an editor and
contributor at several publications. After the war he took a
part-time position with The Times Literary Supplement, supervising
the fiction reviews, and from 1953 to 1959 he was the literary
editor of Punch. He also continued to review regularly for The
Daily Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's later style, described by one critic as Proust rendered
into English by P.G. Wodehouse, was feline and elliptical,
alienating some admirers of his earlier work. ``Some critics
dislike its subtle elaboration of manner, preferring the crisper,
more immediate effect of the prewar comedies,'' the critic Bernard
Bergonzi wrote of ``Dance.'' For admirers of the series, Powell, in
abandoning the quick, satiric strokes of his earlier novels,
created a far more complex and compelling social drama. In his
precise delineation of English manners, he searchingly explored
emotional territory that he had treated flippantly before. In 1997,
the series was adapted for television by Hugh Whitemore.
</P>
<P>
   From 1976 to 1982, Powell completed four volumes of memoirs,
under the title ``Keep the Ball Rolling,'' which include memorable
vignettes of friends like George Orwell, Cyril Connolly, Malcolm
Muggeridge and Kingsley Amis. Three volumes of diaries, covering
the years 1982 to 1992, were published between 1995 and 1997 under
the title ``Journals.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell also edited or contributed prefaces to several volumes
that shed light on his literary influences, from the high-society
novels of Disraeli and Ouida to the works of Firbank and the Swiss
essayist Henri-Frederic Amiel. A selection of his criticism was
collected in ``Miscellaneous Verdicts'' (1990) and ``Under Review''
(1992).
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 he was made an honorary fellow of Balliol College at
Oxford University. He received honorary doctorates from Oxford and
from the Universities of Sussex, Kent, Leicester, Bristol and
Wales. In 1977, he was named an honorary member of the American
Academy of Arts and Letters. From 1962 to 1976, he served as a
trustee of the National Portrait Gallery in London.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was named a Commander of the Order of the British Empire
in 1956 but refused a knighthood in 1973. A knight, he wrote in his
journal, was ``rather an awful thing to be.'' He was happy to be
made a Companion of Honor in 1988, however. ``Rather cheered,'' he
wrote in his journal, ``as CH eminently respectable order (65
members), which most people have never heard of. Those who have
know its standing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
