<HEADLINE>
ANTHONY POWELL, 94, NOTED ENGLISH NOVELIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: A   longer version, OBIT-POWELL, and excerpts from Powell's
writings, POWELL-SAMPLER, are also being sent.)  
(lh) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anthony Powell, the English novelist whose 12-volume work, ``A
Dance to the Music of Time,'' is regarded as one of the great
achievements of postwar literature, died Tuesday at his home near
Frome, Somerset, England. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Powell began his career as a novelist in the early 1930s
chronicling the doings of Britain's bright young things and their
Bohemian hangers-on. His middle period, the quarter-century that
begins with the publication of ``A Question of Upbringing'' in
1951, was given over to ``A Dance to the Music of Time,'' an
ambitious effort to trace the fortunes of a group of schoolmates
from their adolescence at the outbreak of World War I to old age in
the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In his late 70s and early 80s, Powell surprised critics by
producing two novels that compare favorably with the best of his
work, ``O, How the Wheel Becomes It!'' and ``The Fisher King.''
</P>
<P>
