<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, March 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow fell in parts of upstate New York on Wednesday as a
slow-moving low-pressure system over eastern Canada delivered a
brisk flow of air to the interior Northeast. Conditions will
gradually improve across the Northeast on Thursday, with ample
sunshine expected near the coast and brighter conditions over the
interior.
</P>
<P>
   A late-season snow will blanket parts of the southern Rockies
and southern Front Range on Thursday as a jet stream disturbance
intercepts a moist flow of air from the east. Farther west, breezes
from the east will bring unseasonably warm air to the coast of
Central California. These offshore winds will direct unseasonable
warmth to the coast of Southern California on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will end over the Southeast on Thursday, though residual
moisture in the lowest parts of the atmosphere will cause clouds to
linger for much of the day.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TORNADO SHIELD
</P>
<P>
   Urban environments have often been called shields against
tornado formation. Yet, in the past few years, strong twisters have
been observed in Nashville, Tenn., Birmingham, Ala., and Salt Lake
City. The two twisters that ripped through Fort Worth on Tuesday
further challenged this notion. There is some indication that the
roughness associated with tall buildings interferes with the
establishment of the circulation of weak tornadoes. But when a
potent mixture of atmospheric ingredients come together, cities are
not safe from tornadoes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
