A1409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-OSTEOPOROSIS30-COX     03-29 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTEOPOROSIS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OSTEOPOROSIS PANEL DECLINES TO RECOMMEND MASS SCREENINGS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A panel of experts on osteoporosis recommended
Wednesday that physicians follow ``individualized'' strategies,
rather than routine bone density screenings, in deciding whether
patients should receive preventive therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Osteoporosis, characterized by loss of bone calcium, places
millions of Americans, especially older women, at increased risk of
devastating fractures.
</P>
<P>
   However, a consensus panel convened by the National Institutes
of Health said too little is known about the benefits of mass
screenings to recommend them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to learn more about screening, which population should
be screened and how to best do this,'' said Anne Klibanski, a
Harvard University professor of medicine who chaired the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Two types of bone density examinations, one involving ultrasound
on the heel and the other using an X-ray of the femur just below
the hip, have been shown to detect increased risk of osteoporotic
fracture, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   However, it noted that among women between 50 and 59, an
estimated 750 bone density tests would be required to prevent a
single fracture over a period of five years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the committee said doctors and their patients should
decide on case-by-case bases whether to use the scans, it declined
to recommend guidelines for physicians to use in those decisions.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 10 million Americans suffer from osteoporosis, and
another 18 million have bone mass low enough for them to be
considered at risk of the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Among elderly persons, a fracture can have devastating
consequences. Dr. Scott Boden of Emory University in Atlanta, a
member of the panel, noted that surveys indicate 80 percent of
women over 75 ``would rather be dead than have a bad hip
fracture.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel called for research on a wide front, including genetic
factors leading to osteoporosis, the manner in which widely-used
glucocorticoid drugs appear to induce the disorder in some persons,
and the effectiveness and long-term safety of various drugs used to
prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   Although hormone replacement therapy, in which postmenopausal
women take estrogen, is a common treatment, the panel said more
information is needed on how estrogen alone or in combination with
other drugs reduces the incidence of fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Newer drugs, including a class known as biphosphonates, have
been shown to increase bone density, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists said there is no evidence that so-called ``natural
estrogens,'' such as those found in food supplements and some plant
products, such as soy, reduce osteoporotic fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Weight training, even in elderly persons, increases bone mass.
Non-impact exercise, such as walking, does not build stronger bones
but may be valuable in improving balance and preventing falls.
</P>
<P>
   The panel called for increased emphasis on diet and exercise
among children, noting that only about 25 percent of boys and 10
percent of girls between the ages of 9 and 17 meet National Academy
of Science recommendations for daily calcium intake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Childhood is also a critical time for the development of
lifestyle habits conducive to maintaining good bone health
throughout life,'' the panel said in its final ``consensus
statement,'' noting that ``cigarette smoking, which usually starts
in childhood, may have a deleterious effect on achieving bone
mass.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
