<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI COURT SAYS PALESTINIANS EVICTED FROM CAVES CAN RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that
hundreds of Palestinian cave dwellers from the West Bank who were
evicted by the army more than four months ago can return while an
investigator examines their right to live there.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, in response to a petition by Israeli human rights
lawyers representing scores of the evicted Palestinians, overruled
military and defense officials who had refused to allow the cave
dwellers to return.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred Palestinians were expelled from cave hamlets in
the rocky hills southeast of Hebron on the grounds that they were
living in a military firing zone. Most were evicted on Nov. 16, a
few days after militant Jewish settlers were removed from Maon
Farm, an illegal outpost nearby. The settlers had demanded that the
Palestinians also be removed.
</P>
<P>
   The evicted Palestinian families found shelter in tents and
empty buildings in neighboring villages. The Israeli human rights
group B'Tselem said that it had counted more than 700 people who
were displaced.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli military government in the West Bank, known as the
Civil Administration, argued that the cave-dwellers could be
legally evicted from the firing zone because they were not
permanent residents in the area, but seasonal farmers who lived in
the caves a few months a year while maintaining homes in the
neighboring village of Yatta.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians asserted that they had been living in the caves
year-round for generations, grazing sheep and farming nearby land.
They said they had no other homes, noting that they had been forced
to move into makeshift shelters in nearby villages.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel headed by Chief Justice Aharon Barak ruled
that the cave-dwellers could return while their residence rights
were examined by an investigator accepted by the Palestinians and
the Israeli authorities. The results of the examination are to be
submitted within two months from the appointment of the
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the Palestinians, Shlomo Lecker, said the court's
decision to return the cave-dwellers to their homes was ``an
unusual victory, because the court rarely orders a change in the
status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   The umbrella council of Jewish settlements in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip called for the immediate return of the evicted settlers
to Maon Farm. ``Any other decision by the government means racial
discrimination,'' a spokesman for the council said. A group of
settlers who tried to reach the site a few hours later was turned
back by soldiers.
</P>
</TEXT>
