<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DORA GALITZKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring Treat
</P>
<P>
   Q. A bowl of steamed fiddleheads is my idea of the perfect
spring celebration. I have only a few ostrich ferns, and it takes a
lot of fiddleheads to make the meal worthwhile. If I harvest all of
the fiddleheads, will it kill the ferns?
</P>
<P>
   A. Fiddleheads, or crosiers, are a spring delicacy that makes it
worthwhile getting mud on your shoes. As the new fronds of the
ostrich fern, Matteuccia struthiopteris, reveal themselves, but
before they unfurl, they form a tightly curled spiral that really
does resemble the head of a violin or a bishop's staff.
</P>
<P>
   They are tender and delicious, but don't celebrate to excess.
Dr. John Mickel, senior curator of ferns at the New York Botanical
Garden in the Bronx, said not to cut more than three or four from a
fern crown, which typically produces about a dozen fiddleheads. If
you harvest them all, the plant will send out new fronds, but
perhaps at a price. Producing the second set reduces the supply of
nutrients stored in the fern's rhizome, weakening the plant. A
droughty summer or a hard winter and the fern, especially an older
one, may not make it. Since ostrich ferns spread rapidly by
underground runners, have patience. In a few years, you'll be able
to move from clump to clump, harvesting all the fiddleheads you
want without endangering the plants.
</P>
<P>
   Look for upright, dark green fiddleheads clothed in a few tan
scales to make sure they really are ostrich ferns. Other ferns have
fiddleheads that are tough and more scaly or woolly, and won't make
your meal cause for celebration. Ostrich fern fiddlehead scales rub
off easily when you wash them. Take special care to avoid royal and
bracken ferns, which Mickel said are highly carcinogenic. As with
any food gathered from nature, don't eat anything you can't
absolutely identify.
</P>
<P>
   Shady Garden
</P>
<P>
   Q. Living in a wooded area, we have very little sunshine for
gardening. I have an area, facing west, where very little grass
grows, mostly moss. I want to put in a small garden, just for shade
plants, but have heard that any ground that had moss will not be
good soil for a garden. Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A. Just because the moss is outcompeting the grass doesn't mean
nothing else will grow there. The most likely reason the moss is
winning is the shade, which grass dislikes. While some mosses like
full sun, most prefer shade and need moist, reasonably
well-drained, acidic soil. Primitive plants going back nearly 400
million years, mosses have survived this long because they figured
out how to take advantage of their niche. Because their leaves are
only one cell thick, they can absorb all the oxygen and moisture
they need directly from the air. Not needing the water-drawing
roots of more advanced plants, they grow a form of rhizoid that is
just a holdfast, letting them cling to rocks and other hard
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   You can remove the moss and the struggling grass and plant a
traditional shade garden, but why not take your cue from nature and
encourage the moss? A visit to the John P. Humes Japanese Stroll
Garden in Mill Neck, on Long Island, will open your eyes to the
extraordinary beauty of a well-designed garden that uses moss and
other shade plants to their best. The garden is open on weekends
from the end of April to the end of October. For information: (516)
676-4486.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage moss to fill in areas, take some of your existing
moss and mix it with water in a blender, then spread it around and
keep the area moist. Adding buttermilk, which is often mentioned,
isn't necessary unless you want the moss to grow on a rock or
container. The buttermilk isn't a nutrient or an acidifier, it just
dries into a glue that lets the moss adhere to a slippery surface. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(at)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
