<HEADLINE>
A LEGENDARY HARLEM CLUB PREENS FOR ITS SECOND ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Nonsubscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I hope that's not the renovation,'' said a young woman wearing
a black crochet cap and light purple lipstick, a leopard-print
satchel on her shoulder, as she peered through the glass of the
Lenox Lounge into the dark glitter of the unlighted bar. A nicked
and scuffed cafe chair with a zebra-stripe seat stood by the
window, the photographer Art Kane's ``Jazz Portrait, Harlem 1958''
above it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks the way it was,'' the young woman said, rolling her
eyes and walking down Lenox Avenue toward 124th Street. What she
could not see were the 22 cans of oven cleaner that took three
millimeters of gummed nicotine off the gold mirrors and chrome
trim. What looks antique now had been an authentic dirt-brown. The
fake fur is fresh.
</P>
<P>
   After eight months of renovations and $600,000, the Lenox
Lounge, the legendary Harlem night spot built in 1939 _ the year
Billie Holiday first sang ``Strange Fruit'' _ is reopening Thursday
night: the sole surviving Art Deco club interior in New York City.
Holiday, a regular, sat in with musicians there in the 1940s; her
table in the Zebra Room beyond the bar, beneath the mock-zebra
wallpaper that gave the room its name, was the first on the left
through the swinging doors. She is said to have loved Art Deco, as
genuine as glamour ever got. Malcolm X was also a customer.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the lounge has been a featured location in
fashion magazines, music videos and movies, from Madonna's 1995
``Secret'' to the remake of ``Shaft,'' starring Samuel L. Jackson,
opening this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers will appreciate the fact that Shaft hangs out at
the Lenox Lounge,'' said John Singleton, the film's director.
``It's a Harlem landmark; he's a very uptown kind of cat. You think
about Holiday, or Billy Eckstine, walking through those doors, way
back in the day. I couldn't resist having a glass of Hennessy
between shots.''
</P>
<P>
   If the new Lenox Lounge looks faded, it's a fade-in, not a
fade-out.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin M. Reed, a retired policeman and postal worker who has
owned the lounge since 1988, decided last year to bring the club,
which he said was struggling to stay profitable, back to life. His
strategy was to restore its glass-finned, turbine-shaped lighting
towers, black and white hide walls, Bakelite-plated leather ceiling
and other original details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person of the past; I love the past,'' he said. ``When I
first took over, I had some people who didn't really appreciate the
decor of the place. They were like, `Oh we're glad it's a new
owner. Now you can modernize this place.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reed, 60, wearing a black satin baseball jacket with ``Lenox
Lounge: A Cocktail Lounge for the Elite'' stitched across the back
with its picture, was standing by the bar on Saturday with Fred
Ruffin, a friend, who was at the lounge's grand opening party in
1942. Reed said that a trademark dispute with El Morocco over the
use of a zebra motif, for which that storied supper club was
famous, had kept the lounge from opening officially in 1939.
Ruffin, who was one of the few blacks in the crowd that night at
the club, which like many was conceived for white patrons coming
uptown, recalled that it was ``a grand night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beer was 30 cents a bottle,'' he said. ``We were kicking on
that because it was 10 cents cheaper in other places.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of an economic boom uptown that many are calling a
second Harlem Renaissance, Reed said he believed there was also a
renaissance in the wings for Harlem night life and its jazz scene.
</P>
<P>
   With a $450,000 loan from the Upper Manhattan Empowerment Zone _
a development corporation created by the federal government in 1994
that is also assisting Minton's Playhouse and other Harlem
institutions _ Reed closed the lounge in September to begin work.
Yui &AMP; Bloch, an architectural team that specializes in restaurant
interiors, drew plans to renovate as well as to restore the lounge
as a bar and dining room with a program of live jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised around here, about 10 blocks down,'' Reed said.
``You could go into any club and there was a set going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Community preservationists' concerns about the Disneyfication of
Harlem (in particular, the not-unlikely threat of
theme-restaurant-style at period clubs like the Lenox Lounge)
reached Reed through newspaper articles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor his architects retained historical restoration
experts, confident that existing details, which matched 1939
postcards, could guide replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been an easier thing to rip it out and put fresh
sheetrock in,'' said Jimi Yui, the architect, whose office is also
at work on Le Bernardin's new private dining rooms. ``It's a
restoration in spirit only. Historical restorations are incredibly
expensive to do. But it's so rich in history. There's nothing that
you could have created that would have been better than the history
of what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its physical fact _ in continuous operation since 1939,
the lounge was never stripped for sale or vacant _ documentation of
the design is scant. The designer may have been Judson E. Schnall,
a Brooklyn-based architect whose name appears on a city
construction permit for the address, 288 Lenox Avenue, in 1938.
Reed bought the club from Dominick Greco, a nephew of the family
that built it, after seeing it listed for sale in The Amsterdam
News.
</P>
<P>
   Memory of what was there from the start was hazy, too, as thick
and stubborn to clear as the smoke on the walls. An
Egyptian-inspired mural in the Zebra Room, left behind by the
television crew from ``New York Undercover'' that created it in two
hours in 1992, endeared itself inconveniently to patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had more flack over that,'' Reed said. ``Everybody said,
`Please don't tell me that's not original; I don't want to hear
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was replaced by zebra wallpaper, based on a scrap discovered
in the room.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The program from Day 1 was to upgrade the building's systems,
but keep the feel of the original bar,'' said Zachary Kaplan, the
president of the ZMK Group, the general contractor. A new
restaurant kitchen was created at the back, with prep areas in the
basement; the lounge's scarred wooden bar was left intact, not
refinished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger part of that was driven by aesthetics, but some of
it was driven by money, too,'' said Kaplan, who grew up on
Riverside Drive at 116th Street and visited the lounge as a student
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Serendipity played its part in the renovation, too.
Frosted-glass fins to replace those missing in light fixtures were
found under five inches of mud in the basement. A box of glass
ashtrays used as decorative studs in the diamond-square upholstered
ceiling panels in the Zebra Room also appeared in the debris as new
vinyl was being put up to replace the tarred leather.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   When applicable, neighborhood subcontractors were hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was important to work with as many locally based
people as possible,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Reed's clientele will be another issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them really did not want me to do this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prices will go up, and the staff will change. Reed's loan was
dependent upon his creating 15 new jobs. Tourists and downtowners
are likely to be the immediate mainstay of the Zebra Room. Reed has
a 15-year lease, but he is three months behind on his rent, and
``stretched out,'' as he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came in and said, `Make sure you keep this and that,'
and I'm like, `Come in here and spend some money, you know?''' Reed
recalled of the renovation. ``Preservationists don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   A man on the street in a gray suit, a black hat and a gold neck
chain put his face to the window. Reed told Ruffin not to let him
in, explaining that he had been asked not to come back seven years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he thinks it's a new owner,'' Reed said, in the glow of
the unlighted Art Deco interior, suddenly right in the present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
