r a BC-CASINO-BRIBE-HNS &LR;      03-29 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO-BRIBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EX-OWNER OF 49ERS SAYS HE REGRETS INVOLVEMENT IN RACKETEERING
CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ Getting mixed up with a smooth-talking
politician like former Louisiana Gov. Edwin W. Edwards was the
worst thing he ever did, and he's paid a dear price for that
involvement, the former owner of the San Francisco 49ers said.
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. DeBartolo Jr. left the witness stand Tuesday after two
days of testimony that was alternately forceful, pathetic,
persuasive and contradictory in Louisiana's epic riverboat casino
licensing racketeering case.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, his son Stephen and five associates are accused of
rigging the award of 15 riverboat licenses by making applicants
ante up some $3 million in bribes as a prerequisite to tapping into
a Louisiana gambling gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, who raised the San Francisco 49ers to professional
football's heights _ five Super Bowl victories in the 22 years he
owned the team _ said that the damage caused to his life by the
riverboat licensing scandal was irreparable.
</P>
<P>
   He can't vote or own a firearm and will always be remembered as
a felon whose crime cost him his beloved 49ers, not the business
tycoon and respected sportsman he aspired to be, DeBartolo told
U.S. District Court Judge Frank Polozola, presiding over Edwards'
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, ``it caused me to become estranged from my only
blood relative, my sister,'' he said. Denise DeBartolo York is now
sole owner of the 49ers, crown jewel of the billion-dollar Edward
J. DeBartolo Corp. of Youngstown, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo insisted throughout an often brutal cross-examination
by Edwards' attorney, Dan Small, that he had feared, distrusted and
been corrupted by the former governor, who has been a dominant
political figure in Louisiana for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo conceded that it was his word against Edwards' on the
question of whether Edwards had demanded a $400,000 payoff as a
condition of winning the license for a riverboat casino in Bossier
City, La. Although wiretaps and videotapes have played a big part
in the prosecution's case so far, there is no taped evidence of the
March 5, 1997, meeting between the two men at the Radisson Hotel in
Baton Rouge, where the demand was allegedly made.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can harass me, and you can try to make me change my mind,
but what happened on March 5 and what happened on March 12 (when
DeBartolo delivered $400,000 in $100 bills to Edwards) is done, and
that's why I'm here, and that's why I pleaded guilty,'' a visibly
angry DeBartolo told Small.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo is the linchpin of the prosecution's case against
Edwards, because he is the only witness able to testify that
Edwards took money from him in connection with a riverboat casino
license.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution hoped to wrap up its case on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo acknowledged that he had continued to do business with
Edwards after winning the license _ almost up to the day when FBI
agents raided Edwards' Baton Rouge home and seized cash from his
safe. Why not? he asked. ``His influence and his involvement were
still there,'' DeBartolo said. ``I paid $400,000 in extortion for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo-as-victim played heavily on both ends of the counsel
table, with the prosecution portraying Edwards as having conned the
younger man with his patented brand of Louisiana guile, and the
defense saying, in effect, that DeBartolo had been done in by his
own greed and deception.
</P>
<P>
   Small also made repeated reference to the absence of threats by
Edwards to DeBartolo during their many taped conversations, in
which DeBartolo was usually the initiator of the call, and to the
many friendly activities they engaged in together to debunk the
notion that DeBartolo was a victim.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo said that Edwards' political prowess held him in
thrall. With each phone call discussing the Bossier City riverboat
casino project, Edwards ``was telling me he's got all his hands and
all his tentacles right where he needs them,'' DeBartolo said.
</P>
<P>
   When Edwards slid a slip of paper with $400,000 written on it
across a table in the Radisson bar on March 5 and warned him of
problems with the license, ``it was a demand. It was a threat. And
it was paid on March 12,'' DeBartolo said. The license was awarded
to the DeBartolo Entertainment-Hollywood Casinos Inc. partnership
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   When Small probed two conspicuous inconsistencies in the
prosecution's case _ DeBartolo's petition for the lifting of his
one-year suspension from the National Football League and reporting
the $400,000 payment to Edwards on his income tax _ DeBartolo
disclaimed responsibility, although he signed both documents.
</P>
<P>
   The petition to NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue said that
DeBartolo had pleaded guilty only to ``a highly technical
violation'' of the law. ``I didn't tell the NFL anything,''
DeBartolo said. ``That was a submission by my lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo's 1997 Internal Revenue Service form 1099 listed the
payment to Edwards under ``non-employee compensation.'' But
DeBartolo said that was the work of ``my attorneys and
accountants,'' without explaining how they would have known to list
it unless he had instructed them.
</P>
</TEXT>
