<HEADLINE>
(EDS: ACCOMPANIES TORNADO-TEXAS) 
SHELTER PACKED WITH 500 HOMELESS PEOPLE DURING STORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By YVETTE CRAIG 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As the storm raged, hundreds of homeless
people huddled inside the Presbyterian Night Shelter, some praying,
others trying to calm their crying children.
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County's largest walk-in shelter has no windows. But the
echoes of rain and hail pounding the tin roof Tuesday night made
the killer storm a terrifying experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``These walls are the only place many of these people call
home,'' said Julie Walkup, associate pastor for mission at First
Presbyterian Church. Walkup was volunteering at the shelter at the
height of the storm. ``We could hear sheets of rain coming down.
Soon the lights went out ... and we could hear the tornado roaring
down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was harmed at the shelter, but the tornado took its toll
on the homeless and needy in other ways. Neighboring shelters,
which were unoccupied, were damaged. At least one downtown mission
that feeds the poor could not open Wednesday because the area was
shut off.
</P>
<P>
   One homeless woman, who is believed to have paranoid
schizophrenia, wandered from the Safe Haven for the Homeless before
the storm hit and was still missing Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shelter was packed with over 500 people,'' said John
Suggs, executive director of the night shelter. ``People were
spilled into our lobby. It's a miracle no one was hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, glass from downtown businesses cluttered the back
yard of the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Battering winds mangled the roof and sucked the heating and
air-conditioning unit from a Veterans Affairs building at 2320
Cypress St.
</P>
<P>
   A program partly funded by the Department of Veterans Affairs
offers work to homeless veterans. The tornado damage will prevent
veterans from working in the warehouse until the roof can be
repaired.
</P>
<P>
   On March 14, the Presbyterian Night Shelter board declared
victory on its capital campaign, saying the project is nine months
ahead of schedule and $4 million over the target.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $1.9 million in cash and pledges was raised by the
end of February, primarily for a facility for homeless women and
children.
</P>
<P>
   But the facility, scheduled to open in June, lost its roof in
the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Structural engineers estimate that the damage to this roof
will put us behind now about a month,'' said Lee Ann Embry,
development director for the shelter. ``In the grander scheme of
things, we were blessed that none of our residents were hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Smith, director of the First United Methodist Mission at
First and Henderson streets, arrived at the mission building around
7 a.m. Wednesday to check for damage, but police barricades blocked
access to the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in shock right now,'' she said. ``I don't know what the
damage is in the building. My concern is the people who come here
for help.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Lila LaHood contributed to this report. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
