<HEADLINE>
MAYOR USES `POLICE POWER' TO CLOSE OFF FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ An ancient and seldom-mentioned law gave
Mayor Kenneth Barr the authority to use ``police power'' to keep
people away from the storm-ravaged streets and buildings of
downtown Fort Worth, an assistant city attorney said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Police who barricaded the perimeter of downtown for much of
Wednesday stopped onlookers and people trying to reach their
offices as emergency crews assessed damage _ and shards of glass
fell from high-rise buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the storms, city officials said they would close
the hardest-hit areas because of broken glass, fallen power lines
and the possibility of looting.
</P>
<P>
   Some people got through, but officers were told that the
downtown area was ``basically off-limits to everybody for safety
reasons,'' police Detective S.A. Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr called on a law derived from a doctrine that says, ``The
government is there to keep the peace and protect the public's
welfare,'' Assistant City Attorney Hugh Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It dates way, way back. It's been called the police power for
at least three or four hundred years,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
