<HEADER>
A1425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      03-29 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: A NEW HOW-TO FOR WANT-TO'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``No one can help you. A writer is alone with it, by the nature
of it.'' This is a quotation from the novelist James Jones (``From
Here to Eternity''). One very likely could find a similar plaint
from the ghosts of all the authors past and in the petition of all
the writers present and all those to come. Nonetheless, there are
easily a hundred how-to books in print offering coaching in the
intricate technicalities of the writing craft.
</P>
<P>
   The genre could be loosely defined as literary mechanics, and it
includes manuals on how to plot, on beginnings and middles and
ends, on how to develop characters and viewpoints, on action, on
creating suspense, on the narrative. And there are guides to the
use of the American language like Strunk and White's ``Elements of
Style'' (Allyn &AMP; Bacon).
</P>
<P>
   The latest, one with an interesting variation of theme that
takes it beyond writerly mechanisms, went on sale last week. It is
``The Forest for the Trees: An Editor's Advice to Writers''
(Riverhead Books) by Betsy Lerner. In the book, Lerner, now a
literary agent but previously a publishing house editor, doesn't
preach on how to write a book but rather tries to help writers and
would-be authors cope with such problems as being ``alone with
it.'' It's a survival course. Or, as she said in an interview:
``It's not really on how to write. It's how to use your personality
and keep your personality; how to use your neuroses and not let
them overwhelm you; how to tap into self-promotion.'' In sum, there
is great creative power in using your personal craziness as a
tangible asset when writing.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner is not the first one to try to help a writer be
comfortable with the uncomfortable. Mark Twain wrote on writing and
publishing, and Flannery O'Connor has a collection of letters,
``The Habit of Being'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 1979), a number of
which were about writing. Indeed, the first such book about writing
may have been the one written in China around A.D. 200, ``The Art
of Writing'' by Lu Chi. In soothing the writer concerned about
repeating themes, he reminded him that ``a common song sung to a
great melody is another way to find beauty.'' Think of that when
you find yourself imitating Hemingway. (Lu Chi's book, from
Milkweed Editions, is available through Amazon.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Lerner's book similarly tries to ease the writer's psyche. She
explains in its introduction that she wants to help the writer who
cannot get started embark, the writer stalled between projects
ignite. She asks: ``Is your neurotic behavior part of your creative
process or just ... neurotic behavior?'' She wants you to be ``an
effective self-promoter'' and not ``a self-saboteur.'' In the book
she contrasts Walt Whitman, the great self-promoter, with Emily
Dickinson, who Lerner feels could barely slip the pages of her
poetry out the front door of her house. The book is also an
affirmation that late bloomers can become successful writers, which
certainly will appeal to the millions of amateurs who before they
slip off to sleep at night half dream of writing novels.
</P>
<P>
   So the question is, can one learn from a book how to be a
writer? Certainly those who teach writing courses at the graduate
level answer with a ``no'' as pounding as cannon fire, although to
be fair it must be said that probably none had yet read a book
quite like Lerner's message to the writer's spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Conroy, the novelist who heads the Writers Workshop at the
University of Iowa, said: ``We never use a book that teaches you to
write; we never even read them. I don't think you can learn writing
from a book, except from reading literature.'' Jean McGarry, who is
chairwoman of the writing seminars at Johns Hopkins University, and
Melissa Hermerle, who heads the master's program in creative
writing at New York University, agree.
</P>
<P>
   The teaching process in the three programs revolves mostly
around students' writing, and fellow students and teachers'
discussing and criticizing their work. And reading literature.
McGarry said: ``We use novels and short stories and poems. The
student has to learn to read like a writer. He has to read a
paragraph by Hemingway and ask himself why it is so vivid and mine
is not? Why is a story shapely and suspenseful and mine is not?''
</P>
<P>
   That thought was reiterated by Hermerle. ``The closest we come
to craft books in fiction and poetry,'' she said, ``are the texts
of novels and poetry books.'' Still McGarry said, ``The students
don't know that they have lives and episodes.'' Which, of course,
is part of what Lerner hopes readers will realize from her book.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't learn to write by reading a how-to book, can you
become a novelist by going to school? The percentages are better.
Many students do get published; most don't. Those that do justify
the courses. ``Nathan Englander slouched around here for a couple
of years,'' Conroy said, ``and then went out and published this
incredibly good book, `For the Relief of Unbearable Urges.''' The
book, a collection of stories brought out a year ago by Alfred A.
Knopf, received wide critical acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Conroy said of would-be writers in the Iowa program: ``We guide
them. Maybe this should be in the third person, not the first
person. We try to get them to write the same time every day; even
to write in the same place every day. But we try to stay out of the
psychology part.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Into Eternity'' (Houghton Mifflin &AMP; Co., 1985), a
biography of James Jones, Frank MacShane quotes the writer as
having said: ``I'm working in the dark all the time. Whenever I
write something, that black, forbidding doubt is in, making me
wonder if I'm just some damned egotistical fool, or I really have
that spark of genius it takes to be a really great author like
Wolfe. If I only had some way of knowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones concluded, ``Sometimes I get so damned low I feel like
blowing my brains out.'' Maybe a little psychology wouldn't hurt in
these writing courses. Perhaps some of Lerner's survival stuff
would help a future Jones get past such forbidding moments, and
even use them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
