<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1426 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-OIL-HNS &LR;      03-29 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON CALLS OIL PRICE SHOCK `WAKE UP CALL' FOR FUEL
EFFICIENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, welcoming OPEC's agreement to
boost the flow of crude oil Wednesday, called the recent oil price
shock a ``wake up call'' for America to intensify the quest for
energy independence with greater fuel efficiency for vehicles,
homes and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his administration and Congress should seize on the
``sobering experience'' of suffering 60 percent price increases in
gasoline to step up efforts to promote development of alternative
fuels and energy-saving technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have talked `till I was blue in the face about this for
years,'' lamented Clinton, who is now in the final 10 months of his
eight-year presidency. ``I hope very much that this is a little bit
of a wake-up call for all of us and that we can put this on the
front burner and get some action.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the White House and Congress ``should do more'' to
reduce America's reliance on oil for 39 percent of its daily energy
needs. Foreign oil accounts for 52 percent of the nation's daily
oil consumption _ the highest reliance on overseas suppliers in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments at a White House news conference followed a
decision by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to
increase the flow of crude oil by 7 percent in response to
entreaties by the Clinton administration. Saudi Arabia and Kuwait,
two nations defended from Iraqi aggression by the United States in
the Persian Gulf War in 1990-1991, provide roughly one-third of
OPEC's daily crude oil production.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC's action, coupled with increased crude oil production by
non-OPEC nations such as Mexico, will add more than 1.7 million
barrels a day to the international flow of crude oil. The added
production is expected to cut the soaring cost of gasoline in the
United States where the price at the pump has jumped from about $1
a gallon last year to an average of $1.60 a gallon _ and nearly $2
in some regions.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC nations, suffering economic difficulties of their own, had
drastically cut back crude oil production over the past year in an
effort to drive up prices of about $10 a barrel 14 months ago. They
succeeded in pushing the price of oil to $34.37 a barrel earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Without being specific, Clinton urged the nation's oil companies
to immediately give America's consumers the benefit of lower
gasoline prices rather than waiting for the increased flow of crude
oil from abroad to drive down costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge the oil companies to do everything they can to bring
the savings to consumers as quickly as possible,'' Clinton said.
``Right now, I think the prudent thing is to see how quickly these
prices can come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hickman, a spokesman at the American Petroleum Institute,
said the oil industry had no immediate comment about the
president's statements.
</P>
<P>
   It ordinarily takes about two months for Middle Eastern oil to
reach the United States, be refined into gasoline and shipped to
gasoline stations around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   John Llewellyn, global chief economist for the Lehman Brothers
securities firm, told reporters in New York that the increased flow
of crude oil from OPEC and non-OPEC countries will bring the oil
market ``back into balance'' with per-barrel cost edging downward
in the weeks ahead to between $20 and $25 per barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed OPEC's action as ``good news for our economy,''
adding that the increased flow of crude oil would reduce home
heating oil costs and gasoline costs ``in the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged Congress to immediately reauthorize the Strategic
Petroleum Reserve, an underground stockpile of crude oil stockpiled
by the United States for national emergencies. The Clinton
administration has declined to tap the emergency supply of oil to
help drive down consumer prices, saying that the reserve is only
intended to be used for national emergencies such as wartime oil
embargoes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also rejected the suggestions of Republican lawmakers,
led by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., that the federal
government ought to suspend the 4.3 cents per gallon federal
gasoline tax to help ease the burden on consumers. Clinton said
such a cutback may not get ``passed along to the consumers'' by the
oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   In citing steps that the federal government could take to
strengthen America's energy independence, Clinton urged passage of
tax breaks to encourage the development of ethanol, a grain-based
alternative fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also cited steps to encourage production of highly
fuel-efficient vehicles that rely upon self-regenerating batteries
or duel fuels such as electricity and gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of things we can do but we need to create some
markets for doing this,'' Clinton said. ``And there hasn't been a
lot of interest in it, I think, probably since the high prices of
the `70s.''
</P>
<P>
   An Arab oil embargo on crude oil shipments to the United States
in retaliation for U.S support for Israel during the 1973
Arab-Israeli War drove up oil prices for the remainder of the
1970s, prompting President Jimmy Carter to launch a fuel efficiency
crusade that called on Americans to turn down their thermostats in
the winter and turn them up in the summer. Carter wore cardigan
sweaters to symbolize his effort.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's ardent call for national self-discipline coupled with
higher oil prices set the stage for a generation of more fuel
efficient cars. But the fluctuating price of oil has hampered
federal efforts to mount a sustained campaign for energy efficiency
and alternative fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that Americans are buying and driving gasoline
guzzling sports utility vehicles, adding: ``They want to drive
those vehicles. They like those big vehicles. But if they're going
to drive them, we're either going to have to find a way for them to
get batter mileage or run on alliterative fuels over the long
run.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart(at)hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
