<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOWER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHOWER': REDISCOVERING WISDOM   IN A HOME LEFT BEHIND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an updated version of the parable of the prodigal son, the
black sheep who returns to the bosom of his family after a long
absence is less likely nowadays to be a sated sybarite than a rich,
snobbish yuppie revisiting the humble background he fled in shame.
Reconnecting with his roots, his shuttered heart opens, and he
discovers that indeed there's no place like home.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang Yang's sweet but serious comedy, ``Shower,'' offers an
uplifting, witty variation on this scenario. Set in contemporary
Beijing, the movie tells the story of Da Ming (Pu Cun Xin), a
sharply dressed young businessman who returns from the southern
Chinese region of Shenzhen to visit his aged father, Master Liu
(Zhu Xu).
</P>
<P>
   For decades Master Liu, whose health is fragile, has run a
bathhouse in a dilapidated district of Beijing. His right-hand man
is his mentally retarded younger son, Er Ming (Jiang Wu), who takes
a childlike delight in all the ritualized sloshing.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the worldviews of Master Liu and his
elder son is craftily suggested by an opening scene in which Da
Ming puts himself through a coin-operated automated shower that
resembles a human carwash. By contrast, at Master Liu's spacious
establishment everything is done slowly and by hand. Much more than
a steam bath, the place is a popular community center where the
neighborhood men pass the afternoon hours in conversation and games
of chess while drinking tea and being massaged. Two regular patrons
stage heated contests between fighting crickets.
</P>
<P>
   Lolling about in one of Master Liu's steamy pools is a little
like attending a languid group therapy session in which people
confide their secrets and work out their anxieties. In one running
subplot, a shy, chubby teen-ager preparing to appear in a local
pageant loudly rehearses ``O Sole Mio,'' but he is comfortable
singing only when he is under a spray of water. When Er Ming
playfully turns off the shower, the precocious belter instantly
buttons up.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's quirky characters are its best defense against
sentimentality. Besides the operatically inclined teen-ager and the
promoters of fighting crickets, they include a debt-ridden patron
who is chased into a pool by shady creditors and a henpecked
husband for whom the bathhouse is the only refuge from his
screaming harridan of a wife. The ever-patient Master Liu ends up
playing marriage counselor and sex therapist for this frustrated
couple.
</P>
<P>
   As Da Ming's visit lengthens, he begins to absorb his father's
wisdom by a kind of osmosis. He also begins to take responsibility
for the younger brother, whose existence he had kept secret from
his wife. The father-son strife is powerfully conveyed in calm,
sorrowful performances that establish the movie's bittersweet mood.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a daring imaginative leap, ``Shower,'' which New
Directors/New Films is screening Thursday and Saturday at the
Museum of Modern Art, also reaches beyond the present to meditate
on water as a precious natural resource. Interwoven with the story
of Da Ming's return are visionary scenes of earlier generations of
the same family, struggling against drought in northern China's
arid climes. These scenes, staged as quasi-mythical vignettes,
deepen the movie's ambivalent attitude toward progress and the
drastic effects it can have on a settled community.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
PRODUCTION NOTES: &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; `SHOWER' Directed by Zhang Yang; written (in Mandarin, with
English subtitles) by Liu Fen Dou, Zhang, Huo Xin, Diao Yi Nan and
Cai Xiang Jun; director of photography, Zhang Jian; edited by Yang
Hong Yu and Zhang Yang; music by Ye Xiao Gang; art director, Tian
Meng; produced by Peter Loehr; released by Sony Pictures Classics.
Running time: 92 minutes. This film is not rated. Shown Thursday at
6 and Saturday at noon at the Museum of Modern Art in Manhattan, as
part of the 29th New Directors/New Films series of the Film Society
of Lincoln Center and the Department of Film of the Museum of
Modern Art. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WITH: Zhu Xu (Master Liu), Pu Cun Xin (Da Ming), Jiang Wu (Er
Ming), He Zheng (He Bing), Zhang Jin Hao (Bei Bei), Lao Lin (Li
Ding) and Lao Wu (Feng Shun).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
