<HEADER>
A1429 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DELTA-JETS-COX     03-29 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-JETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta to buy up to 500 more regional jets over next decade
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines will buy as many as 500 more regional jets for
its Delta Connection carriers over the next decade, at a cost of
$20 million per plane, or up to $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded aircraft order, announced as expected on Wednesday,
reflects Delta's embrace of the new class of minijets.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are using the planes to replace turboprops on some
feeder routes and to open new long-haul markets that don't justify
big-jet service. They fly faster and farther than turboprops and
are regarded as more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Delta described its deal with Montreal-based jet maker
Bombardier Inc. as ``the largest regional jet order in aviation
history.''
</P>
<P>
   It includes firm orders for 94 RJs for delivery through 2004. Of
those, 52 will go to Atlantic Southeast Airlines, which feeds
Delta's hubs in Atlanta and Dallas-Forth Worth, and 42 to Comair,
which feeds its Cincinnati hub and flies in Florida. Both operate
under the Delta Connection banner.
</P>
<P>
   Those orders will be in addition to 57 previous orders at ASA
and Comair, which already have about 130 of the planes in their
fleets.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's deal also gives Delta options to buy another 406 RJs
through 2010. Options are reserved production slots that must be
confirmed or dropped by certain deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   The planes will include a mix of Canadair Regional Jet models
with 40, 44, 50 and 70 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded order could enable ASA, which still flies more
turboprops than jets, to convert to an all-jet fleet over the next
several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would certainly be our dream,'' said David Siebenburgen,
chief executive of Delta Connection Inc., which oversees ASA and
Comair.
</P>
<P>
   Comair, which was the first regional carrier to use jets, is
scheduled to be all-jet by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has been among the most aggressive carriers in deploying
RJs, in part because its pilots' union contract doesn't limit how
many its feeder subsidiaries can operate. Contracts at some other
carriers have tighter restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's pilots union may seek tighter limits in new contract
talks now under way, but so far the union has not disclosed its
negotiating position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
