<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1430 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DELTA-PILOTS-COX     03-29 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PILOTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'On-time' contract between Delta and pilots' union seen as
unlikely
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contract negotiations between Delta Air Lines and its pilots'
union are unlikely to produce an ``on-time'' deal by May 1 as had
been hoped, company and union officials concede.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very tough to get it done by that deadline,''
said Delta Chairman and Chief Executive Leo Mullin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances have diminished because of the pace of the past
four weeks or so,'' said Charles Giambusso, chairman of Delta's Air
Line Pilots Association unit.
</P>
<P>
   The two spoke in separate interviews this week.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and ALPA opened contract talks in September, six months
ahead of schedule by mutual agreement. The goal was a deal by May
1, when the current contract becomes amendable.
</P>
<P>
   So far, several technical sections of the new accord have been
negotiated and scheduling issues are now being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the stickiest issues _ pay rates among them _
haven't even hit the table.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots' union, still smarting from what it views as a
concessionary contract inked in 1996, is expected to seek hefty pay
increases, as well as a voting board seat and new limits on Delta's
use of regional jets flown by lower-paid pilots employed by
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good and I think the union feels good about the talks
so far, but the problem is discussions on the really tough elements
of compensation have not yet occurred,'' Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it hard to believe we can get it done by May 1, but if
not I hope it will be soon thereafter, and certainly there's
nothing in terms of attitude holding us up,'' he said. ``It's just
a work issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Giambusso said he proposed last month that talks be accelerated.
``The company responded to some degree but it still hasn't really
accelerated progress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with talks starting early, an on-time pilot contract would
have been highly unusual for the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   Typically such talks run for more than a year and usually result
in federal mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Under airline labor law, union contracts don't expire at the
amendable date but continue until a new deal is struck or a strike
occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
