<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHANA-MORRISON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DAUGHTER OF' IS ON HER OWN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL WELIN   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get this out of the way, right up front: Shana Morrison is
the daughter of lyricist-novelist Janet Planet and legendary rocker
Van Morrison. Yes, ``Here Comes the Night,'' ``Gloria,''
``Brown-Eyed Girl,'' ``Tupelo Honey,'' that Van Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   But his daughter chose another path. The 29-year-old holds a
degree in international business from Pepperdine University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved math when I was a kid,'' Morrison said by telephone
from her home in Mill Valley, Calif. But ``I sat in front of a
computer too long _ no offense.'' Stifling a throaty laugh, she
continued, ``That last year in college was too hard. When I
graduated, I knew I wanted to get a job, so my dad offered me a job
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   You see, she's got a voice, she writes intriguing songs and the
business degree is helpful, but is a thing of the past. Morrison
and her band, Caledonia, have a recording contract with Monster
Records, have cut their first CD, have a second in the works and
are on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always sang ... in choir and in school musicals ... that
sort of thing. And I always wrote poetry. It all seemed to come
together one day, and I just began putting the poetry to music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Caledonia'' is an solid, eclectic first effort, ranging from
airy modern pop (``I Spy'') to a more-classic sound (``Yes, Yes,
Yes,'' ``Can't Hold On'') to bluesy rock (``House of Mirrors''),
all with a sweet, country influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there's a definite country tinge there,'' Morrison said.
She said about half of her records are Irish, and ``Irish music is
country music.''
</P>
<P>
   She included ``Sweet Thing,'' a tune from her father's classic
1968 song cycle, ``Astral Weeks,'' and managed to one-up the old
man for passion and commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first song I can remember from when I was very, very
small,'' Morrison said, sighing from the memory, or perhaps because
she's been asked to talk about it so frequently. ``The band wanted
to put it on the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Risking another sigh, another tired question: Just how much has
her father helped her career?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a big `advice guy,' but he's definitely helped me. I
sang with him for records and on a soundtrack. Singing with him on
the Rock `n' Soul Revue and on the soundtrack added to my
confidence as to what I can do, and to say _ for any musician to
say that they've worked with him _ is a thing of credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still I didn't want to be too-much billed as `the daughter
of,' you know?''
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't occur too much longer.
</P>
<P>
   (Joel Welin writes for the Herald-Tribune of Sarasota, Fla.,
which is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
