<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1439 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TERE-O'CONNOR-DANCE-$     03-29 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERE-O'CONNOR-DANCE-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFECTIONIST WHO CAN LAUGH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Joseph Carman's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about the choreographer Doug Varone.)  
(af) 
 By JOSEPH CARMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The choreographer Tere O'Connor was patiently administering
notes to his dancers during a recent rehearsal of his new work,
``Hi Everybody!'' ``One, two, three,'' he intoned, patiently
counting the beat as his six dancer-actors whirled around him.
``Chrysa, there's a step before that attitude turn. Greg, can you
make the Southern guy more of a big old redneck, like you used
to?''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some choreographers, who bark like drill sergeants at
their dancers, O'Connor seldom raises his voice, although inside,
he says, his vision of what should be sometimes collides with his
realization of what is, pushing him to the point of a scream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi Everybody!,'' which opens on Thursday for a three-week run
at Dance Theater Workshop in Manhattan, is a poetic, absurdist
combination of dance and what O'Connor calls ``the theater of the
obvious,'' meant to entertain the audience while disorienting it
and provoking it into a catharsis.
</P>
<P>
   The work, with an original score by James Baker and lighting by
Brian MacDevitt, was cited for its initial production at the
Kitchen last year when O'Connor received a Bessie Award for
sustained achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of his previous pure-dance pieces, ``Hi Everybody!''
integrates text into the choreography and tosses around political
issues as well as dance and acting styles. With his veteran
downtown troupe (Nancy Bannon, Rob Besserer, Marc Kenison, Heather
Olson, Chrysa Parkinson and Greg Zuccolo), O'Connor has created a
distinct theatrical voice that is simultaneously humorous and
ponderous.
</P>
<P>
   As for the title, O'Connor explains that ``Hi Everybody!'' is
his metaphor for the way he acknowledges everything that crosses
his mind. ``I have a very multiplicitous thought process,'' he
said. ``Accidentally, that is quite aligned with the culture right
now. There is much too much to take in. But fortunately I already
have way too much going on, so I have a similar structure.'' Here
he broke into a belly laugh worthy of Falstaff.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mantello, the director of ``The Vagina Monologues'' and a
Tony-nominated actor in ``Angels in America,'' described the effect
of O'Connor's theatrical approach on the audience: ``The
juxtaposition of the formality of the choreography, which is so
beautiful, and then these strange little improvisational scenes
that the dancers break out of are so incredibly moving and yet are
so irreverent and funny. There is this fractured narrative that
goes on, and somehow by the end you've had this complete and total
experience that defies logic and words.''
</P>
<P>
   In one segment of ``Hi Everybody!'' a female dancer stops the
choreographic momentum to cajole the five other performers into
forming an impromptu grief support group. After a series of
dramatic confrontations that range in acting style from 1950s
Tennessee Williams to television sitcom, she is comically swept
into the undertow of an ensemble dance phrase.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers later break into an unexpectedly campy fandango,
followed by a Greek chorus of ``three flamboyant, stereotypical
fags,'' as O'Connor describes them, who comment on gay-bashing.
</P>
<P>
   For O'Connor, 41, the combination of text and choreography is a
recent development. Before the premiere of his work ``Mother'' in
1996 he confined himself to dance steps. Five years ago, Mikhail
Baryshnikov saw his work and was impressed by his choreographic
craftsmanship. Baryshnikov, on a break from his own rehearsals last
week, explained why he admired O'Connor's talent: ``His works are
deeply personal, quirky and utterly amusing, but beneath the humor
lies tenderness and truth.''
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons, in 1995 Baryshnikov commissioned O'Connor to
create an abstract dance work for the White Oak Dance Project. That
became ``Greta in the Ditch.'' There came a point, however, when
O'Connor lost interest in the formal aspects of dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped looking at my own internal world and started looking
at the world around me and was upset by many things,'' he said. ``I
consider theater as a place to exorcise fears. I thought I would
fully confront that, and writing seemed to be the next logical
step.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, he now subjects his text to the same kind of
rhythmic scrutiny he has always applied to his choreography. This
year, he staged a new work, ``Orshi's Dilemma,'' for a dance troupe
in Budapest, for which his English script was translated into
Hungarian rap.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor introduces politics into ``Hi Everybody!,''
specifically issues like the disenfranchisement of the elderly and
the debate over gay marriages. But he does it in a way that doesn't
hit the audience over the head with messages. As Mantello says:
``It's more subversive in its politics. Tere leaves room for you to
come to it. There is air within.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
