<HEADLINE>
PRAGUE TO PRESERVE OLD JEWISH CEMETERY FOUND DURING CONSTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The Czech government said Wednesday
that it would pay to preserve a medieval Jewish cemetery that was
discovered underground during construction in Prague three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to accommodate the claims of Jewish groups in
Prague and the insurance company that is building on the land, the
government agreed to finance the rescue of several hundred graves,
some of which may date back to 13th century.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech minister of culture, Pavel Dostal, said he would
declare the whole area surrounding the site a cultural landmark and
promised to save undisturbed graves and to rebury bones that were
disturbed in the construction. The government will allocate $1.2
million to cover the costs, and the company agreed to pay any
additional costs.
</P>
<P>
   The remains of some 130 skeletons, unearthed in the last two
years, will be reburied at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish groups in Prague and abroad welcomed the decision. ``We
congratulate the Czech authorities and society for recognizing the
sacred interest over economic interest,'' said Rabbi Marc Schneier,
president of the North American Boards of Rabbis, who had been
mediating the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that certain elements of the Jewish community
would accept the jurisdiction of the Prague Jewish community in
this matter,'' he added, referring to groups abroad, including
Orthodox Jews, who demanded that the construction be abandoned
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   According to historians, the cemetery officially operated into
the 15th century. In its day, it served as a central burial site
for all Bohemian Jews. The recent discovery of undisturbed graves
in the deeper layers caused great interest among archaeologists.
</P>
<P>
   Ceska Pojistovna, the insurance company that owns the lot and
several adjacent buildings, had hoped to carry out speedy
construction of its new administration building. But it when it
found the graves, it halted construction and financed the dig.
</P>
<P>
   The underground graveyard, whose tombstones have been reused
over the centuries, will be sealed in concrete on all sides, and
the building will be built around it.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech government allocated less money than the company had
hoped for, but Ceska Pojistovna's spokesman Vaclav Balek said his
company would accept the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to help to save a cultural landmark and make it easier
on taxpayers,'' he said. ``We have no problem with the decision. We
wanted to reach a compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The small Jewish community in Prague also welcomed the
government's decision with relief. ``We are happy with the
solution,'' said Tomas Kraus, the director of the Federation of
Czech Jewish Communities. ``This is a victory of common sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
