A1443 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-PRAYER-HNS &LR;      03-29 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PRAYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT WRESTLES WITH SCHOOL PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tackling the controversial issue of school prayer,
the Supreme Court heard arguments Wednesday on whether school
districts can let students lead stadium crowds in prayer before
high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four decades after the court banned officially sponsored
prayers in public schools, the justices struggled once more to
balance students' free-speech rights with the Constitution's
requirement for the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we draw the line?'' Justice Stephen G. Breyer asked
Jay Sekulow, a Washington-based attorney representing the Santa Fe,
Texas, school district.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the legality of the district's policy allowing
students to vote on whether they want to offer a pre-game message
to ``solemnize'' the event and promote good sportsmanship. School
officials contend that the students, not district officials, choose
who will deliver the message and that the deliver decides the
content of that message.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall during football season, senior Marian Ward was elected
by the student body to present the pre-game message at all home
games. Ward chose religious themes. The adopted daughter of a
Baptist minister, Ward received a standing ovation when she stepped
before the public address system and asked for God's blessing for
the players and spectators.When school officials said they wanted
to review her message before she presented it, she filed suit in
federal district court and won an injunction allowing her to say
what she wanted during the pre-game ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the 5th Circuit struck down the
practice last year, ruling that any policy that allows
proselytizing benedictions and invocations was unconstitutional.
The court also looked at a revised district policy that would
require the messages to be ``nonsectarian and nonproselytizing''
but concluded that under no circumstances could pre-kickoff prayer
be proper for a high school football game.``Football games ...
[are] hardly the sober type of annual event that can be
appropriately solemnized with prayer,'' the appeals court declared.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing before high court Wednesday, Sekulow said that while the
football policy doesn't exclude religious messages, it doesn't
specifically promote them either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school has no say whatsoever in what the student's message
is,'' he said. ``There's nothing in the school's policy that says,
`Do talk about God or don't talk about God' it's completely
neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Stephen Kennedy said using elections to choose the
speaker _ who could then hold a prayer _ at a school function could
lead to a ``majority of students imposing their beliefs on the
minority.''
</P>
<P>
   Sekulow said students could choose not to attend the game if
they objected to a prayer. Chief Justice William Rehnquist made it
clear later that he agreed with that statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice David Souter told Sekulow that members of the band,
cheerleaders and the football players were ``obligated'' to attend
the games and thus ``forced'' to listen to the prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that the fact that a student is forced to
listen to a prayer is as far as we have to go to in deciding this
case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn, in defending the school
district's policy, insisted that the case is about free speech and
preserving ideals of Santa Fe _ a town of 8,600 residents that has
more churches than restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   He said the school's policy is ``viewpoint neutral'' and said
that striking it down could lead to ``viewpoint discrimination''
against students who want their message to be a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg challenged his assertion that
the policy is really neutral. ``I very much doubt whether the
school would allow a student to get up before the game and
proclaim, `All religion is bunk,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Griffin of Galveston, Texas, representing students and
parents who challenged the policy, said that that even though the
school asks the students to vote on whether to have some message,
religious or otherwise, at games, the policy is designed ``to
achieve a single, majoritarian answer ... and to impose that answer
on everyone in the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin said that students should be allowed to ``pray before,
after and even during the game'' but that their prayers should be
``a private discussion between them and God, and not something done
over a microphone.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, who seemed most sympathetic to the
now-suspended policy, noted that it would allow a student to give a
``message or invocation.'' But he added, ``You have no idea whether
that student is going to say anything about religion. The student
could talk about anything.'' He also said that ``you can't say that
in every case it's going to produce a prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin argued that because of the town's deeply-held religious
beliefs, it was ``almost a certainty that sooner or later the
elected student would begin a prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   When the high court last took up the subject of school prayer
eight years ago, it ruled 5-4 that prayer at a public school
graduation violated the First Amendment's rule that government
``shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion.'' In
that Rhode Island dispute, the court emphasized that school
officials had organized the prayer exercise and that students were
obligated to attend the graduation ceremony. Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, has filed
briefs backing the school district. On the Texas Republican primary
ballot earlier this month, voters were asked whether they approved
of student-led prayer at school sports events. More than 94 percent
did.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
