<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-EMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS FAST, EFFECTIVE, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TORNADO-TEXAS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GINGER D. RICHARDSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The unthinkable has happened in Fort Worth _
twice.
</P>
<P>
   As haggard city officials gathered Wednesday at the Police and
Fire Training Academy just west of downtown, the scene was eerily
similar to one just six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tornado tears through downtown, leaving death and destruction in
its wake. Lone gunman opens fire at Wedgwood Baptist Church,
killing seven and then himself.
</P>
<P>
   Both times, Fort Worth leaders implemented a disaster response
plan that they, and some state officials, are saying saved lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city should be praised for the way they handled this,''
Lt. Gov. Rick Perry said during a news conference Wednesday
morning. ``This could have been a tragedy of monumental
proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   As early as 5 p.m. Tuesday, the city was staffing its emergency
management office in the City Hall basement. After monitoring
weather reports, city workers first sounded the emergency sirens at
6:11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado touched down four minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Off-duty police and fire personnel, who were recalled to search
buildings and assist injured victims, received additional help from
the Texas Urban Search &AMP; Rescue Team, a state-funded group created
by the Legislature to help in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Transportation Authority supplied five buses to
take people out of downtown, paramedics treated the wounded at a
triage center at the Will Rogers Memorial Center, and the city set
up a hot line through its Water Department to take calls from
panicked residents.
</P>
<P>
   In less than six hours, 911 personnel dispatched officers and
firefighters in response to 2,100 calls. Normally, emergency
personnel don't respond to that many calls in 24 hours, Police
Chief Ralph Mendoza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the resources to handle it, and we didn't have a
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   None of those things would have happened, officials said, if not
for the extensive destruction training done by Fort Worth's police
and fire departments and its emergency response team.
</P>
<P>
   Fire, police and emergency management personnel have has
training sessions in places such as Oklahoma City, shortly after
the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building was bombed April 19, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And they have had six months to analyze their response to the
Sept. 17 shooting at Wedgwood Baptist, where Larry Gene Ashbrook
fatally shot seven people before killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every situation makes you a little smarter, gives you a little
additional experience,'' Mendoza said. ``This one will, too. You
just hope you don't have to be in another situation where you need
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Mayor Kenneth Barr said extensive training paid off _
both at Wedgwood and during Tuesday's destructive tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we learned that disaster strikes suddenly, and you
better be ready for it,'' Barr said. ``We were ready then. We
tested the system and it worked, and it will work again.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everything went according to plan. There were reports
Wednesday that Fort Worth's emergency siren warning system did not
sound in some parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   For at least two years, City Councilman Clyde Picht has urged
his colleagues to invest in a new system. The item was cut during
last year's budget discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Picht said he believes that the disaster Tuesday underscored the
need for a new system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to say `I told you so.' ... I don't think
that's necessary,'' Picht said. ``But I think the city will be like
the family that puts in an alarm system after their heirlooms are
stolen. We'll put in the system after we have the tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   Emergency management officials have repeatedly advised the
council that a new siren system is not necessary, but Barr said
Wednesday that the city will review the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was lots of warning about this storm and enormous media
coverage,'' Barr said. ``We're going to be looking at our ability
to notify people and whether an early siren system would have made
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
