<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MARRIAGE-BOOK-REVIEW-     03-29 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LE MARIAGE': A FRENCH CONNECTION, UNDER STRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``All tragedies are finish'd by a death, / All comedies are
ended by a marriage,'' wrote Byron in ``Don Juan.'' By these
definitions, whether Diane Johnson's entertaining new novel, ``Le
Mariage,'' is a tragedy or a comedy remains in doubt until its
final pages.
</P>
<P>
   The issue could be resolved either way in this story of
French-American misalliance, loosely a sequel to Johnson's amusing
``Le Divorce,'' in which one or two of the same minor characters
appeared. Thomas Ackroyd (Tim) Nolinger, a half-American,
half-Belgian journalist, is engaged from the opening pages to
Anne-Sophie d'Argel, a dealer in ``horsey artifacts, a hobby since
girlhood,'' who has a flea-market stall in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Their engagement suffers severe strains in the course of ``Le
Mariage'' _ misunderstandings, misapprehensions, false
expectations, differences of temperament, cultural clashes and the
usual anxieties attendant on impending nuptials. The charming,
well-situated apartment Tim finds for them is one flight up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never imagined living on the premier etage,'' Anne-Sophie
exclaims. ``You don't understand the French attitude about the
premier etage.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne-Sophie, a literal-minded person, relies on books for much
of what she knows about life. She looked in Henry Miller for
anatomical slang words in English to upgrade her erotic vocabulary,
but ``trying one or two of Miller's phrases had not had much effect
on Tim, she had concluded.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, the worldly and practical Estelle d'Argel, a
novelist, is not quite pleased by her daughter's fiance, having
hoped for ``a count or a promising politician, or a future
Academician, or at the least a sports figure _ if from a
respectable sport like tennis.'' Or ``at least someone French.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Tim and Anne-Sophie's relationship is challenged by
the elaborate concatenation of events Johnson contrives to test
them: a stolen medieval manuscript from the Morgan Library in New
York; the murder of one of Anne-Sophie's neighboring flea-market
vendors; the intrusion into their lives of a couple from Oregon who
are vaguely linked to ``black-helicopter people'' and survivalists
and religious fundamentalists and Y2K fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these complications seem rather far-fetched and
unintegrated in a novel that lacks the focus and elegance of ``Le
Divorce,'' perhaps because French-American relations lend
themselves better to metaphors of sundering than to those of
uniting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the new novel's overstretched plot does serve several
valuable purposes. For one thing, it links Tim and Anne-Sophie to
Serge Cray, a renowned if somewhat reclusive American film
director, and his wife, Clara Holly, a film actress who has retired
to run the couple's venerable chateau outside Paris, which was once
occupied by Madame du Barry, the mistress of Louis XV. Serge and
Clara's tense union is another referent of Johnson's title.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, what happens to Serge and Clara sets up one
of the novel's most pointed themes. The French in the story are
always complaining about the shortcomings of Americans, their lack
of subtlety, their fanaticism, their simple-mindedness and, above
all, their insidious effect on French culture. Yet how the French
behave in response to the Americans in the novel is, if anything,
even more egregious.
</P>
<P>
   Because Serge and Clara deplore the killing of wildlife, they
try to prohibit local hunters from shooting on their hectares. In
response, the townspeople declare war by accusing Clara of
desecrating her chateau even though it was a previous owner who
removed and sold its ``boiseries and cheminees _ its paneling and
fireplaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Against all logic, Clara is arrested and sentenced to prison.
French opinion becomes inflamed: ``L'affaire Cray, said Clovis
Mornay, a leading French intellectual, on a panel on French
television's Canal Plus on l'antiamericanisme, was a perfect
example of how the innate American desire for hegemony, expressed
by private citizens as much as in actions by the state, was
attempting to interfere with the centuries-old traditions of
France. It also was an example of Hollywood arrogance, and
Hollywood was itself an informal arm of the American state, perhaps
even, covertly, an actual arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet regardless of how cluttered the plot of ``Le Mariage'' may
be or how littered it is with misleading portents and developments
that never get resolved, the book is never dull to read. This is
thanks to the cynical delight that Johnson takes in her characters,
whether she is depicting Anne-Sophie's enchantment with American
commerce (``Oh, Teem, I have been to Circuit City. ... It is
heaven, what is left for me in life?'') or listing the small stock
of books in English in the library in the Crays' village (``by Poe,
William Styron, Melville, James Fenimore Cooper, and Erica Jong'').
</P>
<P>
   ``How can people sleep in Paris?'' one jet-lagged character
complains. ``Horns, sirens that warble in a way that vibrates the
nasal passages, loud car alarms setting themselves off in series,
like jungle messages being passed along. Enormous clashings of
broken glass, as if tons of bottles were being crushed, cars,
voices laughing under her windows, motorbikes starting up.''
</P>
<P>
   A little like all that goes on in the plot of ``Le Mariage.''
Except that it's not at all unpleasant because the one thing you
don't feel like doing is sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LE MARIAGE'
</P>
<P>
   By Diane Johnson
</P>
<P>
   322 pages. Dutton. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
