<HEADER>
A1450 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-29 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RECOGNITION OF COURAGE AND BRAVERY
</HEADLINE>
  
 
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arecent San Francisco Chronicle story described  &UR; Charles &LR; 
 &UR; Liteky &LR; , an Army chaplain who received the Medal of Honor for
saving the lives of comrades in Vietnam and returned it to protest
American foreign policy and practices.
</P>
<P>
   A specific target of Liteky's protest has been the School of the
Americas at Fort Benning, Ga., at which the U.S. Army trains Latin
American officers and noncoms. Returning the medal voluntarily
meant that Liteky gave up a tax-free lifetime monthly pension of
$600.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the story ran, reporter  &UR; Michael Taylor  &LR; got a
message for Liteky from a Bay Area lawyer (who wished to remain
anonymous): ``Enclosed please find our check for $600 _ one month's
worth of the Medal of Honor pension you gave up _ as a small token
of our appreciation for your valor as a soldier ... and as a highly
principled civilian.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer told Taylor that he had been ``reading a book about
Silicon Valley, and I saw that one fellow who was an avid sailor
had a $126,000 model of one of his yachts. The model was 38 inches
long, and he had it on his mantelpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was so refreshing to see an article about
somebody who's actually doing something for the welfare of mankind,
as opposed to someone who was adding up their net worth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CONSIDERING THE OSCARS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chloe Sevigny &LR; , nominated for best supporting actress Oscar for
``Boys Don't Cry,'' talked with SOMA magazine a few months ago,
just after  &UR; Angelina Jolie  &LR; _ who won the Oscar _ had won a Golden
Globe award in the same category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angelina Jolie won, I lost,'' she said. ``They love her there.
I was really starstruck and I loved to see all the stars, but I
don't know, awards, they're not for me. It was too soon. I don't
even know what I was doing there, really. It's nice to be
acknowledged, but I don't know, it's too soon in my career. Lucky
for me, it was a really bad year in film.''
</P>
<P>
   Sevigny, who wore  &UR; Yves St. Laurent  &LR; to the Golden Globes, said
``The whole dress thing was such stress. ... I don't know if I want
to go through that again.'' Sevigny said that &UR; Joan Rivers &LR; 
described her as looking as though ``I was going to a tea party,
but what does she know?'' She wore St. Laurent again last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As to the Oscars themselves, she said she didn't ``really care''
about them. ``They never award the films that I like. Many great
directors have never been recognized. That's the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Simon Doonan &LR; , former chief window-dresser at Barneys, has
begun a style column in the New York Observer, the first of which
pokes at celebrities ``borrowing'' designer dresses for awards
ceremonies. ``If you can't afford designer schmatas,'' he asks,
``who can?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _MSNBC says that  &UR; Howard Stern &LR; 's new girlfriend is  &UR; Robin &LR; 
 &UR; Givens &LR; ,  &UR; Mike Tyson &LR; 's ex.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _Rochester Big &AMP; Tall, which is headquartered in San Francisco,
has sent proud word that  &UR; Michael Clarke Duncan &LR;  of ``The Green
Mile'' was dressed for the Oscars by its Beverly Hills branch.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IS A HUNT ON? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Huntington Hartford &LR; , 88-year-old millionaire (the family
business was A&AMP;P), told Personals spy  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  that he's
looking for a long-lost granddaughter in San Francisco. The woman,
who would be in her late 30s, is the daughter of Hartford's
illegitimate son  &UR; Buzz Barton &LR; , who killed himself. Hartford never
allowed Barton to take his name.
</P>
<P>
   Nearing the end of his life, the eccentric (and some say dotty)
Hartford apparently feels guilty about spurning his son. His
fortune is said to be worth $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   An ex-Mrs. Hartford who still lives with her husband told New
York magazine there is no search, but Jones says the millionaire
asked him to throw a party to publicize his hunt.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I've got a 15-year-old son and a 10-year-old daughter, and
if &LR; 
 &UR; they were going to do one of the following things _ be an &LR; 
 &UR; alcoholic, be a drug offender, beat their wife or their husband, &LR; 
 &UR; or gamble _ I hope they would gamble.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Dear old dad  &UR; Pete Rose &LR;  in Playboy magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1902EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WONDERLAND-REVIEW-     03-29 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WONDERLAND-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WONDERLAND': WRUNG OUT, STRUNG OUT IN BEDLAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To watch ``Wonderland,'' the unsettling series set in a New York
psychiatric hospital, is to step into a world of pure chaos.
Everyone races, everyone yells, doctors scream instructions,
patients scream delusions, somebody dies, someone is saved and at
the end a viewer is wrung out. It is a perverse compliment to say
that near the end of the first episode you may wonder if you'll
ever want to enter this hellish atmosphere again.
</P>
<P>
   But the show is so gripping and often so dazzling in its visual
command that if you had two episodes on tape (as reviewers did) you
might watch them back to back, against your expectations. Whether
viewers who have a week to decompress will choose to re-enter a
landscape of such excruciating intensity is the big question ABC
and ``Wonderland'' are staring at.
</P>
<P>
   This new series is the anti-``E.R.,'' and the fact that it is
running opposite that other medical show is the least of the
reasons. ``Wonderland'' defies the conventions of episodic
television. When someone dies on ``E.R.,'' a doctor's heroic
struggle offers redeeming light and uplift. The doctors of
``Wonderland'' are dedicated, but the very first episode reveals
that one has made a medical mistake that will haunt and maybe ruin
lives, including her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' (originally called ``Bellevue'' for the hospital
where it was researched) is even more directly the anti-``Chicago
Hope.'' It was created, written and directed by Peter Berg, who
played the volatile Billy Kronk on that series. Berg's wily new
series turns his old one upside down. While the ``Chicago Hope''
doctors thrive on up-to-the-minute medical wizardry, the
psychiatrists of ``Wonderland'' are simply trying to keep
themselves, and their patients, afloat. With ``E.R.'' aging into
predictability, ``Chicago Hope'' ready for the scrap heap and the
new ``City of Angels'' already a stale imitation of the others
(despite its largely black cast), ``Wonderland'' comes at just the
right time to reinvigorate the hospital genre.
</P>
<P>
   Because the patients in ``Wonderland'' are psychiatric cases,
the series has a surreal aura, sparing and effectively used. Here a
patient behind barred windows looks down at his slippers and sees a
tiny rhino step around them. Because these shots from the patient's
perspective are rare, watching the show is not like existing in
some mad state of mind. The effect is more jolting, as if the
sanity of the doctors and the illness of the patients were present
in the air, at times colliding with a physical force.
</P>
<P>
   What saves the series from total bleakness is the shaky order
the doctors impose. They are played by a spectacular cast. Ted
Levine is the head of the criminal psychiatry department, Dr.
Robert Banger, who is battling his ex-wife for custody of their two
small sons. Levine is still best known for his chilling performance
as the killer in ``The Silence of the Lambs.'' Add to that his
ominous deep voice and large presence and Banger is not instantly
likable, even though he is first seen making Mickey Mouse-shaped
pancakes for his sons. But Levine is remarkable in making the stern
and thoughtful Banger the sympathetic center and conscience of the
series without moving an inch toward sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Donovan is calmly powerful as Dr. Neil Harrison, also a
forensic psychiatrist. His pregnant wife, Dr. Lyla Garrity
(Michelle Forbes, once the coroner on ``Homicide''), is the head of
the emergency department at the hospital, called Rivervue here.
</P>
<P>
   Early in Thursday night's premiere, as a man walks through Times
Square during morning rush hour, his thoughts are heard in
voiceover: He babbles about Zeus and transmitters. Abruptly he
takes out a gun and shoots half a dozen people. When the police
take him to Rivervue, it turns out that Garrity, cranky, exhausted
and wrong, had examined and released him the week before.
</P>
<P>
   There are horrifying scenes in ``Wonderland'': the shooting in
Times Square and the aftermath in the Rivervue emergency room, when
the pregnant Garrity is stabbed in the stomach. But individual
scenes are not what make the series hard to take; the
relentlessness of its nervous energy does. The cacophony of people
yelling seems constant; the jangly visual style mirrors the
unrelieved tension and high-voltage impact of the story. When
Garrity is attacked, the camera picks up isolated images as she
sees them: one patient's bloody leg, another's bleeding neck.
</P>
<P>
   Berg also wrote and directed ``Very Bad Things,'' a 1998 black
comedy about murders. The film didn't completely pull off its
humor, but Berg was not afraid to go over the edge trying. He
brings that daring and a touch of dark wit to ``Wonderland,'' but
the series is also shrewdly connected to the world of real people.
When the Times Square killer, Wendell Rickle (Leland Orser), is
arrested, he recites his own Miranda rights, ``like `N.Y.P.D.
Blue,''' he says. The line astutely captures the way so many people
gain any knowledge about the police, and also winks at television
cliches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' poses significant questions in a dramatic,
unpreachy manner. Banger tries to protect and treat Rickle in the
second episode; earlier Harrison had tried to strangle him. Should
a mad killer be forgiven or punished?
</P>
<P>
   And the show sheds light on the rest of network television. This
series makes the pablum of typical happy endings understandable;
they're easier. Here, even the commercials may come as a relief
from the tension. ``Wonderland'' asks viewers to be discomfited
week after week and trust that the effort will be rewarded. Even
the toughest series tend to get soft over time, but for now the
uncompromising ``Wonderland'' is worth every demand it makes.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WONDERLAND'
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Thursday night at 10
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Touchstone Television Productions, LLC, in
association with Imagine Television. Created, written and directed
by Peter Berg. Berg, Tony Krantz, Ron Howard and Brian Grazer,
executive producers; John David Coles, co-executive producer; Peter
R. McIntosh, producer; Sirad Balducci, associate producer.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Ted Levine (Dr. Robert Banger), Martin Donovan (Dr. Neil
Harrison), Michelle Forbes (Dr. Lyla Garrity), Patricia Clarkson
(Tammy Banger), Sharon Wilkins (Mrs. Brown), Linda Emond (ADA
Strictler), Erik Per Sullivan (Tucker Banger), Brendan McVeigh
(Mick Banger), Matthew Sussman (Emanuel Treyhill), Michele Barker
(Julie McCray), Leland Orser (Wendell Rickle), Jay O. Sanders (Ed
Butowsky), George DiCenzo (therapist).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1902EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
