   A few days after the story ran, reporter  &UR; Michael Taylor  &LR; got a
message for Liteky from a Bay Area lawyer (who wished to remain
anonymous): ``Enclosed please find our check for $600 _ one month's
worth of the Medal of Honor pension you gave up _ as a small token
of our appreciation for your valor as a soldier ... and as a highly
principled civilian.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer told Taylor that he had been ``reading a book about
Silicon Valley, and I saw that one fellow who was an avid sailor
had a $126,000 model of one of his yachts. The model was 38 inches
long, and he had it on his mantelpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was so refreshing to see an article about
somebody who's actually doing something for the welfare of mankind,
as opposed to someone who was adding up their net worth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CONSIDERING THE OSCARS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chloe Sevigny &LR; , nominated for best supporting actress Oscar for
``Boys Don't Cry,'' talked with SOMA magazine a few months ago,
just after  &UR; Angelina Jolie  &LR; _ who won the Oscar _ had won a Golden
Globe award in the same category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angelina Jolie won, I lost,'' she said. ``They love her there.
I was really starstruck and I loved to see all the stars, but I
don't know, awards, they're not for me. It was too soon. I don't
even know what I was doing there, really. It's nice to be
acknowledged, but I don't know, it's too soon in my career. Lucky
for me, it was a really bad year in film.''
</P>
<P>
   Sevigny, who wore  &UR; Yves St. Laurent  &LR; to the Golden Globes, said
``The whole dress thing was such stress. ... I don't know if I want
to go through that again.'' Sevigny said that &UR; Joan Rivers &LR; 
described her as looking as though ``I was going to a tea party,
but what does she know?'' She wore St. Laurent again last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As to the Oscars themselves, she said she didn't ``really care''
about them. ``They never award the films that I like. Many great
directors have never been recognized. That's the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Simon Doonan &LR; , former chief window-dresser at Barneys, has
begun a style column in the New York Observer, the first of which
pokes at celebrities ``borrowing'' designer dresses for awards
ceremonies. ``If you can't afford designer schmatas,'' he asks,
``who can?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _MSNBC says that  &UR; Howard Stern &LR; 's new girlfriend is  &UR; Robin &LR; 
 &UR; Givens &LR; ,  &UR; Mike Tyson &LR; 's ex.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _Rochester Big &AMP; Tall, which is headquartered in San Francisco,
has sent proud word that  &UR; Michael Clarke Duncan &LR;  of ``The Green
Mile'' was dressed for the Oscars by its Beverly Hills branch.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IS A HUNT ON? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Huntington Hartford &LR; , 88-year-old millionaire (the family
business was A&AMP;P), told Personals spy  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  that he's
looking for a long-lost granddaughter in San Francisco. The woman,
who would be in her late 30s, is the daughter of Hartford's
illegitimate son  &UR; Buzz Barton &LR; , who killed himself. Hartford never
allowed Barton to take his name.
</P>
<P>
   Nearing the end of his life, the eccentric (and some say dotty)
Hartford apparently feels guilty about spurning his son. His
fortune is said to be worth $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   An ex-Mrs. Hartford who still lives with her husband told New
York magazine there is no search, but Jones says the millionaire
asked him to throw a party to publicize his hunt.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I've got a 15-year-old son and a 10-year-old daughter, and
if &LR; 
 &UR; they were going to do one of the following things _ be an &LR; 
 &UR; alcoholic, be a drug offender, beat their wife or their husband, &LR; 
 &UR; or gamble _ I hope they would gamble.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Dear old dad  &UR; Pete Rose &LR;  in Playboy magazine.
