</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PAPA'S SONG': A DYSFUNCTIONAL TRANS-ATLANTIC FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For its first half, ``Papa's Song,'' which opens
Thursday at Anthology Film Archives, is an interesting drama of
domestic tension and cross-cultural misunderstanding. Nico Verema
(Rene van Asten), a decorous, somewhat gloomy Dutch magistrate,
lives happily with his wife, Shirley (Romana Vrede), who is from
Curacao. Shirley's two young nephews, in the Netherlands to escape
a bad situation at home, complete the household.
</P>
<P>
   Its atmosphere of calm bourgeois propriety is soon upended by
the arrival of the boys' mother, Magda (Lisette Merenciana). To
describe Shirley's and Magda's relationship as volatile would be an
understatement: They careen from screaming recrimination to tearful
tenderness without stopping for breath. Nico tries to mediate and
soothe, but when Shirley, who cannot bear children, demands that he
impregnate her sister, the good judge finds himself entangled in an
intergenerational, trans-Atlantic web of family dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa's Song,'' directed by Sander Francken from a script he
wrote with Norman de Palm, touches on a number of fascinating and
difficult themes, including the state of race relations in the
contemporary Netherlands, a subject American audiences are likely
to know little about, and one that Francken, at first, treats with
admirable subtlety. Unfortunately, when Magda's estranged husband,
Hugo (Victor Bottenbly), arrives from the Antilles to claim her and
their children, the film takes a disastrous turn toward overwrought
melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Magda and Shirley share a family history so
baroque in its horrors that it wrecks not only their psychological
stability but the film's coherence as well. The degradations that
the women suffered at the hands of their father _ glimpsed in
nightmarish flashbacks confusingly rendered from Nico's point of
view _ are meant to explain their current problems. Instead, the
more we learn about their lurid childhood in Curacao, the more
baffling their present behavior seems.
</P>
<P>
   Nico's psychology is similarly opaque. His inner life is
conveyed through dreamy flashbacks to his Caribbean childhood and
the pained smile of earnest liberalism he wears around black
people, including his wife. His behavior, including his habit of
siding with the erratic Magda and the abusive Hugo against his own
wife, is often inexplicable, even within the terms that the
filmmakers set out.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the contrast between his uptight, rule-bound ways and the
sensuality, music and violence of Shirley and her kin trafficks in
tired stereotypes about frigid Europeans and the hotblooded,
passionate people they once colonized. A powerful psychological
drama might have been wrung from this story. But ``Papa's Song''
is, in the end, drearily literal-minded and depressingly
predictable in its ideas of cultural conflict, sibling rivalry and
childhood trauma.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:  &QL; 
'PAPA'S SONG' Directed by Sander Francken; written (in Dutch and
Papiamento, with English subtitles) by Norman de Palm and Francken,
based on an original story by de Palm; director of photography,
Rogier Stoffers; edited by Herman P. Koerts; score by Rob Hauser,
songs by Roy Louis and theme song by Bibi Provence; produced by de
Palm. At Anthology Film Archives in Manhattan. Running time: 95
minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WITH: Rene Van Asten (Nico), Romana Vrede (Shirley), Lisette
Merenciana (Magda), Victor Bottenbley (Hugo), Tyronne Meerzorg
(Juan) and Vergill Ford (Roy).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
