<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1455 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TORNADO-ARTSDISTRICT-     03-29 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-ARTSDISTRICT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART GALLERY IS SHATTERED BY TORNADO'S FURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Holding a tiny cross of wood and metal,
Carol Henderson shakes her head. The owner of the Carol Henderson
Gallery, which was all but gutted by a tornado Tuesday, can't quite
fathom how this tiny artwork clung to its fragile hook. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only piece of art in its series that didn't get blown
away,'' Henderson says. ``The artist calls it a `milagro,' which
means miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson could have used lots of little miracles in the face of
the tornado's capricious power. The Carol Henderson Gallery was the
only business in the Seventh Street Chicotsky's Center to suffer
extreme damage. By the time Carol Henderson returned to her gallery
Wednesday morning, an ankle-deep pile of glass lined the front of
her exhibit spaces. Her once-pristine storefront was boarded up
like a tenement, her white interior walls gashed as if a predator
had struck. Acoustic tiles and a mass of electric wires, outlets
and track lighting fixtures sagged from the ceiling, clinging to a
plaster thread.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and artists with a long history with Henderson descended
on the gallery to bubble-wrap paintings, take inventory and offer
free food and some solace.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just tell me when you want lunch, and I'll deliver it,''
said Evelyn Siegel, who owns a neighboring gallery. ``Thank God you
weren't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you so much,'' said Henderson, allowing herself to cry
for perhaps the first time in a harrowing 24 hours. ``It's just so
upsetting and sad.''
</P>
<P>
   All Henderson can do now, buoyed by a stream of unanticipated
kindness, is to keep digging her gallery out of the detritus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know that a man showed up not long after the tornado
hit with his hands full of the our jewelry that had just been
carried away by the wind,'' Henderson said. ``And several of our
prints, which had blown hundreds of yards away behind the nearby
coffee shop, were also returned.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carol Henderson Gallery has long been acknowledged as one of
the city's most noted exhibit spaces. Now, the only sign of its
famously eclectic art collection is the dozens of hooks dimpling
the walls. Still, in the wake of the ferocious twister, much of
Henderson's collection of paintings, works on paper, blown glass
and fine-art jewelry survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just calling all the artists to let them know what's going
on,'' Henderson said. ``I feel so badly because these artists all
entrusted their work to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Fort Worth Cultural District, Carol Henderson Gallery
apparently received the lion's share of the tornado's fury. The
rest of the Arts District was virtually unscathed by the twisters.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell Museum reported downed and split cedar elm trees and
branches littering its grounds, but neither its building nor
artwork suffered any damage. The Amon Carter Museum and the Modern
Art Museum of Fort Worth main construction sites weren't damaged.
The Carter's downtown annex was also untouched.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern at Sundance Square was less fortunate. The popular
downtown museum and gift shop, currently housing 26 works of art by
Andy Warhol, Keith Haring and Helmut Newton, among others, was
hosting a private party when the tornado destroyed seven large
windows along its south side. A hail of glass shards chased the
more than 60 partygoers to the back of the museum. No one was hurt,
and none of the art, which was immediately wrapped up, was damaged.
The windows have been boarded up. and it will be at least five days
before the Modern at Sundance Square reopens.
</P>
<P>
   It could take many weeks for the Carol Henderson Gallery to
regain its footing as one of the Cultural District's most
frequented galleries. Shovels, garden rakes and an industrial
strength vacuum cleaner are being used to scour the billions of
glass particles that encrust its interior.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson can't even speculate on how much it will cost to bring
her gallery back to life. All she can do is keep repeating, like a
well-worn mantra, ``No one was hurt; no one was hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1906EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WINTER-MUSIC-ART-2TAK     03-29 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: LIFE'S A DANCE (CHICKA-BOOM!) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: S. Mnrat Uncuoglu, and Deee-Lite and Darin McFadyen are
CQ)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ As hundreds of people milled past in the
lobby of the Radisson Deauville Resort Hotel here, Kenny Bobien, a
dance-music disc jockey and producer, assessed a homemade CD
through the silvery headphones attached to his portable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``This track is hot!'' he said ``I'm feeling that!''
</P>
<P>
   S. Mnrat Uncuoglu, who had produced the track, was not content
with praise. ``I need distribution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a scene that would repeat itself with variations
throughout the 15th annual Winter Music Conference, which took over
Miami Beach for five days of nearly nonstop music to conclude after
dawn on Thursday. The conference brought together disc jockeys,
singers, producers, managers, broadcasters, Web site makers,
equipment manufacturers, graphic designers, journalists and others
connected to the music, most of it electronic, that makes bass
speakers go boom around the world. They are the movers and shakers
in a business that makes people move and shake.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding an occasional pop hit, like Eiffel 65's current
``Blue,'' dance music accounts for only a small percentage of the
recording market in the United States. (The figure is higher in
European countries, where instrumental dance tracks can become
radio favorites and pop hits.) Hits by Prodigy, the Chemical
Brothers and Fatboy Slim raised hopes in the American recording
business that a newly named category, electronica, might become the
next big thing in the late '90s. But the hits worked as novelties,
not standard-bearers for the genre. Of course, some disc jockeys
and producers seem to make it a point of honor not to market
themselves. They perform tucked away in sound booths and often
change names from project to project.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many fans prefer to enjoy the music as a momentary pleasure
on the dance floor, not as a permanent acquisition, and clubs are
thriving. A star disc jockey can draw thousands of people for the
night, then move on to the next stop on an international circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is already an alternative culture,'' said D.B. Barkenham,
a producer who is a co-founder of F-111 Records and the owner of
Breakbeat Science, a Manhattan record store. ``It doesn't need to
be hyped. It's going to grow organically.''
</P>
<P>
   Because dance music can be produced cheaply, in a home studio or
on a personal computer, a dance single can be profitable with sales
that barely register on the pop charts: a major success if it sells
35,000, a runaway hit with 100,000. And because disc jockeys,
soundtrack compilers and advertisers are constantly searching for
new material with a beat, countless small labels are eager to
supply it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be a need for dance music,'' said the disc
jockey and producer Touche, also known as the Wiseguys. ``And it
will go wherever it's going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other businesses, dance music has high hopes for the
Internet. Judge Jules, a BBC radio disc jockey and dance music
tastemaker, said that Webcasts of disc jockey sets direct from
clubs had the potential to expand the audience greatly, bypassing
the lack of dance music on American commercial radio. Web sites
like www.ministryofsound.com, www.betalounge.com,
www.raveworld.net, www.groovetech.com, www.remixLive.com,
www.netmix.com and www.platform.net are among those that make dance
music available online.
</P>
<P>
   The Winter Music Conference expanded to 5,000 people this year
from 3,500 last year, each paying up to $395 to hear panel
discussions and read one another's name tags. They toted stacks of
12-inch vinyl discs and wielded shiny little gadgets, from CD
players to video cameras to computers. They huddled over tour
plans, production budgets, demo discs, international licensing
deals and Internet promotions. Then they went out to hear the
results of their transactions in a dance-music marathon with two
dozen events each day.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbathers by the Radisson's pool were serenaded by dance-pop
divas and disc jockey battles. Fifty blocks away, in South Beach,
showcases started shortly after noon and extended well past dawn.
There was house music in theater-size clubs, hip-hop at poolsides,
neo-lounge in courtyards, jungle in basements, funk on a rooftop,
ambient music in hotel suites. Nearly every top disc jockey in the
business was in town to spin records; one event, scheduled for 8
Monday night through noon on Tuesday, had a lineup of more than 44
disc jockeys. Along with those who paid to join the conference,
many more people descended on South Beach just for the music.
</P>
<P>
   When electronic dance music started percolating out of drum
machines and synthesizers more than 20 years ago, it was touted as
the sound of the future. Now it also has an extensive past, tinged
with nostalgia. In a show on Monday night the revered disc jockey
Danny Tenaglia celebrated his 25th year in the business with a set
that stretched about 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the music that pounded out of the South Beach clubs _
and in a noon-to-midnight beach event on Saturday afternoon, timed
to coincide with both the conference and spring break, that drew
15,000 people to hear music on five stages _ stuck to established
genres. The disc jockeys generally improvised within familiar
beats. Their job was to please the crowds, not trip them up, and
the disc jockeys willingly stayed within the bounds of house
music's boom-chicka-boom, trance music's marching 4/4 stomp and
jungle's skittering, fractured mixture of double-time and half-time
rhythms. Audiences knew their parts; when George Acosta played a
trance set on the beach and stopped the beat for a long sustained
note, the whole crowd threw its hands in the air and whooped.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The disc jockey Towa Tei, formerly with Deee-Lite, said his job
was about biofeedback with the crowd. ``Disc jockeys have been
researching how records work for people to dance,'' he said. ``But
there's a danger in the music being too functional. Before it's
functional, music has to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of the conference, and of the dance music it
gathered, is house music, the Latin-tinged 4/4 beat that survived
when disco music was laughed off the pop charts. Forged in a
Greenwich Village club called the Paradise Garage, house music has
gone on to spawn countless subgenres that disc jockeys distinguish:
deep house, progressive house, hard house, tech house, trance,
hip-house, garage, speed garage. The seemingly simple 4/4 beat and
moderate tempo of house music make it both durable and flexible; it
impels dancers into motion and meshes with a whole family of
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Masters at Work, a New York-based production, songwriting and
disc jockey team, marked its 10th anniversary with an elegant
demonstration of house music as a generously recombinant beat and a
musical embrace of multiethnic possibilities. In disc jockey sets,
David Morales and Little Louie Vega segued from house music into
salsa, funk, disco and reggae. Then a live band backed up the
singers they had produced, pushing toward pop and gospel. In club
sets, disc jockeys transformed the house beat from a brutal,
austere thud to an ebullient swing; topped it with jazzy flourishes
and eerie dissonances, and even used it to back up hip-hop-style
record scratching.
</P>
<P>
   Some showcases hinted at newer possibilities. Live musicians
performed as if they were in the hands of disc jockeys. A band
called Faze Action, including strings and horns, played '70s funk
as it had been revived by acid-jazz disc jockeys a decade later:
adding a steady dance beat, overlaying the tunes with synthesizer
swoops and pausing for extended percussion breaks. Supreme Beings
of Leisure set Geri Soriano Lightwood's slinky, jazz-tinged vocals
above drum machine rhythms from jungle and hip-hop, as if she were
part of a producer's extended mix.
</P>
<P>
   Jungle, from the mid-'90s, still has some variations left. D.J.
Craze demonstrated turntablism _ the virtuoso refinement of hip-hop
record scratching _ and then combined it with jungle in a set that
sounded jubilantly reckless. James Hardway, an alias of David
Harrow, used samples of jazz trumpet, Cuban percussion and Jamaican
voices to humanize the cold, hurtling momentum of jungle. He said
his next album, though it would be full of computer manipulation,
used no electronic sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenecia, a duo from Miami, explored dance music as electronic
improvisation. Using laptop computers, a drum machine and a mixing
board, they played pieces that sounded like madcap contraptions:
buzzing, beeping and ratcheting with dizzying syncopation. Implying
the beat instead of pounding it out, they sent dancers into
frenetic motion.
</P>
<P>
   Freq Nasty, the disc jockey alias of Darin McFadyen, has been
anointed in Britain as a standard-bearer for an emerging subgenre
called nu skool breaks. In one of his three sets Tuesday night, he
knocked together idioms and fearlessly changed tempos and textures,
from electronic blips to buoyant Caribbean soca to slow dub reggae
to an overlaid rap, like a latter-day version of the master hip-hop
disc jockey Grandmaster Flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have the funk and dance element, and you have to
have the hooks,'' he said. ``But at the same time you can be
twisting up the genres, mashing things up. What I'm trying to do is
to bring sounds to people that make them dance first. And then they
think, `What was  &UR; that? &LR; '''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 1909EST &QL; 
