<HEADER>
A1459 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-STRIPPING-HNS &LR;      03-29 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-STRIPPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NUDE DANCERS MAY HAVE TO COVER UP COURT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nude dancers at some of the nation's 3,000 strip
clubs may have to put on some clothes in the wake of a Supreme
Court ruling Wednesday that local governments may force them to
wear G-strings and pasties.
</P>
<P>
   In a splintered decision, the court said cities may ban fully
nude dancing as part of an effort to fight such ``negative
secondary effects'' as crime and traffic problems caused by adult
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be sure, requiring dancers to wear pasties and G-strings
may not greatly reduce these secondary effects, but (the court)
requires only that the regulation further the interest in combating
such effects,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   With its decision, the court upheld a public-indecency ordinance
in Erie, Pa., that was designed to stop traffic and prostitution
problems around the Kandyland nude-dancing club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erie's efforts to protect public health and safety are clearly
within the city's police powers,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania's highest court had struck down the ordinance in
1998, ruling that it unlawfully restricted freedom of expression
protected by the Constitution's First Amendment.While acknowledging
that nude dancing is ``expressive conduct,'' O'Connor said it
``falls only within the outer ambit'' of First Amendment
protection. She said the Erie law did not violate the Constitution
because it was aimed at combating the ``negative secondary
effects'' associated with adult entertainment rather than at the
erotic message of nude dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Sprenkle, Erie's assistant city solicitor, praised the
decision. ``We didn't ban any expression. What's being regulated is
the means of expression,'' she said.Sprenkle said dancers at a nude
dancing club in the city ``will be required to cover up to the
extent required by the ordinance.''
</P>
<P>
   However, John H. Weston, attorney for the former Erie
nude-dancing club owner who challenged the ordinance, said the
ruling may lead to many attempts to ban nude dancing, but that
``sexually oriented businesses will always thrive'' because of
their popularity.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' decision helped clarify a 1991 Supreme Court
ruling that allowed Indiana to ban all barroom-style nude dancing
under a state law generally prohibiting public nudity.The court
said then that nude dancing is subject to some First Amendment
protection but that community interests of safety and morality may
present overriding concerns.Since that ruling, many lower courts
have complained that the decision was too vague for them to
implement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in Wednesday's decision, the high court was seriously split,
with several of the justices agreeing on some issues and
disagreeing on others. As a result, it may not provide the lower
courts with as much clarity as they hoped.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, six other justices joined O'Connor in agreeing to
allow a ban on nude dancing to prevent ``negative secondary
effects.'' Those justices were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justices Stephen G. Breyer, Anthony M. Kennedy, Antonin Scalia,
David Souter and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   But Scalia and Thomas argued that the court should go further
and allow cities to ban nude dancing on the grounds of ``good
morals.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter also had problems with the O'Connor's opinion, writing in
his own opinion that he believed the city had not shown the
so-called negative secondary effects of the strip club. Therefore,
Souter said, while he accepted a ban on nude dancing to prevent
such effects, he could not endorse the Erie ban because city
officials had not proved that these effects existed.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens and Ruth Bader Ginsburg dissented
from the ruling completely. Stevens wrote in their opinion that the
court had incorrectly decided that secondary effects ``justify the
total suppression of protected speech.''``Indeed, the plurality
opinion concludes that admittedly trivial advancements of a state's
interests may provide the basis for censorship,'' Stevens wrote.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
