<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CZECH-WRITER-ART-NYT &LR;      03-29 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-WRITER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOMERSAULTS OF A CZECH WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(cjl) 
 By ALISON SMALE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a land of letters ruled by a playwright presiding from his
castle on the hill over a dreamy city that has brought out the
absurd in writers from Kafka to Kundera, Jachym Topol is hailed as
a bright new literary star.
</P>
<P>
   His 1994 novel ``Sestra'' (``Sister'') won plaudits from writers
like Ivan Klima and President Vaclav Havel himself. His poetry and
second novel, ``Angel,'' have also earned the eclectic Topol a
place in Prague's pantheon of those who chronicle its ever fertile
mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense Topol was born to his task. His father, Josef, a
friend of Havel, is a playwright, poet, Shakespeare translator and
dissident; his grandfather, Karel Schulz, was also a writer. Raised
in the aftermath of the Prague Spring and formed by the
intellectual dissenters around him, Topol became, at age 15, the
youngest person to sign the Charter 77 human rights document.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Topol was at the Kitchen, an arts center in
Greenwich Village, reading to an enthusiastic crowd drawn by the
publication of the English-language version of ``Sestra,'' titled
``City Sister Silver'' (Catbird Press). Reading in Czech, Topol
delivered the staccato somersaults of his text with the pace and
energy of a guitar riff; his American translator, Alex Zucker,
followed with a more measured English delivery of two passages, one
a mocking account of how a famous writer came to pen his novel, the
second a far more serious deliberation on poverty set on a garbage
dump that Topol said was inspired by a real dump he visited on the
outskirts of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The book's main character lives through the Velvet Revolution,
which ended Communist rule, and all the weirdness that has
followed, but there is also a dream sequence set in Auschwitz and
innumerable leaps of imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Lanzillotto, the host for the program, freely compared the
work to Salman Rushdie's ``Midnight's Children.'' ``Sometimes,''
she said, ``we are caught up in form: we go to fiction school, to
poetry school. This guy goes to the revolution and busts through
form like through skin itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Topol's first poems became lyrics for the rock band Psi
Vojaci (Dog Soldiers), which is led by his younger brother, Filip.
After the 1989 revolution, Topol did investigative reporting for
the weekly Respekt, then founded his own review, Revolver. Nowadays
he is almost settled, living in Prague with his wife and 3-year-old
daughter, of whom he said: ``Three days, it's good to be away from
a child. On the fourth day it's already difficult. After that it's
terrible.'' He professes amazement that he, a child of what he
terms ``the monster,'' or Soviet Communism, himself has a child who
will go to an ordinary Prague kindergarten and immediately start
learning English.
</P>
<P>
   His own English is good, but with the precision of a man whose
very life is words, he criticizes his inflection as he orders a
spinach omelet in a Polish-American diner in Brooklyn. His Czech is
a mixture of fact and fantasy, say aficionados and his translator,
Zucker. The language traces the history of its land, the backdrop
that has given birth to much rich writing with resonance far beyond
Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As Topol writes in ``Sestra'': ``The tongue I use is one of
Czechs, of Slavs, of slaves, of onetime slaves to Germans and
Russians, and it's a dog's tongue. A clever dog knows how to
survive and what price to pay for survival. He knows when to crouch
and when to dodge and when to bite, it's in his tongue. It's tender
and cruel, and has some good old words of love, I think, it's a
swift and agile tongue, and it's always happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even the Avars could get this tongue of mine, not tanks or
burning borders or the most repulsive human species of all:
cowardly teachers. What will eventually get it is cash in a
shrinking world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
