A1462 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TORNADO-CLEANUP-TEX     03-29 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-CLEANUP-TEX </SLUG>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TORNADO-TEXAS) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CRYSTAL YEDNAK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Armed with large brooms, Fort Worth street
crews began about 6 a.m. Wednesday, cleaning streets that were
pelted with glass, rooftops, trees, plastic foam and dirt the night
before. Dumptrucks and bulldozers backed them up, hauling large
debris out of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   A slight breeze moving through at midafternoon did little to dry
the sweat that cleanup crews had earned working since early
morning.
</P>
<P>
   After the storm hit Tuesday night, workers were called in to
clear blocked drains that were flooding streets. They erected
barricades for police and moved trees that were sprawled across
roads, working until 2 or 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just laid down and had to get right back up,'' said street
services employee Darrell Clakely, who said he awoke at 5:40 a.m.
to head back downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is our hometown, and we gotta take care of home.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the shade of a city dump truck, Stephen Mock quickly
ate a late lunch that the Red Cross provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been nonstop,'' he said, his face glistening with sweat.
</P>
<P>
   His crew started on Houston Street, sweeping debris from
sidewalks onto the street so the heavier machinery could pick it
up. A chipper was brought in to dispose of downed trees
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in all the chaos, though, the work has gone pretty
smooth,'' Mock said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his crew cleaned up after the 1995 tornado that hit the
Texas Christian University area, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all different debris this time,'' street services
employee Nicholas Mendoza said. ``All glass.''
</P>
<P>
   As the workers finished off hamburgers, a call came about a
downed tree blocking Fifth Street and Summit Avenue. The crew
climbed into the truck and took off.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, other Transportation and Public Works crews boarded up a
gaping hole in the corner of the public library building, stapling
plastic over the boards to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street at Hunter Plaza, Water Department workers
pumped water out of the apartment building. Four sprinklers had
been set off, flooding the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Private cleanup companies began the arduous process of picking
through the buildings and private parking lots downtown.
</P>
<P>
   As they moved, the crews left behind clean patches in the debris
field.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
