<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-FUTURE-     03-29 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME JAPANESE CONCERNED U.S. BASEBALL PRESENCE WILL HURT LOCAL
LEAGUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Originally skedded as BBN-METS-CUBS-FANS .) 
(jt) 
 By CALVIN SIMS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For 12-year-old Kenji Nakanishi, watching the New York
Mets and the Chicago Cubs play their opening season game at the
Tokyo Dome Wednesday night was better than opening presents at
``Kurisumasu,'' Japanese for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a dream come true,'' the sixth grader said, trying
to control his emotions. ``I got to see my baseball heroes Sammy
Sosa and Mike Piazza, and I feel so excited, so tingly inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Few Japanese in the sellout crowd of 55,000 roaring spectators,
who paid as much as $120 for a ticket, would seem to disagree with
young Kenji's assessment of the first regular season major league
baseball game to be played outside North America.
</P>
<P>
   Motoharu Yanamoto, managing editor of Weekly Baseball Magazine,
said that for Japanese fans, holding a major league season opener
in Tokyo was ``a monumental, unbelievable event.'' The game was a
rare opportunity to witness two of America's top teams in real
competition, he said. In the past, only major league exhibition
games have been held in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   American and Japanese organizers of the event have said they
hope the games will create new markets for major league baseball
overseas while increasing interest in Japan's professional baseball
leagues and improving the level of play.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was euphoric over the opening of Japan's
normally highly protected borders to a prominent foreign product
like major league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the Mets and Cubs arrived here last weekend to great
fanfare, many Japanese teams were expressing concerns that allowing
the immensely popular major league into Japan could be devastating
to the country's own professional baseball leagues, siphoning off
its top talent and fan base.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiaki Kanai, secretary general of the Japan Professional
Baseball Commissioner's Office, said that the commissioner's office
agonized over whether to allow the major leagues to stage the games
but eventually decided to grant approval because Japan could no
longer resist the growing globalization of sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Japanese baseball is to survive, it has to also make its
debut on the global stage, and we need to gain experience competing
at that level,'' Kanai said. ``So we decided to open the door to
major league baseball so we could raise the technical level and
interest in the game in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   With attendance at many Japanese baseball games already on the
decline, due to the country's stubborn recession and waning
interest, some team officials are afraid that given a choice, fans
will spend less money on local games and save their precious yen
for the major league season games. The officials are also upset
over the high price of the major league tickets, which cost $120
for the best seats, compared with $59 for comparable seats at a
Yomiuri Giants game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money fans have is limited these days, and I wonder if
fans who bought expensive tickets to the major league games will
come to our games, too,'' an official of a Tokyo-based baseball
team told the Asahi Shinbun newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, with revenues from ticket sales, merchandising, and
broadcast rights flat or falling at many of Japan's 12 baseball
franchises, the teams can scarcely afford to match the high
salaries that their top players can make in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Some local sports commentators and reporters said that the
concerns of local Japanese teams are not entirely unjustified,
especially if the number of major league baseball games staged in
Japan increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real danger for Japanese baseball is if we start to see a
repeat and expansion of major league games here and if we see a
growing exodus of top Japanese players to America,'' Yanamoto, the
magazine editor, said. ``That could rob us of local talent and
focus the attention of Japanese fans to the major league teams
where our local boys will be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the complaints about major league baseball are coming
from Japanese teams that are struggling economically and have
limited national television exposure. Japanese baseball is divided
into two leagues, each with six clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Teams in the Central League are profitable because they have a
huge fan base, mainly because they compete against the Yomiuri
Giants, who are backed by a powerful media organization that
broadcasts all its games. Clubs in the Pacific League are generally
not profitable and have trouble filling their stadiums. To be
profitable a team must generate about $50 million in annual
revenues. Some baseball watchers are concerned that if the
situation does not improve, the sport could be reduced to one
league with as little as eight or even six teams.
</P>
<P>
   Masaru Ikei, a political science professor at Keio University,
who is considered an expert on Japanese baseball, said that it
remains unclear whether major league baseball would help or hurt
the sport in Japan. But Ikei said that he believes the way Japanese
play baseball will be greatly influenced by the staging of major
leagues games in Japan. He expects that Japanese baseball games,
which are notoriously slow, will become faster and that umpires,
who are not highly regarded in Japan, will gain new credibility as
the country adopts practices of the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Brosnan, executive vice president in charge of international
business for major league baseball, sought to dispel any notions
that his franchise was trampling over Japanese baseball in its
efforts to expand internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese baseball has had some concerns about this project but
we've consulted with them and we've been very mindful to avoid the
downside of those issues,'' Brosnan said. ``Anyone who says these
major league games will make the fans think that Japanese teams
can't compete hasn't been at the same games I've seen this week.''
The Giants won in exhibition games this week over the Cubs and the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Many baseball officials and commentators believe that there is
enough interest in baseball in Japan that fans will watch both
local and international team play.
</P>
<P>
   Satoshi Izumida, a 22-year-old part-time worker, certainly
thinks so. At the end of Wednesday night's season opener, Izumida,
who attended two of the major league exhibition matches this week,
prepared to spend the night outside the Tokyo Dome to insure that
he could obtain tickets to the Giants' season opener on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like both the local teams here in Japan and those in the
major leagues, but the only problem is that there's not enough
money or time to see them all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
