<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1468 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TORNADO-COMMENTARY-KE     03-29 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-COMMENTARY-KENNEDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(EDS: ACCOMPANIES TORNADO-TEXAS) 
COUNTING OUR BLESSINGS IN THE WAKE OF DISASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The windows are broken.
</P>
<P>
   Our cities are not.
</P>
<P>
   When morning sunlight fell across crumbled homes and fractured
lives in Fort Worth and Arlington on Wednesday, we saw how
fortunate we were that so few lives were lost in Tuesday's storms.
</P>
<P>
   I hesitate to say ``blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   I hesitate only because hundreds of families may not feel very
blessed after losing homes in suburban River Oaks, the struggling
Linwood neighborhood west of downtown Fort Worth or the smashed
neighborhoods of south Arlington and southwest Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Yet daylight showed us not only what the tornadoes hit, but what
they missed.
</P>
<P>
   In River Oaks, a twister descended first on tiny Cahill Oval and
cut across residential streets. Castleberry High School was
squarely in that path, but the tornado only brushed the back of the
school and damaged a locker room and band hall.
</P>
<P>
   The funnel turned south toward White Settlement Road. Inside the
Fireside Lodge retirement apartments and nursing center, 90
residents huddled in a hallway. The twister missed them by two
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Bearing down on the upscale Rivercrest neighborhood of Fort
Worth, the twister slapped at a Tex-Mex restaurant on White
Settlement Road and uprooted decades-old trees in Monticello Park.
But it spared most homes until it descended again along West Sixth
and Seventh streets, bypassing evening classes at the University of
North Texas medical school and 150 patients in an adjacent
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A paint store on Seventh Street took a direct hit. So did a
7-Eleven and a barber shop. Two blocks south, the Kimbell Art
Museum and the Cultural District were largely untouched.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado's harshest blow struck the same modest neighborhoods
flooded by the Clear Fork of the Trinity River 51 years ago in Fort
Worth's most deadly natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Homes along Merrimac Street and Mercedes Avenue were bashed
Tuesday, followed by the death of Arlington trucker Howard Thornton
at the Montgomery Ward rear dock and the death of Carl Spence
inside an abandoned building on Seventh Street. Yet no one died in
the crushed small frame homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Cash America International headquarters and the Calvary
Cathedral International church took the last hard hits. Again, no
one died.
</P>
<P>
   Then the twister darted northward to West Third and Fourth
streets, scraping a new apartment complex and missing night workers
in the Radio Shack headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   At Sundance Square, 220 moviegoers in two theaters and 300
reception guests at the Bass Hall lay next in the path. Instead,
the twister turned eastward again, peeling glass from the Bank One
Tower and Union Pacific Resources Plaza but sparing large crowds in
Sundance Square to the north and hotels to the south.
</P>
<P>
   East of downtown, the Riverside and Meadowbrook neighborhoods
received little more than hailstones, heavy winds, rain and a
shower of paperwork blown from downtown office towers.
</P>
<P>
   If downtown Fort Worth's destiny was to face down an oncoming
tornado, I can think of worse days and times than Tuesday at 6:15
p.m., when most office workers had gone home and the entertainment
district was less crowded.
</P>
<P>
   It might be difficult to convince the residents of River Oaks or
Linwood or south Arlington or south Grand Prairie that anyone here
is very lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Just say that many of us are very blessed.
</P>
