<HEADER>
A1509 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-29 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE STRONGEST WEAPON  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Thursday morning, Feb. 12, 1987, federal agents
arrested Richard B. Wigton, a balding, 52-year-old vice president
and senior arbitrager at Kidder, Peabody and Co. They arrested him
flamboyantly _ in full view of dozens of Kidder, Peabody
colleagues. They roughed him up and frisked him and walked him,
handcuffed, across the trading floor. It was as if they got a kick
out of publicly humiliating him.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Wigton was escorted from the building, tears were
spilling down his face.
</P>
<P>
   He was accused of securities fraud, but Wigton had not committed
any crime. He just had the misfortune to get caught up in one of
the celebrated investigations that propelled Rudolph Giuliani from
the post of U.S. attorney to the mayoralty of New York City. He was
a victim of Giuliani zealotry _ the compulsion to push the levers
of government power beyond the limits of fairness and decency and
even reason.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, Wigton's lawyer, Stanley S. Arkin,
said: ``They leaned on me very hard to have him plead guilty even
though I believed he wasn't guilty. And I wouldn't do it. I kept
asking for a trial, and ultimately, we faced them down and they
walked away.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Wigton were dropped, but the damage to him
both personally and professionally was grievous.
</P>
<P>
   Arkin summed the matter up as follows: ``You arrest him like
he's some kind of hoodlum, based upon an amount of evidence that
turns out to be no evidence at all. And you destroy his career, you
ruin his reputation and you don't apologize. And you did that for
effect. You did that because it looked good, and it makes you look
like a tough prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkin is no enemy of Giuliani. He thinks the mayor is
``brilliant'' and ``by and large, has done a quite effective job.''
But what happened to Richard Wigton was ``horrible,'' Arkin said.
He added: ``The strongest, most powerful weapon a prosecutor has is
fairness. And I think that unless you exhibit fairness, you end up
imposing upon people's sense of justice in a negative manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairness, as everybody knows by now, is not one of Giuliani's
strengths. The humiliation of Richard Wigton and the recent
relentless trashing of the memory of Patrick Dorismond are,
apparently, all the same to him _ no big deal. No different,
really, from the mass mistreatment of scores of thousands of New
Yorkers (mostly black or Hispanic males) who are stopped and
frisked and otherwise hassled by the police.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is a bully with a tendency to degrade. It wasn't enough
to force Ramon Cortines out as schools chancellor. The mayor had to
play to nasty prejudices by characterizing Cortines _ a thoroughly
decent man _ as ``precious'' and the ``little victim.'' It was
unconscionable.
</P>
<P>
   Fairness? Ask Richard Murphy about fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Another thoroughly decent man, Murphy was the Youth Services
Commissioner under David Dinkins. Giuliani replaced him with the
Rev. John E. Brandon, who, it turned out, had some embarrassing tax
and patronage problems.
</P>
<P>
   Attention to those problems was deflected when the mayor's press
secretary telephoned reporters with bombshell allegations about
wrongdoing _ including financial chicanery, the improper awarding
of contracts and even charges of breaking and entering _ on
Murphy's watch.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were an abomination _ no truer in Murphy's case than
in Wigton's. But nearly a year passed before the extent of the
smear against Murphy became clear. The New York Times' Joyce
Purnick wrote, in a column in March 1995: ``There has indeed been
mismanagement at the city's Youth Services Department. But it
wasn't in the Dinkins years. It was under Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani, a new review shows.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times, in an editorial, described the episode as a
``gross abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy told Purnick that in the period before he was exonerated
he lost out on prospective jobs and finally had to leave town.
</P>
<P>
   Holding high public office is not a license to push anybody and
everybody around. There are patterns emerging that raise questions
about Giuliani's judgment and temperament and fitness for office.
Those patterns deserve much closer scrutiny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
