<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE AGE OF COURTSHIP ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LISA BELKIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   We know it will end. It's only a question of when. Even the
longest economic expansion in history cannot continue forever.
</P>
<P>
   And when it ends, what will happen to the smaller revolutions it
has created? To the transformation of the office into a place where
workers are acknowledged to have families? To the growing
insistence of employees that their lives matter? Is all this talk
of work-life balance really a change to the social core, or is it
just cocktail conversation that will fade when the party's over?
</P>
<P>
   I recently spent a day in Boston at a company called Circles,
the ultimate icing on the work-life cake. If your employer
contracts with Circles, you are entitled to call a ``convenience
coordinator'' who will run your errands. Coordinators won't do
anything ``that isn't legal, moral or nice,'' says Janet Kraus,
co-founder and chief executive of Circles, but they will wait for
the cable repairman, plan your child's birthday party or take your
car in for servicing.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning I arrived, Kelly Medico, a coordinator, sat at
her computer searching for the perfect birthday gift for a Vietnam
veteran who collects war memorabilia. For nearly two hours, Medico
trawled the Web, choosing between a World War II wrist compass, an
unopened pack of Lucky Strike Greens and a Saddam Hussein
pincushion doll. And all the while the giver of the gift, an Ernst
&AMP; Young employee, was doing her own work, which is why Ernst &AMP;
Young was paying for this in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view it as a way to increase productivity,'' says Denise
Hoffman, the manager of work-life balance at Ernst &AMP; Young. ``It's
valuable in retention of employees, and we use it as a recruiting
tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruitment, retention and the bottom line. Those _ not
generosity or love _ have always been the underpinnings of
human-resource policies, says Ann Vincola, a longtime work-life
consultant in Boston. She said that chief executives are not sold
on job sharing, or flex time or lactation rooms ``just because you
present this as the right thing to do; there has to be some
perceived advantage to the company.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that companies are eagerly seizing that
advantage. The Society for Human Resource Management conducts an
annual survey, asking its members what benefits they offer. Three
years ago, there were 92 choices on the menu. Last year, there were
110. Not only does the survey show an increase in what are now
considered traditional benefits (53 percent offer flex time, an
increase of 7 percent from 1997), but the new perks are growing,
too. Massage therapy is hot now (8 percent of respondents say their
companies offer this), as are concierge services (now at 4 percent
and double the percentage a year ago).
</P>
<P>
   But if we accept that all this attention to our lives is spurred
less by enlightenment than by economics, what can we expect when
the economic realities change? ``There will,'' Vincola says, ``be a
tightening of the belt.'' Those programs that make financial sense
will remain, she predicts. Telecommuting, for instance, which frees
office space. Or compressed workweeks, which don't cost the company
more if they're done right. But things that simply make lives
easier will probably be cut.
</P>
<P>
   The people who make their living from work-life programs
understand this, and they are quietly preparing for the inevitable.
Two weeks ago, I attended a work-life conference, and the talk at
one lunch table was about a human-resource executive's push to get
on-site child care ``right now when times are flush because once
it's built they're less likely to take it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraus of Circles is also storing nuts. ``We're diversifying our
risk,'' she says, describing a recent deal with a major credit card
company: sign up for their platinum card and get a free Circles
membership.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy stalls, she reasons, ``there is a future for us
in the customer loyalty market.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, her coordinators keep fielding requests from
harried but pampered employees. Find a psychologist in Florida who
will perform an IQ test on a preschooler. Find a gym within five
miles of Harvard Square with a basketball court that is open past
10 p.m. A housekeeper with good references in New York.
Child-friendly hotels in Maui. Willie Nelson tickets any place
he'll be playing.
</P>
<P>
   We are standing on a sliver of a moment in a most unusual time.
It may be cold comfort, but you might never be more valued by your
boss than you are right this minute. Savor that while it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
