<HEADLINE>
(EDS: ACCOMPANIES TORNADO-TEXAS) 
NEW LIBRARY IS HARD-HIT SIX MONTHS AFTER EXPANSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB MAHLBURG 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For more than two decades, Fort Worth's
downtown Central Library was underground and as safe as a bunker.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday _ less than six months after the opening of a $7
million street-level expansion complete with a colorful children's
section _ a tornado slammed into the building, shattering windows,
causing up to $1 million in damage and injuring two children,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After years of leaks and extensive remodeling, a new round of
construction work faces library officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are again,'' said Gleniece Robinson,, Fort Worth
library director. ``But we're not in control of those situations,
so we deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who was in the library when the tornado struck, said
she is just happy that the staff remained calm and the situation
wasn't any worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unreal. Unbelievable. Amazing. There was glass flying
everywhere,'' she said. ``The noise was horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Winds shattered a skylight, broke chunks off the outside wall
covering, and broke doors and windows on every side of the
two-block-long building.
</P>
<P>
   The storm overturned a library delivery truck and collapsed a
small wall between the library and the city cable TV studio. Water
damaged books and other parts of the library collection, Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons began screaming and running when the storm hit, and the
air filled with a shower of broken glass and dust, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of kids who were in the youth center, and
we believe they got hurt when the windows blew in,'' she said,
adding that both had minor cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Hunt, an intensive care nurse at Harris Methodist Fort
Worth, was in the lower level when the funnel hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``All at once, simultaneously we heard people yelling upstairs
to get down,'' Hunt said. ```The fire alarms went off. At the same
time, we heard glass breaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Staffers moved people to the lower level, where Hunt helped
treat some, including a boy who thought he had glass in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the outside of the library looked battered and
scarred by debris, and a big piece of the facade on the northeast
corner was missing. City crews were repairing doors and the floor
of the cable TV studio, which was covered with broken glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a pretty sight, but at least we had no loss of life
or injuries on our staff,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance will cover all but $100,000 of the loss, Assistant
City Manager Ramon Guajardo said. The library should reopen by this
weekend, but work will continue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful thing that most of our building is
underground, which is the safest place to be,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   She said having the children's section upstairs reduced other
dangers, such as using stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who was named library director after two decades at
the Dallas library, said she's never been through a tornado before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Alabama, and I'm used to hurricanes,'' she said. ``I
don't want to be in one again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Charlotte Huff contributed to this report. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
