<HEADER>
A1522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER-ART-840     03-29 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT SEEMS RELUCTANT TO ALLOW ORGANIZED PRAYER AT HIGH SCHOOL
FOOTBALL GAMES
</HEADLINE>
   (See also SCOTUS-NUDE) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eight years after it barred organized prayer at
public high school graduations, the Supreme Court on Wednesday
appeared deeply reluctant to permit organized prayer at public high
school football games, at least when led by a student chosen in a
schoolwide election to offer an invocation or message ``to
solemnize the event.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for a small Texas school district labored during a
spirited argument Wednesday to persuade the justices that a student
chosen by election, and not told by school officials what to say or
not say, acted as an ``independent speaker'' when leading a pregame
prayer and so did not place the school district in the position of
breaching the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual student selected is the circuit breaker, who
determines the message,'' the lawyer, Jay Alan Sekulow, told the
court. Under the Santa Fe Independent School District's ``hands-off
policy,'' he said, ``no one knows what that student might say.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to prevent the student from offering a prayer under
those circumstances would ``require the school district to be a
censor, and to censor only religious speech,'' Sekulow said,
adding, ``All speech is protected by the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's skepticism was evident throughout Sekulow's argument
in a case that is being watched closely for signs for any shifts in
the court's view of the appropriate place for religion in the
public schools. In particular, a majority of the justices indicated
through their comments that they did not accept the student's role
as that of a private speaker whose words carried no constitutional
implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not students acting individually,'' Justice Ruth
Bader Ginsburg told Sekulow. ``These students are acting as an
electoral body that the school has designated.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy said, ``We're concerned about
avoiding having the schools become a forum for religious debate,''
and added, ``We're looking for some mechanism to ensure neutrality,
and we haven't seen what it is. I think the election thing doesn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was the author of the court's 5-4 decision eight years
ago in Lee vs. Weisman, which held unconstitutional the practice of
clergy-led prayer at high school graduations. To have a chance of
prevailing Wednesday, Sekulow, chief counsel of the American Center
for Law &AMP; Justice, founded by the evangelist Pat Robertson, needed
to persuade Kennedy that student-led prayer at football games was
constitutionally distinct from clergy-led prayer at graduation. The
Fifth Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in New Orleans barred the
football prayers in a 1998 decision that the Santa Fe district,
near Galveston, is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   By a stroke of bad fortune for the school district, Kennedy was
also the author one week ago of the Supreme Court's decision on
mandatory student activity fees at the University of Wisconsin. In
that decision, all nine justices upheld the fees except for one
aspect that all agreed was constitutionally troublesome: a student
referendum at which organizations could be accepted or rejected for
financing from the pool of student fees. In his opinion last week,
Kennedy said there was a risk that majority rule would overcome the
``viewpoint neutrality'' essential for the program's
constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor pointedly reminded Sekulow of last
week's decision, and raised the further issue of whether students
might conduct campaigns on the basis of the type of prayer they
would offer.
</P>
<P>
   To the justices' various concerns, Sekulow and Attorney General
John Cornyn of Texas, who also argued in support of the school
district, replied that because the policy had been blocked from
taking effect, there was no basis for making dire predictions about
how it would actually be applied. The court should simply uphold
the policy on its face, the two lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices indicated little willingness to do that,
suggesting that they understood the program well enough. ``Is there
any reason to expect we'd get a solemnizing speech to the effect
that religion is bunk?'' Justice David H. Souter asked the attorney
general, adding, ``The point of my question is that I don't think
there's any reason to expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter said: ``We're talking here not about a neutral speech
policy, not merely a discussion about religious subject matter. It
is religious worship, and the question is whether that may be
inflicted upon those who may not want it.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, Santa Fe Independent School District vs. Doe, No.
99-62, began in 1995, when the district was sued by two families,
one Catholic and one Mormon, who objected to the Christian prayers
being offered at school events by chaplains. As the litigation
progressed, the district came up with several different versions of
a policy that now provides for the election of a student, to serve
for the duration of the football season, who can decide whether to
offer an ``invocation and/or message'' as part of the pregame
ceremonies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They were trying to work their way out of a very practical
problem: How do we avoid being sued,'' Cornyn told the court. The
state's brief was also signed by Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer told Cornyn: ``The school district has
figured out a way to have prayer, but the mechanism itself leaves
minority religions out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all subjected to messages we disagree with,'' the
attorney general replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the purpose of the Establishment Clause,'' Breyer
continued, ``is to allow parents to raise their children in the
religion of their choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' lawyer, Anthony P. Griffin, urged the justices
not to accept the policy as one of neutrality. ``It endorses
religion and its whole purpose is religion,'' Griffin said, adding,
``They weave a web and seek to have this court ignore its
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, probing for a difference
between football prayer and graduation prayer, observed that
``nobody has to go to a football game.''
</P>
<P>
   Band members and cheerleaders have to attend, Griffin replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is anybody forced to be a band member or a cheerleader?''
Justice Antonin Scalia asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a teen-ager, yes,'' Griffin, who practices in
Galveston, replied, adding, ``And that's spoken from experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
