<SLUG> BC-PHILIPS-CZECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYAL PHILIPS ELECTRONICS TO OPEN TV SCREEN FACTORY IN PRAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (cjl) 
 By LADKA BAUEROVA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ Royal Philips Electronics NV of the
Netherlands, the largest consumer electronics manufacturer in
Europe, announced one of the biggest foreign investments in the
Czech Republic on Wednesday, a television screen factory capable of
producing 2.5 million color picture tubes a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Philips plant, which will be one of the world's largest
producers of TV screens, was considered a coup for the Czech
Republic. It had been in a heated three-way race with Poland and
Hungary for the investment and had offered generous tax breaks to
Philips to get it.
</P>
<P>
   CTK, the Czech news agency, reported that the government's
incentives were worth the equivalent of $42.9 million, including
10-year tax abatements.
</P>
<P>
   Philips said it would spend at least 200 million euros, or $190
million, to build the factory, which would initially employ 1,000
people. There were widespread expectations among Czech officials
that the size of the investment and the number of employees could
eventually triple.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, which is expected to be operating by the end of next
year, will enable Philips more easily to supply the growing demand
for televisions in the Czech Republic and neighboring nations.
Philips said the broad market for TV tubes was growing at about 5
percent a year and was expected to expand more quickly in Eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a good skilled labor force available in Czech
Republic, and we would like to take advantage of that,'' said Andre
Manning, the spokesman for Philips operations in Central and
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Philips will build the plant in the northeast town of Hranice,
where the impact of the country's 3-year-old economic downturn has
been especially severe. The unemployment rate around Hranice is 15
percent, compared with the national average of 9.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech authorities were eager to express their satisfaction
with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are glad this investment finally ended up in the Czech
Republic, since our neighbors were also extremely interested,''
said Miroslav Gregr, the minister of industry and trade, alluding
to the bids by Poland and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech Republic will also benefit from a plan by Philips to
move some of its research and development operations into the
region. ``This will support the development of know-how and the
growth of our scientific potential,'' Gregr said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
