<HEADER>
A1532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-CYBERSPACE-LESSIG     03-29 1740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSPACE-LESSIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET AT WHAT PRICE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By AARON ZITNER   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States Supreme Court deeply honors its
traditions, but Lawrence Lessig, a clerk to Justice Antonin Scalia,
found one of them just too onerous to stomach. There was simply no
reason, Lessig felt, for the court to keep using an archaic
word-processing system like Atex.
</P>
<P>
   And so, working with several other clerks, Lessig used his
computer skills to install new software and write programs to meet
the special needs of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lessig's grasp of software could have a far bigger impact
on the Supreme Court _ and on the future of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Now a 38-year-old Harvard law professor, Lessig has become one
of the most prominent commentators on law and cyberspace, thanks to
his academic writing, a column in the trendy magazine The Industry
Standard and a new -- and largely pessimistic -- book about the
future of privacy and free speech on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig's chief message is aimed at those who view the Internet
as some kind of democratic wonderland, a place of unfettered free
speech, business competition and creativity. Set the euphoria
aside, he warns. Government and industry are already stripping
privacy, free speech and other liberties from the Internet in order
to suit the needs of online commmerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to believe that the grounding for liberty
in cyberspace will simply emerge,'' he said. ``Quite the opposite
is the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessig's profile has risen lately because of the respect he has
won from one man in particular: Thomas Penfield Jackson, the judge
presiding over the Microsoft antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move late last year, Jackson asked Lessig to
provide guidance on one of the government's most important charges:
that Microsoft improperly merged its Web browser into the Windows
operating system. Lessig turned in a a 45-page brief that,
according to analysts, lays out a strategy for how Jackson can rule
against Microsoft and survive any appellate reviews.
</P>
<P>
   When Microsoft and the US Justice Department made their final
court arguments on Feb. 22, Jackson asked several questions that
showed that the Harvard professor's arguments are already part of
his deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawrence Lessig's issues are the live issues of the day,''
said Thane Scott, who heads the antitrust practice at the Boston
law firm of Palmer &AMP; Dodge. ``He's at the confluence of big money
and big government, and there's no thinker quite at the top of the
pyramid like him.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, Lessig's goal was not just to comment on law but
to shape it as a politician. The son of a Pennsylvania steel plant
owner, the young Ronald Reagan fan headed the state's Republican
teen group. In 1980, he was elected a delegate to the GOP national
convention. While an undergraduate at the University of
Pennsylvania, he managed a campaign for the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, Lessig describes himself as a liberal. ``That
doesn't mean I'm any less skeptical of what government does,'' he
said recenlty by phone from Berlin, where is on sabbatical. ``I'm
concerned about the protection of individual rights.'' He decided
Democrats were more devoted to protecting those liberties than
Republicans. His politics made for lively debates when he clerked
for the famously conservative Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of battles at times. . . But it was great fun,''
Lessig recalled. ``There are obviously some issues we disagreed on,
but it was a lot of fun working with someone who took seriously
trying to get to the right answer.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1989 graduate of Yale Law School, Lessig also clerked for
Judge Richard Posner of the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Chicago. Now both men now have a special role in the Microsoft
case, with Posner working at Jackson's request to negotiate a
settlement between the company and the government. Lessig said he
had talked to Posner about Microsoft during an earlier case but not
since either man was pulled into the current trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig drew attention as a specialist in the new field of
cyberlaw in the mid-1990s, when he was teaching the subject at the
University of Chicago. His new book, ``Code and Other Laws of
Cyberspace,'' is only boosting his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The book is partly a rejoinder to the popular view that any
attempts to regulate the Internet will fail because the network is
so vast that no government can control it.
</P>
<P>
   The notion was famously summed up by Internet theorist John
Perry Barlow in a 1996 declaration of Internet freedom:
``Governments of the Industrial World, you weary giants of flesh
and steel, I come from Cyberspace, the new home of Mind . . . You
are not welcome among us. You have no sovereignty where we
gather.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lessig notes that the Internet is made up of software, and
software writers make deliberate choices about whether or not to
build anonymity, privacy, open access and free speech into the
online experience. As the Net evolves to suit the demands of
commerce, he argues, software writers and government will make
going online a more stifling journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frustrated me that people thought (civil liberties) would
just take care of themselves,'' Lessig said. ``What motivated me to
write the book was to get people to understand that there was
something to defend here.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, he said, Congress has passed a broad law that makes it
illegal to build devices or software that defeat copyright
protections. And courts have used that law to rule against computer
users, even though they were not using the devices to make illegal
copies of tapes or movies. One set of defendants in a recent case
merely wanted to play DVD movies on their Linux computers, Lessig
said, which cannot play the discs without overriding copyright
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig sees these developments as early steps toward a world
where movies, books and music are controlled even more than today.
Currently, a person who buys a book or CD can read it over and over
again or loan it to friends. But soon, Lessig predicts, people will
be charged every time they read a piece of text, or copy it, or
each time they listen to a piece of music.
</P>
<P>
   And just as they regulate copyrights, government and business
will control who can go where online. Because businesses need to
identify their customers by age and home state, Lessig predicts
that people will be encouraged to carry a ``digital ID'' with them
online, possibly built into their Web browsers. It may not be
illegal to go online without an ID, but people who fail to carry
one will be barred from so many Web sites that most will comply.
</P>
<P>
   When digital IDs become pervasive, companies and the government
will be able to control who can do what online. ``Cyberspace would
go from being an unregulable space to, depending on the depth of
the (digital ID) certificates in the space, the most regulable
space imaginable,'' Lessig writes. And because nations will enforce
each other's laws, people will find it impossible to evade the law
by operating overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig has been writing about the online world for several
years, but he has no idea how he came to Judge Jackson's attention.
He almost tossed out Jackson's request for help, thinking it was
one of the thank-you notes that judges send to professors who
recommend potential clerks. ``But it was the wrong timing'' for
that kind of note, Lessig said, and so he opened it.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief, Lessig urged Jackson not to be afraid to
scrutinize the way Microsoft designs its software. Courts regularly
rule on the design of drugs, tires and other products in antitrust
cases, but somehow they are timid when it comes to software, Lessig
said. ``I believe it is a mistake to fetishize code in this way,''
he wrote, adding that software is too important to society for
courts to turn away.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig then took up the government's argument that Microsoft
illegally ``bolted'' its Web browser to its Windows operating
system. The government says Microsoft combined the two products so
that customers would have no reason to use browsers from a rival
company, Netscape Communications Corp. And if Netscape disappeared,
the government says, customers would lose out on the benefits of
competition between browser makers.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say the government's argument is weak. They
point to a 1998 federal appeals court decision in a prior Microsoft
case that seemed to say the company could tie the browser to
Windows as long as consumers benefitted in some way.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief, Lessig told Jackson that under the appeals court's
test, the government's charge would fail. But he offered a new
standard under which judges could look not only at whether
consumers benefit from a company's design decisions, as the appeals
court dictated, but also balance that against any possible harms.
</P>
<P>
   Without saying so explicitly, Lessig was warning Jackson he
would be overturned on appeal if he found that consumers gained no
benefit at all from a combined browser-operating system, said
William Kovacic, a law professor at George Washington University in
Washington, who has followed the case closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``For somebody who is not a witness, for someone who is truly an
outsider, those 45 pages represent a big contribution'' to the
case, Kovacic said.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Lessig says he is not optimistic about the nation's
ability to focus on how the Internet is changing and to debate
which civil liberties to protect. ``I would be grateful to be
proven wrong,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   But he does have one suggestion: Publish the software code that
controls the Net so that everyone can see it, and prevent it from
being owned and kept secret by companies.
</P>
<P>
   A move to this so-called open source software would make it
easier for people to find ways to remain anonymous or express
themselves freely. Government and industry would find it harder to
build regulations into the software of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments like that have won Lessig a big following in some
parts of the software industry. ``He's a hero of mine,'' said
Robert Young, chairman of Red Hat Inc., a provider of the open
source Linux software. ``His gift is to take complex technology
issues and simplify them so they can be explained to the general
citizenship, and that's very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-22-00 1331EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
