u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      03-29 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART SWANK; FARBER'S PASSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So now that Hilary Swank has deservedly won the best actress
Academy Award for her devastating portrayal in ``Boys Don't Cry''
of Brandon Teena, who was raped and murdered after it was
discovered that he was actually a she, how long do you think it'll
be before the backlash begins?
</P>
<P>
   Such is the way of our chew-'em-up, spit-'em-out culture. We
fall in love with a particular person, recommend their work to
everyone, and proclaim them as the best thing since frozen pizza
until they get too many awards (see Tom Hanks), and too much
acclaim (see Matt Damon), and then we turn on them like bad
mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet dollars-to-donuts that it'll happen to Swank, and
that would be a shame since she comes across in Interview as a
smart, thoughtful young woman more concerned with making art than
making money. Editor Ingrid Sischy caught up with Swank _
post-nomination, pre-Oscar coronation _ but she gets the full star
treatment with a come-hither cover shot, and several sexy photos in
which she _ with the help of Herb Ritts _ proves that she is most
definitely not a boy.
</P>
<P>
   In a story that is quickly becoming Hollywood lore, Swank
recalls strapping her breasts and packing a sock in her pants to
look more like a young man. But even more than looking male, Swank
was committed to capturing a deeper essence of Brandon Teena. ``I
realized as well that instead of playing how lonely it feels to be
treated differently, I wanted to play the joy of living your life
the way you want to. It's a beautiful love story.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm, maybe we won't turn on Swank after all.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the issue, teen singer Christina Aguilera assumes
all the obligatory pop tart poses _ a short dress with her legs
parted, her hands placed in provocative places, and lots o' belly
button.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Evelyn McDonnell accurately describes her as a ``Disco
Barbie,'' then slides into hyperbole about Aguilera's
better-than-Britney voice, which she calls ``a force to be reckoned
with, maybe even a supernatural force.'' Well, of course, she has a
good voice _ she sounds so much like Mariah Carey that Carey could
sue for plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, Celia Farber has been one of the best AIDS
reporters in the country. She used to write the Spin magazine's
``Words from the Front'' column, a must-read for anyone with more
than a passing interest in AIDS and HIV. She earned devotees and
enemies as she distinguished herself by investigating such issues
as whether HIV causes AIDS, and whether AZT, the first approved
AIDS drug, was killing more people than it was saving.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after moving her column to the online magazine Iron Minds,
Farber has a sit-down with Richard Berkowitz in Poz to confront
those who still find her columns more dangerous than informative.
Says Farber, who seems always primed for a good battle, ``I no
longer give a damn about respect or credit from my peers. Why do I
need acknowledgment from a bunch of whores? Little do-gooders.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the ``bunch of whores'' Farber refers to are the
``legions of crisp-shirted AIDS reporters at the major newspapers
who churn out this `responsible' babble.'' Ouch. But Farber is
equally passionate about her dedication to the AIDS fight at a time
when the red-ribbon trendiness it once enjoyed has gone out of
style. ``I wanted to save people,'' she said. ``To crack the
mystery. To break new ground.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before she was a first lady wannabe, Tipper Gore was trying to
save the world from artistic freedom with the Parents Music
Resource Center. That was the group who lobbied for warning labels
on albums they deemed offensive _ which, of course, only made those
records even bigger sellers. For Gore, public enemy No. 1 was
Luther Campbell, former leader of the Miami raunch-rap group, 2
Live Crew, which gave the world the immortal ``Me So Horny.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a decade removed from his First Amendment battles,
Campbell is still as nasty as he wants to be with CD and movie
``Luke's Freakfest 2000.'' But he's also a big golf fan(!) and has
been thinking a lot about presidential politics lately. In XXL, he
shows no love for George W. Bush (``I see a right-wing guy,'' he
says), and he's not feeling Al Gore either, believing Gore must
support his wife's censorship crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's interested in getting more young people to
participate in the voting process, and especially encouraging
rappers to use their community clout to make things happen
politically. ``Just imagine Rap-A-Lot rallyin' their people in
Texas. Three 6 Mafia and Memphis rallyin' their people,'' Campbell
said. ``P and Cash Money in New Orleans, Jermaine and Dungeon
Family in Atlanta, Dre and Snoop and them in California, Luke in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine all of us being responsible for our area and
bringin' people to the table.'' Hey, if the notoriously party-happy
Campbell, who never met a thong he didn't like, can spend more time
talking about ballots than booty calls, then it's easy to imagine
just about anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
