<HEADLINE>
COMPANY DOESN'T GET ANY RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens all the time now: A company in an industry that has
fallen out of favor on Wall Street can't seem to get credit for one
of its business divisions in some other, more popular field.
</P>
<P>
   Typically it's an Internet or telecom unit buried inside an
otherwise unloved technology company. But our case of the moment
finds one of Boston's most successful mutual fund firms practically
printing money for its life insurance company parent.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Life Financial Services of Canada, based in Toronto, went
public last week, greeted by the same tepid market all life
insurance companies currently face. The company, founded in 1865,
went public at $8.50 per share and finished Tuesday at $9.1875.
That translates into a market value of about $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It got little, if any, boost from its ownership of MFS
Investment Management Inc., manager of $155 billion in mutual funds
and other accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The question: Will that situation lead to an initial public
stock offering by MFS itself? It seems like the smart thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   It might not happen overnight and Sun Life has been adamant
about holding on to a majority interest in MFS, but no one
dismisses the idea of a partial spinout of the investment company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't surface that value in Sun Life stock over time as
we are currently structured, we would consider other options,
including the possibility of floating some minority piece of MFS,''
said Michael Hasley, senior vice president of finance at Sun Life.
</P>
<P>
   Comments by MFS executives on the subject are opaque, to say the
least, but we didn't hear any protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly deal with public companies all the time,'' said
MFS chief executive Jeffrey Shames. ``We think it would be an
interesting option.''
</P>
<P>
   MFS managers are hardly disinterested spectators in the debate.
They already own 20 percent of their company and Sun Life has
agreed to assign another 2 percent of equity to MFS managers this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The logic behind partial spinouts is simple: Get the stock
market to put a high valuation in the new public shares and the
real worth of the parent's majority interest will become obvious.
Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   But the current arrangement certainly doesn't work. Depending on
how aggressively you might like to value MFS's business, Sun Life's
stock price allows investors to buy the rest of the insurance
company on the cheap or for nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   MFS is such a valuable piece of Sun Life because it is growing
much faster than the rest of the parent company and profit margins
just keep getting better the more revenues rise.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sun Life's 80 percent share of MFS revenues grew 40
percent to $1.3 billion. During that same period, comparable
operating profits jumped 65 percent to $129 million. Profits from
Sun Life's other leading business lines were flat or declined last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The question surrounding ownership of MFS resembles a similar
debate over the future of Putnam Investments, another Boston money
manager, a few years ago. Putnam was hot and the stock of its
parent, insurance brokerage Marsh &AMP; McLennan Cos., definitely was
not.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, talk of a Putnam sale was doused. The difference
now: MarshMac stock rebounded and trades at a premium today, and
subsequent financial deregulation has made the opportunity for a
publicly traded MFS greater than ever.
</P>
<P>
   An argument can be made that life insurance stocks will recover
in the future and there would be no need for Sun Life to create a
public stock for its investment management firm.
</P>
<P>
   A more likely scenerio is that Sun Life and another Canadian
life insurer, perhaps number one ManuLife Financial Corp., will
eventually be merged and a public MFS will give everyone involved
more attractive options.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   What color is your parachute?
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer Group Inc., the struggling Boston money management
business that may be sold, signed ``executive retention
agreements'' with top managers last month while the company was
being shopped by investment bankers and attacked by one of its
largest shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the agreements, detailed in a proxy statement filed this
week, offer executives three years of salary and full bonus (an
amount equal to 100 percent of base salary) if they get axed within
two years of any transaction. Pretty standard stuff, as 'chutes go.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive John Cogan, 73, was the lone senior manager who
declined to strap one on, according to the proxy. Nevertheless, the
company agreed to pay Cogan a $1 million fee ``upon the
consummation of a significant transaction involving the company.''
Nice work if you can get it.
</P>
<P>
   Cogan, who earned $575,000 last year, received no bonus because
Pioneer's performance was ``disappointing'' in 1999, according to
the proxy. But then the company promptly offered him 100,000 stock
options at December's nearly rock-bottom price of $14.9375 each, to
emphasize ``his focus on returning the company to profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Those options were worth about $744,000 on paper Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
