<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S HOCKEY ENJOYING HIGHER PROFILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women's college hockey will never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Brown became the first university to begin a women's
ice hockey program 34 years ago, East Coast schools have dominated
the sport. Indeed, until three years ago, the ECAC champion won the
de facto national title as well: There was no need for a nationwide
tournament, because all the teams were in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. Three seasons ago, the University of Minnesota
elevated its program to varsity status, and a four-team national
tournament was founded by the American Women's College Hockey
Alliance, a group under the auspices of USA Hockey that stepped in
to organize a tourney until there were a sufficient number of teams
_ 40 _ to warrant sanctioning by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   This season, a second league finally got off the ground, as the
Western Collegiate Hockey Association put five women's teams on the
ice, with quick expansion foreseen.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Saturday night at Northeastern's Matthews Arena,
Minnesota defeated Brown, 4-2, to become the first non-ECAC
national champion. Coupled with the rise to NCAA status beginning
next season, the victory kicks women's college hockey up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we showed in this tournament is there's some
great teams in the Midwest,'' said Minnesota coach Laura
Halldorson, still on the ice Saturday night as her team skated
around her in glee after the win. ``Certainly by expanding college
women's hockey outside the East Coast at this level, that's a very
positive thing for our sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Although even Minnesota-Duluth coach Shannon Miller was quick to
acknowledge that the ECAC is still deeper and stronger
top-to-bottom _ her 25-5-3 Bulldogs, after all, won the WCHA
tournament but lost the national consolation game to Dartmouth,
which finished the season 21-12 _ Harvard coach Katey Stone said
the league should heed the wakeup call. ``I think it's wonderful
what's happening in the West, and the amount of money being put in
the sport is tremendous,'' said Stone. ``But the ECAC has been the
leader in women's hockey, and it needs to continue to be. It needs
to make a conscious effort to continue to look ahead to do
everything possible for our conference, for the betterment of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All-around recognition
</P>
<P>
   Mandy Mosby hopes the best is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   A senior member of the University of Massachusetts gymnastics
team, Mosby last week was named a finalist for the American Award,
given to the nation's top women's gymnastics student-athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely a huge honor for me,'' said Mosby, a native
of Lilburn, Ga. ``I was really suprised, because I was associated
with a lot of amazing gymnastics.''
</P>
<P>
   The award will be presented at the Awards Banquet in Boise,
Idaho, site of the NCAA Championships, on April 15.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Mosby is preparing, as an all-around
competitor, for the NCAA Regionals Saturday at Penn State. The top
two finishers from each region advance to the NCAA Championships
April 16 (Mosby is in Region 5).
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little pressure because this is the end for me and I
want to perform well,'' Mosby said. ``I have been working on my
routines the last couple of weeks. Right now I am trying to clean
them up. At this point, there is no reason for me to add anything
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosby, who stands just 4 feet 8 inches, finished third in the
Atlantic 10 Championships, posting a career-best overall score of
39.375. Although she was dissapointed that she did not place
higher, she turned in an impressive performance, tying the
conference championship record with a 9.975 to win the floor
exercise and placing second on the vault with a 9.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not put any expectations on myself going into the (A-10
championships),'' Mosby said. ``I was very proud of my score
because I did as well as I possibly could.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She foiled the competition
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Purcell, a sophomore from MIT, won the women's saber
title at the NCAA Championships at Stanford last weekend. Purcell,
a gold medalist in sabre at the last Junior Pan-American Fencing
Championships in Brazil, defeated North Carolina's Kim Treiber in
the final after holding the lead throughout the tournament . . .
The Boston University women's lacrosse team slipped to 11th in the
Intercollegiate Women's Lacrosse Coaches Association Division 1
poll after falling to No. 18 Vanderbilt, 9-8, in overtime Sunday.
Junior midfielder Chrissy Lombard is the Terriers' leading scorer
with 22 points (15 goals). . . . Fifteen members from the US soccer
team that won the Women's World Cup last year were among 30 picked
for the Olympic training camp by new coach April Heinrichs. The
team must be cut to 18 for the Sydney Games in September . . . The
US field hockey team tied Spain, 2-2, and is fourth in its
five-team group in qualifying for the Olympics, leaving the
Americans little chance of earning an automatic berth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
