<SLUG> BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: 5 A.M. TREAT IN THE BIG APPLE: BASEBALL! 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was only the sixth inning and Craig Pearson still had 45
minutes before he was due in the office downtown at the World Trade
Center. This was opening day, or opening daybreak, on the big
screen, live. The subway and those commodities that Pearson would
eventually be trading would just have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have them play now than late at night,'' said
Pearson, 22, and fresh off the train at Penn Station. ``Now I'll
know the result at, what, 9 a.m.?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the final out of the Mets' 5-3 defeat to the Chicago
Cubs in Tokyo was recorded at 8:33 Wednesday morning, or 3 hours
and 26 minutes after the New York major league baseball season
began under the cover of darkness and when most fans were under the
covers.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this being the mass transit system that never
sleeps, Ray Carrington estimated that three to four dozen fans
witnessed the historic first pitch of the 21st Century minutes
after 5 a.m. on the screens in the Long Island Railroad terminal at
Penn Station.
</P>
<P>
   Carrington and his co-workers from the Audio Visual Workshop _
Michael Tibbs and Matt Bunn _ were not too impressed. He was more
interested in saying that he had been up at 1:30, and all set up
for the promotion run by the Mets and their broadcast partners, by
3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even a Mets' fan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By the dozens every minute, commuters rounded the corner, and
couldn't help but smile as they trained their eyes on the images
being beamed in from a domed stadium affectionately known in Tokyo
as The Big Egg.
</P>
<P>
   Most remained in stride, perhaps with visions of more
standard-size eggs, with potatoes and toast. Many stretched their
commuting time 15 or 20 minutes to have a look. And one Con Edison
worker, who shall remain nameless in order to avoid being jobless,
said, ``To tell you the truth, I was due out on the street 45
minutes ago. But this is so cool.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Mets will surely survive one dome defeat, the country
won't crumble now that opening day, 2000, has been exported to
Japan. Among other critics, no less an impact hitter than Mark
McGwire has taken the opportunity to chastise the guardians of the
national pastime for shredding one of its grandest traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The longer McGwire expounded on the subject _ insisting that Our
Game ought to remain in Our Country _ the more it sounded like a
less strident variation on a certain left-handed reliever's theme.
Did McGwire forget that Our Game happens to be played now by
several Japanese and packs of Latin Americans, and those countries
relish seeing their homegrown stars?
</P>
<P>
   While the Japan Series is primarily in the interest of global
growth and a supplementary buck, it is also likely that more New
York baseball fans were literally dreaming of a Subway Series when
the previous Mets' season ended in Atlanta than when the Cubs' Rick
Aguilera retired the side Wednesday in the ninth, with the tying
run at bat. For schoolchildren typically forgotten during October _
not to mention newspaper columnists forever typing late into the
postseason night _ baseball with bagels is practically a concept to
die for.
</P>
<P>
   As for the diehards, the time zone that is incompatible with the
start of a noteworthy ball game has not been invented, witness the
4 a.m. line outside the ESPN Zone at Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Penn Station telecast that was open to the
sleepy-eyed masses, admittance to the Disney-spawned theme
restaurant was determined by contest, in a joint promotion with
WFAN. What a coincidence _ a few of the Mets' fans greeted at the
door by Joe Benigno in his Mike Piazza jersey were Benigno's
regular callers from his overnight show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prophet, it's me, Carlos,'' said one caller, recognizing
another, by voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos, I heard you tonight,'' Prophet said, embracing the
smaller man. ``Nice to meet you.''
</P>
<P>
   Prophet came straight from his night work with his good friend,
Lenny from Queens, recently cited by Benigno in a magazine article
as the most distinguished caller of all. Lenny, actually a Houston
fan, wasn't quite in tears when Mike Hampton, the Mets' opening-day
starter who was acquired from the Astros, couldn't find the plate
and lasted only through the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three keys are Hampton, who must win 20, Derek Bell and
Todd Zeile,'' said Prophet, 51, and a Mets' fan from their
inception. Twenty-six years ago, he picked Ali over Foreman in
Zaire, and the round. Al Goodman was gone. Prophet was born.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny and Prophet took seats at the bar (the taps were wisely
turned off) in front of the oversize screen. The rest of the fans
settled in. The banter ceased with the first pitch of the pennant
race. Television camera crews made the rounds. Before taking a walk
down Broadway to Penn Station, Mr. Met _ the identical twin of the
Mr. Met in Japan _ took a bow.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Mets fell behind. The festivities were forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have jet lag when they come back,'' Donn
Lloyd told his friend, Garvey Austin, who had worked late last
night, fallen asleep and come straight from the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time they lose this season, it's jet lag,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The long and winding season was under way. The Mets were 0-1. On
their way out, the fans didn't care about the time of day, and
weren't in much of a mood to give it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
