<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES CONGRESS TO ACT ON TRADE PACT, GUN CONTROL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With time running out on his presidency, Bill
Clinton urged Congress on Wednesday to act on his top legislative
priorities, including normalizing trade relations with China and
approving gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Congress adjourns this summer we ought to be able to look
back and say we took real steps to make America better,'' Clinton
said during a White House news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton fielded questions for more than an hour on a variety of
domestic and foreign policy issues. He praised the decision by the
oil-producing nations to increase production and said he hoped the
latest spike in gas prices would prod Congress to approve measures
to promote development of alternative fuels.
</P>
<P>
   On the lighter side, Clinton said he did not want to get in the
middle of a debate raging in Britain over whether Prime Minister
Tony Blair should take paternity leave when his next child is born.
Although, he joked, he would have loved ``to be a fly on the wall''
when Blair and his wife discussed the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Only once did Clinton appear defensive, when he said that
neither he nor Vice President Al Gore had knowingly done anything
wrong in regard to the fund-raising scandals during the 1996
election.
</P>
<P>
   With a new presidential election season already heating up, both
Clinton and congressional leaders realize that the window for
legislative activity will soon close.
</P>
<P>
   One measure Clinton wants Congress to consider soon is
normalized trade relations with China, an issue that has proved
dicey for congressional Democrats, who are being pressured by
unions to oppose the pact.
</P>
<P>
   The president expressed some frustration that he has faced
opposition within his party. He said the trade pact would open up
Chinese markets to a variety of U.S. ventures and industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can just get everybody to read what this agreement does,
it will pass handily because this agreement will create jobs for
America; it will create jobs for organized labor,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that could undercut Clinton's ability to marshal
support for the pact, Gore has pledged that, if elected president,
he would change the treaty to ensure that China abides by
environmental and labor standards.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said that even if Congress approves the China pact
this year, Gore would still be able to negotiate labor and
environmental standards in the future.
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, the congressional divisions are more along
partisan lines. Clinton accused Republican leaders of refusing to
hammer out compromises on a series of provisions, such as
background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he does not agree with the National Rifle
Association's argument that the main problem is the
administration's unwillingness to enforce current gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA's position is that if somebody does something wrong,
throw the book at them, but do not have any preventative measures
when it comes to guns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said applying the gun lobby's logic, airports would do
away with metal detectors and ``the next time a plane blows up,
we're going to throw the book at them.''
</P>
<P>
   The president stepped gingerly around the recent controversy
over police shootings in New York City, which has become an issue
in the Senate campaign between first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Justice Department is reviewing the practices
of the department. And in a dig at Giuliani, Clinton said in many
cities ``there is ample evidence that the crime rate can go down
and the tenor of community police relations can go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was more eager to weigh in on the latest campaign
finance plan by Gore, who has proposed creating a $7.1 billion
endowment fund to pay for congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wish I had thought of it myself,'' he said. But
Clinton bristled at the suggestion that Gore's admission that he
``was an imperfect messenger'' on fund-raising reform implied that
the administration had tried to bend the law .
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I disagree with that,'' Clinton said. ``He has never said
that he knew that any of the money that he raised was not lawfully
raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he directed the party to make changes when he
realized the party had accepted illegal foreign money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wrong. And we did everything we could to correct it and
set it right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Gore is a ``good messenger'' for campaign finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I think he was showing a little humility, and I
think that's always a good thing. We're all flawed in one way or
another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also touched on a number of foreign-policy
concerns, including recent presidential elections in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he looked forward to working with Russian President
Vladimir Putin and said he had ``expressed a genuine commitment to
economic reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also said that in recent Mideast peace talks
between Syria and Israel there had been no mention of sending U.S.
advisers, monitors or troops to the disputed Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he hoped the newly elected president of Taiwan
and the leaders of China would be able to begin a dialogue on how
to deal with future relations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
