<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY THE RICH CAN AFFORD TO SELF-INSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Problem: How to fund health-care emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Ages: mid-70s.
</P>
<P>
   Income: $57,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Expenses: $53,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Investments:
</P>
<P>
   --Health-care account: $25,926 in fixed-income funds, $4,000
added annually.
</P>
<P>
   --Annuities: $102,750 fixed-rate; $44,453 with moderate asset
allocation.
</P>
<P>
   --IRAs:
</P>
<P>
   $43,115 cash; $26,400 fixed income at 8.78 percent; $32,815
Washington Mutual Investors; $40,104 Legg Mason Value Trust;
$12,982 Legg Mason Special Investment Trust; $15,904 Legg Mason
Value Trust (wife's account)
</P>
<P>
   --Taxable accounts: $17,959 Legg Mason Value Trust; $25,585 Bell
Atlantic common stock; $10,000 US Treasury bond; $937 Pimco Total
Return fund; $61 money market fund.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We retired in 1986 and own a home in Pennsylvania and a
townhouse in Arizona, where we spend up to five months a year. We
anticipate possibly another 10 years of longevity. In the past, we
considered purchasing long-term care insurance, but our current
plan is to accumulate money in a separate emergency account for
this purpose. We also plan to sell the Arizona property, should
either of us need long-term care. Our current position is 45.4
percent equities, 37.8 percent bonds, and 16.8 percent cash. All
dividends are reinvested. We'd appreciate advice about the
allocation. What would you do with the $43,000 cash currently in my
IRA?
</P>
<P>
   R.H., Center Valley, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your allocation of assets is fine. The only change I would
make is to move that $43,000 in your IRA from cash to a
fixed-income holding, probably an intermediate-term bond fund, such
as a GNMA offering.
</P>
<P>
   But your plan to self-insure when it comes to long-term health
care is very dubious. Long-term care insurance is so expensive
because the costs such a policy would cover can be astronomical.
They could be far beyond your likely accumulation in that emergency
account.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose both of you went a full decade before needing to tap
into that account. With a presumed 6.5 percent average portfolio
return and with contributions of $333 per month, you would have
$105,691. Alas, that can be an insignificant sum when compared with
some of the health-care costs that loom for people with serious
health problems. Even if you sold your Arizona home, that, too,
could be inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Self-insuring for long-term health care is a luxury that can be
afforded only by mega-millionaires. For the rest of us, the
insurance premiums are onerous, but they represent the only
realistic way of facing up to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: Seeking to retire with $2,000 monthly income from
savings.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 53.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement accounts:
</P>
<P>
   --Employer: $103,000, 25 percent in domestic equities, 25
percent in international equities.
</P>
<P>
   --Tax-Sheltered annuity: $350 biweekly contribution, $80,000
balance, in New Perspective, EuroPacific Growth, and Investment Co.
of America funds.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I hope to retire in five years with a monthly income of
$2,000 from my savings. I have been adding $300 biweekly to my
tax-sheltered annuity and plan to add $50 to that payment. Where do
you suggest I put the additional funds? In addition to American
funds, the plan offers funds in the Fidelity family. My husband is
retired from the military and receives a $2,600 monthly pension,
$2,300 of which is used to pay our mortgage, which is due to be
paid off in 14 years. We have no other debt. How much do I need to
save so I can retire comfortably?
</P>
<P>
   R.L., Bonita, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You should come pretty close, at least on paper. The trouble
is that making projections gets iffier and iffier as the investment
time frame shortens. When you get down to five years or less, I get
a bit nervous about using the 10 percent growth figure, with which
I am comfortable for a decade or longer.
</P>
<P>
   But on paper, if you achieved average 10 percent portfolio
growth, both within the retirement account and the tax-sheltered
annuity, and if you contributed $758.88 a month (which is what $350
biweekly works out to), you would amass $359,734 after five years.
If we presume that in retirement you could then move your savings
to fixed-income accounts yielding a portfolio average of 6.5
percent, you would need about $370,000 to produce that desired
$2,000 monthly income stream.
</P>
<P>
   So, as I said, you'd be pretty close. But if the vagaries of the
markets were such that you achieved only 8 percent portfolio
growth, the accumulation would be only $328,302. You need to bear
in mind that at this stage the internal growth of your retirement
savings should far exceed the value of your contributions, so the
projected growth figure is pretty important.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, and because using even the 10 percent growth
figure you fall a little more than $10,000 short of the target, I'd
suggest that you think in terms of retiring in five or six years _
or even seven if you encounter sour markets. If the markets are
kind to you, it might turn out that you do indeed reach the desired
pool in five years, but I wouldn't suggest you set yourself up to
be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Just to give you an idea of where you would end up if you
delayed retirement: If you kept saving at the current rate and
earned 8 percent returns over seven years, the accumulation would
be $404,723. If you followed the same assumptions but inserted a
projected 10 percent growth rate, the pool would be $459,065 after
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   I tend to throw cold water on the idea of putting all of your
retirement money to work to produce an income stream, with nothing
left aside to protect you against the likely inflation of the later
years of retirement. But in your case, you have an extra element _
that military pension that is now paying the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   After eight or 10 years of retirement, the mortgage will be paid
off, freeing up a significant monthly income, some of which could
be used to improve your income stream and deal with higher costs of
living, with the rest saved in stock accounts to deal with
inflation. You also could improve the situation by consigning the
entire military pension check of $2,600 to the mortgage, thus
prepaying it by $300 a month and bringing the payoff date closer.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as to where to invest that additional $50 you will be
putting away every two weeks for the next five years or so, if all
of the Fidelity funds are available to you under the plan, my
suggestion would be Fidelity Select Health Care fund. This is a
little riskier than the funds you are now using _ after all, it's a
sector fund, and the pharmaceutical and health care equipment
companies on which it focuses are expensive stocks. But it has
excellent long-term growth prospects and could supply the spark in
your portfolio that allows you to reach your target in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: Is it time to take on some risk?
</P>
<P>
   Age: 74.
</P>
<P>
   Investment: $70,594 bank IRA at 5.83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Q. A bank financial specialist has been urging me for months to
reinvest my IRA CD in stocks or annuities. I'm not sure of the
mutual fund family name he mentioned; I think it was Evergreen. I'm
not sure investing in stocks or annuities is as risk-free as a CD.
</P>
<P>
   C.F., Allentown, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You're right _ investing in stocks or annuity accounts that
are invested in mutual funds carries a vast amount of risk when
compared to buying a government-insured bank CD. And if you are
uncomfortable with the prospect that you might lose money by
changing from the CD to a fund account, you should politely say no.
</P>
<P>
   If the fund family is indeed Evergreen, one factor you should
consider is that if you decide to try funds, you will pay some sort
of sales charge, either up front or when you cash out, or through
annual charges called 12b-1 fees. For most Evergreen funds, the fee
is 4.5 percent (and more in some cases) if you choose to pay at the
outset. If you paid a 4.5 percent fee, that would represent a
little more than 9 months interest on your CD.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the fact that you seem so vague about what the banker
is offering leads me to believe you would be best off sticking with
CDs.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
