<HEADER>
A1546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-SUIT30-COX     03-29 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SUIT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson wants `honorable' deal in Coke suit
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson is scheduled to meet this
morning with Coca-Cola officials for the second consecutive day as
he attempts to persuade them to quickly settle a racial
discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   If there is not an ``honorable settlement'' soon, Jackson said
Wednesday, he will participate in a bus ``ride for justice'' to the
company's annual shareholders meeting in Wilimington, Del., on
April 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come April, either the buses will roll or justice will roll,''
Jackson told reporters following a two-hour meeting with top
Coca-Cola officials at their Atlanta headquarters. He said he had a
``positive meeting'' with Chairman Doug Daft, President Jack Stahl,
Executive Vice President Carl Ware and Vice President Ingrid
Saunders Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The company agreed with Jackson's assessment of Wednesday's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very constructive conversation with Rev. Jackson,''
said Ware, who serves as co-chair of the company's Diversity
Advisory Council, along with Stahl. ``The Coca-Cola Co. has had a
long-standing relationship with Rev. Jackson and, as always, we
value his insights and perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke has provided financial support to Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition for more than 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Jackson has maintained a low profile on the case,
although he has sent two letters to the company in support of the
plaintiffs since the suit was filed nearly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But with former and current African-American employees
organizing a three-bus convoy to the Wilmington shareholders
meeting, as well as rallies along the way in Greensboro, N.C.,
Richmond, Va., and Washington, D.C., Jackson decided to take a
public stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is in Coke's corner,'' Jackson said. ``Coke should
choose an honorable settlement over a protracted fight.''
</P>
<P>
   He highlighted four essential ingredients for reaching an
agreement with the plaintiffs:
</P>
<P>
   _ A fair financial settlement in the case.
</P>
<P>
   _ No retaliation against workers for being involved in the
current action.
</P>
<P>
   _ Empowerment of someone at the company who can transform its
corporate culture with regard to its treatment of African-Americans
and other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   _ A plan to include minorities as business partners, including
suppliers, lawyers, investment managers and distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' attorneys declined to comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said a settlement could be reached before court-ordered
mediation talks take place on April 17 and 18, which would be after
the buses started to roll on April 15.
</P>
<P>
   If a settlement is reached, he said, ``mediation is moot.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Jackson said a settlement would stop the buses, the
chief organizer of the protest ride made no such commitment
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, I'm taking three buses to Delaware,''
said Larry Jones, a former Coca-Cola human resources manager who
has spent the last 10 days organizing the trip. ``Our agenda hasn't
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who was one of 500 people laid off last month as part of
the company's restructuring, was unequivocal on this issue _
before, during and after Jackson's news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that more than 50 people have signed up to ride the
buses, which he says will transport about 150 former and current
employees. He also said about $9,500 of the $60,000 needed to pay
for the buses and lodging has been raised for the April 15-20 trip.
</P>
<P>
   But several company observers said Coca-Cola should try its best
to stop the buses from rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Company efforts to resolve this issue quickly need to be
galvanized,'' said Scott Wilkins, an analyst with Deutsche Bank.
``The last thing this company needs right now is bad PR.''
</P>
<P>
   Before meeting with the company on Wednesday, Jackson spent
Tuesday night talking with about a dozen former and current
African-American employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some workers worked for 10 to 12 years without promotions,''
Jackson said he was told. ``This is a crisis that can be turned
into an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal suit, filed by eight current and former employees,
alleges that Coca-Cola has discriminated against African-Americans
in pay, promotions and performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are seeking class-action status so they can
represent about 2,000 current and former black employees in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company has denied the suit's allegations and opposed the
plaintiffs' efforts to make it a class-action case.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said it's in the company's best interest to settle the
suit, partially because blacks represent 25 percent of its consumer
base.
</P>
<P>
   While Jackson did not talk about a possible boycott of Coke
products, Jones has said that is an option if a settlement is not
reached soon.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said his relationship with Coca-Cola dates back some 20
years, when he negotiated with the company to open up its doors and
markets to include more talent and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of those meetings, he said, ``Carl Ware was put on
the leadership track. ... Ware has a significant position now _
maybe 10 years after he earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
