<HEADER>
A1547 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DDT-OCEAN-NYT &LR;      03-29 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DDT-OCEAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA ANNOUNCES PLAN TO CONTROL DDT CONTAMINATION SITE IN PACIFIC
OCEAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Taking the first steps toward controlling the
largest known site of DDT contamination in the country, the
Environmental Protection Agency plans to cap parts of the deposit,
which lies deep in the Pacific Ocean off the Southern California
coast near Palos Verdes Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The $5 million pilot program, which would focus on four areas
within the 17-square-mile site, was announced Wednesday as the
agency unveiled a separate $22 million plan to raise public
awareness about the contamination and provide tools to enforce
fishing bans in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really huge environmental problem in Southern
California,'' said Keith Takata, director of the agency's Superfund
division for the region that includes California.
</P>
<P>
   The DDT came from Montrose Chemical Corp. in Torrance, Calif.,
which was once the world's largest producer of the pesticide DDT,
Takata said. The company manufactured DDT from 1947 to 1982. Its
use in the United States was banned in 1973. Until 1971, the EPA
said, Montrose discharged high levels of DDT into waste water
lines, which then flowed seven or eight miles into ocean outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The ocean site is also contaminated with PCBs, polychlorinated
biphenyls, which were discharged through municipal sewer pipes.
Both chemicals are suspected of causing cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a decade-long ban on commercial fishing in the area and
efforts to warn the public about the danger of eating fish caught
there, contaminated fish are still being found in markets, the EPA
said.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of markets in 1997 by Heal the Bay, a local
environmental group that monitors water quality and beaches, found
that 85 percent of the 130 samples taken exceeded the EPA's
acceptable risk level for DDT contamination, said Mark Gold,
executive director of Heal the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Gold applauded the EPA's increased attention to the area, but
called the effort ``long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's plan, which is subject to a public hearings, would
provide money for two wardens to be on duty around the clock,
increased public outreach and education and further monitoring of
contaminant levels in commercially sold fish. The actions, which
would be in force for 10 years, would be interim steps as the EPA
continued to evaluate how to best address contamination off the
Palos Verdes Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The site is one to three miles off the peninsula between Point
Vicente and Point Fermin. The continental shelf and an adjoining
slope 100 to 300 feet deep are polluted.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the U.S. Geological Survey in 1992 and 1993 found
DDT-contaminated sediment from about 2 inches to 2 feet thick, with
the highest concentration in a 3-square-mile band near the sewer
outfall pipes.
</P>
<P>
   The accumulation is estimated at 110 tons of DDT and 11 tons of
PCBs.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA hopes to diminish the effects of the deposit by capping
at least parts of the site with sand and sediment. But scientists,
environmentalists and a lawyer for Montrose have questioned the
action. There is concern that such a move might not be effective
and that it might smother marine life or stir up the deposit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't evaluate what they're going to do in this pilot
program,'' said Stephen B. Weisberg, director of the Southern
California Coastal Water Research Project, an agency of local and
regional officials monitoring ocean water quality in the region.
``There are a variety of unknowns. They include amongst others: Can
they physically get the material in place and get it to stay there
without disturbing the existing sediment?''
</P>
<P>
   Weisberg, who resigned from a technical advisory committee for
the project because he believed it was ineffective, said more
scientific review was necessary before the EPA proceeded.
</P>
<P>
   While officials have capped contaminated areas underwater
before, they have never done so at such depths or over such a wide
area. EPA officials said the purpose of the pilot program was to
provide more information about how sediment would best be
deposited, how much would be necessary and the feasibility of
covering a large area.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest natural-resource damage cases in the nation
is being waged over the site, with federal and state agencies
seeking about $170 million in damages for cleanup and restoration
from Montrose and five other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Lytz, a lawyer for Montrose, did not return a phone call,
but he has been quoted as calling the EPA's plan unnecessary and
wasteful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
