<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PANEL HEARS CALLS FOR MEDICARE COVERAGE OF PRESCRIPTION DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration and key Republican and
Democratic lawmakers urged Congress Wednesday to broaden Medicare
to cover prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But in testimony before the Senate Finance Committee, they
differed on how to fund the program, who should be covered and
whether it should be passed before Medicare itself undergoes a full
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to the witnesses' differing proposals, Committee
member John Breaux, D-La., said, ``We've got to quit hearing and
start writing (legislation). We have a very, very narrow window of
opportunity'' to pass a bill. He was referring to the fact that
Congress' session will be shorter during this election year.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare provides health care for more than 39 million elderly
and disabled Americans. It does not cover prescription drugs
although about two thirds of Medicare recipients have some type of
outside drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Because of rising costs, some experts say Medicare will go
bankrupt by 2015. President Clinton and many lawmakers have
proposed ways to keep the program solvent longer, but none of the
plans is expected to pass this year. However, polls show that the
prescription drug proposal has considerable support among voters.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla., said Congress must make
prescription medicines available for those with little or no
medical coverage regardless of whether Medicare itself is
restructured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must act this year to help the poorest and sickest
beneficiaries obtain prescription drugs,'' he said. ``These
vulnerable individuals should not have to wait any longer for the
assistance they so desperately need.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hash, deputy administrator of the Health Care Financing
Administration, which oversees Medicare, said Congress should also
revamp the whole program this year. He noted that Clinton's plan
would extend the life of the Medicare Trust Fund until at least
2025 and make prescription drug coverage available to all
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., said only prescription drug
legislation is ``realistically'' possible in this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, said she feared Clinton's overall
plan would limit patient choice and competition among medical
providers, which she said keeps down costs.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe and Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said their own plan, which
would fund prescription drugs outside of Medicare, would provide
immediate drug benefits and keep down spending.
</P>
<P>
   But Frist argued that drug benefits not linked to Medicare
risked runaway costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., also advocated drug coverage
within Medicare. Disagreeing with Bilirakis' plea to offer coverage
to poor people first this year, Kennedy urged that such coverage
should be available to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Committee member Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla, said, ``To deny
prescription drug coverage in today's times is almost ludicrous,''
but he said Medicare overhaul is necessary too.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
