<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-ISHIHARA-860&AMP;AD     03-29 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ISHIHARA-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UPSTART GOVERNOR TAKES ON JAPAN'S MANDARINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ If any politician was ever going to try to break the
central government's hold over almost all aspects of even local
governing, the most likely candidate has been the crusading
shoot-from-the-lip governor of Tokyo, Shintaro Ishihara.
</P>
<P>
   For a man whose political career has been fueled by provocation
and controversy, he had a relatively quiet first year as governor
of one of the world's biggest cities. There had been a
uncontroversial proposal to impose strict pollution controls on
diesel vehicles, for example.
</P>
<P>
   There had also been talk about somehow ridding Tokyo of the
black crows that noisily haunt its streets, systematically ripping
through trash left outside for collection. Ishihara suggested crow
pie.
</P>
<P>
   But the city has grave fiscal problems, in part because of the
national economic downturn. In a jam, Ishihara's populist
inspiration was to soak the banks, one of the least popular
institutions, along with the government, in this society enmeshed
in a long financial crisis. The banking system was recently given a
$73 billion bailout from the national government.
</P>
<P>
   And so the uproar over his proposal to begin taxing the largest
banks with headquarters in the city on April 1, to a total of $1
billion a year, has shown that the governor's first months in
office were merely the quiet before the storm. Coincidentally or
not, the expected revenues almost match the size of the city's
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The ruckus has little to do with the banks or any other narrowly
defined policy matter, and everything to do with a creeping
revolution in which local governments are flexing their muscles and
speaking up.
</P>
<P>
   For the provinces, Ishihara's tax proposal resembles a sort of
Boston Tea Party, the first dramatic crack in a system
euphemistically called administrative guidance, under which the
central government decides everything from budgets to road projects
on behalf of the local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Ishihara seems eager to be at the forefront of the movement for
local control.
</P>
<P>
   Ishihara, 67, a prize-winning fiction writer and a former
transportation minister, has clearly returned to the spot that he
most enjoys, the center of unrelenting political and media
attention. Members of the City Hall press corps say he exultingly
refers to his proposals as kamikaze, or a divine wind, and finds it
difficult to suppress the characteristic smirk he wears when things
are going his way.
</P>
<P>
   The last time so much fuss was made about him, in 1989, Ishihara
had just published his best-selling anti-American screed, ``The
Japan That Can Say No.'' Now, to the endless irritation of Tokyo's
bureaucratic mandarins, he is showing the traditionally powerless
prefectures, and their residents, they can say no, too.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the central government officials who decide on
matters large and small looked around desperately for anything in
the law that would allow them to stop Ishihara's plan. When they
found no legal way to stop him, executives of the big banks and the
people who regulate them took to calling the governor names.
</P>
<P>
   ``The devil,'' is one epithet that has frequently been used.
Eisuke Sakakibara, the former deputy finance minister who was
Japan's candidate to lead the International Monetary Fund, and one
of the few other public figures known for speaking his mind,
recently compared Ishihara to Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not saying he is a right-wing dictator, but that's what
his tactics remind me of, and I'm worried,'' Sakakibara said.
</P>
<P>
   What is most worrisome to those fighting to preserve control
over Kasumigaseki, the area of the city that is home to the
national ministries, is that the movement for local control is
spreading. Other localities have rejected government-supported
nuclear-power projects and huge dam-building plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not really at war with the national government, but the
direction is toward change and destroying the central authority,''
Ishihara said in an interview in which he discussed his ambitions
at length. ``In order to do that, we don't need to drop a bomb on
Kasumigaseki. We need to make them aware that the real needs of the
people and what the government is doing are really far apart from
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Ishihara has always seemed obsessed with Japan's direction and
place in the world. In the financial bubble years of the 1980s, he
reveled in excoriating Americans for their racism and urged the
United States to become used to learning at the knee of an Asian
powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   For the new century, with his country locked in a 10-year slide,
he has a new diagnosis and a new prescription. Japan has no worthy
political leadership, no real intellectual or political debate and,
worst of all, no direction. Unsurprisingly, the tonic he offers _
with his favorable public opinion ratings soaring into the 70s _ is
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The English historian Toynbee said that the biggest cause of a
country's decline and eventual disappearance is the inability to
make decisions,'' Ishihara said. ``That is exactly the condition
that Japan finds itself in. The decision-making process in Japan
takes forever, because people shun responsibility.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To be sure, under Ishihara's brash leadership, Japan would not
have that problem. The trouble, some caution, is that with a figure
so impish, the country would have plenty of new troubles, instead.
Already, Ishihara conducts his own parallel foreign policy of
sorts, for example mischievously inviting the Dalai Lama and the
departing president of Taiwan to Tokyo, drawing stern warnings from
China.
</P>
<P>
   Others warn of a troubling streak of emotional nationalism and
an association with militarist causes throughout his career. ``He
advocates the revision of the Constitution and associates himself
with people who are extremely dangerous,'' a prominent Japanese
commentator, Makoto Sataka, said. ``Then there is the matter of his
style, a top-down approach that neglects the details. Also, I would
say that he doesn't regard himself with a very critical eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Ishihara brushes off criticisms of his nationalism and openly
longs for a strong Japan that honors the values of old. ``There are
no more samurai in Japan,'' he said. ``You could use another word,
tough guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would lead a revival, he spoke almost like a
cowboy. ``I had that ambition once,'' Ishihara said. ``But I see
the sun is setting, and the road is long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
