<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-NEW-PLANETS-ART-N     03-29 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NEW-PLANETS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 TINY PLANETS DETECTED LIGHTYEARS AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT15, is being sent to New York Times photo
clients and  a graphic is being sent to New York Times graphic
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a discovery boosting prospects of finding Earth-size worlds
beyond the solar system, astronomers have for the first time
detected planets apparently smaller than Saturn that are orbiting
other Sun-like stars.
</P>
<P>
   Using the world's largest ground-based telescope and refinements
in their search techniques, the American astronomers found
compelling evidence of two relatively small planets around separate
stars a little more than 100 light-years away. The orbits of the
planets are so close to the host stars that scorching temperatures
there rule out the existence of life or liquid water.
</P>
<P>
   But with the new findings, the discovery team and other
scientists said Wednesday, the search for extrasolar planets
crossed a new frontier of expectations. Of the 30 such planets
detected until now, all have been the size of Jupiter, the solar
system's giant, or much larger. This raised nagging questions: Were
all these true planets? Did this undermine the prevailing theory
that planets form by a snowball effect of growth from small ones to
large bodies?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists were thus reassured to learn that in other planetary
systems there are worlds the size of Saturn and smaller, perhaps
many of them. Now they suspect that it will be only a matter of
time and improved technology before Earth-size worlds will be
detected in other planetary systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This suggests there are going to be many, many more planets
out there that are small,'' Dr. R. Paul Butler of the Carnegie
Institution in Washington, one of the discoverers of the two
Saturn-class planets, said Wednesday at a news conference at the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Heidi B. Hammel, an astrophysicist at the Space Science
Institute in Boulder, Colo., who was not a member of the discovery
team, predicted that in a year or two extrasolar planets with the
masses of Uranus would be discovered. In the solar-system
hierarchy, Jupiter's mass is 317 times that of Earth, Saturn's 95
times, Neptune's 17 and Uranus' 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely critical step towards finding
terrestrial-type planets,'' Hammel said. ``We are pushing
boundaries that we have not pushed before.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five years since extrasolar planetary exploration began,
Butler and Dr. Geoffrey W. Marcy of the University of California at
Berkeley have been the most successful at it. They conducted the
most recent observations at the Keck Observatory on Mauna Kea, in
Hawaii, using an improved spectrometer developed by Dr. Steve Vogt
of the University of California at Santa Cruz. NASA and the
National Science Foundation supported the research.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomers did not actually see the planets. They monitored
slight wobbles of the host stars as they responded to the
gravitational pull exerted by planetary objects near them. The
minimum mass of a planet and its orbital time and shape were
calculated from these gravitational perturbations.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, Marcy and Butler determined the presence of a
planet at least 80 percent the mass of Saturn orbiting 3.8 million
miles from the star HD46375, 109 light-years away in the
constellation Monoceros. Being so close to its star, the planet
takes only three days to complete an orbit; that is a full year. An
extremely hot year it is, with temperatures averaging 2070 degrees
Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   The other planet was detected orbiting the star 79 Ceti, also
known as HD16141, located 117 light-years away in the constellation
Cetus. Its mass is estimated to be 70 percent that of Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   Because this object was farther away from its star, about 32.5
million miles, it took the astronomers longer to be sure that they
were indeed observing a planet and could calculate the time and
shape of its orbit. Though they were reasonably sure by last
August, they said they waited to collect more confirming data
before announcing the Ceti planet. Marcy said they were still
tracking another Saturn-class object before making any definitive
statements.
</P>
<P>
   From their observations, Marcy said, the Ceti planet travels an
extremely lopsided orbit, compared with the more neatly circular
orbits of the other newly discovered planet and all the members of
the solar system. Each orbit takes 75 days, and the planet follows
a course that would be equivalent to moving inside and outside of
Mercury's path around the Sun. Like Mercury, it is blasted by heat
up to 1500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomers said their discoveries so far were mainly
confined to the immediate vicinity of stars, where planets would be
close enough to have a pronounced gravitational effect on their
host stars and complete orbits in a matter of days or months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a planet took more than four years to orbit a star, we
haven't been looking long enough'' to be sure it is a planet, Marcy
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Marcy-Butler team accounts for 21 of the 30 extrasolar
planetary discoveries until now, and as Marcy noted, ``We've never
made a false claim, and we are proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Impressed by the most recent discovery, Dr. Alan P. Boss, a
theorist of planetary evolution at the Carnegie Institution, said
he could foresee ``the incredible number of other planets we will
be finding as the search techniques are improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was surprised to find Saturn-size planets, Butler
responded, ``I would have been more shocked if we hadn't found
smaller and smaller planets.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
