<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-HUMAN-GENOME-NYT &LR;      03-29 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HUMAN-GENOME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE PROGRESS REPORTED IN DECODING KEY OF HEREDITARY INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (cjl) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The public consortium of universities engaged in decoding the
human genome has accomplished two-thirds of its preliminary goal,
Dr. Francis Collins, director of the National Human Genome Research
Institute, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate the public consortium is on track to complete a
rough draft of the genome by the end of June, Collins said. If so,
the consortium's version of the genome would probably be available
to researchers before the more finished version being promised by
its private competitor, Celera Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The decoding of the genome, the DNA molecules in which the human
hereditary information is inscribed, is expected in time to
transform medicine by revealing the genes that make the body
vulnerable to disease.
</P>
<P>
   The rough draft, by the consortium's definition, will constitute
90 percent of the genome with an error rate no worse than 1 in
1,000 among its component chemical units.
</P>
<P>
   The rough draft will fall well short of a finished, complete
sequence but should still prove valuable for researchers because it
will contain most of the human genes, even though some will be in
bits and pieces. The public consortium, Collins said, has now
decoded 2,178,076 DNA units, or about two-thirds of the expected
total. Altogether the human genome contains about 3 billion units
of DNA, packaged in the form of 23 chromosomes.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium's rival, Celera, is decoding the human genome by
a different method and has said it will publish its sequence only
when it is almost fully assembled, sometime later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Celera said that in January it had decoded 2,580,000 DNA units,
putting it roughly at the stage the consortium has now reached. Dr.
J. Craig Venter, the company's president, has said the material
being deposited by the consortium in Genbank, a publicly accessible
Internet data bank, is in the form of fragments that cannot be
further joined together and whose position on their parent
chromosomes is largely unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Lipman, director of the National Center for
Biotechnology Information, confirmed that the public consortium's
data are mostly in the form of short fragments about 10,000 units
long and that the site of each fragment on its chromosome is
roughly but not always precisely known.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the disjointed nature of the fragments, ``A lot of
what people want to do can be done with draft sequence _ people
will find it very useful,'' Lipman said.
</P>
<P>
   The public consortium thus seems on track to achieve the goal it
announced after Celera entered the race, producing a quick rough
draft containing most human genes in a form useful to researchers.
Celera may or may not have decoded more DNA data by the end of June
but its equivalent product will not be publicly available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
