<HEADER>
A1560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEX-TORNADO-NYT &LR;      03-29 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-TORNADO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO LEAVES TRAIL OF DESTRUCTION IN DOWNTOWN FORT WORTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Although at least three people died and 100
were injured Tuesday evening when tornadoes swept through downtown
Fort Worth and nearby Arlington, the most common sentiment
expressed here Wednesday was relief that more people had not been
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have been a tragedy of monumental proportions. We
have sidestepped a major disaster,'' Lt. Gov. Rick Perry of Texas
said after surveying the damage Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Officials searched Wednesday to see if any more bodies were in
the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's streets were littered with debris, and battered
buildings, demolished automobiles and downed trees marked the
blocks-wide swath of the twister that sliced through the city.
Trees still standing near the city's center were stripped of leaves
and covered with dangling shards of building insulation.
</P>
<P>
   Roofs of warehouses were thrown into the street.
Tractor-trailers were tossed about. The roof of one church had
collapsed and the facade of another's steeple was stripped away to
reveal twisted steel girders.
</P>
<P>
   City officials, fighting massive traffic snarls and hazardous
conditions created by debris that drifted down from damaged
high-rise buildings, sealed off about 2 square miles of the city's
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a very dangerous situation,'' said Police Chief
Ralph Mendoza. ``We could have 200-pound pieces of glass dropping
from some of these buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Two people died in collapsed buildings in Fort Worth. Two
motorists were swept from their automobile into the Trinity River
by flood waters at the edge of downtown Fort Worth. The body of
only one had been recovered by late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Don Coash, a meteorologist with WeatherData Inc., a forecasting
firm in Wichita, Kan., said the destruction was a result of
separate twisters in Fort Worth and Arlington that remained on the
ground much longer than usual for such storms.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials and weather forecasters said that early warning
of the impending storm, and the fact that most downtown workers had
already returned home for the day, had played a major part in
limiting the loss of life.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, who was filling in for Gov. George W. Bush, who was
campaigning in the Northeast, said that he had spoken to the
governor earlier Wednesday and that they both wanted to express
``heartfelt sympathy to those who have lost loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush declared Tarrant County, which includes Fort Worth and
Arlington, a disaster area Wednesday morning and has sent a request
to the federal government for a disaster relief, Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth residents spent Wednesday surveying the damage and
reliving the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Gearhart, 23, had been waiting with his roommate for a
Dallas Stars hockey game to begin on television in his apartment
when, he said, ``Everything started to get really dark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Papers started flying down the street, and we could see banks
of clouds swirling and intertwining above us,'' Gearhart said.
``When big chunks of wood started blowing past, we hit the
stairwell to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   The twister split into two funnel clouds just west of his
apartment building, Gearhart said, and both leapfrogged past and
hit the 35-story Bank One building down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bank One just got mauled,'' Gearhart said.
</P>
<P>
   This was to have been opening day for the Nostalgic New Orleans
Apartments, an eight-unit building that Brett Thomas and his
brother Mark had worked six months to restore. Instead, they spent
Wednesday picking through the wreckage left of their project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first ad ran in this morning's paper,'' Brett Thomas said,
as he sat on a chimney that had blown off a building across the
street. The roof of his two-story building sagged, and broken glass
littered the yard.
</P>
<P>
   The twisters struck near sundown, moving from the west to the
southeast through downtown Fort Worth, retreating into the sky to
drop down again in Arlington, 30 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Gehren said the funnel passed about two blocks from her
house. ``The power went out, and my husband had just managed to get
the garage door closed when the wind picked up and we started
hearing explosions,'' Gehren said. ``I started screaming and didn't
stop until it was over.''
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 people remained without power Wednesday, according
to Pat Nichols, a spokeswoman for the major electric supplier in
the area, Texas Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   City officials, still scrambling to respond to the disaster,
said it was too early to say exactly how much damage had been done
in financial terms or how long it would take to recover from the
storms.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Terrell, Fort Worth's city manager, said a preliminary
survey by his staff had found 52 commercial structures damaged and
eight buildings destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville, Tenn., was struck by a similar storm in April 1998
that killed one person and did $200 million in damage. Billy
Fields, coordinator of that city's Tornado Recovery Board, said it
would probably take Fort Worth three or four years to rebound from
the tornadoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
