<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-STOCK30-COX     03-29 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-STOCK30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth to offer tracking stock for Latin American unit
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. announced plans Wednesday to create a
tracking stock for its Latin American businesses, a bold move aimed
at raising billions of dollars that could be used to expand that
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Coming as AT&AMP;T prepares its own blockbuster public offering for
a wireless tracking stock, the BellSouth plan is meant to get
investors to see the unit's solid growth and potential.
</P>
<P>
   By separating Latin America from the rest of BellSouth _ if only
on paper _ the company hopes to set its market value free from the
doldrums that have beset the mother company.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's operations would be unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   What could be dramatically different is the company's market
value.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth stock has for the past year traded within a fairly
narrow range, even when many technology stocks were surging
skyward. Yet $25 billion-a-year BellSouth has within it several
businesses that would _ the company believes _ be highly valued if
they were on their own as ``pure plays.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the aim of a tracking stock: to unlock the market value
of a unit within a company without spinning it off.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation was that BellSouth was preparing to issue a tracking
stock for its wireless operations. But BellSouth and SBC began
talking about combining their wireless units, perhaps also allying
their international businesses or going all the way to a complete
merger.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth Chief Executive F. Duane Ackerman has long been
adamant that the company means to thrive on its own. In announcing
its own Latin American tracker, BellSouth has put some muscle
behind that intent.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth officials Wednesday declined comment on their filing,
citing concern about violating federal restrictions against hyping
a stock before an IPO. The public offering will come later this
year after review by federal regulators and approval by
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's filing makes clear that the company sees Latin
America as a big market.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has operations in 10 countries that have more than 6
million customers and last year produced $2.4 billion in revenue.
Growth potential is enormous, especially in wireless, where
BellSouth has most of its Latin American money. About eight of
every 100 people has a wireless phone compared to rates of about 40
percent in the United States and twice that in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, millions of people in the region have no phone service
at all and only a tiny handful are linked to the Internet.
BellSouth's filing cites analysts who predict yearly growth of 28
percent in the number of wireless customers in Latin America, 21
percent in wireless revenues and 16 percent in overall
telecommunications revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has issued a tracker for its wireless business, and that
stock has far outpaced the performance of the parent company's
shares. AT&AMP;T last fall announced plans for a wireless tracker, and
this week said it hopes to raise more than $13 billion when the
stock is issued _ which would make that public offering more than
twice the size of the previous record holder, UPS, whose IPO raised
$5.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   However, no other telecommunications company has tried issuing a
tracker for one geographic area.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's tracker will include all the company's Latin
American businesses _ from wireless to Internet _ but leave the
company free to manage its U.S. wireless business separately.
</P>
<P>
   How much could a BellSouth tracking stock be worth?
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have said the Latin American group is worth about
$14 billion, but BellSouth has not yet set a price, a decision that
will come later. The filing sets a goal of $1 billion to be raised
by the IPO, but the company has plenty of time to modify that, too.
The company is mum on the question of how many shares will be
issued, and what proportion of them will be sold publicly.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has licenses covering 176 million people in Latin
America _ roughly equivalent to the U.S. population covered by AT&AMP;T
wireless.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, for example, saw its stock gain about 10 points _ the
equivalent of roughly $35 billion _ after announcing plans for its
wireless tracking stock, noted analyst Anthony Ferrugia of A.G.
Edwards &AMP; Co. ``You can't extrapolate from that to BellSouth, but I
would expect some incremental increase.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hours after the announcement, BellSouth stock climbed
about $2.375 a share, finishing the day at $47.25, up $2.125 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   With the tracker, BellSouth surrenders nothing, retaining
control of operations while waiting to reap a multibillion-dollar
bonus, Ferrugia said. ``I would say that BellSouth has an excellent
presence in South America and they know that trackers have been
getting very good valuations lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
