<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-OWNERS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anti-crime measures considered at close of NFL owners meeting
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The NFL closed its annual owners meeting
Wednesday without adopting a new discipline policy for players who
commit off-field criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
   But tougher penalties might not be too far away.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue, other league officials and a
handful of coaches met for more than two hours Wednesday to discuss
the issue. Tagliabue presented a two-page list of proposals,
including more education for players and stiffer discipline for
those who break the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to keep talking to the Players Association and
we'll keep having our internal discussions,'' Tagliabue said.
``(The meeting) focused on goals and it focused on issues. There
were very positive feelings about the programs we have in place.
The challenge is not to get frustrated. It's to continue educating
our players.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Henderson, the NFL's executive vice president of labor
relations, co-chaired the unprecedented panel discussion. Henderson
said a toughened anti-crime policy could be in place after the next
league meetings in Baltimore in May.
</P>
<P>
   Several high-profile incidents involving NFL players in recent
months prompted the self-examination. Baltimore Ravens linebacker
Ray Lewis will go on trial in May for the Jan. 31 murders of two
men outside a Atlanta nightclub. Carolina Panthers receiver Rae
Carruth is charged with plotting the murder of his pregnant
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue imposed a policy on violent crime in 1997. Under that
plan, players who are charged with criminal acts undergo a
mandatory clinical evaluation and possibly counseling. If players
are convicted of crimes, they can be fined and suspended. A second
conviction can lead to expulsion from the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel strongly the American public is fed up,'' Patriots
owner Robert Kraft said. ``They're sick of it. We in the NFL need
to be mindful of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the solutions discussed at Wednesday's meeting were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Identifying players deemed ``at-risk'' for problems and
requiring them to undergo counseling before they enter the NFL.
Those players would enter the league under probation and would face
stiffer penalties if convicted of crimes. Some players who have
more questionable pasts might be required to wait one or two years
before entering the league.
</P>
<P>
   _ Creating support groups within each team consisting of veteran
players who would serve as mentors for younger players. The groups
might also include an assistant coach, trainer or security
official.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren established a six-man veterans
committee last season. Buccaneers coach Tony Dungy said he will
consider adding such a group to his team.
</P>
<P>
   _ Creating standardized interviews and background checks for
prospective players, instead of the individual teams conducting
them at the combine workouts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Asking military leaders to serve as security consultants in
locker rooms. NFL officials pointed out that the military meshes
personnel from diverse backgrounds, much as pro football does.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever solutions are adopted, most owners agreed that the
league needs to be active earlier. And at least one owner suggested
it might be time to stop taking chances on players with
questionable pasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had a policy, at least in the last four to five
years,'' Broncos owner Pat Bowlen said, ``that we're very concerned
about taking guys that have had problems in college, and I believe
that's a very good policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
