<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDERLAND-TV-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC IN WONDERLAND
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3{ stars 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's all in the name for ABC's Thursday lineup. At the
beginning of this season, the network offered up a little dud
called ``Wasteland,'' which disappeared promptly enough.
``Wasteland'' lived up to its title, and, amazingly enough, so does
``Wonderland,'' debuting tonight. It's a grim, frantic, unruly and
at times obtuse production, but it's also, no doubt about it,
pretty amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' was created by Peter Berg, who starred in
``Chicago Hope'' and wrote and directed ``Very Bad Things'' (which
also lived up to its name). His concept here is pretty simple:
``ER'' set in a mental institution and shot in the
drunks-manning-the-Steadicam, documentarian manner of ``NYPD
Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg does not appear in the show, but as a consolation he has
assembled the best cast of actors you've never heard of. Character
actor Ted Levine stars as Dr. Robert Banger, who heads the forensic
psychiatry department of a New York public hospital, and therefore
deals with crazies who have run afoul of the law; he's also going
through a messy divorce and custody battle. Martin Donovan, a
veteran of filmmaker Hal Hartley's verbiage-fests, plays Dr. Neil
Harrison, who works with Banger and (just barely) heads up some
group therapy sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison's married to Dr. Lyla Garrity (Michelle Forbes), who
runs a psychiatric emergency program and is having issues with her
pregnancy. When a basket case who thinks he's Zeus (Leland Orser)
guns down five cops and causes a ruckus at the hospital that
endangers the health of Garrity's unborn baby, it's discovered she
had denied him medication a few days earlier _ medication that
might have prevented the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland's'' multiple narratives are dense and fractious
and, as is often true of pilots, the material is piled on furiously
_ you may be sympathetic when a character repeatedly shouts out,
``Can we turn down the volume?'' And since it deals with the
mentally ill, the stories invariably are going to be tinged with
tragedy. The show whistles along, but not with ``ER's'' calculated
slickness; it's a little more frazzled in its storytelling,
presumably mirroring its subject matter. In its own way,
``Wonderland'' is as visceral in its milieu and sliding-scale
morality as HBO's ``Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong performances from Levine, Donovan and Forbes all
evince a decency that is being ground down by impossible daily
pressures. Even the guest stars dazzle, including Jay O. Sanders as
a suicidal spurned lover and, in next week's episode, Lenka
Peterson as an elderly woman who virtually explodes in apoplectic
rage at the mere thought of her husband. And, here and there, are
disarming little touches that keep the show compellingly watchable:
At one point, apropos of nothing, a patient watches with mute
delight while a miniature rhinoceros roams amid his huaraches.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's what I think of the show; here's what ABC thinks:
It's thrown ``Wonderland'' opposite the juggernaut that is ``ER''
without so much as a courtesy run in a less competitive time slot.
Which means audiences are unlikely to find the show and, if they
do, they're unlikely to be able to suss out everything that's been
going on when they do. Unless ABC does the show a favor, it's
likely to be gone by May sweeps. It's a little shocking the network
isn't trying to help out a show of this verve and energy a little
more; after all, it can't live off of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' forever, can it? &QL; 
________ &QL; 
The show: ``Wonderland.'' &QL; 
Drama set in and around a mental institution. &QL; 
The stars: Ted Levine, Martin Donovan, Michelle Forbes. &QL; 
Where: ABC (Channel 7). &QL; 
When: 10 p.m. Thursdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
