<SLUG> BC-SENATE-FLAG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REJECTS PROPOSED AMENDMENT TO PROTECT U.S. FLAG 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate rejected a proposed constitutional
amendment Wednesday that would have banned the burning or
desecration of the U.S. flag, but supporters insisted they would
reintroduce the measure until it passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passage of this amendment is inevitable ...We know we don't
have the votes here today, but sooner or later we're going to get
this through,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said shortly before the
Senate failed by a 63-37 vote to muster the two-thirds majority
needed for passage of a constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The vote ended three days of politically charged debate over the
amendment designed to challenge a 1989 Supreme Court decision
striking down flag-protection statutes in 48 states as a violation
of free speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat marked the third time in a decade that supporters had
failed to muster the 67 votes necessary to approve the amendment.
In 1995, it failed by three votes.
</P>
<P>
   The House, meanwhile, has passed it three times, the most recent
in June. But the amendment must be approved by both houses of
Congress before it can be sent on to the states for ratification.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., criticized opponents
of the measure, as well as the 1989 Supreme Court ruling, for what
he called their ``fundamental misunderstanding of the nation's
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was ``ludicrous'' to interpret desecration of the
flag as free speech when most ``patriotic'' Americans consider it
to be a ``repugnant'' form of expression that should be outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American flag is a sacred, basic, fundamental symbol of
our nation's freedom,'' Lott said, adding that it should be treated
respectfully as if it were one of the country's most valuable
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to the heart of who we are as a people and as a
nation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W. Va., said that while the flag may be
the ``symbol of our nation's values,'' it does not warrant
protection by tampering with the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love that flag. But we must love the Constitution more,''
Byrd said, referring to the 209-year-old document as ``the thing
itself,'' that the nation's democratic principles are built on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe it belongs in our Constitution ... because I
believe that many instances of flag desecration can be prosecuted
under general laws protecting public and private property, laws
which do not require any constitutional amendment,'' Byrd said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that flag burning, in his view, is ``only a rare
occurrence,'' and protecting it with a constitutional amendment
would only give ``attention seekers who defile the flag the
opportunity to defy the Constitution as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's opposition to the amendment surprised Hatch, chief
sponsor of the measure, who had been counting on Byrd to help
convince wavering lawmakers to support it. Going into the debate,
Hatch believed he was only one or two votes shy of the 67 he
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's opposition marked a reversal from his past stands on the
issue. He has voted in favor of it twice before, and his decision
not to back it a third time may have swayed other senators who
often look to him for guidance on constitutional matters.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing to oppose the amendment, Byrd said he went against
the prevailing sentiment in his state and that his decision had
caused him ``greater anguish'' than any other he has made during
his 41 years in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that after careful study, he had concluded a flag
amendment could not be justified because it would extend rather
than narrow the power of government and would not protect any
``basic civil right'' guaranteed under the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
