<HEADER>
A1570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-ART-350&AMP;ADD-N     03-29 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ART-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT PRESS CONFERENCE, CLINTON URGES CONGRESSIONAL GOP TO WORK WITH
HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT9 and 13 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mindful that he is running out of time to reach
deals with Congress, President Clinton called on Republicans on
Wednesday to work with him on a wide range of issues including gun
safety, the addition of prescription drug coverage to Medicare and
regulation of the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Republicans in the House and Senate were stalling
or playing politics with many issues he considers to be his
priorities, and he portrayed himself as eager to ring up real
accomplishments in the relatively short time left in the
legislative calendar of his final year in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people want action, and they deserve it,''
Clinton told a news conference in the East Room of the White House.
``The only thing left is for the congressional leadership to reach
across party lines and to work with us to break the grip of special
interests and do the people's business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton offered no concessions on any of the issues he
brought up, and left the impression that his idea of compromise was
for the Republicans to give in. And he did little to dispel the
feeling among Republicans that he is more interested in provoking
confrontations that can be used to the advantage of Democrats in
the campaign than he is in getting legislation signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``With less than 10 months remaining in his administration, Bill
Clinton faces a very clear choice,'' Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the
House Republican whip, told reporters on Capitol Hill. ``Does the
president want to exploit political issues or does the president
want to help us implement effective solutions?''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans themselves face much the same choice. Some of them
favor reaching accommodation with Clinton on a few issues to
insulate themselves against the inevitable charge from Democrats
that they oversee a do-nothing Congress. Other Republicans are
convinced that the best strategy is to push through bills that
reflect their agenda, even if they draw a veto, in an effort to
send a clear message to voters as they fight to regain the White
House and retain control of the House.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even as Clinton tried to increase the pressure on Republicans on
domestic issues, he continued his efforts to work with them to win
approval in Congress for what is perhaps his top goal this year,
bringing China into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the trade agreement, reached in November after
long negotiations between Beijing and Washington, ``a
100-to-nothing deal'' for America, because the United States lowers
no tariffs and opens no markets, while China must do both. He also
defended the deal on national security grounds.
</P>
<P>
   But he bristled at criticism from organized labor and many
liberal Democrats that his negotiators should have included labor
standards and goals for environmental improvement in the accord.
Clinton is struggling to convince Democrats, especially in the
House, to support the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we had a bilateral trade agreement,'' he said,
differentiating a country-to-country deal from an agreement to make
China a full member of the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's own negotiators said last year that the talks were a
bilateral accord. China, however, has made it clear that it
considers labor and environmental issues beyond the scope of the
WTO, and refused to negotiate on those issues. Vice President Al
Gore, in comments that were interpreted as less than enthusiastic
about the WTO deal, said earlier this year that, if elected
president, he would try to negotiate a tougher agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also praised both President Jiang Zemin of China and
Taiwan's president-elect, Chen Shui-bian. Chen, whose party has
called for Taiwan's independence, has backed away from that
position in carefully worded statements since his election 11 days
ago. That has defused tension with China, at least initially.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference, which lasted an hour and 15 minutes, was
the second held by Clinton this year. He appeared relaxed as he
discussed the stalled Middle East peace talks, the presidential
election in Russia and his delight that his 20-year-old daughter,
Chelsea, still enjoys traveling with him despite having reached an
age when many children do not want to hang out with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Only once did Clinton appear to get a bit riled, when he was
asked whether he and Gore had played fast and loose with campaign
finance rules in raising money for their 1996 re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was as appalled as the next person when I found out that we
had taken funds, that people had given us money that wasn't
legal,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president said Gore ``was showing a little humility'' this
week when he described himself as an imperfect messenger for
campaign finance reform, in part because of the controversy
surrounding the vice president's fund-raising appearance in 1996 at
a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he liked Gore's idea of establishing an endowment
to help fund general elections as a way of diminishing the
influence of campaign contributions in politics. And he said
Congress would function better if members of both parties did not
have to spend so much time raising money.
</P>
<P>
   In setting out his domestic agenda for the rest of the
legislative year _- which will be shortened by the eagerness of
members of Congress to go home and campaign _ Clinton stressed his
desire for passage of gun legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Congress to pass his request for $300 million in new
funding to help reduce gun violence through an array of initiatives
including faster and more comprehensive background checks on gun
purchasers and the hiring of new prosecutors on the local, state
and federal level to prosecute gun-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   And he demanded that the Republican leadership move forward on a
gun-related bill that has been bottled up since in a House-Senate
conference. The legislation would tighten rules on the sales of
guns at gun shows, require child safety locks on handguns and ban
the importation of large-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears the opponents of reform have run out of arguments,
so now they're just trying to run out the clock,'' Clinton said.
``The argument is over. Gun safety measures do work and do not
interfere with the interests of ordinary hunters and sports
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he wanted to see movement on a bill, already passed
by the House, giving patients more rights in dealing with health
maintenance organizations. He criticized Republicans for attaching
a $123 billion package of tax cuts to legislation that would
increase the minimum wage by $1, to $6.15, over two years.
</P>
<P>
   The president repeated his longstanding request for more money
for school construction and modernization. And he urged Congress to
respond to a recent Supreme Court ruling that the Food and Drug
Administration does not have the authority to regulate tobacco as a
drug by passing legislation that would give the agency that power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
