<HEADER>
A1572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CENSUS30-COX     03-29 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Census staff ensures homeless not left out
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nine people were hidden under a bridge in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it was hours before dawn and they were covered with
layers of blankets, the homeless people were cooperative and polite
to the census workers who interrupted their rest with flashlights
and questions.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men, who told a reporter his name was ``just Harry,''
said he didn't mind that census takers had come to question him
while he was in bed, because he hadn't gone to sleep yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just laid down,'' Harry said.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn Wednesday, between the hours of 4 a.m. and 7 a.m.,
census workers wearing orange vests searched nationwide for people
living under bridges, in abandoned buildings and in secret spots
sheltered by bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Their instructions were to take basic information from any of
the street people they found _ name, race, gender and age. The
address on the form was the address of their campsites. Census
workers were warned not to wake anyone, not to press if someone
didn't want to answer questions, and to leave if there was a chance
of confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials did not demand a full name if a homeless
person, like Harry, did not want to provide it, or offered only a
nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are stressing the importance of finding the homeless
this year because an estimated 2 percent of the nation's people
were not counted 10 years ago; many were street people. The
undercount cost states and local communities billions of dollars in
federal funds, distributed based on population, for community block
grants and education, transportation and social service programs.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, 1,000 census takers were dispatched Wednesday, 690
in metro Atlanta. Spokesman Lance Robertson said the teams were
everywhere _ downtown Atlanta; Marietta, where there were dozens of
``pockets''; around Six Flags Over Georgia; and behind a restaurant
in Gwinnett County.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they do not know yet how many homeless people
were counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what I expected,'' a nervous Eric Cathcart said
moments before he followed other census takers through a hole in a
chain-link fence to the place where Harry and his friends were
sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   After negotiating boulders on the dirt embankment that led to a
3-foot-high passage under the bridge, 12 census workers filed into
the place Harry and his friends have called ``home'' for eight to
10 years. Shabby mattresses were spaced for privacy, and a rusted
barrel served as a stove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning. Good morning,'' the census workers announced.
Then one muttered, ``Watch out for rats.''
</P>
<P>
   No one complained that they were awakened. Several suggested the
easiest way for the workers to get back to their cars from under
the bridge. A couple pointed the way to the sleeping area of
homeless people who were not connected to their community.
</P>
<P>
   One census worker gave $1 to the man who had just answered the
questions.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a mile away, two women and two men were found
at the home they had built by positioning a shredded mattress and
abandoned sofa around a trash can that contained a fire. One of the
men was breaking up a headboard from a bed, using it for firewood.
</P>
<P>
   He left when the census workers walked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning, y'all,'' a woman shouted from beneath her covers
on the bed. ``Give me some money for some breakfast. You. With your
brown eyes. Y'all are going to have breakfast, aren't you? Give me
some money.''
</P>
<P>
   Change was handed over and the census workers turned to leave
when she shouted sarcastically, ``Take my telephone number so you
can call me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
