<HEADLINE>
HEALTH CARE SUPPLIERS TO FORM ONLINE EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also INSURERS-ONLINE) 
(Eds.: `Lyn' cq in last graf) 
(cjl) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five big health care companies, which account for about 70
percent of the equipment, drugs and other supplies bought by the
nation's hospitals, said Wednesday that they planned to form an
online exchange that would provide information about products and
enable customers to place and track orders.
</P>
<P>
   The companies _ Johnson &AMP; Johnson, Baxter International Inc.,
Abbott Laboratories, Medtronic Inc. and GE Medical Systems, a unit
of General Electric Co. _ say the exchange's purpose was to cut
hundreds of millions of dollars out of the costs that they and
their customers incur while handling the drudge work of processing
orders. Although customers would continue to negotiate prices with
individual manufacturers, they would use the exchange to place
orders under previously negotiated contracts, check on the status
of orders, arrange delivery, check supporting documentation and
learn more about products.
</P>
<P>
   The companies, which will own equal shares of the exchange, say
they expect little opposition from regulators. They are not banding
together on prices, and they are inviting all other medical
suppliers to join. ``There will be a firewall so that we can't even
see each other's prices,'' said Miles White, the chief executive of
Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   The five companies are still in the process of hiring the
exchange's managers and putting the finishing touches on its
software. They expect the exchange, which will be based in Chicago,
to go online in the United States this summer and to expand
globally next year.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange will be a free service for customers. It will be
financed by fees from participating suppliers, including the five
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never take this entity public, because we don't want to
have to maximize profits for shareholders,'' said Jeffrey Immelt,
the chief executive of GE Medical.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur D. Collins Jr., Medtronic's president, added, ``The CEO
of this exchange will be gauged on how efficiently he can move
large volumes of transactions and how well customers are satisfied,
not on earnings per share.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the companies do stand to benefit financially in more
ways than just cutting costs. Numerous Web-based exchanges,
including Neoforma.com, MedCenterDirect.com, Promedix and
Broadlane, already offer health care customers one-stop shopping
for medical products. Those companies take their fees from
suppliers. By forming their own exchange, the five companies avoid
such fees.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on prices remains uncertain. Over the last decade,
many hospitals have formed powerful buying coalitions that have
forced prices for medical supplies way down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this exchange can help the hospitals lower their
transaction costs, it could alleviate the pricing pressure the
suppliers are under,'' said Michael Weinstein, a medical products
analyst at J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   But the trend lately is for huge purchasers in concentrated
industries to form online buying coalitions. The automotive and
retail industries have both announced buying consortiums, and just
Wednesday, 15 utilities said that they would form a buying
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Efforts to buy and sell on the Web always seem to lead to
lower prices for buyers at the vendors' expense,'' said Mike
Krensavage, an analyst with Brown Brothers Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   If the hospital groups put their own consortium on the Web,
their negotiating power could increase exponentially. And even if
they do not, hospitals could tap into the buying services offered
by the myriad of dot-com companies that offer such services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology is two-thirds of the reason we can negotiate
low prices,'' said Matthew Lekstutis, a senior vice president of
EDS CoNext, an online procurement service.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange may be particularly useful to small hospitals that
are still processing many orders by hand. ``We're certainly not as
automated as we could be, so putting all this on the Web can be
really useful,'' said Lyn Moore, director of health information
management for the Covenant Health System, a network of four
hospitals in Lubbock, Texas.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
