<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1575 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILTH-AND-FURY-FILM-$     03-29 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILTH-AND-FURY-FILM-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, THE SEX PISTOLS' POINT OF VIEW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Ken Tucker is critic-at-large for Entertainment Weekly.  
 By KEN TUCKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early on in ``The Filth and the Fury,'' the new documentary
about the British punk-rock band the Sex Pistols, the group's
endlessly quotable lead singer John Lydon (aka Johnny Rotten)
observes that the group was ``a bit like a Harold Pinter play: it
shouldn't work, but it does.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of the movie that Julien Temple has
assembled from footage of the band in performance, along with new
and archival interviews with the band members, their supporters and
their detractors.
</P>
<P>
   Lydon, the drummer Paul Cook, the guitarist Steve Jones, the
bassist Glen Matlock and Matlock's replacement, Sid Vicious, were a
band for little more than two years, and they recorded exactly one
album, ``Never Mind the Bollocks, Here's the Sex Pistols,''
released in 1977. It sold poorly in an America then dominated by
the Bee Gees and the Eagles, but immediately went to No. 1 in
England.
</P>
<P>
   The Sex Pistols' existence was brief, and alternately thrilling
and appalling. The brevity was due in no small part to the group's
incessant internal bickering and to its insistence, closely
documented in the new movie, on turning the usual show-business
promotional opportunities into expletive-filled assaults that would
have been unsuitable for broadcast even if mass America had been
interested in seeing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This band wasn't about making people happy,'' Lydon says in
the film; ``it was about attack _ attack, attack, attack.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this guarantees that, nearly a quarter of a century on,
many who go to see ``The Filth and the Fury'' (which is playing at
the Film Forum in Manhattan will be experiencing the spectacle of
the Sex Pistols for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   As the film makes clear, the Sex Pistols existed not to have a
career so much as to have an impact _ to release an invigorating
blast of poisonous gas into the clean, crisp air of the '70s
pop-music industry. Using footage of Laurence Olivier in ``Richard
III'' like a hiphop DJ uses record beats, Temple replays the
wretched king repeating two words of Shakespeare _ ``deformed,
unfinished'' _ over and over.
</P>
<P>
   He intercuts this filmic stutter with other images: scenes of
the Sex Pistols bashing convincingly through Jonathan Richman's
two-chord masterpiece ``Roadrunner''; shots of the shaved-headed,
safety-pinned, ragtag fashion statements the band inspired among
its young fans; and Lydon's assertion of the Pistols' ultimate
effect: ``People who had no self-respect suddenly started to view
themselves as beautiful in not being beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   A fair percentage of the movie contradicts such positive
conclusions. The group is seen being boringly loutish on a British
talk show, an infamous appearance that inspired the newspaper
headline that provides the film's title; Vicious, we are reminded,
died of a heroin overdose in 1979 after stabbing to death his
girlfriend, Nancy Spungen.
</P>
<P>
   But then, everything about the Sex Pistols turns on
contradiction. They were anti-rockers who claimed to possess little
musicianship, yet they created some of the most exciting rock
recordings ever, including ``Anarchy in the U.K.,'' ``God Save the
Queen'' and ``Pretty Vacant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pistols' behavior was consistent only in being
unpredictable: When this writer interviewed Lydon, who was sitting
on a bed in a ritzy Los Angeles hotel room in 1978, soon after the
group's breakup, the singer answered questions with polite
directness; but he stopped abruptly and leaned over the side of the
bed to vomit vigorously onto the floor to make a point about how
disgusted he was by rock-star excesses. Then he resumed the
conversation as if nothing surprising had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Filth and the Fury'' is actually the second documentary
Temple has made about the band, and it stands in polar opposition
to the first, ``The Great Rock &AMP; Roll Swindle'' (1980). ``Filth''
uses Lydon's contemporary commentary to cast the Pistols as
heroically trying to expose hypocrisy in the music industry and in
the government, while ``Swindle'' presented them as know-nothing
puppets, the creation of their manager, the former boutique owner
and self-styled anarchist Malcolm McLaren, who in that movie went
so far as to refer to ``an invention of mine they called punk
rock.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Sex Pistols: were they puppets or prophets? And how
could the same director present both notions with equal conviction,
two decades apart? The production notes for ``The Filth and the
Fury'' explain the disparity by saying that Lydon, who had feuded
with McLaren from the start of their business relationship, refused
to participate in the making of ``Swindle.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Lydon sued McLaren and won ownership of the group's
master recordings and of Temple's footage. In ``Filth,'' Temple is
obliged to give Lydon his revenge, with the singer referring to
McLaren only as ``the manager'' and calling him ``evil.'' ``He had
no control over us,'' Lydon says.
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Filth and the Fury'' is far more engrossing than
``Swindle,'' it's not because it clarifies any of the
behind-the-scenes history. Temple evinces no point of view, no
convictions; he sides with whoever's holding the film cans. But
Lydon in ``Filth'' is a far more articulate and entertaining
character than McLaren was in ``Swindle.'' It's not only that
Lydon's observations are more sociologically pointed (describing
the Thatcherite policies he sees as the source of punk's
philosophical despair, he says of his contemporaries, ``You would
not be capable of questioning your future because you didn't have
one'').
</P>
<P>
   The stage performances in ``Filth'' showcase one of the most
charismatic figures in rock history. Lydon's slicing vocals have
the sharpness of a buccaneer's sword, and he holds the stage like a
pop-music Captain Ahab. (``He hung onto the mike,'' wrote Greil
Marcus in a Rolling Stone review of the band's final concert, on
Jan. 14, 1978, in San Francisco, ``as if he were caught in a wind
tunnel, about to be blown off the stage.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The Filth and the Fury'' is a hodgepodge of self-justifying
memories; a compromised, often slapdash history of a band that
insisted rock was dead even as its own music resuscitated the form
for millions. In other words, it's a movie that shouldn't work, but
it does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
