<HEADLINE>
U.S.-JAPAN TIES HONORED IN A ROOM WITH A PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ There was a history to the elegant room at the U.S.
Embassy Residence, where Henry Aaron, Lou Brock and Ernie Banks
gathered Wednesday in a celebration of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same reception hall where Emperor Hirohito visited
Gen. Douglas MacArthur on Sept. 27, 1945, only 25 days after Japan
had surrendered on the U.S.S. Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a victorious general meeting a defeated emperor, this
time Japanese and Americans saluted the modern sporting heroes,
Sammy Sosa and Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, wearing a dark suit, and Piazza, wearing a leather jacket,
presented their respective team caps to Ambassador Thomas A. Foley.
Practicing the diplomacy that made him speaker of the House for
part of his 30-year stint in Congress, representing the Spokane
area of Washington, Foley alternated both caps for a photo
opportunity and said, ``I'll wear them both.''
</P>
<P>
   The three current Hall of Fame players and the two future Hall
of Fame players were walking on the same floor where Hirohito had
walked the entire 70-foot length to where MacArthur waited, an
obvious symbol of the new relationship between the nations. At the
end of the meeting, MacArthur had a military photographer take a
picture of him with the emperor, who was many inches shorter,
another indication to the world of the status between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, the theme was the peaceful, even joyous, link
between the two nations. Banks gave a very snappy salute to U.S.
Marines attached to the embassy. One of the Marines, Sgt. Clint
Joseph from Brooklyn, got Banks' autograph and never mentioned to
Banks that he is a diehard Mets fan _ another sign of modern
diplomacy in this historic reception room.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
