<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ DOWN AGAIN AS TECHNOLOGY STOCKS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks sent the Nasdaq stock market to the
biggest of three consecutive losses Wednesday as more investors
abandoned recent market favorites for the perceived comfort of
General Electric and other household names.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index shed 189.22 points, or 3.9 percent,
to 4,644.67.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in terms of points was the biggest since March 14,
and the percentage loss, 3.91 percent, was the biggest since March
20.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who as a group have been heavily overweighted in
technology, have become increasingly nervous about stretched
valuations. In addition, on Wednesday there were reports that one
of the biggest hedge-fund operations, Tiger Management, has decided
to close, and ``the news on Tiger Management clearly precipitated
some rotation out of these higher-momentum areas,'' said Christine
A. Callies, chief U.S. strategist at Credit Suisse First Boston.
This pall over the market was in spite of the fact that Tiger's
holdings are mainly New York Stock Exchange issues.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts pointed to a lingering effect from the
recommendation on Tuesday by Abby Joseph Cohen, the influential
Goldman, Sachs strategist, that investors trim their exposure to
stocks and hold as much as 15 percent cash. Technology companies,
she contended, were no longer undervalued.
</P>
<P>
   As the Nasdaq sagged, the Dow Jones industrial average staged an
afternoon rally of as much as 165 before losing half of it toward
the close. It ended the day with a gain of 82.61 points, or 0.76
percent, at 11,018.72.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric accounted for nearly half the Dow's gain,
jumping 7{ to a record close of 163{ after an analyst at Prudential
Securities raised his price target to 210 from 185.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart and Exxon Mobil each surged more than 4 points, the
latter among the many oil-related stocks that more than reversed
Tuesday's ragged performance as analysts and investors further
digested OPEC's announcement of plans to raise production.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a realization now that crude prices are not going to
collapse here,'' said M.J. Matts, a value-oriented portfolio
manager at National City Investment Management in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, Texaco and Atlantic Richfield all gained more than 3
points while oilfield companies Schlumberger and B. J. Services
were up more than 4 and Halliburton more than 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, less dominated by
high-technology than Nasdaq, finished up 0.79 points, to 1,508.52.
Of its components, 280 advanced and 203 declined, the biggest
point-losers being technology companies such as Motorola,
Hewlett-Packard, Texas Instruments, Micron Technology and Yahoo,
though some regained part of the lost ground after the normal 4
p.m. close. Micron's announcement of a 2-for-1 split may have
contributed to the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks joined energy in the winner's circle, with
Warner-Lambert ahead more than 3 and Merck, Bristol-Myers and
American Home Products each ahead more than 2. On the New York
Stock Exchange, advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by
1,632 to 1,336, as 57 stocks hit new 52-week lows and 54 hit new
highs. Volume climbed to 1.06 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2029EST &QL; 
