<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-MARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA CHIEF TAKES BLAME IN MARS PROGRAM FAILURES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA administrator Dan Goldin on Wednesday shouldered the blame
for recent back-to-back Mars program failures, acknowledging he
expected too much for too little.
</P>
<P>
   ``As head of NASA, I accept the responsibility'' Goldin told
workers at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., the
facility that develops the agency's planetary spacecraft, including
its Mars probes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The warning bells are sounding,'' the space agency chief said.
``The trend is very, very sobering and one we can't ignore. It says
we pushed too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldin's JPL visit and his remarks followed Tuesday's public
release of a scathing investigative report into the Dec. 3 loss of
the Mars Polar Lander, a robotic probe that was to search for water
frozen in the subsoil of the planet's south pole.
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander failure followed the Sept. 23 loss of NASA's
Mars Climate Orbiter, a probe that was to track the migration of
water vapor in the planet's thin atmosphere for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency invested $372 million in the two-mission
package.
</P>
<P>
   An 18-member panel of experts, led by Thomas Young, a retired
aerospace company executive, blamed the losses on mismanagement,
underfunding and inadequate staffing. The lapses led to a lack of
pre-launch testing and independent oversight that could have
prevented the design flaws and errors that led to the failures, the
panel concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander was out of communication with Earth as it
descended toward the surface of Mars. Investigators believe that it
most likely shattered on the frozen Martian terrain when a computer
software flaw caused the probe's descent rockets to shut down while
it was still 130 feet above the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The Climate Orbiter was lost as it attempted to maneuver into
orbit around Mars. Investigators believe it dove into the Martian
atmosphere because of errors in navigation. The errors were
attributed to JPL's use of English rather than metric units of
measurements to compute a series of small propulsive maneuvers
during the transit from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The package of missions was underfunded by at least 30 percent,
the Young panel concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The funding constraints prompted inexperienced managers at JPL
to skimp on independent oversight of their activities, pre-launch
testing, staffing and adequate training of their personnel.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's remarks, Goldin said he and his Washington staff
had pushed their ``faster, better, cheaper'' strategy for dealing
with NASA's declining budgets throughout the early and mid-1990s
too far. The strategy called on JPL to cut the size and cost of its
missions but to increase their frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin told the workers that in the future agency officials in
Washington will monitor the development of NASA's Mars probes more
closely and create reserve funds from which money can be drawn to
respond to unexpected problems.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that risk and failure are inherent in any
exploration effort that relies on innovation and breakthrough
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need you more than ever before,'' he told the workers. ``We
need you to help fix the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
