<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, April 2,
2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDKIN-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ William Friedkin was a golden boy
in Hollywood in the early 1970s. Two of his films, ``The French
Connection'' and ``The Exorcist,'' were among the most successful
of that decade. But Friedkin responded to sudden wealth and power
with the kind of self-destructive arrogance all too common in
Hollywood. The town waited for him to fail. And he did. ``Sure, I
was arrogant, I let success go to my head, I did not suffer fools
gladly,'' said Friedkin, the director of the new drama ``Rules of
Engagement,'' which opens Friday. He spoke quietly. ``I probably
was more enamored of myself than my talent deserved,'' he said. ``I
thought I was infallible. I wasn't.'' At the age of 64, Friedkin
accepts his infallibility with a shrug, and still seems brashly
confident. But the years have taken their toll. By Bernard
Weinraub. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HIP-HOP-FILMS (Undated) _ Hip-hop, to the discomfort of artistic
purists and cultural puritans alike, has become the lingua franca
of global youth culture. Nowhere is this more evident than at the
movies, where hip-hop increasingly provides not only a source of
subsidiary revenue (thanks to soundtrack sales), but a repertory of
styles, references and attitudes now showing at theaters
everywhere. By A.O. Scott. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-FIDELITY-FILM (Undated) _ In the transition from novel to
film, Rob, the hero of ``High Fidelity'' _ Nick Hornby's 1995
novel, Stephen Frears's new film _ undergoes some minor
transformations: he ceases being British and becomes American,
relocates from London to Chicago and sees his last name change from
Fleming to Gordon. The first two changes were no doubt to
accommodate the casting of the Chicago native John Cusack; the last
you can speculate about on your own. Otherwise, much remains the
same. Rob is still the owner of a marginally failing vintage record
shop, still called Championship Vinyl, which is still manned by
``the musical moron twins,'' Dick and Barry; he is still moping
about his love life, especially his recent dumping by his
girlfriend, Laura; and he is still the gloomy underachiever whose
relentless navel-gazing is made palatable by his honesty about his
shortcomings and his often quite funny insights about men, women
and romance. As film adaptations go, this one is almost fiercely
faithful. By Jamie Malanowski. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILTH-AND-FURY-FILM (Undated) _ In ``The Filth and the Fury,''
the new documentary about the British punk-rock band the Sex
Pistols, the group's endlessly quotable lead singer John Lydon (aka
Johnny Rotten) observes that the group was ``a bit like a Harold
Pinter play: it shouldn't work, but it does.'' The same could be
said of the movie that Julien Temple has assembled from footage of
the band in performance, along with new and archival interviews
with the band members, their supporters and their detractors. ``The
Filth and the Fury'' is now playing in Manhattan. By Ken Tucker.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TERE-O'CONNOR-DANCE (Undated) _ Unlike some choreographers, who
bark like drill sergeants at their dancers, Tere O'Connor seldom
raises his voice, although inside, he says, his vision of what
should be sometimes collides with his realization of what is,
pushing him to the point of a scream. ``Hi Everybody!,'' which
opens on Thursday for a three-week run at Dance Theater Workshop in
Manhattan, is a poetic, absurdist combination of dance and what
O'Connor calls ``the theater of the obvious,'' meant to entertain
the audience while disorienting it and provoking it into a
catharsis. By Joseph Carman. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATRICK-STEWART-THEATER (New York) _ Patrick Stewart's first
``Ride Down Mount Morgan,'' at the Joseph Papp Public Theater in
1998, brought him mixed reviews and a mild concussion. So why has
he decided to star again in the Arthur Miller play _ this time on
Broadway? ``There are some roles that gnaw at you,'' the Royal
Shakespeare Company veteran and ``Star Trek: The Next Generation''
captain said recently; he was taking a lunch break during
rehearsals. ``Leontes in `The Winter's Tale' is one, and Lyman Felt
in `The Ride Down Mount Morgan' is another. There's this impulse
that I must do it again, that I almost got it right, but not
quite.'' In the play, Stewart, 59, plays a bigamist who has led a
self-indulgent life; the character is in part Miller's comment on
the Reagan era. By Mervyn Rothstein. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EILEEN-HECKART-THEATER (New York) _ Eileen Heckart has been
acting for more than 50 years now, almost always as the second
banana. She was the alcoholic mother whose son is drowned in ``The
Bad Seed,'' the spinster teacher in ``Picnic'' on Broadway who gets
tipsy. ``You do one, they have no imagination,'' said Heckart about
all the drunks she has played. Sometimes she is the aunt, as in the
Mary Tyler Moore television show. She was Marilyn Monroe's waitress
friend in the movie ``Bus Stop.'' But this time, and at 81, Heckart
has the lead. Indeed, she dominates the stage at the Promenade
Theater for nearly every one of the 110 minutes of ``The Waverly
Gallery,'' Kenneth Lonergan's memory play about his grandmother's
decline, in which Heckart portrays Gladys Green, a woman who is
gradually becoming senile. By Dinitia Smith. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARK-O'CONNOR-VIOLINIST (New York) _ When the cellist Yo-Yo Ma,
the bassist Edgar Meyer and the violinist Mark O'Connor take the
stage on Wednesday at Avery Fisher Hall to play selections from
their best-selling album, ``Appalachia Waltz,'' and its new sequel,
``Appalachian Journey,'' most eyes will be on Ma. The trio's
celebrity, its meal ticket, he is a classical-music superstar,
perhaps the greatest string player of our time. But he's not as
remarkable a musician as his 38-year-old ensemble-mate on violin.
O'Connor's unfinished trajectory, from largely self-taught fiddle
player to concert-hall virtuoso and classical composer, is already
one of the most spectacular, if underpublicized, journeys in recent
American music. By Tony Scherman. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRINTS-ART (Philadelphia) _ Not until the printing press made
cheap multiple copies of a picture available _ in woodcuts,
engravings, drypoints, etchings and aquatints _ could Europe's
artists, few of whom could travel to Rome, see for themselves the
masterpieces of antiquity. Thereafter we hear regularly of prints
as the inspiration for particular images, but it is not often that
we focus on the source of the information that now flooded through
Europe. Put simply, what was it that printmakers chose to show when
they depicted the ancient world? That is the question the
exhibition ``Revivals, Reveries and Reconstructions: Images of
Antiquity in Prints From 1500 to 1800,'' on view at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art until April 16, seeks to answer. By
Theodore K. Rabb. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-DIRTY-PICTURES (Undated) _ Exactly 10 years ago this Friday,
Dennis Barrie became the first American museum director known to be
indicted for doing his job. Barrie, then 42 and director of the
Contemporary Arts Center in Cincinnati, was well aware that there
were objections to the new exhibition there: photographs by Robert
Mapplethorpe, which included depictions of sadomasochistic
homosexual acts and portraits of nude children. Business leaders
had pressured the center to cancel the show, but the opening for
museum members the evening before had gone smoothly, so Barrie was
optimistic. But Barrie and the art center were indicted on
obscenity charges (pandering and using minors in pornography).
``Dirty Pictures,'' the television film version of Barrie's story,
is scheduled to have its premiere next month on Showtime. Barrie is
played by James Woods in the first criminal trial in the United
States over the content of a museum exhibition. By Anita Gates.
(Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-VIDEO-ART (Undated) _ On March 23, 1969, the infant medium of
video art launched a guerrilla raid on broadcast television. The
attack, a show titled ``The Medium is the Medium'' and described in
the program guide as ``six avant-garde artists take over
television,'' consisted of a barrage of abstract images and visual
non sequiturs. And if most viewers were too busy singing along with
Peter, Paul and Mary on ``The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' to
notice the artistic coup d'etat, the broadcast nevertheless marked
a turning point in the history of an art form that is now firmly
entrenched in the bastions of high culture. Excerpts from the ``The
Medium is the Medium'' return to broadcast television this Sunday
at 4 p.m. when WGBH in Boston presents ``The Electronic Canvas,'' a
history of video art that highlights that city's crucial
contribution to the medium. By Miles Unger. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
