<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1586 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-GUTHRIDGE-BOS &LR;      03-29 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GUTHRIDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUTHRIDGE TOPS ON DEAN'S LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ They talk all the time. But generally it's always
on Bill Guthridge's dime.
</P>
<P>
   The Teacher and The Pupil, which sounds odd since The Pupil is
62 years old and has a coaching resume that dates back to 1962.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, when The Teacher is named Dean Smith and you
work in a building called the Smith Center, named after the man who
won more college basketball games than any other coach, you don't
mind second billing.
</P>
<P>
   This week that will change. North Carolina is in the Final Four
for a record 15th time. The Tar Heels arrived with more losses (13)
than any UNC team has ever brought to college basketball's final
ball.
</P>
<P>
   But they are also here on Bill Guthridge's dance card. Oh, there
are still players _ like senior point guard Ed Cota _ making
contributions. But for the past three seasons, Guthridge has tried
to make his own footprints in one of college basketball's most
storied programs.
</P>
<P>
   And while Smith remains sequestered nearby in retirement after
36 seasons, 879 wins, and two national championships, Guthridge has
proven that he can run the shop just fine. You think not? Consider
this: In his first two seasons, Guthridge won 58 games quicker than
any other coach in NCAA history. With 59-55 win over Tulsa Sunday,
Guthridge has won 80 in three seasons, matching the quickest
three-year start in NCAA history. In three seasons, Guthridge has
been to two Final Fours.
</P>
<P>
   Guthridge chooses to keep his talks with his mentor _ he was
Smith's assistant for 30 years _ private. ``I generally call him,''
said Guthridge, who will be guiding the Tar Heels in Saturday's
Final Four semifinal against Florida. ``I generally ask him for
advice on things that happen. He's always helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is not as reticent about his friend. When UNC won 34 games
in 1997 and reached the Final Four, Smith was the first to offer
praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill did a marvelous job, but it was not a surprise to me or
anyone who knows college basketball,'' said Smith, who has
deliberately kept a low profile during the run three years ago and
during the rough trip the Tar Heels had this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never did receive enough credit, although he didn't ask for
it, for all his years as Tex Winter's assistant and my assistant.
Bill's basketball savvy, ability to remain composed, and genuine
affection for his players are just some of the reasons for his
success as a head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthridge is not comfortable talking about himself. Sounds like
bragging, which traces back to his Kansas routes, where if a person
did his job that was all the praise he needed. But make no mistake.
He suffered through the early part of the season when the Tar Heels
were losing not only to highly-regarded teams like Michigan State,
Cincinnati, and Indiana, but also to ACC rivals Virginia and Wake
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Guthridge said his faith in his team never wavered. ``I had
confidence in this team all year. Its ability to bounce back is a
great trademark,'' he said. ``I was just disappointed I was not
able to push the right buttons to get the thing going earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tournament, the Tar Heels, who were projected as a Top 10
team, have found that formula as Guthridge has been able to ``push
the right buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty much written off,'' said sophomore forward
Jason Capel, who understands what Guthridge endured as the team
faltered. ``I'm a coach's son. I know what's that about.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Guthridge. He came out of Kansas State in the 1950s with
an appreciation for coaching as he learned under longtime Wildcats
coach Tex Winter. He came to UNC in 1967, found a niche with Smith
and thought he had found basketball heaven. ``When Dean Smith
retired (in 1997), I thought I would retire,'' said Guthridge, who
found that he wasn't quite ready to give up the game Smith retired.
``That threw a monkey wrench into the plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a teacher,'' said Guthridge, who was quickly
named as the replacement. ``Thirty years at Carolina, five years at
Kansas State. When I started out I wanted to be a head coach. I had
opportunities in the '70s. But because of the success of the
program, I finally decided I had the best job in country: an
assistant at North Carolina, working with Dean Smith and all the
great assistant coaches. At that time, I felt I could be happy as
an assistant forever.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the underlying themes that Smith harped on in talking to
Guthridge over the years was to get him to think like a head coach.
``What would you do if you were me?'' Smith used to ask Guthridge
when the inevitable crisis of a season developed.
</P>
<P>
   Guthridge used that training this season. As recently as a week
ago he was reading media reports that he was too old and out of
touch and the best thing he could do was retire. Guthridge
dismissed the criticism, the same way he has shrugged off the
praise. He says seeing his team succeed derives his pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm truly happy for this team,'' he said. ``I had a lot of
satisfaction in my life and some disappointments, too.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he celebrated a win over Tennessee last Friday
night in the South semifinal, Guthridge smiled. ``I went back to my
hotel room and kissed my wife,'' he said. ``That was my
celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens in the next several days, don't expect
much more from its coach.
</P>
<P>
   That's his way and it works for him, which is all that really
matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
