<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SWIMWEAR--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A SPLASH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DeWITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poolside parties and pinup girls.
</P>
<P>
   They were the essence of Old Hollywood glamour _ and the theme
of this year's swimsuits.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for structured suits with padded cups. These new
water babies are unstructured and skin-tight like that racy red
number Farrah Fawcett wore in her now-famous `70s poster. Or the
nude-colored low-cut style worn by Bo Derek in ``10.'' Yes, even as
a maillot, these new styles are as revealing as Jennifer Lopez's
Grammy dress.
</P>
<P>
   But the new-again bikini is the real showstopper on the beach.
The style, first seen on screen goddesses such as Ursula Andress in
``Dr. No,'' is back with a tad less fabric and a lot more glitz.
These little triangles of snakeskin and satin are beaded like
evening gowns, accented with rhinestones, and trimmed with feathers
and fringe. With a pair of stilettos and a matching pareo wrapped
at the hips, they can go from the pool to the Polo Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Love it or hate it _ swimsuit inspirations reflect the sex
appeal of European fashion designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a European trend, and if it weren't for them, we wouldn't
have the excitement we're seeing in swimwear this year,'' says Los
Angeles swimsuit designer Anne Cole.
</P>
<P>
   While the designer suits may not actually be suitable for
swimming, Cole's new collection of suits with rhinestones and
sequins and glittery gold lame straps are waterproof. ``They have
to be, or our customers will send them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she personally prefers suits with what she calls
``button-down'' sex appeal, she admits this is a ``vixen's year,''
right down to those new snakeskin print suits that she personally
dislikes. Even the winter cruise line of suits have more sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   For those more modest types without a personal trainer to carve
out curves and tone tummies, not to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Besides an abundance of pareos, sarongs and scarves to tie
around the hips or bustline, there are a number of swimsuits made
with high-tech fabrics such as Lycra Soft, a new microfiber that
works like a girdle or corset for aging baby boomers who need
support. The fabrics have the bonus of being chlorine-resistant so
they won't fall apart before the summer's over.
</P>
<P>
   Although most swimsuit designers claim the bikini is big this
year, especially the triangle and string types, the `90s fave _ the
tankini _ is still sizzling on the sand. According to Heather
Moldenhauer, spokeswoman for Jantzen swimsuits, the tank top
portion has gotten a little longer this season which makes it more
appealing to those with less-than-perfect figures.
</P>
<P>
   In the junior department, which is geared to younger, trimmer
bodies, the tankini still reigns, but triangle bikinis sold as
separates with alternate choices of bandeau tops and matching
trunks are the latest trend, says Tracy Marciano, who designs for
Electric Beach swimwear. And those trunks have options, too, from
high waists to micro styles, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   It's really a bright season for solids in turquoise, pink and
orange. But think exotic with influences of Africa, Asia and Indian
translated into crochet styles, tie-dye designs, stenciling and
embroidery in shades of olive and bronze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
