<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-WINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITES FOR WINE INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Mo.)  (pr) 
 By HOWARD G. GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wine neophytes can use the Web to learn about it and where to
buy it. Those who favor whites, for example, may be interested in
the rising popularity of German rieslings in the United States. The
Web can provide an introduction to this most versatile of white
wines.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of reviews of 1998 German rieslings at
www.winetoday.com, which is owned by New York Times Digital. At
www.winespectator.com, the magazine's library archives are a gold
mine of estate listings. A 1999 article, ``The New Golden Age of
Riesling,'' names producers whose wines are exceptional, among them
Reichsgraf von Kesselstatt in the Mosel-Saar-Ruwer region and Georg
Breuer in the Rheingau (look for the Ruedes-heimer Berg Schlossberg
bottlings).
</P>
<P>
   At the Web site of the Manhattan-based German Wine Information
Bureau, a trade office (www.germanwineusa.org), the Addresses,
Contacts and Links button leads to the Breuer and Kesselstatt home
pages. Both estates relate their wine-growing philosophies and
carry links to their American agents: Breuer's is Classical Wines
in Seattle; Kesselstatt's include Valckenberg International in
Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's site opens a side trip to www.vonschubert.com _ to
Carl von Schubert's estate Maximin Gruenhaus, in Ruwer. In good
vintages and poor it makes long-lived rieslings of such
transcendent beauty from the Abtsberg and Herrenberg vineyards that
they qualify as national treasures.
</P>
<P>
   These estates' sites have included e-mail addresses. Inquiries
are almost surely to yield information about distributors,
purchases as well as retailers and restaurants carrying the brands.
</P>
<P>
   What foods go with white, dry, semidry and sweet rieslings? The
bureau site's mix-and-match Food and Wine Pairing Guide provides
guidance.
</P>
</TEXT>
