</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRIVACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES RELEASE OF   CLINTON'S LETTERS ILLEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge Wednesday ruled that President
Clinton ``committed a criminal violation of the Privacy Act'' by
releasing the private letters of a woman who accused him of making
a sexual advance.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling brought a quick reply from Clinton, who said at a
wide-ranging press conference just a few hours later that he
``reluctantly'' authorized releasing Kathleen Willey's letters
because it was the only way he knew to rebut her charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we don't agree with the ruling,'' Clinton said. US
District Judge Royce C. Lamberth ordered White House lawyers to
answer questions about the issue in a lawsuit that has been filed
by Judicial Watch, a conservative legal group that has filed
several lawsuits against the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   A violation of the Privacy Act is a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reacted to the ruling as he fielded 22 questions ranging
from oil prices to the Elian Gonzalez case, missing White House
e-mails, Middle East peace talks, gun control, and Vice President
Al Gore's campaign finance initiative.
</P>
<P>
   He began by hailing Tuesday's announcement by OPEC members that
they will increase oil production, calling it ``good news for our
economy and for the American consumer.'' He said gasoline prices
and home heating costs should fall in the next few weeks, and he
urged oil companies ``to do everything they can to bring the
savings to consumers as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he did not expect that a bill in Congress to repeal
the 4.3-cents-a-gallon gasoline tax, which he helped push through
in 1993, would ever reach his desk, and he was not convinced that
savings from such a measure would be passed along to consumers. But
he said lawmakers should act quickly on a bill in the House to
renew his authority over the oil stockpile in the strategic
petroleum reserve, before the authority expires Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who appeared less energetic than in some of his
previous meetings with reporters, was at times wistful and
reflective, and untypically disarming when asked about White House
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   He cracked that Lamberth, a Republican judicial appointee whose
decisions involving administration officials have sometimes been
overturned, ``does seem to have somehow acquired a significant
percentage of the cases involving the White House.'' And he
chuckled when told that one of his legal advisers had described the
judge as a ``loose cannon.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Lamberth wrote that evidence in the case
``established that the president had the requisite intent for
committing a criminal violation of the Privacy Act'' when Clinton
authorized the release of the letters during the 1998 criminal
investigation that led to his impeachment and acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   The Privacy Act protects individuals from the release of certain
materials about them without their consent. The Clinton Justice
Department maintains that the act does not apply to those
components of the White House that advise or assist the president.
</P>
<P>
   Willey's letters were released by White House aides after she
alleged in a ``60 Minutes'' interview that Clinton made an unwanted
sexual advance next to the Oval Office in 1993. The letters were
meant to show that she remained friendly with Clinton after the
alleged incident.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the president said the Privacy Act never came up
in White House discussions about releasing the letters. ``I never
thought about it, never thought about whether it applied or not,
and decided to do it reluctantly, only because it was the only way
I knew to refute allegations that were made against me that were
untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   On another matter, Clinton pledged the cooperation of the White
House with judicial and congressional investigators looking into
what happened to thousands of electronic messages that disappeared
but had been sought during inquiries into 1996 campaign
fund-raising excesses, the Monica Lewinsky scandal, and other
criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't handle the e-mail things,'' Clinton said,
acknowledging his limited ability with computers. ``I'm confident
that whatever's the right thing to do, we'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   On other domestic issues, Clinton said the Miami relatives of
Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban boy entangled in an
international custody battle, should accept the decision of federal
courts, should they order the boy returned to his father in Cuba.
``If they do not prevail in court, they will clearly appeal,'' he
said. ``I would just hope that the law would be followed by
everyone, including them.''
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, Clinton said that there needs to be ``a balance
between prevention and punishment,'' and that he was unfazed by
attacks from the National Rifle Association and its leader, actor
Charlton Heston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of the president's job description _ being
attacked by people who disagree with him,'' Clinton said. ``That
doesn't matter. I still think Charlton Heston is a great actor, and
I love his movies, and I still watch them every time I get a
chance. . . . And I loved having him here at the White House not
very long ago when he got one of the Kennedy Center awards.''
</P>
<P>
   On states' taxing of Internet sales, Clinton said he supports
the current moratorium on taxes and predicted that ``over the next
year or so, you will begin to see some kind of consensus emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also praised Gore's plan to rid politics of special
interest money, specifically to create a $7.1 billion endowment to
pay for House and Senate races, and eventually the White House. ``I
kind of wish I'd thought of it myself,'' he said. He said such a
proposal would eliminate the need for candidates to spend so much
time raising money for their campaigns, and give members of the
House and Senate time to be ``home resting, you know, reading good
books, spending time with their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he ``was outraged'' and ``as appalled as the next
person'' when he discovered that the Democratic National Committee
and his reelection team had taken illegal contributions from
foreign donors in the 1996 campaign. ``We didn't need it to win. It
was wrong. And we did everything we could to try to correct it and
set it right, and we spent a lot of money doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   On foreign matters, Clinton said Syria and Israel should come up
with ideas and start talking about peace in the Middle East, an
effort he tried unsuccessfully to revive Sunday by meeting with
Syrian President Hafez Assad in Geneva. ``If we're going to have a
negotiation, I don't think it's enough to say, `I don't like your
position. Come back and see me when I like your position,' '' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also pledged to work with President Vladimir Putin of
Russia ``regardless of personal chemistry,'' which he said he hoped
would be good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
