<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TOWER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWER OF FAITH: CHURCH MEMBERS SURVIVE TORNADO'S FURY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sue Belew and Margie Young were at the top
of the five-story tower of Calvary Cathedral on Tuesday night,
keeping alive the church's five-year chain of uninterrupted prayer,
and were unaware of the tornadic force bearing down on them.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground floor, the 30 or so church members who had
gathered for Bible study, also suspected nothing until Louis Cruz,
a security guard, entered an office where Debbie Dahman, a
secretary for the church's private school, was finishing up her
work for the day.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly 6:30 p.m. CST.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tornado touched down at Montgomery Ward,'' Cruz said,
referring to the office building 10 blocks away on the west side of
the Trinity River.
</P>
<P>
   A light rain had been falling, but the early evening air had
been still, Dahman said. They were momentarily stunned, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at each other and then the lights went out,'' she
said. ``Suddenly we heard this whoooosh. It was like a locomotive
... like a train coming through the church.''
</P>
<P>
   The guard alerted the church pastor, Rev. Robert Nichols, and
his wife, Joy, and got them to a secure location in a hallway
outside the pastor's office, Dahman said. Church members also
scrambled for cover.
</P>
<P>
   The building trembled as the tornado crossed the Trinity, tore
the glass facade from the Cash America International building and
then pounded the cathedral. Belew and Young were still praying when
the brick walls of the tower disappeared, leaving them exposed to
the howling winds.
</P>
<P>
   Below, a stairway collapsed and one man was injured by falling
debris. Another, a member of the Bible study class, also suffered
minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   As the twister moved on, it hammered other nearby buildings and
apartments and uprooted trees on a wooded knoll on its path to
downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Behind it, the Cavalry Cathedral appeared to be little more than
a bombed out shell. The women in the prayer tower made it safely to
the ground and the two injured men were taken to a hospital for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Dahman said the timing of the storm was fortunate. Had it struck
two hours earlier, more than 500 children and teen-agers, students
of the private school and wards of the day-care center, would have
been in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The miracle here is that nobody was killed'' Nichols told the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Especially fortunate, he said, were the
two women in the prayer tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miracle they weren't sucked out of that building and
killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prayer tower has been continuously occupied for the past
five years as members of the non-denominational church scale the
stairway to pray in two-hour shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always at least one person up there, usually two,''
Dahman said. The prayers are for ``our church, our nation, our
elected representatives all across the nation, for our governors
and for our pastors.''
</P>
<P>
   The prayer chain was broken Tuesday night, but only temporarily,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
