<HEADER>
A1597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUS-TRAIN30-COX     03-29 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-TRAIN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Devastation of school bus-train wreck more acute day after;
thousands attend vigil for victims
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TENNGA, Ga. _ The holes in lives and hearts became apparent
Thursday in this Blue Ridge town near the scene of the worst
train-school bus wreck involving Georgians in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The second day of grieving for the six injured and two killed in
the crash started with schoolchildren raising the elementary school
flag to half-mast and ended with about 1,000 tear-stained faces
glistening in candlelight at a vigil on the courthouse lawn about
15 minutes outside town. Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes was among those
attending the vigil at the Murray County courthouse in Chattsworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest of sorrows: the memory of joy in the face
of grief,'' said Barnes. ``We can not understand why they were
taken.''
</P>
<P>
   About 30 miles away, in Chattanooga, Tenn., the chairman of the
National Transportation Safety Board was blasting the situation
that contributed to the wreck at the unprotected crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Loaded school buses should never cross a train track that isn't
protected with either crossing gates or warning lights, said NTSB
Chairman Jim Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would urge all of the local school districts in the United
States to immediately contact the railroads in these school
districts and find out where the passive (unmarked) crossings are
and (have schools) provide a plan for the safe crossing.''
</P>
<P>
   As the frenzy of the early Tuesday crash at a narrow railroad
crossing subsided, residents of this blue-collar community of about
600 people felt the full weight of their sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday I was numb. Today I woke up and realized that she
was not there,'' said Jenny Agan, 26, the aunt of Kayla Silvers, a
6-year-old who died in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Kayla was among seven students on the long yellow bus picking up
students for Northwest Elementary School. They all lived near one
another in this enclave of trailer homes and small dwellings at the
top of a hill. Nine-year-old Daniel Pack also died when the 33-car
CSX freight train collided with the bus at the unprotected
crossing. Six were injured and hospitalized, three in critical
condition. One girl, Brittany Gaddis, who stumbled from the twisted
hulk of the train to a nearby store, was released from the hospital
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   School officials braced Thursday for a hard day of sorrow and
tears _ and they got it. In Tuesday's confusion, many students
hadn't heard what had happened, or, if they had, they did not know
who was injured.
</P>
<P>
   For the students and teachers, the day after hit harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my heart is broke,'' said Zachary Mantoota, 8. He
rides that bus some days, but was driven to school Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   He said his class talked about ``how that train hit the bus. A
couple of kids were crying.''
</P>
<P>
   In private conversations with his grandmother, he shared his own
sadness. He knows two of those injured, Kevin Sherrill, 8, and
Amber Pritchett, 9, both of Tennga.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had deep sadness and love. It really tore my heart out to
hear him,'' said his grandmother, Janice Medlin.
</P>
<P>
   At Northwest Elementary, Principal C.L. Dunn tried to keep the
day as normal as possible. ``We feel the children need a sense of
routine right now to reassure them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grief counselors visited the classes of the accident victims.
Bus routes were reconfigured to avoid train crossings. Some buses
carried yellow ribbons in tribute to the students.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents kept their children off the buses, driving them to
school instead. Among them were the parents of Zachery Watson, 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was crying a lot last night,'' said his father, John
Watson, who was among those who helped at the accident scene.
</P>
<P>
   At the railroad crossing on Liberty Church Road, eight small
yellow ribbons hung on the wooden post holding the yellow sign with
the X on it to symbolize a railroad crossing. The post on the other
side of the one-track crossing, sideswiped as the train dragged and
shredded the bus, had been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Crews from the Tennessee Highway Patrol and the National
Transportation Safety Board measured and marked the site in
preparation for an accident restaging today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to mirror the conditions, to determine at what point a
driver could see the train and hear the train,'' said NTSB
spokeswoman Lauren Peduzzi.
</P>
<P>
   The train's on-board computer revealed that the warning whistle
had been blowing and that the train was traveling at about 50 mph
on impact. The speed limit at the crossing, where trains can pass
as often as every half hour, is 60 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials acknowledged that many questions remain and
that it is too early to place blame. Dana Keeton, spokeswoman for
the Tennessee Highway Patrol, rattled off a short list of some
outstanding issues: Was the bus moving or was it stopped upon the
tracks? Did the bus driver follow the law by stopping before the
tracks to check both ways? Why was the bus on the tracks when a
train was coming?
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB expects to release a preliminary report in about a
week, but a full finding could take 10 months, Peduzzi said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Keeton said the bus driver, Rhonda Cloer, whose own
daughter was among the injured students, had only one previous
violation on her driving record, a 1991 speeding ticket. The record
did not indicate whether that occurred while she was driving a bus,
Keeton said.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators turned the scene of horror and destruction into
one of analytical review, a man in jeans and cowboy boots walked
across the tracks, which have no warning lights or gates.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Duckett said he didn't need a study to see the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need some crossing lights up there bad, and those arms
that come down,'' said Duckett, who was planning to attend the
vigil.
</P>
<P>
   And the fixes shouldn't end at this crossing, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two or three down the line that need it, and another
over in Crandal where my brother lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
