<SLUG> BC-TUFTS-GIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBAY FOUNDERS PLEDGE $10 MILLION TO TUFTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pam Wesley wanted a place where she and other collectors could
trade their Pez candy dispensers. Her boyfriend _ a computer
programmer named Pierre Omidyar _ built her eBay Inc., the biggest
auction site on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now the couple, married in February 1999, plan to invest $10
million in their alma mater, Tufts University outside Boston. The
donation, which will be spread over the next five years, will help
launch the new College of Citizenship and Public Service this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The investment will also fund financial aid packages for 24
undergraduates annually, plus projects that encourage students to
become more civically involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pam and I hope this new program will educate future business
leaders, artists, and computer scientists alike to the personal
impact they can have on and off the job in addressing society's
most pressing issues,'' Pierre Omidyar, eBay's chairman, said in a
prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Omidyar, a Boston native who received a biology degree from
Tufts in 1989, played a strong role in the decision to make the
award to the school. Her mother and grandfather also attended the
university.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they're wealthy beyond their dreams, the Omidyars and
others who have gotten rich quick in the high-tech industry are
increasingly dipping into their fortunes to help schools and
charities.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Patrick J. McGovern Jr., founder of International
Data Group in Boston, said he would give an estimated $350 million
to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology over the next two
decades. The donation, which will go toward brain research, was the
largest donation ever bestowed on a university.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation promised $1
billion for a program that will help 20,000 minority students
attend college.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Omidyar, a computer science major from California,
started building eBay in 1995. Since then, the online auction site
has attracted more than 10 million registered users. Sales more
than quadruped last year to $224.7 million. And unlike many
dot-coms, eBay posted a profit, earning $10.8 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Before the San Jose, Calif., company's initial public offering
in September 1998, Omidyar stepped aside to make room for former
Hasbro executive Margaret Whitman, now eBay's chief executive. He
holds stock options in the company worth billions.
</P>
<P>
   The Omidyars split their time between Paris, where Pierre
Omidyar was born, and California. Their goal: to give away 99
percent of their fortune during their lifetimes, a spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the new Omidyar Foundation made its first large
pledge, $1 million to New Profit Inc., a Boston venture
philanthropy firm, said Lorna Lathram, executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's most recent pledge will be among the largest ever
made to Tufts, said John DiBiaggio, the school's president. Last
year, Tufts alumnus Bernard Gordon, founder of Analogic Corp.,
donated $20 million to his alma mater. Tufts has received several
$10 million gifts.
</P>
<P>
   A robust economy, driven in large part by dot-coms and other
technology firms, has been a boon to university fund-raisers. But
many schools accustomed to coddling Old World wealth over years are
discovering the new moneymakers operate at a faster pace and are
willing to give larger first-time donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things they are finding is some of these young
philanthropists don't have time to go through long cultivation
processes,'' said Eugene Tempel, executive director of the Indiana
University Center on Philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Omidyar and DiBiaggio started discussing a possible donation
less than a year ago and recently came to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a gift, that's an incredibly short time,'' DiBiaggio said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
