<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-VICTIM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO VICTIM DIED AFTER WARNING OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRISTY GONZALES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Howard Douglas Thornton .MDNM/banged on the
door of a small guard shack near the Montgomery Ward building and
told three people inside to take cover, because a tornado was
headed their way.
</P>
<P>
   He slammed the door and ran toward the warehouse, but before the
52-year-old father of five could make it to safety, he was swept
away by the storm he was warning people about, witnesses and police
reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, an Arlington resident known as ``Doug'' to his family
and friends, was a quiet, hard-working family man, said his wife of
almost 29 years, Patty Thornton. His children described him as
neat, meticulous and quirky, a collector of Nutcracker figurines
and model ships.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon at her southwest Arlington home, Patty
Thornton tried to make sense of what happened to her husband, a
shuttle driver for American Delivery Service. He made frequent
trips around the Metroplex and to Oklahoma, mostly for Montgomery
Ward. In 1994, he received a driver of the year award from the
company in recognition of his safety record.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Thornton was not surprised that her husband tried to warn
others of danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see him sitting back and watching something that
could hurt someone and not saying anything about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Thornton, 24, said her father probably considered the wooden
shack unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he figured he would be better off in the main building
than in that little rinky-dinky shack,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Godoy Jr., .MDNM/a Montgomery Ward maintenance worker who
watched the tornado rush toward the building, said perhaps Thornton
thought there was no room for him in the shed, which housed four
large desks. Godoy said he believes that Thornton saved the lives
of the supervisor, truck driver and security worker, who took
shelter under the desks inside the shack.
</P>
<P>
   As for the shack, ``It was completely gone,'' Godoy said.
Amazingly, the people inside were unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   American Delivery Service President Chip Dorger .MDNM/said
Thornton worked for the company for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a dedicated shuttle driver,'' he said. ``We're going to
miss a good employee.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the storm, Patty Thornton .MDNM/was listening to weather
reports while her husband completed his driving logs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said the storm was headed more toward Meacham Field, so I
thought it would be all right and he said he'd leave before it got
bad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the storm, the family drove to her husband's work site but
did not learn of his death until they returned home.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton grew up in Oak Cliff, a Dallas suburb, and graduated
from Sunset High School. He enjoyed fishing and working in his
yard, said his brother, Fred Thornton, 44, of Cedar Hill, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Thornton decorated his study with his children's framed
awards and more than 30 photographs of his children and
grandchildren, including a 10-year-old granddaughter who lives at
the home. Her brother and sister were killed in a car wreck about
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been around death a little too much for their ages,''
Patty Thornton said of her children. ``I have my moments when I
cry, but I know he's in a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
