<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-REUNITED-IMMIGRANTS30     03-29 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUNITED-IMMIGRANTS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One again: Seven-year separation ends for family torn by borders
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Until last month, Silvia Umana had not seen two of her
children for seven years. She left them with her mother in
Nicaragua after she decided in 1993 to come to the United States,
an arduous four-month trip that would have been impossible with a
4-year-old boy and a 6-year-old girl. Umana entered this country
illegally and got a job cleaning offices and hotels in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   She has known her children for years mainly as voices on the
phone and smiling faces in snapshots mailed from home. Now she is
one of dozens of parents from Nicaragua to be reunited with
children they last saw years ago. She and other Nicaraguans here
used a federal law to become legal residents. Now they're racing to
bring their children here and use that same law to make the kids
legal residents, too.
</P>
<P>
   They face a deadline of midnight Friday to apply for residency
under two laws designed to give legal status to illegal immigrants
from Nicaragua, Cuba and Haiti. Nationally, the laws have so far
made legal residents of 47,500 Nicaraguans, 2,500 Cubans and 26,000
Haitians, said Dan Kane, spokesman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The INS had estimated that 50,000 Nicaraguans and 10,000 Cubans
would obtain legal status through the Nicaraguan Adjustment and
Central American Relief Act of 1997. It estimated that 50,000
Haitians would become residents by taking advantage of the Haitian
Immigration Fairness Act of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Irmina Owens, director of immigration and legal services at the
Latin American Association in Atlanta, said her staff has helped
about 30 Nicaraguan children come here since January. Other
attorneys and advocacy groups have helped children, too, but the
INS said it does not have an estimate of the number of kids
reunited with parents through the law.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Owens said, she helped a man finalize paperwork for
the 10-year-old son he left in Nicaragua when the boy was 8 months
old. The boy ``wasn't so sure about the whole thing. It's a lot of
change,'' Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   Demographers say metro Atlanta is home to 400 Nicaraguans, 6,000
Cubans and 3,000 Haitians.
</P>
<P>
   Many Cubans are requesting residency through a different law
that has no deadline. Haitians are not applying in large numbers
because many have lived in the United States for years and have
become legal residents _ by marrying a U.S. citizen, for example _
by the time they come to Atlanta, said Andre Lubin, general manager
of Radio Savannah, a station serving Haitians that broadcasts in
Creole and French to 3,000 people with special receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason that fewer Haitians have applied is because the
regulations for Haitians are tighter than for Nicaraguans. A
Haitian who entered the United States on a forged passport, for
example, is ineligible even though a Nicaraguan who did that is
eligible.
</P>
<P>
   About 260,000 illegal immigrants from El Salvador, Guatemala and
some Eastern European countries qualify for benefits that could
lead to legal status, but they do not face a deadline. About 29,000
of those eligible have applied, Cane said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering extending the deadline, and several
senators have asked President Clinton to create a grace period for
those who miss Friday's cutoff. No decision has been made on either
proposal, and government officials and immigrant advocates urge
anyone who plans to apply to do so before Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Faulkner, an assistant director for the INS district
covering Georgia and three nearby states, said the INS office in
downtown Atlanta will remain open until midnight Friday to take
applications. He said he does not expect crowds because most
eligible immigrants already have filed.
</P>
<P>
   Umana, 32, left home when she was 25. She traveled for four
months by foot, train, horse and boat through Honduras, El
Salvador, Guatemala and Mexico to get to this country.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Atlanta, she called her children often and ``cried and
cried'' after hanging up.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,460 miles away, in the Nicaraguan capital, Managua, her
children also felt the pangs of separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I thought about her I cried,'' said her son, Moises, 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote to my mom,'' said Umana's daughter, Katya, 14. ``It
was hard, but I had a nice grandmother.''
</P>
<P>
   They flew to the United States and had a tearful airport reunion
with their mother last month. Now they're getting to know a
2-year-old brother, Robert, and trying to adjust to new
surroundings. Katya is learning English at a DeKalb County school _
she can already say, ``Where are you from?'' and ``I'll see you
tomorrow!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a country of great opportunity where you can
study and learn more,'' she said in Spanish, ``but the weather is
very cold here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The schools are more modern,'' Moises said. ``The buildings
are big.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
