<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-SIGHTPATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO BUYING NET FIRM SIGHTPATH FOR $800M 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The networking giant Cisco Systems Inc. is continuing its
expansion in Massachusetts by acquiring an Internet data-delivery
firm for $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   SightPath Inc., founded in 1998 by researchers at MIT, uses
software and hardware to create storehouses of Internet data nearer
to the end user. The system is designed to make it easier for
companies and individuals to use Internet services that demand lots
of bandwidth, such as video broadcasting. Cisco will incorporate
SightPath's software into its existing hardware products.
</P>
<P>
   ``SightPath had been moving up to be one of the leaders in this
space,'' said Matthew Barzowskas, vice president of First Albany
Corp. in Boston. It makes sense, he said, for Cisco to acquire the
company to fill out its product line.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is the world's leading producer of networking hardware for
use in the Internet and in corporate networks. Nearly every piece
of data on the Internet passes through Cisco equipment during some
part of its journey.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Cisco passed Microsoft Corp. to become the world's
most valuable publicly traded company, with a market capitalization
of about $527.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is further proof that content distribution networks are
going to be a big area,'' said Jim Ricotta, president and CEO of
SightPath, which is based in Waltham, Mass. He and the 76 employees
of SightPath will continue to develop the technology as a business
unit within Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco has been on an expansion binge. ``They like to say this is
a way to get continual injections of start-up DNA into the
company,'' Ricotta said.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the SightPath deal, Cisco had spent $3 billion to
acquire eight New England firms since 1994. The San Jose, Calif.,
company also plans to build a New England development center that
could employ up to 5,000 workers within five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
