<HEADER>
A1612 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AL-AMIN30-COX     03-29 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Al-Amin's car found in Alabama
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ The black Mercedes-Benz police say sped away
from a shootout that left one Fulton County, Ga., deputy fatally
shot and another wounded, was found Wednesday afternoon in the same
Alabama town where accused killer Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin was
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got it,'' Lowndes County Sheriff Willie Vaughner said a
couple of hours after the vehicle was located in White Hall. ``It's
got a lot of bullet holes, probably from the shooting, but it's
being impounded and it will be tested in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents found the car around midafternoon, Vaughner said, but
he would not elaborate on the circumstances that led authorities to
the vehicle. The car, equipped with a sun roof, was discovered on
County Road 17, near the only school in the rural town 25 miles
west of Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle was towed in the middle of a blinding rainstorm on
Ala. 80 from White Hall on a flat-bed truck just before 5 p.m. CST.
About 25 minutes later, the tow truck, owned by Waldrip Wrecking of
Montgomery, delivered the Mercedes to the parking lot of the
Montgomery Police Department's crime scene bureau. At least one
bullet hole was evident on the passenger side door.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Howard Kenney, commander of the bureau, would not comment on
the vehicle, saying only, ``We are assisting the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI wasn't saying much about the car either, and it was
unclear whether the vehicle would be processed for evidence in
Montgomery or Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokeswoman Celeste Armstead confirmed that the
Mercedes-Benz was the car authorities have been looking for since
March 16, when deputies Ricky Kinchen and Aldranon English were
shot. ``We believe it is the car that Al-Amin reportedly fled in,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen, 35, was critically wounded and died the next day.
English, 28, was seriously injured. English later identified
Al-Amin, a former black militant known as H. Rap Brown, as the
shooter.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy told Atlanta police he and Kinchen spotted Al-Amin
standing by a black Mercedes-Benz outside his grocery store in
Atlanta that night as they attempted to serve him with a Cobb
County, Ga., arrest warrant. The warrant originated from Al-Amin's
failure to appear in court on several charges, including theft by
receiving a stolen car.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Al-Amin opened fire on the deputies when they
approached him just after 10 p.m. and asked him to show his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Sheriff Jackie Barrett said her officers fired at
Al-Amin at least 10 times with department-issued .40-caliber guns.
Ballistics tests should show whether the bullet holes in the
Mercedes came from shots the deputies fired.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Alabama authorities found the Georgia license
plate belonging to the Mercedes-Benz behind a restaurant on Freedom
Road in White Hall, Vaughner said. The small cafe was once operated
by Al-Amin, but has been closed for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta and Alabama authorities are still trying to find out
whether someone helped Al-Amin get from Atlanta to White Hall after
the deputies were shot. They are also trying to determine who in
White Hall might have harbored Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mercedes-Benz was being unloaded at the Montgomery Police
Department, Montgomery County Sheriff D.T. Marshall announced that
extradition papers for Al-Amin had arrived from Gov. Roy Barnes'
office.
</P>
<P>
   Selma lawyer J.L. Chestnut, who is representing Al-Amin, filed a
motion Wednesday in Montgomery County Court requesting a court
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The extradition process could take two weeks to two months,
Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said he would serve Al-Amin the warrant in his jail
cell either Wednesday night or this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to get Mr. Al-Amin back to Georgia where he
belongs,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
