<HEADER>
A1613 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-WONDERLAND-SPI &LR;      03-29 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WONDERLAND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIES ON MENTALLY ILL EXHAUSTING, WONDERFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: A-  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday's ``ER'' is a repeat. So why not check into
``Wonderland'' on ABC? It's new. It's interesting. It's possible
you'll never check out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' is from Peter Berg, who for three seasons played
the slightly bizarre, hockey-playing Dr. Kronk on ``Chicago Hope.''
With backing from Ron Howard, Brian Grazer and Tony Krantz at
Imagine Television, Berg created a drama that'll either scare the
ohmigosh out of people (and cause them to swear off ``Wonderland''
forever), or hook 'em good.
</P>
<P>
   The prize in this case is complete intellectual engagement. But
be warned: The cost may be emotional exhaustion because
``Wonderland'' is about mental illness. Not the kind where the docs
on ``ER'' request a psychiatric consult and the patient is never
seen again, or the kind where a guy kills in a psychotic rage on
``NYPD Blue'' and is locked up forever. It's about prolonged
exposure to the behavior ``normal'' people consider ``abnormal.''
Week in and week out. For as long as ABC is willing to go at it in
TV's toughest time slot.
</P>
<P>
   Pitted as it is against ``ER,'' ``Wonderland'' probably has as
much chance of ratings success as I have of winning the lottery.
(And I don't buy lottery tickets.) So, either ABC has placed the
series in its lambs-to-the-slaughter file, or it genuinely is not
worried about ratings because the show is so good it deserves to be
on the air as an example of ABC's well-known commitment to quality
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ABC hopes the enormous audience for ``Who Wants To Be
a Millionaire'' at 9 will stay put at 10 and give ``Wonderland'' a
huge opening night. With NBC airing an old ``ER'' at 10, it's
possible: ``ER'' reruns don't score well. And last week, an ABC
News program, ``The John Stossel Special: You Can't Say That!'' did
manage to crack the Nielsen Top 20 going up against ``ER.'' But
where the Thursday ``Millionaire'' delivered an audience of 17.4
million homes last week, according to Nielsen Media Research,
``Stossel'' was seen in only 9.6 million homes (compared to 18.4
million for a new episode of ``ER.'')
</P>
<P>
   This kind of audience slippage drives network executives crazy.
No doubt they'd be welcome in the psychiatric ward of Rivervue
Hospital, where the walls are soft, the doors are locked and sharp
implements are taken away.
</P>
<P>
   Patterned after New York's storied Bellevue Hospital, Rivervue
is where ``Wonderland'' takes place. It's a noisy, clattering
public facility where gifted-but-harried doctors handle unrealistic
caseloads, where the patients scream and twitch and lash out and
hallucinate and generally do things that ``stable'' people find
unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   Berg obviously finds it fascinating, but after watching two
episodes back to back, I was dishrag city. Do I want to tune in
again? Right now, yes. Can I commit to such emotional mayhem every
week? I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliance of ``Wonderland'' is in writing that allows the
actors to improvise, and acting that allows viewers to empathize.
The effect is a heightened realism that never loosens its grip.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable Ted Levine leads a fine ensemble cast that also
includes Michelle Forbes, who was always my favorite player on
``Homicide: Life on the Street.'' Levine is Dr. Robert Banger, the
brooding but likable head of the forensic psychiatry department,
which deals in the criminal side of things. Forbes is Dr. Lyla
Garrity, director of the Comprehensive Psychiatric Emergency
Program, a critical-response facility for people suffering
psychiatric emergencies. She's married to Dr. Neil Harrison (Martin
Donovan), another forensic specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured that not everything on ``Wonderland'' is ``Cuckoo's
Nest'' revisited. The doctors have private lives, too. Banger's
marriage is failing and he's fighting to retain custody of the
kids. Garrity and Harrison are expecting, but the health of the
child may be compromised. Other staffers have the usual endearing
traits and peccadilloes.
</P>
<P>
   As with most shows that challenge their viewers, ``Wonderland''
is like crunchy peanut butter. It's richly textured and will stick
to the roof of your mind long after the credits roll. But its aim
is clear and noble: to publicly pay attention, in a sympathetic,
compassionate way, to one of society's most marginalized groups.
</P>
<P>
   Berg slams it home in episode two, in a scene that pits Banger
against a defense lawyer, even though both want to help a patient
who shot and killed five people in Times Square. Banger wants to
medicate the man to control his manic episodes; the lawyer wants to
keep the man off medication to enhance his plea of insanity. As
they argue strategy in front of the patient and his family, the
man's distraught father shouts: ``He's my son! My son who got into
Columbia and loves Chinese food and rock climbing in the Catskills.
My son, whose dream was to build a boat and follow the journey of
`The Odyssey.' He's my son! He has a name! You call him by his
name!''
</P>
<P>
   It's a reasonable request. The bigger question is: How many
times are we willing to hear it?
</P>
<P>
   Wonderland. One-hour drama series about the doctors who handle
the psychiatric cases at a New York City hospital. Starring Ted
Levine, Michelle Forbes, Martin Donovan, Billy Burke, Michael Jai
White and Joelle Carter. Series premiere Thursday night on ABC.
Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
