<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-LEBANON-ARMY-ART-2TAK     03-29 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ARMY-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S SOUTH LEBANON ALLIES ARE WORRIED BY WITHDRAWAL PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADASIYE, Lebanon _ When Lt. Col. Robin Abboud looks down from
his home high in the rugged hills of southern Lebanon, the view is
of Israel. Less than 500 yards away lies the border fence topped
with electrified barbed wire, and beyond it a military road flanked
by minefields that snakes steeply uphill to an Israeli army post
bristling with radars and lookout towers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israel that the 42-year-old Lebanese colonel sees most
plainly is the Israel that lies beyond the bands of steel _ the
Israel represented, a few miles down a lush valley visible from his
veranda, by the town of Qiryat Shemona.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of neat green fields, gleaming apartment blocks and
tidy industrial zones, the town looks like a poster for all that
Israel has carved out of these stony biblical lands during the last
half-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compare the history of Israel and the Arabs, of Judaism and
Islam, if you will,'' Abboud said over Arab pastries and thimble
cups of thick Turkish coffee in his living room. ``The Arab past
has been a history of deception, of rivalry and dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``But look at the Jews _ how they decided, after the Holocaust,
to establish Israel, to commit themselves to each other and to
create the only real democracy in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   In his view, the vision makes for a stark contrast with Lebanon,
where progress has been confounded by years of religious and ethnic
enmity and a civil war that lasted from 1975 to 1990. Lately,
though, Abboud's view has been tinged with melancholy and even
fear.
</P>
<P>
   For Abboud, the colonel, an Arab and a Shiite Muslim, is also _
in the eyes of a Lebanese military court _ a traitor, sentenced in
absentia to life imprisonment at hard labor for having served more
than two decades in a militia force allied to Israel in its
military presence in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Now Israel is preparing to leave, and as a member of the South
Lebanon Army, or SLA _ , a 3,000-member militia of Lebanese
Muslims, Christians and Druse _ Abboud is more than ever a marked
man.
</P>
<P>
   The critical moment came this month when the Israeli cabinet
endorsed a campaign pledge made last year by Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to withdraw the 1,500-soldier Israeli contingent back into
Israel by July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, from the SLA militia's viewpoint, the Israeli
cabinet decided to complete the pullout with or without an
agreement with Lebanon and Syria. The Syrians effectively control
most of Lebanon through the 35,000 troops they maintain beyond the
military buffer zone that Israel controls within nine miles of its
border.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The territory Israel is vacating has become a curious hybrid, a
place where the resentments that its presence engenders have been
offset by advantages: superior roads and other public services,
like water and power, stores richly stocked with foreign goods
imported duty free through Israel, and _ at least for SLA officers
and their families _ prosperity unrivaled elsewhere in rural
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also an elusive sense of lifelessness and a lack of
authenticity, as if this were no more than a stage set, to be
dismantled when the players move on.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the villages are half-deserted, abandoned by residents
who long since migrated north to other parts of Lebanon or abroad.
In shops and cafes, people not working for the Israelis or their
Lebanese allies shy away when approached by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The hills and valleys held by the Israelis, flanked by the
Mediterranean to the west and the snowy peaks of Mount Hermon to
the east, have been marked by the ebb and flow of conquest for
thousands of years. The Phoenicians, the Greeks, the Romans, the
Ottoman Turks, the British and the French all left their traces
before being driven out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 22 years, the retreating power is Israel, and the
repercussions for the South Lebanon Army are profound.
</P>
<P>
   Without an agreement among Israel, Syria and Lebanon setting
terms for the withdrawal, the men of the militia force, and
possibly even the 5,000 other residents of the buffer zone who work
in Israel _ in total, counting families, about a quarter of the
120,000 residents of the zone _ appear to be prime targets for
reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   For ordinary members of the militia, many little more than
conscripts, Lebanese officials have said the punishment will be
prison terms _ probably of a year, possibly two or three _ but the
outlook for the force's 350 officers is grimmer.
</P>
<P>
   A small flicker of hope remains in the possibility of a peace
agreement between Israel and Syria before the July withdrawal date,
which would enable Israel to negotiate the terms for withdrawal
with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Israeli-Syrian peace talks deadlocked, President
Emile Lahoud of Lebanon has ruled out talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, SLA officers say that with the Israeli deadline
near at hand, too little time may be left for negotiations.
Anxieties have been heightened by warnings from the leaders of
Hezbollah, or the Party of God, the Shiite Muslim militant group
backed by Iran and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, the Muslim cleric who leads Hezbollah,
has described the South Lebanon Army's soldiers as ``criminal
collaborators who must be tried for treason,'' and has warned
Western countries inclined to offer the militiamen refuge that
they, too, should expect to ``treated as enemies'' by Hezbollah.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In addition, pledges of lenient treatment for defectors that
Hezbollah held out several years ago have been withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Despite persistent speculation in Israel that militia members
may have tried to curry favor with Hezbollah by tipping its
guerrillas about Israeli military movements _ thus resulting in a
wave of casualties suffered by Israeli forces earlier this year _
Hezbollah leaders say it is ``too late now'' for the militiamen to
switch sides in hope of being spared.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 30 a Hezbollah bomb assassinated the SLA's top field
commander, Col. Akl Hashem, as he walked his dog in his native
village near here. For Hezbollah the attack was second only to its
most startling operational success, the roadside bomb in February
1999 that killed Brig. Gen. Erez Gerstein, the 36-year-old Israeli
officer who was the main liaison to the militia. He was the
highest-ranking Israeli soldier to die since Israel declared the
border area its ``security zone'' in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Hezbollah has shown its ability to infiltrate
deep into the occupied zone and pick off militia members at will.
</P>
<P>
   It announced in early March that it had carried out a ``death
sentence'' against a corporal in the militia's security branch. The
man, a Shiite Muslim, was saying goodbye to his wife and children
after breakfast at his home in the village of Markabe, two miles
south of Colonel Abboud's home in Adasiye, when a Hezbollah hit man
shot him in the head with a silenced pistol.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has prompted scores of defections from the militia
and prompted discussions within the Israeli high command about an
accelerated withdrawal if the Lebanese force begins to
disintegrate. The militia maintains many of the 90 hillside forts
that are the backbone of the Israeli zone, and undertake risky road
patrols and door-to-door searches. Its scouts are stationed in
every Israeli post.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Israel seems to have decided there is no future
for the militia inside Lebanon, but it is against providing refuge
in Israel. Israel's deputy defense minister, Ephraim Sneh, said
that ``bringing the members of the South Lebanon Army and their
families to Israel and transforming them into refugees is not a
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, according to a report in Yediot Ahronot, an Israeli
newspaper, Israel has identified 200 senior officers who with their
families will be accepted as refugees elsewhere, most likely in the
United States, Canada, France and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is also said to be preparing an indemnity fund. Israeli
newspapers have suggested that it will involve an average severance
payout of $30,000, with a maximum, for senior officers, of $175,000
_ sums apparently to be funded from the $74 million that Barak has
set as the cost of a unilateral withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats have said Israel has been told that there is no
possibility that the sum will be met by increased American
subsidies to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is much solace to men like onel Abboud. Like all
SLA men, the colonel wears an olive green Israeli army uniform,
with the Hebrew acronym for ``Israeli Defense Forces'' above his
left breastpocket.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Israeli military colleges with distinction.
And last year his 15-year-old daughter, Zeinab, was saved by
Israeli doctors who performed a double heart valve replacement
operation at Schneider Children's Medical Center in Petah Tikva
outside Tel Aviv, with Israel absorbing the $80,000 cost.
</P>
<P>
   The colonel can barely disguise his sense of abandonment.
</P>
<P>
   Of his Israeli military counterparts, Abboud had only praise,
saying, ``We have shed blood together, and that is the strongest of
all bonds.'' But for Israeli politicians, the colonel had a barely
disguised contempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truth means nothing in politics,'' he said. ``You have only to
compare what Benjamin Netanyahu was saying only two years ago with
what Barak is saying now to see that. In politics, there is no
principle, only self-interest, whether it be individuals or
nations.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Shi'ite Muslim, Abboud has particular reason for concern.
For the moment, he is rejecting emigration with his wife and eight
children, perhaps to Canada, where he has a sister, but staying in
Lebanon is clearly not an option.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, at the house of another SLA officer, a visit
to the washroom led past a kitchen where fitted appliances had been
pulled from the walls. In the next room, a mass of personal
belongings, including furniture and exercise equipment, had been
stacked, apparently for packing.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the prospect of being driven from their homeland,
possibly for ever, the SLA officers, many of whom were low-ranking
corporals and sergeants in the Lebanese army before the Israeli
occupation, stand to lose luxuries accumulated over the years of
Israeli occupation _late-model BMWs and Mercedes-Benz, sumptuous
homes with pink granite facings, marbled floors and copies of
18th-century French court furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Other residents of the occupation zone said that Israeli
military commanders had turned a blind eye for years to corruption
and criminality among high-ranking SLA men. These practises are
said to have included drug-trafficking, protection rackets,
skimming of tax revenues, and vehicle-theft rings.
</P>
<P>
   But if the good life they have led suggests that SLA officers
made a Faustian deal in siding with Israel, the reality seems more
complex. As these men tell the militia's story, it grew from a
desire among people in southern Lebanon to protect themselves
against armed Palestinians who, in the 1970s, became a law unto
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When Israel invaded in 1978 to halt Palestinian attacks across
the border, many Lebanese flocked to throw flowers on Israeli tanks
_ while others, now SLA veterans, say they took up arms alongside
the invaders as the only force that seemed capable of bringing
order.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after the Palestinians were routed, matters became more
complicated still. Since the mid-1980s, Hezbollah has cast itself
in the role of a ``national resistance force.'' Then, in the 1990s,
Lebanese nationalism was rekindled from the rubble of the civil
war, when the country disintegrated into a mosaic of armed
fiefdoms.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the SLA was isolated. Abboud, looking back,
tells the story in a wistful tone. ``Things just developed,'' he
said, ``in ways none of us could have foreseen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
