<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WILLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS CLINTON'S RELEASE OF LETTERS VIOLATED WILLEY'S PRIVACY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton released personal letters
from a woman who had accused him of making a sexual advance, he
illegally violated her privacy, a federal judge said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Royce C. Lamberth found that Clinton had
committed ``a criminal violation of the Privacy Act'' in releasing
letters from Kathleen Willey in March 1998, after she accused him
in an appearance on the CBS News program ``60 Minutes'' of making
an advance.
</P>
<P>
   A violation of the Privacy Act is a misdemeanor, and punishable
by up to 1 year in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton brushed off the judge's finding at a news conference
Wednesday. He and his counsel, Beth Nolan, said they would appeal
the judge's rulings, including one that White House lawyers submit
to questions from Judicial Watch, a conservative group that has
been a persistent critic of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch has sued the White House several times. The case
addressed by Lamberth Wednesday was a suit concerning the improper
transfer to the White House of hundreds of FBI files on former
appointees and employees of the Reagan and Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has contended that the transfer of
files, while wrong, was done in error rather than with malice.
Judicial Watch contends otherwise and is seeking $90 million on
behalf of people whose files were sent to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the discovery process, Judicial Watch questioned the
release of the Willey letters, even though Willey is not a party to
the suit. White House aides refused to answer some of those
questions, leading to Wednesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth ordered White House lawyers to submit to questioning by
Judicial Watch within 20 days. The White House has balked at some
Judicial Watch questions before, especially ones pertaining to the
release of the Willey letters.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Clinton did not seem fazed by the order.
When a questioner noted that a White House lawyer had called
Lamberth ``a loose cannon,'' Clinton looked amused and replied,
``Well, he does seem to have somehow acquired a significant
percentage of the cases involving the White House.'' The judge was
appointed by President Ronald Reagan in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that, before releasing Willey's letters, he had not
talked to anyone about the Privacy Act, which usually prohibits
release of information about a person from federal records without
that person's consent.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he had released Willey's letters
``reluctantly, only because it was the only way I knew to refute
allegations that were made against me that were untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Willey, a former White House volunteer, said Clinton made an
improper advance in the fall of 1993. Her account added to the
burdens of a president then being investigated for his relationship
with Monica Lewinsky and coping with a sexual-misconduct lawsuit
filed by Paula Corbin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton released letters Willey had written him after the fall
of 1993, hoping that their friendly tone would deflate the
accusation that he had behaved improperly.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Lamberth said that when Clinton and his aides
released the letters, they surely knew of his 1997 finding that the
White House was bound by the Privacy Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court cannot accept or condone this unlawful action,''
the judge wrote. He said there might have been no violation had the
letters been ``strictly personal'' and kept by the president
himself, instead of in White House records.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what, if anything, the independent
counsel Robert Ray would do about Lamberth's finding that the
president had acted illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan disagreed with Lamberth's ruling, saying that in 1975
Antonin Scalia _ then an assistant attorney general and now a
Supreme Court justice _ had advised officials that much of the
White House operation was not subject to the Privacy Act, and that
Republicans and Democrats had agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly disagree with Judge Lamberth's opinion and are
confident it will be overturned,'' Nolan said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was also asked Wednesday about reports the White House
had a previously undisclosed computer disk with e-mail messages
from Lewinsky to two witnesses appearing before the grand jury that
investigated their affair. Asked why the disk was not turned over
sooner, Clinton said he believed that the material on the disk
``was known years ago,'' and that Nolan would clarify the issue
when she testifies on Capitol Hill on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of White House e-mail correspondences from 1996 to
1998, sought by a grand jury and congressional committees, was
electronically misplaced and never turned over to investigators.
The Justice Department is investigating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
