A1620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN30-COX     03-29 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Education may need new menu
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Education _ the issue polls big time this year, and
the candidates have enough differences to fight over. But with
little precedent for how to make it the centerpiece issue of a
presidential campaign, both Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George
W. Bush have fallen into the martial rhetoric of our previous
``wars'' on various social ills.
</P>
<P>
   Gore kicked off his campaign with a promise to bring ``radical
change'' to the nation's schools from the White House. Bush,
rolling out his proposal this week to spend $5 billion to ensure
that every child can read by the third grade, called education a
``national emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   To many a frustrated parent, the need for radical change in a
student's math scores does rate as an emergency of pretty serious
proportions. But the proposals attached to this big-program
rhetoric amount to larger versions of the education initiatives
that have already become the staple of so many State of the State
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Very real problems exist in education, but in most states the
alarm bell has already been rung more than once.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been as widely recognized as such, but another factor
tends to dampen the din of both candidates' education rhetoric: the
spectacular success of so many of the recently educated.
</P>
<P>
   Not every engineering school dropout is doing as well as
Christopher Klaus, the 26-year-old entrepreneur who announced a $15
million gift to Georgia Tech on Tuesday, the same day Bush gave his
education speech.
</P>
<P>
   But enough young Americans have had early success in the new
economy to provide much of the philanthropical muscle needed to
tackle the problems of public schools. They also raise some
interesting questions about the priorities put forth in the crisis
rhetoric over education.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly literacy, in some broad sense, is fundamental to any
national education policy. But does it matter more, in terms of
their educational and professional trajectory, that fourth-grade
students be able to read the word ``mosquito'' (and maybe spell
``potato''), or that they know their way around the Windows menu
bar?
</P>
<P>
   Both abilities involve literacy in different forms, one worth
preserving and the other steadily evolving. But the spelling
abilities demonstrated on the Web sites of some promising startups
make a powerful argument for the relevance of the menu bar.
</P>
<P>
   There may yet be a debate about what literacy really means, but
the exchanges between the two camps this week had some of the worst
characteristics of a bitter battle for a PTA presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign distributed copies of newspaper stories about
an unreleased Education Department report suggesting that the
improved test scores in Bush's Texas aren't reliable. Bush's
campaign quickly condemned the report as a taxpayer-funded piece of
political research. Much more of this, and the nation will
collectively long for a summer break from school.
</P>
<P>
   (In case you're curious, a check with Klaus' firm, ISS, revealed
that the Tech donor attended Roman Catholic parochial schools
through junior high, then went to a public high school in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
