<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TACKLE PRAYER ISSUE AT HIGH SCHOOL FOOTBALL GAMES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court grappled Wednesday with prayer at
Texas high school football games, grilling attorneys with questions
such as whether student attendance at the games in Santa Fe is a
choice or a requirement.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, appearing as divided as the Texas lawyers arguing
before them, asked these and other questions in considering whether
students can continue to deliver prayers before kickoff without
violating the Constitution's separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn sought to defend the Santa Fe
Independent School District's policy of permitting a student,
chosen by peers, to deliver a personal statement before game time.
But attorney Anthony Griffin made comic reference to the exalted
role of football in Texas as he argued that student pre-game
speeches invariably invoke religion, a subject that public schools
generally may not broach under the constitutional mandate that
states not endorse any particular religion.
</P>
<P>
   During the hourlong argument before a packed courtroom, Justice
David H. Souter expressed doubt that the school board is neutral on
religion, saying the policy smacks of sectarian endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Antonin
Scalia said a brief student message before such a minor social
gathering as a football game probably doesn't raise constitutional
concerns. After all, students are not compelled to attend pregame
ceremonies, enabling them to avoid listening to another student's
prayer, they said.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, Griffin responded. Missing football-related
events is frowned upon in gridiron-mad Texas, where most students
are either in the band, on the team or cheering on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is anyone forced to be a band member, cheerleader or football
player?'' asked Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a teen-ager, yes,'' responded Griffin, prompting
laughter throughout the packed courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision in the case,
Santa Fe Independent School District vs. Doe, by July.
</P>
<P>
   The case marks the high court's first major foray since 1992
into the First Amendment issue of governmental endorsement of
religion at public schools. The justices, in several decisions
since 1962, have ruled that the Constitution generally prohibits
school-district involvement in religious activities, saying that
such participation alienates students of minority faiths.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision in Santa Fe, located about 35 miles
southeast of Houston, can help define whether that general
prohibition extends to school playing fields.
</P>
<P>
   Under Santa Fe's policy, the student body each spring elects a
student to deliver a ``statement or invocation'' before football
games. The selected student can draft his or her own message ``to
solemnize the event, to promote good sportsmanship and student
safety and to establish the appropriate environment for the
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy has been suspended pending the Supreme Court's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents and students in the school district sued in 1995 to
stop the pregame practice as unconstitutional. Fearing opposition
from the overwhelming majority of parents who endorsed the policy,
the families sought and received a court order that their names not
be used in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, citing the high court's
line of religion cases, ruled in February 1999 that Santa Fe, by
permitting students to recite prayers before football games,
endorsed faith in violation of the Constitution. The First
Amendment prevents public schools from compelling students to
listen to expressions of religions they do not accept, the 5th
Circuit ruled, prompting the school district to appeal to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, and the school district's lawyer, Jay Sekulow, argued
that the policy is constitutional because it neither endorses nor
rejects religion. Rather, it allows students to decide for
themselves how best to rally their football team before kickoff,
they added.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said the school board plays virtually no role in
selecting which student will give the message or what the student
will say, thereby eliminating any connection between the government
and any potential student prayer. State and local officials have
``no way to predict'' what a student will say, Cornyn added.
</P>
<P>
   But Souter and Justice John Paul Stevens appeared unconvinced
that the school board is not involved and does not oversee what the
students say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to get a speech at the football
games saying `religion is bunk,''' Souter said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens asked Cornyn whether school administrators would
tolerate a student who used foul language or delivered a deeply
religious statement.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn responded that school leaders could bar the student from
using obscenities as part of their responsibility to regulate the
manner of the message. But school leaders cannot edit the content
of a student's statement, even if it is religious in nature, he
argued.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said school districts are in a Catch-22 due to the First
Amendment's competing demands of allowing students to speak freely
while prohibiting them from mentioning religion. ``How do we avoid
getting sued?'' Cornyn asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sekulow added that the school's policy is ``neutral'' on the
subject of religion, leaving students free to include a prayer in
their pre-game message if they choose. He said the main purpose is
to ``solemnize'' the event, an argument that drew scorn from
Souter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is solemnization?'' the justice asked, noting that the
word has religious overtones.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy also expressed concern that the
policy endorses religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about schools becoming forums for religious
debates,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Sekulow responded that the policy prevents schools from getting
involved in religion by taking a ``hands-off approach'' and letting
students say what they want.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin challenged the district, saying that although its policy
does not mention religion, the practice has always been that
student speakers delivered prayers.
</P>
<P>
   School districts, as the educators of children, have a
constitutional responsibility to be secular and leave religious
teaching to parents and churches, said Griffin, who is representing
the parents and students challenging the policy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe High School senior Marian Ward, who offered a brief
prayer before the football team's opening game Sept. 3, attended
the court hearing and voiced support for the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country was founded on the principles of freedom of
religion and freedom of speech, and I believe in the separation of
church and state,'' Ward said after the arguments. ``But I don't
believe in restricting personal expressions in public. I would just
like to see some clarification from the justices.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
