A1624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-FOUNDATION-GIFTS30     03-29 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-FOUNDATION-GIFTS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. foundations' giving nearly tripled in decade
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A vibrant economy is driving the nation's
foundations to give away more money than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, foundations gave $22.8 billion in grants to nonprofit
groups.
</P>
<P>
   That record figure is up from $7.9 billion a decade ago,
according to a new report conducted by the Foundation Center, a New
York-based organization that monitors foundations.
</P>
<P>
   And Georgia has been a major player in the surge of
philanthropic giving.
</P>
<P>
   The number of foundations in the state has jumped to 906, up 64
percent since 1989. By comparison, the number of foundations across
the country increased by 47 percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Georgia's foundations gave $495 million in 1998, up
312 percent from 1989. At the same time, assets increased to $11.3
billion, a 335 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an extraordinary growth in philanthropic capital,''
said Charles McTier, president of the Atlanta-based Robert W.
Woodruff Foundation Inc., and chairman of the Foundation Center's
board. ``It is attributable to our nation's healthy economy and the
success of American business.''
</P>
<P>
   Foundations are forced by law to give away at least 5 percent of
the value of their investments in the previous year. This means
that foundations are increasing the size of their donations by the
millions and making an impact in areas such as the environment,
health and education.
</P>
<P>
   Giving by every type of foundation _ corporate, individual and
community _ is on the rise, according to the Foundation Center's
report.
</P>
<P>
   And large companies have increased the size of their gifts,
which has helped boost foundation endowments.
</P>
<P>
   Endowment values rose to $385.1 billion in 1998, up 16.7
percent. In part, this was due to record-size gifts from Bill Gates
to the Bill &AMP; Melinda Gates Foundation. The Gates Foundation's
assets jumped ninefold to $5.4 billion as a result of gifts of $4.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, corporate foundation assets grew 20.4 percent to $13.11
billion. Most of the increase resulted from higher stock values,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``1999 was a watershed for corporate foundations,'' said Sara
Engelhardt, president of the Foundation Center. ``This is good news
for communities that rely on companies as a key source of private
giving.''
</P>
<P>
   The increase in assets means more money for projects that
government agencies and corporations reject, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foundations don't have to play by the same rules,'' Engelhardt
said. ``Very often, when someone comes in with a completely
outside-the-box idea, they can't get funding.''
</P>
<P>
   The surge in giving could change that. The nation's largest
foundations may be able to achieve goals in communities that
weren't possible before, Engelhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Rand Wentworth, director of the Georgia office of the Trust for
Public Land, understands that from experience.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Wentworth met with McTier at the Woodruff
Foundation to generally discuss conservation needs.
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth mentioned that the Trust for Public Land was
interested in preserving land along the Chattahoochee River to
address water quality and to create more green space.
</P>
<P>
   McTier told Wentworth to research what was possible. ``He said
to think big,'' Wentworth said.
</P>
<P>
   With that challenge, Wentworth worked with the Georgia
Department of Natural Resources, the Nature Conservancy of Georgia
and other environmental groups. They came up with a plan to buy
property along the river stretching 200 miles from the mountains in
northern Georgia to downtown Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   When they presented their plan, McTier didn't blink. The
Woodruff Foundation offered a commitment of $25 million over three
years with the challenge of finding matching grants from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodruff grant gave Wentworth and other environmental groups
the leverage they needed to convince Congress to ante up.
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth's group was able to raise an additional $25 million in
federal funds with help from the Georgia congressional delegation.
The state in two budget cycles came up with $35 million. Local
governments along the river gave another $25 million to the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Woodruff Foundation's leadership allowed us to dream big
and it opened a door of credibility with Congress,'' Wentworth
said. ``They are birthing a great new regional park on a massive
scale.''
</P>
<P>
   The Woodruff Foundation is the biggest foundation in Atlanta,
with $3.7 billion in assets. In 1998, the foundation gave $86.6
million in grants, mostly to Georgia-based organizations.
</P>
<P>
   After the Woodruff Foundation, the state's largest foundations
are: The UPS Foundation; the Bradley-Turner Foundation; the Joseph
B. Whitehead Foundation; the J. Bulow Campbell Foundation; the
Community Foundation for Greater Atlanta; the Turner Foundation,
Inc.; the Murray M. Rosenberg Foundation, Inc.; the Coca-Cola
Foundation, Inc.; and the Lettie Pate Evans Foundation, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
