<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEETING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL SPENT TIME ON MONEY MATTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. This was a shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meetings weren't about football,'' said one of the NFL's
best coaches. ``The meetings were about money. Money won. Football
was zero. All of the time was spent on money.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL annual meetings closed Wednesday and very little was
done to change the game on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Said one owner of an AFC team, ``We've been going at this since
Sunday and all the talk is about the Internet. How can we maximize
the Internet? We didn't come up with any answers, but they are
going to study that hard and see how we can use it best in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners agreed in a resolution to have all 32 members of the
league participate in one NFL Internet system.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the owners voted instant replay back for another
season by a margin of 28-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were happy with the system that was in place last year,''
said Vikings coach Dennis Green, who is a member of the Competition
Committee, which is responsible for changing the rules. ``The
feeling is to give it another year, and if it works well again,
then voting next year to have this system for the future. I don't
think we should vote on this one year at a time. If it's good,
let's keep it in the books, and I think most people feel (that
way).''
</P>
<P>
   There were just a handful of changes and most of them were
minor.
</P>
<P>
   Players can be fined for excessive on-field celebrations and any
sexual gestures. If more than one player is involved in a
celebration after a touchdown then the players can be subject to
fines by the league.
</P>
<P>
   The owners also hit the assistant coaches from the blind side,
putting through a rule that says an assistant can only move to
another team to become a head coach. In the past, assistants could
leave to go to another team for a promotion (e.g. from running
backs coach to offensive coordinator). The coaches see this as an
attempt to drive down their salaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-OPEC-1STLD-WRITETHRU-     03-29 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-1STLD-WRITETHRU-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN AGREES TO INCREASE OIL PRODUCTION
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for complete writethru to update and restructure) 
 (See also CLINTON-OPEC) 
(js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Just hours after Iran angrily broke ranks with
all other members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, its leaders reversed themselves and announced that they
would, after all, try to raise production in line with the rest of
the oil-producing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to keep and preserve our market share,'' said
Iran's OPEC governor, Hossein Kazempour Ardebili. ``Beyond that, we
will see what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran's quick reversal Wednesday morning added to the drama that
has surrounded the meeting of oil ministers, which ended here early
Wednesday when nine of the 11 members of OPEC decided to raise
production quotas by 1.45 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   If Iran continued to pump in line with its share of the market,
the cartel's production limit would rise by 1.7 million barrels a
day beginning next month, or about 7 percent. Iraq is the only
other OPEC member not a party to the agreement, as its production
has been limited by the United Nations since the Persian Gulf War
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's reluctant acceptance reflected OPEC's continued ability
to enforce a unified pricing strategy. Despite the messy process
here, economic analysts said there was little danger that the group
would dissolve into the bickering _ and erratic production _ that
occurred years ago when prices plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Oil markets Wednesday interpreted the agreement as a sign that
production would indeed rise and prices fell moderately in
commodity trading around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In New York Wednesday, oil prices fell 64 cents, or 2.4 percent,
to $26.45 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the lowest
level since Jan. 12. Since a nine-year peak of $34.37 a barrel
three weeks ago, prices have fallen 23 percent mostly because
traders had anticipated that oil cartel members would raise their
production quotas here.
</P>
<P>
   One OPEC official predicted that by May oil prices will have
declined further and Iraq's oil minister, Amer Mohammed Rasheed,
told reporters here that he was ``pessimistic'' about the oil price
outlook over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   But lower prices at gasoline pumps in the United States are
probably months away, experts said, especially with inventories low
and demand for fuel likely to rise in the summer. Also, the
increased production is not so sizable that it is expected to
substantially reduce prices at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the total OPEC increase will be much smaller
because several members are already overshooting quotas by 1.2
million barrels a day. Analysts estimate that, after the quotas are
raised, most of this cheating will simply be absorbed into the new
limits.
</P>
<P>
   As for crude oil prices, analysts predict that they could start
climbing again by this winter, because demand is likely to remain
strong, the world's oil inventories are low and will not be fully
replenished.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, several OPEC countries have little excess capacity
and would not be able to further exceed their production limits
even if they wanted to.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tuesday night when Iran refused to participate in the agreement,
several analysts worried that it could set off a frenzy of cheating
by a few OPEC members. But Wednesday, Iran's grudging compliance
suggested that Saudi Arabia has enough power to enforce the pricing
and production regime in the face of objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excess capacity is unevenly distributed,'' said Irene
King, senior oil economist at J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. ``Seventy percent
of the excess capacity is in three countries _ Saudi Arabia, Kuwait
and Abu Dhabi.'' Those countries, she added, are the ones most
interested in preserving OPEC's grip on the market.
</P>
<P>
   In a fierce feud with Saudi Arabia, Iranian officials initially
argued here that any significant increase could send prices
plunging and would be a capitulation to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Iranian officials also knew that if they insisted on holding
the line on oil production it would be both futile and costly. On
the one hand, their refusal to pump more crude would do little to
keep oil prices high. On the other, Iran would lose sales as
countries like Saudi Arabia simply filled the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the real point Iran wanted to make Wednesday was to
attack the United States and its aggressive lobbying campaign for
higher production.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a question about influence,'' said Ardebili Wednesday,
asserting that Bill Richardson, the energy secretary, had
telephoned OPEC's president, Ali Rodriguez of Venezuela just as the
OPEC oil ministers were meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 40-year history of OPEC there has never been a case of
the Secretary of Energy calling OPEC ministers in the middle of a
meeting,'' Ardebili complained. ``We are very upset and
disappointed at the external pressure. We don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the increase in oil production quotas did not live
up to the 2 million barrels a day that the United States had
sought.
</P>
<P>
   However, the OPEC agreement will probably be supplemented by
several hundred thousand additional barrels from Mexico and Norway,
non-OPEC countries that participated in last year's cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City Wednesday, the energy minister announced that the
country would raise production by 150,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, exhausted oil ministers described the marathon
battles that were over ideology as much as money.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia, the conservative kingdom whose enormous oil
reserves overshadow those of any other OPEC member, was determined
to increase production enough to bring oil prices down to about
$25.
</P>
<P>
   Why seek a lower price at all? Analysts say Saudi officials were
worried about jeopardizing the United States. At $30 a barrel or
higher, Saudi officials feared that demand would eventually
decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a stable market, we want a well-supplied market and we
want a market that will be in equilibrium all the time,'' Ali
Naimi, the Saudi minister, said
</P>
<P>
   But Iran's Ardebili wanted to keep prices high and worried that
OPEC risked repeating the blunder at a meeting in Jakarta in 1997,
when Saudi Arabia pushed through a production increase only to see
prices fall.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC leaders have always wanted to present a unified front and
even the Saudis had preached about the need for unanimous
consensus. But after hours of fruitless wrangling, Naimi decided to
ignore Iranian opposition and go ahead without them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
