<HEADLINE>
THIS `BUDDY' NOT YOUR PAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 star 
 
 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Hanlon's metaphorical mish-mash of a movie, ``Buddy Boy,''
is almost as unlikable as its characters, and that's saying
something. While Hanlon demonstrates some skill at building
suspense in this, his first feature film, his cartoonish writing
sabotages the enterprise, making ``Buddy Boy'' a tedious exercise
in vapid voyeurism.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins with grainy black-and-white crucifixion images
that lead to our first encounter with the film's protagonist,
Francis (Aidan Gillen), who is seen masturbating in front of a
drafting table full of pornography. Is it, as with Kevin Spacey's
Lester Burnham, the highlight of his day? One can only imagine so.
</P>
<P>
   Francis lives in a filthy, rat-infested apartment with Sal
(Susan Tyrell), a figure he introduces as his mother, but given
Sal's dubious wig and beefy build, anything is possible. Francis'
homelife primarily consists of eating Spam-like meat for dinner and
lugging Sal's unconscious body back to her recliner after she has
passed out for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   So you can imagine Francis' delight when he discovers that a
beautiful woman has moved into the building across the street and
that she enjoys disrobing nightly in front of her window. After
gazing at her through a peep hole for several evenings (which gives
him plenty of fuel for his masturbatory fantasies, particularly
after he spies her pleasuring herself), Francis sees his neighbor
on the street and intervenes during an attempted mugging. The
woman, Gloria (Emmanuelle Seigner), improbably invites him to
dinner, and then, even more improbably, the two begin a romance.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that this would be pretty heady stuff for a homely,
mumbling virgin who develops film by day and dines on Spam at
night. But Francis is a tortured soul, weighted down by his
Catholic upbringing and the unfairness of life. Soon, he's
confronting the confused Gloria over imagined atrocities, using a
butcher's knife to make his point clear.
</P>
<P>
   Francis' self-pity would be more meaningful if Hanlon managed to
depict the character with any measure of skill. But the character,
and the movie for that matter, can only be seen in the most
absurdist of terms. Matters of faith are touched on, but never with
any kind of depth or meaning. ``Buddy Boy'' is a grotesquerie in
every sense of the word.!end!
</P>
<P>
   ________ &QL; 
The film: ``Buddy Boy'' (R; for language, violence, sexuality,
nudity and some drug use). &QL; 
The stars: Aidan Gillen, Emmanuelle Seigner, Susan Tyrell. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Mark Hanlon. Released by
Independent Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 43 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
