<SLUG> BC-GUNS-SMITH-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN INDUSTRY SHUNS SMITH &AMP; WESSON; STATES OPEN ANTITRUST
INVESTIGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD and RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson, which recently agreed to restrictions on the way
it makes and distributes handguns, has come under such fierce
financial pressure from other firearms manufacturers and dealers
opposed to the agreement that state officials have started
antitrust investigations of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Federal, state and city officials are also trying to protect
Smith &AMP; Wesson by persuading police agencies nationwide to buy the
company's weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to help Smith &AMP; Wesson comes after the company agreed
on March 17 to a wide array of restrictions in exchange for ending
many of the 30 lawsuits filed against it by cities and counties and
averting threatened suits by the states of New York and Connecticut
and the federal Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, one of the nation's largest gun wholesalers
announced it will stop distributing Smith &AMP; Wesson handguns, many
retail dealers have proclaimed they will not sell Smith &AMP; Wesson
products and the National Rifle Association has denounced the
company as a foreign-owned business that has ``run up the white
flag of surrender'' to the Clinton administration. Smith &AMP; Wesson,
based in Springfield, Mass., is owned by Tomkins PLC of London.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ken Jorgensen, a spokesman for Smith &AMP; Wesson, said
the Chicago law firm that had long jointly represented Smith &AMP;
Wesson, Sturm Ruger &AMP; Co. and Colt's Manufacturing Co., three of
the largest handgun makers, has said the firm will drop Smith &AMP;
Wesson as a client. And some shooting match organizers have told
Smith &AMP; Wesson that the company is not welcome at their events.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago law firm that informed Smith &AMP; Wesson it would no
longer represent the company is Wildman, Harrold, Allen &AMP; Dixon.
Anne Kimball, a lawyer at the firm who has represented Smith &AMP;
Wesson, did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Spitzer, the attorney general of New York who helped
strike the deal with Smith &AMP; Wesson, said that officials are
investigating whether there is a conspiracy against the gun maker.
``We are seeing behavior on the part of Smith &AMP; Wesson's
competitors that raises the specter of illegal anti-trust
activity,'' Spitzer said in an interview Wednesday, adding: ``This
is serious stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Richard Blumenthal, the Connecticut attorney general who was
also involved in the deal and is helping coordinate the measures to
protect the company, said, ``Smith &AMP; Wesson is under absolutely
unprecedented pressure, both financial and personal within the gun
industry, with threats that are almost violent in nature, and I
have heard the fear that it could be put out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Delfay, president of the National Shooting Sports
Foundation, the gun industry trade organization, said, ``there is
no conspiracy'' against Smith &AMP; Wesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not be more confident that these are just independent
actions by businessmen,'' Delfay said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The antitrust investigation is being conducted under state
antitrust laws in New York, Connecticut and Maryland, with more
states expected to join and subpoenas to be issued starting
Thursday, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits filed against the gun makers by cities and counties
charge them with negligently marketing and distributing their guns
in ways that have helped criminals and juveniles gain access to
them. Some of the cities are seeking to recover the cost of gun
violence for the hiring of additional policemen and in hospital
care while other cities say their main goal is to improve gun
safety and change gun makers' marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Jorgensen, the Smith &AMP; Wesson spokesman, said it is too early to
tell what the settlement's financial impact on the company will be.
But, Jorgensen added, ``We've been getting beat up pretty bad, and
the whole idea seems to be a boycott of Smith &AMP; Wesson products.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort to get law-enforcement agencies to buy Smith &AMP; Wesson
handguns could prove very helpful to the company, whose sales are
primarily to civilians. Nationwide, police forces purchase about 25
percent of the 2.5 million handguns made each year. Only a very
small part of the police handgun purchases are from Smith &AMP; Wesson.
But Blumenthal and other federal, state and city officials who met
in Washington on Tuesday to try to find a way to help the company
acknowledged that there are difficult contractual and legal
problems in getting police forces to make the change to Smith &AMP;
Wesson.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Several cities and counties around the country, including
Atlanta, Detroit, Miami-Dade County, Buffalo, Rochester, N.Y., and
Albany, N.Y., have recently agreed to buy only from Smith &AMP; Wesson.
New York City, which buys Glock handguns for its police officers,
has withheld a decision.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The effort to support Smith &AMP; Wesson is critical to regulating
the firearms industry, government officials say, because the deal
it struck splintered the powerful united front of gun makers and
gun owners that has blocked tough gun laws in Washington and state
capitals for years. The company agreed to improve the safety of its
handguns, for instance, by including trigger locks with all sales,
and to allow its dealers to sell weapons at only those gun shows
where all sales are subject to background checks on the buyer. It
also requires, within three years, so-called smart-gun technology
that will allow each of its new handguns to be fired only by
authorized users.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said that if Smith &AMP; Wesson were undermined financially,
it would weaken the government's hand in drawing other gun makers
into similar agreements. ``If one company signs on and is left out
to dry, we can't credibly go to other companies and ask them to
join this agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The wholesaler that announced it will stop distributing Smith &AMP;
Wesson guns is RSR Group Inc. of Winter Park, Fla., which called
for Smith &AMP; Wesson to reopen negotiations to ``find a workable
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although RSR has been a leading distributor of Smith &AMP; Wesson
products for more than 20 years, we have come to the difficult
conclusion that we cannot continue to do business with Smith &AMP;
Wesson under the problematic terms of the current agreement,'' the
company said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said these were precisely the kinds of actions the
investigation would examine to see whether ``they are part of a
concerted, illegal campaign to retaliate against Smith &AMP; Wesson,
restraining trade and impeding the development of a safer
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew M. Cuomo, secretary of housing and urban development, who
helped organize the Tuesday meeting in Washington, said, ``It seems
the industry is doing everything it can to make an example out of
Smith &AMP; Wesson.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Almost overlooked in the dispute over what has happened to Smith
&AMP; Wesson is the view of some gun control advocates, who asserted
that the settlement two weeks ago let the company off easy because
it only accepted provisions it was already practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, six municipalities that did not take part in the
agreement _ Chicago, Cleveland, Cincinnati, New Orleans,
Washington, D.C. and Wayne County, Mich. _ said they would continue
with their lawsuits against Smith &AMP; Wesson as well as other gun
makers.
</P>
<P>
   John Komako, for example, a lawyer for Cleveland, said he saw
``no reason to sign onto the agreement'' without seeing what
documents Smith &AMP; Wesson would be forced to disclose in the
discovery stage of the lawsuits. On March 14, just before Smith &AMP;
Wesson reached its agreement, U.S. District Judge Donald Nugent, in
Cleveland, rejected the gun companies' motion for summary dismissal
and ordered that discovery in the case could proceed. Lawyers
advising the cities suing the gun industry have contended that if
they could get into discovery of corporate documents they would
find evidence that the firearms makers have long known how easily
their guns are sold to criminals and juveniles, providing the kind
of proof that led to expensive settlements by the tobacco
companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
