<HEADLINE>
SEARCH CONTINUES FOR WOMAN SWEPT AWAY IN CREEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINGO RAMIREZ Jr. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Yolanda Dickens leaped to safety as
floodwaters swept away a car carrying her husband and his
grandmother near Trinity Boulevard on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She looked on helplessly as they disappeared into a swollen
creekbed.
</P>
<P>
   Dickens, 22, never saw her husband again.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, family members and authorities searched fruitlessly for
Ashlyn Dickens, 24, and his grandmother, Adele Warren, 62.
Relatives found Ashlyn Dickens' body Wednesday morning in the
Valley View Branch creekbed. He is survived by his wife and two
young children, ages 2 and 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   By late Wednesday, searchers _ including a helicopter, military
personnel, a Fort Worth Fire Department rescue team and dogs _ had
not found Warren.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very joyous woman,'' said Andre Allen of Mansfield,
her nephew. ``This is all unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, along with friends, relatives and more than 15 of
Warren's co-workers at nearby Bell Helicopter Textron, kept vigil
Wednesday as searchers combed the creek. Warren worked at Bell for
more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, family members and friends huddled in prayer
for the 62-year-old Everman grandmother. Her mother was scheduled
to arrive Wednesday afternoon from Colorado Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster happened after 6 p.m. Tuesday, when Warren left
work just as massive thunderstorms dumped heavy rain in far east
Fort Worth. About the same time, a tornado was working its way
through downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Ashlyn and Yolanda Dickens, of Fort Worth, had driven to the
Bell Helicopter plant on Hurst Boulevard to pick up Warren.
Initially, family members had reported that the Dickens' 2-year-old
son was in the car, but he was not, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always drove home on Trinity Boulevard,'' said LaCreecha
White of Fort Worth, Warren's granddaughter. Ashlyn Dickens was
White's brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got on Trinity and was going that way, (west) but there
was water, so she turned this way,'' White said, pointing to the
eastbound lanes of Trinity Boulevard. White said Yolanda Dickens
gave her an account of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was more water. She tried to make a U-turn, but the
water was too strong,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Warren's car was caught in the rushing water and fell into the
creek, which crosses Trinity Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives found the car Tuesday night about 200 yards from the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just too dark to keep looking,'' White said. ``We were
back here at 6 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   More than two hours later, Ashlyn Dickens' body was found about
100 yards down the creek from where the car was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers found a tan purse and a maroon sweater in the creek,
but family members told authorities that the items did not belong
to Warren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll stay here as long as it takes,'' White said. ``We have
to find her.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
