<HEADER>
A1644 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-UNITER30-COX     03-29 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-UNITER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gay GOP group: Bush is no uniter
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's credentials as a
self-labeled ``uniter'' are under fire from a Republican group that
says the probable GOP presidential nominee talks a better game than
he plays.
</P>
<P>
   After months of unsuccessful attempts to set up a meeting with
Bush, the national director of the Log Cabin Republicans, the
party's gay rights organization, said it's hard to bring people
together if you refuse to talk with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it does question calling yourself `a uniter not a
divider,''' said Rich Tafel, echoing Bush's oft-repeated
description of himself. ``He said he went to Bob Jones University
because he speaks to all groups, but he won't meet with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's February speech at the South Carolina university left him
with weeks of political problems because of his delayed
condemnation of the school's anti-Catholic policies. He also was
criticized because he didn't speak out against the school's ban on
interracial dating during his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Tafel's comments came in conjunction with a memo to members of
the Log Cabin Republicans about the months-long effort to meet with
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush, far from being a uniter who is compassionate, has
actually played upon divisions to win the nomination, and now shows
little desire to heal them. A candidate who cannot unite the
Republican Party won't win this election,'' Tafel said in the memo.
</P>
<P>
   The Log Cabin Republicans' attack on Bush's credentials as a
uniter came as the GOP's effort to expand its base came under fire
on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Anderson, a black GOP activist who had been vice chairman
of a Republican effort to recruit minorities, recently quit the
party because of what she called a ``pattern of racial blunders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the recent spectacle of the two leading Republican
presidential candidates, Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain,
refusing to condemn the flying of the Confederate flag _ a symbol
of defiance of the first Republican president _ over the South
Carolina Statehouse,'' Anderson said in a column explaining her
decision. ``And Governor Bush has yet to apologize to
African-Americans for failing to speak out against Bob Jones
University's ban on interracial dating.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he disapproved of the university's policy, since
revoked, against interracial dating. In a letter to Catholic
leaders, Bush said he regretted not speaking out against the
university's anti-Catholic policies. There was no equivalent effort
to express regret for his delayed condemnation of the ban on
interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics made up an important bloc of voters in key GOP primary
states. African-Americans did not.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee spokesman Mike Levy on Wednesday
downplayed the significance of Anderson's departure from the
party's New Majority Council. She was one of more than 500
co-chairs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that she decided to leave,'' Levy said. ``I
think she is completely misreading the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee also is trying to poke holes
in the GOP's big tent by noting that former California Republican
Gov. Pete Wilson, whose positions on immigration and affirmative
action alienated many Hispanics, helped a new group raise $1.5
million for television ads espousing its conservative views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush preaches unity. When the camera lights are on,
he reaches out to people of color. However, when the camera lights
are off and when behind closed doors, he allows Pete Wilson to send
out negative messages,'' said DNC General Co-chairman Dennis
Archer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan discounted efforts to link his
boss to the California effort. ``We are not involved,'' he said. A
top Bush adviser said a Bush meeting with gay Republicans is in the
works, but it probably will not involve leaders of Log Cabin
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
