<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Complex $19 Billion Deal to Take Seagate Private
</P>
<P>
   In a complex $19 billion deal, Seagate Technology, the disk
drive company, will be taken private by an investor group led by
Silver Lake Partners, Seagate executives and the Texas Pacific
Group. Under terms of the deal, Veritas Software will buy back its
one-third stake held by Seagate and redistribute the assets to
Seagate's stockholders. The investor group will acquire Seagate's
disk drive business.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Falls on Technology Flight
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index plummeted as investors abandoned
technology stocks for the perceived comfort of General Electric and
other household names. The index lost 189.22 points, or 3.9
percent, to 4,644.67. As the Nasdaq sagged, however, the Dow Jones
industrial average rallied, climbing 82.61 points, to 11,018.72.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 0.79 point, to
1,508.52.
</P>
<P>
   TriZetto and IMS Health to Combine
</P>
<P>
   TriZetto Group, an Internet health care company that went public
less than six months ago, said that it was using its highflying
stock to buy IMS Health, a decades-old company that gathers
prescription information for drug companies, for stock valued at
more than $8 billion. The complex transaction, which leaves IMS
executives and shareholders in control of the new company, left
Wall Street analysts and investors perplexed. Shares of TriZetto
lost more than 40 percent of their value, falling $24.5625, to
$33.50. IMS declined $5, to $16.625.
</P>
<P>
   Five big health care companies, which account for about 70
percent of the supplies bought by the nation's hospitals, said they
planned to form an online exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Iran Joins OPEC Accord After All
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after it broke ranks with other OPEC members, Iran
reversed itself and announced it would try to raise oil production.
If Iran pumps in line with its share of the market, the cartel's
production limit would rise by 1.7 million barrels a day, or 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton urged oil companies to pass the savings
quickly along to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Even More Added to Mattel's Plate
</P>
<P>
   When the embattled board of Mattel meets today, its agenda will
have a couple of new elements. One is Ralph Whitworth, managing
member of a private investment fund that owns 4.2 million shares.
Whitworth may shake up the sleepy Mattel board. Another issue is
the reappearance of a civil lawsuit filed in 1995 by a former
Mattel executive, who contends she was wrongfully dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Patent Office to Revise Procedures
</P>
<P>
   Facing accusations that it has been too ready to issue patents
for Internet business methods, the Patent and Trademark Office said
that it was changing its procedures to ensure that such patents
cover true innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Audit Questions CDNow's Future
</P>
<P>
   Shares in the online music retailer CDNow fell 30.9 percent
after an audit by Arthur Andersen expressed ``substantial doubt''
about the company's future. Jason Olim, CDNow's chief executive,
played down the significance of the audit, saying the firm was
obliged to make a qualified endorsement given that CDNow had said
it lacked enough money to operate through the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Coke Executives Meet
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson met with Coca-Cola executives to discuss
the company's treatment of women and minority employees.
</P>
<P>
   Airline Union Details Concessions
</P>
<P>
   The union representing flight attendants at US Airways disclosed
details of concessions it made in the tentative agreement that the
two sides reached to avoid a strike.
</P>
<P>
   No Bonus for Ex-Sotheby's Chief
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's former chief executive, Diana Brooks, who resigned
amid allegations that the auction house conspired with rival
Christie's to fix prices, received no bonus and no stock options
last year, according to the company's proxy statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
