<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-PRAYER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONY FLIGHT 261 STORY CIRCULATING ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A story getting widespread circulation on the Internet
claims Monroe minister Linda Knight led passengers of Alaska Flight
261 in prayer over the plane's intercom system during the final
nine minutes before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Her words were picked up by the doomed jet's cockpit voice
recorder, according to the story.
</P>
<P>
   While no one survived the crash so exactly what was happening in
the passenger compartment is not known, sources close to the
federal crash investigation said that no such prayer can be heard
on the cockpit voice recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Internet story has taken on a life of its own.
Several people from around the country, including family members of
crash victims, have called or e-mailed the Post-Intelligencer in
recent days, wanting to know if the story is true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of hoping there might be some credibility to it,
though I had my doubts,'' said Ben Johnson, editor of a monthly
magazine in Greenville, S.C., for the Associate Reformed
Presbyterian Church.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was sent the Internet story via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes these things look too good to be true,'' he said.
``But you have to balance that with the fact that truth can be
stranger than fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey Stokes, whose mother Janice of Ketchikan, Alaska, was
among the 88 passengers and crew who died in the crash, said he
searched the Internet for the prayer story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of new information on the crash has been
frustrating,'' he said. ``There have not been many updates lately
from the NTSB. Then, when I heard about this web site that
supposedly had the story, it got my hopes up. I searched for two
hours but didn't find anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The story in question says an Alaska Airlines pilot listened to
the cockpit voice recorder and that for the last 9 minutes of
Flight 261 the wife of the pastor from Monroe can be heard
``sharing the Gospel'' with the crew and passengers over the
intercom system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just before the final dive into the Pacific Ocean, she can be
heard leading the sinner's prayer for salvation,'' the Internet
story says.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Knight and her husband Joe were co-pastors of The Rock
Church in Monroe, Wash. They were on returning from from a
humanitarian trip to Puerto Vallarta, Mexico. Their son, Jeff
Knight is in Mexico and could not be reached for coment about the
Internet story.
</P>
<P>
   But a family friend said she and Jeff have spoken about the
story and he told her he believed it to be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows his parents' character,'' said the friend, Johanna
Little. ``Knowing his mother, she would do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The jet was heading to Seattle, with a scheduled stop in San
Fransciso, when it crashed into the Pacific off the California
coast north of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board has publicly released
little information about what is on the cockpit voice recorder
during the jet's last 30 minutes of flight, other than that the
pilots were in radio contact with Alaska mechanics on the ground as
they worked on a problem with the plane's stabilizer.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that an unsubstantiated Internet
story has surfaced in the wake of an air crash.
</P>
<P>
   Former newsman Pierre Salinger lost credibility after he used an
Internet story as the basis of a claim that a Navy missile brought
down TWA Flight 800 in July 1996. The FBI and the safety board
discounted the missile theory, but many people still believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Two years earlier, Microsoft learned the power that an an
Internet story can have as it moves through cyberspace when it had
to issue a press release denying it had bought the Catholic Church.
Someone posted the bogus story on the Net and people who believed
it called Microsoft to complain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
