<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WELCOMES THE OPEC DECISION TO SELL MORE OIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON and OPEC, moved in `i' category) 
(jt) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Wednesday welcomed the OPEC
decision to increase crude oil production and urged oil companies
to pass the savings quickly along to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference that covered a gamut of other issues from
China policy to gun control to taxes on the Internet, the president
began by saying that the production increase announced on Tuesday
by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was ``good
news for the economy and for the American consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   He proposed no new policies. Until it becomes clear whether
gasoline and fuel oil prices fall and by how much, Clinton said,
``we have to just keep our powder dry, keep our options open.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plans to take up legislation on Thursday to cut and
potentially repeal the federal gasoline tax, but there is
considerable opposition to the measure in Congress. Asked if he
would veto the bill, the president said he did not anticipate
having to make that decision because he did not expect Congress to
approve the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress, hoping to get political mileage from
the steep increase in gasoline prices this year, continued
Wednesday to attack the administration on energy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is, unfortunately, a Clinton-Gore anti-energy policy,
and the American people are paying the price _ at the gas pumps _
for eight years of neglect,'' said Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the
Republican majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Armey and many of his colleagues want tax breaks for oil
producers and more oil and gas exploration on federal land,
including the waters off Florida and California and the Arctic
National Wildlife Refuge in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton opposes those measures. Wednesday, he renewed the call
he made in his State of the Union address in January for new steps
to promote fuel conservation and alternative energy sources.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Republican Congress has rejected the
administration's requests for more money for energy research and
for tougher fuel economy standards for automobiles and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress are divided over whether to try to lower
the federal gasoline tax, now 24.4 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The measure before the Senate would immediately roll back the
4.3 cents enacted in 1993, which was part of a large budget measure
approved by the Senate after Vice President Al Gore cast the
tie-breaking vote. The remaining 18.4 cents would be rescinded if
average gasoline prices, now slightly above $1.50 a gallon, reached
$2 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
