<HEADLINE>
HENDERSON GETS THE CALL-UP FROM PROVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ With Shawn Bates gone for the season as a result of
wrist and hip injuries, forward Jay Henderson Wednesday became the
latest player to get the call from Providence. In a season in which
the Baby B's have had an even tougher time fielding a healthy team
than the parent club, Henderson's presence here is a tough blow to
the Bruins' AHL affiliate but a boost for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little reward for the end of the season, that's the way
I look at it,'' said Henderson, who left Providence as the team's
second-leading scorer with 45 points (18 goals) in 60 games.
``Hopefully I'll be here for the rest of the season. It'll boost my
confidence going into the (AHL) playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson is one of the few players in the organization who
hasn't been seriously injured this season. The worst he's had to
endure was being elbowed in the face last Friday against Kentucky.
It resulted in a broken front tooth and 15 stitches in his lip.
Despite that nasty bit of business, which is healing, Henderson
said he's had a satisfying year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone pretty well,'' he said. ``I've been very lucky,
knock on wood, with injuries. Offensively, I think I've been doing
pretty good. Injury-wise it's been tough for the team but I can't
complain about the ice time I've been getting. It's going well.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins' season ends, Henderson and others will be
returned to Providence as the Baby B's attempt to capture a second
straight Calder Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait for it,'' said Henderson. ``We've got six, seven,
or maybe eight guys coming down for the playoffs. I know (coach
Peter Laviolette) is really excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said as hard as this season has been on the players,
it's been more difficult on the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done very well. I don't know how he's done it,'' said
Henderson, of Laviolette's ability to keep the ship afloat. ``I'd
go crazy. I'd have lost my mind. He's been really positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The rash of injuries actually has worked in Henderson's favor
with more ice time and more responsibility than he had last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had four solid lines and the expectation of me
scoring goals wasn't on my shoulders,'' he said. ``This year, all
year we've been shortstaffed. I've put higher expectations on
myself in terms of scoring goals. I like that role. Guys have been
up in Boston so there's been more responsibility on myself and
other players down there to score goals and take over the
leadership roles. It's worked out well for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tallas is back
</P>
<P>
   Having improved significantly since suffering a neck injury
March 21 against Tampa Bay, Rob Tallas was back in net Wednesday
night against the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of days off helped,'' said Tallas. ``It's still a
little sore, though. I think sleeping on it all night, when you
first wake up it's a little stiff. Sometimes you feel a little
muscle spasm in it. For the most part, though, every day I've
massaged it, put heat and ice on it. It was just a muscle so it's
healing.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago Tallas couldn't turn his head, but now he's close
to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to affect me one bit out there,'' he said.
``Unless I get scored on from behind the net, I'll blame it on the
neck, but other than that I think it's pretty good. This is a fun
building to play in and I know this game means a lot to (coach Pat
Burns).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It could always be worse
</P>
<P>
   As bad as the Bruins' injury woes have been this year,
Montreal's have been worse. The Habs went into Wednesday night's
game with more than 500 man games lost to injury. The Montreal
Gazette reported the payout to injured players this season was just
over $9.62 million in US funds out of a $32 million payroll. Saku
Koivu, Vladimir Malakhov (since traded to New Jersey), Trevor
Linden, and Brian Savage accounted for nearly two-thirds of the
$9.62 million . . . Jeff Hackett made his eighth consecutive start,
and 14th in 16 games, in net for Montreal. Hackett, 31, is expected
to start every one of the Canadiens' remaining games as they
continue their fight for a playoff spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
