<HEADER>
A1653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PATENT-OFFICE-NYT &LR;      03-29 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENT-OFFICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AGENCY RETHINKS INTERNET PATENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing charges that it has been too ready to issue
patents for Internet business methods, the Patent and Trademark
Office said Wednesday that it was changing its evaluation
procedures to ensure that such patents cover true innovations.
</P>
<P>
   The agency will be ``fine-tuning our examinations in a lot of
areas,'' its director, Q. Todd Dickinson, said. ``These changes
have been in the works for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The actions announced Wednesday are the first substantial move
to address a growing debate over whether ownership of business
methods can be awarded to someone exclusively because they are
applied online. The debate centers on these questions: Do recent
patents for practices like single-click purchases or
name-your-price sales, to name just two, protect legitimate
innovations? Or do they stifle electronic commerce and competition
when issued to inventors exploiting a patent system designed in a
non-digital age?
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time the agency has made changes after being
criticized for lagging behind technology; a similar controversy
arose several years ago over its processing of software-related
inventions. Both then and now, critics have castigated the agency
for lacking the trained staff and resource materials to make
informed judgments _ this time, to know enough about software, the
Internet and electronic commerce to understand which business
methods are universal or already in the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said Wednesday that it would tackle those challenges
by increasing review of its' examiners work, and by inviting
representatives of the software industry to help educate the
agency's staff. The plans were first reported Wednesday in The Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson said the examiners who analyze and approve patents
will be required to search databases looking for ``prior art,'' or
existing evidence of a business method. Each patent application
will now undergo an initial examination and two reviews, instead of
one review, and the agency will double the number of business
method patents it randomly scrutinizes a fourth time each year.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson said he hoped ``to get more examiners into the
field,'' where they could visit laboratories and offices in the
software and computer industry, for example.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would also like industry representatives to offer
their expertise to the agency and that he planned to invite them to
a roundtable discussion this summer, to share databases and to
bolster the agency's research resources and the expertise of its
examiners, managers and policy makers.
</P>
<P>
   Software makers and others would find themselves dealing with
Group 705, a department created in 1997 to process business-method
software patents. At the time, it employed 12 examiners; now it has
40. It was set up not long after a furor arose over
software-related inventions.
</P>
<P>
   For years software had been covered by copyright law and was
believed, like mathematical algorithms, to be ineligible for
patents. But that changed as the software industry grew and as
ownership of lines of code became increasingly valuable.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute grew, too, and culminated with a patent awarded to
Compton's New Media for a search-and-retrieval method. Critics
immediately pointed out that the technology was already in the
public domain. The Patent and Trademark Office was forced to reveal
that it had few software engineers on staff to evaluate such
applications and a pitiful supply of software manuals in its
research library. The Compton's debacle ended in a rare
re-evaluation of an issued patent, and an even rarer rescinding of
that patent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the agency issued new guidelines, hired new software
engineers to train as patent examiners, opened a new computer
database of existing software technologies, and dedicated itself to
collecting reference material for its software library. But
evidently, the lesson was not easily transferred to the explosive
growth in electronic commerce and the sudden glut of
Internet-related business method patents.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the agency has found itself castigated for
issuing patents for what appear to be common ways of conducting
electronic business, like the 1-Click purchasing patented by
Amazon.com or the name-your-price method patented by Priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Amazon, Jeffrey Bezos, proposed this
month that the controversy might be resolved by publishing
applications while they are pending, and by shortening the lifespan
of business method patents.
</P>
<P>
   But Dickinson rejected the idea that the 210-year-old patent
system was not well suited for a rapidly evolving computer-based
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've adapted to every technology that has come along,''
Dickinson said. ``People made the same argument when the telephone
came along. They said the same thing with Henry Ford and the motor
car. The automobile industry was the main part of the economy in
the first half of the century. This will sort itself out in the
same way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
