<HEADER>
A1654 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS &LR;      03-29 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO BACKS OFF FROM SUSPENSION THREATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A day after promising ``major suspensions'' of more
than one player for ``un-Celticlike behavior'' during Tuesday's
blowout loss in Orlando, Rick Pitino Wednesday did . . . nothing.
But he did say he could not envision staying in Boston if the
Celtics continue to flounder next season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of following through on the suspensions, Pitino backed
off after what he said was a soul-searching, two-hour meeting on
the team plane following the 122-87 loss, its worst of the season
and fifth in a row. The candid admission about his future in Boston
represented the first time Pitino has put a timeline on his stay in
town.
</P>
<P>
   In a rambling news conference at the Celtics' practice facility,
Pitino said he would forfeit the remainder of his contract _ some
$20-plus million after next season _ because he wouldn't feel right
taking money if he wasn't producing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come next year, if this team doesn't reach its potential,
doesn't make the playoffs, I'd be honest with you at that point, I
would definitely make a move myself,'' Pitino said. ``I would,
without question. Because all I would be doing if I stayed at that
point (would be) trying to take (owner) Paul Gaston's money.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's what he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   What he said on Tuesday night was unequivocal and unambiguous:
unnamed players _ believed to be Antoine Walker and Danny Fortson _
were due for suspensions that could range from a couple games to
the season's final 11 games. His one qualifier: that he would sleep
on it. But he certainly sounded like someone who had had enough of
what he termed ``childish behavior'' of some of his players,
adding, ``Unfortunately, they're going to pay dearly for this.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is going to pay a thing. Pitino said he was impressed
enough by the cathartic talk on the plane ride and the players'
understandable frustration over a series of tough losses that he
decided not to suspend anyone. He also has decided that he probably
won't make major trades involving those same players, which he also
said he was thinking of doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dead wrong what happened,'' he said. ``It was something
untypical of Celtic behavior, but I don't want to make anyone a
scapegoat and that's why I'm not doing that. Believe me, they
understand where I am coming from. If I thought suspensions would
help them as people, and help them as a team, I'd suspend all of
them right now. But I don't think that's the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Walker, ``What happened? Nothing happened. We lost the
game. That's not y'all's business if something did happen. That's
my point. You can talk about the game, but what happened between
the team is our business and our business only.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a difficult time for us because we're fghting
for the playoffs. We've lost five straight games and it hurts. We
got 11 games left. Our job as a unit is not to throw the season
away and end the season on a bad note. We gotta take these 11 games
and turn it around and get back on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino was asked if he thought he was blowing his credibility
with his turnaround. ``Do I believe suspensions were in order? Yes
I do,'' he said. ``But I think professional basketball is a
partnership. I listened to them. They understand that this is never
to happen again, that this is never going to be tolerated again.
After listening to them, I did not feel suspensions were in order.
If that makes me soft, or losing credibility, then so be it. That's
the way I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Pitino has done a quick 180. He made
a threat last year after a big loss in Cleveland, promising that
after reviewing the tape, if he saw people degrading the Boston
uniform, those players would not start or play anymore. The next
day, he stuck with the same lineup and made no changes because he
said everyone was culpable.
</P>
<P>
   Also last season, Walker and Kenny Anderson were fined for
arguing on the court during a game in Washington. Pitino said he
talked to both players and added, ``It won't happen again. I'm
confident of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the flip-flop this time wasn't the only issue Pitino
addressed in a rambling session with reporters that touched a lot
of bases. Inevitably, the question of his future in Boston came up,
again, and Pitino talked about what he felt next year's team needed
(veterans and athletes). But not before he said he'd step back at
the end of this season to make sure that, in his mind, he's
``making a difference in the lives of athletes. That's where I get
my gratification.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was saying, for the first time, that he might not
return for the 2000-2001 season, Pitino said that was not the case.
He also said no one should worry about being traded or losing a job
based on Tuesday's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only change I'd make down the road is to myself,'' he
said. ``What I have to do, down the road, is if these guys don't
get it done, I have to say to myself, `Self, these are the guys you
wanted. These are the guys you brought in. This is your team.
You're not winning. . . . I'm not here to take Paul Gaston's money.
That will never happen. I'm not in it to say I've got a 10-year
contract. What I will say is, `Thanks, Paul, appreciate the
opportunity very much, keep your money and spend it wisely, on
players.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
