<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDORADO-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MUCH GOLD AT `EL DORADO'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
It's been reported that DreamWorks honcho Jeffrey Katzenberg fought
to keep a realistic edge in the studio's new animated feature,
``The Road to El Dorado.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   If so, he lost. And so did the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Suspended somewhere between a Bob Hope/Bing Crosby comedy and
surreal jungle adventure, ``El Dorado'' sure could have used some
kind of coherent basis. Yes, it's a cartoon fantasy, but the film's
inconsistent inner logic keeps throwing you out of its story, a
condition that's only exacerbated by a broader lack of
believability.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a caper comedy, at other times a straightforward
adventure, mixed up with supernatural elements that come out of
narrative nowhere and saddled with distractingly surreal production
numbers, the movie is constantly marching in different directions.
Marry that to an underfocused, meandering narrative that never
quite engages, and you've got a film that virtually invites you to
pick apart its flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Which is too bad, since there's a good bit of lovely work that
went into the graphic end of this. Set mostly in the legendary lost
city of gold, the film makes marvelous use of Meso-American
designs, lush foliage and, through impressive new computer
programs, difficult-to-animate water motifs. The look is
appropriately mythic and as lavish as a conquistador's wildest
dream of New World opulence.
</P>
<P>
   What a half-baked buddy comedy is doing in the middle of all
this brilliance remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1519, and two likable Spanish ne'er-do-wells, quick-witted
Tulio (voiced by Kevin Kline) and dreamy Miguel (Kenneth Branagh),
wind up hiding from the law on one of Hernan Cortes' ships. Then
they're somehow in a rowboat with the helpful warhorse Altivo and,
amazingly enough, a map to El Dorado that starts right where their
dinghy happens to beach.
</P>
<P>
   They soon discover the great golden city, which is otherwise
safely inaccessible behind a waterfall and mountain grotto. The
Europeans _ who, like all the pre-Columbian locals, miraculously
speak English _ are naturally enough mistaken as gods (by immense
good luck, not to mention story contrivance, a belching volcano
chokes just when a miracle demonstration is required).
</P>
<P>
   Our con-happy heroes set about collecting as much treasure as
possible, which they plan to sail back to Spain in a seaworthy ship
that the adoring Indians, who presumably know nothing of the world
beyond their immediate environs, are capable of building in three
days.
</P>
<P>
   But even in a cartoon dimension as astounding as this one, there
are complications. It seems that Tulio and Miguel have stumbled
into a power struggle between El Dorado's roly-poly, life-loving
Chief (Edward James Olmos) and its hissable, human sacrifice-happy
high priest Tzekel-Kan (Armand Assante). There's also a shrewd
little gal, Chel (Rosie Perez, who besides her voice provided
remarkably well-copied body models, movements and attitudes), who's
onto the Spaniards' scam, wants in on it and gets PG erotic with
Tulio.
</P>
<P>
   You can decide whether you think Chel represents a physically
accurate celebration of indigenous femininity or a sexualized
Latina stereotype _ or just a latter-day Dorothy Lamour. While
that's arguably an individual judgment call, there should be little
debate that Elton John and Tim Rice's attempts to infuse the film's
songs with authentic Latin flavor fall well short of their
African-inspired ``Lion King'' music.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a monstrous stone jaguar that comes to life and
large bird and fish creatures that wander through frames from,
well, the gods know where. If this sounds like a stab at magical
realism, be warned that very little of it seems real at all.
</P>
<P>
   And the magic doesn't exactly work, either. &QL; 
________ &QL; 
The film: ``The Road to El Dorado'' (PG; violence, nudity). &QL; 
The stars: Voices of Kevin Kline, Kenneth Branagh, Rosie Perez,
Armand Assante, Edward James Olmos. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Eric ``Bilbo'' Bergeron and Don
Paul. Written by Ted Elliott and Terry Rossio. Produced by Bonne
Radford and Brooke Breton. Released by DreamWorks Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 23 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
