<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATTEBERG WILL BE WAKEFIELD'S RIGHT-HAND MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Scott Hatteberg will be seeing a lot of Tim
Wakefield. In fact, the Red Sox catcher can expect to see the
knuckleballer every fifth day.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg would like to be a starter, but that job belongs to
Jason Varitek. Since it doesn't appear that he will be traded,
Hatteberg's role in Boston will be Wakefield's personal catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, they are both starters. I can only catch one of them,''
Sox manager Jimy Williams said of Hatteberg and Varitek. ``I've got
two good catchers. They both deserve to catch. We need them both.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Hatteberg will catch for Wakefield exclusively.
The 30-year-old catcher solely from the left side (while Varitek
switch hits), but Williams said Hatteberg will catch Wakefield even
when the opposing team starts a lefthander.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg, who was limited to 80 at-bats in 1999, had surgery on
his right elbow last May. In 1998, Hatteberg appeared in 112 games
and had 170 more at-bats than Varitek. But last season Varitek
emerged as one of the American League's best catchers, leaving
Hatteberg as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Down and dirty
</P>
<P>
   Reds general manager Jim Bowden is a New Englander (Weston) who
grew up worshiping the Red Sox. There are many reasons he is
popular in Cincinnati. One of them was on display Wednesday.
Bowden, dressed in shorts, T-shirt, and baseball cap, did infield
work with the grounds crew. He had a cup of water thrown in his
face during the routine, courtesy of Barry Larkin . . . Gary Gaetti
left the Red Sox' 4-3 win against the Reds early, packed his bags,
and left Ed Smith Stadium for the airport. According to the Red
Sox, Gaetti has permission to go home. He will miss Thursday's home
finale against the Twins at City of Palms Park in Fort Myers. The
plan is for the veteran first baseman/designated hitter to rejoin
the team in Phoenix Friday. No reason was given for his departure .
. . Many Red Sox have begun calling Carl Everett ``Dr. Evil.''
``It's an inside joke,'' Everett said. ``You know, it's from
(`Austin Powers.')'' . . . Everett and Jose Offerman were given the
day off . . . John Valentin hit a seventh-inning solo homer, a hit
that turned out to be the winning run. John Wasdin (two scoreless
innings) was credited with the win . . . As expected, the Red Sox
exercised one of two club options on Nomar Garciaparra's contract.
That means the shortstop will be with the team until at least 2003.
The Sox also have the right to trigger an option for 2004 . . .
Williams said he isn't concerned with the team's 10-17 spring
record. ``I've seen the same intensity all spring,'' the manager
said. ``Maybe I can't see the trees from the forest, I don't
know.'' . . . Ed Smith threw out the first ball. Not familiar with
Mr. Smith? The Reds' stadium here is named after him.
</P>
</TEXT>
