<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1659 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FIRE-8DEAD30-COX     03-29 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-8DEAD30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire consumed a family's dream
 &HT;    By Steve Visser and Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACWORTH, Ga. _ Joanne Cochran, mother of four and surrogate mom
to more, had almost escaped the trailer park in Acworth.
</P>
<P>
   With two jobs, long hours and little pay, the hard-working woman
had scrounged enough money for a home of her own _ an unremarkable
tale of the working poor's survival in suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, an hour before she was to supervise the 4 a.m.
browning of biscuits at a nearby Hardee's, Cochran's trailer home
burned to the ground. The 37-year-old woman and seven other people
died. The youngest victim was a baby born two weeks into the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just got everything going right, and now it's all gone,''
said Tammy Kines, assistant manager of the Modern Living Mobile
Home Park. ``She couldn't give her kids everything, but she made
sure they had everything they needed _ food, clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor reported the fire at 3:15 a.m. and a pumper truck
arrived minutes later, emptying its 750-gallon tank onto the
1,500-square-foot home, said Cobb County fire Capt. Mark Gresham.
</P>
<P>
   The trailer park covers 18 acres and has 114 homes, but the only
fire hydrant is at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll was the worst from a single fire in Cobb County
history. State Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine, who is also
the state fire marshal, said it was the worst residential fire in
Georgia since at least 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were unable to locate any smoke detectors in the
rubble _ which are typically found, said Oxendine, who was at the
scene. Investigators determined that an electrical short in an
unvented dryer in the living room caused the blaze, igniting
clothing around the appliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fire would have put out a lot of smoke,'' Oxendine said.
``From the nature of the fire, we are saying there wasn't a smoke
detector or it wasn't operational. ...There would have been more
than enough time for everybody to get out safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobile home park owner Ed Converse disputed the apparent absence
of a smoke detector.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran had just quit her second job as a maintenance worker in
the park and knew the importance of safety, he said. Other
maintenance workers said they recently saw smoke detectors in the
trailer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   An ashen Converse said park employees had a going-away party for
Cochran two weeks ago. ``Everybody liked Joanne,'' he said. ``She
was close to her kids. If there was a stray, she took them in _
anyone, anything. She had a huge heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Also killed in the fire were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cochran's son Brandon, a rambunctious, blond, 6-year-old
first-grader at Acworth Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   _ Daughter Melissa, 15, a student at Awtry Middle School, who
baby-sat Brandon when her mother worked the evening shift at
Hardee's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Daughter Nicole, and her cousin Jennifer Lacy, both 18, who
worked full-time at the Subway sandwich shop in the shopping center
across from the trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   _ Son Jessie, 19, who worked at Hardee's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jessie's 16-year-old girlfriend, Sarah Hilliard, and their
11-week-old daughter, Destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters found three bodies in the front of the mobile home,
five more on the floor in a rear bedroom about 10 feet from the
back door. ``It appears they were all trying to exit,'' said Mark
Gresham, a Cobb County Fire Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran's estranged husband, Dwight Cochran, identified the
bodies. ``He's torn up,'' said neighbor Patricia Harris. ``All her
kids are his.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wheeling said he awoke to find his neighbor's trailer
ablaze. He tried to open windows to get to the victims by breaking
a window with a rock, but it wouldn't shatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bounced off like it was hitting a wall ... the police said
it must have been the pressure from the fire inside,'' said the
40-year-old construction worker. ``The back end was burning pretty
good and you could see the smoke coming out all around the trailer.
I knew it was too late then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish to God there was something else I could've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran and her family had lived in Modern Living park for four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just getting ready to move,'' said neighbor Donna
Travis, shaking her head. ``Joanne just got a new car and her
daughter had just got a new car and they were excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole's car was a 1985 Mazda MX6, and Cochran's was a 1991
Chevrolet Cavalier. Both cars sat unscathed by the shell of the
trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and friends milled around, vowing they would do what
Cochran didn't manage to do _ leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen so much in here, it's got me scared,'' said Patricia
Harris, who lives two doors down from the Cochran home. ``I've got
to get out of here. I'm ready now. I stood here and watched it all
go up. It didn't take no time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeling concurred: ``I'm not going to live in a trailer
anymore. I knew it was dangerous when we moved in here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're leaving,'' said Donna Travis as she watched firefighters
poke through the rubble. ``I've got three kids. They don't need to
be here.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Cobb County, as elsewhere in the generally affluent
suburbs of Atlanta, ``getting out'' doesn't come as easily as do
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile home parks such as Modern Living park, where rent ranges
from $120 to $180 a week, are one of the few options for low-cost
housing in a county where the average monthly rent for a
two-bedroom apartment is $783.
</P>
<P>
   Low rent opportunities _ and more specifically, the deposits and
credit history _ are beyond the reach of many working in service
and construction jobs, said Katheryn Preston, community coordinator
of the Cobb Human Services Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Paying $630 a month on rent would eat up 30 percent of the
income of someone making $25,200 year. Moving into a typical
one-bedroom apartment takes a wage of at least $10.96 an hour,
according to a study done by Preston's group.
</P>
<P>
   James Drummond, who lives in Modern Living park, makes $12 an
hour installing irrigation systems. After paying child support, he
doesn't have enough cash left to save for the deposit it would take
to live somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   But money wasn't uppermost on the minds of friends, neighbors
and relatives Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   They had set up four silk-flower wreaths outside the home. One
was in the shape of a cross. Another was decorated with a white
baby's rattle.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old Joseph Wilmont and his 7-year-old sister Crystal
live catty-cornered to the trailer that burned. As they watched
mourners setting flowers down, the two children decided to pay
their own tribute to their friends.
</P>
<P>
   They walked through the rain to lay Pokemon cards on the wet
ground by the floral arrangements. Across the cards, Crystal placed
a pink bracelet stamped with the letters W.W.J.D., which stands for
``What Would Jesus Do.''
</P>
<P>
   The cards and bracelet were for everyone who died, but
especially for Brandon, their playmate. ``I'm saying that I'll be
your best friend forever and ever,'' Crystal said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the charred trailer lay the trappings of a family's
life. A heap of blackened paperback novels, a torn blue-and-white
checkered tablecloth with Piglet on it, a single roller-skate with
lavender laces. A Big Wheel plastic tricycle, bikes and a plastic
rocking horse lay in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Hilliard, whose granddaughter of the same name died in the
fire, came with relatives to survey the scene. Stanley Hilliard,
the younger Sarah's father, salvaged a picture frame with a Glamour
Shots photo of his daughter. In the picture, Sarah is wearing an
elegant blue gown and is smiling through the soft lens, her blond
hair styled and her eyes sparkling.
</P>
<P>
   The father's hands trembled as he cradled the photo, careful not
to cut his fingers on the broken glass. His daughter and the baby
will be taken to Chattanooga, Tenn., to be buried, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Sarah Hilliard smiled at a photo of her granddaughter
and the baby. In the photo, Sarah is sitting on the floor, nestled
with her child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't they precious?'' the grandmother asked in a voice
barely above a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   At Awtry Middle and Acworth Elementary schools, counselors
talked to classmates of Melissa and Brandon Cochran.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just tough on the kids. ``I had one officer who said
he was OK until they brought the kids out,'' said Acworth police
Chief Billy Fuller. ``That really got to him. I've been in this 34
years. I hope I never see it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Yolanda Rodriguez,
Brad Schrade and Clint Williams contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
