u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-POLICE-11     03-29 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-POLICE-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY OFFICERS SAY GIULIANI WIDENS COMMUNITY BREACH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even as he defends his Police Department daily from
what he has characterized as bashing, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is
facing increasingly vocal criticism of his style and tactics on law
enforcement matters from an unlikely quarter: police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Although many officers say they appreciate Giuliani's support
for the officers involved in the recent shooting of an unarmed
black man, many also say the mayor's zero-tolerance approach to
crime, his limited outreach to the black and Latino communities and
his criticism of the dead man, Patrick Dorismond, have needlessly
widened the breach between the police force and people in many
neighborhoods it serves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Absent a survey, it is difficult to measure the extent of police
disaffection with Giuliani. But in interviews with 18 officers of
various ranks in the last few days, six supported the mayor's
stance, while a dozen, including several union officials, have
talked about how the mayor's strong language and aggressive
policies have undermined one of the force's greatest assets,
community support.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made it more difficult to patrol in minority
neighborhoods,'' said one detective who works for a squad in
Manhattan, ``because even though people may look at any officer and
not necessarily group them, when the mayor acts this way, he is
making it sound like it is `us against them.' I think it's adding
to the anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas J. Scotto, the president of the Detectives Endowment
Association, which endorsed Giuliani in 1997, said the
administration needed to do much more to repair the frayed
relationship between the police and many minorities. He noted that
even the detective who shot Dorismond, Anthony Vasquez, had issued
a statement of compassion for the man's family.
</P>
<P>
   The Dorismond shooting was ``100 percent justified,'' Scotto
said, ``but even being justified, you have to have a sense of
sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Lynch, the president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, said that, while he did not believe either Giuliani or
Police Commissioner Howard Safir was to blame for heightened
criticism of the police, his organization had nonetheless had to
increase its outreach efforts because the city had not done enough
to explain the police perspective to minority leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And a number of officers from a variety of ranks said that many
of their colleagues, caught between the scorn of some communities
and the pressure to produce ever-declining crime rates, had begun
to count the days to their retirement at 20 years. Some are
sporting hats that say ``20 and Out,'' one officer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the ones being hit with the bottles, not Howie and
Rudy,'' said John Loud, the PBA's second vice president. ``We do
appreciate their help and their support, but we have greatly
reduced crime, and even though you always have to keep your eye on
it, now is the time to respond to the community's wishes and let
them know we are here for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that most police officers had full
confidence in the mayor and that much of the discontent was the
rhetoric of unions looking for an advantage in ongoing contract
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several officers interviewed applauded the mayor's
unflinching approach, calling it a brave stance in an era when many
politicians pandered to police critics. They said the media and
habitual police detractors had undermined the department's morale,
polarized the debate and caused declines in the number of
applicants interested in a police career.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least he is sticking up for us against these hand-grenade
throwers out there,'' one Manhattan detective said of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's office would not comment on the overall question of
criticism by police officers, except to refer to a comment the
mayor made earlier this week when asked to respond to remarks by
Scotto, the head of the detectives' union. The mayor called Scotto,
who is a frequent visitor to the White House, a strong ally of
President Clinton and his wife, Giuliani's opponent in the race for
the U.S. Senate. He dismissed the criticism as overtly political
and ``part of the pile on from people who support the Clintons.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said detractors were intentionally overlooking
the many efforts the administration had made to reach out to
various communities, including a meeting Safir had Wednesday with a
task force of Bronx clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda B. Jimenez, the deputy commissioner for community
affairs, said the department had held large meetings in each
borough six times a year and countless smaller sessions to bring
people together with the officers who policed their streets. She
cited a number of strategies, including efforts to work with
neighborhood residents to build relationships after drug sweeps on
targeted blocks. ``The only limit we have is the physical limit of
time,'' said Jimenez, who oversees an office of 300 officers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the interviews indicated that Giuliani's
relationship with the 40,000-member police force is a complex one,
even if the debate since the death of Dorismond on March 16 has
made it appear at times as if he and police officers speak with one
voice, from the same side of the issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rather, many officers said that the city's outreach efforts had
been half-hearted and that the pressure to produce higher arrest
tallies and lower crime rates had forced them to pursue lesser
offenders, a policy that had exacerbated tensions in many
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the lions and tigers; now we are out there looking for
the rabbits,'' said Loud, who said he had been a volunteer in the
mayor's 1993 campaign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When police controversies occur now, several officers said, some
people are unwilling to await the facts because they already
believe the police are guilty of overzealous enforcement.
Wednesday, for example, civil libertarians complained that police
truancy patrols were sometimes stationed outside high schools and
arrest students who are late, but on their way to class.
</P>
<P>
   To improve the image of police, the unions that represent
lieutenants and captains took out an advertisement in The New York
Post Wednesday that proclaimed, ``New York City Police Officers Do
Care.'' Lt. Anthony Garvey, the president of the Lieutenants
Benevolent Association, said the ad was intended to counter
criticism that police routinely use excessive force. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Garvey said the mayor was no more guilty of undermining
support for officers than Hillary Rodham Clinton, or Comptroller
Alan Hevesi or any number of other politicians. ``I think they are
being used by everyone,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scotto said the city needs to expand the number of
police-sponsored athletic leagues and other initiatives that put a
human face on police officers. ``The New York City Police
Department is only engaged in enforcement,'' he said, ``not in
enforcement and community relations.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Lynch said he had met twice in recent months with
black leaders in Harlem to improve the dialogue. Wednesday, he
said, he met with Dennis Walcott, president of the New York Urban
League. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least some of the mayor's critics admitted they were still
bitter from the labor dispute several years ago when officers
received no wage increase for the first two years of their current
five-year contract. Others said they believe the department should
have followed a strategy recently championed by William Bratton,
the former police commissioner, who has suggested taking advantage
of the ``peace dividend of safer streets to increase training and
build relationships.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But a lieutenant who commands a detective squad in Manhattan
said the mayor's critics have forgotten it is Giuliani who deserves
the credit for reinvigorating the police force, bolstering its
budget, defending its officers and supporting its mission of
cutting crime. ``I'm certainly not going to repay his support of me
by not supporting him,'' the lieutenant said. ``People have short
memories. I don't.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
