<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-5THSTARTER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves pick up Burkett, cut Simon
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The Braves may have found their fifth starter.
They signed veteran right-hander John Burkett to a major-league
contract on Wednesday afternoon, only hours after he was released
by the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be able to really help the first two weeks,'' said
Bobby Cox, referring to the time when John Rocker will be suspended
and the bullpen will be short-handed. ``And our fifth starter's
job, which we'll need on April 22, it will be maybe him, maybe
(Bruce) Chen, maybe (Luis) Rivera.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves also released Randall Simon, whose .317 batting
average in 1999 wasn't enough to earn him a spot this year on a
roster that still includes four first basemen _ Andres Galarraga,
Wally Joyner, Brian Hunter and Bobby Bonilla. Reliever Rafael
Medina also was released, leaving 36 players in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, 35, is expected to join the Braves on Friday in Atlanta
when they play the first of two exhibition games at Turner Field.
Contract terms weren't available. He was 1-2 with a 5.29 ERA in 17
innings this spring, but he held the Braves scoreless on one hit in
two innings when they played the Devil Rays in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a terrific acquisition,'' Cox said. ``We saw
(Burkett) pitch in Venezuela and he looked good. I've always liked
John. He's not overpowering, but he throws strikes; he's able to
move the ball around the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, one of only five pitchers who have made 25 or more
starts every season in the 1990s, spent the last four seasons with
the Texas Rangers, who declined his $4.2 million option for 2000.
He was hindered by bursitis in his right shoulder early last season
and wound up with the second-highest ERA of his career at 5.62 and
a 9-8 record. But he was 5-1 with a 3.51 ERA over his last seven
starts.
</P>
<P>
   He was with the Marlins for all of 1995 and parts of 1996 before
going to the Rangers. Befoe that, he pitched six years for the San
Francisco Giants, winning 22 games in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has struggled in his bid to become the Braves' fifth
starter. He's 0-3 with a 10.13 ERA in five appearances this spring,
including four starts. He pitches today against the Florida Marlins
in the Braves' final exhibition before heading north to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves won't need a fifth starter until April 22 because of
the off days in their schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Simon _ the player Rocker referred to as ``a fat monkey'' in the
Sports Illustrated article that led to his suspension _ was out of
options, so teams interested in acquiring him were willing to wait
for his possible release.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to trade (Simon and Medina) and we couldn't, so we
had a decision to make,'' general manager John Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   By releasing the two players now, the Braves had to pay them
one-fourth of their salaries, saving $339,375. Simon, 24, would
have made $222,500 this season, Medina $230,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Randall will land on a team in the near future,'' Cox
said. ``He's got some big-league talent, no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
