<HEADLINE>
IN BASERUNNING, A ROSE IS A ROSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ There was only one distressing moment in Brian
Rose's start Wednesday at Ed Smith Stadium. If you had watched the
troubling sequence on television, you might have cursed the screen
and asked, ``What exactly is that guy trying to prove?''
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't have been screaming at Rose, who is officially part
of the Red Sox' rotation as the fifth starter. You would have been
yelling at third-base coach Wendell Kim, who, I am convinced,
momentarily transposed his Roses. The Sox were playing the
Cincinnati Reds, so maybe Kim quickly went back to baseball's 1970
All-Star Game. That's when a fierce Pete (No Relation) Rose
barrelled into catcher Ray Fosse and separated the catcher's
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The hit in '70 was a bit much, and so was Wednesday's wave by
Wendell. In the second inning, Brian Rose singled. The next batter,
Donnie Sadler, doubled. The ball was mishandled in the outfield _
but not that badly _ so Kim waved Rose home. He had no chance. The
ball was relayed from Gold Glover Ken Griffey Jr. to Gold Glover
Barry Larkin to solid catcher Eddie Taubensee.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Rose did have a chance, so what? These are rationing
times in baseball when it comes to pitching. This is an era that
features Pat Rapp as a No. 3 starter in Baltimore. When teams find
a young guy who can throw strikes (and that's the 24-year-old
Rose's profile), they nearly put him under surveillance. What
exactly is the necessity of sending a pitcher home in an exhibition
game? At best, you're going to get an uneven pitcher-catcher
collision. At worst? Use your imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness to Kim, controversy comes with his position.
Fans and self-righteous sportswriters don't say, ``That was a
terrific job of baserunning management by the third-base coach.''
It's easy to focus on the mistakes. Wednesday's was even easier
because of how damaging it could have been. (Imagine if Kim had
sent Pedro Martinez home. The Sox probably wouldn't have let him on
the team bus.)
</P>
<P>
   Sox manager Jimy Williams was a third-base coach in Atlanta from
1990-96. He shrugged off the sacrificial wave and added, ``I
probably would have sent him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Sox and their fans, this story has a happy
ending.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was even teased about his plate collision. ``He embarrassed
the entire pitching staff with his baserunning,'' reliever John
Wasdin joked. Rose hesitated when asked if Kim's ``go'' sign at
third surprised him. Wasdin was in another room when the question
was asked, but he still shouted ``Yes!'' as Rose paused.
</P>
<P>
   When Rose was away from the basepaths, he pitched well. He went
five innings and gave up seven hits. He was a mess his first couple
innings, allowing five of the seven hits, including an Aaron Boone
home run. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan immediately noticed Rose's
mechanics were off. Between innings, Kerrigan motioned as if he
were playing an accordion. Rose got the message: His body was
flying open too much as he threw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all over the place,'' Rose said of the early innings.
``I was throwing the ball right over the plate.'' He wasn't
credited with the win in the Sox' 4-3 victory, but he faced the
lineup that the Reds will use on Opening Day and gave up three
runs. If he keeps his turn in the rotation, he will pitch April 8
against Mo Vaughn and the Angels in Anaheim, Calif. A five-inning,
three-run duplicate would certainly be welcomed by Williams and
Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   Even before his good outing against the Reds, Rose was being
complimented by the manager. Rose worked with Rich Zawacki, the Sox
physical therapist, over the winter. They used weights and tubing
exercises to improve his arm strength. The theory last season when
Rose was optioned to Pawtucket in August is that his arm was tired.
Few people question his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched some great games last year,'' Williams said. ``How
many did he win, six? He could have had a lot more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose was a respectable 7-6 last season with a 4.87 ERA. His ERA
this spring is 3.26, although Williams said he is less concerned
with the numbers and more with the performance. The performance has
been impressive. The Sox are fortunate to have a No. 5 starter the
caliber of Rose (or, if it doesn't work out with him, Juan Pena).
But for some reason, I can't stop thinking that their No. 5 is
going to have a better season than their No. 3 (Jeff Fassero).
</P>
<P>
   The next step for Rose comes Monday. He and Tim Wakefield will
not make the trip to Phoenix on Friday. Wakefield will pitch a
minor-league game Sunday. Rose will work on Monday and throw 85
pitches. Both pitchers will then fly to Seattle for Tuesday's
opener at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens on Monday, Rose will have a couple things
in his favor: National League rules will not be in effect, and Kim
will be a few time zones away in Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
