<SLUG> BC-INSURERS-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 HEALTH INSURERS ARE DEVELOPING ONLINE VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: budgeted earlier as HEALTHEON-OUTLOOK; see also
HEALTHCARE-ONLINE)  
(lh) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move to block Internet health care companies from usurping
their relationships with patients and doctors and eventually taking
large portions of their business, six of the biggest health
insurers are developing their own online project.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers hope the project, tentatively called MedUnite, will
make it easier for patients to enroll in health plans and choose
doctors and hospitals by replacing paperwork and telephone calls
with online channels; smooth relations with disaffected physicians
by speeding communications; and cut business costs, according to
people working with the group.
</P>
<P>
   The online system would also handle administrative services like
approving or denying medical procedures and processing payment
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the consortium _ Aetna U.S. Healthcare, Cigna Corp.,
WellPoint Health Systems, Oxford Health Plans, Foundation Health
Systems and PacifiCare Health Systems _ have been discussing their
plans with IBM, Oracle Corp. and several smaller technology
companies, and they plan to announce the project in the next 60
days or so. That could happen at back-to-back meetings that
Foundation, WellPoint and PacifiCare have scheduled with Wall
Street analysts on May 15. Oracle declined to comment, and IBM
could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   The new initiative pits these insurers against Healtheon/WebMD,
by far the biggest Internet health care company. Before these
companies developed the venture, they were candidates to become
some of Healtheon's biggest customers.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Kroll, a health care analyst at SG Cowen, said: ``The health
plan companies want to stake out their claim. They have very
important relationships with doctors and patients and lots of data
and information that they have aggregated. They want to be
participants in this connectivity process, rather than risk being
left out of the loops.''
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon, as one of its main businesses, hopes to charge
transaction fees for the use of online connections that would link
insurers, patients and providers of care, including doctors,
hospitals and laboratories, as well as employers, who pay for most
care. The competition could cut into Healtheon's potential earnings
by eliminating important customers and even leading to pressure to
cut prices.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said that speculation about the insurer
group, which has not yet publicly discussed its plans, was already
affecting investors' confidence in Healtheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a response to Healtheon's perceived market dominance
and the desire of payers to retain some control,'' said Janice
Young, a research director with the Gartner Group Research and
Advisory Service, which analyzes technology-related industries.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon's frequently volatile stock price has been sinking
over the last four weeks since it announced disappointing financial
results for the fourth quarter of 1999. Shares of Healtheon fell
$1.375, to $30.6875, in trading on Nasdaq, which was down sharply
over all.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for the insurers declined to confirm or deny the
plans for a consortium. But Joyce Oberdorf, a spokeswoman for
Aetna, said it was ``a prospective alliance that we think holds
promise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By virtue of the market leadership of the companies in this
group, it is uniquely positioned to drive change in the industry,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   From the perspective of Aetna, she said, the consortium is
``only one of a number of alternatives dealing with connectivity
that we are looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   David Olson, a senior vice president of Foundation, said,
``Clearly the Internet presents a lot of opportunities for us as a
health plan to do a lot of things more efficiently.'' There are
efforts to create partnerships, he added, but ``I can't say very
much about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, several Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans nationwide
are developing joint Internet projects, and regional cooperative
online arrangements are also being discussed by insurers in New
England and the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Sullivan, a senior vice president of the national Blue
Cross and Blue Shield Association, said the group was holding
discussions with ``a major technology company'' to create an
Internet platform that the association members could gain access to
for all types of transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But some Blue Cross plans, including Empire in New York and
Horizon in New Jersey, will have contracts with Healtheon for
online services when its recently announced merger with CareInsite,
a competing Internet company, is completed. CareInsite also has
contracts with the HIP and GHI health plans in New York and
Massachusetts Blue Cross and Blue Shield.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Arnold, the chief executive of Healtheon, said he
expected that competitors would offer ``many initiatives, now and
in the future.'' But he said that Healtheon, which has alliances
and cooperative agreements with dozens of Internet and health care
companies, was in a better position ``than anyone else to decrease
costs, increase health plan members' satisfaction and ultimately
improve the quality of care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to be one of the winners in this space,'' added
Martin J. Wygod, the founder of CareInsite, who will be co-chairman
of Healtheon.
</P>
<P>
   Other big insurers are closely watching the consortium plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``United Healthcare is not an active part of the process, but we
are kept informed,'' said Jay Silverstein, a United vice president.
``We are willing to get involved in anything that will make life
simpler for physicians and consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Several insurance officials said they wanted to be sure that the
joint effort did not obscure the special products they offered to
``differentiate one health plan from another'' in competing for
customers, as Silverstein put it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
