<HEADLINE>
SMITS BRINGS POWER TO `PRICE OF GLORY'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many a fight fan will tell you what a beloved boxer may lack in
finesse, technique or skill can often be made up for with heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price of Glory'' proves pretty much the same the thing about
filmmakers with little more to their game than earnest
understanding of well-proven cliches. This family boxing drama hits
all of the expected combinations, but does so in a sincere and
committed enough way to pack real emotional punch.
</P>
<P>
   Written by New York Times sportswriter Phil Berger _ who
collaborated with heavyweights Joe Frazier and Larry Holmes on
their autobiographies _ and directed by energetic feature
first-timer Carlos Avila, the film succeeds more often than not at
bringing something like individual life to its collection of genre
stereotypes. You've definitely seen all these characters and their
problems before, but you haven't felt their pain this acutely in a
while.
</P>
<P>
   The battling Ortega brothers have been sparring on the Arizona
Silver Gloves circuit since they were old enough to stand up
without getting knocked down. That's because, of course, their
Mexican-born father Arturo (Jimmy Smits) could have been a
contender before he was injured, and he's directed all of his
vicarious vitality into training his three sons to become
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Arturo's determination often borders on child
abuse, although he thinks he's lovingly providing his progeny with
an invaluable advantage that will advance their status in the
world. As you might expect, the boys don't grow up quite like
Arturo hoped. Eldest Sonny (Jon Seda of ``Selena'' and TV's
``Homicide: Life on the Streets''), is the most talented, but he's
more interested in his personal life outside the ring. Middle man
Jimmy (Clifton Collins Jr.) is the worst fighter, but the most
eager for his father's oft-withheld approval _ and self-damagingly
resentful when he doesn't get it. Baby Johnny (Ernesto Hernandez)
is a natural brawler and daddy's boy all the way, right down to the
featherweight temper control.
</P>
<P>
   There's a sensible mom (Maria Del Mar) who fights a losing
battle to keep peace at home, does somewhat better at instilling
good values in the boys and manages to love Arturo in spite of his
moody excesses. There's an exploitative promoter and shady
underworld characters. The fight footage is fair to middling. There
is a wedding. There is a funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Along with all of these generic elements, ``Price of Glory''
boasts a few unique assets. The manner in which it presents the
Ortegas with both pinpoint specificity as a Mexican-American family
and in more universal detail without making a fussy deal either way
is refreshing and, more important, it adds much needed groundwork
of truth to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   And while all of the performances are worthy, and the younger
men certainly go the extra mile physically for their parts, Smits'
efforts to find the humanity in the tyrannical Arturo are most
impressive. Hateful as the guy often is, Smits does draw us deep
into his blinkered, selfishly well-meaning point of view. On the
few occasions when Arturo does see the error of his ways, Smits
makes us feel the impact, and often by nicely understated means.
</P>
<P>
   In a movie that's usually as subtle as a haymaker, those are
some sweet shots. &QL; 
________ &QL; 
The film: ``Price of Glory'' (PG-13; violence, language). &QL; 
The stars: Jimmy Smits, Jon Seda, Clifton Collins Jr., Ernesto
Hernandez, Maria Del Mar, Ron Perlman, Paul Rodriguez. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Carlos Avila. Written by Phil
Berger. Produced by Moctesuma Esparza, Robert Katz and Arthur E.
Friedman. Released by New Line Cinema. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 58 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
