<HEADLINE>
PATRONS HID IN BEER COOLER DURING TWISTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Customers in Angelo's Barbecue kept their
cool, if not their calm, as Tuesday's tornado tore over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rode it out in the beer cooler,'' cook Timmy Gil said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The storm struck just before the time when the dinner crowds
begin to arrive at Angelo's. The restaurant, a cavernous place on
White Settlement Road, just west of downtown, is possibly the most
popular barbecue spot in the city.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:15 p.m. CST, however, only about 25 patrons were gathered
near the bar. Gil was slicing brisket when he saw a group of
customers charging from the front door, shouting that a tornado was
heading straight toward them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `I'm heading to the cooler,' and they all
followed,'' said Gil.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the group of about 35 huddled in the back of the
chilly vault and listened to the increasing roar of the approaching
storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so scared I started cussing,'' said waitress Katy
McCorkle. ``I said a few choice words, then I realized nobody else
was making a sound and they were all listening to me. That
embarrassed me so much I got quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the frigid room waitress Carol Kreig was
pulling on a beer she had grabbed on her way in and trying to
ignore the increasing rumble overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the beer and my cigarettes 'cause I figured they might
be my last ones,'' said Kreig. ``I wanted everybody to sing so we
wouldn't have to hear that thing, so I started singing `Ninety-nine
Bottles of Beer on the Wall' 'cause it seemed appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I sang one chorus by myself and they all started yelling
at me to shut up, so I gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the cooler, one man remained in the dining area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to go in with everybody else, but I looked around
and thought `I've put 35 years in this place and, if it goes, I
think I'll just go with it,''' said owner ``Skeet'' George. ``So I
sat down and waited for it to hit, and it didn't. It jumped right
over us.''
</P>
<P>
   The tornado all but destroyed the Montgomery Wards building and
the Calvary Cathedral International a few blocks from Angelo's, but
left the restaurant undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must have stayed in that cooler about 20 minutes,'' said
Kreig. ``And, you know, I don't remember being cold.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
