<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN OFFICER CHARGED WITH KILLING A CHECHEN CIVILIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A Russian officer was charged Wednesday with killing a
civilian in Chechnya, a rare move by the Russian military to crack
down on human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of the Russian general staff, Gen. Anatoly Kvashnin,
informed Acting President Vladimir Putin of the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tank regiment commander, Colonel Budanov, humiliated a woman
citizen of Chechnya and then killed her,'' Kvashnin told the RTR
television network. He said Russia troops had apologized to the
woman's family and expressed regrets by attending her funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Although international human rights organizations have reported
numerous cases in which Chechens have been robbed, beaten, killed
and raped, there has been little or no action until now by the
authorities to bring the culprits to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a welcome step, but not a substitute for a thorough
investigation of the massacres that have been documented so far,''
said Rachel Denber, a deputy director at Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Curbing rights abuses is not only important for Russia's effort
to maintain smooth relations with the West, but also for its
longer-term effort to build credibility with the Chechen people and
win the peace.
</P>
<P>
   But peace, as Russians learned Wednesday, remained elusive. In a
deadly replay of recent clashes, Chechen rebels ambushed two
military units in the Chechen highlands.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, reported on state-owned television, undercut the
military's assertions that the war was virtually at an end and gave
new ammunition to some leaders who have begun to call for a
political solution to the 6-month-old war.
</P>
<P>
   The episode began when 41 militia members were traveling in a
convey near the mountain village of Zhani-Vedeno. The convoy was
attacked. When a rescue party went to the scene, it, too, was
ambushed.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said that they did not know how many soldiers
had been killed or wounded in the convoy and that 14 were wounded
in the 20-member rescue group.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin spokesman on Chechnya, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, said
Wednesday night that other forces were being dispatched to the area
and that Russian troops were using helicopters and artillery to
attack the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks were the latest in a series of setbacks for the
Russian military. They were especially embarrassing, because they
occurred during a visit by Interior Minister Vladimir B. Rushailo
to Chechnya to plan ways to capture rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And it seemed to set the stage for a new call by regional
leaders for a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Putin Wednesday, two leaders from the
northern Caucasus regions that border Chechnya again urged him to
open a dialogue with President Aslan Maskhadov of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a kind of envoy between Maskhadov's government and
Moscow,'' President Ruslan Aushev of Ingushetia said in remarks
broadcast on the state-owned television.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has refused to talk to Maskhadov, who was seen as a
relative moderate before Moscow mounted its offensive. But
Yastrzhembsky said on Wednesday that Maskhadov could be given
amnesty ``if it is proved that there is no blood on his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's military campaign, which has had broad public support
and has accounted in large measure for Putin's popularity, was
barely an issue in the recent presidential campaign. But the call
for a political solution to the war could pick up additional
support now that the election is over.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, Boris Nemtsov, a reform-minded leader
in a coalition called the Union of Right Forces, said his party had
decided that it was too politically costly to oppose the war during
the election campaign. But more reform politicians might begin to
speak up now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then to organize a big noise was inefficient,'' Nemtsov said
in an interview. ``Now I think it is the thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
