<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-WHITMAN-ART-NY     03-29 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-WHITMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN'S STAR BLINKS ON AND OFF IN GOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT20, 31 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ As Gov. Christie Whitman stood beside Texas Gov.
George W. Bush on Tuesday night, addressing the Somerset County
Republicans who helped give her political career its start nearly
20 years ago, there were those in the audience who could not help
but wonder about what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, made a
daylong stop in New Jersey to campaign and replenish his coffers as
he prepared for the general election. Whitman, whose most visible
role this presidential season has been to serve as a punching bag
for Gary L. Bauer and other conservatives who object to her support
of abortion rights, dutifully escorted Bush around the state and
gave several heartfelt speeches on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But to longtime supporters of Whitman, like Somerset County
Surrogate Patrick J. Fittipaldi, it was impossible not to think of
the days, not long ago, when it was Whitman who was considered
possible presidential material and Bush was just another governor
with a well-connected father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she would have brought a lot of balance to things,''
said Fittipaldi, who served as a freeholder with Whitman in the
early 1980s. ``She's conservative on some things, and open-minded.
She even would have mixed in a little bit of liberalism. But I
guess it just wasn't meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when she was chosen to make the nationally televised
rebuttal to President Clinton's State of the Union address, many
Republicans regarded Whitman as a rising power. She was fiscally
conservative, and she had kept her campaign promise to cut taxes.
She was also socially moderate, with a solid record on defending
gay rights, abortion rights and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   She was viewed as the kind of Republican who could attract
independents and women to the party.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, when Whitman vetoed a bill that would have banned
the late-term abortion procedure that opponents call ``partial
birth abortion,'' she became the Republican conservatives loved to
hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to know what happened to Whitman and Republicans,
it boils down to three words,'' said Gerald Pomper, a political
science professor at Rutgers University. ``Partial, birth and
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has since moved slightly to the right on abortion
rights. Last year, she signed a bill requiring parental
notification for girls under 18 to obtain an abortion _ the first
restriction on abortion rights she has ever enacted.
</P>
<P>
   But that shift has done little to soothe the anti-abortion
campaigners who would demonize Whitman as a liberal in Republican
clothing. During this year's Republican primary campaign, Bauer and
Steve Forbes criticized Whitman, spitting out her name as if it
were a synonym for social permissiveness and moral decay. In one of
the debates, Bauer even challenged Bush to assure Republican voters
that he would not choose Whitman as a running mate. Bush dodged the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Whitman has remained largely silent, supporting
Bush, but not in a way that would jeopardize his support among
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was practically the last Republican governor in the nation
to be allowed to show her support for Bush,'' said Tom Wilson,
campaign manager for Whitman's 1997 re-election effort. ``She puts
a good face on it publicly. But the way they've treated her,
there's also a part of her which tries to moderate the party, that
must think, `Don't shun me!'''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the ideologically charged primary campaign has ended,
moderate Republicans are urging Bush to move back toward the center
by making Whitman a more visible part of his campaign. Some Whitman
supporters even hold out the fleeting hope that she could still be
his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it was too early to consider a running mate and
sidestepped a question today about whether Whitman's support for
abortion rights would disqualify her. ``Good people can disagree on
the issue, and I understand that,'' Bush said. ``I mean, I'm
standing up here with a friend of mine. We disagree on some aspects
of the issue. That doesn't mean we can't be pulling for the same
thing, being on the same team.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's spokesman, Pete McDonough, said the governor would be
honored to be chosen as Bush's running mate, but considered it
unlikely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
