<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-SKYVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINERS WATCHED FROM 35TH FLOOR AS STORM APPROACHED
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TORNADO-TEXAS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SARAH LUNDAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Dramatic escapes were on the menu Tuesday
night at Reata, the well-known restaurant perched on the 35th floor
of the Bank One tower in downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The next course, cleaning up, could take weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When the sirens sounded, 100 guests and 40 staff members were in
the restaurant. Briefly, they had a bird's-eye view of the
approaching storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw stuff flying by, and then you saw this mass of
twisting debris coming at you,'' said Mike Evans, an owner of the
restaurant. ``And as it was coming, it was blowing out electrical
poles.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that evacuating the restaurant took just 45 seconds as
customers took shelter in a stairwell. Staff members had time to
shut off the gas, electricity and water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miracle that no one got hurt in that whole thing,'' he
said. ``It really hit us like nothing you've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The upscale restaurant, which specializes in Texas cowboy
cuisine, has a commanding view of the city from one of the highest
points in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the windows were blown out, and ceiling tiles and
furniture were tossed about. Carpets were soaked.
</P>
<P>
   Al Micallef, another restaurant owner, said damage is estimated
at $300,000. He said he hopes to reopen in about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Cherry, president of Dalcan Investments in Dallas, which
owns the building, said it will be many weeks before the building
reopens for tenants.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
