<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-HUNTER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTER ADVOCATES DEER-HUNTING HIATUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SAN DIMAS, Calif. _ It might be another six months before
hunters can take aim at deer in the San Gabriel Mountains, but one
hunter wants the next season to be held off for two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   Cancelling a hunting season might seem sacrilegious to some but
not to J.R. Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to postpone the season for two or three years,'' the
San Dimas resident said. ``This herd is down at least 70 percent
from the late '60s and we need to let them grow back.''
</P>
<P>
   But while wildlife officials admit the idea has merit, it is
also impractical; and a burgeoning mountain lion population is an
important part of the decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it would make much of a difference,'' said J. Bradford
Crow of Pasadena, a L.A. County Fish and Game commissioner. ``What
we have going on is the deer population is in such a sad degree and
there are a bunch of different reasons. One reason we're talking
about this is because of the mountain lion. They've eaten almost
all the deer and now there's nothing left for them to eat except
dogs and cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Mountain lions eat about two or three deer a month, according to
biologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been hunting in the San Gabriels since I was a kid and
there have been major changes,'' Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime hunter, who got a 110-pound field-dressed buck
above Rincon in San Gabriel Canyon last October, admitted mountain
lion predation has been a problem. But he also pointed to other
sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a lot more populated than 30 years ago,'' he said. ``It
used to be that we'd go up and if we didn't see five or six bucks
in one day, you weren't looking. Now when we go, we're lucky to see
one. I was up by Frazier Park (in Los Padres National Forest)
recently and we did not see a single deer. But we saw three
mountain lions. A lot of the deer have moved farther into the
mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodard advocates that the state should transplant deer into the
area, something all government officials say will never happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're seeing are bucks and doe that are no more than 2 or
3 years old,'' he said. ``Maybe we should import them from
somewhere else. There are so many deer in other states, it's
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Crow said he's had the same arguments with his cronies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just a lot less deer and I don't think the amount of
hunters that shoot them makes that much of a dent in the herds,''
Crow said.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Woodard's contentions was the 1999 season. The area's
antlered archery season was Sept. 25-Jan. 31. The regular season
was Sept. 4-26 and Oct. 9-Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be really hard for archers to get a deer, but with
these new composite bows, anyone can get one,'' said Woodard, who
at times has hunted with a bow and arrow. ``Their season is too
long. Four weeks for the general season is just right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
