u w BC-FLAG-DESECRATE-NYT &LR;      03-29 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-DESECRATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMENDMENT TO BAN FLAG BURNING FALLS SHORT IN SENATE BY 4 VOTES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following two days of heartfelt speeches about
patriotism and symbolism, the Senate Wednesday failed to approve a
constitutional amendment to give Congress the power to ban the
desecration of the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth time in 11 years that the Senate had taken up
the question, and each time supporters of the flag measure failed
to collect the 67 votes needed to pass such an amendment.
Wednesday's bipartisan tally was 63-37, four votes short of the
threshold. The last time around, in 1995, the proposal ended three
votes shy of passing.
</P>
<P>
   Although flag burning has been on the wane since the war
protests of the 1960s, supporters of the amendment argue that a
single desecrated flag is one too many, a view that public opinion
surveys say jibes with that of most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is illogical for the Senate to ignore the feelings of the
overwhelming number of Americans who support flag protection,''
said Sen. Orrin G. Hatch of Utah, the Republican chairman of the
Judiciary Committee. He sponsored the amendment and said he would
revive it another year. ``The flag is not just a piece of cloth or
a symbol. It is the embodiment of our heritage, our liberties and
indeed our sovereignty as a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate remains the final stumbling block to a constitutional
amendment banning flag burning. Last year, 305 House members voted
for the amendment, well beyond the two-thirds needed. Every state
but Vermont has passed measures expressing support for an amendment
that protects the flag. A constitutional amendment requires
approvals by three-quarters of the states' legislatures after it
clears Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional amendment Wednesday was intended to
circumvent a 1989 Supreme Court ruling that said flag burning was a
protected form of political speech. The proposed amendment stated:
``The Congress shall have power to prohibit the physical
desecration of the flag of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court's failure to act responsibly on this issue
leaves us no other means to protect this symbol,'' Sen. Trent Lott
of Mississippi, the majority leader, said on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, burning the flag is not speech,'' he added.
``It is conduct of the most offensive kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve Democrats supported the amendment and four Republicans
opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of debate, the amendment's opponents received
an important boost from two Democrats, significantly Robert Byrd of
West Virginia, a senior member of the Senate who is known for his
knowledge of the intricacies of the Constitution and of Senate
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the Senate floor, Byrd stated solemnly that he would
reverse his previous endorsement of the flag amendment _ which he
said had resulted from ``shock'' over the Supreme Court decision _
and would now oppose the measure. The decision, he said, came after
days of research and of discussion with Constitutional scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of few subjects that have come before the Senate that
have given me greater anguish,'' said Byrd, who first made his
announcement on Tuesday before a group of American Legionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Byrd said, he concluded the amendment did not fit
the confines of the Constitution and would serve to debase it, just
as the constitutional amendment on Prohibition had, before it was
repealed.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said he rejected the flag-burning amendment for several
reasons: such acts are not pervasive, an amendment would only
encourage them and flag desecration could already be dealt with
under existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``That flag is the symbol of our nation,'' Byrd said. ``That
flag is the symbol of our nation's history. That flag is the symbol
of our nation's values. We love that flag. But we must love the
Constitution more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., also changed his position after long
deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   With military veterans standing at the center of the debate,
both sides produced the words of their own war heroes to buttress
their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch cited a letter by Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf, who commanded
the troops during the Persian Gulf war. ``The flag remains the
single, pre-eminent connection among all Americans,'' the general
wrote in a letter dated April 5, 1999. ``It represents our basic
commitment to each other and to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats quickly brandished their own letter from a war
hero, from Gen. Colin Powell, and pointed out that a diminishing
number of veterans saw a need for an amendment. ``I will not amend
that great shield of democracy to hammer a few miscreants,'' Powell
wrote on May 18, 1999. ``The flag will still be flying proudly long
after they have slunk away.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight over flag-burning has changed little over the years.
Supporters of the amendment argue that the flag is a unique symbol
that binds the country, one that men and women have died to
protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who has traded the life of a loved one for a flag,
folded at a funeral,'' Hatch said. ``Let's think about that trade _
and about the people who made that trade for us _ before deciding
whether the flag is important enough to be addressed in the
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Those on the other side of the debate maintain that an
individual's right to free speech, including the right to burn a
flag, is paramount. If the Senate approved the measure, they
argued, it would be following the example of such notorious
countries as Iraq, Iran, Libya and Nazi Germany, which banned flag
desecration.
</P>
<P>
   ``A desecrated flag is replaceable,'' said Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., a decorated Vietnam War veteran. ``Desecrated rights are
lost forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
