<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-WILLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES CLINTON VIOLATED WILLEY'S PRIVACY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge said Wednesday that President
Clinton and top aides intentionally violated federal privacy laws
by releasing personal letters from Kathleen Willey to undermine the
credibility of her sexual-misconduct claims against the president.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion was mentioned in a memorandum from U.S. District
Judge Royce Lamberth, a Republican appointee, ordering presidential
aides to respond to queries from Judicial Watch, a conservative
group spearheading a civil lawsuit against the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton disputed the finding, saying he had been reluctant to
release the letters from Willey but did so two years ago because
``it was the only way I knew to refute allegations'' that he had
groped her during a private meeting in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   White House Counsel Beth Nolan said Lamberth's order would be
appealed. ``We are confident it will be overturned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Unless reversed, Lamberth's decision clears the way for Judicial
Watch and its clients to question White House aides about how
Willey's letters to Clinton were made public in 1998 in the midst
of the Monica Lewinsky sex-and-perjury scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch and its clients ``have sufficiently established
that the White House and president were aware that they were
subject to the Privacy Act, and yet chose to violate its
provisions'' by releasing the letters, Lamberth wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court cannot accept or condone this unlawful action,''
said Lamberth, who has allowed Judicial Watch's legal team wide
latitude in examining whether the Clinton White House compiled
dossiers of damaging information for use against political
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lamberth's decision Wednesday allows Judicial Watch to
delve into the letters, Willey, the Democratic activist and former
White House volunteer, is not a party to the lawsuit. The suit was
filed on behalf of former employees of the Reagan and Bush
administrations over the White House's gathering of hundreds of FBI
files on Republican appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton approved the release of Willey's letters the day after
her appearance on CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes'' in which she accused him
of fondling her during a meeting in 1993. Her allegation was made
as the president was scrambling to keep secret his affair with
Lewinsky, a coverup that eventually led to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The letters, written by Willey after her Oval Office encounter
with Clinton, spoke of him in glowing terms and appeared to some
presidential supporters to cast doubt on Willey's claim that she
was offended and upset by Clinton's alleged behavior. The president
denied making any improper advances toward Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lamberth told Clinton's lawyers nine months before
Willey's letters were released that the White House is required to
abide by the Privacy Act, Clinton on Wednesday said the subject
never came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the decision was made to release those letters, I didn't
even have any conversation with anybody about the Privacy Act,''
Clinton said during a White House press conference.
</P>
<P>
   In his order, Lamberth said three White House attorneys who
advised Clinton about releasing the letters _ longtime confidant
Bruce Lindsey, former White House Counsel Charles Ruff and former
Deputy White House Counsel Cheryl Mills _ also may have violated
the act.
</P>
<P>
   Violation of the Privacy Act is a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth's ruling came amid calls for the Justice Department to
investigate reports of missing White House e-mail relating to the
Lewinsky scandal. Justice already is examining possible wrongdoing
in the failure of White House officials to turn over computer
records sought in conjunction with a campaign finance investigation
by congressional committees and a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, White House spokesman Jim Kennedy downplayed
reports that a previously undisclosed computer disk had turned up
containing e-mails from Lewinsky to two confidants while her affair
with Clinton was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand it simply contains duplicative e-mails that were
already examined in 1998,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The disk reportedly has copies of e-mail correspondence between
Lewinsky and the two friends, both of whom testified before a
federal grand jury _ presidential secretary Betty Curry and White
House aide Ashley Raines.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department also is investigating the release of
information damaging to the reputation of another Clinton critic _
Linda Tripp. Data from her personnel file at the Pentagon was
provided to a reporter during the investigation that led to
Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Maryland judge said she would rule in May whether
Tripp would be tried on charges of violating the state's
wiretapping laws when she tape-recorded conversations with
Lewinsky. The tapes, which provided the basis of the impeachment
investigation of Clinton, included Lewinsky's description of their
affair and discussions of an attempt to defy court orders in an
effort to keep it secret.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
