<SLUG> BC-GEN-UNIBEAT-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES KNOW MATADORS CAN BITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Respect is evident, but can it translate into
victories?
</P>
<P>
   Men's volleyball opponents recognize that Cal State Northridge
no longer is a pushover. UCLA lost. Pepperdine won the fifth game
16-14. USC won the fifth game 21-19.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Matadors, while ranked 11th in the USA Today/American
Volleyball Coaches Association poll, are 8-12 (4-10 in the Mountain
Pacific Sports Federation) heading into Wednesday's match with UC
Irvine. They have by far the worst record of any top-15 team.
</P>
<P>
   One reason: Northridge no longer can sneak up on unsuspecting
teams.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, the Matadors went into Wooden Center and shocked
UCLA for just the third time in 42 matches. Less than a week later,
they almost shocked Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   That's no longer the case. Pepperdine won in four games last
week. Now, fourth-ranked UCLA gets its second chance Friday night
at 7 at Northridge, a place where they haven't lost in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be super-focused,'' CSUN coach Jeff Campbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   How right he is. UCLA watched tape of Northridge this week,
looking for sideout preferences. Northridge doesn't have time to
focus on UCLA because of the Irvine match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double-edged sword,'' Campbell said. ``You're
legitimate and you've got teams that are no longer taking you
lightly. If they do, they're going to lose. It means we're getting
better.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA (21-3, 11-3 MPSF), meanwhile, will sport a different look
on Friday: Setter Brandon Taliaferro will play. Taliaferro missed
the last CSUN match with back injuries. Now, he's playing with four
degenerative discs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandon knows the offense,'' UCLA coach Al Scates said.
``Brandon leads the nation in aces with 42 in 62 games. That's
amazing. We score a lot of points when Brandon serves.''
</P>
<P>
   __ On the track: USC hosts one of the top four-way meets in the
country Saturday. Beside the Trojans, Nebraska, North Carolina and
Louisiana State will compete at 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   So far, USC has several athletes who have qualified for the NCAA
meet. Triple jumper Djeke Mambo has leaped 53 feet, 10 inches,
second-best in school history. Hammer throwers Szabolcs Maroti
(225-10) and Dagan Massey (204-7) also have qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Three football players have provisionally qualified: Sultan
McCullough in the 100 meters (10.26), Kareem Kelly in the 100
(10.33) and Marcell Allmond in the decathlon (7,152 points).
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, defending NCAA 100-meter champion Angela
Williams has secured a berth in the 400 relay, joining Candace
Young, Malika Edmonson and Kinshasa Davis in running 43.76,
fourth-best in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska has won four of the last six men's Big 12 Conference
titles and 19 of the past 21 women's. North Carolina is the
defending ACC men's champion, and the women finished third in the
recent NCAA Indoor Championships. LSU returns five All-America men.
</P>
<P>
   __ USC vs. UCLA tennis: The men meet Friday at USC, for the
157th time. UCLA (14-2) is ranked first nationally and is led by
Jean-Noel Grinda, last year's national runner-up. But Grinda has a
shoulder injury and is 2-2 in singles this season. He remains
effective in doubles, where he teams with Jean-Julien Rojer for a
10-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   The big matchup is UCLA's Jong-Min Lee and Brandon Kramer,
ranked fourth, against sixth-ranked Ryan Moore and Nic Rainey.
</P>
<P>
   USC (12-5) is 19th and looks to senior Patrick Gottesleben,
ranked 40th, to lead. He'll battle Lee, ranked 26th.
</P>
<P>
   The USC women are ranked seventh and play at No. 8 UCLA on
Saturday at noon. This is the 52nd time these two teams have met.
</P>
<P>
   USC senior Jacqui Boyd has won 11 consecutive singles matches.
Freshman Jewel Peterson, at No. 8, is the team's highest-ranked
player. She'll battle Sara Walker, at No. 6, in a can't-miss battle
of freshman phenoms. Walker is also ranked ninth in doubles when
teaming with Amanda Basica.
</P>
</TEXT>
