<HEADLINE>
ON BUSH, PATAKI AND GIULIANI AGREE TO AGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three weeks after winning a presidential primary that
exposed new fissures in New York's Republican Party, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas returned to the state Wednesday, attending a
fund-raiser with a party establishment that tried to demonstrate
that it had put its bickering behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who before the
primary had publicly disagreed over the Bush campaign's strategy in
New York, took the stage at a Manhattan hotel to praise Bush and
one another. Bush hailed his ``long and steadfast'' friendship with
Pataki and said he appreciated the ``reform-minded agenda'' of
Giuliani, who is running for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But the three men did not pose for the customary
hands-clasped-together-in-solidarity photo at the fund-raiser,
which netted roughly $500,000 for the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bush visited a charter school in Newark,
N.J., with New Jersey's governor, Christie Whitman. He was asked at
a news conference whether he could choose a running mate who, like
Whitman, backed abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   He responded that he was not yet focusing on the makeup of the
ticket. But, he added: ``Good people can disagree on the issue, and
I understand that. I mean, I'm standing up here with a friend of
mine. We disagree on some aspects of the issue. That doesn't mean
we can't be pulling for the same thing _ being on the same team.
And I respect Governor Whitman's views and I respect her as a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani showed fealty to Bush, the mayor gave no
indication that he wanted Bush's help in the Senate race in New
York, which tends to skew Democratic in presidential contests.
Giuliani is to campaign next month with Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, who lost in the primaries to Bush, suggesting that
Giuliani believes that he has more to gain aligning himself with
the acknowledged loser than the putative standard-bearer.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, appears
to consider Bush a liability for Giuliani, and she is trying to
link the two in her attacks on the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York primary, Giuliani endorsed Bush, but he
criticized Pataki, who led the Bush campaign in New York, for
running negative commercials against McCain. Polls show that McCain
was relatively popular with Democrats and independents, who could
not vote in the New York primary but obviously can in November.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the fund-raiser about Bush, Giuliani's campaign
manager, Bruce J. Teitelbaum, said: ``The mayor was with John
McCain last night in Washington. He was with Governor Bush today in
New York, and of course looks forward to campaigning with Senator
McCain and Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush declined to get entangled in the Senate race
beyond expressing his general support for Giuliani. At the news
conference in Newark, he was asked about Giuliani's criticism that
Clinton has not adequately reimbursed the federal government for
her campaign travel aboard government planes. ``I don't have an
opinion,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raiser, Bush, besides a few lines about Pataki,
Giuliani and other state Republicans, offered his standard stump
speech without tailoring it to the state. ``I will proudly wave our
banner of compassionate conservatism all across the land,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There was one unexpected bit of local color: A few death-penalty
protesters briefly interrupted his speech before being removed by
security officers. Bush staunchly favors the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Bush began his day with a breakfast with Archbishop Theodore
McCarrick of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Newark. Bush has
sought to court Catholic voters in the wake of controversy over his
South Carolina visit to Bob Jones University, whose leaders have
espoused anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   Bush then visited the Newark charter school, the North Star
Academy, which has a predominantly black student body. Bush, who
believes the federal government should help create more charter
schools, said the academy represented the kind of local innovation
he hoped to foster. ``Had we tried to invent North Star at the
federal government, they'd still be in committee hearings,'' Bush
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
