<HEADER>
A1691 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CUSACK-LADN &LR;      03-29 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK OF ALL TRADES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Cusack loves music. Sinatra, Mozart, the Cramps _ you name
it, he'll have an opinion about it. He prefers LPs to CDs, knows
the locations of the best record stores around the world and has
already picked out what song he wants to be played at his funeral
(Jimmy Cliff's ``Many Rivers to Cross,'' unless he changes his mind
again).
</P>
<P>
   Cusack's appreciation for music was evident in ``Grosse Point
Blank,'' the charmingly offbeat 1997 film that he co-wrote and
co-produced under his New Crime Productions banner. Clash frontman
Joe Strummer scored the movie, and the soundtrack, a nice sampler
of Reagan-era pop music, continues to be a big seller to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack's latest film, ``High Fidelity,'' continues along the
same path. Cusack and his Evanston, Ill., pals Steve Pink and D.V.
DeVincentis have again written the screenplay, adapting Nick
Hornby's novel about a music junkie trying to figure out women. The
film, which is often set in a barely functioning record store,
features 65 different songs, ranging from classic rock to cult
bands like the Thirteenth Floor Elevators and the Beta Band.
</P>
<P>
   Here we talk to the 33-year-old Cusack about his feelings for
rock, ``Crocodile'' and otherwise, his proclivity for wearing Clash
T-shirts in his films and why music always seems to sound better in
a record store.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did you discover music?
</P>
<P>
   A: As soon as my sister (actress Joan Cusack) allowed me into
her room to play 45s on her turntable. There was no turning back
after that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of stuff did your parents listen to?
</P>
<P>
   A: They would listen to classical and stuff like Gladys Knight
and the Pips and Sinatra. But nothing modern. We'd introduce stuff
to my dad and he'd say, ``Where was I?'' I remember when I got out
of high school, I told him, ``You've got to listen to Bob Dylan.''
He had never heard one of his records.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do your tastes run?
</P>
<P>
   A: All over the map. There's something satisfying about
listening to classical music and then there's something equally
satisfying about listening to music that sounds like it was made in
a concrete bunker underwater with some tape rolling. It makes no
difference, as long as it's got soul creeping through it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``High Fidelity'' features some pretty heated debates among
the three guys working in the record store. Did you and your
co-writers get into the same kind of arguments?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, the battles were huge. It was a war. It was just like in
the book. We'd talk about music and each one of us was absolutely
right beyond a question of a doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the biggest fights about?
</P>
<P>
   A: What 65 songs we'd have in the movie. If it were up to those
guys, we would have limited it more to these specialized bands that
nobody knows. Don't get me wrong. I love those groups, but there
comes a point where you have to broaden the range and include songs
for people who don't know as much about music.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Like Elton John's ``Crocodile Rock''?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Grimacing) That was (director) Stephen Frears' choice. I
hate that song with a passion to this day, but he liked the faux
innocence of it to match the scene it's in. And that's OK. It's not
that big of a deal. But at the time for us, including ``Crocodile
Rock,'' was a travesty and we made a great big stink about it:
``You can't! You can't!'' That's how obsessive we were about the
music in this movie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Any song you wanted in that didn't make the cut?
</P>
<P>
   A: There was this one Warren Zevon song that I thought was
perfect, but nobody else felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you remember your first concert?
</P>
<P>
   A: I went to a simulcast of the Who just after Kenny Jones
joined them. The first concert that blew off the back of my head
was Fishbone. Back in the day, those guys were great. They were so
ahead of their time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've worn Clash T-shirts in a few of your films. That had
to be another favorite band.
</P>
<P>
   A: Definitely. But I started out listening to ELO, KISS and
Cheap Trick. I guess you'd consider them guilty pleasures, but
those were the bands that I cut my teeth on. You know, when you're
13, 14 years old and you want to figure out what's radical and you
realize you can be an individual and buy stuff that your parents
don't like.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And what was your parents' reaction?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think, like all parents, they didn't understand what the
hell we were listening to. There was this store in Chicago, Rick's
Record Exchange, that's just like Championship Vinyl (the record
store in the movie). I used to go there every day after school and
listen to music.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You must have a pretty fair collection.
</P>
<P>
   A: You'd think. But I don't collect. I have things and then they
go away. I don't have a place where things stay. It's probably
because I'm so disorganized. I'll grab a CD to go somewhere and
I'll leave it in somebody's car. I'll go out and buy stuff ...
</P>
<P>
   Q: But you just won't hold onto it.
</P>
<P>
   A: Right. I mean, I'll be in a record store and hear something
great, buy it, listen to it for a while and then it's gone. But in
my head, I'll have it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why does music always sound better when you're listening to
it in a record store?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a good question. It's true. I've bought albums I've
heard in stores and then when I listen to them again, I wonder what
the hell I was thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because everybody goes to a record store hoping to
find that piece of treasure and you have all that energy around
you. It's almost a sacred observance. Everybody's kind of serious
when they're in a record store. You know what I mean? There's this
undercurrent of focus where people are looking, looking, searching
for something.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the last treasure you've found?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's this band called Ozomatli. The music is like a
cross-cultural block party.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And you say you agree with your ``High Fidelity'' character
that Jimmy Cliff's ``Many Rivers to Cross'' would be your funeral
song?
</P>
<P>
   A: That would do just fine. (Pause) But then again ... actually
... nah, I'd probably want Bob Marley. He'd turn it into a party.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It doesn't usually turn out that way despite the best of
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   A: It doesn't, does it? Maybe we could start with Cliff and
segue into Marley. You've got to give it a try.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
