<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKATING-PAIRS-BOS &LR;      03-29 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATING-PAIRS-BOS </SLUG>
  
 FRENCH BRING PAIRS TITLE HOME
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   NICE, France _ It was, simply put, the most bizarre pairs event
in world figure skating history.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time defending champions withdrew on Sunday after
testing positive for a banned drug last month. Stephane Bernardis
opened his hotel door Tuesday and was slashed on the arm by an
unknown man while his bodyguard was shopping with his partner.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Bernardis and Sarah Abitbol came back to win
France's first pairs medal in 68 years. A Ukrainian skater tripped
on a lift, whacked his head on the ice, and was wheeled off
unconscious to the hospital. And the second-string Russians rose to
beat the favored Chinese _ and heard the Ukrainian anthem played
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too much to think about,'' said Alexei Tikhonov after he
and partner Maria Petrova defeated Shen Xue and Zhao Hongbo to
bring the gold medal back to the motherland for the fourth time in
five years and the 30th time in the last 36. ``We are very
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Elena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze were pulled out by
the Russian federation after her doping sample at the European
championships turned up ephedrine from bronchial medication, the
Chinese figured to win the pairs title for the first time. But Shen
and Zhao felt the squeeze and skated flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we didn't skate so good,'' conceded Zhao after he and
Shen had settled for silver again. ``I think it was because we were
too nervous. This time, we want to win too much. There was too much
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   There was too much squeeze, too, on Canada's Jamie Sale and
David Pelletier, who had a lovely chance to win a bronze medal in
their global debut. But Sale double-footed her triple toe loop and
singled both double axels and the Canadians missed the podium by
one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sport is life,'' said Pelletier with a shrug after Sale wept
in the kiss-and-cry area. ``This is nothing compared to what life
can bring you. We're going back with heads high. We're fourth in
the world. Last year, we were nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Abitbol and Bernadis thought they had a fine shot at the podium
until Bernadis had his arm opened nearly from wrist to biceps by an
assailant's razor. The wound turned out to be more psychological
than physical, but Bernadis was stung by whispers that he'd
concocted a fairy tale to garner sympathy from judges and a home
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you saw on the ice was the truth and my injury is the
truth, too, as you can see,'' Bernadis declared, ripping off the
bandage to show the gash after he and Abitbol had claimed their
country's first pairs medal since Andree and Pierre Brunet won gold
in 1932. ``Sarah and I have proved we are great champions tonight.
We gave what we had.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if the evening had lacked drama. Ninety minutes
earlier, Dmitri Palamarchuk fell while hoisting partner Julia
Obertas and lay prostrate on the ice. It was a frightening reminder
of last autumn's horrifying practice tumble by US pairs skater Paul
Binnebose, who fractured his skull, nearly died in the hospital,and
is still undergoing therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the event's medical staff merely yanked Palamarchuk to his
feet and slapped his face when he grew woozy as he walked off the
ice. After Palamarchuk fainted and was out cold for five minutes,
he was brought to the nearby Hospital St. Roch and kept overnight
for observation.
</P>
<P>
   While Palamarchuk was still on the ice, officials shouted at
Canada's Kristy Sargeant and Kris Wirtz to warm up. ``It was hard
on me,'' said Sargeant. ``I saw it happen. I saw him come by me on
the stretcher. But there was nothing we could do. We had to
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaken, Sargeant and Wirtz botched their first two elements and
asked for a reskate, but were told by referee Alexander Lakernik to
pick up where they left off.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Americans seemed exempt from the craziness. Kyoko Ina
and John Zimmerman ended up a disappointed seventh after each
missed a jump. ``The stars weren't aligned for us tonight,'' said
Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   But Tiffany Scott of Hanson, Mass., and partner Philip Dulebohn
were delighted with a ninth place effort in their global debut.
``Top 10 was our goal,'' said Scott. ``As long as we got a single
digit, we were going to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day Russia's Irina Slutskaya, making her first
world appearance in two years, easily won her qualifying group
ahead of the US rivals Michelle Kwan and Sarah Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little nervous here because I didn't skate last
year,'' said the 21-year-old Slutskaya, who didn't make the Russian
team then after winning the silver behind Kwan in 1998. ``When you
go on the ice, it's difficult. It's like the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 19-year-old Kwan, who lost her world crown to Russia's
Maria Butyrskaya last year and finished behind Slutskaya at this
season's Grand Prix final, this is the week of redemption. She
hasn't skated without error at a major event since the 1998
Olympics in Nagano and was irked at herself Wednesday for doubling
the back end of her triple-triple combination and then popping her
triple salchow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to get tougher inside, and that goes for the whole
performance,'' said the two-time world champ, who's been juggling
skating and her UCLA studies this season. ``I keep on saying that.
But I have to turn it on and do it and stop saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a solid day for the Americans, who skated in the
tougher of the two groups. Hughes, who finished seventh last year
at 13, didn't land a triple-triple combo (she usually does two),
but pronounced herself satisfied. ``Same as any round,'' Hughes
said. ``Just go and skate your best. You need to qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 27-year-old Butyrskaya, the world's oldest female
titlist, Wednesday was a walkthrough. Even though she staggered in
mid-combination and touched down on her double axel, it was more
than enough to dominate a bunch of Ukrainians, Uzbeks, and Poles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quite relaxed because I was in the easier group,'' said
Butyrskaya, who lost the Russian, European, and Grand Prix titles
to the resurgent Slutskaya this season. ``This is OK for
qualifying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
