<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, MARCH 30
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CLINTON-TOBACCO-NYT (moved on Saturday, March 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, March
25, about President Clinton's radio address on the regulation of
tobacco misstated the House title and ranking of Representative
J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, who said the Food and Drug Administration
could not handle an added workload. He is the fourth-ranking
Republican, not the third. And he heads the Republican caucus; he
is not the whip.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COLO-OWENS-RAMSEY-NYT (moved on Friday, March 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, March 24,
about comments by Gov. Bill Owens of Colorado on the JonBenet
Ramsey killing, and their effect on his legislative influence,
referred incorrectly in some copies to the progress of education
measures he backed. The education package had not passed by then;
the Legislature adopted them on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-SUIT-NYT (moved on Tuesday, March 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, March 28,
about the legal dispute between Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and the
Brooklyn Museum of Art over its ``Sensation'' exhibition
erroneously included one category among the city-supported members
of the Cultural Institutions Group. Its members include museums,
zoos, theaters, historic societies and botanic gardens, but not
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCOTUS-IMMIG-NYT (moved on Monday, March 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, March 27,
about a complaint that lawsuits over New York City's handling of
First Amendment issues have burdened the federal courts misstated
the number of judges who made the complaint. It was one, not two.
Judge Guido Calabresi of the United States Court of Appeals for the
Second Circuit made the criticism in a decision in a case involving
an artist's plans to photograph nude models on a city street. While
Judge Robert D. Sack concurred in the outcome of the decision, he
did not join in the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BANKONE-DIMON-NYT (moved on Monday, March 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, March 27,
about the appointment of James Dimon as chairman and chief
executive of Bank One misstated the amount of the company's stock
he said he planned to buy. It is two million shares, not $2 million
worth.
</P>
</TEXT>
