<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: GERMANY, FRANCE, RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: COPING WITH REFUGEES
</P>
<P>
   To cope with more than 1,000 requests for political asylum every
month, the government is to spend $86 million to build temporary
housing for 8,000 refugees. The accommodations will include
so-called flotels, housing blocks on barges moored in ports. Most
of the refugees come from Eastern Europe and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: IRA REBUFF
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein's president, Gerry Adams, rebuffed a call for an Irish
Republican Army declaration that violence is ended in the province,
saying the request from the Northern Ireland secretary, Peter
Mandelson, was ``an absolute nonsense.'' Adams said the only way to
guarantee that war did not break out again was to restore home rule
government, suspended after the IRA, which Sinn Fein represents,
failed to begin disarming.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN: POPE RECALLS TRIP
</P>
<P>
   Calling it ``an unforgettable experience,'' John Paul II
declared at his weekly audience at St. Peter's that his historic
pilgrimage to the Holy Land was ``this gift from God that I had
hoped for so long.'' The pope, who was bombarded by Israeli and
Palestinian leaders' competing claims to Jerusalem, called it ``the
city of peace for all peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   BULGARIA, ROMANIA: DANUBE BRIDGE
</P>
<P>
   After nine years of negotiations, Bulgaria and Romania agreed on
the site for a new bridge over the Danube River. The bridge, near
Vidin, Bulgaria, will allow truck and rail traffic from Greece and
Turkey to reach Western Europe without crossing Serbia. It will
take about three years to build and cost $200 million, much of it
in European Union aid.
</P>
<P>
   NORWAY: ATHIESTS, LOUD AND CLEAR
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to come up with a solution to a religious dispute,
Oslo will allow Muslims to broadcast calls for worship once a week,
and permit atheists using megaphones to proclaim once a week, ``God
does not exist!'' Jan Willy Lyng. a city councillor, said of the
atheists' demand, ``To give fair treatment we had to say yes, but I
don't really think these atheists actually will climb on the roof
and shout too often.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: PRESIDENTIAL DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   The three leading presidential candidates have agreed to two
debates before the July 2 vote, their representatives said. All six
registered candidates will take part in the first, on April 25.
Only the three leading candidates, Francisco Labastida, Vicente Fox
and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, will debate in the second encounter on May
23.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: GIs PULLING OUT
</P>
<P>
   American troops will end their relief mission this week. The
troops, who arrived with helicopters and emergency supplies, have
transported over 1,100 flood victims and moved more than 1.5
million pounds of food and other supplies since March 6.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: VERDICT DUE
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers concluded final arguments in the two-month
hijacking trial of the ousted prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, and
Judge Rehmat Hussain Jafri said he ``will try to announce the
judgment on April 6.'' Sharif, his brother Shahbaz and five others
face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: U.S. TALKS
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger,
met with senior Chinese officials for talks aimed at improving
tattered relations. Chinese leaders urged the United States to
press Taiwan's newly elected president to accept the principle of
``one China,'' according to the New China News Agency, and to avoid
deeper military ties with Taiwan. The Americans did not comment on
the talks, which end Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG: BACKING CHINA
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa is joining the lobbying campaign
for the setting up of normal trade relations between China and the
United States. Tung plans to travel to Washington on April 6 to
meet with administration officials and legislators. Although he
said his main purpose was to promote Hong Kong, Tung said he would
try to persuade members of Congress of the advantages of making
China a full member of the club of trading nations.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: WARNING TO U.N.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, which has barred a visit by the chairman of the Security
Council's Iraqi sanctions committee, said he would not be welcome
until he ``behaved.'' Baghdad demanded in effect that Peter van
Walsum, the Dutch ambassador to the United Nations, lift holds on
contracts under review by the committee. Van Walsum reminded the
council in a debate on the effects of sanctions that he has been
denied the right to witness the situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
