<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIGER-MARKETPLACE-NYT     03-29 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGER-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE:   A ONCE-HIGHFLYING HEDGE FUND APPEARS LIKELY TO SHUT
DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (cjl) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Undone recently by bad bets on old-economy stocks,
Julian H. Robertson Jr. is closing his Tiger Management investment
company, according to someone close to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, 67, who is revered for his long-term record as an
investor, appears to be succumbing to rapid change in the world
financial markets. At his peak two years ago, he had $23 billion
under management at Tiger, which runs six different investment
pools known as hedge funds, putting him on a par with George Soros,
the hedge fund manager known for his big currency bets.
</P>
<P>
   But a combination of investment losses and heavy withdrawals
have left Tiger a shadow of its former self. About $900 million
will be distributed to investors who have requested redemptions as
the first quarter ends on Friday, leaving the company with just
$5.2 billion in assets, according to the person close to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   In the last couple of years, Robertson has been on the wrong
side of a series of big investment bets. The first was a $600
million loss in the fall of 1998 when Russia defaulted on its debt.
It was followed by a $1 billion loss on the Japanese yen later that
year.
</P>
<P>
   Retreating then from global bets as many other hedge fund
managers did, Robertson refocused on beaten-down stocks in the old
economy, shares of US Airways Group, Bowater Inc. and Sealed Air
Corp. Those stocks, too, have proved disappointing, continuing to
lag far behind the white-hot technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to shareholders earlier this year, Robertson wrote:
``We are in a market where reason does not prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of Tiger's demise have raced through Wall Street before.
But with Robertson's funds down about 13 percent so far this year
after a 19 percent decline last year, the person said, the end
seemed not just plausible but likely Wednesday. A hedge fund
manager who declined to be identified said, ``It's hard to come
back from being down that far.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser Seitel, a Tiger spokesman, said Wednesday: ``Tiger is not
commenting on the rumors. Tiger's investors have not been notified
about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Robertson nor Philip Duff, Tiger's chief operating
officer, returned phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   A native of North Carolina, Robertson spent much of his career
as a stockbroker and money manager at Kidder, Peabody. But in 1980,
he left to found Tiger, taking a name suggested by one of his young
sons.
</P>
<P>
   With $2 million of his own money and $6 million in outside
investments, Tiger surged from the start. Until 1998, it lost money
in only one year, 1987, the year the stock market crashed. In
several years, returns exceeded 40 percent. Even after the tough
years of 1998 and 1999, the Tiger Fund had a 27 percent average
annual gain since its inception almost 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Robertson started five additional funds,
available only to wealthy individuals. The Jaguar and Puma Funds
were opened in 1986, the Lion Fund and two Ocelot funds in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the unwinding of Long Term Capital Management, Tiger's
unraveling did not rattle world financial markets. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 82.61 points on the day, while the Nasdaq
lost 3.91 percent. Shares in some of the stocks that Robertson is
known to own were weak.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways, in which Tiger had a 25 percent stake at the end of
the year, slipped 43.8 cents Wednesday to $25.438. According to
end-of-year filings, Tiger's big positions included UAM, the fund
management company in which it owned nearly 15 percent; Sealed Air
at 7 percent and the Bear Stearns Cos. at almost 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because Robertson has lost so much money in recent years, the
remaining assets could no longer generate enough fees to cover
operating expenses, according to a person close to the firm. As is
the case with other hedge funds, Robertson's clients pay incentive
fees of 20 percent to the manager only if their gains exceed what
is called a high-water mark. Because of that threshold, Robertson's
recent losses meant that he would have to be up 85 percent this
year to generate any incentive fees, according to the person close
to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, given that roughly $2 billion of the $5.2 billion
remaining at Tiger is said to belong to Robertson and his
colleagues, the $3 billion from outside investors would not
generate enough in management fees _ 1 percent annually _ to pay
for operations at the firm's elegant New York, London and Tokyo
offices.
</P>
<P>
   One thorny issue in the closing of Tiger is related to
Robertson's incentive fees, which have been kept offshore where
they compound tax-free until the funds are repatriated, according
to a source. This person said Robertson might have a $200 million
tax liability on those fees.
</P>
<P>
   While shutting Tiger Management seems to signal the end of an
era for Robertson, his legacy runs up and down Wall Street. Indeed,
13 hedge funds, known as Tiger Cubs, are run by Tiger alumni. Last
year, all but one of these funds had positive returns.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, even as word of Tiger's woes was once again
seeping into the markets, Robertson was honored at a reception in
New York held by a group of former Tiger managers. At the event,
the managers announced that they had made a gift to the University
of Virginia in Robertson's name. At the celebration and among old
friends, Robertson was near tears, someone in attendance said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
