r a BC-TORNADO-NEIGHBORHOODS     03-29 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-NEIGHBORHOODS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD-HIT NEIGHBORHOODS CLEAN UP, TAKE STOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE LEE 
and REBECA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Linwood neighborhood of mostly small
wooden rental houses, tucked in the shadow of the Montgomery Ward
building, appeared to sustain the worst tornado damage outside the
city center.
</P>
<P>
   In many places along Mercedes Avenue and Merrimac Street, homes
were shattered, glass carpeted the yards and leaning tree limbs
threatened to fall at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   Under a warm spring sun and brilliant blue skies, the
neighborhood was alive Wednesday with the buzz of chain saws as
residents began clearing trees and limbs. Tufts of insulation were
shot through the chain link fences in some places, and a white
plastic dryer vent hose hung like a streamer in one tree.
</P>
<P>
   From the porch of his home at 2709 Mercedes, Pedro Salas looked
at a 40-foot long strip of industrial steel lying in his front
yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea where that came from,'' Salas said in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks west, homeowners in the Rivercrest neighborhood
were clearing fallen trees and assessing their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Burk, 50, lost part of her roof in the 100 block of
Westview Avenue. Her back yard was a jumble of toppled trees. The
brick chimney of her 60-year-old house, a candidate for the
National Register of Historic Places, lay in a pile of bricks by
her front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 19 post oaks - `had','' she lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she was in good spirtits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really pretty neat, if you just like amazing things,''
she said in wonderment at the damage.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburb of River Oaks, close to where weather officials
think the tornado began its deadly journey, officials counted 80
damaged buildings. Among them, houses on Roberts Cutoff Road and
Blackstone Lane lost roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters from River Oaks and Sansom Park worked into early
Wednesday morning, bringing plywood and plastic sheets to residents
to help with home repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds of whirring chain saws filled the air there as well, as
neighbors helped one another remove the debris.
</P>
<P>
   The city lost many stately trees that were over 100 years old,
River Oaks Mayor Jack Adkison said.
</P>
<P>
   At Castleberry High School, students were expected to be back in
classes Thursday despite widespread damage to the campus.
</P>
<P>
   The roof of the fieldhouse collapsed and locker and weight rooms
were destroyed, school officials said. In the main building,
windows were broken and rooftop air-conditioning units toppled into
the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers, students and members of the National Guard 136th
Airlift Wing based at the Naval Air Station Joint Reserve Base
pitched in to clean up the mess. They went from classroom to
classroom with vacuums to clean up the water and other debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been a lot worse,'' said interim Superintendent
Joddie Witte. ``We're going to have school tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   In Linwood, more than a dozen homes and duplexes were destroyed
or heavily damaged. Among them, the duplex on the corner of Carroll
and Mercedes where Lee Harvey Oswald lived with his young family in
the 1950s was wrecked.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the duplexes were built in the 1940s and were originally
used to house workers at the defense plants in west Fort Worth.
Residents said the tornado came just as they were seeing results in
their campaign to revitalize the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Salas, his wife and two children were not home when the storm
hit, but they returned less than an hour later to find little more
than broken glass, sheetrock and insulation everywhere. Salas said
he had been making home improvements since he moved in about two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my efforts are in the trash,'' he said somberly.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the Salas home was what remained of Ted Haga's home. The
north wall of his living room lay about 30 feet from the house.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled how he squeezed into a tiny hall closet to protect
himself from the winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wind just kept blowing and blowing and blowing,'' Haga
said, shaking his head. ``I kept thinking, `When's it going to
stop?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He spent Wednesday trying to salvage what was left of a 1974
Corvette and a 1969 classic Camaro. He did take time to prop up an
American flag on top of the battered home, a testament to his
survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be alive,'' he said, a tired smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Old-timers said it was the second time disaster had struck the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these buildings were inundated to the gables'' during the
1949 flood of the nearby Trinity River, said James Ayres, who owns
12 duplexes.
</P>
<P>
   C.A. Riggs, who owns four duplexes, said he helped rescue people
from the neighborhood during the flood, and began buying houses
shortly after that.
</P>
<P>
   He later became Oswald's landlord and testified before the
Warren Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, residents formed a neighborhood association and
began working with the Police Department to overcome gangs and
other problems, said Archie Pearce, who owns three houses on Foch
Street. Several duplexes were sold to individual owners, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have gotten a lot better down here,'' Pearce said.
</P>
<P>
   But the tornado has put a question mark next to the
neighborhood's revitalization plans.
</P>
<P>
   Ayres pointed to a duplex that had lost a roof and said, ``I'm
going to have to make a decision to rebuild it or demolish it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Bill Teeter and Elizabeth Campbell contributed to
this report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
