u a BC-TORNADO-RDP-HNS &LR;      03-29 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEANUP BEGINS AFTER DEADLY TWISTER ASSAULTS FORT WORTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By EVAN MOORE 
and KIM COBB 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A large portion of downtown Fort Worth
remained cordoned from the public Wednesday as haggard city
officials scrambled to recover from the city's most destructive
tornado.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado, which assaulted downtown Tuesday night with winds
in excess of 150 mph, and accompanying storm injured 95 people and
killed four. Another person is missing and believed drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Of downtown's 150 blocks, 24 remained closed Wednesday and
likely would remain that way through the weekend. Officials asked
residents not to enter the area unless absolutely necessary for
fear that pieces of broken glass could fall on them from damaged
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The twister caused $157 million in damage to commercial and
public buildings, ranking it among the costliest of Texas
tornadoes. At least eight businesses were destroyed and 52 others
suffered at least minor damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to stress that, that includes no residential estimate,
no estimate for lost wages, income or anything else, just damage to
the structures themselves,'' said Fort Worth City Manager Bob
Terrell.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, similar assessments took place Wednesday in the
neighboring communities of Arlington and Grand Prairie, where a
second tornado damaged more than 100 homes Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The four fatalities occurred in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carl Spence, 65, died when he was crushed inside a collapsed
industrial building. Howard Thornton, 52, of Arlington, was killed
by flying debris.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Ashlyn B. Dickens, 24, was recovered Wednesday
morning. His car had been swept into the Trinity River. The body of
Dicken's grandmother, a passenger, still had not been located as of
late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Juan C. Oseguera died Wednesday at Harris Methodist Hospital
from injuries he received when he was struck in the head Tuesday
night by a large piece of hail, a hospital spokeswoman said.
Another man struck in the head by hail remained in critical
condition at the Osteopathic Medical Center of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr was amazed that more people
weren't hurt. About 35,000 people work downtown. But the tornado
hit after most workers and students from a nearby church-school had
left for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the tornado's 11-block swath of disaster stopped eight
blocks shy of commuter-filled Interstate 30.
</P>
<P>
   While this will likely be Fort Worth's costliest tornado, Texas
has experienced far more deadly storms. The most recorded deaths
from a Texas tornado was May 11, 1953, when 114 were killed and 597
hurt in Waco. More than 25 have been killed in nine other tornadoes
in the state since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible thing, but the saving grace is that we're
not dealing with hundreds of people dead and hurt,'' said Kem
Bennett, head of the Texas A&AMP;M University-based Texas Urban Rescue
Search Team, which searched Fort Worth buildings. ``I am amazed
because the damage you see would dictate that there would be a lot
more deaths and injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush declared Tarrant County a disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth city officials said it will take through the weekend
to clean up downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest challenge is getting these big, high-rise
buildings back in operation,'' said Barr. ``They can be boarded up
and made operable, but it will take weeks or maybe a month to get
all the glass back in. Some of it has to be custom ordered.''
</P>
<P>
   The tornado dropped down at 6:15 p.m. CST just west of downtown
Fort Worth and tore its way into the northern portion of the city
center. It damaged at least 20 major buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The twister left mounds of broken glass in streets and parking
lots, particularly around the popular Sundance Square area.
Curtains waved in the wind from gaping holes in several buildings
around the square. Debris covered awnings and sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Three of those buildings are major hotels, all of which had many
reservations because of the scheduled race at Texas Motor Speedway
this weekend. Most people kept their rooms, even though plywood
replaced picture windows by Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Police closed the Sundance portion of downtown Wednesday amid
fears of falling glass that could weigh as much as 200 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very severe downtown, with all kinds of destruction``
Bennett said. ``There are high-rise buildings with most of the
windows gone, buildings that are totally flattened, cars turned
over, power lines down, glass everywhere _ it's a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the offices damaged by the storm were those of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation. FBI officials spent Wednesday looking for
sensitive documents, which may have blown from their offices in the
Cash America Building.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, Mayor Elzie Odom estimated 93 of his city's homes
were uninhabitable. In Grand Prairie, the storm destroyed as many
as six houses and damaged others.
</P>
<P>
   To help, the Red Cross opened four shelters in Forth Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest hit neighborhood near Arlington Municipal Airport
suffered block after block of roofless, windowless homes.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowner Mahmmed Khan was still somewhat dazed Wednesday as he
stood behind his ravaged home.
</P>
<P>
   Khan had been monitoring the storm's progress on TV, he said,
but thought the danger was in West Arlington. He was upstairs,
shutting the window in his son's room when the tornado struck,
blowing out the window he had just closed and flinging him back
into the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was flying me,'' Khan said. He decided he needed to get to
the safety of a bathroom, but the windows at either end of the
hallway he had to cross had turned the corridor into a deadly
gantlet of flying glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked like flying saucers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Khan's wife and two sons had been visiting relatives across town
when the tornado struck. They spent agonizing hours trying to find
him _ looking under overturned furniture in the house, checking the
hospitals and finally finding him at a shelter set up at a nearby
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just sitting on a bench, holding his head in his
hands,'' said Khan's 14-year-old son Wali. ``I was real, like,
scared.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
