 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Thursday, March 30, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at 415-777-6055
or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running
in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SCOUT  &LR; _ If the Giants win the pennant this season, it might be
thanks to former Florida State University first baseman Matt
Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   No, incumbent first baseman J.T. Snow hasn't been traded for a
bunch of minor league prospects. Rather, Woodward has joined the
Giants as a high-tech player development coach using a
state-of-the-art computer system installed in the team's new
Pacific Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants will be the first team to employ the Video Coaching
System, which uses an Intranet tying in PCs, TV cameras and a
database program with a high-capacity DVD RAM storage drive. By
Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PATENT &LR;  _ The 210-year-old U.S. Patent and Trademarks Office is
trying to get with the lightning-fast pace of Internet time.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with mounting criticism that it has awarded patents for
online business processes that aren't original, the patent office
yesterday wed  &LR; said it would revamp its procedures to more
thoroughly scrutinize patents for electronic-commerce and Internet
inventions. By Carolyn Said
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXCITE &LR;  _ AT&AMP;T has found its answer to the America Online-Time
Warner merger: taking control of ExciteAtHome in what could amount
to a $3 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications giant announced plans yesterday to
increase its control over Redwood City's ExciteAtHome, the
country's largest provider of cable modem service, giving it a
partner to take on AOL-Time Warner in the battle to deliver
high-speed Internet access. AOL agreed to buy Time Warner in
January for what was then a $165 billion deal, combining its
popular online service with Time Warner's cable lines and media
content.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T already controlled 56 percent of ExciteAtHome's voting
stock, but due to some byzantine agreements with other cable
partners that own stock in Excite, the New York company has only a
minority of the seats on ExciteAtHome's board. By Todd Wallack
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PENDER _  &LR; While some online brokers are setting up
brick-and-mortar shops, Web Street Inc. is opting for 360 degrees
of glass.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago e-broker is taking over the round see-through
building previously occupied by Sharper Image at Bush and Market
streets in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Web Street will announce today that it's opening real-life
financial centers in San Francisco, Boston and Denver. It already
has one, &LR;  in Beverly Hills. By Kathleen Pender
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDIABYTES  &LR; _ The rumor was too good to ignore. Too bad it
wasn't true.
</P>
<P>
   A tipster told me Forbes ASAP was about to fold. I liked this
rumor, because I had always wondered about ASAP, based in the
Forbes building in Burlingame: Why does a big magazine like Forbes
continue publishing a bimonthly tech supplement? After all, Forbes
has not only beefed up tech coverage in the main magazine, but is
also pouring money into Forbes.com.
</P>
<P>
   ASAP's editor, Michael Malone, and Forbes President Jim Berrien
set me straight. ASAP is not only not DOA, it is A-OK. By Dan Fost
</P>
</TEXT>
