r f BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     03-29 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Forbes ASAP May Be Redundant, But Rumors of Demise Are DOA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The rumor was too good to ignore. Too bad it wasn't true.
<P>
   A tipster told me Forbes ASAP was about to fold. I liked this
rumor, because I had always wondered about ASAP, based in the
Forbes building in Burlingame: Why does a big magazine like Forbes
continue publishing a bimonthly tech supplement? After all, Forbes
has not only beefed up tech coverage in the main magazine, but is
also pouring money into Forbes.com.
</P>
<P>
   ASAP's editor, Michael Malone, and Forbes President Jim Berrien
set me straight. ASAP is not only not DOA, it is A-OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's twice as big as it was last year,'' Malone said,
referring to the ad pages and revenue. In fact, Berrien said the
most recent issue has 94.2 ad pages, up from a paltry 42.3 a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Berrien said ASAP is ``a core piece of our franchise,''
especially as it benefits from the same advertising boom that's
boosting every tech-business journal.
</P>
<P>
   Malone is adding staff, and this week, he started writing a
weekly column for ABCNews.com, which should help promote the
magazine. The new art director has also redesigned the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This baby is a juggernaut,'' Berrien said.
</P>
<P>
   While Forbes has a circulation of 850,000, ASAP goes only to
those 810,000 readers who subscribe. Yet while only two-thirds of
those people actually read ASAP last year, surveys now show the
figure is up to 83 percent, Berrien said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said that's because of ASAP's raison d'etre: By
publishing only six times a year, it can take its time and produce
thoughtful, well-written pieces. Contributors have included
novelists Tom Wolfe and Kurt Vonnegut Jr., historian Stephen
Ambrose and even former heavyweight champ Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Other so-called New Economy magazines like Business 2.0, the
Industry Standard and Red Herring have ``mediocre writing,'' Malone
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You thumb through them for information, but you don't read
them for enjoyment,'' Malone said. ``We're the last bastion of real
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say all is rosy. ASAP just lost News Editor Blaise
Zerega after only six months on the job; he returned to his old
stomping grounds at Red Herring, where he'll be a senior writer.
</P>
<P>
   He joins people defecting from the main magazine, such as Josh
McHugh, who went to the forthcoming ECompany Now, and Stephan
Herrera and Robert LaFranco, who both went to Red Herring. (Is it a
coincidence that Red Herring is spiriting staff from Forbes, given
that the Herring's founder and Editor in Chief Tony Perkins once
teamed with Forbes Publisher Rich Karlgaard to found Upside? Or
that Red Herring Publisher Ted Gramkow jumped from ASAP last year?
That depends whether you believe in coincidence in this incestuous
business.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet such battles to recruit and retain staff, at least point out
that reports of ASAP's demise were, as the saying goes, greatly
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STAYING WIRED:
</P>
<P>
   With the departure earlier this year of Executive Publisher Dana
Lyon, the top business spot at Wired magazine moved for the first
time out of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Schutte, who's been with the magazine since 1994, ascended
to the publisher's post but is based in New York, home of Wired
parent Conde Nast. Not only does Schutte get to work more closely
with Conde Nast execs, especially those at other magazines, but
``our ad revenue is split between both coasts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Associate Publisher Moira McDonald remains in San Francisco to
handle the West Coast accounts. Wired, with a monthly circulation
of 475,000, has had an easier time of  &LR; attracting nontech companies
to advertise than other mags, and that has gotten even easier since
it joined the Conde Nast stable in 1998, Schutte said.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers such as Ralph Lauren and Kenneth Cole have found it
``easy to add Wired to the plan'' of other Conde Nast buys, such as
Vanity Fair, the New Yorker, Vogue and GQ. ``With tech, it works in
reverse,'' Schutte said. ``We're introducing tech and business
advertisers into other Conde Nast magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   Schutte is off this week for Japan and South Korea, meeting with
big electronics firms as well as startups to sell them on trying to
reach Wired's tech-savvy readership.
</P>
<P>
   He has some other tricks up his sleeve as well: In July,
Digimarc, an Oregon company, will give special PC devices to 25,000
Wired subscribers. The device hooks up to the PC and allows users
to read a digital watermark on selected ads in the magazine, which
will launch a Web page.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a company called Digital Convergence will send
similarly equipped laser ``pens'' that link to the PC to every
Wired subscriber, so that they can read bar codes and launch Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the beginning of something very exciting,'' Schutte
said. ``It reminds me of when we started on the Net in '95, and
we'd all jump up and down when a Java applet moved something.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Schutte's old boss Lyon is working feverishly to
start her new company, One Ventures, which will produce a magazine
and Web site devoted to all things design this fall. Chee Pearlman,
former editor of I.D. Magazine, will be editor in chief of the San
Francisco company.
</P>
<P>
   Lyon said last month that many of the ideas are still taking
shape. The audience will be ``people who are culturally creative,''
Lyon said, ``who have adapted technology in their lives.'' The
content will focus on design as it applies to everything, from
clothes to buildings to the Apple iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately enough, the offices are in a Decatur Street loft
behind the San Francisco Gift Center _ a neighborhood once
dominated by fashion and design firms, and increasingly being taken
over by dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
