<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1717 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-FLORIDA30-COX     03-29 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FLORIDA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harvey Gators' energizer
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was only half an hour after Florida had beaten
Oklahoma State for the NCAA East Regional championship. The game
had left both teams physically and emotionally drained.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Florida locker room, Donnell Harvey was playing with
the young son of coach Billy Donovan. Harvey was running around the
locker room, having a grand time.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Gators, too exhausted to move, shook their heads
in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could play two more games,'' assistant coach Anthony Grant
said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's limitless energy was put to good use in the regional
championship game against Oklahoma State. The Gators' victory sent
them into Saturday's NCAA Final Four semifinal against North
Carolina. While the other nine players on the floor were running on
empty, Harvey was scoring 10 points, including a left-handed
tomahawk dunk that snuffed the life out of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when Donnell is tired, he's more athletic than anyone on
the floor,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   That athleticism and relentless energy could make Harvey,
Georgia's Mr. Basketball in 1999, the difference in Saturday's game
at the RCA Dome in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels have the biggest front line Florida has seen:
Center Brendan Haywood (7-0, 271 pounds) and forwards Kris Lang
(6-11, 240) and Jason Capel (6-8, 230). After plodding through an
18-13 regular season, North Carolina in the tournament improved its
defense and started to use its size. In the South Regional
championship game, the Tar Heels played Tulsa, a quick, deep team
similar to Florida. North Carolina controlled the tempo and the
rebounds (35-28) and won 59-55.
</P>
<P>
   But the Florida players say that the Tar Heels haven't seen
anybody like the 6-8 Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just an unbelievable athlete and an unbelievable
competitor,'' sophomore forward Mike Miller said. ``He never takes
a play off and that's hard to do with the way we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates and coaches usually have to speak for Harvey because
the native of Shellman, population 1,162, rarely will do it for
himself. He was raised by a strong grandmother who protected him
from drug dealers and instilled a strong work ethic in him. By the
time Harvey left Randolph-Clay High School, he was one of the most
decorated players in Georgia basketball history. He was the USA
Today player of the year, the Naismith player of the year and a
McDonald's and Parade All-American.
</P>
<P>
   At many schools, he would have been the focus of the basketball
program. For example, Jim Harrick, the new coach at Georgia, made
that pitch. Instead, Harvey chose Florida, where Billy Donovan
already had recruited several high school All-Americans and sold
them on a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a part of something special, and I thought
that's what Coach Donovan was going to do at Florida,'' Harvey
said. ``I didn't just want it to be about me.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about as much insight as one can get out of Harvey, who
speaks softly but carries a big stick when he enters the game. With
exceedingly long arms, he has an wingspang that is estimated at 90
inches. At 220 pounds, he has a very low body fat percentage and
steel-spring legs. He leads the the team in rebounding with 7.0 per
game, even though he is playing only about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But his impressive physical gifts are not what make Harvey so
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is relentless,'' roommate Matt Bonner said. ``He
figures every rebound belongs to him. And if you get in his
way...''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan knew exactly why he wanted Harvey. Last season, the
Gators were within one rebound of beating Gonzaga and playing for
the NCAA West Regional championship. Instead, Gonzaga forward Casey
Calvary jumped over a group of Gators for a last-second tip-in to
beat Florida 73-72.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been in that game,'' Harvey whispered, ``we would
have had a chance to go to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   While Harvey can rebound with anybody, the rest of his offensive
game needs some work. Florida officials think he needs another
season, maybe two, to be ready for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   As with most subjects, Harvey is quiet on this one. ``I haven't
really thought much about it,'' he said. ``I don't have a
timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
