<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-EXCITE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 AT&AMP;T Moves to Control ExciteAtHome  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
AT&AMP;T has found its answer to the America Online-Time Warner merger:
taking control of ExciteAtHome in what could amount to a $3 billion
deal.
<P>
   The telecommunications giant announced plans yesterday to
increase its control over Redwood City's ExciteAtHome, the
country's largest provider of cable modem service, giving it a
partner to take on AOL-Time Warner in the battle to deliver
high-speed Internet access. AOL agreed to buy Time Warner in
January for what was then a $165 billion deal, combining its
popular online service with Time Warner's cable lines and media
content.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T already controlled 56 percent of ExciteAtHome's voting
stock, but due to some byzantine agreements with other cable
partners that own stock in Excite, the New York company has only a
minority of the seats on ExciteAtHome's board.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, AT&AMP;T said it had worked out deals with two other
major cable operators and Excite investors, Cox and Comcast, to
take control of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that AT&AMP;T is serious about this space,'' said Clay
Ryder, an analyst with Zona Research, also in Redwood City. Ryder
said AT&AMP;T could now pump money into ExciteAtHome, or work more
closely in new areas such as interactive television.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T also plans to use ExciteAtHome's brand and content to help
market its high-speed Net services over wireless and other
technologies. ``AT&AMP;T wants to up its ante,'' Ryder said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T agreed to buy Comcast and Cox's stock for at least $48 per
share between Jan. 1, 2001, and June 4, 2002. Comcast and Cox each
own 30 million shares, or 8 percent, of Excite. The repurchase
price is capped at $3 billion. Both companies will also resign
their seats on the board, which AT&AMP;T will be able to fill.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, however, both Cox and Comcast also agreed to extend
their agreements to use ExciteAtHome's Internet service for their
cable wires through 2006, although they can end the agreements
starting in June 2001 by sacrificing some of their ExciteAtHome
stock options.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T also extended through 2008 its pact with Excite, which was
set to run out in 2002. Those three companies account for
two-thirds of ExciteAtHome's North American territory, which
includes 59 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us clarity and the ability to start planning after
2002,'' said Mark Stevens, ExciteAtHome's executive vice president
of business development. ``We have the ability to execute crisply
with long-term relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the complex deal, AT&AMP;T will increase its control
of the voting stock to 74 percent, up from 56 percent today. Its
financial interest will remain at 25 percent, but the company will
roll ExciteAtHome's earnings in with its own. However, ExciteAtHome
will remain an independent, publicly traded company, which will
also report its earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent ExciteAtHome shares up nearly 10 percent to
$37.69, up $3.38.
</P>
<P>
   Both Comcast and AT&AMP;T said they plan to open up the cable
television wires to rival Internet service providers when the
exclusive portions of their contracts begin running out. But even
then, the cable partners pledged to continue using ExciteAtHome's
vast data network to let customers access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals like AOL could be able to use their marketing power to
sign up new customers and distinguish themselves with customer
service and different online services, but ultimately, all cable
modem users would still use ExciteAtHome's service for Net access.
</P>
<P>
   Also yesterday, ExciteAtHome scrubbed plans, announced in
November, to create a separate tracking stock for its portal
business.
</P>
<P>
   Executives and analysts said the tracking stock was originally
created to help the unit focus on its Internet media business,
without becoming entangled in ExciteAtHome's complex governance by
several cable operators.
</P>
<P>
   But now that AT&AMP;T will take control of the company, analysts
said it was no longer needed. ``They have their ownership house in
order,'' said Forrester Research analyst Bruce Kasrel. A tracking
stock, which lets investors place bets on only a single part of a
business, ``would have created confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
