<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENT-PATENT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Better Patents Pending 
 &HT;     By Carolyn Said 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The 210-year-old U.S. Patent and Trademarks Office is trying to get
with the lightning-fast pace of Internet time.
<P>
   Faced with mounting criticism that it has awarded patents for
online business processes that aren't original, the patent office
yesterday wed  &LR; said it would revamp its procedures to more
thoroughly scrutinize patents for electronic-commerce and Internet
inventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are inventing on their computers now instead of a
workbench or kitchen table,'' said Patent Commissioner Q. Todd
Dickinson in an interview. ``We've done a good job and need to do a
better job'' in awarding patents for computer innovations,
particularly ``business method'' software, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish this, the patent office will now have a second
examiner review all applications in this area, require more
comprehensive searches of databases of prior art and double the
number of random quality checks it performs.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson wants to involve the computer industry more through
formal meetings and feedback mechanisms, including a roundtable
this summer. And the patent office will increase technical training
for examiners and seek to improve its database covering software
innovations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes come after months of industry outrage that
some Internet companies have landed patents _ which essentially are
20-year government-sanctioned monopolies _ for translating basic
business practices into the medium of cyberspace. Among the most
controversial are Internet bookseller Amazon.com's patents on its
``one-click'' shopping process and affiliates customer-referral
program, and Priceline.com's patent on online ``reverse auctions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a gap where people could file patents that are
not as exacting, as carefully drawn,'' as they could be, said Carey
Heckman, director of Stanford University's Law &AMP; Technology Policy
Center. ``Every time there's a little zig in the zag of
fast-changing technologies, for some time regular procedures like
patents will be caught off guard and people will take advantage of
it until the system can stabilize.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, observers said the changes should help reduce broad,
``kitchen sink'' applications and increase the quality of patents
awarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible relief to hear the patent office admitting
there's a problem,'' said Sebastopol publisher Tim O'Reilly, who
has spearheaded calls for patent reform, notably in an open letter
to Amazon CEO Jeff Bezos last month that drew 10,000 responses in
31/2 days. ``A lot of patents are just a joke, but there's a lot of
complicity by the computer industry in this patent debacle.''
</P>
<P>
   Bezos released a statement applauding the patent office changes.
Earlier this month, he responded to O'Reilly's letter by suggesting
revisions to the system for patenting business methods and
software, including shortening patent life span in these fields to
three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson said that particular suggestion is not feasible due to
international treaty obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Gray, an intellectual property lawyer in Menlo Park, said:
``Anything that helps screen and make more rational the process of
granting Internet-related patents is a good thing, no question
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics have charged that some recent patents are so broad they
give an unfair advantage to companies that who  &LR; did nothing more
innovative than beating &LR;  a path to the patent office door.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the system point out that the patent office is
open to rectifying problems. ``I make this challenge all the time:
Send in prior art and file a re-examination request,'' Dickinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Rivette, a patent attorney and author of ``Rembrandts in
the Attic,'' a book on how to make the most aggressive use of
patents, said he thinks the patent office is doing the best it can
to handle rapid technological innovations and would need additional
funding to do a better job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to protect what you innovate or invent,''
said Rivette, chairman of Aurigin Systems, a Cupertino company that
makes software for comparing intellectual property against prior
art.
</P>
<P>
   Patent examiners must be attorneys with degrees in the fields
they cover, such as engineering or biotechnology. ``I haven't seen
anyone do an IPO for the U.S. government yet, so you have to pay
these people well,'' Rivette said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carolyn Said at csaid(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
