<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1720 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SCOUT-SCOUT_SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOUT-SCOUT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Giants Seek Edge With Video System  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
If the Giants win the pennant this season, it might be thanks to
former Florida State University first baseman Matt Woodward.
<P>
   No, incumbent first baseman J.T. Snow hasn't been traded for a
bunch of minor league prospects. Rather, Woodward has joined the
Giants as a high-tech player development coach using a
state-of-the-art computer system installed in the team's new
Pacific Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants will be the first team to employ the Video Coaching
System, which uses an Intranet tying in PCs, TV cameras and a
database program with a high-capacity DVD RAM storage drive.
</P>
<P>
   The still-experimental system is designed to record every pitch,
every hit, every out and just about every spit of tobacco juice
from four different angles during the 81-game home season at the
downtown stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The all-digital video system replaces the cumbersome videotapes
that most baseball teams use and gives the  &LR; players the ability to
instantly see what they're doing wrong or uncover weaknesses in
their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, Snow strikes out against the Phillies' Curt
Schilling to end a game, Snow could storm into a video replay room
behind the Giants dugout, instantly watch the failed at-bat from
different angles and match his swing to one he used to homer off
Schilling in a prior game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might see something different with your swing that you
hadn't noticed or the coaches hadn't noticed,'' said Woodward, who
will work for Giants administrative coach Carlos Alfonso and the
players to operate the system designed by Panasonic Corporate
Systems Co., the business-to-business unit of Matsushita Electric
Corp. of America.
</P>
<P>
   At 3Com Park, the Giants used two VCRs to record games from the
TV broadcast feed. If a player wanted to look at his swing during a
game, he would have to switch tapes, put the original tape in the
second VCR and rewind it to his last at bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't the most efficient system, but it worked,'' said
Bill Schlough, head of the Giants' information systems. ``Here,
we're taking it to a whole new level.''
</P>
<P>
   At Pac Bell Park, Panasonic will station four remote-controlled
TV cameras custom-designed to provide a sharper image than needed
for regular TV broadcasts. The Giants hope to have views of the
field from behind the plate, center field and along the first- and
third-base lines but are still trying to figure out the best camera
locations.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras will be operated from a small room next to the
Giants locker room underneath the stands behind third base. The
video feeds into an elaborate system that includes nearly a dozen
monitors, four computers and a video-effects generator.
</P>
<P>
   The video and data will be stored on a 4.7-terabyte, 750-disc
DVD RAM drive, enough to hold about 2,000 hours of game action.
That should be more than enough capacity, room,  &LR; without recording
the lulls between pitches or innings, to capture the entire
162-game season, said Kelly Kotera, chief engineer for Panasonic
Corporate Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Using a database program developed for baseball by Dixon Sports
Computing of Long Beach, the images will be sorted with about 25
fields of data, like whether the pitch was a curve or a slider or
whether the pitcher was left- or right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   The database will allow the video from different angles of the
same play, or two different plate appearances in different games,
to be replayed in synch, said Michael Dixon, president of Dixon
Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tying the video into the database in DVD RAM makes it all come
together,'' Dixon said. ``We can look at all Barry Bonds' at bats
with two strikes on him against left-handed pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaching system will be accessible through a Web browser
from a PC set up in a room behind the Giants new dugout. General
Manager Brian Sabean will also have access from his office computer
to help him evaluate players.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player moves to another team, it might be that his value
in a trade is (determined by) how he does against left-handed
batters,'' said Chris Baumgard, Panasonic's national sales and
marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, because the system uses standard Microsoft server
and browser software, players could access the system on the road
from a laptop. But that would require a high-speed Internet
connection because the video quality would be poor with
slower-speed connections, Kotera said.
</P>
<P>
   But players will have the use of a portable DVD player, which
they can use to watch the video clips while they're away from home.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are the first to combine digital video with Dixon's
database. The Cleveland Indians _ the first to use Dixon's database
combined with videotape _ gave it a shot in the middle of the 1995
season, when the team made it to the World Series for the first
time since 1954. Dixon also noted that then-Indians slugger Albert
Belle went on a home-run tear during the last two months of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Computerized scouting is not totally new to baseball. Last year,
Philadelphia's Schilling, Arizona's Matt Williams and the New York
Mets' Darryl Hamilton used a computer scouting system with similar
features to the one in Pac Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   Petaluma pollster and entrepreneur Richard Hertz' Big League
Systems combined a computer database program with game videotapes
converted to digital video.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Kim, third base coach with the Boston Red Sox, said
Hertz' Big League Systems program did help the players prepare for
games. A batter like Williams (after he returns from the disabled
list) could take a laptop on the road and learn an opposing pitcher
has a tendency to throw a slider 49 percent of the time after
throwing a fastball on the corner of the strike zone, Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to go to 10 tapes to see what you want to
see,'' Kim said. ``It gets you to focus on his repertoire of
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kim noted most baseball teams balked at using such high-tech
systems because ``it's going to cost them more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hertz has struck out in the past trying to interest
teams such as the Giants, Red Sox, Oakland Athletics and San Diego
Padres. But he hopes the Giants' new system shows the value of
digital scouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to take a bad club or terrible player and make
them great, but it's just another thing to give you an advantage or
get you better prepared,'' Hertz said.
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic and the Giants aren't saying how much the Video
Coaching System cost, although Schlough said it's in the ballpark
of ``several thousands of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the newfangled system earns the team more wins or hits
during the season is unknown because it hasn't been tried in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The more technologically savvy National Basketball Association
has more experience with high-tech scouting. This season, 22 of the
NBA's 29 teams, including the Golden State Warriors and Los Angeles
Lakers, used a program called Advance Scout that is a showcase for
database mining programs IBM sells to corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Advance Scout crunches game statistics such as points, rebounds
and minutes played to reveal strengths and weaknesses not seen in
the box scores.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 playoffs between the Orlando Magic and Miami Heat,
the program showed that when little-used point guard Darrell
Armstrong was in the game, teammate Penny Hardaway had better shots
and Miami's shooting percentage was lower. That helped Orlando
rally to win the next two games, although the Magic lost the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the most high-tech gadgets can't guarantee success.
The Warriors are one of the NBA's doormats. And Dixon Computer
Sports' oldest customer, football's St. Louis Rams, had one of the
two worst records in the NFL in the 1990s before a miracle 1999
season that ended with a Super Bowl win.
</P>
<P>
   But he notes that the University of North Carolina men's
basketball team, which is in this year's NCAA Final Four, uses his
system.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Woodward, a Florida State Seminole from 1995 to 1998 and
the son of former major-league infielder and general manager Woody
Woodward, had a brief career as a Seattle Mariners farmhand. But
now he hopes that through video coaching he can help the Giants to
a few more hits or wins during the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   And in baseball, a few more hits in a season turns a .250
journeyman into a .300 hitter. Or, as the Giants remember from the
1993 and 1998 seasons, one win is the difference between the
playoffs and second place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at bennye (AT) sfgate.com.
</P>
