r f BC-PENDER-PENDER_SFCHRON     03-29 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENDER-PENDER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH/KATHLEEN PENDER 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Web Street Inc. Moves Into Glass House 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
While some online brokers are setting up brick-and-mortar shops,
Web Street Inc. is opting for 360 degrees of glass.
<P>
   The Chicago e-broker is taking over the round see-through
building previously occupied by Sharper Image at Bush and Market
streets in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Web Street will announce today that it's opening real-life
financial centers in San Francisco, Boston and Denver. It already
has one, &LR;  in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Like other online brokers, Web Street has found that it helps to
have a physical location for people who need help navigating its
site or want to pick up their stock-market winnings in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed to be the first brokerage firm born online to
plant an outlet in the city, but it will be within a few blocks of
other online /off-line competitors, including Charles Schwab and
Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The online firms that have branch offices have done a very
good job in terms of opening new accounts,'' said Dan Burke, a
Web-broker analyst with Gomez Advisors in Lincoln, Mass. On the
other hand, ``some brokers are doing well without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Web Street is leasing the high-traffic space _ 3,800 square feet
at street level and 2,900 in the basement _ from its owner, the
government of Singapore. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   There were at least five bidders for the property, including
several other online brokers and someone who wanted to turn it into
a television studio, said Kazuko Morgan, a real estate broker for
Whitney Cressman who handled the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Web Street plans to restore the quirky building to its original
splendor. Believe it or not, the circa-1959 building is a city
landmark, part of the old Crown Zellerbach complex.
</P>
<P>
   Web Street intends to bring back a spiral staircase, rip out the
carpets to expose the stone floor, and replace countertops and
teller booths like those that existed when the building was a Wells
Fargo bank.
</P>
<P>
   It will open in three to four months, assuming the city
permitting process goes smoothly, said Web Street Vice President
Harleigh Mandel.
</P>
<P>
   The site will have a high-tech look similar to the Beverly Hills
office, which has ``a wall of TVs, a curving stock ticker and flat
panel monitors all over the place,'' Mandel said.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly traded Web Street (ticker symbol: WEBS) is a
mid-size Web broker, ranking 13th with about 115,000 accounts,
according to Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   It originally targeted active traders, and was the first to
introduce real-time streaming quotes, Mandel says.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors, which monitors and rates online brokers for
performance and customer satisfaction, ranks Web Street 13th
overall, but fourth for ``hyperactive'' traders.
</P>
<P>
   It ranked 16th overall in a recent analysis by Barron's.
</P>
<P>
   Web Street said it eventually plans to open locations ``in major
U.S. and international cities,'' including New York, Paris,
Frankfurt and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Branch offices provide another channel of communication for
investors,'' said Burke. ``You can do it over the phone, over the
Web, by e-mail, in live chat sessions and with a live branch. If
you're not everywhere, you're really not helping everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Palo Alto's E-Trade is planning to open a storefront in
Manhattan but has not said if it will move into San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
