<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HIGH FIDELITY' HITS ALL THE RIGHT NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 FIDELITY-REVIEW-LADN  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3{ stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the opening moments of John Cusack's wonderfully acerbic new
comedy,``High Fidelity,'' Cusack's character, Rob, muses that there
are thousands of songs about misery and he wonders: Do I listen to
pop music because I'm miserable or am I miserable because I listen
to pop music?
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of question the self-obsessed Rob specializes in,
precisely because there's no easy answer. All the better: He can
torture himself for days while searching for the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Music, love and misery are insightfully intertwined in this
quirky comedy about a record store owner who sifts through his past
relationships to discover why women are always dumping him. Rob's
latest loss is Laura (Iben Hjejle), who has just left him for
living his obsessions. Rob baits her, saying she doesn't even make
his top-five list of painful break-ups. After Laura leaves, though,
he compiles a top-five list of reasons he misses her.
</P>
<P>
   Rob, as you can see, is big on lists. He owns a barely
functioning record store in Chicago where he spends his days with
his two clerks _ shy softy Dick (Todd Louiso) and the loud,
opinionated Barry (Jack Black) _ rattling off lists of musical
minutiae while serving or belittling the occasional customer who
manages to find the store. (Sample list: Top Five Songs For Letting
the Person Who Dumped You Know That Even Though They Broke Your
Heart You Can't Get Over Them).
</P>
<P>
   Rob can't get over Laura, particularly after he learns she has
taken up with a pompous, pony-tailed blowhard (Tim Robbins in a
hilarious cameo). Now, Laura is on Rob's break-up list (she's No. 5
with a bullet). A glutton for punishment, Rob tracks down the other
women on the list to find out why ``he's doomed to be rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack and his ``Grosse Point Blank'' writing partners D.V.
DeVincentis and Steve Pink (along with Scott Rosenberg) have done a
brilliant job in bringing Nick Hornby's painfully wry 1995 novel to
the screen. The setting has seamlessly shifted from London to
Chicago, but that's the only change of substance. Rob's
angst-ridden monologues (Cusack spends much of the movie directly
addressing the camera) remain, as do all of his very real character
flaws. There are reasons women are wary of this guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Fidelity'' sports one of the best supporting casts you'll
ever find in a movie. Lili Taylor, Lisa Bonet, Joelle Carter and
Natasha Gregson Wagner dazzle as the women in Rob's life, and
Catherine Zeta-Jones steals several scenes as the ex-girlfriend Rob
knew was always out of his league. Joan Cusack plays Laura's best
friend with fetching candor, and Danish actress Hjejle grounds the
movie with genuine grace.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all are Louiso and Black, Laurel and Hardy teammates who
invest their characters with a touching authenticity that goes well
beyond the sort of cartoonish portrayals we usually get from comic
sidekicks. Such depth is this movie's strength, and Stephen Frears'
solid, simple direction allows these satisfying details and
characterizations to come to the fore. ``High Fidelity'' heads my
list of best movies we've seen so far this year. &QL; 
________ &QL; 
The film: ``High Fidelity'' (R; language and some sexuality.) &QL; 
The stars: John Cusack, Jack Black, Iben Hjejle and Todd Louiso &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Stephen Frears. Screenplay by D.V.
DeVincentis, Steve Pink, Cusack and Scott Rosenberg. Released by
Touchstone Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 54 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
