<SLUG> BC-COKE-DISCRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON MEETS WITH COCA-COLA OFFICIALS ON RACIAL DISCRIMINATION
LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (Eds: no byline) 
(cjl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson met Wednesday with top
Coca-Cola executives to discuss the company's treatment of minority
and female employees.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came three weeks before the company's annual meeting
on April 19, in Wilmington, Del. About 150 current and former Coke
employees plan to travel there to protest what they say is
discrimination against blacks in pay, promotion and performance
evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Jackson called for ``a fair and just
settlement'' of a racial discrimination lawsuit filed against the
company by a group of Coke employees nearly a year ago. The lawsuit
seeks class action status, which could broaden the suit to include
as many as 2,000 current and former black workers. He also said
that the company had a historic opportunity to establish itself as
a leader among corporations in its treatment of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson met for more than two hours Wednesday with Douglas N.
Daft, Coke's chairman and chief executive; Jack L. Stahl, its
president; Carl Ware, executive vice president; and Ingrid S.
Jones, vice president for corporate external affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Ware said, ``The Coca-Cola Co. has had a longstanding
relationship with Rev. Jackson and, as always, we value his
insights and perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Coke nor Jackson disclosed details of the discussions.
But both spoke of their relationship: a Coke spokesman noted that
the company had been a financial sponsor of Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH
organization, and Jackson said that the organization was a
Coca-Cola shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Daft has said that Coca-Cola is working to settle the employees'
lawsuit, whose allegations the company had denied.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, referring to the busloads of protesters expected to
travel to Wilmington, said Wednesday, ``Either the buses will roll
or justice will roll as water down a river stream.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
