<SLUG> BC-BBC-GALLOWAY-COACH-CANCER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR COACH, LIFE'S CURVE IS NO SINKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ The five-hour drive back from Houston last week was
hard for Clay Gould. There was a lot of thinking time, not only
about the just-received bad news from the famed M.D. Anderson
Cancer Center, but also about the future.
</P>
<P>
   At age 28, and being the nation's second-youngest head coach in
NCAA Division I baseball, life seemed to be serving up fat
fastballs for Gould.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, the pitch selection changed dramatically. A
sweeping curveball came in at the knees, outside corner. Every
hitter dreads being buckled by that particular pitch, and only five
springs ago, Gould was a UT-Arlington player being recognized as
one of the best hitters in college baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ready or not, Gould had major adjustments to make, meaning
there was much to ponder on that drive from Houston. Baseball had
always been such a large part of his young life. How in the world
could colon cancer be making this unwelcome intrusion?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually kind of funny that just as soon as we hit the
city limits of Arlington, I immediately felt better,'' Gould was
saying yesterday. ``My spirits quickly lifted. Just getting back
home, back to Arlington, quickly changed my whole attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, that figures. Gould's roots grow deep in Arlington.
Three generations deep.
</P>
<P>
   Gould was born, went to kindergarten, grade school, middle
school, high school and college, all within the same Arlington ZIP
code.
</P>
<P>
   He met his future wife, and married her last fall, also within
that same ZIP code. Their first child is due in August, and that
birth _ you guessed it _will be at the same hospital where Gould
was born.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Gould has been all Arlington, all the time. The lone
exception was the one year at Texas A&AMP;M to receive his master's
degree and also serve as a graduate assistant coach for the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Clay returned to UTA as head baseball coach and
immediately recruited one of the best freshmen classes in the
country _ ``Collegiate Baseball'' magazine ranked it 26th
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   But in February, very early in this first season, Gould felt
stomach pains, which were followed by a problem of digesting food.
From that, colon cancer was discovered in surgery two weeks ago at
M.D. Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's the last thing you want to tell your family
members and your friends,'' said Gould, sitting in the baseball
office at UTA. ``Here I was, in the best physical condition of my
life, doing 50 minutes on the stationary bike every day, and adding
20 more minutes on the StairMaster, and from that, it's now this.
</P>
<P>
   ``People hear the word cancer, and they automatically think of
death. They feel sorry for you because they have a great amount of
concern for you. You have to tell them that it's still OK. I'm
gonna still be me. The recovery process is going to work. I sure
don't think about dying. Actually, I'm kind of eager to get the
next step started, and get it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   That next step is the chemotherapy treatments. ``The doctors are
certain they got out what they needed to get out, but the chemo
will be to make sure no active cells are still there,'' Gould said.
``The only thing that scares me about the chemo is the feeling of
fatigue that will come with it. I like to do what I like to do, and
if that means spending 12-hour days involved in baseball, so be it.
I love this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Gould put on the uniform yesterday and coached again
from the dugout as the Mavs played Tarleton State. His biggest
worry until a few weeks ago was about his team's midseason slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at cancer as the best thing that ever happened to me,
because of the way it has already changed my perspective on life,''
Gould said. ``That change is for the better. I am more relaxed, I
have a different outlook and focus on the day-to-day process, and
it has also already made me a more positive person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I now enjoy some of the things that before I didn't think I
had time to enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fat fastballs are never forever. But a positive attitude and a
strong will can overcome almost all. At the Arlington city limits
sign last week, Clay Gould found what he needed.
</P>
<P>
   {Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
