<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FALL AT BUZZER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canadiens4Bruins3
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Bruins moved one giant step closer to playoff
elimination Wednesday night as the Canadiens rallied for a 4-3
victory over Boston at the Molson Centre.
</P>
<P>
   The crushing goal came with 14.4 seconds left in regulation when
ex-Bruin forward Sergei Zholtok zigzagged through center ice before
teeing up a slapper from the right point that eluded goaltender Rob
Tallas to the stick side.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns, his hand over his mouth, could only
shake his head.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Canadiens leapfrogged ahead of Buffalo by
one point for the eighth and final playoff spot in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins came out strong, scoring a pair of goals a little
more than three minutes apart to take a 2-0 lead into the first
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Knuble, who made his Bruins debut March 11 against the
Canadiens, potted his 12th goal of the season and third with Boston
to get things started.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Axelsson made it all happen by skating the puck around the
right circle while being chased by rookie defenseman Francis
Bouillon. Axelsson backhanded the puck in front and Zholtok tried
to get his stick on it but missed. Knuble was there to rap it past
goalie Jeff Hackett at 10:06.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Nickulas made it 2-0 with his third tally of the season at
13:25. Hal Gill relayed a pass up to Joe Thornton, who took off up
the left side of the ice. Thornton, in the left circle, saw
Nickulas driving to the net and dished a perfect cross-ice feed
that Nickulas buried.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens rallied to within one midway through the second on
a Benoit Brunet strike. Zholtok teed up a slapper from the right
circle that Tallas stopped. But Brunet, who had been battling with
Cameron Mann in front, got free and fired in the rebound from the
left side of the crease at 8:05.
</P>
<P>
   It was Brunet's 14th goal of the year, tying a career high set
last season, but it was just his 45th game of the year because of
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens, smelling vulnerability, increased the pressuer
and eventually tied it on a freakish goal at 16:51. Patrice
Brisebois fed a lead pass to Brunet, who was scooting up the right
side. Brunet dished it to Sheldon Souray at the left point and
Souray, seeing traffic in front, flipped the puck at the net.
Tallas either didn't see it or was fooled because it sailed right
by him, pulling the Canadiens even.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case many times this season, the Bruins proved
themselves incapable of putting a team away.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins came close to regaining the lead on two bids by left
wing Sergei Samsonov early in the third but Hackett turned them
back.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for the Canadiens to take their first lead of
the game at 5:43. With Steve Heinze off for high sticking,Bouillon
was credited with a goal after his shot caromed off Bruin
defenseman Brandon Smith and past Tallas for the 3-2 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins fought back to pull even at 7:57 on a goal by
defenseman Kyle McLaren. Thornton, skating up the right side,
sailed a backhand pass from the far end of the right circle and
McLaren, off balance, put the puck, along with himself, into the
net on top of Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams pulled out all the stops the rest of the way. One of
the Bruins' finest chances came with 5:15 remaining in regulation.
Center Brian Rolston found himself with a breakaway from center
ice. Rolston raced down the slot on Hackett, switched from his
forehand to his backhand, and tried to slip his shot inside the
right post. But Hackett blocked it with his left skate, making the
save.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston could only shake his head in frustration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
