<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1736 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-MICHIGAN-ST.-FLIN     03-29 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHIGAN-ST.-FLINT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE'S `FLINTSTONES' LEAVING RIVALS IN RUBBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Morris Peterson arrived as a freshman at Michigan State, he
quickly acquired a catchy nickname: ``Shotgun.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical 17-year-old. Shoot from the hip and leave the defense to
those who want to be bothered with it.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled through that first year, partly due to an injured
thumb but mainly because he lived in coach Tom Izzo's doghouse:
``Hey, Morris, found anyone on campus yet that you can guard?''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been inviting ridicule then to suggest that the
day would come _ as it has now _ that Peterson would be the Big Ten
Player of the Year and leading scorer on a Michigan State team
arriving for a second consecutive Final Four appearance, this time
favored to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   But early in his sophomore year, the blessed event that would
transform his life finally occurred: he hit iron on a slam dunk and
came down with a broken wrist. Decked out in a cast that reached to
his elbow, Peterson acquired a new nickname: ``The Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, he also developed a new outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cast made it tough to shoot, so I had time to develop some
other skills, and to learn some things,'' he says. ``I learned how
to play Michigan State basketball. I learned that if you play for
coach Izzo, he doesn't care about you dropping shots in from 30 to
35 feet if you can't play defense. On this team, you run, you
scramble, you dive for loose balls, you battle people, no matter
what.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play like Antonio Smith did. He was a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   More than that, the now-departed Smith was the charter member of
the core group of players known as ``The Flintstones.'' The name
stems from the fact that they all grew up in Flint, Mich., and not
because they crush rocks during timeouts, although that has become
the hardhat image of Izzo's Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   There are three of them left now _ Peterson and point guard
Mateen Cleaves, both seniors, and junior shooting guard Charlie
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The acknowledged heart and soul of the Spartans, Cleaves _ who
won Big Ten Player of the Year honors in his sophomore and junior
years _ opted to return for his senior season for specific reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have loved every minute I have spent in this school,'' he
says. ``And I love the opportunity that it gave to all of us. And I
wanted to help us win a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The enterprise began badly for Cleaves, who sat out the first 13
games this season with a stress fracture. During that stretch,
playing a brutal schedule laced with ranked teams because, Izzo
says, ``I thought we needed a challenge,'' the Spartans went 9-4.
Since Cleaves' return, they are 21-3.
</P>
<P>
   During his recovery, Cleaves busied himself with a pet project:
badgering the 6-foot-7, 215-pound Peterson into ``being the
All-American we all know you are.'' Peterson had little choice but
to listen, since the two are roommates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of the quiet one,'' he says. ``Mateen, he'll get in
your face and he won't let up, but it always works. He can lift you
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the day he came into the room and told me about his
injury, I thought he was kidding, because he's always so up. Then I
saw the tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `It's your team now. You're the one everyone is
counting on, and you've got to get it done.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As time wore on, a few things rubbed off. After hitting the last
of a series of shots that cemented an 86-76 victory over North
Carolina in Chapel Hill, Peterson started back upcourt, glanced up
at the stunned throng of UNC fans, and put his finger to his lips.
</P>
<P>
   Shhhhh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess a little of Mateen jumped out of me there,'' he says,
grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return, Cleaves resumed running the floor, running the
team on and off the court, and launching those patented MSU
comebacks _ ``They love to dig themselves out of a hole,'' one fan
marveled, after watching the Spartans wipe out a 14-point Syracuse
lead and win, 75-58, by scoring the game's final 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   That one followed a seismic locker room speech by Cleaves at
halftime, in which he cornered his towering roomie and said,
``You've got to lead us back, because we're counting on you. And
I'll kick your butt if you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson hit a quick 3-pointer after the half, yelled at Cleaves
to ``keep it coming,'' and scored 16 points down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it goes the other way. On an evening when once-mighty
Michigan was in tatters, the hot hand belonged to Bell, and Cleaves
was near an all-time assist record.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want that record,'' Bell told him, ``just keep bringing
it over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves wound up with 26 assists, Bell scored 32 points, and the
Wolverines went down, 114-63.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the group are the non-Flintstones _ A.J. Granger
(6-9, 230), who crashes the boards and shoots threes with equal
gusto, and Andre Hutson (6-8, 240), who had 17 points and 11
rebounds in the finals of the Midwest Regional while bearing the
primary responsibility for guarding Iowa State's Marcus Fizer.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Spartans are down to their last gasp, someone from
Flint usually gets the ball. The game-turning play against Iowa
State, hurriedly agreed upon during a timeout, was an alley-oop
pass from Cleaves to Peterson, who executed the dunk _ no iron this
time _ and set MSU on its way to Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned about the play afterward, Izzo smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't want to be trite about it,'' he said, ``but
that's what All-Americans are supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the Spartans win it all, Peterson will indulge himself a
brief ritual: to reach up on top of his locker and remove the cast
that has been there for two years as a reminder of a different
time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
