<HEADLINE>
WEB START-UP TO BUY IMS HEALTH IN PERPLEXING DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (cjl) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Internet health care company that went public less than six
months ago announced Wednesday that it was using its highflying
stock to buy a leading health care information provider that has
long been one of America's top 500 companies.
</P>
<P>
   TriZetto Group, a start-up that provides software to doctors and
health care companies online, said it would acquire IMS Health
Inc., a decades-old company that gathers prescription information
for drug companies, for stock valued at more than $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The complex transaction gives IMS executives and shareholders
control of the new company, which nevertheless will be called
TriZetto. The deal left Wall Street analysts and investors of both
companies perplexed. Shares of TriZetto plummeted $24.5625, to
$33.50. IMS fell $5, to $16.625.
</P>
<P>
   Satish K. Tyagi, a managing director at SG Cowen, who follows
IMS stock, said shareholders in each company were uncertain about
the benefits of the deal _ and also about each other. Many IMS
shareholders have held their stock for many years, Tyagi said,
while many TriZetto stockholders may have invested just weeks or
even a day ago, hoping for a repeat of the whirlwind appreciation
of many Internet stocks. Indeed, before Wednesday, TriZetto shares
had gained more than 500 percent since the company went public on
Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a shareholder of IMS, you're saying: `Wait a minute.
Who are these guys?' '' Tyagi said. And as for TriZetto investors,
Tyagi said, ``Those guys don't really care for these old-economy
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyagi said it was not yet clear why the experienced management
at IMS, a successful company founded in 1954, had decided to team
up with executives at TriZetto. TriZetto, based in Newport Beach,
Calif., was founded in 1997 by Jeff Margolis, 36. Margolis,
TriZetto's chairman and chief executive, will be vice chairman and
president of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   ``TriZetto is unseasoned,'' Tyagi said. ``They've only reported
one or two quarters as a public company.''
</P>
<P>
   But both companies boasted about the deal Wednesday, saying it
would create a company that was the dominant leader in the
fast-growing business of providing information services to health
care companies. The new company would have 9,500 employees and
would have had revenue last year of about $1.4 billion. Only about
$80 million of that amount was earned by TriZetto.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Weissman, the chairman of IMS, which is based in
Westport, Conn., said Margolis and other executives had many years
of experience in the business of providing information services to
health care companies.
</P>
<P>
   The deal helps IMS move its business onto the Internet, Weissman
said. And TriZetto, which sells services to doctor groups, health
maintenance organizations and other insurance companies, gets
access to the thousands of drug companies that are IMS customers,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies are most excited about creating a new
business, Weissman said, by combining the information that IMS has
on drug prescriptions with the data that TriZetto has on a
patient's health care history and the cost of that care. The
information would be sold to drug companies and health care
companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking about this got both companies really excited,''
Weissman said. ``We don't know how anybody else will be able to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, IMS stockholders will receive 0.4655 share
of TriZetto for each IMS share. Based on TriZetto's closing price
on Tuesday, IMS shareholders would receive TriZetto stock with a
value of $27.03 for each IMS share. The deal, which is expected to
be completed this summer, will give IMS shareholders control of
about 85 percent of the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Weissman will be chairman of the new company; Victoria R. Fash,
the chief executive at IMS, will hold that same title at the new
company. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
