<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS DELAYS REVOKING CUBAN BOY'S TEMPORARY STATUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After 4 1/2 hours of negotiations between attorneys for
Elian Gonzalez's Miami family and immigration officials, the
federal government Wednesday night delayed for 24 hours revocation
of the boy's parole that allows him to stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Talk were to resume Thursday morning on government demands that
the boy's relatives promise in writing to return him to Cuba if
they exhaust their court appeals to keep him in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides have agreed to reconvene (this morning) and
continue to discuss this very important matter,'' Robert Wallace,
regional director of the Immigration and Naturalization Service in
Miami, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials originally set a 9 a.m. Thursday deadline
for the written promise. The deadline has been extended to 9 a.m.
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro, meanwhile, escalated the political
tug-of-war by announcing that Elian's father is willing to travel
to the United States to claim his son and stay with him, while
their Miami relatives continue a legal battle to keep him in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Castro made the announcement during a live television broadcast
Wednesday, saying Juan Miguel Gonzalez ``is ready to immediately''
go to Florida to take custody of the 6-year-old boy, according to
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Castro added that the trip was conditional on guarantees that
the U.S. government would turn Elian over to his father or at least
make a maximum effort to do so.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time anyone has said the boy's father would be
willing to stay in the United States during the legal process.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has demanded that Elian's Miami relatives promise in
writing to hand the boy over if they lose their court battle to
keep him in this country.
</P>
<P>
   If INS officials revoke Elian's parole, ``that means the end of
Elian's permission to stay in the United States and the end of
Lazaro Gonzalez status to provide temporary care,'' said Maria
Cardona, INS spokeswoman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the negotiations Wednesday included the process under
which Elian would be remanded to INS custody, Cardona said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the family said after Wednesday's negotiations
that ``there's no agreement and the government is going to make
sure there's no agreement that will hurt Elian Gonzalez.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez, the great-uncle Elian has been living with, has
said he would be willing to release the boy to his father if Juan
Miguel Gonzalez came to Florida from Cuba, but he said he would not
deliver the boy to the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy lives in my house, and they'll have to go find him
there,'' Lazaro Gonzalez told Spanish-language network Telemundo.
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex Penelas, meanwhile, said hours
before Wednesday's crucial meeting began that the city would not
offer to its police resources to help federal officials remove the
child from his home.
</P>
<P>
   Penelas said he and the mayors of 22 nearby towns would hold
Attorney General Janet Reno and President Clinton responsible for
any violence that might occur if immigration officials revoked
permission for the boy to stay in this country, the AP reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never cease being police officers. It would just be
in the event of the retraction of Elian; that would not be our
jurisdiction. That would be something we would leave to the federal
authorities,'' Miami police spokesman Angel Caozadillas.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported that some Miami officials warned
that the city could erupt in violence if federal agents tried to
forcibly take the boy from his great-uncle's house in Little Havana
and send him back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In a White House news conference, President Clinton said
everybody should abide by the decision of the courts, adding ``I
have done my best not to overly politicize this. And I don't think
we should. There is a legal process here; we ought to let it play
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Elian have appealed a Miami federal judge ruling
that paved the way for the boy to be reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Cuban exile community has rallied around Elian, lifting
him as a symbol of hard-fought freedom, whose mother died in a
desperate attempt to provide a better life for her son in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The INS decision to return the boy was based on two interviews
by an INS officer with Juan Gonzalez in December. As a result of
the meetings, the INS determined that Gonzalez was a fit father who
had maintained a relationship with his son after his separation
from the boy's mother.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gonzalez derailed attempts by family members in Miami
to seek political asylum for the boy by asking the INS officials to
withdraw those applications.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing his ruling last week, District Judge K. Michael Moore
said Elian's great-uncle had the right to seek legal action on the
boy's behalf and that the court had limited jurisdiction in the
case. He also stated that Elian's attorneys could proceed with the
lawsuit to determine if the INS violated the boy's right to due
process.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a group of U.S. lawmakers seeking to block the
deportation of the child introduced legislation to confer permanent
U.S. residency status on Elian and nearly all his Cuban relatives,
the AP reported. But even supporters of the measure, written by
Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., suggested its chances of being enacted
seemed slight.
</P>
<P>
