<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SC-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      03-29 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 CLINTON MAKES CAROLINA CAMPAIGN STOP   AND WEIGHS IN ON CONFEDERATE
FLAG DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (cjl) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ President Clinton showed Wednesday that while
he might not be a candidate anymore, he still knows how to pull off
an attention-getting campaign stop.
</P>
<P>
   He spent about four hours on the ground here, from the time Air
Force One touched down at Columbia Metropolitan Airport until it
lifted off again en route to his home away from home in Chappaqua,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But in that brief time, Clinton managed to raise more than
$500,000 for the Democratic cause, press a volatile issue that is
making Republicans squirm and thumb his nose at Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas without even uttering his name.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stepped square in the middle of the raging debate over
the Confederate battle flag flying over the South Carolina
Statehouse. He called on flag supporters to stop living in the past
and compared the standoff to the senseless clashes that are
occurring throughout the world between different ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This flag controversy here, you shouldn't be surprised by how
tough this has been,'' Clinton said to loud applause. ``Why are the
Catholics and the Protestants still fussing in Northern Ireland?
Why did the Orthodox Christians run the Albanian Muslims out of
Kosovo, a million of them? Why did 800,000 people in Rwanda get
killed in a tribal war in 100 days _ with no guns practically, they
were almost all hacked to death? I could go on and on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeating a line he first delivered during a visit to Selma,
Ala., this month, Clinton said, ``As long as the waving symbol of
one American's pride is the shameful symbol of another American's
pain, we have bridges to cross in this country and we better get
across them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his remarks at a tribute for Rep. James E. Clyburn,
the first black congressman from South Carolina since
Reconstruction. The event was held at Allen University, a small
historically black college whose mission is to ``teach the mind to
think, the hands to work and the heart to love.''
</P>
<P>
   The locale stood in marked contrast to the educational
institution that Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee, visited in February. Bush has been roundly criticized for
giving a speech at Bob Jones University in Greenville, S.C., in
which he failed to criticize anti-Catholic statements by the
university's founders or its restrictions on interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the president's visit said they did not choose the
location to score political points. Clyburn, chairman of the
Congressional Black Caucus, has been an advocate of black
institutions, and he encouraged organizers of the tribute to hold
it at such a school. All the same, Democrats were relishing what
they saw as the symbolism of the dueling visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Jones University and Allen University are about as far
apart as two places can be,'' said Dick Harpootlian, chairman of
the South Carolina Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Harpootlian said the money that Clinton helped raise would go to
Democratic state legislators who have been singled out by
supporters of the Confederate flag. One such race, he said, pits
Jim Bryan, a longtime Democratic state senator who wants the flag
taken down, against Daniel B. Verdin, who is a leader of the
pro-flag forces.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan said he needed the help in what he expected to be a tough
race against Verdin, who is commander of the South Carolina
Division of the Sons of Confederate Veterans and has vowed to make
the flag a prime campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Verdin believes passionately in his cause. ``Any so-called
`compromise' would be dishonoring to the 20,000 plus South
Carolinians who gave their lives for the cause and dishonoring to
the more than 75,000 others who defended hearth and homeland from
ruthless and barbarous invaders without giving their lives for the
cause,'' he said in a memo on his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But in his speech Clinton urged such flag supporters to give the
rest of the world a lesson in tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the South has got something to teach the rest of the
country and to help our country teach the rest of the world _ we've
got to let this go,'' he said. ``I know, you say, this is easy for
you to say, but, look, everybody's got a beef in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments on the flag controversy stood in marked
contrast to those of Bush, who has studiously avoided taking sides
in the battle. Bush has said it is a state issue, not a
presidential one.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential aide, however, said Clinton thought differently.
``The president has to play the role of a unifier whether it's a
symbolic issue like the flag or a specific, ugly racial incident,''
the aide said. ``The president has to bring the country together.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, expressed little concern that a visit by a
president who never carried South Carolina would sway many voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled to death that Bill Clinton is coming to South
Carolina,'' said J. Sam Daniels, executive director of the state
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels called Clinton ``one of the most corrupt, scandal-ridden
presidents we've ever had,'' and said his comments on the flag
would not help resolve the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help the issue to have another outside force coming
into this state,'' Daniels said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
