<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1752 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-FRANCIS-H     03-29 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-FRANCIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
It should be an interesting race, to say the least, among the
Chicago Bulls, the Los Angeles Clippers and the Rockets.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say what?
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, who are in Minnesota tonight to play the
Timberwolves, have long been out of the playoff race, but there is
another race to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   That race is wide-open, with Chicago's Elton Brand the slight
favorite and the Clippers' Lamar Odom more of a long shot. Steve
Francis of the Rockets is somewhere in between, closer to Brand
than to Odom.
</P>
<P>
   Francis could be much higher on many ballots, but in one of the
strangest ironies, the things Francis refuses to do _ padding his
stats, playing extra minutes, jacking up shots whenever the mood
strikes him _ are the things that make him a better player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' Francis said. ``It might come back to haunt me
(in the Rookie of the Year voting), but as long as my coach and my
teammates believe in me, that's what's keeping my confidence high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up by 40 (points), and I could be shooting those
wide-open shots, but I'm looking to get others involved. And I
think that all comes with learning the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the things, though, that could wind up costing him the
Rookie of the Year honor because his stats aren't as gaudy as they
could be.
</P>
<P>
   But they're still pretty impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Francis averages 17.6 points, second only to Brand's 19.4-point
average among rookies. Brand is the top rookie rebounder (10 per
game), but Francis leads in assists (6.6). Among the three top
rookies, only Francis is in the top 10 in scoring, rebounding (5.2
per game, sixth), assists, steals (1.58, third), minutes played
(35.5, third), blocks (.33, eighth) and 3-pointers made (91,
first).
</P>
<P>
   Pretty good for a guy who, at least according to some critics,
wasn't supposed to be able to play point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stress enough how much I think the position that I
play is probably the hardest position because the competition is so
tough,'' Francis said. ``It (Rookie of the Year) would be a great
feat and a great honor, and I would definitely accept it, but I
still think I have to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to prove anything to anybody but myself, but I
want people to realize that I can be a legitimate point guard in
this league, and be a point guard for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be, if history is any indication.
</P>
<P>
   He is on track to become just the seventh rookie in NBA history
to average 15 points, five rebounds and five assists, joining Oscar
Robertson (30.5 points, 10.1 rebounds and 9.7 assists with
Cincinnati in 1961), Alvan Adams (19 points, 9.1 rebounds and 5.6
assists with Phoenix in 1976), Magic Johnson (18 points, 7.7
rebounds and 7.3 assists with the Lakers in 1980), Michael Jordan
(28.2 points, 6.5 rebounds and 5.9 assists with Chicago in 1985),
Penny Hardaway (16 points, 5.4 rebounds and 6.6 assists with
Orlando in 1994) and Grant Hill (19.9 points, 6.4 rebounds and five
assists with Detroit in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   All but Johnson and Hardaway went on to win Rookie of the Year
(beaten out by Boston's Larry Bird and Golden State's Chris Webber,
respectively).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look strictly at skills, there's not a better rookie
out there,'' said one Western Conference scout. ``He can handle the
ball, break you down, stick the outside shot, dunk on you, pass the
ball and even rebound. There is not a more skilled rookie out
there, but I'm not sure that's what the (Rookie of the Year) voters
are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   He has exactly what Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich was looking
for when the organization decided to send popular players Othella
Harrington, Michael Dickerson and Brent Price, along with Antoine
Carr, to Vancouver for the rights to Francis, who was taken by the
Grizzlies with the second pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a really good attitude,'' Tomjanovich said of
Francis. ``We had good feelings about the trade from the beginning,
but when I saw him play in those eight exhibition games I took him
aside and told him, `Steve, you have a chance to be one of the best
players ever to play your position, and you're going to be a star
in this league. Do you want to do it the right way?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And by that, I meant playing both sides of the ball, not being
a guy who's going to say, `Hey, I have the ball so I'm going to get
all the shots.' And he was on the right wavelength. And then
there's the way he carries himself with people. He's a fun guy to
be around. Kids love him, and he's good to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great opportunity (for success) because a lot of guys
don't have that whole package of talent and personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's what drew Francis back into the gym at 9 p.m.
Monday for more work on his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think about trying to get better,'' Francis said. ``I
want to be better. The reason why I came (to the gym) is because I
was watching a game on TNT, and just watching those guys I started
thinking that all of our games should be (nationally) televised,
which keeps me aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning awards would be a bonus. Francis, 23, has bigger plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully five years from now I'll just be coming off a trip
to the Olympics,'' Francis said. ``And I want to be a three- or
four-time All-Star and at least to the Western Conference finals by
then, as well as having a chance to better my skills and help my
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, if I can be the Finals MVP and make the Olympic team,
I'll give the Rookie of the Year to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
