<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-AGENT-2TAKES     03-29 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-AGENT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENT'S CONTACT WITH PLAYERS IS QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Tenn., Ga., Ill., N.C., Mich., Ohio, Ind.) (Exclusive) 
(DW) 
 By JOE DRAPE and JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A professional sports agent who figures prominently in the N
CAA's investigation of St. John's basketball program appears to
have broken the law in two states by repeatedly contacting
prominent college players without registering as an agent in those
states or alerting the athletes' universities about the
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone records and diary entries belonging to the agent, Andy
Miller, show that he had numerous phone conversations with Mike
Miller, the star guard for the University of Florida, which on
Saturday will play in the Final Four of the national college
basketball tournament. The records also show repeated calls to Tony
Harris of the University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Both states have strict laws governing agents, including a
requirement that they register with the state and that they notify
the university when contacting an athlete. In Florida, violating
these provisions can be considered a felony; in Tennessee, it is a
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is not registered in either state. After athletic
officials at the University of Florida were contacted Wednesday by
The New York Times, they spoke with Mike Miller. According to Jamie
McCloskey, the University of Florida's associate athletic director
for compliance, the player acknowledged that Andy Miller had called
him at least 45 times since Sept. 1 and that he had spoken to the
agent at least 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Tennessee said Wednesday that Harris had
acknowledged speaking with Andy Miller at least a dozen times. A
Tennessee spokesman said the school planned to report Miller to the
state agency that oversees agents.
</P>
<P>
   McCloskey said Wednesday that Florida would turn the information
over to the authorities in Gainesville and that the school would
also inform the Southeastern Conference and the NCAA about Miller's
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's phone records and diaries, which were reviewed by The
Times, are evidence in a lawsuit filed against him by the agent
Eric Fleisher, Miller's former employer at Assist Sports
Management. Fleisher accuses Miller of stealing his clients and is
seeking $30 million in compensatory and punitive damages from
Miller; Wilhelmina Models Inc., with whom Miller is associated; two
other businesses; and 10 former clients.
</P>
<P>
   Miller did not return repeated calls to his Manhattan office and
cellular phone Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA rules do not forbid contact between an agent and a player,
but they do prohibit the player's reaching an oral or written
agreement with an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's phone records show that he reached Mike Miller on his
cell phone and at his girlfriend's home, speaking to him as long as
23 minutes. He began contacting him last July 20, according to the
records. Under Florida law, agents are allowed only to send written
materials to players, as long as they send the same materials to
the school's athletic director. Agents are not permitted to
initiate contact with a player, as Mike Miller said Andy Miller
did. If the player initiates the contact, the agent is obliged to
alert the university.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief phone interview Wednesday, Mike Miller said of Andy
Miller, ``He started calling me.''
</P>
<P>
   McCloskey said Mike Miller admitted having met at least once
with Andy Miller _ at a basketball game at Rutgers University last
December _ and that the agent had offered the player tickets to a
professional basketball game the next night in Orlando between the
Magic and the Minnesota Timberwolves, who feature Kevin Garnett,
Andy Miller's biggest client. Mike Miller told the school officials
that he declined the offer, sparing himself a violation of NCAA
rules against players' receiving extra benefits.
</P>
<P>
   McCloskey said he called Andy Miller Wednesday after talking to
Mike Miller and explained to him the Florida statute saying agents
must be licensed by the state. According to McCloskey, Andy Miller
said he was unaware of the statute, which was enacted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association Players Association, which
regulates agents, gives a synopsis of every state's requirements to
agents, according to Ron Klempner, an attorney for the players'
association. There are 361 athlete agents registered in Florida,
according to state officials.
</P>
<P>
   If the State Attorney's office determines that Miller violated
the law, it could charge him with a third-degree felony, according
to Jerry Wilson, a supervisor in the bureau of investigations of
Florida's Department of Business and Professional Regulation, which
oversees agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlicensed activity is a felony and we basically get him to
stop,'' Wilson said. ``If we have good information, let's say we
have the diary, if we have good hard evidence, we'll ask him to
stop. That's the least of his problems. The felony is an extremely
serious charge. We'll write a report and turn it over to the State
Attorney and he'll be charged.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Tennessee officials, informed that several
Volunteer players' names appeared in Miller's diary and phone
records, said Wednesday that they had no record of Miller's seeking
permission to contact those players, most notably Harris. Harris
told Malcolm McInnis, the university's associate athletic director,
that Miller began calling him last year and that the two talked as
recently as midseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the conversation was general, the kinds of
things one might say if we were attempting to establish a
relationship,'' McInnis said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis said he would probably turn the information over to the
state's Division of Elections, a section of which oversees agent
activity. According to Donnie Jones, an administrative assistant in
the sports agents permits department of Tennessee's Division of
Elections, activity by an unregistered agent is a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Renfro, a spokesman for the NCAA, said neither Miller nor
Harris violated rules so long as there was no written or oral
agreement and no extra benefit was accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is indicative of how deep some agents will go to compromise
a student-athlete,'' Renfro said. ``I hope this is a lesson for
student-athletes that they need to be aware of the contacts they
make innocently and how it could affect their career.''
</P>
<P>
   The records show that Andy Miller attempted to reach at least 24
players from at least 17 teams that were in this year's NCAA
tournament, including Cincinnati, North Carolina and Michigan
State. Along with Mike Miller and Harris, he also placed many
telephone calls to Seton Hall point guard Shaheen Holloway and
Indiana's A.J. Guyton.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller has been linked to the former St. John's point guard
Erick Barkley. Barkley brought Miller to a meeting last week with
Coach Mike Jarvis shortly before Barkley declared that he would
enter the National Basketball Association draft.
</P>
<P>
   In Miller's day planner on Dec. 17, he makes a notation:
``Barkley _ meeting with Bearup in January.'' He was referring to
an Atlanta-based financial adviser, Bret Bearup.
</P>
<P>
   Bearup, who represents a number of NBA players, including Elton
Brand of the Chicago Bulls, said he spoke with Barkley at Miller's
request in late January or early February. Bearup, who talks
frequently to Miller, according to Miller's phone records, said
Barkley made it clear to him that he was turning pro.
</P>
<P>
   Bearup said Wednesday that Miller was Barkley's agent, although
Barkley has not announced that. Bearup said an employee of his at
ProTrust Capital had arranged a $50,000 line of credit earlier this
week for Barkley to draw on until he begins earning an NBA salary.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2250EST &QL; 
