<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-911-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH'S 911 STAFF FIELDS 1,600 CALLS IN 4 HOURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The calls came rapidly: the panicked
19-year-old with an apartment full of children; the calm woman atop
a hill as a tornado churned toward town; a breathless department
store security guard reporting that a man was dead.
</P>
<P>
   As a deadly twister snaked its way across west Fort Worth and
into downtown Tuesday night, the 911 calls tracked its progress and
its deadly touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just scared, because we think a tornado's coming,'' a
frantic 19-year-old woman cried into the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, well ma'am, just go, try to reach safety somewhere. Go
where it's safe,'' call-taker P. Guillory told the teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where? We don't know where,'' the young woman said, as
children began screaming and crying in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Guillory repeatedly told the woman to move everyone into a
closet. Then the screams rose in pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're scared. It's coming! The tornado is coming!'' the teen
said.
</P>
<P>
   After securing a promise from Guillory that she would call back,
the young woman hung up the phone to take the children to the
closet.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange was one of the nearly 1,600 fielded by Fort Worth's
911 call takers between 5 p.m. and 9 p.m. Tuesday. The tornado
touched down shortly before 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Others callers were calmer, describing the tornado above
Rockwood Drive heading east toward downtown Fort Worth or reporting
that their office building had been hit by the tornado and was
encircled by shattered glass and live power lines.
</P>
<P>
   An employee inside the Montgomery Ward store called to say that
about 100 people were in the store when the twister struck it and
churned toward the Cash America building across the river.
</P>
<P>
   She said she heard a child crying in the darkness but was
unaware of any injuries. But a call from a store security officer
four minutes later brought blunt bad news from another part of the
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's at least one dead,'' the man told call-taker C. Burt.
On a static-filled cell phone, he said the man was dead in the
distribution area. The victim was later identified as Howard
Thornton, 52, of Arlington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he knew of anyone else injured, the security guard
said he was unable to get into the main building because of downed
power lines and a broken water main.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a confirmed hit,'' Burt said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
