<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-ELDERLY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO DISPLACES ELDERLY, DISABLED RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN ROUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Elizabeth Hester sat at the edge of a cot
and sipped orange juice from a paper cup at the Will Rogers
Memorial Center.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the center is home to the 76-year-old woman, who has no
family to take her in. Nearly 195 senior and disabled residents
were displaced from the Hunter Plaza Apartments downtown after a
tornado shattered windows on the building's west side Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Transportation Authority shuttled the residents
to Will Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard glass. It was flying,'' Hester said. ``I went up under
the table'' and then hid in a bathroom. When it settled, she said:
``I was shaking so bad. ... I thought I was going to have a heart
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chisholm Trail Chapter of the American Red Cross provided
cots, food, medical care and counseling to 105 residents. An
additional 89 were unaccounted for Wednesday afternoon, said Gloria
Owens, assistant executive director for the Fort Worth Housing
Authority, which owns Hunter Plaza. They may have gone home with
relatives or gone to local hospitals, housing workers said.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth fire officials evacuated residents about two hours
after tornado winds heavily damaged the 11-story building at 200
Burnett St. At least one tenant had cuts on her hand, said Lt. Kent
Worley, a Fire Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the residents left with only a few personal belongings,
which they stuffed into grocery sacks and tote bags. Firefighters
tried to retrieve medications, checkbooks and other items at
Wednesday at Hunter Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents rely on wheelchairs, motorized scooters or
walkers. At least two people use oxygen machines. Some were still
wearing their pajamas Wednesday night, although few said they were
able to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses and outreach workers from the Red Cross, the Fort Worth
Public Health Department and Mental Health Mental Retardation of
Tarrant County provided counseling and medical attention, such as
monitoring blood pressure and filling prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man said he saw his medications fly out the window,'' said
Ajay Amin, an outreach worker for the Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents appeared irritable, confused or sad. One man was
concerned that food he had just purchased would spoil in his
refrigerator because the electricity at Hunter Plaza was cut off.
Others appeared more at ease as they ate snacks, chatted or curled
up on floor mats. A few kept a lookout for relatives to take them
in.
</P>
<P>
   It could be more than a month before residents can return to
Hunter Plaza, workers said. Owens said the housing authority will
cover the cost of temporary housing.
</P>
<P>
   Some may find shelter at Westchester Plaza, an assisted-living
facility that caters primarily to seniors at 554 S. Summit St. It
has opened 60 apartments to help as many people as possible, said
Carl Ballew, executive director of Westchester Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can stay as long as necessary,'' Ballew said. ``This is
something we have to do, because it's what God tells us to do. Help
others.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Yvette Craig contributed to this report. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2256EST &QL; 
