<HEADER>
A1886 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CLIPNOT-LADN-(SLA     03-29 0284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS NOTEBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tyrone Nesby, who put the ``lip'' in Los Angeles
Clippers, has not talked himself into a suspension.
</P>
<P>
   For sassing interim coach Jim Todd late in the first half of
Tuesday's loss to Dallas, Nesby's penance was a seat on the bench
for the rest of that game. He's expected to be in action tonight
when the Clips take on Milwaukee at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is status quo,'' said Todd, whose displeasure with
the second-year small forward included a tribute to friend and
ex-teammate Troy Hudson written on Nesby's sneaker. After the point
guard was waived Monday, Nesby blamed the transaction on a personal
problem between Todd and Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   The coach said the decision on Hudson was strictly a basketball
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes in the heat of battle, tempers flair, but
everything's cool,'' Todd said, referring to Tuesday's situation
that reached a boiling point when Nesby snapped back at the coach,
who had reprimanded him for not hustling back on defense. ``We're
going forth ... Nez will play.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't necessarily promote joy in Clipperville, where
Nesbygate was only one dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Taylor (ankle sprain) and Lamar Odom (calf strain) are
listed as goners for the Milwaukee game. This will be Taylor's
sixth absence in a row, while Odom is expected to be out for the
fifth time in seven games due to pain in both calves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make much sense for me to come back before I'm
completely healthy,'' Odom said. ``If I do that, I could get hurt
worse and miss a lot more time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
