<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NBC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAG-TEAM TELEVISION: NBC JOINS XFL VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT41, has been sent to New York Times photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The World Wrestling Federation's proposed smash-mouth eight-team
football league called the XFL received a mammoth injection of
credibility Wednesday when NBC Sports announced that it was a 50
percent partner in the venture.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's decision to join the league, and carry games in prime time
on Saturdays from February to April, signals its avid desire to
reach male viewers 12 to 24 years old, whom the WWF attracts in
droves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Vince McMahon, we believe we're getting the best promoter
to that audience,'' Dick Ebersol, the chairman of NBC Sports, said
in reference to the federation's chairman during a news conference
at the WWF's Midtown restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The federation's ``Raw Is War'' series on the USA cable network
outdrew ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' in 1999 among males 12 to
24 by 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes NBC's purchase of $30 million in shares of a
new class of World Wrestling Federation Entertainment stock. The
venture expects to spend close to $100 million before it makes a
profit in its third season.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's partnership with the XFL creates risk for the network
because of the WWF's often crude, tasteless programming, featuring
unflattering and stereotypical portrayals of women and
African-Americans. A pimp character, the Godfather, is preceded
into the ring by bikini-clad women. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In response to the suitability of an octogenarian ``pregnant''
female wrestler being body-slammed by the brawny Kurt Angle,
McMahon asked, ``Where's your sense of humor?''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said, ``In my viewing of Vince's programs, I wouldn't
classify anything as vulgar.'' But he acknowledged that some parts
of the USA program or ``WWF Smackdown'' on UPN are inappropriate
for his 13-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``NBC is a pretty forward-thinking network. It gave us
`Saturday Night Live' and `Rowan and Martin's Laugh-In.'''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the host of ``Saturday Night Live'' was the Rock,
the popular wrestling star and best-selling author. It produced the
show's highest rating in two years and its strongest male
demographics in six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday nights, we need to reinvent what's on,'' said
Scott Sassa, the president of NBC West Coast. ``We need a big event
to get people in.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, NBC and the WWF think the XFL's blend of
``extreme fun,'' capitalizing on the end of the National Football
League season, is the type of programming craved by young men
weaned on scripted pro wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   The XFL will be played without a fair-catch rule, require
receivers to keep only one foot inbounds on passes, institute a
35-second play clock, limit halftime to 10 minutes and bring back
the bump-and-run.
</P>
<P>
   Players, coaches, locker rooms and huddles will be wired for
sound, and cameras will be in locker rooms, on sidelines and inside
helmets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The youth of America hasn't seen the type of football we're
going to present,'' McMahon said. ``A generation of fans haven't
seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said NBC's presence ``puts up a modicum of a firewall''
against the WWF's storied excesses creeping into the XFL.
</P>
<P>
   Although McMahon says the games will be legitimate _ just more
fun, unlike the stodgy old NFL, he contends _ he is reticent about
detailing the participation of star wrestlers in marketing or the
use of scripted shtick before and after games, or at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Rock won't be going out for a long pass,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the XFL wonder whether there are enough credible
players to field eight teams, whether there is enough fan interest
to fill stadiums like RFK Stadium in Washington, and whether the
WWF can transfer to football the magic touch it possesses in
television, publishing, music and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Pilson, a sports industry consultant and former president
of CBS Sports, said: ``The issue for me is whether the promotion
power of NBC and the WWF can create demand. Right now, there is
little demand or interest in a winter-spring outdoor professional
football league.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The tricky part is, whereas you can choreograph
wrestling, you can't do it with football. And bad football is bad
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Igiel, president for the broadcast division of the Media
Edge, a unit of Young &AMP; Rubicam, said: ``Of all the things we don't
need is more football. I don't care what McMahon has to do with it.
It may be an interesting experiment to observe, or McMahon will
make it a travesty that won't be pretty to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The XFL follows in the failed cleats of the U.S. Football League
and the World Football League. The World League of American
Football, created in 1991 by the NFL, nearly folded before being
recreated as NFL Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of future Kurt Warners, the former NFL Europe
and Arena Football League quarterback who led the St. Louis Rams to
a Super Bowl victory this year, gives psychic sustenance to the
XFL's partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you consider how many play Division I college football,
and only 250 are drafted,'' Ebersol said. ``The brand of football
will depend on the openness of the rules and the desire of the
athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   The close McMahon-Ebersol connection goes back to the mid-1980s,
when Ebersol produced a wrestling show on NBC that helped make the
television executive wealthy.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
