<HEADLINE>
CORPS OF ENGINEERS WILL RETHINK MISSOURI RIVER PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers has put the
brakes on its new plan to control flows from Missouri River dams _
in the name of endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   The corps' plan, which was announced early this year, had been
hailed as a historic consensus among states in the Missouri River
basin. The corps has struggled for a decade to revise its river
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, however, now says the corps'
new plan does too little to help restore threatened fish and birds
along the Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   So the corps has agreed to shelve the plan, at least for 90
days, and to enter into a formal process under the federal
Endangered Species Act in a new effort to restore those species.
</P>
<P>
   This news troubled downstream river users Wednesday, including
farmers, the barge industry in Missouri and a coalition of states
along the Missouri that had helped broker the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is horrible,'' said John Madgett, senior vice president
of Mid-West Terminal Warehouse Co., the largest river terminal in
the Kansas City reach of the Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to mess up farmers, and it's going to mess us
up, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to halt the corps' revision of the so-called Master
Manual, the document by which the river's flows are managed, is
tantamount to eliminating navigation on the lower river, Madgett
said.
</P>
<P>
   That would impose a huge economic cost on farmers, industry and
consumers, one much greater than the loss of a fish that once
roamed the river, Madgett said.
</P>
<P>
   If the endangered-species advocates ``had been around when the
dinosaurs were here,'' Madgett said, ``we'd all be eaten up.''
</P>
<P>
   Madgett was referring to American Rivers, a national river
conservation group that has worked diligently behind the scenes to
support the Fish and Wildlife Service and restore the Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has listed as endangered three species on
the Missouri: the pallid sturgeon; the interior least tern; and the
piping plover. The sturgeon population, in particular, is in
danger, wildlife officials say.
</P>
<P>
   American Rivers will file, as early as Thursday, a legally
required notice that it intends to sue the corps for failing to
protect endangered species, said Chad Smith, the group's regional
representative.
</P>
<P>
   The corps deserves praise for deciding to halt its revision of
the Master Manual process, Smith said. ``It's a positive step,'' he
said. ``I applaud the fact that the corps has the guts to say they
feel like they made a bad decision with the initial preferred
alternative and they need to think about it more.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith added that the formal consultation on the Missouri River's
current operation should have occurred years ago. The service had
indicated that the river's operation, as early as 1990, placed
endangered species in jeopardy. But it had never pushed for a
formal consultation process under the federal Endangered Species
Act.
</P>
<P>
   The key problem, according to the service, has been the corps'
leveling of flows, eliminating spring high water and supplementing
reduced natural flows each summer. But proposals for increasing
flows in spring or allowing the river to dwindle in summer have
angered downstream users because they fear it could flood cropland
during planting season or halt barge traffic in summer.
</P>
<P>
   By law that consultative process can last as long as 90 days. At
its conclusion the service will produce a ``biological opinion''
that will detail the threats to endangered species from the corps'
operations of the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully the corps will take to heart what the Fish and
Wildlife Service says and make that part of its new
recommendation,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Johnston, a corps spokesman in Omaha, Neb., confirmed
Wednesday that the corps planned to announce this week that it
would delay its process of revising the Master Manual and enter
into consultation with the Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said Brig. Gen. Carl Strock, commander of the corps'
Northwestern Division, had decided that he wanted a plan for the
river's operation that would not result in the Fish and Wildlife
Service's saying it jeopardized endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the indications are that the current water control
plan does not contain all the elements that would preclude a
`jeopardy opinion,' &UR; '' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Correcting those flaws may conflict with other legal
requirements, Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Congress has precluded the corps from instituting
higher flows in spring.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, federal law requires the corps to maintain
navigation on the lower river, except during extreme drought. So it
is unclear whether altering or shortening the current season _ now
April to December _ would be legal.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear, Johnston said, is that the corps' plan, announced
in January, will be back on the shelf. ``Any alternative will be
reviewed in light of what comes out of this consultation'' with the
service, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The corps' decision also perturbed Richard Opper, executive
director of the Missouri River Basin Association, which includes
Missouri and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the association won a near consensus _ Missouri being
the lone dissenter _ on how the corps should operate the Missouri's
dams. In turn the corps adopted the basin association's
recommendation as its ``preferred alternative,'' its choice for the
river's future operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish and Wildlife Service sat in on those discussions, Opper
said, and he wishes those representatives had expressed these
concerns as forcefully earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some anger over this,'' Opper added. ``There
already is. But that's because people care passionately about this
river....
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do our best to find a way out of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
