<HEADLINE>
SANTA FE TRAIL ENTHUSIAST FEARS FOR TRAIL SWALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It was a bit like deja vu for Walter Cook, a
Santa Fe Trail enthusiast.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the din of bulldozers lured the southeast Kansas
City man into his back yard where he saw the hulking machines
clawing away at trail swales _ long depressions that resemble ruts
in the landscape, left by wagon trains traveling through the area
more than 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So this week, when Cook heard the bulldozers roaring in back of
his home, he knew exactly what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Cook contends that the landowner, Blue Ridge Bible Church, is
destroying the last of a Santa Fe Trail swale _ an estimated 55
feet long _ east of Manchester Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, Cook protested when the Blue Ridge Bible Church
developed an adjacent plot containing a 120-foot swale to build a
soccer field for its Blue Ridge Christian School at 8524 Blue Ridge
Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   Now the church plans to use the land currently under development
to expand the soccer field to include a track, said William Ross,
the church's pastor.
</P>
<P>
   The digging started Monday but was temporarily halted Wednesday
when the Kansas City Public Works Department learned the church did
not have all the necessary permits.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Swenson, project manager for the Public Works
Department's engineering section, said the church had not secured a
land disturbance permit. But Swenson said once that hurdle is
cleared early next week, the church could resume digging.
</P>
<P>
   Cook is none too pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is it a neighborhood landmark, but it is a historical
landmark,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ross said that as far as he knows, the area has not been
declared a national historic site. He declined to comment on
whether he considered the depressions to be trail swales. He would
say only that there has been great debate on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people don't agree that this is a swale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the authenticity of some trail swales has become a
greatly contested issue among trail historians.
</P>
<P>
   The routes used by early pioneers through the Kansas City area
changed a lot between the 1820s and 1850s, said John Mark
Lambertson, director of the National Frontier Trails Center in
Independence. The resulting trails and swales have led to a lot of
confusion and controversy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has taken up the leadership of trying to identify and
document these swales and put them in some kind of protected
status,'' Lambertson said. ``So unfortunately, all the controversy
has muddied the waters of preservation, of preserving what little
remains of the trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of trail swales remain, he said. They include
those in Harmon Park in Prairie Village, Kan., Minor Park in south
Kansas City, and swales discovered last year in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Ross added that swales still exist on the west side of
Manchester Avenue near 85th Street.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook is not encouraged by what remains. He said he is more
concerned about what is vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have a legal right to do so (develop the land),'' he
said. ``But from a moral and ethical standpoint, it is not the
right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders say the bottom line is that it is their land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are free to do with it what we wish so long as it is within
the limitations of what the city will allow us to do,'' Ross said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
