<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-THIRD-BASE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM EVANS CHOSEN RANGERS' STARTER AT THIRD BASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers' original plan was for third
baseman Mike Lamb to spend the season in Triple A. There was a
slight variation when Todd Zeile signed with the New York Mets. But
the plan is back in effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers officially named Tom Evans as their starting third
baseman yesterday and told Lamb he will begin the season with the
Oklahoma Redhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make the ballclub,'' Lamb said. ``It's a
disappointment not to make it and be told you're not good enough at
this point in time. That doesn't mean a month from now, a year or
two, I won't be ready. I will be ready. The next opportunity will
be mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates mulled over the situation almost every day
this spring and said a final decision wasn't made until yesterday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a plan a year ago and at the bottom of my heart that's
the best way to go,'' Oates said. ``Lamb will start the year at
Triple A, get a full year and see how it goes. Maybe he won't need
a full year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb was the Rangers' Minor League Player of the Year at
Double-A Tulsa last year, hitting .324 with 21 homers and 100 runs
batted in. That led the Rangers to believe he could skip Triple A.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Evans got off to a hot start in spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evans played very well for us,'' Oates said. ``He did
everything we asked him to do. He played good defense. This is the
right fit for our ballclub. We get the best of both worlds. We get
to see what Evans can do, and Lamb gets a chance to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans has been in Triple A for most of the past three seasons.
He hit .280 for Oklahoma last year with 12 home runs and 80 RBI. He
is batting .302 this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good opportunity for me,'' Evans said. ``Everyone in
the game wants to make it to this level and show what they can do.
I realize nothing is set in stone. That's the way I'm going to
approach it, doing my best to keep the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans was once a top prospect for the Toronto Blue Jays, but a
series of injuries kept him from winning a regular spot. He has
just 48 major-league at-bats with a .229 average, one home run and
two RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``First off, I need to play solid defense,'' Evans said.
``Johnny told me I would be hitting deep in the order. If you look
at the heart of the order, those are the guys who are going to put
up numbers. I don't consider myself an out, but anything I add to
that will be a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb finished this spring batting .280 and made five errors. He
will stay with the Rangers for their final three exhibition games
before being sent to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be an everyday big-league third baseman,'' Oates
said. ``He's going to have to work on his defense, but he's going
to hit when he's a big-league third baseman.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
