<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS OWNER-TO-BE CUBAN TURNS DOWN CHALLENGE FROM TURNER
ANALYST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That heated war of words between Mavericks owner-to-be Mark
Cuban and national reporter Peter Vecsey escalated late Tuesday
night when Vecsey issued a challenge to Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   Vecsey said he wants to meet Cuban on a Turner Sports telecast
so the two can air their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Vecsey is an analyst for Turner Sports _ which carries NBA games
_ and a columnist for the ``New York Post.'' Vecsey recently
criticized Cuban for having a 10-man coaching staff. He also
criticized the Mavericks for their wild on-court celebration after
they came from 22 points down to defeat the San Antonio Spurs,
97-96, on March 21.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban took exception with Vecsey, telling the ``Star-Telegram:''
``You can quote me on this, Peter Vecsey is an idiot. I wanted to
do some research on Peter Vecsey's background, and I saw an
interview he did where he called himself a journalist. And if he's
a journalist, we're all in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Vecsey's Turner Sports studio partners, Ernie
Johnson and Kenny Smith, kidded him about Cuban's remarks. Vecsey
responded by challenging Cuban to come on a telecast to debate the
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In Portland, Ore., with the Mavericks, Cuban said such a
challenge is a win-win situation for Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to make the challenge,'' Cuban said. ``The problem
of saying `yes' is that it's on his court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He controls the time. He can set it up so he gets five minutes
to ramble and I get 10 seconds. There's no chance in a situation
like that.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
