<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUFFLE QUESTIONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Los Angeles Dodgers second baseman Mark
Grudzielanek said he understands plans change, but it doesn't make
the scenario that played out this spring any easier for him to
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   He had a renaissance defensive season at shortstop, but when
Eric Young was traded to the Chicago Cubs, it left a hole at second
and the Dodgers had no one in their system to patch it. So
Grudzielanek was asked to move to second base. Dodgers officials
told him they wanted Alex Cora to start at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with Cora in the minor leagues and 35-year-old Kevin
Elster slated to start opening day in Montreal, Grudzielanek can't
help but wonder what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it, no question,'' said Grudzielanek, who signed
a four-year , $18 million contract in the offseason. ``I want to
know what the hell they're doing. But what are you going to do? I'm
trying to push myself away from that. I'm just kind of curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of weird seeing what they said would happen not
even come close to happening, and having a couple guys fight over
there (for the spot) and picking up a couple of guys. It's strange,
and to move me over there and move me out of my spot for something
that was out of control and didn't happen, it was kind of
strange.''
</P>
<P>
   With Elster nothing more than a one-year plug-in at the
position, it fuels speculation about what's going to happen next
season. More than Cora being ready, it's perceived throughout the
industry the Dodgers will make a run at signing free agent-to-be
Alex Rodriguez in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   However, Grudzielanek, who said he might not have played his
last day at shortstop for the Dodgers, added that he was placing
all his energy on improving at second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying not to worry about that over there,'' Grudzielanek
said. ``I'm trying to concentrate on my position, and what's next
for me is to start the season. I'm a second baseman, so that's how
it's going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it's not just Dodgers manager Davey Johnson and the
front office who are glowing about the transition. Several scouts
who've watched the Dodgers for extended periods this spring said
Grudzielanek was impressive at second, considering the position
switch is in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because I've been out there so much in the middle
of the infield,'' Grudzielanek said. ``I've seen plays, what I
wouldn't do if I was playing over there. I tried to learn what to
do and how to do it correctly and more consistently. They turn
double plays differently or do this or that. There's a lot of
options and you have to try and do what's comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one thing I have to do is on the ball to my left, I
have to make that play more consistently. I get caught sometimes
when I'm trying to turn too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Karros puts foot forward: The night's rest apparently did
wonders for Eric Karros' bruised left ankle. A day after putting a
scare into the Dodgers, Karros was at Dodgertown working out
lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Karros would likely return either Friday or
Saturday in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came in he was walking normally,'' Johnson said.
``There's nothing structurally wrong. I'll check with him (today),
but he's going out doing some tee work. That tells me all I need to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros was hurt when he fouled a pitch off his ankle Tuesday.
X-rays were negative.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: The Dodgers survived another scare in the
bottom of the first Wednesday against Atlanta when Chipper Jones
lined a ball off pitcher Kevin Brown's left ankle. After a few
minutes talking to medical personnel behind the mound, Brown
continued to pitch until the fifth inning. He left after reaching
his pitch count (70) and, though he iced afterward, said he was
fine. Brown finished the Grapefruit League 3-0 with a 1.35 ERA. . .
. If the Dodgers carry 12 pitchers for the first week of the
season, it might not mean outfielder Geronimo Berroa's chance to
make the club is gone. The Dodgers' hope is they would need to
carry an extra pitcher for only a week, and the Dodgers could keep
Berroa, a nonroster invitee, off the roster a week into the season
before losing him. ``We have until the end of the first week of
April to see. That's part of the options we have,'' Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone said. . . . The Dodgers optioned pitchers Eric
Gagne and Mike Judd and catcher Paul LoDuca to Triple-A
Albuquerque. . . . Johnson said the club would carry infielder Jeff
Branson through today before either releasing him or sending him to
the minors.
</P>
</TEXT>
