A1902 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-AZR &LR;      03-29 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE THAT DIDN'T MAKE PAGE ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before she left for work last Thursday night, Cynthia Bernal
made sure there were bottles in the refrigerator for her
3-month-old son, Andrew, and food for 6-year-old Jacob and
1-year-old Matthew. She set out clothes for them to wear the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   It's what Cynthia did every night before leaving the home she'd
recently purchased in the West Valley and heading for her night
shift job at a post office station in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Vicki Fernandez, was staying with Cynthia and the
boys, helping out, but Cynthia made sure everything was in order
before she left for work. She and her husband, Edmund, had gone
through some difficult times, like a lot of couples, but Cynthia
wouldn't allow it to affect her life with the boys. Mostly because
her life ``was'' the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her world revolved around them completely,'' Vicki says of her
daughter. ``For her it was work and her sons. She didn't do other
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Cynthia purchased a van, figuring it was the kind
of vehicle a young mother needed with three children. She was
saving for a trip to Disneyland, which she figured to take this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cynthia was 19 when she had Jacob,'' her mother says. ``But
she started working right out of high school, and she has been with
the post office for five years. She believed in doing right for her
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The work day began for Cynthia at 10:45 p.m. The next morning,
she'd trade off with her mother, who'd leave for work as her
daughter arrived home. Last Thursday, knowing there was
construction on Interstate 10, Cynthia left the house earlier than
usual.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Public Safety investigators say that shortly after
10 p.m., near 51st Avenue, where freeway traffic was slowed by
roadwork, a car driven by 29-year-old Jacquline Nez plowed into the
back of Cynthia's van.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics revived her, but the injuries were too severe. Early
the next morning, as her boys slept in their beds, Cynthia's family
watched as she was removed from life support and died. She was 25.
</P>
<P>
   A trust fund for her sons has been set up in Cynthia Bernal's
name at Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Nez, suspected of driving under the influence, has
been charged with manslaughter and several counts of endangerment.
According to prosecutors, she faces up to 27 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can a person do what this woman did?'' Vicki asks. ``Now,
the rest of us must make sure that Cynthia is remembered, and tell
her boys how special their mother was.''
</P>
<P>
   She thought local news outlets might do part of that job.
</P>
<P>
   After all, in the days since Cynthia's death, her family has
read several stories about another young woman, Emily Ell, who was
killed by a drunken driver. She died on her prom night last year,
and the driver, Richard Foley, recently received 20 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   It made all the papers and the TV news.
</P>
<P>
   And they read about the brother of the boxer Michael Carbajal,
Angel, who died in a bar fight that spilled out into a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   It was in all the papers, too. And on TV.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from an obituary, there has been nothing about Cynthia
Bernal. And today, as Vicki Fernandez buries her daughter, she
wonders if there has been a more important story reported recently
in ``The Arizona Republic,'' or any newspaper, than one involving
the tragic death of a loving mother who did nothing but work hard
and care for her boys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
