<SLUG> BC-FORD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD AND UAW TENTATIVELY AGREE TO CONTRACT AT CLAYCOMO PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Ford Motor Co. and the United Auto Workers
union have tentatively agreed to a new contract covering the
Claycomo plant.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary agreement was reached earlier this week after a
round of talks that had continued through last weekend, said Jerry
Kline, president of UAW Local 249.
</P>
<P>
   Kline said the local agreement would be explained and voted on
by hourly Ford employees at 2 p.m. Sunday at Winnetonka High
School.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the local contract will supplement the national
agreement Ford reached with the UAW in September. The four-year
pact would expire in September 2003, Kline said.
</P>
<P>
   Kline declined to comment on specifics of the agreement until it
was discussed with the union's members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our major concerns were addressed in the
negotiations,'' he said. ``It's a good contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Kline said several health and safety issues were in
dispute, including a proposal by the union for a new entrance for
commercial tractor-trailers supplying the plant.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,900 people would be covered by the agreement at the
Claycomo plant, which builds F-series pickups and is about to
launch a compact sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also was satisfied with the tentative agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy with the way things have proceeded,'' said Ed
Miller, a Ford spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2333EST &QL; 
