<HEADER>
A1907 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      03-29 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 ASPs AND ADDING CHARACTER  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here and there, at work:
</P>
<P>
   One of the stiffest corporate dress codes in the world is
relaxing by a hair. After decades of a firm no-facial-hair policy,
Disney theme parks will allow employees _ presumably the male ones
_ to grow mustaches.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney empire carefully cultivates a clean-cut image.
Permission to be more hirsute wasn't granted lightly. Disney
summoned focus groups, polled guests and employees, and convened
meetings. Finally it accepted neatly trimmed, upper-lip hair.
</P>
<P>
   Bans remain on beards, multiple earrings, flagrant fingernails
and other makeup or hairstyles not considered Main Street enough
for patron approval. As it is, the change may be so innocuous that
few will notice.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, few employees may care. These days, young men's
preferences tend toward goatees or I-haven't-shaved-in-days beards,
not mustaches alone.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Disney marketing magic might make mousetaches all
the rage.
</P>
<P>
   - At any moment, when I glance up from my desk, I might see a
Baroque pianist, a Civil War re-enactor, a tenor or a master
quilter walk by. And they all work here.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing about co-workers' talents differentiates them from
others and makes conversational connections. It's a reminder that
any workplace is not a pack of automatons, but a collection of
individuals with personal passions.
</P>
<P>
   The value of knowing about co-workers' interests and talents is
partly why the Business Committee for the Arts is promoting a
program it calls art &LR; work. This October, the national group wants
businesses to encourage employees to bring art they create or
perform into their workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions include hanging employee artwork on the walls or
posting it on the company's Web site or intranet; holding readings
of employees' written work; presenting vocal, instrumental, dance
and theatrical performances by employees; and inviting family and
community to share.
</P>
<P>
   For information about the national art &LR; work program, call
Michele DeSantis at (212) 664-0600.
</P>
<P>
   - Do you know an Aberrant Self-Promoter? Are you one?
</P>
<P>
   Sigrid Gustafson, a researcher in industrial and organizational
psychology, says 5 percent of workers are ASPs who ``believe they
are superior to others and have the right to do what they please.''
</P>
<P>
   Gustafson, who works at the American Institutes for Research in
Washington, says ASPs have trouble operating within workplace
structures. These types also are likely to carry out corporate
sabotage and espionage, so it's good to figure out who they are
before hiring mistakes are made.
</P>
<P>
   Gustafson will share her assessment tools for identifying ASPs
with colleagues at the Society for Industrial and Organizational
Psychology convention in April in New Orleans. Check the
organization's Web site at www.siop.org for information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
