<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAGEL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL WOES TAKE THEIR TOLL ON EINSTEIN//NOAH BAGEL CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Einstein//Noah Bagel Corp., the national
bagel company built in part on the efforts of a Kansas City bagel
bakery, has reported that because of its deteriorating financial
condition, there is ``substantial doubt'' that it will survive.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report, filed Monday with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the company reported that it was trying to
reorganize its finances and was hunting for new bank financing.
Without the financing, it expects to be unable to pay interest it
owes in June.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein//Noah operates 22 Einstein Bros. Bagel stores in the
Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the company also was negotiating with the
holders of $125 million in debentures and other creditors about
converting their debt into stock in the company. That transaction
would leave current stockholders ``with little, if any, meaningful
stake in the reorganized company.''
</P>
<P>
   Einstein//Noah was started in 1995 by the combination of several
bagel companies around the country, including the Bagel &AMP; Bagel
stores in the Kansas City area. Bagel &AMP; Bagel was formed by Gail
Lozoff in 1988 and had its first shop in Brookside. Einstein, which
started with 54 stores, currently has 540 stores nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the company, including Lozoff, could not be
reached for comment. Lozoff, 49, is chief marketing officer of
Einstein//Noah.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein is 52 percent owned by Boston Market, which filed for
bankruptcy protection in October 1998. McDonald's Corp. agreed in
December to buy Boston Market's 859 stores for $173.5 million cash
and assumed debt. There was talk at the time that Einstein might be
acquired by New World Coffee-Manhattan Bagel.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein's stock was de-listed by the Nasdaq Stock Exchange on
March 7 because the company failed to meet minimum financial
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported a $3.5 million net loss on sales of $375.5
million for the fiscal year that ended in December. It reported a
loss in 1998 of $235 million after taking a write-down of $212.4
million in good will and assets. It had profits of $3.7 million in
1997 and $10 million in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0450 </DOCNO>
