<HEADLINE>
CELL PHONE PLAN AIMS TO HELP LIKELY VICTIMS CALL 911, FAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A plan to use old cellular phones to help protect the
elderly and other people who are vulnerable to crime is to be
announced Thursday by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor will ask people to donate their old or unused cell
phones at one of more than 300 drop-off points that will be set up
around the city, said Rhea Mallett, the coordinator of the city's
domestic violence program.
</P>
<P>
   The phones will be reprogrammed to dial 911 at the push of a
button, and distributed to cabdrivers, the disabled, the homebound,
victims of domestic violence and neighborhood-watch groups.
</P>
<P>
   Collection sites for the program _ known as Phones, or People
Helping Others Needing Emergency Services _ will be located at
movie theaters, police and fire stations, Grand Central Terminal
and Pennsylvania Station. The city expects to collect 10,000 phones
a month.
</P>
<P>
   People will be asked to donate the phones in clear plastic bags
along with their batteries and chargers.
</P>
<P>
   The phones are being reprogrammed free by Bell Atlantic Mobile.
It will be impossible to make calls from the phones or to receive
calls. The phones will be given away, with the help of a number of
corporate sponsors, this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic started a similar program just over a year ago and
has given away 10,000 phones, said Lynette Viviani, a spokeswoman
for Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Mallett, the city coordinator, said the earlier program had been
a success. ``I know that a taxi driver has used it twice to report
accidents,'' she said. ``He was able to get ambulances quickly.
Those few minutes can save a life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
