<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCFOOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAFNESS NO HANDICAP FOR LINEBACKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's nothing extraordinary about junior college
transfer John Cousins making an impressive showing in USC's first
spring practices. Until you consider the former West Los Angeles
College linebacker is completely deaf in his left ear and can
barely hear in his right ear.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the handicap hasn't deterred Cousins, who made several
nice plays in the Trojans' first scrimmage last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hearing doesn't really come into affect,'' Cousins said.
``Players help me out and I can get signals from the sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   Cousins said his hearing has gradually declined over the years
from strain and pressure problems. He underwent an operation on his
right ear, but it did little to improve his hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been deaf in my left ear for more than 10 years,''
Cousins said. ``I lost most of the hearing in my right ear in the
last five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Cousins is not totally deaf, however, and wears a hearing aid in
his right ear, although it does not give him regular hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hearing aid amplifies the sound,'' Cousins said. ``I hear
everything, but it's not like it can replace your ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than the hearing deficiency, Cousins' biggest
transition has been playing linebacker full time. He was primarily
a defensive end at West L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been doing real well,'' said USC linebackers coach A.J.
Christoff. ``He just needs to make the adjustment to linebacker.
I'm excited about his progress. He has great athletic ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Christoff said he has learned to tailor his coaching toward
Cousins' situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to coach as much as possible where I'm looking at him,''
Christoff said. ``From a distance, it's hard to talk to him, but
straight up close, it's no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Cousins has a good shot at playing time next season, because the
strongside-linebacker position is wide open, with Kori Dickerson,
Chris Prosser and Scott Huber also fighting for the starting role.
</P>
<P>
   __ Scrimmage follow up: After getting a chance to watch tapes of
last Saturday's miniscrimmage, USC coach Paul Hackett offered some
detailed explanations about how the Trojans looked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long, long way to go. The defense is ahead of the
offense,'' Hackett said. ``I think we have a strong secondary. I
thought (linebacker) Darryl Knight made some plays. (Defensive end)
Lonnie Ford played real well, but I expected that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought John Cousins and (defensive end) Omar Nazel made
some plays and showed their athleticism.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Penalty problem: The Trojans had 11 penalties in the
scrimmage, which was reminiscent of last season, when they had 128
in 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll continue to have a full (officiating) crew (at practice)
and talk about it and work on eliminating penalties,'' Hackett
said. ``If I had a magical answer, I would use it. I don't think
for a first scrimmage, the penalties were outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Next scrimmage: The Trojans will hold their first extended
scrimmage on Friday afternoon at Howard Jones Field. They will also
hold scrimmages on April 8 and April 15.
</P>
<P>
   __ Local candidates: Several former area quarterbacks are
spending this spring trying to make the team as walk-ons. Among
those competing are John Terzian of Harvard-Westlake High, Taylor
Talt of San Marino and Ray Kasper of Loyola.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting candidate could arrive in summer camp, when
6-foot-8 volleyball player Trevor Julian is expected to try to make
the team as a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett would like to keep one or two walk-ons to complement
scholarship quarterbacks Carson Palmer, Mike Van Raaphorst and Matt
Cassel.
</P>
<P>
   __ Strange injury: Defensive end Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed is
questionable this week after feeling a pop in his shoulder while
rolling over in bed, Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
