<SLUG> BC-EMBRAER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBRAER POSTS RECORD EARNINGS, EXCEEDING FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (cjl) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Embraer, a leading manufacturer of small
passenger jetliners and Brazil's biggest exporter, reported
Wednesday that fourth-quarter and full-year earnings in 1999 soared
to records on strong sales in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The results at Embraer far exceeded the forecasts of securities
analysts and underscored the company's transformation from a
money-losing state-run enterprise six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A reduction in Brazil's manufacturing costs, caused partly by
the country's currency devaluation in early 1999, also contributed
to Embraer's strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   Embraer's net income in the October-December quarter more than
quadrupled to 226.3 million reais, or $130.3 million. For all of
1999, the company's earnings nearly tripled, to $240 million.
</P>
<P>
   The jet manufacturer's 1999 sales totaled a record 3.38 billion
reais, or $1.95 billion, up 114 percent from 1998 sales of 1.58
billion reais.
</P>
<P>
   ``Results were much better than anyone expected, which should
better position Embraer to expand in other areas, especially those
that are defense-related,'' said David Wheeler, a managing director
in the Brazilian office of Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   This year, analysts expect Embraer's sale of jets to rise nearly
50 percent, to 150 from an estimated 100 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Embraer is often cited as an industrial symbol of Brazil's
economic modernization. Its clients include some of the largest
American and European airlines, and Embraer has continuously
pressed forward with expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   The sale last year of a minority stake to a French aerospace
consortium led by Aerospatiale Matra and Dassault Aviation was part
of this push. The alliance is seen as enabling Embraer to improve
its technology to win more military contracts for its fighter jets,
which currently account for only about 10 percent of production.
</P>
<P>
   Latin American nations including Mexico and Chile have
reportedly shown interest in acquiring military aircraft from
Embraer. The company's aggressive efforts to get more international
orders have caused considerable friction with competitors, most
notably Bombardier of Montreal. Both companies have roughly a third
of the $55 billion market for regional jetliners, which are
commonly defined as aircraft with 100 or fewer seats.
</P>
<P>
   The generous financing made available to Embraer's clients from
the Brazilian government has resulted in a dispute with Bombardier
at the World Trade Organization, with Bombardier accusing Embraer
of benefiting from unfair subsidies. A ruling on the dispute is
expected later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a politically charged issue, so I'm sure that whatever
the decision is one side will appeal, and the dispute will
continue,'' said Mauricio Botelho, the president of Embraer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
