<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES FROM AROUND THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE SENATE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENTIAL HELP IN MICHIGAN
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton helped the U.S. Senate bid of Rep. Debbie
Stabenow, D-Mich., by attending a cocktail party in Washington on
Tuesday that raised $250,000. Stabenow led Sen. Spencer Abraham, a
freshman Republican, by 52 percent to 48 percent in a poll early
his month by Epic/MRA Inc., a polling company in Lansing, Mich.
Abraham's standing suffered partly because he had backed Gov.
George W. Bush, who lost to Sen. John McCain in the state's
primary, a poll spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEPHARDT OR GEBHARDT
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in the St. Louis area may have to read the
congressional primary ballot closely in August. On Tuesday, Richard
A. Gebhardt filed to run against Rep. Richard A. Gephardt, the
House minority leader. Even though Republicans have acknowledged
that Gebhardt has attended party meetings, they deny any role in
his candidacy. Roy Temple, executive director of the Missouri
Democratic Party, does not believe them. ``It's a despicable
Republican dirty trick,'' Temple said.
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT WHO?
</P>
<P>
   Just how closely are the Bush and Gore campaigns watching each
other? When it spotted a release Wednesday from Vice President Al
Gore's office on the U.S. Newswire, an electronic service, that had
dropped the word ``vice'' from his title, the Bush camp likened the
mistake to other verbal slips or grand claims by Gore. ``Since he
invented the Internet, inspired ``Love Story'' and discovered Love
Canal, it's fitting that the vice president promote himself to
president,'' said Ari Fleischer, a Bush campaign spokesman. But it
was the Bush campaign that was overreaching: The Newswire said it
made the error.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Eau Claire, Milwaukee, Wauwatosa and Pewaukee,
Wis.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Washington.
</P>
