<HEADER>
A1921 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CDNOW-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      03-29 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDNOW-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CDNOW STOCK PLUMMETS AFTER AUDITOR EXPRESSES CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
  (cjl) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares in the online music retailer CDNow Inc.
fell 30.9 percent to $3.50 Wednesday after the company filed an
audit with the Securities and Exchange Commission expressing
``substantial doubt'' about the future of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the audit foreshadowed challenges that would be
faced by online retailers in general as narrow margins fail to
compensate for marketing costs.
</P>
<P>
   The audit, by the Arthur Andersen accounting firm, was published
as part of CDNow's annual report, filed on Tuesday with the SEC. It
states that ``recurring losses from operations'' cast doubt on
CDNow's ``ability to continue as a going concern.''
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, which ended Dec. 31, CDNow had $34.5
million in operating losses. While posting $53 million in sales, it
spent about half that _ $26 million _ on marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The audit put a fine point on previous disclosures from CDNow
that its current liquidity would run out before the end of the
year. In Tuesday's filing, the company said it had sufficient cash
to operate through Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow had pinned hopes for its future on a merger with Columbia
House, a direct-mail music company owned jointly by Sony and Time
Warner, but the deal fell through earlier this month. In backing
out, Time Warner and Sony said they would invest a combined $51
million in CDNow, money that had already been factored into the
company's ability to operate through September. At least $21
million of that investment has already been delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Olim, CDNow's president and chief executive, played down
the significance of the audit language, saying that Arthur Andersen
was obliged to give only a qualified endorsement, given that CDNow
had acknowledged it lacked enough money to operate through the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think there is new information, which there is not,''
he said, adding he has ``high confidence'' the company will find
new investors. CDNow has retained the investment banking firm Allen
&AMP; Co. to find a new partner, though Olim declined to discuss the
progress of the search.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, the struggles of CDNow appear to be a painful
harbinger for online retailers, analysts said, because CDNow failed
to achieve profitability despite being early to market and
establishing a strong brand name _ assets that popular wisdom has
long equated with success in e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brand development in and of itself does not guarantee
success,'' said Ken Cassar, senior retail analyst with Jupiter
Communications, a market research firm based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly susceptible, Cassar said, were commodity
businesses, like online pet stores or beauty stores, which have low
margins and offer products that differ little if at all from their
competitors'.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of online retailers are going to go out of business,
and a number are going to be identified by traditional retailers
that don't yet have an online strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cassar said that while CDNow had failed to capitalize on its
early lead _ for example, it did not broaden its product base to
ticket sales _ it remained a viable takeover candidate. He added
that it was too soon to write a eulogy for the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-00 2353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000329.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-NUDE-RECONSIDE     03-29 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NUDE-RECONSIDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOUTER, A CHANGE OF MIND AND A DEFT MEA CULPA 
</HEADLINE>
   (With SCOTUS-NUDE)  
 (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his concurring opinion in the nude dancing case
Wednesday, Justice David H. Souter of the Supreme Court was hardly
the first to make what judges have long regarded as a painful
confession: that he had changed his mind on a question of law.
</P>
<P>
   Souter now believes, he wrote, that cities should have to prove
that nude dancing is actually causing them harm. In a 1991 nude
dancing case, he was willing simply to make the assumption of harm.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining his change, Souter joined a long line of judges
who have deflected the potential embarrassment of a public
recantation by a graceful turn of phrase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have demanded the evidence then, too,'' Souter said,
``and my mistake calls to mind Justice Jackson's foolproof
explanation of a lapse of his own, when he quoted Samuel Johnson,
`Ignorance, sir, ignorance.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to Justice Robert H. Jackson's concurring
opinion in a 1950 case, McGrath vs. Kristensen, in which Jackson
explained why he was abandoning a position he had advocated 10
years earlier as attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion Wednesday, Souter also alluded to Justice Felix
Frankfurter's explanation for a change of heart, in 1949: ``Wisdom
too often never comes, and so one ought not to reject it merely
because it comes late.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it is enlightenment on my part, and acceptable even if
a little late,'' Souter said of his own new position.
</P>
<P>
   He did not, however, quote perhaps the most famous of all
judicial recantations, that of Baron Bramwell, a 19th-century
English lawyer and judge, who explained himself in the 1872 case of
Andrews vs. Styrap by saying: ``The matter does not appear to me
now as it appears to have appeared to me then.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, it was hardly incumbent on Souter to provide a
compendium of prior recantations. The words with which Jackson
concluded his apologia in McGrath vs. Kristensen are undoubtedly
sufficient: ``If there are other ways of gracefully and
good-naturedly surrendering former views to a better considered
position, I invoke them all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
