<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1926 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-BOYS-AZR &LR;      03-29 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 ILLEGAL MINORS, 2 TALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY DANIEL GONZALEZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Juan Sebastian and Elian Gonzalez are two immigrant boys
with a lot in common, yet their cases are being handled in widely
disparate ways.
</P>
<P>
   Both boys arrived in the United States through heart-wrenching
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, as the world knows, is the 6-year-old Cuban boy rescued
in the waters off Florida on Thanksgiving after his boat sank and
his mother and 10 others drowned.
</P>
<P>
   David, an obscure 13-year-old Indian boy from Guatemala, was
discovered in October wandering alone in the equally dangerous
Arizona desert after he was abandoned by his stepmother.
</P>
<P>
   Although Elian has been showered with media attention, David's
plight is far more representative of the thousands of minors
apprehended by the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, immigration lawyers and human-rights
activists say, unaccompanied minors apprehended by the INS are
quickly returned to their countries. Otherwise, they languish in
detention centers, sometimes for months, until their status is
sorted out away from public scrutiny and with little or no legal
representation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real problem,'' said Jo Becker, advocacy director of
the children's rights division of Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Elian, he's been able to stay with relatives, go to
Walt Disney World and Universal Studios and receive lots of gifts.
In contrast, there are several thousand children a year who are in
similar situations who have arrived here without their parents and
are picked up by the INS and placed in detention.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many immigrants, both Elian and David escaped hardships
back home.
</P>
<P>
   Elian left a Communist country that's run by a dictator. David
comes from a region of Guatemala still reeling from the aftermath
of a protracted civil war that killed thousands.
</P>
<P>
   But Elian's case has somehow floated to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Elian is surrounded by the love and affection of relatives in
Miami, bathed in the riches of capitalism, and represented by
high-powered attorneys and politicians fighting to keep him in the
United States. David sits deprived of his freedom in a juvenile
detention center in Coolidge.
</P>
<P>
   Elian has a loving father waiting for him in Cuba. David, if
deported, will most likely wind up a street kid in Guatemala, where
he could fall easy prey to gangs, prostitution, or worse, his
lawyer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Elian's case highlights the disparate treatment under
the law of unaccompanied minors. . . . The vast majority of
unaccompanied minors are initially subject to detention,'' said
Chris Nugent, director of the Florence Immigrant and Refugee Rights
Project, a non-profit organization that provides legal services to
immigrant detainees.
</P>
<P>
   Most unaccompanied immigrant children are from Mexico and
Central America, including El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras,
Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration attorneys and human-rights activists describe
Southwest Key, the detention center where David is held, as a model
facility where undocumented juveniles attend school and are
generally well cared for.
</P>
<P>
   But Becker says many undocumented juveniles apprehended by the
INS are placed in juvenile jails where they are mixed with
juveniles accused of committing crimes, sometimes as serious as
rape, assault and murder.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of treating the undocumented juveniles as de facto
criminals, Becker said, a better alternative would be for the INS
to hand over undocumented juveniles to local child-welfare
authorities while their cases are being processed.
</P>
<P>
   But Russell Bergeron, a spokesman for the INS in Washington,
D.C., calls those contentions ``ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The facade that this child is in jail is simply an attempt to
mischaracterize the circumstances under which he is being cared
for,'' Bergeron said. ``A 13-year-old with no competent or capable
relatives, and no means to support himself, should not be free to
come and go as he pleases.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did these undocumented juveniles enter the United
States illegally, Bergeron said, the conditions inside the
facilities where they are held are often better than the conditions
they left. The average stay is 37 days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Key, where David is being held, is staffed by
teachers, child psychologists and other specialists, Bergeron said.
</P>
<P>
   The only time undocumented juveniles are placed in juvenile
jails, Bergeron added, is when the undocumented juveniles in INS
custody are accused of committing a crime or are placed there for
their own protection.
</P>
<P>
   During fiscal 1999, there were 4,607 undocumented juveniles
under age 18 in INS custody, according to agency records. During
the same year, 1,218 undocumented juveniles were returned to their
own countries.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Flanagan, a Phoenix lawyer representing David for free,
stumbled upon the boy's case. Without her efforts, David likely
would have already been returned to Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan is trying to obtain special immigration juvenile status
for David, which would allow the boy to apply for permanent
residency in the United States. She argues that David has no
relatives to return to in Guatemala and that his father, although
possibly a legal resident of the United States, is an unfit parent.
If she is successful, David may eventually be placed in foster care
or in a group home.
</P>
<P>
   David was picked up by the INS on Oct. 6 on the Tohono O'odham
Reservation in southern Arizona, a barren stretch where many
illegal immigrants have died. In interviews, David told Flanagan
that his stepmother abandoned him in the desert after the pair
crossed the border near Sasabe. The pair were trying to reunite
with David's father, who moved to the Valley several years ago
looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says his stepmother left him with very little water, no
food and no money,'' Flanagan said. ``She said she was going to
come back, but she didn't. He waited for her, then started walking
and walking. He was crying.''
</P>
<P>
   David told Flanagan he comes from San Jose, a dirt poor village
outside San Sebastian Coatan in the indigenous Huehuetenango region
of Guatemala. There are no schools in San Jose, and David can't
read or write. He speaks Spanish, but his first language is Chuj, a
Mayan language pronounced ``chew.'' His real mother is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Elian Gonzalez have argued it would be unfair to
send the boy back to a Communist dictatorship. Eric Popkin, a
sociology professor specializing in Cuba and Guatemala at Sarah
Lawrence College, said the conditions in Guatemala are worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cuba, what I see is economic hardship, particularly in the
1990s after the fall of the Soviet bloc,'' said Popkin, who has
spent time in both Cuba and the Huehuetenango region of Guatemala.
``In San Sebastian, there is poverty and misery. Absolute
misery.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
