<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL FANS RUNNING THROUGH HOOPS IN GATORLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the story goes, the sports information office of a
Southeastern Conference school once crafted a news release
announcing that the school's head basketball coach had ``resigned
to accept a promotion as defensive line coach of the football
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that the ``promotion'' really did happen, though
no one remembers who or exactly where.
</P>
<P>
   But it could have been Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sunshine State, college basketball used to be merely the
diversion between the bowl game and the launch of spring football
practice. The Gators' basketball coach in the 1950s was, in fact,
Johnny Mauer, who doubled as the football staff's defensive
backfield coach.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, the Gators played their hoops in a brick earache
known as Alligator Alley. The building was said to hold around
7,000, an audience that seemed to sway with the fickle fortunes of
the basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, here the Gators are, a Final Four team for the second time
in seven seasons. They could win it all, much to the chagrin of
college basketball purists, including Lon Kruger.
</P>
<P>
   Florida basketball isn't just a good story this 1999-2000
season. It's a walking ``X-Files'' episode.
</P>
<P>
   If you quizzed the average college hoops fan and asked which
Final Four hopeful boasted five McDonald's All-Americans on its
roster, the answer likely would have been anything but Florida. But
it's true. Coach Billy Donovan, he of the Eddie Munster haircut,
starts four of the prep All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   How he got forward Mike Miller to Gainesville, Fla., from South
Dakota defies all basketball logic and area codes. But in truth,
Donovan has a rich Final Four pedigree of his own, having played in
one and assisted in one, and he seems to have inherited his old
boss' knack for gathering the talent.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a sophomore, explained at a news conference yesterday,
``I had to make a sacrifice in that I had to go far from home, and
to a program that didn't really have all of the hype and publicity
that the other schools that I was looking at did.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I fell in love with coach Donovan and what he was
preaching to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's old boss, of course, is Rick Pitino and there are
remnants of the ex-Kentucky coach's system everywhere. The Gators
like to press and shoot the 3-pointer. And Donovan substitutes like
a hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   They have a way, as Pitino's Kentucky teams did, of imposing
their tempo on people, as it showed in the East Regional victories
against Duke and Oklahoma State. No one wants to run with the
Gators, but the Blue Devils and Cowboys found themselves hurrying
things, nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   During the SEC season, the Gators won a snore-fest at Georgia,
33-20. Illinois, coached by Kruger, tried the same thing in the
NCAA tourney's second round, and the Gators escaped, 40-33.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Kenyan Weaks suggested, ``You really have to try and play
a half-court game, I guess. You have to get us in foul trouble,
make shots, get offensive rebounds. Do the things that are
weaknesses to us, and I think you can beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, a lightly regarded No. 12 seed, thought it worked the
game plan to perfection in the tourney's first round, but the
Gators survived, 69-68, on a basket at the overtime buzzer. In the
Florida locker room afterward, there were tears of relief.
</P>
<P>
   It speaks volumes about how far basketball at Florida has come
that Donovan's team actually felt pressure not to underachieve.
When Kruger bolted for the Big Ten four years ago, he said it was
because, in part, Illinois was much more ``basketball country.''
The insinuations were obvious.
</P>
<P>
   At least Steve Spurrier hadn't tried to promote him to
special-teams coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think early in the year we had a very hard time handling
success and the amount of preseason hype,'' Donovan said. ``I think
our guys came into the season with inflated opinions of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``But through the course of the year, I think our team has
remained relatively humble.''
</P>
<P>
   If you grew up in SEC country, there is more than a passing
irony in having a Florida basketball team favored over
tradition-rich North Carolina in the Final Four semis.
</P>
<P>
   And they could win it all. It would be the highlight of spring
football practice.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
