<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUS-TRAIN30-COX-1STLE     03-29 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-TRAIN30-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST LEDE
 &HT;    EDs: Adds death of third victim; updates throughout
 &HT;    
 &HT;    `Greatest of sorrows': Shock turns to grief at vigil for victims
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider and David Bennett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TENNGA, Ga. _ While about 1,000 people were grieving the death
of two children in the worst train-school bus wreck involving
Georgians since 1974, another of the injured children died.
</P>
<P>
   Amber Pritchett, 9, died about 8 p.m. Wednesday at T.C. Thompson
Children's Hospital in Chattanooga, Tenn., hospital officials said.
The hospital is where all the injured children were taken.
</P>
<P>
   Amber's death came about an hour after a vigil had begun in
Murray County for the victims of the crash. Word did not reach
those at the vigil.
</P>
<P>
   The second day of grieving for the five injured and three killed
in Tuesday morning's crash started with childrenlowering the flag
at their school to half-staff and ended with about 1,000
tear-stained faces glistening in candlelight at a vigil on the
courthouse lawn about 15 minutes away in nearby Chatsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes was among those at the vigil at the
Murray County Courthouse. ``This is the greatest of sorrows: the
memory of joy in the face of grief,'' he said. ``We cannot
understand why they were taken.'' As the frenzy of Tuesday's crash
at a narrow railroad crossing subsided, residents of this
blue-collar community of about 600 felt the full weight of their
sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday I was numb. Today I woke up and realized that she
was not there,'' said Jenny Agan, 26, the aunt of Kayla Silvers, a
6-year-old who died in the crash early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kayla was among seven students on thebus picking up students for
Northwest Elementary School. They all lived near one another in
this enclave of trailer homes and small dwellings at the top of a
hill. Daniel Pack, 9, also died when the 33-car CSX freight train
collided with the bus at the unprotected crossing. Two children
remain in critical condition. Brittany Gaddis, who stumbled from
the twisted hulk of the train to a nearby store, was released from
the hospital Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two children myself,'' a weeping Karen Ross of
Chatsworth said as she stood among the crowd in 40-degree
temperatures. ``This has made me aware of what can happen any
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Clark drives her daughter, Felisha, to preschool at
Northwest Elementary. ``I'm lucky my little girl wasn't on the
bus,'' Clark said at the vigil. ``It makes you stop and think.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Silvers, who discovered his daughter Kayla dead in the
wreckage, told the crowd, ``Cherish (your children). You'll never
know how much you miss them until they are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Chaney, who organized the service, was overwhelmed by the
turnout. The wife of the pastor at nearby Mount Zion United
Methodist, Chaney started out planning a small service at the
church. But it quickly became apparent the church wouldn't hold
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very profound,'' Chaney said. ``This sends a message to
the families that we love them and support them. I hope this helps.
We will continue to pray for them.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials had braced Wednesday for a hard day of sorrow
and tears _ and they got it. In Tuesday's confusion, many students
hadn't heard what had happened or, if they had, did not know who
was injured.
</P>
<P>
   For the students and teachers, the second day of grieving hit
harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my heart is broke,'' said Zachary Mantoota, 8. He
rides that bus some days, but was driven to school Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   He said his class talked about ``how that train hit the bus. A
couple of kids were crying.''
</P>
<P>
   In chats with his grandmother, he shared his own sadness. He
knew Amber Pritchett and was friends with Kevin Sherrill, 8, who
was injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had deep sadness and love. It really tore my heart out to
hear him,'' said grandmother Janice Medlin.
</P>
<P>
   At Northwest Elementary, Principal C.L. Dunn tried to keep the
day as normal as possible. ``We feel the children need a sense of
routine right now to reassure them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grief counselors visited the classes of the accident victims.
Bus routes were reconfigured to avoid train crossings. Some buses
carried yellow ribbons in tribute to the students.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents kept their kids off the buses, driving them to
school. Among them were the parents of Zachery Watson, 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was crying a lot last night,'' said his father, John
Watson, who was among those who helped at the accident scene.
</P>
<P>
   At the railroad crossing on Liberty Church Road, eight small
yellow ribbons hung on the wooden post holding the yellow sign with
the X on it to symbolize a railroad crossing. The post on the other
side of the one-track crossing, sideswiped as the train dragged and
shredded the bus, had been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Crews from the Tennessee Highway Patrol and the National
Transportation Safety Board measured and marked the site in
preparation for an accident restaging today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to mirror the conditions, to determine at what point a
driver could see the train and hear the train,'' said NTSB
spokeswoman Lauren Peduzzi.
</P>
<P>
   The train's on-board computer revealed that the warning whistle
had been blowing and that the train was traveling at about 50 mph
on impact. The speed limit at the crossing, where trains can pass
as often as every half-hour, is 60 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials acknowledged that many questions remain and
that it is too early to ascribe any blame. Dana Keeton, spokeswoman
for the Tennessee Highway Patrol, rattled off a short list of some
outstanding issues: Was the bus moving or was it stopped upon the
tracks? Did the bus driver follow the law by stopping before the
tracks to check both ways? Why was the bus on the tracks when a
train was coming?
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB expects to release a preliminary report in about a
week, but a full finding could take 10 months, said Peduzzi.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Keeton said the bus driver, Rhonda Cloer, whose own
daughter was among the injured students, had only one previous
violation on her driving record, a 1991 speeding ticket. The record
did not indicate whether that occurred while she was driving a bus,
said Keeton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
