<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-29 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-TEX     03-29 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TORNADO DAMAGE IS IN HUNDREDS OF MILLIONS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: CORRECTS NAME OF FOURTH VICTIM TO `Oseguera' STED `Osequera';
adds contributors' line at end; adds information about closed area
in second graf) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERNIE MAKOVY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The governor's office declared Tarrant
County a disaster area Wednesday as workers began cleaning up the
devastation from tornadoes that ravaged Fort Worth and Arlington,
killing five people, wiping out neighborhoods and making downtown a
ghost town.
</P>
<P>
   Damage in Fort Worth alone was projected to top $300 million,
with most of the destruction downtown and in the Monticello,
Rivercrest and Linwood neighborhoods. More than 30 blocks of
downtown Fort Worth were closed yesterday and will remain closed
today. Figures for Arlington, where 100 homes sustained major
damage and 1,000 had light to moderate damage, were not available.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr accompanied state officials on a
helicopter tour of the two cities and said he was ``just completely
shocked'' by the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mike Moncrief said he was awestruck by the disaster.
``I've seen the aftermath of Oklahoma City and Wichita Falls
(tornadoes), but I just didn't expect it here in our own back
yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Two tornadoes hit Fort Worth and Arlington about 30 minutes
apart Tuesday evening. They plowed through the Fort Worth business
district, shattering plate-glass windows in high-rise buildings,
and ripped through a residential area south of Interstate 20 in
southeast Arlington. Fifty-six homes were damaged in Grand Prairie,
east of Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service gauged the Arlington tornado at its
peak as an F3, which packs winds of 158 to 206 mph. The Fort Worth
tornado was an F2 with winds ranging from 113 to 157 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry granted the county disaster declaration in
the absence of Gov. George W. Bush, who was out of state
campaigning for president. The governor issued a statement saying
the damage is ``a tragic reminder of the fierce power of nature. My
thoughts and prayers are with the victims and their families. Our
state disaster recovery teams are already working with local
officials to assess the damage and provide relief.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington damage was primarily confined to the area around
Matlock and Bardin roads near the municipal airport; no serious
injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, the major path of destruction was a two-mile
stretch from University Boulevard along West Seventh Street through
downtown. More than 80 people were treated at area hospitals, and
at least two were in serious or critical condition Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Bob Terrell estimated preliminary damage in Fort
Worth at $157 million, but comparisons already were being made to
the 1995 hailstorm, which produced $400 million in insured damages
alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwestern Insurance Information Service estimated that
the final damage total for the Tuesday tornadoes will exceed $300
million in Fort Worth alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hailstorm was more widespread, whereas now, the damage is
more concentrated and obviously more extensive,'' Assistant City
Manager Ramon Guajardo said. ``But I don't know which will be more
costly.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 50 buildings hit by the tornado in Fort Worth, eight were
destroyed, 27 sustained major damage and 15 had minor damage. At
least one, the Cash America building, may have to be torn down,
Deputy Fire Chief Jim Tidwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Also damaged in Fort Worth were the downtown Central Library,
the Cowtown Coliseum and the International Center.
</P>
<P>
   Local hospitals treated more than 80 people for injuries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The confirmed death toll stood at four Wednesday night, with one
person missing and presumed dead. Two victims were crushed on the
outskirts of downtown _ Carl Spence, 67, by a collapsing wall and
Howard D. Thornton by a truck trailer that toppled onto him _ as
the tornado plowed its way through the heart of the city about 6:30
p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The body of the third victim _ Ashlyn B. Dickens, 24, _ was
recovered Wednesday morning along a creek in the 9500 block of
Trinity Boulevard, behind the Bell Helicopter plant in northeast
Tarrant County. Dickens and his grandmother, Adele Warren, 62, were
in a car that was swept away by rising creek waters as they left
Bell Helicopter. Warren's body had not been located by Wednesday
afternoon, but she is presumed to be dead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Juan C. Oseguera, 19, who suffered severe head trauma when a
softball-size hailstone hit him, died Wednesday night at a Fort
Worth hospital. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon Wednesday, authorities had reopened many
downtown streets that had been barricaded, leaving the business
district a virtual ghost town bounded by glistening sidewalks
sprinkled with broken glass.
</P>
<P>
   Streets surrounding the most heavily damaged high-rise buildings
_ Bank One, UPR Plaza, Tandy Towers and the Tandy Technology Center
_ may remain closed through the weekend as workers remove cracked
or broken plate-glass windows, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Owners and managers of downtown properties were allowed into
their buildings Wednesday afternoon to assess damage and secure the
contents.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the thousands of downtown workers who received an
unexpected holiday Wednesday will probably be permitted to return
Thursday, Police Chief Ralph Mendoza and Guajardo said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the downtown area, the heaviest damage was in the
Linwood neighborhood. More than a dozen homes and duplexes,
including the former home of presidential assassin Lee Harvey
Oswald, were destroyed or heavily damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Also hard-hit in Fort Worth was the Monticello neighborhood,
where the storm ripped roofs from homes and uprooted 80-year-old
trees along Hamilton Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   In the 3900 block of Hamilton Avenue, winds lifted one family's
garage and moved it 10 feet north. A basketball goal was knocked
horizontally, and winds drove it into the family's white sedan,
embedding the backboard in the left taillight.
</P>
<P>
   The only reported neighborhood injury was a man working at the
West Seventh Street Barbershop. The owner's son, Michael Moore, was
the last to leave the barbershop, said his mother, Rosa Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had just walked out of the shop, and the wind blew him
against the building and it collapsed on top of him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, the tornado destroyed a section of roof at the
Bell Helicopter Textron facility. Flying debris damaged a V-22
helicopter and an XV-15 demonstrator but did not damage two CV-22
Osprey helicopters housed there, Bell spokesman Bob Leder said.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado skirted the I-20 corridor of car dealerships, then
slammed into a residential neighborhood flanking both sides of
Matlock Road just south of Bardin Road. Some houses, particularly
along Embercrest Lane and Chasemore Lane, caught the brunt of
powerful winds that left only clumps of rubble atop concrete
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents credited their survival or lack of serious injury
to residential construction that places bathrooms in the middle of
the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those bathrooms saved lives,'' said Laura Donovan, whose home
on Sandalwood Lane was damaged but not destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington Fire Battalion Chief John McQueary also marveled at
the absence of serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has blessed us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration imposed a strict ``no fly
zone'' over downtown Fort Worth at the request of the FBI, said
John Clabes, an FAA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why is that the downdrafts from the helicopters
flying over downtown were blowing some of the remaining shards of
glass out of those tall buildings and blowing those shards down on
the people trying to clean up the mess below,'' Clabes said.
</P>
<P>
   The ban will remain in effect until the FBI or Barr requests
that it be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   In the Fort Worth suburb of River Oaks, Castleberry High School
students, whose classes were canceled Wednesday, are expected to
return Thursday. The campus sustained widespread damage to the
field house, vocational building and main building.
</P>
<P>
   River Oaks City Administrator Joy Williams said 80 structures
sustained damage.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhoods on the southern and western fringes of River Oaks
were hard hit, with fallen trees, broken windows and roofs blown
off.
</P>
<P>
   The city lost many stately trees more than 100 years old, Mayor
Jack Adkison said.
</P>
<P>
   Retired graphic artist Jerry Grimes, 65, now working part-time
for the U.S. Census, recalled how he was leaving Tandy Center on
Tuesday evening when he saw the storm developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started forming from the ground up,'' Grimes said. ``Then I
saw it begin a slow counterrotation. The sky turned black, and then
the clouds were pulled right out of the sky... The yellow stripe on
my back started to grow. At that point, I decided the tornado was
bigger and badder than me, so I took off.''
</P>
<P>
   ( Staff writers Jennifer Autrey, Anita Baker, Paul Bourgeois,
Elizabeth Campbell, Yvette Craig, Tawnell Hobbs, Mike Lee, Steve
McLinden, Mede Nix, Domingo Ramirez, Dan Reed, Ginger D.
Richardson, Rebeca Rodriguez, Karen Rouse, Neil Strassman, Kristin
N. Sullivan, Robert Tharp and Chris Vaughn contributed to this
report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
